<SLUG> BC-SAMESEX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME-SEX UNIONS VIOLATE CHURCH LAW, METHODISTS DECLARE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A United Methodist pastor who blesses a same-sex union violates
church law, and if found guilty will be removed from the church,
the denomination's Judicial Council said in a ruling released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling clarified whether a statement in a church document,
Social Principles, was advisory or law.
</P>
<P>
   The line, ``Ceremonies that celebrate homosexual unions shall
not be conducted by our ministers and shall not be conducted in our
churches,'' was added to Social Principles by the denomination's
General Conference in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeff Procter-Murphy, pastor of Asbury United Methodist
Church in Phoenix, said he was disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a United Methodist minister, I celebrate my denomination's
heri tage, theological pluralism and diversity,'' said
Procter-Murphy, whose church is one of 148 United Methodist
congregations in the country that welcome gays and lesbians into
all aspects of church life without seeking to change them.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I grieve that it wasn't until the 19th century that
we took a decisive stand against slavery, the 20th century before
we ordained a woman, and now we will be into the 21st century
before we truly understand that ` Homosexual persons no less than
heterosexual persons are individuals of sacred worth,' '' he added,
quoting a line also found in Social Principles.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Beard, editor of an evangelical magazine for United
Methodists, was thrilled with the decision, saying it reflects the
view of the majority of the 8.5 million members in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow folks to be ordained who are self-avowed,
practicing homosexuals,'' said Beard, editor of Good News,
</P>
<P>
   based in Kentucky. ``Why in the world would we try to recommend
a relationship for something we don't believe in?''
</P>
<P>
   The debate centered on whether Social Principles should be
considered church law and enforced the same as its Book of
Discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jimmy Creech of Ne braska tested the rule and was
brought to trial after he blessed a union between two women. After
his acquittal this spring, several groups within the denomination
requested clarification.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the nine-member Judicial Council declined to say
whether the entire Social Principles is church law.
</P>
<P>
   But the line about homosexual unions was intended to govern a
minister's conduct and ``failure to do so is a disciplinary
violation,'' the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Council members do not comment on rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop William W. Dew Jr., leader of Arizona's 50,000 United
Methodists, was on vacation and could not be reached for comment
Tuesday. He has said previously that he believes Social Principles
are instructive standards for leading a Christian life. He would
investigate any complaint brought against a pastor for blessing a
same-sex union in an Arizona church, he said, and would uphold
church rules. There have been no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibition on same-sex unions may be moved to the Book of
Discipline, Methodists predict, at the next General Conference in
2000. The General Conference meets every four years and is the
church's legislative body. &QL; tagKelly Ettenborough can be reached at
444-4877 or at
kelly.ettenborough &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
