<HEADER>
A9276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-COX     08-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Methodist court upholds ban on marrying gays
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ United Methodist Church pastors who conduct
same-sex weddings and other union ceremonies can be defrocked, the
church's highest judicial court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling pulls the nation's second-largest Protestant
denomination, with some 8.5 million members, back from the brink of
schism. Conservative Methodists had threatened a mass exodus over
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is the second in a week in which a major religious
body has dealt a setback to wider acceptance of homosexuals in
church circles. Last Wednesday the world's Anglican bishops,
meeting in Canterbury, England, passed a resolution declaring
homosexual activity ``incompatible with Scripture'' and advising
Anglicanism's 37 church provinces, which include the Episcopal
Church in the United States, against ordaining homosexuals as
priests.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the United Methodist Church Judicial Council,
which came after a two-day hearing in Dallas, also called into
question whether other Methodist Social Principles _ the church
opposes capital punishment and supports choice on abortion, for
example _ can be interpreted as church law. Retired Washington
State Bishop Jack Tuell the high court did not intend for the
ruling to have broader implications, but church members may
interpret it that way. ``Somebody might get the idea they want to
make a point about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some church critics say, that's exactly what will
happen. Charges for violating church laws can be filed against
clergy and laity in the church, but usually it is clergy who are
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this ruling, it's going to encourage people to file
charges against pastors and other laypeople who violate other
Social Principles,'' predicted the Rev. Jimmy Creech. ``The ruling
seems to imply a (social) position taken by the church can be
upheld as the law of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Creech was acquitted of violating a church stance against
same-sex unions in a Nebraska church trial six months ago. He
argued before the Judicial Council that if the gay marriage ban was
made church law, rather than a social position, then Gov. George
Bush's church status could be in jeopardy because he supports
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But in its ruling, the Judicial Council said it was only dealing
with one Social Principle, and more specifically, one sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sue White, pastor of Parker Lane United Methodist
Church in Austin, said the sentence is clearly binding because it
says, ``You shall not as a clergy perform a same-sex marriage.''
Other Social Principles, she added, do not use such direct
language.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the high court has ruled on one of the
church Social Principles, generally considered to be guidelines and
not church law.
</P>
<P>
   Tuell said clergy ban on gay marriages is unique because of the
language and because it is the only Social Principle the church has
control over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another place in the Social Principles where
United Methodist ministers are directed to do something,'' Tuell
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the governing body of the United Methodist Church
approved placing the ban on same-sex marriages in the Social
Principles. The same body rejected five attempts to place the ban
into church law.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church has been in turmoil since the 1996
General Conference. The issue escalated in March when Creech was
acquitted in a church trial after he joined together a lesbian
couple. Since then, conservative church leaders have taken the
denomination to the brink of schism. Some regional conferences
threatened to withhold contributions to the denomination, and
churches threatened to leave. At least one pastor and church did.
Conservative leaders, including the Rev. Bill Hinson, the Houston
pastor of the largest Methodist congregation, and some bishops
demanded a special national conference to deal with the issue once
and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Then the College of Bishops of the South Central Jurisdiction,
which includes Texas, asked the church's Judicial Council to take
up the matter. The council called a special session to hear
arguments on the issue Friday and Saturday in Dallas. Bishop Ray
Owen of the Southwest Texas Conference, which includes Austin,
could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most mainline denominations openly welcome gays and lesbians as
members but are struggling with the idea of gay marriages and
ordinations.
</P>
<P>
   The Presbyterian Church (USA), for example, said earlier this
year that ``chastity in singleness and fidelity within the covenant
of marriage between a man and a woman'' are the standards for
ordination, virtually eliminating any chance for homosexuals to be
ordained in the church.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
