<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-FOR-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. to pay Texas family for gunning down son
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Without explanation or admission of fault, the
federal government has agreed to pay $1.9 million to the survivors
of a West Texas teen-ager gunned down by a Marine patrolling the
border, the family's lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, the third grand jury to review the case reached
the same conclusion the others had: No crime was committed when
Marine Cpl. Clemente Banuelos shot Esequiel Hernandez in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was enough evidence to support an indictment,''
said District Attorney Albert Valadez of Presidio. ``But, I'm not
going to persuade a grand jury with my opinion. And, I couldn't
persuade them with the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 18, was herding his goats in Redford, about 200 miles
southeast of El Paso, when he was shot after crossing paths with a
four-man Marine patrol doing drug surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said Hernandez shot twice at the Marines with
his .22-caliber rifle. He was shot, they said, when he raised the
weapon again. The explanation has never satisfied Hernandez'
family, some area residents and U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The civil-suit settlement was announced Tuesday by Pecos lawyer
Bill Weinacht, representing the Hernandez family.
</P>
<P>
   While the money will help, Weinacht said, his clients got what
they really wanted in February when they met with a justice
department official.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told the family that what happened to their son was
wrong,'' Weinacht said. ``That's what they really needed to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Magarito Hernandez, Esequiel's older brother, said the
settlement is confirmation of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they accepted the deal, they accepted it was a wrong thing
that happened,'' he said. ``Nothing is going to bring him back. But
at least it will help my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest grand jury decision, coincidentally, came several
hours after the lawsuit settlement was announced. Valadez, who
presented the case to another grand jury last year, quietly brought
the matter before a new grand jury after getting materials
collected by federal investigators looking into a possible civil
rights violation case.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in February returned no indictments in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Valadez began presenting the case to the second local grand jury
in July. He said the federal probe produced almost 5,000 pages of
evidence, compared with 200 he had last time.
</P>
<P>
   Grand jurors had the option of indicting Banuelos for murder,
manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valadez said he accepts the grand jury decision, and, barring
new information that he does not believe is out there, the case is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied I made every effort that I can humanly make to
present all the facts. Their decision is final in my book,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston lawyer Jack Zimmerman, who represents Banuelos, said he
was not surprised by the grand jury no bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three grand juries determined there was not enough evidence to
present a charge,'' Zimmerman said. ``Corporal Banuelos was
completely justified in his actions under the law. The case is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinacht said the family's civil claims against the U.S.
Department of Justice and U.S. Navy also are now over.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be ``structured with an expected payout to the
family of $1.9 million,'' he said. A source familiar with the
settlement said it would be paid over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Watney, a justice department spokeswoman in Washington,
confirmed that a settlement had been signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Military Claims Act permits components of the federal
government to settle claims caused by their activities without a
showing of fault on the part of any person, so long as the injured
person or claimant was not at fault,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the no-fault claim by the government, some Redford-area
residents saw the settlement as proof of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just hand out money if there is no reason to hand
money out,'' said The Rev. Melvin LaFollette, a longtime friend of
the Hernandez family.
</P>
<P>
   But Weinacht said the Hernandez family never was driven by a
need to explore the full details of what led to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, we had to fight off people with other
agendas,'' he said. ``My only concern was what the Hernandez family
wanted to do. What they wanted was some type of compensation for
the loss they suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio and chairman of the House
immigration subcommittee, remains convinced the whole truth about
the incident has not yet been heard. In May, Smith's panel
subpoenaed records from the justice and defense departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``His focus from the beginning has been on getting answers,''
spokesman Allen Kay said. ``He has promised a public accounting of
this tragic death, and he intends to deliver one.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
