<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pirates, Reds go to battle for last place
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Battle for the Bottom did not start well
Tuesday night in Cinergy Field for the Cincinnati Reds _ unless
they want to finish last in the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   They began the night in fifth place, one game ahead of the
last-place Pittsburgh Pirates, but they never even raised their
fists to defend themselves while bowing meekly, 7-0, on a
six-hitter (all singles) by Francisco Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the two teams test each other again tonight, they will
do so tied for last place _ 53-66 and 19 games behind first-place
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Reds' fans among the 16,399 found worth watching
were the Cincinnati debuts of outfielder Jeffrey Hammonds and
pitcher Jason Bere.
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds, obtained Monday from Baltimore in a trade for Willie
Greene, started in center field and contributed singles in his
first two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Bere, activated off a minor-league contract, made his debut in
relief in the eighth and went 1-2-3 on nine pitches. His second
inning, the ninth, was ugly _ double, wild pitch, hit batsman, walk
(to the pitcher), 22 pitches. . .and got out of it with one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't exactly consider it a good one or a bad one,'' Bere
said of his appearance. ``It was kind of a necessary outing. It's a
start. Now we'll go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds began his Reds career on a quick upper and a quick
downer.
</P>
<P>
   On his first at-bat, he pulled a 2-and-0 pitch into left field
for his first National League hit. Mere moments after they rolled
the baseball into the dugout as a keepsake memento, Pittsburgh
pitcher Francisco Cordova picked Hammonds off first base.
</P>
<P>
   On his second at-bat, he used his feet to beat out an infield
hit to third base to make him two-for-two in the National League. .
.and he didn't get picked off base.
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds didn't take batting practice after arriving at 4:40,
even though he had time to dress and do it. He said he didn't need
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenaline I'm running on right now can't be matched,'' he
said. ``It has been a while since I've been this excited about
playing a game. I was told (Monday) to get here because I was going
to start, so I was anxious to get here and get this party
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds said he heard the rumors of his trade to the Reds for
Willie Greene on Saturday, ``But I made light of it, didn't think
much of it. When I got the call Monday that it happened, it was a
shock of sorts. I didn't know how to act at first, but it didn't
take long to get excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance to start over,'' he said. ``I realize it was
time for a change, time to move on. I harbor no ill feelings toward
the Orioles. It was time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys they're bringing in here, they're trying to find
something,'' Hammonds added. ``I feel very privileged more than
anything that they would to find me to come in and try to shore up
center field.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds was Baltimore's No. 1 draft pick (fourth overall) in
June, 1992, and played nowhere else but in the Orioles system and
for the Orioles until Monday's trade.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Hammonds was the principle of a bizarre play in the
seventh inning. With Lou Collier on first, Tony Womack lobbed a
shallow fly into center. Hammonds tried for a sliding catch and
missed. But as he slid, he kicked the ball toward the infield,
where second baseman Bret Boone was able to pick it up and throw to
shortstop Barry Larkin to force Collier at second.
</P>
<P>
   Reds starter Brett Tomko, who has only one victory in his last
five starts, gave up a little bit of everything in absorbing his
eighth loss _ four runs, five hits, two wild pitches, a hit batsman
and a home run.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only 4-0 when manager Jack McKeon pulled him for a
pinch-hitter after five innings, a move to which Tomko reacted by
going into the tunnel behind the dugout and screaming some
expletives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left me in there to take a beating in Atlanta in my last
start (nine runs, eight hits in 5.1 innings), then they take me out
against the Pirates when it is only 4-0. I've been throwing the
ball well for about a month-and-a-half. This wasn't my best, but I
located well and was getting a lot of ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova nearly didn't start Tuesday. His hand hurt after his
last start. The Pirates took X-rays and discovered some healed
broken bones in his pitching hand that may have occurred up to four
years ago. Treatment with a lot of ice enabled him to put the big
chill on the Reds for his fourth career shutout, the sixth time the
Reds have been shut out this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
