<SLUG> BC-TEN-CONNORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNORS HINTS HE MAY NEAR END OF HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Sounding very much like a player nearing the
end of the line, Jimmy Connors strongly indicated Tuesday that he
might be in the waning days of his Hall of Fame tennis career.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before he defeated John Fitzgerald of Australia, 6-4,
7-6 (7-3), in a first-round match of the $150,000 Citibank
Champions tournament for players 35 years and older, the
45-year-old Connors said that his competitive fires _ long the
hallmark of his game _ were flickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're down to embers now,'' said Connors, who is seeded No.
1 in the 16-player event that runs through Sunday at Manhattanville
College.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe, seeded No. 2, plays his first match Wednesday
night against Shlomo Glickstein of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As the dominant player on the Nuveen Tour, Connors has won three
of the eight tournaments played this year and 32 of the 63 that
have been held since the 35-and-over circuit was started in 1993 by
Connors and Ray Benton, a veteran tennis promoter and sports
marketer.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks Connors has been hobbled by an injured right
foot that forced him to default a semifinal match in Boston last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It hampered him noticeably in his victory tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injuries heal a lot slower nowadays,'' said Connors, who,
approaching his 46th birthday on Sept. 2, is the oldest player on
the Nuveen Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this, but it's tough for me to carry them anymore,''
he said. ``I'm getting too old for that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Connors did say that he would fulfill a commitment to the Nuveen
Tour that runs through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I don't know what I'll do, although I'll probably
stay involved with tennis, at least on a part-time basis'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But first I may just put my feet up and take a year off.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, who was inducted into the Tennis Hall of Fame last
month, said he thought his slashing style and overall game had not
changed appreciably since he left the regular tour after he turned
40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can strike the ball better now than I could 15 years
ago,'' Connors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think I anticipate better than I did in the past. But
the foot injury has slowed me down and my game depends on how I'm
moving. Also, I don't see the ball as well I used to, and wear
glasses now.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors was asked whether he would miss the adulation once he
retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``I don't need it and I don't want it.
I don't want people seeing me at the U.S. Open or at Wimbledon and
saying, `That's Jimmy Connors.' And when I do leave tennis, it will
be on my own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
