</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres capture series opener
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It was only last month the Atlanta Braves called San
Diego to see if Joey Hamilton was available for trade. He was not.
And Tuesday night, the native Georgian returned the compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Dousing the hot-hitting Braves, Hamilton pitched the Padres to a
3-1 victory in the first of three games between the two leading
clubs in the National League. Hamilton (10-9) halted the Braves'
four-game win streak by limiting the Braves to one run, only the
fifth time since the All-Star break the Braves had scored once or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Denny Neagle (11-10), he has been Atlanta
starting pitcher in three of those games and lost for the fourth
time in his last seven starts. Only two of the three runs he gave
up were earned, after he allowed six hits and one walk while
striking out four in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley homered for the Padres, who also used a pair of
Braves error for the deciding run in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Braves have won every series played in San Diego
since 1989, the Padres are redefining the joint this season. The
victory left them 43-13 at Qualcomm, the best home record in the
majors after the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tried rally in the eighth, after pinch hitter Greg
Colbrunn walked and Ozzie Guillen singled to chase Hamilton. Newly
acquired left-hander Randy Myers struck out Tony Graffanino and
retired Chipper Jones before Dan Miceli retired Andres Galarraga on
a long fly to center to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Hoffman came on in the ninth and quickly closed out the
Braves on two strikeouts and a weak grounder.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego doubled its way into a 3-1 lead in the fifth. After
Carlos Hernandez opened the inning with a double, Neagle retired
the next two batters, but after he threw three straight balls the
Quilvio Veras, the Padres shortstop doubled into center, scoring
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko waited until the 119th game of the season to make
his first error, but the Braves left fielder made it count. With
Ken Caminiti on first with one out, Neagle appeared to have gotten
out of the fourth inning when he induced a routine grounder to
third from Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   But Chipper Jones lost the ball off the heel of his glove,
giving Caminiti third base, and Vaughn set off for second. Klesko
charged well enough but made a clumsy sliding stop and uncorked a
wild throw past second and backup man Andres Galarraga, allowing
Caminiti to score for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had tied the game 1-1 in the third with an RBI single
through second base, giving him six straight hits and eight RBIs in
12 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
