<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PANTHERS-SIGNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers agree to terms with forwards
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Florida Panthers moved closer to
their goal of having all their players signed before the Sept. 12
start of training camp Tuesday when they announced forwards Ray
Whitney and Viktor Kozlov had agreed to contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Whitney, a two-year package worth about $2.8
million, cancels what would have been only the team's second
arbitration case ever. The two sides were scheduled to appear
before an arbitrator Friday. Whitney made $300,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlov signed a one-year deal worth $1 million plus incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The deals leave only five players unsigned, all of whom are
restricted free agents: goaltenders Kevin Weekes and Todd
MacDonald, and forwards Radek Dvorak, Steve Washburn and Chris
Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to avoid contract issues when camp starts,''
Assistant General Manager Chuck Fletcher said. ``We want to give
(first-year coach) Terry Murray a chance to bring everybody
together and get off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are too many players who can look
themselves in the mirror and say they had a great year.'' Florida's
24-43-15 record last season ranked 25th among the league's 26
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, who tied the team scoring record with 32 goals after
being acquired on waivers last Nov. 6, had filed for arbitration
last month. Whitney reportedly was seeking about $2 million, while
the Panthers were offering $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was important to both sides to avoid arbitration if
we could, to keep the relationship very positive,'' General Manager
Bryan Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Ray wanted badly to be here and get it done. He's
real happy with it; with incentives, he can make considerably more,
so it's a positive deal for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozlov was the team's best player down the stretch, scoring
eight goals in his last 14 games and showing star potential the
last half of the season. But he has totaled just 41 goals in his
four NHL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a guy starting to emerge who can be a real force,''
Murray said. ``But we want to find out where he's going to be in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Viktor a great opportunity. We're hoping this can
be his platform year; if he's the player we think he is, then we'll
be happy to reward him down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Biggane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
