u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-COX     08-12 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullish run may not have stopped, but correction has begun
 &HT;    By Danielle Herubin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signals are growing stronger that U.S. stock markets are
nearing the end of a historic six-year bull run. One thing is
certain: A correction is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week after losing 299 points in its third-worst loss
ever, the Dow Jones industrial average, buffeted by bad economic
news worldwide, dropped 258 points at its low point Tuesday, then
recovered to close 112 points down at 8,462.85.
</P>
<P>
   That means the market has plunged 875 points since its historic
high of 9337.97 just 3 1/2 weeks ago. And that translates to a 9.3
percent fall in stock value _ a loss in paper wealth of about $3.3
trillion (that's a 3 followed by 12 zeroes), according to Daniel
Morgan, an analyst at Boca Raton-based Noble Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   How big is $3 trillion? That's the equivalent of a $30,000
salary paid to each of 100 million workers.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, and there is some good news: The market still is
up 6 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a correction. It could be a little more,'' said Donald
Ratajczak, director of the economic forecasting center at Georgia
State University in Atlanta. ``We have fundamentally ignored the
rest of the world, saying, 'Things are OK here. What's it matter in
the world?' Now we're saying, 'Maybe it does matter.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off was triggered by a series of factors:
</P>
<P>
   Investors and economists are concerned about Japan's weakening
currency, the yen, and $500 million to $1 trillion in bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   Other Asian economies are suffering currency problems, which
have touched off market slides throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American markets, skittish because of weak currencies and
Asia's problems, began falling as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported Tuesday that the United States
suffered its first drop in worker productivity in more than three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Federal court officials said Tuesday Americans are filing for
personal bankruptcy at a record rate.
</P>
<P>
   Trade and economic pressures abroad are expected to continue to
damage earnings of U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to U.S. stock markets most likely is already hurting
you. Pension plans tied to markets and 401(k) plans have lost
value. Economists are predicting job losses in technology and
retail manufacturing because Asia's sliding currencies will mean
cheaper imports.
</P>
<P>
   And business deals such as bank mergers could be in jeopardy if
they involve stock because such deals usually include triggers that
block the transactions if the affected companies' stock prices fall
too low.
</P>
<P>
   In West Palm Beach, Republic Security Bank's deal to buy First
Palm Beach Bancorp for $256.9 million has such a trigger, but
Republic Security Chief Executive Rudy Schupp said the transaction
could be renegotiated if there is a problem with the stock price
toward the end of the year, when the deal is to close. Republic
stock (Nasdaq: RSFC) dropped 6 cents Tuesday to close at $10.19.
First Palm Beach shares (Nasdaq: FFPB) closed at $38.94, down 31
cents. There is some short-term good news for consumers, however.
NationsBank economist Lynn Reaser said that consumers can expect
cheaper gasoline prices because Asian countries are not consuming
as much energy, meaning more supply and less demand.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty over Asia, with banking and currency problems in
Japan, China and elsewhere, rippled around the globe. Stock markets
across Europe and Latin America retreated. In Russia, trading was
halted temporarily Tuesday during a sharp selloff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a similar round of currency attacks and stock market
declines last October,'' NationsBank's Reaser said. ``This is a
repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried investors swamped brokers and money managers with calls
Tuesday. Morgan, with Noble Financial Group, said his phone was
busy. While his assistants handled the nervous clients, he spent
the day trading. His advice was to move portfolios into safer
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of investors, repositioning meant getting out of
stocks and into bonds and money market funds. Investors are
starting to move money out of stock funds, according to
Trimtabs.com, a firm that tracks 3,400 mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, the day the market fell 299 points, investors
withdrew $1.1 billion from stock funds. Money flowed back in last
Wednesday and Thursday, but at the end of the three days, the net
result was a $129 million drain. That compares with a daily average
inflow of $900 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not buying, which means they're worried,'' said Carl
Wittnebert, the Santa Rosa, Calif.-based company's director of
research. ``It gives me the feeling that they're waiting for the
market to stabilize.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no clear consensus about whether the market is going to
rise or fall from here. Ralph Acampora, Prudential's chief analyst,
said on the CNBC cable network Tuesday that he thinks this
correction is going to be bigger than he originally thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been saying that the secondary stocks are already in a
bear market, and my call . . . is that the blue chips will also go
into a bear market,'' Acampora said. ''It's a bear call.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Hanna, president of Frost Hanna Capital Group in Boca
Raton, said the bull isn't dead.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna argues the dollar is showing strength against foreign
currencies, the U.S. government expects budget surpluses, and
interest rates are low. All are good signs that the economy is
strong, and Hanna's still buying stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Those choosing to stay in the market are looking for safe
havens. Banking, technology and aerospace have been hit hard by the
declines in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Although NationsBank's Reaser said she does not believe the
banking industry will be affected, Noble's Morgan said brokers he
knows are backing away from the financial-services sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The big banks) all have huge exposure to Asia,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   United Technologies (NYSE: UTX, $87.69), parent of Pratt &AMP;
Whitney, is on a cost-cutting program, partly because of Asia.
United Technologies sells air conditioners, elevators and aircraft
engines in Asia, where sales represented about 12 percent of the
company's revenue in 1997. Shares in United, whose Pratt subsidiary
has 4,900 employees in northwestern Palm Beach County, fell $2.94
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, with 3,200 employees in southern Palm Beach County,
also has been hammered by the collapse of Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses appeared to be unaffected, but were watching the
stock market warily.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Rim countries represent emerging markets for Florida
citrus sales, said Andy Taylor, controller for Caulkins Indiantown
Citrus Co., which grows citrus on 16,000 acres in Martin County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more concerned about . . . the ability of those
customers to buy citrus products,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for retail and real estate interests said they don't
think their businesses will suffer even if the markets continues to
drop.
</P>
<P>
   Retailer Office Depot Inc. (NYSE: ODP, $31.38), which employs
about 1,800 at its headquarters in Delray Beach, said its $600
million in available cash and credit means the stock markets won't
affect its plan to open 90 stores this year. Its stock was down
$1.19 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not dependant on the market for capital,'' said Chief
Financial Officer Barry Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial real estate brokers and home builders said interest
rates, not stock markets, drive real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life cycle of the real estate market is different than the
stock market,'' said Neil Merin, a broker at NAI Merin Hunter
Codman in West Palm Beach. ``If the Federal Reserve said they were
going to raise interest rates, that would certainly have a negative
effect. It would take a 2- to 2 1/2-point increase in interest
rates for the real estate markets to start shutting down.''
</P>
<P>
   But real estate investment trusts already have been hit, mostly
because of risky derivative investments tied to Asia. That could
slow down the domestic building boom.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Page, director of operations for Fort Lauderdale-based
Stiles Corp., a commercial developer with projects planned for Palm
Beach County, said that if REITS slow their investing, Stiles will
have ''second thoughts'' about building.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lehman, executive director of the Palm Beach County
Tourist Development Council, said stock market volatility might not
affect some of the bigger hotels, which nail down bookings two to
three years in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think a loss in confidence in the stock market will
cause people to have second thoughts about whether to spend as much
for a vacation,'' Lehman said. ``Will they eliminate vacations
altogether? I don't think it's gotten to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Herubin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Staff writers Julie Waresh, Stephen Pounds, Paul Owers
and Marguerite M. Plunkett, staff researcher Lynne Palombo, The
Associated Press and Reuters contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
