u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-APPLEBY-PGA-COX     08-12 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-APPLEBY-PGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appleby's sorrow shows in his return to golf
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Stuart Appleby was in mid-sentence when the
words suddenly stopped. He rubbed his moist, red eyes. He tried
again. Nothing. He wiped away a tear. Finally, after another long
pause, he was able to continue.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most emotional press conferences in recent golf
history, Appleby spoke publicly for the first time Tuesday since
watching his wife, Renay, die in a car accident in London 19 days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like she was the first prize of a raffle in life and
picking partners,'' Appleby said, ``and I was lucky enough to win
her.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was lost July 23 when she was hit by a taxi outside
Heathrow Airport. She went to retrieve a bag when another car, the
driver not realizing he was in reverse, struck her and crushed her
between two cars. She never regained consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Renay, 25, and Stuart, 27, were about to fly to Paris for their
second honeymoon. The Australian couple had been married since
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   They shared a life inside and outside the yellow ropes. They had
met in 1992 when both were junior golfers touring the United
States. They even played together as a team on the trip before they
eventually fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   She caddied for him for several months in 1997, when his career
on the PGA Tour was starting to take off. He has won two titles,
including the 1997 Honda Classic, and more than $2 million. Renay
was a fixture in his gallery after letting someone else carry his
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm walking around the course and I see no one,'' he said.
``She's not there walking, not helping me when I need help. The
things I will miss about her aren't the big things. It's all the
little things that add up and make someone's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an hour that goes by that I don't think of her,
not an hour. And that's OK. You just wish things were different.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, who's usually clean-shaven, showed up for the press
conference with a beard, still wearing the wedding ring on his left
hand. He stopped on his way to the media room to chat with Davis
Love III, who lost his father in a plane crash several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said he made the difficult decision to return to
tournament golf at this week's PGA Championship because he said
that's what Renay would have wanted and because this is what he
does for a living. This represents another step he must take. Other
steps, such as returning to their American home near Orlando, have
to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two options I can take,'' he said. ``One, is to to dig
myself into a hole and really begin to feel how deprived and
unllucky and ripped off and angry I could be. Or I can say, hey, I
was lucky that I got to know her for the years I had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she would want me to come back. She obviously would
understand this is obviously not a very easy time for me, so I've
got to let her memory steer me in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Allenby, a fellow Australian who's one of Appleby's
closest friends, is among the pros who have tried to help him
during this difficult time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very tough on him, but I think he's doing the
right thing coming back out here,'' Allenby said. ``You can't just
sit around and think about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other players don't know what to say. They instead
show their emotions with hugs and handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a very sad time,'' said Tiger Woods, a
neighbor of Appleby's in Isleworth. ``I saw him (Monday) for the
first time and I almost teared up on the spot. Even now I get
choked up talking about it. But he knows we're always there for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players have admired Appleby's courage in returning
to golf so quickly. They hope that's a sign he'll be able to deal
with this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has a positive outlook on life,'' said Jupiter's
Jesper Parnevik. ``It's not like it's over. He just has to live it
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said he's not concerned how he does this week. Just
making it to the first tee Thursday will represent another of those
steps he must get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even worried what I do here,'' he said. ``I'm just
going to take it as it comes. Days are more important than
scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
