<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SAMPSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPSON LOOKS BACK _ AND AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ If Steve Sampson had it to do over again --
if he could go back to before the 1998 World Cup and prepare for
France knowing what he now knows _ there is only so much he would
do differently.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Lassiter, who has become Major League Soccer's most-feared
scorer since joining D.C. United, would be heading to the Cup, and
a few veterans -- Alexi Lalas, Tab Ramos, Eric Wynalda _ would join
John Harkes at home.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight makes some things apparent, it is true, but the former
U.S. national team coach, who resigned in the wake of the
Americans' last-place finish in France, would only change so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been given a year ago the confidence and assuredness
that I'd be the World Cup coach in France, I probably could have
begun the process of transition into a much younger national
team,'' Sampson, who prefers to look forward, said last week. ``But
without the confirmation (as coach) until December of '97, I could
not begin to make those kinds of changes. Maybe January '98 was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe I began what was the right process for the
future of soccer in the United States, exposing a Brian Maisonneuve
and a Frankie Hejduk and a Brian McBride to the international
level.''
</P>
<P>
   That decision was, it turned out, at the heart of the problems
that dogged the Yanks in the World Cup, but there is little doubt
it was the right choice. McBride scored the Americans' only goal,
and Maisonneuve, Hejduk and naturalized Frenchman David Regis were
three of the U.S. team's finest World Cup performers.
</P>
<P>
   That they were seeing significant playing time at the expense of
others -- Lalas, Wynalda, Jeff Agoos and Marcelo Balboa _ led to
turmoil that surfaced after the loss to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who gathered at a Beverly Hills news conference last
Wednesday with Iran coach Jalel Talebi, says he knew there was
trouble after the 2-0 loss to Germany in the opener. The dissidents
were Lalas, who didn't see a minute of Cup action; Wynalda, who
struggled against the Germans and saw his playing time trimmed; and
Ramos, who played a far less significant role in France than he'd
hoped to.
</P>
<P>
   They immediately voiced their displeasure, then went public
after a 2-1 defeat to Iran eliminated the Yanks from second-round
contention. Sampson, heavy criticised by the trio, admits he felt
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt their reaction was unwarranted, very disappointing and
unprofessional,'' he says. ``From that standpoint, especially when
you hold a position open for someone (Ramos, recovering from knee
surgery) for eight months and they react the way they did, it was
very hurtful and disappointing. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time Alexi Lalas was at his lowest, I supported him. At
the time Tab Ramos had no international future because of his knee
injury, I supported him, I gave him confidence, and I left a spot
open for him. And Eric Wynalda _ no one has supported him more over
the last two or three years, and under sometimes very difficult
situations. I have supported him and believed in him. The way they
reacted was unwarranted and disrespectful.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is little Sampson could have, would have, done
to alleviate their concerns. They wanted to play, but Sampson
believes he had better players. They wanted their friend Harkes,
dropped from the squad in April, with the team in France, but
Sampson insists he made the right decision. They wanted the
veterans who have provided the backbone of the team the past few
years to play the key roles, but Sampson went with what he believed
was a better lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``As national team coach,'' he said, ``I have to make a decision
based on what's best for the team or on what's best for the
individual. Always the answer must be to do what's best for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lalas, Balboa and Agoos were key defenders in the build-up to
the Cup, but the switch from a four-man zonal defense to a
three-man man-to-man system _ meant to shore up problems in the
back _ cost them their roles. It's hard to argue with Regis and
Eddie Pope in place of Lalas and Agoos, and Sampson admits that
Balboa, who never complained, might have had a beef. Balboa might
have been a more effective sweeper, Sampson acknowledges, than
captain Thomas Dooley, who was slowed by injury.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial move was dropping Harkes, the U.S.
captain. ``I think there were two or three individuals who were
still very upset that John was not part of the team, and they did
not understand or accept the reasoning behind his removal ...,''
Sampson told Soccer America. ``I would make the same decision today
... it was the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a deterioration of trust between myself and John. I
called into question his off-the-field leadership, and it was a
series of events -- whether it was missed plane flights or the last
one in the meetings or staying up 'til all hours of the evening
drinking -- that forced me to make a decision that this was not the
type of leadership that we needed going into a World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that, there were issues about John's unwillingness
to play a different (defensive) role on the team -- a role that I
wanted him to play. Even though he stated publicly, after I had
decided not to take him to France, that he would be willing to play
any role whatsoever, that was not the case in my private
discussions with him. He was adamant about playing a significant
role in midfield and was unwilling to play as an outside back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' failure in the Cup turned on the loss to Iran, in
which the Americans hit the posts or crossbar three times. A
victory in that match would have left the Yanks in position to
advance heading into their first-round finale against Yugoslavia,
and that is all that was expected of the team.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations, Sampson says, hindered the team. ``I seriously
believe we were a victim of our own success,'' he says. ``I believe
the reaction to a 2-0 loss to Germany was an overreaction. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ludicrous to believe we are the 32nd-best team in the
World Cup. Statistically, yes -- we had the fewest points. But our
group was very difficult and the quality of play we demonstrated
has grown. It's very clear we have to become a much more dominant
team physically, that the team must have much greater technique ...
and we have to have much greater precision and poise in
goal-scoring opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something, Sampson says, that needs to be addressed while
identifying and developing players for the future, something he'd
like to do as head of Project 2010, the program designed to make
the U.S. squad true World Cup challengers within 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's realistic or not,'' he says. ``The
fact is we are making the statement that we want to be the best in
the world. If it happens in 2010, great. If it happens in 2014 or
2018 ... we've made our statement and we are investing in our youth
and our coaches and putting together a program that will allow us
to do so. That's the most important thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
