<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS HOLD OFF INDIANS, 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ General manager Doug Melvin's July acquisitions
supplied the Rangers with a tool necessary to seize the American
League West.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Esteban Loaiza and shortstop Royce Clayton _ two of
the four players Melvin acquired before the July 31 trade deadline
_ last night demonstrated how their talents will benefit the
Rangers' glaring deficiencies in low-scoring games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' 2-1 victory against the Cleveland Indians at Jacobs
Field accentuated that point. The triumph also kept the Rangers
11/2 games ahead of the second-place Angels, who beat the Tigers,
5-4, in 11 innings last night in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play a low-scoring game now and win,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``We couldn't do that earlier in the year. We
can win 4-3 and 2-1 ballgames now.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night represented the Rangers' third victory in four games
this month when scoring four or fewer runs. The Rangers went 13-35
in those games before July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: starting pitching and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin improved those areas with the acquisitions of
right-handers Todd Stottlemyre and Loaiza, Clayton and third
baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza (1-2) surrendered only seven hits and one walk during his
86-pitch, 71/3-inning appearance, and the Indians managed their run
on an eighth-inning home run from third baseman Jeff Manto.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who pitched brilliantly for the third consecutive
outing, benefited from a defense that converted three ground balls
into double plays with Clayton involved on each occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you want do is make sure you give the other team 27
outs,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers appear better equipped now to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no defeat typified the Rangers' inability to win
low-scoring games more than their 1-0 setback July 30 against the
Blue Jays at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wasted a brilliant performance that evening from
Loaiza, who recorded a career-high nine strikeouts and surrendered
one run on four hits during that eight-inning performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays scored the game's lone run on a two-out,
fifth-inning single by center fielder Shannon Stewart. Loaiza's
94-mph fastball on the inner half of the plate broke Stewart's bat,
yet the ground ball rolled through the middle of the infield.
Former shortstop Kevin Elster, who did not possess great range,
chased the ball behind second base and made a sliding attempt to
prevent it from reaching the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Elster's range failed him, and the ball rolled into center
field. Catcher Darrin Fletcher scored from second base without a
throw.
</P>
<P>
   That served as the first of three starts in which Loaiza
received a loss or no-decision despite a 2.91 earned-run average
during that span. The Rangers managed only seven runs during those
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joked with him after the game that I didn't want him to hear
him saying that we don't score runs for him,'' Oates said. ``We got
him two tonight and got him a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder Mike Simms, who replaced the injured Juan
Gonzalez in right field and as the cleanup hitter for the second
time in as many games, gave the Rangers a 1-0 lead with his
fourth-inning home run on a 2-1 fastball from right-hander Steve
Karsay (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   The start represented only the second this season for Simms
against a right-hander, and he hit a home run in each with Gonzalez
absent from the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it this way: I just want to go up there and have
productive at-bats,'' said Simms, who is hitting .370 (10-for-27)
in limited at-bats against right-handers. ``I don't look at it as,
`Here's my opportunity to prove I can hit right-handed pitching.'
That's not my role on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Tom Goodwin drove home the other run with a
fifth-inning double, and that would be enough.
</P>
<P>
   It once was not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
