<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' RECEPTION AT NO. 2 WIDEOUT REMAINS FUZZY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La. _ After more than three weeks of training camp,
Cowboys receiver Ernie Mills is positioned as the probable starter
opposite Michael Irvin at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Mills lined up that way in the Cowboys' two preseason games
against the Seattle Seahawks and Oakland Raiders. And he opened
with the first team in the scrimmage against the New Orleans Saints
at Independence Stadium last night.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had no receptions in the first two games, Mills, an
eight-year veteran, has looked solid in practice, and his knowledge
of Cowboys coach Chan Gailey's offense seems to have given him an
edge over Billy Davis for now.
</P>
<P>
   But when Davis signed a multimillion-dollar contract in the
off-season, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones anointed the former
special-teamer as the starter opposite Irvin. And he has bettered
Mills in the preseason by exactly four receptions.
</P>
<P>
   So with less than a month before the season opener against the
Cardinals, neither Mills nor Davis has offered proof that he will
become a consistent threat opposite Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like someone to distinguish themselves,'' Gailey said.
``That hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was more of the same last night against the Saints.
Neither player had a reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the games have gone,'' Davis said. ``I wish we
could have done better, but the reads haven't come our way. We want
to make plays, that's why you play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two preseason games, not only have Mills and
Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman yet to connect in a game, Mills has
not even had a ball thrown in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he is not worried. He said he'll only be concerned if
the drought continues in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he's not alarmed and that the passes will soon get
to Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those situations, where the reads are not taking
Troy that way,'' Gailey said. ``It's not like we're not looking to
him to throw the ball to him. It could happen in the next game
three or four times. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   And to think, the receiver quandary was a question the Cowboys
came into training camp hoping to answer. They were looking for a
replacement for Anthony Miller, who caught 46 passes last season.
Now the leading candidates for his replacement have career
season-best totals of 39 (for Mills in 1995 with the Steelers) and
three (for Davis last year) and haven't shown to be an upgrade from
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, is still an unknown quantity in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey even admits as much. However, he remains confident that
Davis has the goods to make an impact at wide receiver and that
between Davis and Mills, the Cowboys will find a complement to
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   And so far during the preseason, Mills and Davis have nowhere to
go but up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
