A9297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HENRY-COX     08-12 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HENRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henry means business in bid
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ John W. Henry, who might just value his
privacy more than the millions he's earned as a commodities trader,
made a rare public appearance Tuesday to say: ``I would like to be
the next George Steinbrenner.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the first thing Henry offered _ to 20 reporters
invited into his inner sanctum on the second floor of the
black-glassed Northern Trust Building on Yamato Road _ was a
disclaimer about his latest deal-in-the-making:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here to say I am very serious about attempting to
purchase the Florida Marlins.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, looking a bit startled as a turret of cameras popped and
whirred in his face, he fielded questions for 30 minutes about
several topics, including his desire to own a big-league team in
his ``back yard,'' plans to build a new stadium (with his own
money, if necessary), and a proposed holding a ``town meeting'' if
he gets the team, allowing fans to offer suggestions on how to
bring the World Series back to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The only question that went unanswered was perhaps the most
important: How serious is H. Wayne Huizenga about selling the
Marlins _ to John W. Henry, Don Smiley ... or anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Henry said. ``If the seller doesn't want to
sell, you can't get to the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga was in Europe on vacation Tuesday. ``We simply don't
negotiate through the media,'' said Huizenga spokesman Stan Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, 48, is ``surprised'' Huizenga has not responded to a
$150million cash offer he made two weeks ago. This after it
appeared Smiley's yearlong effort to meet Huizenga's $165million
asking price had failed.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Henry agreed to join a proposed ownership
group headed by Smiley, the Marlins president and a Huizenga crony.
Henry, who owns 1 percent of the New York Yankees, said he was set
to chip in $10 million ``as a good South Florida citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Henry said he eventually dropped out because Smiley was
unable to persuade Major League Baseball to relax a rule that
prohibits a person from owning interest in more than one team. At
the time, Henry was not willing to give up his Yankees share in
exchange for holding a limited share of the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   After he dropped out, Henry said he started learning details of
Smiley's plan, including the possibility the Marlins may leave
Florida. After waiting a year _ ``out of respect for Don Smiley and
his bid'' _ Henry said he recently made his own offer of
$120million to $130million to Huizenga's representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Henry called that ``a generous offer'' because the Minnesota
Twins are asking $120 million and the Kansas City Royals are asking
$75 million.
</P>
<P>
   He was rejected, but two weeks ago, ``I offered $150 million
because (the team) is in my back yard. I'd be willing to pay a
premium for that.'' And he also was willing to part with his
Yankees share in exchange for assuming sole ownership of the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But, Henry said, ``The reaction was, ``Let's talk about it
later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Henry tried pushing the process, calling Major League Baseball
about approving him, which he figured would be a formality because
he had gone through a similar review before retaining his Yankees
interest in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But he was told that baseball rules call for the seller to
submit the name of a prospective buyer _ something that Huizenga
has not done.
</P>
<P>
   Does Henry believe Huizenga is reluctant to field offers?
``That's my feeling,'' he said. ``But it's summer. There could be a
number of reasons they're not overly anxious to sell the club.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has ``no way of knowing'' the status of Smiley's
bid, which has been endorsed by key baseball executives and was
approved in a handshake deal with Huizenga last month on the
condition that baseball approve ``certain documents.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Smiley deal hinges on a complicated four-way agreement
involving the sale of Huizenga's interest in SportsChannel to
Charles Dolan of Cablevision, who would sell Marlins TV rights to
Barry Diller of USA Broadcasting. Diller would then join Smiley's
investment group, which could include Huizenga retaining $50million
in interest.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who said he'd welcome Huizenga as a minority partner, has
been given no timeline on a response to his bid.
</P>
<P>
   While his personality is different from Yankees owner
Steinbrenner, Henry said they share a trait that would encourage
Marlins fans who have seen their championship team dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he fields winners,'' Henry said of Steinbrenner. ``In
spite of what the media says about him, I have learned a lot from
him. No one is more committed to winning than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Capozzi writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
