<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami recruit roams secondary
 &HT;    By Jorge Milian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL GABLES, Fla _ Normally, Mike Rumph likes to wake up at
noon or 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday was not a normal day for Rumph, the former Atlantic
High School star, who arose from bed at 5:45 a.m. to join nearly 30
other University of Miami newcomers for the first day of freshmen
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's early for me,'' said Rumph, a solidly-built 6-foot-2,
196-pound defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Rumph appeared wide awake at Tuesday morning's workout, earning
quick praise from UM coach Butch Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He practiced like a veteran,'' Davis said. ``He's a guy that
we'd like to count on.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be too early to tell whether Rumph will contribute
as a first year freshman, chances are that he will.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four returning players competing at free and strong
safety, only Jeff Popovich has starting experience. Rumph will also
get a look at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you count on freshmen to contribute, you're usually
reaching, but first indications on Mike are outstanding,'' said UM
defensive coordinator Bill Miller. ``He looks great on the hoof.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumph says he was a Hurricane long before he put on the uniform.
Growing up in Delray Beach, Rumph followed UM religiously and
repeatedly watched highlight tapes of the school's four national
championship teams. In high school, Rumph wore No. 4 in honor of
former UM defensive back Earl Little.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to decide where to attend college, Rumph had
little thinking to do. He orally committed to UM after his junior
season and stuck by his decision despite prodding from many of the
nation's top football programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I was coming,'' Rumph said.
</P>
<P>
   Rumph says he spent the entire summer preparing himself for
Tuesday's first practice. Lifting weights added 12 pounds of muscle
to his frame. Running sprints regularly with Atlantic secondary
coach Chris Bean kept him lean.
</P>
<P>
   Still, waking up extra early and working out under the hot South
Florida sun on Tuesday wasn't easy for Rumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running agility drills kill you first thing in the morning,''
Rumph said.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like a dream being on the field today,'' Rumph
said. JOSEPH WANTS TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Carlo Joseph, who applied for the NFL Draft in April but was not
selected, has appealed to the NCAA to have his eligibility
restored.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph started eight games at fullback last season as a junior,
but decided to skip his senior season to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph's appeal is unlikely to be granted by the NCAA because
the Pompano Beach native signed with an agent following the 1997
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a longshot,'' Davis said about the possibility of Joseph
returning to the UM squad. ``But it's an option Carlo should
explore.'' MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   Davis says he has ``no idea'' whether back-up quarterback Steve
Kelly will report with the rest of the varsity today. Several UM
sources say Kelly will remain home in Texas. ``We certainly would
like to encourage him to come back, but this football program is
moving forward,'' Davis said...Matt Walters, a freshman defensive
lineman from Melbourne, will miss 2-3 weeks because of a broken
left foot sustained in the Florida-Georgia high school game earlier
this summer...Linebacker Dan Morgan is one of 68 players selected
as Butkus Award nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
