<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS EARN CHORUS OF BOOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers were talking about the meltdown, not
the comeback.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-August, scoring five runs in the ninth doesn't matter.
Losing 8-6 to the last-place Florida Marlins on Tuesday afternoon
did.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter how many ex-Marlins are in the Dodgers'
lineup. None of them are hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that the Dodgers have a $61 million payroll and that the
stripped-down Marlins' is $6 million. The only reason the Dodgers
were in a position to win at the end was Florida's bullpen walked
six batters, including three with the bases loaded that forced in
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We badly need an eight- or nine-game winning streak to take a
run at this thing,'' said Bobby Bonilla, knowing his new team
hasn't won three straight in three weeks and has done it only twice
in three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' pitching allowed a season-high 17 hits to the
second-worst hitting team in the National League. Until the eighth,
no Dodgers runner had reached third base against the league's
second-worst pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the Dodgers are now only a game over .500. A much
kinder judge of their season, the National League wild-card race,
has them five games from the final playoff spot with 43 games left.
But the harshest critics were the fans, who hopped on every Dodgers
misstep with loud booing.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 35,270 represented the amount of tickets sold, but
was it about 12,000 more than the actual attendance Tuesday. The
fans know that, since salvaging a split nine days ago with the Mets
at Shea Stadium, the Dodgers have gone 2-5 against teams that have
lost 69 games more than they have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone is happy with the way we've been playing the last
seven games, they're an idiot,'' said Eric Karros, who lined out
with the bases loaded to end the game. ``Were not hitting, we're
not pitching. Our 3-4-5 hitters aren't doing anything. We're
getting beat by guys we have no right losing to.''
</P>
<P>
   Since blowing a four-run lead in the eighth inning to Montreal a
week ago, the Dodgers have lost to a ``Who's Who'' of Carl Pavano,
Jay Powell and Chris Peters. Tuesday, rookie left-hander Jesus
Sanchez (6-6) joined the gang, limiting the Dodgers to five hits
and no runs in 61/3 innings. That makes it three rookies and one
second-year pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first loss against Montreal, No.3 hitter Raul Mondesi
is 3 for 18 with two RBI. Cleanup hitter Gary Sheffield is 2 for 15
with one RBI. Karros is 5 for 25 with two RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Mondesi missed two games with a sore lower back and
Sheffield was suspended for three games. But they still have not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers' pitching also has struggled. Darren Dreifort
(6-11), who has one victory since June 30, allowed 11 hits and five
runs in five innings. He gave way to Darren Hall, who immediately
gave up a home run to Todd Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   Dunwoody was the scourge of the Dodgers all day, adding a double
and two-run single. And there were others. Derrick Lee had a
two-run double in the eighth that made it 8-0. But Lee's most
memorable at-bat came in the third, when his bloop single to left
dropped in front of Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   A tender left Achilles tendon limits Bonilla's mobility, but the
play looked bad and the fans let him have it. When Bonilla failed
to come up with Greg Zaun's double into the corner during Florida's
three-run fourth, the boos just kept on coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
