<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Dolphins' reality check: Jaguars, Bucs
 &HT;    By GREG STODA
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A few S(t)oda crackers to snack on as
summer's dog days reach full yelp:
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated, in its pro football preview issue, picks
Jacksonville over Tampa Bay in Super Bowl XXXIII in Pro Player
Stadium. How would that scenario, if it plays out, stand as the
ultimate insult to the Dolphins?
</P>
<P>
   Don't know who's going to be named 1998's Female Athlete of the
Year. But the winner among the guys is Jeff Gordon, and the
checkered flag has fallen on that race.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that's out of whack in the link between television
money and sports is demonstrated, now and forever, by the reported
$600 million proposal from Disney (read: ABC and ESPN) for NHL
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the ragamuffin United States hoops team did no better than
a bronze medal in the World Championships. But, even if you weren't
paying close attention, weren't you secretly pulling harder for
those CBAers and European Leaguers than you ever did for the Dream
Teamers?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin gets into a fight with Everett McIver, allegedly
cuts him on the neck with a pair of scissors and then _ facing a
possible prison sentence if discovered to have violated terms of
probation stemming from a no-contest plea to felony cocaine
possession in 1996 _ reaches a financial agreement with McIver,
reportedly brokered by Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, to buy
silence. That's called hush money, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour. Union. Spare me.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter what those silly tennis rankings indicate on
any given weekly flip-flop. Marcelo Rios is not the No. 1 men's
player in the world. That would be Pete Sampras, who will prove the
point _ again _ next month at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   There's a simple formula for computing the probability that Jim
Leyland will not manage the Florida Marlins next season. Take the
number of Marlins losses, and put a percentage sign behind it. By
the end of the year, Leyland should be, oh, 103 percent gone.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali's recent short-term involvement with the
magnetic-wave machine for regeneration of nerve cells as an
experimental treatment for his Parkinson's disease seemed sadly
desperate and desperately sad.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr., through games
played Monday night, had combined for 133 home runs ... and 313
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a state of conFusion. What's the big deal with this
Valderrama guy?
</P>
<P>
   The guess is that Florida State, Florida and Miami will lose six
regular-season games as a group. Do your own applications. And
nobody among the Seminoles, Gators and Hurricanes has the best
college quarterback in the state. Not even close. The rumor mill
has 6-4, 240-pound Central Florida senior Daunte Culpepper as a
possible No. 1 _ that's overall _ pick in the next NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs in cycling. Drugs in swimming. Drugs everywhere. It's not
competition, anymore. It's pharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter how careful the coaches are. These long high
school practices in the sweltering heat of South Florida's
summertime scare me.
</P>
<P>
   A basic question concerning the capital-H Heat, if the NBA
actually gets around to playing a 1998-99 schedule: Are they on the
way up or down?
</P>
<P>
   This rivalry, finally, between Coronado's Quest and Victory
Gallop _ Haskell Invitational and, soon, Travers Stakes _ sure
makes you wish they had hooked up in the Triple Crown gigs.
</P>
<P>
   About those Marlins ... there's no truth to the rumor the
franchise plans to scrap the nickname because it can't afford the
bill(fish).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
