<HEADLINE>
JUDGE LETS STRIP CLUB REOPEN, WITH DANCERS WEARING BIKINIS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx strip club that was one of the first closed
under the city's new zoning law can reopen, a state judge ruled
Tuesday after the club's owners promised that they would clothe
their dancers in bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which came over protests from city lawyers,
suggested that if strip clubs become go-go bars _ clubs that
feature scantily clad, but not nude, dancers _ they may be able to
operate in New York under the Giuliani administration's new
anti-sex shop measure.
</P>
<P>
   Although lawyers for the city predicted that the owners of the
Bronx club, El Coche, were likely to lapse into nude dancing,
Justice Douglas McKeon said they should be given a chance to
operate under strict new guidelines. ``They are entitled to an
opportunity to comply,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   While approving the reopening of the club, McKeon made it clear
that the new law would be strictly enforced. The judge, who said he
might visit the bar to check on compliance, warned that violations
of the ground rules established in court Tuesday would not be
tolerated. He ordered the club's owner, Jobo Salazar, to post a
$50,000 bond and face potential jail time and fines if any of the
ground rules were broken.
</P>
<P>
   In a six-point proposal submitted by Solomon Kaplan, the club's
lawyer, the club agreed that all dancers would wear bikini bottoms
and tops at all times. Customers would be barred from touching
dancers and performers would be prohibited from simulating sexual
acts.
</P>
<P>
   The club also pledged to hire security personnel to separate
dancers from customers, who would be required to place any cash
tips in a basket to prevent them from touching the women.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the above conditions are violated, the judge warned,
Salazar would be held in contempt of court and face arrest.
Violations could lead to fines of up to $50,000 and result in the
permanent shutdown of the club, McKeon said. Despite the
conditions, El Coche's lawyer called the ruling a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said that Salazar was trying to post the $50,000 bond
and hoped to reopen the bar in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on it right now,'' Solomon said. ``They're very
happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
