<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FALL, NEED LIFT FROM GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Ken Griffey Jr.'s single into left field Tuesday night
came too late to do the Mariners much good. But hitting coach Jesse
Barfield senses the end of an August drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting that knock will help and it's just a matter of time
before he breaks out,'' said Barfield of the Mariner center
fielder. ``You can keep him down for a few days, but not much
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who sizzled in July (.351 with eight homers and 21
RBIs), went 1-for-4 in the Mariners' 7-4 loss to the Toronto Blue
Jays in front of 33,137 fans at SkyDome. The loss, ending Seattle's
four-game winning streak, went to starter Jeff Fassero. He carried
a 2-1 lead into the seventh inning, compliments of solo homers by
John Marzano in the second inning and Jay Buhner in the fourth, but
the Blue Jays took advantage of a questionable call by plate umpire
Joe Brinkman to score six runs in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey still leads the American League in home runs with 41,
but he hasn't hit one in 10 games this month. In fact, he hasn't
been getting many hits of any kind _ 8-for-37 with five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been overanxious,'' said Barfield.
</P>
<P>
   That was demonstrated again in the first inning when Griffey
came to bat against Blue Jay starter Chris Carpenter with two on
and none out. Carpenter struck out Griffey, retired Edgar Martinez
on a line drive to third baseman Tony Fernandez and then got David
Segui to hit a routine fly to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make good pitches on him (Griffey) and I
did,'' Carpenter said. ``I got lucky with the line drive Edgar hit
to Tony and was able to work myself out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, working on three days' rest, pitched his usual game
against the Blue Jays ... until the fifth inning, when Toronto
sliced a two-run deficit in half. Sammy Stewart doubled over
Griffey's head in center field, scoring Craig Grebeck, who had led
off with the second of his three singles. Fassero, 3-0 with a 0.75
ERA in three previous career starts against Toronto, didn't survive
the seventh inn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
