<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SAYS BURGLAR SOUGHT ITS ICON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Queens detectives dusted for fingerprints Tuesday
around the altar of St. Irene Chrysovalantou Greek Orthodox
Cathedral in Astoria, where church officials said they were once
again the victims of an attempt to steal their most precious
treasure: the icon of St. Irene that, the faithful maintain, wept
on the eve of the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the icon was left safe in its case to the
left of the altar, and the burglar was apparently frightened off by
an alarm system the church installed after its last brush with
crime in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, church officials said, a group of armed bandits
took the icon, only to return it five days later in the mail,
intact but without frame heavy with gold and jewels.
</P>
<P>
   It was a case that ultimately widened a rift between rival
factions of the Greek Orthodox Church. There were accusations that
the theft was a hoax, and a lawsuit filed as a result of those
accusations was only recently resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's scenario was all too familiar to worshipers. ``You
mean they tried to steal it again?'' asked Joseph Perez, a
cafeteria worker who said he often prayed before the icon. ``It's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Vikentios of Avlon, the spiritual leader of St. Irene's,
said he was called shortly after midnight Tuesday by a nun who
heard the church alarm. The burglar apparently entered from the
roof, shattering a window 30 feet above the altar and lowering a
rope, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The burglar was apparently cut by the glass, the police said,
since there was a trail of blood.
</P>
<P>
   The church had just finished a four-day celebration of the feast
of St. Irene, during which the icon was carried through the
neighboring streets in a solemn procession. Bishop Vikentios
speculated that the icon _ which is always bedecked by gold
watches, diamond rings, pearl necklaces and other valuables left by
supplicants _ may have attracted the attention of the burglar then.
``It's the treasure of the church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After worshipers reported that the icon started weeping just
before the Persian Gulf war _ St. Irene had lived in the ninth
century in what is now Turkey _ thousands of people started going
each day to the small but ornate church.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Christmas neared that year, church officials announced that
bandits who were masked and armed had invaded the church and taken
the icon.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the robbery deepened the break between St. Irene
Chrysovalantou _ the headquarters church of a dissident group
within the Greek Orthodox Church _ and the Greek Orthodox
Archdiocese of North and South America. The two groups were divided
by 13 days, the difference between the Julian calendar used by St.
Irene and the 30,000 members of the Old Calendrist group, and the
Gregorian calendar followed since 1924 by the 1.5 million members
of Greek Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese cast doubt on the
icon's weeping and suggested that its theft and recovery were
hoaxes. Officials at St. Irene's responded with a $30 million libel
suit against the archdiocese and two local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But after the dispute, there was a rapprochement. After
Archbishop Spyridon was appointed leader of the Greek Orthodox
Archdiocese of North and South America, he opened discussions with
Old Calendrist churches, and in April the Old Calendrists were
welcomed back into the mother church, as both sides agreed to
disagree on which calendar to use.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Archbishop Spyridon attended some of the festivities
over the weekend for the feast of St. Irene, and Tuesday afternoon
he visited the church and surveyed the bloodstains and the
shattered case of the icon of the Virgin. This time there were
words of consolation, not consternation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a lack of respect for the religious beliefs of
others,'' Archbishop Spyridon said as he stood by the icons. ``I
can only hope that this will not be repeated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
