<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS KNOW THE SCORE AFTER BEATING ST. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Whether he lets on or not, Manager Bobby Valentine
is obviously keeping close track of where his Mets stand in the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked through the tunnel to the Busch Stadium field while
the Mets took batting practice Tuesday afternoon, Valentine could
be overheard updating himself after he had watched the end of the
Chicago Cubs' 8-7 loss in San Francisco. All even in the standing,
two up in the loss column, was the gist of what he was saying.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bobby Jones went out and led the Mets to an 8-3 victory
over the St. Louis Cardinals with his arm and bat Tuesday night.
That leapfrogged the Mets (64-53) over the Cubs (65-55) and pulled
New York into the NL wild-card lead for the first time since June
1.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the two Mets who seemed most interested in the
Cubs' game were Valentine and Jones. And even though Jones (8-7)
surrendered a mammoth home run to Mark McGwire _ the St. Louis
slugger's major-league leading 47th _ he limited the Cardinals to 3
runs and 8 hits in 7 innings, and drove in the game's first two
runs with a second-inning double. It was Jones' first victory in
more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the Mets' 16th in their last 23 games and pulled
them a season-high 11 games over .500 for the fourth time this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had not won since July 2, a span of six starts. But if the
28-year-old right-hander felt any pressure knowing that he had the
chance to help the Mets overtake the Cubs, it did not show.
</P>
<P>
   Jone allowed three bases-empty homers, but only McGwire hit him
hard with any consistency. McGwire rifled a vicious one-hop double
off third baseman Edgardo Alfonzo's glove in the first inning, hit
a 464-foot homer in the fourth, hit a fly out to the warning track
just right of center in the sixth and, for the second consecutive
night, was struck out by Turk Wendell in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's homer came with the Mets already up, 4-0, thanks to
their second-inning outburst, which was keyed by Jones' two-out hit
of Kent Mercker (8-9) after an intentional walk to Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' eighth hit in 33 at-bats this season doubled his runs
batted in total to 4. It was not cheap either. Jones drove
Mercker's first pitch past the outstretched glove of Willie McGee
in the left-center field gap to score Brian McRae and Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   McRae had doubled to open the inning, before Todd Hundley and
Luis Lopez struck out. After Jones' double, Jermanine Allensworth,
playing his first game for the Mets a day after being acquired from
Kansas City, singled the pitcher home, then took second on an error
by McGee.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo followed with a single to score Allensworth. And
Jones had a four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire homered to make it 4-1, McGee drilled a one-out
double in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones stranded him and did the same to Ray Lankford after a
two-out double in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied for runs in the fifth and the seventh to give
their starter a cushion. Mike Piazza drove in one with a
fifth-inning sacrifice fly, following a lead-off double by Alfonzo
and a single by John Olerud. Hundley, who struck out three times
batting right-handed against Mercker, singled home the other run
batting left-handed against Mark Petkovsek to give the Mets a 6-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Those runs came in handy in the Cardinal seventh because Jones
allowed homers _ one batter apart _ to Fernando Tatis and
pinch-hitter Tom Lampkin, as the home team closed to within, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets came right back with 2 runs in the eighth. And for
the first time in more than two months, they left a ball park in
the lead for the fourth post-season spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
