<SLUG> BC-NY-BATTERY-PARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE EXAMINING EXPENSES OF OFFICIAL OF BATTERY PARK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ State investigators disclosed Tuesday that they were
looking into allegations that the top executive of the mammoth
Battery Park City complex improperly used his expense account to
pay for a private trip to California and for hotel stays in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry, by the state inspector general's office, also
concerns $18,000 in raises that the executive, John LaMura, awarded
to his chief administrative aide without approval from the
three-member Battery Park City Authority, which oversees the
development of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and former employees of the residential and
commercial complex in lower Manhattan said that the inquiry had
brought into the open and intensified rising friction between
LaMura, the authority's president and chief executive, and James
Gill, chairman of the authority's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friction is an understatement,'' Martin Begun, a director,
said Tuesday. ``It's gotten hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement issued Tuesday, LaMura called the charges
false. Investigators and former employees said that LaMura had
privately blamed Gill, an influential lawyer and adviser to Gov.
George Pataki and other Republican officials, for igniting the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the investigation and the dispute between LaMura and
Gill are future policy decisions on developing the 92-acre site,
which includes luxury and middle-income housing for 7,600 residents
and office space for more than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching from the northern tip of Battery Park to Canal Street
along the Hudson River, the uncompleted complex includes a yacht
basin, a 1.2-mile park esplanade, the Mercantile Exchange, the
World Financial Center, Stuyvesant High School and the Holocaust
Memorial and Museum of Jewish Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   LaMura and Gill did not return telephone calls Tuesday to their
offices for comment concerning their disagreements. But in separate
written statements, both men alluded to their feud. ``In any
organization as large, active and complex as Battery Park City,''
Gill said, ``one of the main challenges is not to let differences
that typically arise interfere with objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the allegations that led to the investigation, Gill
said that they were brought to his attention by an employee and
that he passed the complaint along ``to the appropriate people.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMura, a Republican and the former supervisor of the Long
Island town of Brookhaven, was recommended for his $129,837-a-year
job by Pataki and was appointed to head the agency in October 1996
by Gill and two other members of the authority's board.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, a Democrat, was placed on the board in 1995 by Pataki
after he had supported Pataki's election bid and the re-election of
another Republican, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, LaMura said, ``False allegations of a personal
nature, are, unfortunately, a risk of being part of the public
sector.''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed confidence that he would be cleared of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Adler, LaMura's lawyer, said ``personality differences''
had developed between his client and Gill. Adler insisted that
LaMura had the discretionary authority to grant raises and that
``his expense account expenditures were within the correct
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints against LaMura focus on a trip he took to San
Francisco, several overnight hotel stays in New York City and
raises he gave this year to his executive assistant, Alice Kent,
that pushed her salary to $59,000 from $41,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Del Giacco, a spokesman for Roslynn Mauskopf, the
state's inspector general, said Tuesday that ``an investigation of
these matters is under way.'' He declined to provide details on the
amount of expense account payments in question.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators who spoke on the condition of anonymity said that,
at most, the expenditures amounted to several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Begun, an authority director for the last seven years, said that
the board had not been informed of Ms. Kent's raises, which he
described as excessive. The board, he added, did not review expense
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kent did not return telephone messages left for her Tuesday
at her office. But investigators said she had told them the salary
increases were justified since she was filling two jobs: executive
assistant to LaMura and the agency's assistant director of special
events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
