<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-APPLEBY-HNS &LR;      08-12 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-APPLEBY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Appleby determined 
to revive life, career 
after death of his wife
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Stuart Appleby came to the 1998 PGA Championship at Sahalee Country
Club to heal, not to win.
</P>
<P>
   He came seeking the companionship of his fellow touring pros,
the quiet solitude of the golf course and the normalcy that comes
from doing something you have done a thousand times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to take little steps at a time, trying to fit
my life back to where I was,'' he said Tuesday. ``Here I am. Here's
Stuart Appleby. Basically, I'm the same guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But also forever changed.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Appleby's wife, Renay, died from injuries she
suffered in a freak traffic accident at Waterloo Station in London.
Renay was 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of tough to decide on whether I was going to come
back, and how quickly,'' Appleby, 27, said. ``I wanted to come
back. I was drawing a lot of positives out of coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's just a million little things that I'll miss. So
many small, little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm walking around the course _ I see no one. She's not
there walking, not helping me when I need help. Simple, simple,
simple things. It's not the big things. It's all the little things,
and they all add up. They make someone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   The day that Appleby's life changed started out with such
promise. It was July 23, just after the British Open, and the
Applebys were headed on a vacation. They pulled up at Waterloo
Station in London in a cab and were unloading their luggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two parked cars, separated apart, and we were sort
of double-parked next to another car,'' Appleby said. ``We were
getting luggage out. I was just finishing getting the last items
out of the car and paying the cab when the driver, which was sort
of opposite us, parked in the parking lane, reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of felt as though Renay was near me. You know you have
the presence and feeling of someone's near you. And then the car
backed up and hit her, and I turned to see the car still reversing.
Then immediately the car stopped when it hit the other car.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed seemed almost unreal to Appleby. He and another
man tried to do CPR and heart massages while waiting for the
ambulance, but through it all Appleby said he remained calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not that scary at the time,'' he said. ``I didn't feel
very upset. I knew it was a very serious situation, but I felt like
I had it under control. It was just weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see these things on TV. It didn't seem real. Then the
ambulance came, and we went to the hospital. And I knew this was
not a simple thing. I knew it was very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Renay died shortly after arriving at the hospital. The funeral
was July 31 in the couple's native Australia, and Appleby was left
trying to pick up the pieces of his life and his career.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby was having a solid year on the PGA Tour. He had won the
Kemper Open this season and was No. 26 on the money list with
$678,562. Appleby was regarded as one of the up-and-coming young
foreigners in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby maintains he hasn't lost his passion for the game, but
it is now only that. A game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to look at it from what would Renay really like
me to do,'' Appleby said. ``What would she want me to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved being with me on the road. She would want me to get
back on, like falling off your bike, and get back on with the right
frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't forget someone like Renay, someone who means so
much to you. She's going to steer me in the right direction. And
that's what I've got to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tournament and I'm going to take it, each round,
each day, for the moment. Days are more important than scores, more
important than anything. This is bigger than any good or bad round
I can have.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it put some perspective back in what I'm trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said the support he has received from his fellow touring
pros and the golf community has been amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Recent winners Billy Mayfair and Nick Price dedicated their
victories to Renay. Other players have made a point of talking with
Appleby and offering to help in any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   The fans have also responded, sending flowers, cards, faxes and
e-mails by the thousands to Appleby, who was overwhelmed by the
outpouring at Renay's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows some of the toughest moments have yet to come. He
hasn't returned to the Florida home where the couple lived for much
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another one of the steps I have to take,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting through this week's PGA Championship is another. And
Appleby is counting on the one person who was always there for him
to see him through this time as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to talk about the person like they're still
there,'' Appleby said. ``You never have to fear to mention their
name. You laugh about things and the jokes that you might have told
them. You just feel as though that person is still there. You don't
feel as though that person is gone. Physically, yes, she's never
going to be there again. But mentally she'll always be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to imagine that she's here and she's helping me
and everything will be OK. She's going to help me. It will just
take patience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
