<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS, A FIRST-CLASS PLAYER, FLIES COACH THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Winston Moss has been called a lot of things in
his NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Tenacious. Intense; even dirty. A leader. A leading tackler. A
role model. But coach? That's one he wasn't expecting, and
definitely not this early in his life.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is at the Seahawks' training camp, helping coach the
position he was playing just eight months ago. Moss, 32, is a
volunteer assistant. He has the title of defensive quality control
coach, but his job is to help new assistant coach Jim Johnson work
with what is the best collection of linebackers in club history.
</P>
<P>
   Moss would rather be one of them. Instead, he is working with
all of them because he was forced to retire after fracturing a
vertebra in his neck last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I wish I could still play. I still wish I could get
out and hit some guys and cause some problems and have some fun,''
Moss said Tuesday. ``But that's not in the works anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching occasionally crossed Moss' mind during the 10 weeks he
spent in a halo brace so his neck could mend, but the thought never
lingered that long. He was too busy coping with the present to deal
much with the future.
</P>
<P>
   If it is difficult for Moss to adjust, think about those players
who were his teammates a year ago but are now playing for coach
Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of tough to say coach Moss,'' offered linebacker
Chad Brown, who still calls his coach Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Moss doesn't have this job just because he's a former player
whose career was ended by an injury. Or because he played for
Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson at the University of Miami. Or
because he has a glare that can melt face masks.
</P>
<P>
   Moss was hired out of respect and because of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston is a high-character individual who I've always had a
lot of respect for and the players have a lot of respect for,''
said Johnson, who joined the Seahawks in February after being the
defensive coordinator in Indianapolis the past two seasons. ``It's
working out really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss isn't just window dressing either. He is coaching. In the
meetings and on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him, `Hey, if you see something, go coach him up,'''
Johnson said. ``If he was a guy off the street it would be
different. But I've got a lot of respect for Winston.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is glad Moss is still around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston has taken some of the burden off the older guys by
coaching the younger guys. He's in their ear so we don't have to
be,'' Brown said. ``I guess he's kind of their guardian angel. It's
kind of cool for me because now I don't have to worry about telling
this guy to do that and make sure he's in the huddle and all those
little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss' prot &UR; gfacute &LR; eg &UR; gfacute &LR; es are first-round draft choice
Anthony Simmons and fourth-round pick DeShone Myles. The talented
rookies are ``Winston's draft choices,'' as Brown puts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston is playing the game with them in practice,'' Brown
said. ``He's shuffling along the line with them. He throws his hat
down when one of them makes a mistake. I think it shows he probably
misses the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no probably about it. Moss had played 11 seasons _ the
past three with the Seahawks after spending four each with the Los
Angeles Raiders (1991-94) and Tampa Bay Buccaneers (1987-90).
Productive seasons. Fulfilling seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the neck injury did not allow him to walk away from the game
on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real disappointing thing. I didn't get a chance to
know when my last ball game was,'' he said. ``Every once in a while
I think about being able to have that luxury of knowing the last
time I'm going to play in Denver or the last time I'm going to play
in Oakland. That's special. Not to have that is obviously
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking away from the game is what his wife, Zoila, anticipated
Moss doing _ and at times is probably wishing he had done since she
is expecting their third child in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd rather have me home,'' Moss said. ``But she understood
that this is something I love to do and enjoy immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss' wife also understands this is another chance for her
husband to achieve the one thing that was missing from his playing
career: The Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get to the Super Bowl and win that,'' Moss said, ``it
will be able to erase those disappointments. Winning solves all
those little headache and heartaches and all aches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
