<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHED NO TEARS FOR KINGDOME'S PENDING DOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ So, the finger is on the trigger. The trigger finger
is itchy.
</P>
<P>
   That's the news from the Kingdome, where the Mariners have
actually set a date for their last game at the ol' concrete cavern.
</P>
<P>
   On June 27, 1999, the M's will bid farewell to the Kingdome _
the nine acres of architectural blunder that has nobly served the
Seattle sporting public for the past 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Next July 15, the M's will celebrate Opening Day II in their new
stadium, making obsolete the summer home of major league baseball
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me. Isn't this weather fantastic?
</P>
<P>
   Aren't these just the sort of humidity-free, the
bluest-skies-you've-ever-seen-are-in-Seattle days that make you
salivate for the return of outdoor baseball, Randy Johnson or no
Randy Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   The countdown has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after the 1999 NFL season ends, after the Seahawks play
their Kingdome finale, the sticks of dynamite will be carefully
arranged, the plunger so indelicately pushed and, KABOOM!
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear Mariner announcer Rick Rizzs making the
call: And it's goodbye, Kingdome!
</P>
<P>
   There is only one thing to worry about _ those seismic studies
commissioned by former Seahawks owner Ken Behring. We're talking
major red herring, because if the tectonic plates under Pioneer
Square are as San Andreas-shaky as Mr. Behring's experts
proclaimed, then our little Kingdome implosion event might set off
one pesky quake.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck, right? Seattleites pride themselves on
fearing no temblor, so the new millenium will be inaugurated with
the explosion to end all explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Mount St. Helens went up in a violent blur of volcanic
ash will the Puget Sound experience such a landscape-altering
blast.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes you wonder:
</P>
<P>
   As the Kingdome implosion draws near, isn't it about time we
started identifying other annoying, obsolete or nefarious items
that should be in the Kingdome the day the dynamite blows it to
smithereens?
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, have gone to the trouble of starting just such a
list, entitled:
</P>
<P>
   Things to put in Kingdome on Demolition Day.
</P>
<P>
   1) Planet Hollywood, because if we wanted Southern California,
we would have moved to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   2) The KeyArena sign, because that retina-jarring red neon makes
lower Queen Anne look like Aurora Avenue on a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   3) NikeTown, just because.
</P>
<P>
   4) The city of Seattle Animal Control Department, which takes
oppression to a new level. Ever heard of the phrase ``police
state?''
</P>
<P>
   5) The Astro-turf at Memorial Stadium, for making Sounders
soccer more like human pinball.
</P>
<P>
   6) The Miss Bud.
</P>
<P>
   7) The Duck. Have you seen this oversized amphibious tourist
trap now hogging up the roadways through Pioneer Square, Fremont
and other points of Emerald City interest?
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't experienced the Duck yet, you're lucky. If you
have, you know what I mean. The obnoxious disco music. The drivers
who must be trained at the Richard Simmons school of aerobic
roadsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   The Duck is like the ``It's a Small World'' ride at Disneyland
on hallucinogenics.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, regardless of what gets blown up with the
Kingdome, the Kingdome must go. It's all in the name of progress.
</P>
<P>
   For proof that modernizing our local sports stadia is the right
thing to do, all one has to do is look up at the new baseball
stadium, whose entire frame now stands just south of the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that many concerned citizens are outraged at the $500
million pricetag for this new baseball-only ballpark, especially
since Mariner ownership has made it look as if Mr. Magoo could do a
better job with baseball decisions and Mariner public relations.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy. Randy. Randy.)
</P>
<P>
   But, frankly, as a visitor to our fair city recently commented
as we walked south along Myrtle Edwards Park, gazing up at the
downtown Seattle skyline, the new baseball park is humanly scaled.
It looks good. It fits in rather than overwhelms the majestic
Seattle skyline.
</P>
<P>
   The closer to completion Safeco Field becomes, the bigger and
more obtrusive the Kingdome looks by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   And so to be irrevocably rooted to the Kingdome is like being
rooted in cement. Which is why I hope no one is experiencing any
pangs of remorse.
</P>
<P>
   This is no time for bouts of sentimentality. Our collective
urban will must remain strong, even as the timetable is established
and farewell parties are being planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome's final days are at hand. Change is on the horizon,
literally, which is a good sign for a city as worldly, as
progressive, as cultured and as caffeinated as Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
