<SLUG> BC-NY-HORSES-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 STOLEN HORSES RECOVERED, MAN CHARGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tex, Jack and Sheppard's Go Boy were safely back in
their Pelham Bay Park horse stables Tuesday, their would-be rustler
cooling his boots in a Bronx jail.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Dennis Grimes, 39, a part-time stable hand from New
Jersey, was taken into custody Tuesday after he walked into the
45th Precinct station house for questioning. He was charged with
sneaking into the Pelham Bit Stables last Tuesday, hot-wiring a
truck, then driving the horses to New Jersey to be auctioned. The
charges include burglary, grand larceny and criminal possession of
stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Grimes had expected to get $1,500 to $2,500 apiece
for the horses, which had been left on consignment at Camelot
Auction Co. in Cranbury, N.J., about 50 miles from New York. But
the scheme began to unravel after the stable's owner, in an effort
to track down the horses, called the auction house on Friday and
said the horses were missing.
</P>
<P>
   As Grimes was led from the precinct house for booking Tuesday,
he denied being a horse thief. ``No, I'm a horse trader,'' he
yelled. Police said Grimes had told them that he bought the horses
in a Newark junk yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I don't know what goes on around Newark,'' Jim Martyn,
owner of Pelham Bit Stables, said, ``I would think that a sale like
that would be pretty rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Martyn was less equivocal about what should happen to the man,
or his possible accomplices, if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be hanged,'' he said dryly, before wondering aloud
whether someone could easily dig up an old statute on the subject.
``When you steal a horse,'' he said, ``it's more than a monetary
thing. It's taking a part of the family. It's like a dog that the
kids fall in love with. What's the attachment value of the family
dog?''
</P>
<P>
   Martyn's 1998 Dodge Ram pickup truck and his eight-horse trailer
were found in a field in Elizabeth, N.J., shortly after Grimes'
arrest, Sgt. William Larkin said. He said more arrests were
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse community is tight-knit and well-networked,'' he
said. ``People know each other and their horses.'' He also said
Grimes had been employed as a part-time horse exerciser and stable
mucker at the auction company ever since he was a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Tex, Jack and Sheppard's Go Boy spent Tuesday recuperating in
their stalls after a long trip that left them with a few nicks and
scratches, and in need of a cool trough of water, Martyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack, a 7-year-old quarter horse, prepared for a trot, though he
remained ``a bit shy'' after his abduction, his owner, John
Sikoryak, said. ``He got a nice bath and we put his feet back
together,'' he said, ``and he's all right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were frantic because we didn't know if someone was
sacrificing him to some voodoo god or abusing him,'' Sikoryak
added, noting that they also worried that Jack could have turned up
as dog food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy he's back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
