<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES: STRAIGHT, NO CHASER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Already it seems like the PGA Championship has
been here for a millennium or three. Yet the tournament doesn't
start until Thursday. The visiting golfers continue to be amazed
and annoyed that the amount of newsprint consumed to cover this
thing still has not threatened a single tree on the blasted Sahalee
course.
</P>
<P>
   So far the most entertaining thing to happen in Redmond _ other
than the delivery of another boxcar-load of beauty bark for a
course-side home _ was the pre-tournament interview given by Fred
Couples Tuesday at the media tent.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as much an interview as a thrill ride: Freddy's
Loop-de-Loop. The more he talks, the more he goes in circles.
Veteran golf writers are long used to Couples' meandering,
contradictory thoughts, but he's such an endearing and popular
figure that it remains a treat to take the Loop-de-Loop.
</P>
<P>
   Part Yogi Berra, part Randy Johnson, part Prof. Irwin Corey,
Couples' ride is harmless, except for the occasions when he bumps
into himself coming around his own quotes.
</P>
<P>
   A few examples from Tuesday, all given straight, no chaser:
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the distractions in playing before the hometown
crowd eager for him to win:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much distractions. It's just the people screaming
and yelling at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his sometimes-troublesome back, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a few pills and roll around on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, describing further the therapy regimen:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-hour workout.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he will play this tournament differently, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This course is in my hometown, so it's a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I can't go out there and play differently than I normally
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his chances to win, he said, ``I wish I was ready to play
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. As you can tell, Freddy's ride is worth an old Disneyland
E-ticket, although the whiplash can leave a sore neck.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean, however, that Couples isn't capable of a
little reflection on his own thoughts. Explaining what he thinks it
will take to win the championship, he said, ``Your patient guys
that are playing very well are going to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's about as dumb as something you can say.''
</P>
<P>
   But who hasn't spoken the obvious here this week? I mean, the
tourney hasn't started and if I hear one more golfer say, ``You
have to stay out of the trees,'' I will plunge multiple fingers
down my throat.
</P>
<P>
   Couples is nowhere close to dumb. But he is so eager to please
this week, so earnest in his unofficial appointment as Northwest
golf ambassador, he is saying the same things so many times to so
many people that his desire to do everything right overtakes his
oral throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Couples appears to be approaching a bit of a life
crossroads that seems to be creating some fresh questions about his
eventual routing.
</P>
<P>
   His engagement in June to Thais Bren of Los Angeles, the mother
of two youngsters Couples adores, has created a serenity that his
friends and associates rarely have seen in him. Perhaps for the
first time, and especially since the death of his parents over the
past four years, Couples is looking forward to something besides
golf.
</P>
<P>
   On the straight parts of the Loop-de-Loop, Couples mentioned
several times that despite his overall success this year _ two tour
victories and a No. 3 ranking in prize money at $1.5 million _ his
enthusiasm for the full-time grind has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have the motivation to go out there and
practice for a full year,'' he said, explaining how his fast start
has faded into a combined 37-over-par in the U.S. and British
opens. ``I kind of relaxed (recently). I'm to the point where I
don't have the energy to do this all year round. To have your last
three tournaments in a two-month period be the three majors is not
really the brightest thing. You don't want to lay back, but on the
other hand you get tired of it. And I just got tired of worrying
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who know Couples think that while, at 38, he has many years
remaining of quality golf, he's also had one marriage and one
serious relationship go bad. Combine that with a quarrelsome back
and 17 years of the same relentless schtick, and it is not
surprising that Couples might be on the threshold of something
different.
</P>
<P>
   Said one friend who followed Couples Tuesday during his practice
round: ``His first two relationships were like midnight in an
Alaskan winter compared to Thais, who is like the weather today.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the round, Couples' foursome was followed on the
fairways by Thais' 5-year-old, Oliver, who seemed to completely
occupy the grateful attentions of a state trooper and county deputy
sheriff assigned to the party. Couples periodically stopped to play
with him, as well as chat up the affectionate gallery and sign as
many autographs along the way as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss fairly raged from the scene. It was obvious that Couples
can entertain in more ways than the Loop-de-Loop.
</P>
<P>
   Older women want to mother him.
</P>
<P>
   Younger women want to marry him.
</P>
<P>
   Men feel unthreatened by him.
</P>
<P>
   Kids identify with him.
</P>
<P>
   Last month at the British Open, a Scottish couple began talking
with two Americans at a hotel in Southport. They spent part of
their summer vacations in each of the past 22 years attending the
Open. Without knowing the hometown of their fellow travelers, they
offered up unprompted that their favorite golfer was Couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think he's wonderful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some things reach beyond explanation. Especially if Couples has
to do the explaining.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
