<HEADLINE>
CIVIC LEADERS URGE BETTER SITE FOR MILLION YOUTH MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of Harlem community leaders, concerned about
the possibility of violent clashes with police, urged city
officials and organizers of the planned Million Youth March Tuesday
to keep open the prospect of having the event in Harlem but at a
site other than Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Paterson, D-Harlem, and other community leaders
said they were convinced that organizers of the march were going to
go forward on Sept. 5 even though the city has denied them a
permit, and were seeking a pragmatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders reiterated their opposition to or reservations about
the march's primary organizer, Khalid Abdul Muhammad, but said that
the best course now was to try to minimize the potential for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that this is an event that's going to
happen,'' said Michael Demarzo, a spokesman for the Manhattan
borough president, C. Virginia Fields, who has called Muhammad a
bigot and who issued a statement Tuesday urging the city and
organizers to hold the event in a park, not the streets of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supporting or condemning Khalid Muhammad is ceasing to be the
issue,'' he said, adding that the focus now should be on ``managing
the event in a way that protects the community and is respectful of
people in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad was dismissed by the Nation of Islam as its spokesman
in 1994 after a 1993 speech in which he referred to Jews as
''bloodsuckers'' and made other inflammatory remarks against Roman
Catholics, whites and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   He and other organizers have billed the Million Youth March,
which is to include pop music stars, as an opportunity for young
blacks across the country to assert unity and to help strive for
the economic, social and political advancement of black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be modeled after the Million Man March three years ago
in Washington, which was organized by Louis Farrakhan, the Nation
of Islam leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration and march organizers have been
deadlocked over when and where the march should take place. The
city has denied Muhammad a permit to hold the rally Sept. 5, a
Saturday, on Malcolm X Boulevard, which city officials say cannot
safely accommodate the 1 million participants the organizers say
they expect.
</P>
<P>
   The city has offered Randalls Island and Van Cortlandt Park in
the Bronx as alternative locations and Sept. 19 as a more suitable
date, to avoid conflicts with parades and other community events
already scheduled for the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson said that the organizers of the march had a
constitutional right to deliver their message and that the city
should work with them to come up with a mutually agreeable site. He
suggested that officials look into holding the event at Riverbank
State Park or on Adam Clayton Powell Jr. Boulevard, places he said
could better accommodate large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Bill Perkins, who represents Harlem, said in an
interview Tuesday that he would organize a ``peace patrol'' of
local clergy members and off-duty police officers to head off
confrontations between marchers and the police should the event
take place on Sept. 5. Perkins said that he had had several
discussions with city staff and organizers, as recently as Monday
evening, but that neither side seemed willing to change its
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be, inevitably, a clash,'' said Perkins, who
opposes the march because of Muhammad's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Tuesday that he was confident the city's law
department, the office of the corporation counsel, working in
concert with the Police Department, would find an alternative site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact is that the corporation counsel will look for
a reasonable alternative for them,'' Giuliani told reporters. He
declined to comment further but has been outspoken in recent days
in his criticism of Muhammad. Lorna Goodman, a spokeswoman for the
law department, declined to comment on the status of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Muhammad nor march representatives returned telephone
calls seeking comment, but the recorded message at the group's
Washington headquarters Tuesday said the march ``will be held
Saturday, Sept. 5, in Harlem, New York City, on Malcolm X
Boulevard.'' The voice emphasized ``will.'' The group's Web site
also gave that date and location for the march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
