<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECTRIC-CARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS N.Y. PLAN TO REQUIRE SALE OF ELECTRIC CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a setback for the nation's fledgling market in
electric cars, a federal appeals court Tuesday rejected New York
state's plan to require that automakers immediately begin selling
thousands of electrically powered vehicles in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by a two-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, reverses a lower court decision upholding the state
rule requiring that 2 percent of all vehicles sold beginning last
October be powered by electricity. Under the rule, the quota would
have gradually increased each year until it reached 10 percent in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling still allows New York to require that 10 percent of
all vehicles sold in 2003 be powered electrically. But because New
York was the only state seeking to require the immediate sale of
electric cars, many experts looked to it to help create a market
that could lead to the cars' mass production at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Both California and Massachusetts, under intense pressure from
the automobile industry, scaled back similar plans two years ago.
Those states will not require the sale of electric cars until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is disappointing but not devastating,'' said
Jason Grumet, executive director of Northeast States for
Coordinated Air Use Management, which represents air-pollution
control programs in eight Northeast states. ``But the ruling
removes the transitional sales targets that were intended to guide
the introduction of these vehicles into the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision disappointed Gov. George Pataki and other state
officials who have long maintained that their plan would help the
state meet tough pollution standards set by the federal Clean Air
Act of 1990. But Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, said
administration officials had not decided whether they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling pleased automobile industry officials, who said it
bought them time to develop electric cars that would be popular.
The industry has argued that the state's mandates were onerous
because consumers have shown little interest in buying electric
cars now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly provides us needed but not necessarily
sufficient time for the development of vehicles that would meet the
demands of car customers,'' said Mark Slywynsky, a lawyer for the
American Automobile Manufacturers Association, which represents
Chrysler, Ford and General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The state's regulation was enacted in 1991 under Gov. Mario
Cuomo, who wanted to use amendments to the Clean Air Act permitting
states to impose rules on automobile emissions that were as tough
as California's. That state required manufacturers to sell
increasingly clean-burning cars, culminating with a mandate for
zero-emission, or electric, cars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers challenged that rule in court on three occasions and
lost each time. Then, late last year, after California had
abandoned its plan to mandate the sale of electric cars between
1998 and 2002, they appealed the latest ruling against them. The
companies argued that the Clean Air Act required New York's
standards to be identical to California's.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals court, in an opinion written by Chief Judge
Ralph Winter, sided with them Tuesday. Judge Joseph McLaughlin
concurred with the opinion; a third judge had recused himself.
</P>
<P>
   New York officials estimated that the mandate would have
required the sale of 8,000 electric cars in 1998. With Tuesday's
ruling, the sole requirement on carmakers is that they sell at
least 40,000 electric cars in 2003, according to state officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 0103EDT &QL; 
