<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZDANCE-AZR &LR;      08-12 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZDANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCERS REDEFINE JAZZ AT CONGRESS HELD IN PHOENIX
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LaFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along Adams Street, they redefined jazz dance.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix Symphony Hall and at the Orpheum Theatre, dancers
from Canada, Japan, England and the United States leapt with blind
abandon into each other's arms, drilled a funky beat into the
floor, flipped across stage with hyperthyroid glee.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jazz Dance World Congress 1998 in downtown Phoenix, jazz
dance was the heavy boots of Anglo-African dancer De Napoli Clarke
slamming to hip-hop; the fleet gymnastic evocation of ancient Ninja
warriors by the Masashi Action Machine of Nagoya, Japan; the
sophistication of Les Ballets Jazz de Montreal's
classical-crossover take on relationships.
</P>
<P>
   And it was MTV, embodied by megastar Paula Abdul, who was to be
given an award by the congress at Tuesday's concluding gala at
Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the World Jazz Dance Congress 1998 was light-years from
Fred Astaire. But once in a while, you could glimpse the past in
the present of this dynamic art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz is an accessible art form. We keep contact with the
audience,'' said choreographer, teacher and congress founder Gus
Giordano, addressing a class of more than 50 mostly female, mostly
teenage students in the Phoenix Civic Center Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Those students and hundreds of others joined with professionals
and teachers to make up a conference force of about 2,000 jazz
dance aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, for decades one of the mainstays of jazz dance,
instilled the accessibility he praised by instructing in proper
technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``In jazz,'' he said to his students, ``the upper body is regal,
and the lower body is hootchy-kootchy.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``hootchy-kootchy'' was an archaic term to most of the teens,
the meaning still got across: jazz lifts the rib cage and frees the
hips. It has ballet's upward mobility with an expressive earthiness
below.
</P>
<P>
   Yet much of the newer jazz dancing, seen in several performances
over the weekend, seemed to be eliminating or de-emphasizing the
regality while fortifying the earthiness, making jazz today a
motley of styles _ or a clash of sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano's own company, Gus Giordano Jazz Dance Chicago,
presented three pieces that point both backward and forward to very
different ways of moving. In Michael Taylor's Just Because, set to
sleek singing by Luther Vandross and others, a gracious lyricism
pervaded, dominated by balletic control; in Randy Duncan's Can't
Take This Away, dancers, decked out in billowing costumes, made the
upper-lower body dichotomy into a spiritual quest, assisted by
gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   But in Chain of Rocks, a Giordano project in three sections,
choreographed by three different artists including Nan Giordano
(Gus' daughter and his company's artistic director), a hip-hop
sensibility came blasting through.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Michaels, a Miami-born choreographer whose move to New York
two years ago was followed by an astonishingly fast rise to
prominence, said jazz today has a responsibility to look ahead even
while glancing over its shoulder, to ``take (Bob) Fosse and add
yourself,'' as she put it in a panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
   This came through in the second of two Michaels works over the
weekend, No Strings Attached, a deft blending of finger-snapping
four-beat jazz that would've put Broadway denizen Fosse at ease,
with the contemporary, street-beat,
</P>
<P>
   two-count feeling of hip-hop. Against the Current, the first
Michaels piece danced by the small company of polished, strong
dancers she calls R.A.W., looked more to the influence of modern
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, all American things are popular,'' said
choreographer Kumiko Sakamoto, explaining why the company she runs
with Masashi Mishiro, Masashi Action Machine, was part of a
conference of jazz dance.
</P>
<P>
   Lula Washington Dance Theatre of Los Angeles took the audience
to American backwoods and a celebration of rural innocence in Mahal
Dances, a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   From Tucson, members of Quinn Williams Jazz, based at the
University of Arizona, showed that young dancers understand this
vocabulary with an immediacy to be envied by ballet or modern.
</P>
<P>
   And from Palm Springs, solo dancer Sam Watson demonstrated the
laughs inherent in jazz dance _ especially when your costume is a
pair of boxer shorts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
