<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WIN DEMOCRATIC PRIMARIES IN COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Colorado Democrats chose women Tuesday as their
candidates for two significant races this fall: Dottie Lamm, a
former newspaper columnist and wife of a former governor, for
senator and Lt. Gov. Gail Schoettler for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Republican voters largely rejected right-wing candidates,
endorsing Ben Nighthorse Campbell to run again for the Senate and
choosing state Treasurer Bill Owens to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, is barred from running for a fourth
term because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   With most precincts reporting, Campbell, 65, running in his
first Republican race since he switched from the Democratic Party
in 1995, had 70 percent of the vote, to 30 percent for Bill Eggert,
a Denver lawyer who is himself a former Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lamm, wife of former Gov. Dick Lamm, had 57 percent of the
vote against state Rep. Gil Romero, with 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the races for governor, Owens had 59 percent of the vote in
the Republican primary against state Senate president Tom Norton.
On the Democratic side, Ms. Schoettler had 55 percent, to 45
percent for Mike Feeley, the State Senate minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's primaries brought several new faces to the fore. Mark
Udall, son of former congressman Morris Udall, will be the
Democrats' candidate to represent the district encompassing Boulder
in Congress. Republicans, seeking to break a 24-year Democratic
lock on the district, chose Bob Greenlee, a moderate who is
Boulder's first Republican mayor in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a fund-raising dichotomy, the winners had raised
enough money to buy television advertisements. The losers, on
tighter budgets, bought radio advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, Democrats face a disadvantage in
statewide races. Republicans are a growing presence in Colorado and
have a registration edge of 5 percent, or 120,000 votes, over the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans controlling the State Legislature, Democrats
argue that the election of a Democratic governor is the only way to
stop Colorado from following its neighbors into ``one party''
status. In Kansas, Wyoming and Utah, Republicans control both the
legislatures and governorships. Colorado has had a Democratic
governor since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's election was also stamped by the impact of Colorado's
term limits laws. Twenty-five members of the Legislature sought to
extend their political careers by running for new offices.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the significant migration into Colorado,
natives of New York and natives of California outnumbered natives
of Colorado in the pool of eight candidates for the two top offices
Tuesday _ senator and governor. The lone Colorado native was
Romero, of Pueblo. In the Senate race, Ms. Lamm and Eggert are
natives of the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
