A9436 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEEDLES-SAFETY-SFCHRO     08-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEEDLES-SAFETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTPOURING OF FRUSTRATION OVER DEADLY NEEDLE STICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM CARLSEN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tim Ulatowski, a top official from the Federal Drug
Administration, had been speaking for about 15 minutes Tuesday when
a wave of frustration broke over him at a health-care worker safety
conference.
</P>
<P>
   How many hundreds of medical workers need to die from
contaminated needle sticks before the agency bans standard needles
and syringes that are causing the injuries, asked a nursing safety
expert.
</P>
<P>
   When is the FDA going to mandate the use of safety needles, a
doctor asked. Another safety specialist accused the FDA of
``weaseling out'' of its obligations to prevent injuries to workers
from medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   Although such outbursts were rare at the two-day conference on
the hazards of accidental needle injuries, they served to
illuminate the frustration expressed by many health care workers:
Despite more than 1 million needle sticks and four such conferences
in the past 10 years, the government and hospital administrators
have done little to improve safety.
</P>
<P>
   It is particularly urgent matter for many of the participants at
the conference. Needle sticks are responsible for infecting tens of
thousands of medical workers with HIV and hepatitis viruses over
the past decade, as described in a series of Chronicle articles
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  With no solid, comprehensive proposals offered to solve the
problem, Murray Cohen, a former official of the federal Centers for
Disease Control who organized the meeting, told participants at the
end of the conference that ``we must aim for zero injuries.'' But
he left the attendees with no clear outline of how that might be
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Needle manufacturers who attended the conference had their own
solution, however. More than a dozen of them lined the hallways and
small meeting rooms outside the conference hall at the Marriott
hotel with exhibits _ an array of ingenious designs created to keep
contaminated needles from piercing the hands and fingers of medical
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ulatowski, speaking at one of the conference's workshops, said
he took great pride in the speed with which his agency is now
approving new safety designs for the market, pointing out that more
than 250 such devices have been granted approval.
</P>
<P>
   But as &UR;  &LR; for mandating the use of safety needles and banning most
standard needles, he said the agency is not even considering that
step. ``We still don't have the ideal mousetrap,'' he said. ``We
cannot regulate the practice of medicine. It's not our job.
Mandatory standards don't work well.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the members of the audience jumped in. ``Is there
any threshold (for the number of medical workers' deaths) before
the FDA will act?'' asked Susan Wilburn, a representative of the
American Nurses Association. She gave several examples of medical
devices that the agency pulled from the market after only a few
reported incidents of injuries to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the hall, Tom Sutton was seething. As a marketing
executive for Bioplexus, a small manufacturer of safety
blood-drawing needles, he said that FDA was actually penalizing
safe needle makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perverse form of logic that the makers of safety
needles are required by the FDA to report even the smallest failure
of their devices,'' he said, ``while no reports are required for
the standard needles made by the big manufacturers that are causing
all the needle sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   The other chief frustration repeated throughout the conference
was the absence of health care employers, insurers and hospital
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital administrators are missing,'' said Janine Jagger,
one of the nation's leading experts on needle injuries. ``If they
decided that they wanted better technology for their workers, we
could end this logjam and solve this problem tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that a few hospital executives did show up but he
admitted that most sent their infection control officers. He added
that a consultant from the American Hospital Association did attend
and speak.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Borwegen, a representative for the nation's largest health
care workers' union, the Service Employees International Union,
scoffed at that, pointing out that the hospital association several
years ago disbanded its worker health and safety division.
</P>
<P>
   Borwegen then repeated a refrain heard frequently in the
conference _ that hospital administrators have shown little
interest in needle sticks because they are protected from being
sued by injured workers because of workers' compensation laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're shielded,'' Sutton said, ``so many don't want to be
bothered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
