<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-SFCHR     08-12 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODISTS TIGHTEN BAN ON GAY UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON LATTIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northern California's divisive battle over gay rights in the
Methodist church is expected to intensify after a ruling Tuesday
that pastors in the nation's second-largest Protestant church may
be tried and defrocked for performing ``ceremonies that celebrate
homosexual unions.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the highest court of the United Methodist Church
was a major setback for liberal clergy and others asking for
greater legitimacy for gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling issued in Dallas, the Judicial Council of the
8.5-million-member denomination said pastors can be tried under a
1996 resolution prohibiting gay marriage that was adopted by
national church delegates and added to the Social Principles of the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conduct in violation of this prohibition renders a pastor
liable to a charge of disobedience to the order and discipline of
the United Methodist Church,'' the nine-member court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision puts Northern California Methodist Bishop
Melvin Talbert between a theological rock and an ecclesiastical
hard place.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Methodist ministers _ including the popular and powerful
leader of Glide Memorial United Methodist Church in San Francisco,
the Rev. Cecil Williams _ are among 150 Christian, Jewish and
Buddhist clergy in Northern California who have signed a
declaration stating, ``I have officiated or would be willing to
officiate at the religious marriage of a same- &LR; ju  &LR; gender couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's ruling, Talbert declined to discipline any
Methodist clergy who performed gay rites, arguing that ``performing
a holy union does not violate the law of the church, even though
such an act does go against the spirit of the Social Principles.''
</P>
<P>
   When he made that statement in May, Talbert said he could
continue to allow same-sex unions ``until instructed otherwise by
our Judicial Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbert, who was reached last night while on vacation in
Arizona, said he was ``deeply saddened'' by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a bishop of the church, I will abide by the discipline
and action of the Judicial Council,'' said Talbert, the immediate
past president of the National Council of Churches, the nation's
major ecumenical organization.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop said no disciplinary action will be taken against
pastors who have performed same-sex ceremonies in the past, but he
said, ``Now that the law has been clarified, we have to hold people
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not take action against pastors for signing
petitions stating their continued support for same-sex ceremonies.
Church law ``doesn't say anything about signing statements,'' he
said. ``It's about performing a same-sex union.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbert said he was hoping for a different outcome in Dallas.
``This is not the first time I have found myself in disagreement
with the church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Talbert's support of gay rights has caused a revolt by a
coalition of conservative evangelical clergy in Northern
California, the Evangelical Renewal Fellowship. Some have left the
denomination, taking entire congregations with them, and are now
negotiating over the real estate left behind. Others are
withholding funds from the denomination or threatening other
action.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Christie, president of the Evangelical Renewal
Fellowship and pastor of Mission City United Methodist Church in
Santa Clara, said his coalition feels vindicated by the court
ruling and will wait to see whether Talbert actually enforces it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is now in Bishop Talbert's court,'' said Christie.
``Bishop Talbert needs to get back in line and be held
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Alan Jones, executive director of the United Methodist
Mission in San Francisco, called Tuesday's ruling ``sad news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those clergy who support holy union will continue to do
them,'' Jones said. ``For me, it's a pastoral issue. Either I
respect the integrity of my sisters and brothers, or I don't. I
don't believe in `love the sinner, hate the sin.' I either love
someone, or I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling by the Methodist version of the Supreme Court
was on an appeal by conservative bishops upset over the acquittal
earlier this year of a Nebraska pastor, the Rev. Jimmy Creech, who
had been charged with violating church law by performing a holy
union for two lesbians in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McAnally, spokesman at the United Methodist Church
headquarters in Nashville, said local bishops like Talbert ``don't
have the authority to overrule this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Supreme Court,'' he said. ``The decision is
final.''
</P>
<P>
   McAnally said any member of the church could begin judicial
proceedings against a pastor or bishop for violating church law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would go to trial just like the Nebraska trial, which
probably would have gone differently if they had this ruling in
front of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the pastor at Glide church in San Francisco, said
Tuesday that he wants to read the ruling and talk to his lawyer
before commenting on the court action.
</P>
<P>
   Other Methodist ministers who signed the interfaith declaration
supporting same-sex marriage include the Revs. Karen Oliveto,
Stephen Lee, Ronald Swisher, John Chamberlin, Gary Barbaree, Kelvin
Sauls, Charlie Lerrigo, Paul Sweet and Phillip Lawson.
</P>
<P>
   The gay rights group that circulated the declaration, the All
Our Families Coalition, plans to hold a worship service in support
of same-sex marriage on September 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clergy are making public stands because of their conscience,''
said Cheryl Deaner, executive director of the coalition. ``That's a
higher authority than the church hierarchy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
