<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CALIFORNIA-SF     08-12 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISIT A $3 MILLION BOOST FOR CALIFORNIA DEMOCRAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ With crises at home and abroad swirling around
him, President Clinton focused on political campaigning in San
Francisco Tuesday, bringing a shower of dollars to California's
leading Democrat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In less than 24 hours, the president raised $3 million at three
events in San Francisco and Los Angeles for Democratic
gubernatorial nominee Gray Davis, members of the lieutenant
governor's staff said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cut short his California trip in response to the U.S.
Embassy bombings in Africa, and he conferred by phone briefly with
economic advisers over the steep stock market drop Tuesday. But he
also accomplished Job One in California: raising big bucks to help
Democrats meet their 1998 election goals.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, he was cheered by a crowd of 1,000 at a
$1,000-a-head lunch. In Los Angeles, he raised a total of $2
million at two exclusive events, one at the estate of real estate
mogul Bruce Karatz and the other a $25,000-a-couple dinner in the
home of SKG Dreamworks President Jeffrey Katzenberg, which drew
stars such as Sharon Stone, Rob Reiner, Diane Keaton and Steve
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important election. This is a huge deal,'' Clinton
told the noontime crowd at the St. Francis Hotel on San Francisco's
Union Square. ``I think you can make a compelling argument that it
is more important than ever before who is the governor of
California . . . Will it be an administration that makes the most
of every opportunity that we should provide in the next two years
and, hopefully, beyond?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the president is scheduled to testify next week to a
grand jury in Washington, D.C., about his alleged sexual
involvement with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, that
subject was not on the agenda Tuesday. Reporters were kept at a
distance during tightly scripted events, making it impossible to
pose questions to the president.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton only vaguely alluded to his political troubles. ``No
matter what you read,'' he told a Beverly Hills crowd last night,
``every day has been a joy to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, spokesman for the president, acknowledged that
Clinton would probably be meeting with his attorneys in the next
few days, but he declined to give details. Instead, he said last
night that the president was ``in a very positive frame of mind''
during his California swing _ and that Clinton spent his free time
during the trip reading mystery novels and playing cards with staff
members aboard Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   The apparently relaxed mood about the troubles ahead was also
reflected among San Francisco Democrats like August Longo, who
showed up at the St. Francis to support the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let any of this Lewinsky stuff sway us,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel, only a few anti-Clinton demonstrators were
among the 500 or so onlookers who waited patiently in the warm
summer weather, hoping to catch a glimpse of the president.
</P>
<P>
   In his lunchtime speech, Clinton pounded home the theme of
Democratic accomplishments and stressed the importance of
November's election in California. And he urged California
Democrats not to get complacent, but to work hard to elect the
entire Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has always been about the future. This is not a
time to relax. . . . We've worked too hard to get this far,''
Clinton said. ``We have to take advantage of it, and the best way
to do it is to elect Gray Davis governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton's California trip was tinged with troubles at
home and abroad. At every stop, the president spoke strongly about
last week's deadly terrorist bombing of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Americans must send a clear signal to the world that ``we are
not going to back away from our involvement with other people, and
we are not going to back away from our opposition to terrorism,''
Clinton told a crowd of local officials and environmentalists at a
water filtration plant in San Bruno Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Although the country's tough stand against terrorism may make
Americans more inviting targets for international violence, ``now
is the time to bear down, not back up, on that,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the stop at the Crystal Springs water treatment
plant to announce a measure that will require water utilities to
make regular reports to their customers on the quality of their
drinking water. Although California has required similar reports
for some time, ``it's a big step forward for much of the country,''
said Marguerite Young, California director for Clean Water Action.
</P>
<P>
   The president also used the occasion to address Republican
complaints that the growing number of environmental regulations is
hurting the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never create the 21st century America we want for our
children until we do not think of economic growth as divorced from
the preservation of the environment and public health,'' Clinton
said. ``They must be seen as absolutely part of one, indivisible
effort to create the good life for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president complained that Congress has refused to fund his
Clean Water Action Plan, which he said would help restore ``the 40
percent of our waters that are still too polluted for fishing and
swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Safe water for our children is something all Americans agree
on,'' Clinton said. ``This should not be a partisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's swing through California was originally planned to
last through Wednesday, but he rescheduled his return and planned
to fly back to Washington late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to confer with his foreign policy team in Washington
Wednesday and then meet the plane carrying the remains of Americans
killed in the bombing when it arrives at Andrews Air Force Base
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats were glad to see Clinton for even a day and
said the president's personal woes will have little effect on his
popularity in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's acceptance by the public here has never been
higher,'' said state Controller Kathleen Connell, who is up for
re-election. ``He's a tremendous asset. He represents the
opportunity for people to see a better future for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sosnick, one of Clinton's political advisers, emphasized
the importance of California's in the Democrats' national political
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is increasingly Democratic; it's a big state for
us,'' he said. ``There are political implications'' far beyond this
election season.
</P>
<P>
   Sosnick stressed Clinton's value to California Democrats, even
with when he is under the cloud of scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president has abundantly shown he can raise money
for Democrats,'' Sosnick said. ``They really want him to come out
and campaign for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 0356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
