<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9440 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHR     08-12 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHRON-BASEBALL </SLUG>
  
 WOOD, HERSHISER, SOSA _ 3 NAMES OF THE GAME  &HT;     By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   August in san Francisco, and those seats in the shade look
pretty inviting. The pennant race is here, steaming and oven-baked
and feeling much like the heartland. Try as the analysts might,
there are no hard baseball truths of any kind. Only Kerry Wood vs.
Orel Hershiser and two teams that won't be dropping out of
contention any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heaven for the good fans of Candlestick Point, who know
these things and don't get overwhelmed by the Big Picture search.
They were loud Tuesday in moments of utter inactivity. They had a
constant buzz going, like jazz enthusiasts before the next act in
Monterey, positively thriving on the act of anticipatory
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   When you get a contrast as delightful as Hershiser vs. Wood,
with a dash of Sammy Sosa, there's an awful lot to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's face is pure country. It looks like something you'd find
in a stack of 1959 baseball cards. This guy doesn't look like a
beach volleyball player, a Calvin Klein model, David Spade or Andy
Ashby. He looks like baseball. His card would fit nicely between
Bob Purkey and Johnny Callison.
</P>
<P>
   He walks to and from the mound like a highway patrolman on a
114-degree afternoon. He's got you pulled over, and he'll take his
sweet time wrecking your day. There's a raw, naive side to Wood,
but you imagine him laughing at Craig Lefferts, who used to sprint
out of the bullpen like a man fleeing the cops. You figure he's
baffled by the frolicking, leaping Dennis Martinez (who needed,
what, 38 years to break Juan Marichal's record?) because good
pitchers just don't act like that.
</P>
<P>
   They say he's suffering from a ``dead arm,'' whatever that
means, and we're here to discount the fatality. But it isn't the
Kerry Wood we saw in May, either. The radar guns had his fastball
in the mid-90s Tuesday, but the scouts knew better. They didn't
hear the familiar pop in the catcher's glove. They didn't see the
howling insanity he unleashed on the Houston Astros when he struck
out 20. They saw a kid trying to settle for less.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's curveball was all over the map. He hung one to Barry
Bonds: two-run triple in the third. He hung the next one to Jeff
Kent: two-run homer. He threw one to J.T. Snow that missed the
target by nearly two feet. Then, all of a sudden, he was Bert
Blyleven. He froze Snow for a called third strike. He fanned
Charlie Hayes with something straight out of Cooperstown. And then
Brent Mayne went down on yet another deuce. A real clinic _ but
with the score 5-0 against him.
</P>
<P>
   Because Wood is a ballplayer, the way the National League likes
its pitchers, he got a couple of bunts down _ the second time on a
two-strike count against Hershiser. With a bat in his hands, Wood
can deaden a live fastball like kids popping balloons with safety
pins. He was plenty angry about leaving, too. Manager Jim Riggleman
deemed him incapable of dealing with Bonds in the fifth, nobody out
and a man on first, and that just fried the young right-hander.
With Terry Mulholland coming in (about to walk Bonds), Wood fired
his glove against the dugout floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was forced to leave after walking two batters to load
the bases in the sixth, and that was a shame. There's nothing
professional about Julian Tavarez fielding a comebacker and heaving
a force-play throw so wide of the plate, Mayne can't come up with
it. There's nothing even remotely competent about Jose Mesa, who,
unbelievably, walked home the go-ahead run for the third time in
eight days. But there was beauty in Hershiser's performance. His
first two confrontations with Sosa were straight out of the
textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has been laying waste to the countryside, including two
prodigious homers here Monday night, so Hershiser sawed him off the
first time _ a broken-bat, double-play grounder. And the next time,
with the safety of a 5-1 lead, he hit Sosa. Nothing rude or
life-threatening; just a tailing fastball off the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa cast a quick, hard look toward the mound and then quietly
took his base. No idiot temper tantrums from this man, because he
knows the deal. He knows all of it. He's not like Mark McGwire, the
Third Rockhead From the Sun. For McGwire, everything is an
annoyance. Batting practice? Major hassle. Way too many people
enjoying it. Chasing the legendary Babe? Big Mac has no idea what
it means. Absolutely can't figure the public's and media's
fascination. He's like an alien who was sent here to hit 538-foot
homers, and he's doing just that, but they messed with his brain.
He wakes up each morning, downs three of Dr. Irritable's pills,
then goes bitterly on his way.
</P>
<P>
   You might be smart to bet Sosa in the three-man pursuit of Ruth
and Roger Maris, because he knows how to have fun with it. And
speaking of players with the right perspective, don't forget to
take Hershiser along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked to the plate for his first at-bat against Wood,
Hershiser heard his name being announced by a 5-year-old boy (a
clever, season-long brainstorm by the Giants' marketing
department). Most players just keep on walking. Hershiser stopped
and looked back, his heart melting for just a moment, because he
has kids. Because he  &LR; is  &LR; a little kid at heart and isn't afraid to
show it.
</P>
<P>
   On the first three pitches from Wood, Hershiser started backing
off before the ball was even thrown, as if to say, ``Too much for
me, man. Couple more and I'm out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the fourth pitch, he spanked a clean single to center.
</P>
<P>
   For all of these reasons, and many more, the Giants' fans kept
that buzz going under the glaring sunlight. It was one of those
days when the best stories were told early. The Giants' bullpen has
taken some fun out of pennant-race baseball lately, but people like
Wood, Sosa and Hershiser keep it fresh and alive, a reason to come
back the next day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
