<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BBN-SFGIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GIANTS PASS A SURVIVAL TEST  &HT;     By HENRY SCHULMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The faithful would no doubt like to hear that all is well with
the Giants after they beat the Chicago Cubs 8-7 Tuesday to snap
their five-game losing streak and tighten the wild-card race. But
that would be inaccurate reporting.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Giants emerged from battle looking like the winner
of a 120-round boxing match. They blew a 5-0 lead they built
against rookie standout Kerry Wood _ no news there _ and fell
behind 6-5 when reliever Jose Mesa incredibly walked home the
go-ahead run for the third time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the Giants had enough muscle left to tie the
game on Barry Bonds' RBI single in the seventh and take an 8-6 lead
on Jeff Kent's subsequent two-run homer, his second of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Cubs closed the gap with a run off Mesa in the
eighth, but John Johnstone saved the day by holding Chicago at 8-7.
Robb Nen then pitched an uneventful ninth for his 30th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lucky,'' Bonds said after he drove in three runs to
raise his total to 92. ``We're playing hard, but we've got to stop
the other team from scoring as much. We get out there, and all of a
sudden we're right back in the war zone. This is August. Everybody
is tired. Everybody is doing their best out there. Fortunately,
we're swinging the bats well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bonds has 23 RBIs since July 31. Kent has 26 since July
24, as well as 10 homers in 18 games. And the Giants have needed
every morsel of that production merely to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitchers have been the principal culprits. In 31
games since the All-Star break, the rotation is 6-17 with a 5.75
ERA. Kirk Rueter, who pitches Wednesday, is the only starter with
two victories in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Dusty Baker has decided to shake things up by moving
Danny Darwin to the bullpen. Chris Brock will start in his place
Sunday against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out there, and go as hard as you can and as long as you
can, but that has not been enough lately,'' said Orel Hershiser,
who could not retire a batter in the sixth inning Tuesday before he
was pulled. ``I felt good. I know I looked like a time bomb waiting
to go off. As a competitor, I wanted to stay in, but the manager
has to make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed in myself that I couldn't go deeper
in the game,'' he said. ``I had a pretty big lead. The bullpen is
carrying a big burden right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It should not have been that way.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants pounded on Wood, hitting for the cycle in the third
inning to take a 5-0 lead. Hershiser started with a single,
followed by Marvin Benard's RBI double, Bonds' two-run triple and
Kent's first two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No knock on Kerry, but he wasn't at his best today,'' Kent
said. ``You can throw as hard as you want, but if you don't get
your offspeed pitches over you're not going to be able to survive
with your fastball. He was not getting that awesome slider we've
seen on TV over for strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood was done after four innings, but the Giants, as they have
done almost religiously lately, squandered the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored single runs in the fourth, fifth and sixth
against Hershiser _ the sixth-inning run was unearned because
reliever Julian Tavarez threw away a sure out at home _ then three
more off the bullpen in the seventh inning to take a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the Giants still clinging to a 5-4 lead, it came down to
Mesa with the bases loaded again, this time with one out. He
actually pitched well to pinch-hitter Glenallen Hill, but Hill hit
a lucky dribbler 45 feet up the third-base line, tying the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Houston then stepped in and took four straight balls from
Mesa to force home Sammy Sosa, who had been walked intentionally,
for a 6-5 Cubs lead.
</P>
<P>
   At least Mesa did not let the game get away. As 25,065 fans
booed him, he got pinch-hitter Mickey Morandini to bounce into a
force at home, then retired Sandy Martinez on a ground ball to end
the seventh and keep it a one-run game. That enabled the Giants to
storm back to an 8-6 lead on Bonds' single and Kent's homer off
Terry Adams in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   When Mesa put two runners on in the eighth, Baker called on
Johnstone. After a sacrifice, Baker decided to walk Sosa
intentionally and face Mark Grace, a .319 hitter. The ploy worked
when Grace bounced into a force. A run scored, but the Giants
maintained the lead. Johnstone then retired pinch-hitter Jeff
Blauser to secure a game which took 3:14 to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the toughest victories we've had,'' Baker
said, ``and one we probably needed the most. Everybody is just
tired and exhausted. Everybody gave whatever they had today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
