A9444 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAMING-JUVENILES-SFCH     08-12 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMING-JUVENILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMING CHILD CRIME SUSPECTS SPAWNS MEDIA DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOAN RYAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a week after an 11-year-old boy was charged with
shooting and killing his teenage neighbor in Antioch, Calif., two
months ago, the editors of the local Contra Costa Times decided to
print the name and school photo of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, after the boy was convicted in juvenile court of
involuntary manslaughter instead of the more serious murder charge,
the paper ran a front-page photo of him. The San Jose Mercury News,
which is owned by the same company, ran the same photo.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage escalated a difficult and sensitive debate in the
nation's newsrooms over how to write about the burgeoning number of
criminal suspects who look like children but kill like hardened
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The debate rose to the forefront at most newspapers after
virtually every paper in the country, including The Chronicle,
printed the names of the suspects, now 12 and 14, in the deadly
ambush at a Jonesboro, Ark., school in March. The Chicago Tribune,
the Los Angeles Times and the San Francisco Examiner resisted at
first, but they, too, gave in within three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, it was ridiculous not to print them because the
names were all over the place,'' said Chicago Tribune ombudsman
George Langford.
</P>
<P>
   The spate of horrific crimes committed by children has tested,
and cracked, journalism's long-standing policy of respecting a
child's right to privacy over the public's right to know.
Increasingly, newspapers are following the trend in the legal
system to treat children more like adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old idea was you don't want to taint someone forever at
such a tender age,'' said Mike Silverman, managing editor of the
Associated Press. ``But in some of these cases, that argument seems
less compelling. I mean, you turn on the TV and the parents of one
of these children is holding a press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   So our policy has evolved somewhat in the aftermath of Jonesboro
and other cases. There are more and more news stories of young kids
doing these horrible things.''
</P>
<P>
   Langford said the Chicago Tribune reviewed its policy about
naming minors after the Jonesboro case, sending reporters out to
elicit opinions from judges, child psychologists, lawyers and
educators.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune decided to stick by the traditional guidelines used
by most papers around the country, taking into account the child's
age, the severity of the crime, whether the child is being tried as
a juvenile or an adult, and the child's criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   This week, neither the Tribune, the competing Sun-Times nor
Chicago TV stations have revealed the names of the 7- and
8-year-old boys charged in Chicago on Monday with murdering and
molesting an 11-year-old girl. But, as Silverman of the AP bluntly
points out, ``That could change. . . . If the media in Chicago is
using (the names), then probably we would, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Saundra Keyes, managing editor of the Contra Costa Times, said
the decision to use the Antioch boy's name was a ``difficult and
sad'' one but that it passed the newspaper's litmus test. ``All
newspapers have a threshold that has to do with the heinousness of
the crime,'' she said. ``And unfortunately, there are so many more
crimes that rise to the threshold.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's editions, the Times' story and photo were
accompanied by an editor's note explaining that the paper ``does
not normally identify juvenile suspects, (but) we decided to do so
in this case because of the severity of the charge. . . .
Additionally, we decided to publish today's front page photograph
of the young boy in the belief that the image illustrates the
enormity of this tragedy in a way that words alone cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Keyes, ``There's also the broad issue of guns _ the
availability and the tragedy that ensue from that. The photo can
emphasize that more than the story. It's one thing to say an
11-year-old did this; it's another to look at that slight frame,
that face. So many who look at it will attach it to their own
children, to their nieces and nephews.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle generally does not use the names of young
offenders, but that policy is reviewed on a case-by-case basis.
Because of the horrific nature of the Jonesboro shootings, The
Chronicle printed the names and photographs of the suspects, who
were found guilty Tuesday of killing a teacher and four classmates.
The decision was different in the Antioch case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't print the name of the Antioch boy because he and his
family live in our circulation area,'' said Chronicle Executive
Editor Matthew Wilson. ``We didn't want to add to the stigma when
he was not being tried as an adult. The verdict, which was
involuntary manslaughter and not murder, gave us no compelling
reason to change our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Krim, assistant managing editor at the Mercury News,
said printing the Antioch boy's name was a mistake that slipped by
the editors. The wire services had included the name in their
stories, and the Mercury had used the wire stories without deleting
the name _ which went against the newspaper's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Then when the Mercury sent its own reporter to cover the boy's
conviction Tuesday, the reporter used the boy's name, probably
assuming that it was all right because the paper had already
printed it in at least one previous wire story, Krim said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, it's our policy not to name juveniles,'' he said.
``There's supposed to be a real good conversation among editors
(before naming juveniles), and that didn't happen in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the boy's trial, bailiffs instructed photographers
not to take pictures of the youth as he was taken to and from the
courtroom. Cameras were banned from the courtroom itself.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gagen, the boy's attorney, said that he was troubled that
the Times ran the photo and that he intended to bring the matter up
with Contra Costa Superior Court Judge Lois Haight, who presided
over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Charlie Goodyear contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
