 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 397- August 12, 1998   We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. VANESSA WILLIAMS DANCES UP A STORM Vanessa Williams gets down
and dirty with Latin pop star Chayanne In ``Dance With Me.'' She
plays a competitive ballroom dancer and he stars as a Cuban imigri.
Williams talks about the new movie, taking dance lessons for the
role, her career, her family and how she survived the 1984 nude
picture scandal that cost her the crown as the first black Miss
America. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
THE KARMA CHAMELEON'S NEXT LIFE Boy George has grown up. The
singer, flamboyant personality and leader of '80s British band
Culture Club has been through drugs, therapy and various other side
trips to emerge a thoughtful, still outspoken '90s revival story.
The reunited Culture Club (all the original members) is on tour
this summer. ``It's amazing how you can discover your own music
years later,'' says George, adding that many of the tunes were not
the sugary ditties they were thought to be at that teen-idol time,
but were really ``personal stories'' connected to his now-defunct
love affair with drummer Jon Moss. By Steve Morse. From The Boston
Globe. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
VAN CLIBURN'S GHOST APPEARS IN THE SHED Last month, celebrated
pianist Van Cliburn returned to the concert platform, 30 years
after his last performance with the Boston Symphony Orchestra. The
expectancy surrounding the occasion at the Tanglewood Festival in
Lenox, Massachusetts, was all the greater because a thunderstorm
was gathering (the concert was to be held in the Shed, a kind of
hangar half-open to the elements,) and because Van Cliburn was
rumoured to be nervous. Review by Renaud Machart. From Le Monde.
English translation available. 700 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
IS GARY SINISE A MOVIE STAR? After he appeared in ``Forrest Gump,''
(one of the highest-grossing films in movie history,) as Vietnam
veteran Lt. Dan Taylor, Gary Sinise was called ``a mainstream movie
star.'' But is he truly a name, a face, a Travolta, a Cruise? If he
is, someone forgot to tell him. Sinise gets the scripts with
fingerprints on them, reading for the parts that have already been
considered and rejected by other actors. He is also, however, the
kind of actor who makes you pay closer attention to any film,
simply because he's in it. While his name is in smaller type in
advertisements for ``Snake Eyes'' than that of Nicolas Cage, Sinise
is one of the film's most compelling characters. Interview by Renee
Graham. From The Boston Globe. 1,400 words.
________________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. BO DEREK BUCKS THE SEX SYMBOL FATE In the 1979 movie ``10,''
Bo Derek was the world's perfect woman, and an instant corn-rowed
sex symbol. Today she is 41, and while men at that age can continue
to be box office icons, her sex symbol movie career is virtually
over. However, still able to slip easily into a bikini, in the
steamy new TV series ``Wind on Water,'' she plays a beautiful widow
with two teenage sons, a strong woman battling to keep her Hawaiian
ranch. It's a kind of ``Dallas'' meets ``Bonanza'' via
``Baywatch.'' Interview by Ivor Davis. (N/A Great Britain and
Australia.) 1,000 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
ALAN ARKIN IS A MAN FOR ALL SEASONS Alan Arkin has been around for
a long time, doing just about everything in show business. The
64-year-old is currently doing an off-Broadway show, ``Power
Plays'' and has a new movie, ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' due out
soon. Arkin talks about his current and new projects as well as his
long-standing versatility in the business. He says he's quite happy
with who he is and has no desire to be a Bruce Willis or Steve
McQueen. By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
A LOOK BACK AT THE RAT PACK They were hot back then, and they were
cool at the same time. The ``Rat Pack,'' was the Frank Sinatra &AMP;
Co. group that followed the original Lauren Bacall and Humphrey
Bogart crowd, (they got the name from appearing like a bunch of
drowned rats.) A new HBO movie takes a look at this phenomenon and
the 1950s and 1960s when the Rat Pack ruled. Jean Oppenheimer talks
to several of the key players in the movie. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FACE VALUE : LEADERS OF THE PACK - SAMMY, FRANK AND DEAN In this
new cartoon feature, artist Ricardo Castaneda caricatures Sammy
Davis Jr., Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin of the ``Rat Pack.''
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
BEAU BRIDGES GOES OVER THE TOP IN NEW SERIES Director Barry
Sonnenfeld told Beau Bridges and the rest of the cast in the new
series ``Maximum Bob'' to go over the top, but not to appear as if
they were joking. Sonnenfeld should know : he produced two of
Hollywood's most zany movies in recent years - ``Men in Black'' and
``Get Shorty.'' The cast of the show, based on an Elmore Leonard
best-selling novel, seems to get it. Stephen Cole takes a look at
the show. (Colour slide shows Bridges wrestling with an alligator
..... ) From TV Guide. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
