<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKPACK-SAFETY13-COX     08-12 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKPACK-SAFETY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is school becoming too much of a pain in your kid's back?
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jayce Gill has a purple canvas backpack. And one
day this summer, the 10-year-old filled it with: A plastic case
stuffed with doll clothes and some pennies. Doll-sized pom-pons and
leg cast. A brochure from a doll company. Jayce's clothes.
Hair-ties. Several pairs of doll shoes. A desktop accessories box
secured with a red bandana. And a doll.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming school year, the contents of Jayce's backpack will
lean more to books and notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a pretty big load for a 74-pound girl.
</P>
<P>
   As backpacks have become a must-have for schoolkids, concern
about how much they're carrying_ and the way they carry them _ has
become an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Back specialists are hearing sporadic reports of children
developing muscle strains and backaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same as an adult gaining 20 pounds overnight, and
then trying to be as active as their 10-year-old,'' says Dr.
Randall Dryer, a spinal surgery specialist with the Central Texas
Spine Institute. ``It's going to lead to back pain. Little bodies
aren't meant to carry the same kind of weight as adults.''
</P>
<P>
   There are things parents and children can do to prevent backpack
related back strain, which usually surfaces in the lower back or
between the shoulder blades, according to Dryer.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Jayce complained about her pack hurting during
the last school year, that her dad, Thomas ``Woody'' Gill, realized
he needed to replace the heavy dictionary she was toting around
with a small paperback version.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he says, he'll be more attentive, since the pack is a
constant presence in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't go anywhere without it and she never forgets it,''
Gill says.
</P>
<P>
   Other things parents should be aware of when using backpacks:
Kids should carry the pack on both shoulders to evenly distribute
any weight. Reduce the load. Make copies of textbook materials
children need for a particular day so they don't have to carry so
many books. Choose lightweight notebooks. Substitute paperback
versions of dictionaries or other reference books. Clean out
backpacks periodically to remove unnecessary items.
</P>
<P>
   Restrict backpack use if kids complain about the weight, or if
they've injured themselves during another activity.
</P>
<P>
   If children complain badly enough about the pain and it keeps
them from participating in an activity they enjoy, that's a strong
signal to see a doctor, Dryer says. Other warning signs that need a
physician's attention: complaints for more than seven days, pain
accompanied by fever and chills, numbness or leg pain.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bonnin is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
