<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CROQUET13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If city manicures, croquet will come _ to South Florida
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The wicket and mallet set is hoping a
city park in a mixed-income neighborhood will join the ranks of
Mar-a-Lago and The Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, love. They're talking croquet in Howard Park,
across the bridge from Palm Beach and down a few blocks. It's a
good deal east of Wellington and quite a bit north of Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the benefits Tiger Woods has brought to golf. We
want the next Tiger Woods to be a croquet player,'' John Curington
wrote in a letter to city commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Curington is president of the Florida section of the United
States Croquet Association, based in Wellington. His group has
offered to spend $250,000 on five championship courts in Howard
Park if the city agrees to manicure the lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city would have to provide added irrigation and buy
a special mower to keep the 2 acres neatly trimmed, it would cost
taxpayers $82,000 the first year and $61,000 every year after that.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor thinks it's a smashing idea. ``It's the one thing I
might be able to play,'' Nancy Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   But commission approval might prove a bit of a sticky wicket.
``I don't see a lot of kids playing croquet,'' said Commissioner
Howard Warshauer.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Al Zucaro questions whether equal treatment should
be given to area cricket players, who've been asking to use city
park land for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Croquet (pronounced cro-KAY) is a 15th-century French sport that
has largely been dominated by older, wealthier people who play at
exclusive clubs. Prices for a good set (not the $40 barbecue
backyard variety in your grandmother's basement) start at more than
$200. The average income of United States Croquet Association
members is $150,000, according to association data.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to don those whites on the lawn. Most private
clubs that offer croquet require white clothing from head to foot.
</P>
<P>
   But the croquet association is trying to shake those patrician
roots. By bringing the sport to communities of different races,
incomes and ages, they want to build its popularity. This would be
the second public course in Florida, joining one in Winter Park,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the players are dying off and they don't have anybody
to play the sport,'' said Laura Schuppert, West Palm Beach's
recreation director.
</P>
<P>
   The croquet association has offered to buy the equipment so the
city can loan it to residents for free. They've also offered to
send a teacher a few days a week to give lessons. And residents
won't have to wear white unless they're playing in a tournament,
Schuppert said.
</P>
<P>
   To lease the land for 10 years, the association needs support
from four of five commissioners later this month. If it gets it,
the association would host national and international tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Local instructor and four-time national champion Archie Peck
said people of all backgrounds enjoy the sport. He called croquet
``a cerebral game'' combining billiards, chess and putting.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting, 21 of 35 area residents agreed to cede two
of the park's 30 acres for croquet, Schuppert said. The land is now
being used for lawn-bowling and a horseshoe pitch.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five croquet courts would double as a bowling lawn,
according to the association's plan. As it is, lawn bowling in
Howard park is played on clay, so the lawn bowlers are ``very
supportive,'' Schuppert said.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Bierman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
