<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie aimed at kids may do more harm than good
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a perfect night _ just hot enough, not too
hot. We were all in the mood for some good family entertainment,
not too serious, not too stupid. Something to delight every member
of the family from, say, 42 (picking a random number) to 3.
</P>
<P>
   We settled on a drive-in movie _ Parent Trap _ popped our
popcorn, packed our cooler and hit the road. Here indeed was
something for every taste: Dennis Quaid in tight black jeans for
me; Natasha ooh-la-la Richardson for Jim; musical lawn chairs for
Veronica; and slapstick campfire high jinks for Alec.
</P>
<P>
   It was all fun and froth, exactly what we'd been looking for. Of
course, we had to suspend our disbelief and not ask the obvious
questions: Who but a pair of sociopaths would do this to their
kids? How could they be so attractive and likable?
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the tricks you don't want your kids to try
at home. ``What was your favorite part of the movie?'' I asked Alec
afterward. ``When they put rocks in her backpack!'' he chortled.
</P>
<P>
   How would he have reacted if we were divorced? Would the pranks
still be the film's most delightful fantasy?
</P>
<P>
   For Alec there was no subtext to this remake of the tale of
separated-at-birth twins who meet for the first time at camp and
conspire to bring their parents back together. The split-family
theme didn't resonate with me and my pals, either, when we saw the
Hayley Mills original in 1961. Not one of the kids on my block
lived in a single-parent home. Scheming to reunite your folks
seemed as far-fetched as the jet-setting parents.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy carries a more wistful element for many of today's
kids and complications for single parents: whether to let their
kids see a movie that might foster unrealistic hopes.
</P>
<P>
   One friend said she won't take her almost-teen daughter to see
the film: ``It's been three years and she has felt _ up to the time
her dad told her a few months ago that he was probably going to
remarry _ that we were going to get back together. I think Mrs.
Doubtfire is a much better movie to see, where the parents work out
an amicable resolution to their separateness and redefine family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a movie I'll take my kids to see,'' concurred Kathy
Crews of Vandalia. Divorced since November, she has two daughters,
12 and 6. ``My younger one hints around her mom and dad are going
to get back together. . . . I think the movie ought to carry a
warning for parents who are newly divorced, that your children may
have a recurrence of pain and false hope of getting back together.
And then when you explain that won't happen, it would just bring
more pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'd have a problem taking them to see it,'' said
Cindy Hochwalt of Centerville, whose children are 5 and 10. ``My
only worry is having them thinking, 'Hey this is maybe something
that could happen to me.' It's a matter of talking to them, helping
them to understand in the easiest, kindest way.''
</P>
<P>
   Donita Garner of Dayton said she might take her son, Joshua, 7,
to the movie to get him to open up. ``He still dreams, but I don't
do anything to discourage the dream other than to say that's not
what the cards are all about. It has been a year since we had that
conversation. I might take him to see where his head is.''
</P>
<P>
   This film from 1961 ``doesn't translate very well into the late
'90s,'' Crews observed.
</P>
<P>
   You can remake careers, slang, wardrobes and hairstyles all you
like, but how do you graft a '60s fantasy about families onto the
reality of families in the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   Looks like somebody fell into a Producer Trap.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
