</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At the square, we drove in circles, refusing to yield
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIANA, Ohio _ Let me tell you about this town. It is small
_ 6,000 people. It has the most wonderful park, the most wonderful
old cinema, the most wonderful fall street fair. For $100,000, you
could buy yourself the prettiest house on the
</P>
<P>
   nicest part of Elm Street.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this town's not totally bucolic. You must still
supply the pretty life that goes inside.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up here in the 1970s, this is what we did.
</P>
<P>
   We rode around and looked for Mark Harrold.
</P>
<P>
   We rode through the park and we rode through the Dairy Queen
parking lot and we rode around out on old Metz Road.
</P>
<P>
   We rode around after football games and on hot summer nights
after the pool closed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, my moments of greatest teenage solitude and independence
came inside my father's green Ford LTD, learning the words to a
Karen Carpenter song and looking, always looking, for the cutest
guy to ever fill a Columbiana Clippers football jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The oddest part about this little town, the thing that makes
people really sit up and yak, is The Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Square is this little traffic circle in the center and, of
course, The Square is round, not square. It is also where
16-year-olds in Columbiana are first taught good manners, a little
something people around here call ``yielding.''
</P>
<P>
   Had I married a local boy, I would have never married someone
who zoomed through the square all willy-nilly. In Columbiana, you
are expected to marry a good yielder. And if you don't, everybody
knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you leave here?'' asked my 7-year-old, the boy who on
previous visits was not interested in any life I had prior to being
his mother. ``College,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``I like it. It's so old-fashioned.'' And
because mothers are always looking for moments to teach their sons
great lessons, especially when they're driving around in their
small Ohio hometown with nothing but time on their hands, I
proceeded to talk to him about life and leaving and how some things
always look a little better from the outside. But his mind was
already on miniature golf and the Dairy Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his question is one I've asked myself many times,
especially since he was born. Wouldn't it be best for this child if
his father and I raised him in a place like this? A place where
children can ride their bikes out of sight without striking fear in
a parent's heart. A place where families are safe. Indeed, there
have been just three murders in this town since Columbiana Police
Chief John Krawchyk came here as a young officer in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But I guess my heart knows the answers to all this.
</P>
<P>
   Before I left here, I had never seen a homeless person. Before I
left here, I'd never had a black as a friend or a gay as a
neighbor. Before I left here, the only diversities I knew were the
simple differences of morals that divided one white family from
another.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as with all matters of the heart, I've always believed
that the reasons I love this little town are a complicated
combination of family, sentiment and social standards.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the other day, 42 years old with a bored child
on my hands, that it all came to me, that it all made sense.
</P>
<P>
   The most marvelous thing about Columbiana, Ohio, is that when
you come home, an old married woman, you can take your kid and
drive out to Ross' Lake Front Miniature Golf Course and play a
quick nine holes for $3.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can stop at Sparkle Market, pick up some coffee and do
all your socializing.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't even have to keep your eyes peeled for Mark
Harrold.
</P>
<P>
   Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
