<SLUG> BC-MULAN-HAIR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking your child to `Mulan'? Hide the hair shears
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As if you didn't have enough to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the spirited heroines of two new
made-for-little-girls movies, some youngsters are taking up
scissors and trying their hands at shearing their own locks.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the real parent trap.
</P>
<P>
   Snip. ``Look, Mom, I'm Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, a dozen desperate parents have rushed to
Austin hair stylist Margo Bower, owner of the Hair's Lair, to clean
up the handiwork of their daughters, ranging in age from 3 to 6.
The girls, Bower says, all have chopped their hair just like Mulan
did with a sword to masquerade as a man to defend her family's
honor, or as the high-toned Annie did to look exactly like her
down-to-earth twin sister, Hallie, in ``The Parent Trap.'' All the
parents told Bower their kids got the idea from the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cutting clumps of hair here and there, on the side,
their bangs, whatever they can hold up and cut,'' says Bower, who
thinks creatively in approaching her little fashion victims, giving
them a ``nicer-looking haircut to camouflage the damaged area.''
</P>
<P>
   So as not to make matters worse _ Bower says the girls got
enough grief at home _ she did not want to disclose their names,
although two irritated parents confirmed that Bower rescued their
daughters' locks. ``I didn't want them to feel badly for what they
had done,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of advice, parents: If you don't want to make a 3 a.m.
hospital visit because your kid wants her tonsils out, don't take
her to see ``Madeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-REUNION13-COX     08-12 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-REUNION13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'I didn't know we had so many people in our family!'
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PARK, Fla. _ The Walker family photos are on display.
</P>
<P>
   They are proof of what can go wrong in family photos _ blurs,
thumbs, misfired flashes _ and what can go right in a family.
</P>
<P>
   The boy in the suit at the drum set in the den. The two girls in
their bedroom with pinups of the Jackson 5. The wedding cake. The
Navy portrait. The girl in the pink sweater with ``Teen Angel''
spelled in sequins. The graduate. The playpen. The
clutching-the-wagon-wheel school photo. The party hats. The rose
corsage. The surprised look. The pout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me _ Lord, you can't tell!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go on, 'fess on up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got rid of that sweater last week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what's with the Afro?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Sherry. Look at Sherry right here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Reggie? You sure?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Reggie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a dress on? That's a dress, hon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Reggie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Magic. Come here and look at Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not Pam. That is Sylvia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon looks just like herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Family photos for a family of 310. They have to keep a census.
</P>
<P>
   Every two years, a different family member plays host to the
Walker family reunion. Last weekend, it was Dorothy Whigham's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy is 54 and lives in Lake Park, and she thinks she has
spent $2,500 on the whole three-day, $10,000 deal _ banquet at the
Marriott, hospitality suite, fashion show with the kids, all-day
picnic and Sunday service. The reunion T-shirts alone were $600.
</P>
<P>
   And after 31 years of reunions, someone finally thought to pull
out the photos. ``We're trying to do something different,'' said
Latoya Whigham, 19, Dorothy's granddaughter. ``We had kids falling
asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   So while family members recited poems, and family historian Rosa
Jordan, 72, brought everyone up to date, people kept leaving the
banquet hall for peeks.
</P>
<P>
   And with all the camera action, no doubt they'll update those
photos fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year, I took 285 photos,'' said Charlie Saffore of Kokomo,
Ind. ``I didn't know we had so many people in our family!''
</P>
<P>
   (ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two years, we've had an increase of 17 people,''
Rosa Jordan says. (Applause.)
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The reunions started with Thanksgiving get-togethers in Orlando,
where the 13 children of Ernest Walker and Annie Mae Morris Walker,
both farmers, grew up. The family outgrew Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the 13 children started taking turns hosting the
reunions every year in California and across the South. The family
outgrew that schedule and changed it to every two years.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough. The family finally started having regional
birthday fellowships every three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out our grandchildren were going to the same school
and didn't know each other, and started dating each other,'' Rosa
Jordan explained.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandson's cousin started dating a girl, and the grandson
tried to set him straight. ``Go call granny,'' he told the boy.
Turns out the couple's grandparents were sister and brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy called from school one day and said, `Don't tell me!
Don't tell me!' '' Jordan said. ``That really struck me.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie Ruth Favors has lived in West Palm Beach since 1964, but
it took 10 years to learn she had relatives here.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, a lady was going to get an address from me and looked
at my address book, and she asked, `Are you any kin to the Favors
on 44th Street?' She took me over there. We were first cousins.''
</P>
<P>
   This was her first reunion. ``You see so many faces you look
almost like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (ital)
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Jordan: ``I have five daughters, 10 grandchildren, three _
wait, gotta count, she's got two _ three. Three
great-grandchildren. Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The last time the 13 Walker children were together was in 1991,
before sister Emma Terry died. Four brothers couldn't come this
year for one reason or another.
</P>
<P>
   At final count, about 250 people showed up this time.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Whigham is the youngest of the 13. The reunion was
special, she said, because after this, the younger family members
take over as hosts.
</P>
<P>
   And thank God for that. ``I got to bed at 2:30 this morning,''
she said after the Sunday service. ``The last guest leaves on
Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she doesn't love the family reunion. Still, she's
taking the week off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
