A9733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN13-COX     08-12 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Why we are targets
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Suddenly my plan to put a few pesos on the
caballitos was blocked by a picket line of intense men holding
automatic weapons, rifles and pistols.
</P>
<P>
   The men were lined up across the front entrance of the Del Prado
Hotel, which in 1959 was perhaps the best hotel in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said one of the armed men holding up his hand as I
exited the hotel dressed in a madras sport jacket and a stylishly
narrow tie.
</P>
<P>
   These men, I realized, had their guns at the ready to protect me
and the other American hotel guests from the angry, boiling crowd
that filled the street.
</P>
<P>
   I stood in by the front door and listened to the crowd shout
anti-American obscenities and watched as they burned the American
flag.
</P>
<P>
   My first encounter with international anti-Americanism came
during a last-fling adventure through Mexico before I left for boot
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of an American flag being torched in anger was
startling. My friend and I stood there slack-jawed.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators spotted us and began shouting and pointing. We
were obviously Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The armed men herded us back through the front door into the
quiet, comfortable lobby that was a world apart from the ugly melee
outside on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 39 years later, I am not so startled when I encounter
anti-Americanism. I am still not sure, however, why America, which
has never taken over one square-inch of anyone's land, is so
despised by so many of the world's discontents.
</P>
<P>
   When we find out who is responsible for the recent bombings of
the American embassies in Africa, I doubt that we will be any
closer to understanding why America was the target for this deadly
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorist acts associated with Northern Ireland, the Middle East
and more recently in the former Yugoslavia can be traced to ancient
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   These grievances don't apply to the United States, which happens
to be the world's oldest democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A nation that believes in individual freedoms and practices
religious tolerance should not be a hate target, but it is.
</P>
<P>
   When my friend and I asked why the demonstrators were denouncing
the United States, we were told to not worry. Before long the
protesters, who were from the university, would get tired and go
home.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than wait for the crowd to leave, we slipped out a side
door and took a taxi to the race track.
</P>
<P>
   Our reation to all this anti-American passion must be one reason
Americans are so so despised by people who see us as disgustingly
fortunate compared to their own conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are winners simply by luck of birth. What's more, our
culture emphasizes winning. We keep score with money. Not only are
Americans born lucky, we keep piling it on.
</P>
<P>
   Although the days of pushy, ugly American travelers are in the
past, the United States also has a history of being fairly pushy
when it came to supporting U.S. business interests overseas.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States has intervened here and there in foreign
affairs to protect national security during the Cold War years.
</P>
<P>
   But those actions appear reasonable, if not defensible.
</P>
<P>
   Religious fanaticism, however, does not bend to reason. Even
though the United States has been the world's leader in trying to
broker a peace between Israel and the Palestinians, we are
perceived as taking sides against Islam by many fundamentalist
Muslims who never take a secular view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, understanding anti-Americanism becomes
unnecessary. When reasonable methods fail, the United States should
be prepared to meet force with superior force.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
