u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLBIZ-RETIREMENT13     08-12 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-RETIREMENT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More small businesses offering retirement plans
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Alan Tillman built a successful business making
custom guns in his home over the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the company hit $100,000 in gross annual
revenues, he was finally earning enough that he could think about
putting money aside for retirement. But until recently he found it
difficult to take advantage of the salary deferral plans common
today at large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the 55-year-old gunsmith set up a simple individual
retirement account (IRA) that allows him to put aside up to $6,000
a year of his pre-tax salary. He estimates the plan costs him only
$35 a year in administrative fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relatively inexpensive for the gain,'' he says. In
today's tight job market, more and more small businesses are
offering retirement plans as an incentive to attract good workers
and compete with bigger employers. But picking the right type of
plan depends on the size of the company, how much it can spend on
plan administration and how much it might grow.
</P>
<P>
   Most big employers offer retirement plans in the form of 401(k)
programs, which were first authorized by Congress in 1978. Some
small growing companies also can find it cost effective to set up
401(k) plans, but others should look to other, newer programs, said
Neile Wolfe, who sets up salary deferral plans for Prudential
Securities in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   While the situations may vary, there are some basic rules of
thumb to guide companies on which plans will likely work best for
them.
</P>
<P>
   To establish a 401(k) plan at a minimum cost, a company should
have at least 25 employees, plan to be adding employees, and have
more than half of its employees willing to participate, Wolfe says.
He says some advisers may quibble with those figures, but it really
depends on the specific company. A 401(k) plan allows employees to
put aside up to $10,000 in pre-tax salary for their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a very small company _ like a family owned convenience
store, or family owned retail shop, or a couple of attorneys or a
couple of paralegals, or a small home builder _ a 401(k) is more
likely than not a poor choice for an employer,'' Wolfe says.
</P>
<P>
   But a 10-person consulting firm where each person earns $100,000
a year could find a 401(k) plan the best option.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer lies in tests the IRS uses to decide how much
can be deferred by the highest paid employees. The tests determine
whether highly paid executives and lower-paid employees are
participating in acceptable ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those requirements, the administrative costs associated
with setting up and running 401(k) plans can make them too onerous
unless the company is large enough, Wolfe says. If a 401(k) plan
isn't right, a small business may want to consider another plan,
the simple 401(k), which allows only $6,000 to be deferred, but has
lower salary thresholds and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The simple IRA like the one Tillman started was authorized by
Congress and went into effect in January 1997. It is one of the
more attractive ways small companies can help employees save for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The simple IRA has virtually no set-up costs, administrative
fees and no discrimination tests. Under the simple IRA the employer
matches dollar for dollar the first 3 percent of the salary being
deferred by an employee.
</P>
<P>
   Also a simple IRA, unlike the IRAs for individuals, allows up to
$6,000 vs. $2,000 of an employee's salary to be contributed pre-tax
to a retirement plan. Unlike the traditional IRA, which may or may
not be tax deductible, a simple IRA is automatically tax
deductible. (Tillman says one of the reasons he set up the simple
IRA is that because of his wife's retirement plan at work, he was
no longer able to make a tax-deferred contribution to a traditional
IRA.)
</P>
<P>
   Another option is the Simplified Employee Pension (or SEP),
which has been around for several years. SEPs haven't been as
popular with small businesses because unlike 401(k)s and Simple
IRAs where the employee makes all or most of the contribution SEPs
are fully paid for by the employer. Up to 15 percent of the
employees' full compensation may be deferred using an SEP.
</P>
<P>
   Motive Communications Inc., a young, fast-growing software
company with 32 employees, recently set up a 401(k). Its plan
offers employees 12 funds for investments, ranging from bond funds
to small cap, international, government securities and money market
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is a good benefit to offer the employees,'' says
Linda Hamann, director of finance for Motive. ``It's really one of
the few ways for employees to shelter part of their income from
federal income taxes and allow it to grow tax-free for
retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four percent of Motive's employees have signed up so far.
It cost Motive about $1,000 to set up, and ongoing administrative
fees are based on employee participation and the type of plan
selected. Motive is not yet matching employee contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Hamann estimates that once the 401(k) program was set up, it
takes an extra hour each pay period, when the money is withheld
from employees' paychecks. One of the main attractions of 401(k)
plans is the money is withheld by the employer and immediately sent
to be invested _ making it easier for employees to save and invest.
</P>
<P>
   In the highly competitive high-tech world such plans have become
a common perk even among smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just viewed as one of those things as soon as you
can do it, you do it,'' Hamann says.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman. Send
information to her at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767 or by e-mail
at ktyson(AT)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
