<SLUG> BC-CPT-ADOBE-LOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE WARNS OF POSSIBLE LOSS IN 3RD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adobe Systems Inc. warned Tuesday that its
third-quarter revenue would fall below analysts' expectations,
resulting in a potential loss. Adobe also announced the departure
of three senior executives and a reduction of 240 to 300 jobs, or
13 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Adobe fell $1.375, to $30.8125, on Nasdaq before
trading was halted for the company's announcement late in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, based in San Jose, Calif., is a leading maker of software
programs used in publishing, including Photoshop, Illustrator,
Pagemaker and the Postscript language used in printers. Although
Adobe has modified many of its programs to take advantage of the
Internet, and many are used to create Web sites, analysts said the
company had run into difficulty exploiting the transition to
electronic publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adobe is a tremendously successful company in the print world,
but they haven't really figured out the right products and strategy
for making money and being successful on the Web,'' said
Christopher Galvin, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe also said in its announcement Tuesday that business
continued to be hurt by Japan's recession. The company said that
cost-cutting efforts, including the reduction of jobs, would lower
expenses by as much as $60 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The company said revenue for the quarter that will end Aug. 28
was likely to be $220 million to $225 million, compared with $230
million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-time reorganization charge and other nonrecurring
expenses, Adobe said, net income may break even or be a loss,
compared with net income of $53.4 million in the quarter a year
earlier. Analysts had expected Adobe to earn 52 cents a diluted
share, according to First Call, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe also said Tuesday that three top executives, P. Jackson
Bell, executive vice president and chief administrative officer;
Robert Roblin, executive vice president for marketing, and Ross
Bott, executive vice president for product divisions, had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-98 2228EDT &QL;
</P>
