<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES GATES MUST GIVE DEPOSITION IN PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered Tuesday that the government's pretrial
questioning of Bill Gates and other executives of Microsoft Corp.
must be opened up to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling giving the press and the public access to
depositions in a major antitrust case is somewhat unusual, but it
is not unprecedented. One similar instance came during the Justice
Department's 13-year pursuit of IBM, a case that the government
dropped in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   A deposition from Gates, chairman and chief executive of
Microsoft, had been scheduled to begin Wednesday, but it was
postponed temporarily as the company's lawyers decided whether to
appeal the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District
Court in Washington applies not only to depositions of Gates but
also to those of 16 other Microsoft employees. The Justice
Department and 20 states have charged Microsoft with illegally
protecting its monopoly in operating systems for personal computers
and trying to extend its monopoly into the new Internet software
and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman said the company was ``very concerned
about the possible impact of the ruling on our trial preparation
and on the trial moving ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to begin on Sept. 8 in U.S. District
Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the company spokesman said, wants to insure that its
trade secrets and confidential business information are protected
during the deposition process. Until a procedure for assuring
confidentiality and the logistics for giving reporters access can
be resolved, ``all depositions are stopped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling came in response to a motion filed by The New
York Times, The Seattle Times and the cable-television and online
news units of Ziff-Davis, a computer trade publisher. Their filing
was joined by two news services, Reuters and Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The motion to open up pretrial depositions was made under a
provision of the nation's antitrust laws. The law states that in
civil antitrust actions brought by the federal government, the
taking of depositions ``shall be open to the public as freely as
are trials in open court, and no order excluding the public from
attendance on any such proceedings shall be valid or enforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Publicity in Taking of Evidence Act was passed in 1913 as
public concern about the power of industrial monopolies was at its
peak. The law was enacted, legal scholars say, to insure that the
market practices of the industrial trusts were scrutinized in
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an unusually clear and powerful statute,'' said Adam
Liptak, a lawyer for The New York Times. ``In antitrust cases
brought by the government, the presumption of public access is
almost absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Liptak said, The Times favors open court
proceedings, and the Microsoft case, in particular, is one of
considerable public interest.
</P>
<P>
   In the Microsoft case, Jackson had approved a protective order
in May limiting public access to confidential business information
gathered by the government and Microsoft during pretrial discovery.
</P>
<P>
   But in Tuesday's ruling, he said that the 1913 evidence act did
allow the press and the public access to the depositions. And he
instructed Microsoft, the news organizations and the government and
the states to figure out a procedure that would open the taking of
depositions but would also prevent ``unnecessary disclosure of
trade secrets and other confidential information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-98 2138EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
