A9759 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-ONTECH-SFCHRON &LR;      08-12 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Sun Refutes Idea of Eclipse By Microsoft  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems as if a lot of people don't buy the idea _ posed in a
Chronicle article last month _ that Sun Microsystems faces a
serious threat from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   No way, say Sun officials. Not only do they believe that they're
well-positioned to repel any attack from Microsoft, they think that
as corporate computing relies increasingly on the Internet, Sun,
with its powerful computer servers and Java programming language,
will be the company to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Sun sees no disadvantage in the fact that its computers use
Sun's own chips and operating system rather than the ``industry
standard'' combination of Windows NT and Intel Pentiums. In fact,
the Mountain View company boasts that its Unix operating system,
called Solaris, is faster and far more reliable than Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wants Windows NT to be the operating system of choice
everywhere inside a big company _ running Intel-based servers in
workgroups, departments and even entire networks. In other words,
it is targeting Sun's main markets.
</P>
<P>
   Windows NT 4.0 has been a stunning success in department and
workgroup situations. But it doesn't work reliably on high-end
servers. Microsoft hopes to conquer the enterprise market with
Windows NT 5.0, which it plans to ship sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Forrester Research has predicted that the software
giant will be disappointed. The Year 2000 problem and fear of bugs
in the new Windows NT will slow adoption of the software through
2001, a report by Forrester read.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then, NT's enterprise aspirations will be usurped by the
rise of Internet Computing and a new competitive landscape,'' the
report stated.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, Sun could be in great shape. Analyst Daniel
Kunstler of J.P. Morgan, a staunch Sun booster, said that if Sun
continues the momentum that has brought it three-straight quarters
of record earnings, it could amass an installed customer base that
will make it impervious even to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Sun thinks it's hurting Microsoft more than the other
way around. It believes that its low-end servers are competing well
against powerful PCs armed with Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sun says a number of big companies including
Fujitsu, Siemens-Nixdorf, Toshiba and NCR have agreed to use an
Intel-based version of Solaris as the operating system for their PC
networks _ dealing a blow to Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Sun also appears to be having a jolly good time jousting with
IBM and Hewlett-Packard, its main rivals in the Unix market.
According to International Data Corp., Sun shipped more Unix
servers last year than anyone, passing both IBM and HP, which had
been tied for first the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Sun topped the market in both the entry market (systems priced
under $100,000) and the midrange market (systems from $100,000 to
$1 million).
</P>
<P>
   And in its first year selling high-end servers ($1 million and
up), Sun ranked third in shipments, outpacing Silicon Graphics,
which was fourth, and IBM, which was fifth. Sun's Enterprise 10000
server, also known as Starfire, took the market by storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun has made incredible strides in enterprise computing over
the past few years and really caught competitors by surprise in
1997,'' said Jay Bretzmann, vice president of worldwide systems at
IDC. He said Sun is likely to maintain the momentum this year ``and
will continue to gain share at the expense of its competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-05-98 2114EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
