<HEADLINE>
WANT FRIES WITH THAT E-MAIL?
</HEADLINE>
 SITE-REVIEWS-TEX  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By TOMMY CUMMINGS  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've gotten your Whopper meal for lunch at the Burger King at
182 Broadway in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see ... napkins, straw, salt packet, mustard, e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. E-mail.
</P>
<P>
   It's available at the world's first Internet-enabled Burger King
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled near New York's financial district in lower Manhattan,
the fast-food joint lets its customers not only hoard the
condiments and cardboard crowns but also access any of the 20
high-speed Internet stations ... by king-sizing your Value Meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are sending and receiving e-mail, checking their
stocks and financial news, looking for apartments and jobs,
obtaining travel information, joining chat groups and playing
various interactive games,'' Peter Allen Abramson, Burger King
franchisee, said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes dining, particularly alone, more enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Abramson's customers _ some tourists, some residential, but
mostly from nearby Wall Street _ are allowed 20 minutes to navigate
the Web from high-speed T-1 connections. A two-minute-warning
message appears on the monitor when Internet access is about to be
terminated. Filtering technology prevents access to inappropriate
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Abramson said the concept for the restaurant ``just came in my
head one day.'' The location of his business, which has stiff
competition from other fast-food restaurants, meant he had to have
a niche; ``I had to get something to differentiate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What are the chances of Burger King starting a cybercafe
elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   Abramson answers in his news release: ``I will make my
technology available to other franchisees. It is a concept I want
to share with the entire Burger King system.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's will probably answer the challenge with something
called Power Big Macs or McInternet.
</P>
<P>
   NETTING THE BIKERS
</P>
<P>
   If you can't be one of the 250,000 who are expected to make it
to the Sturgis Rally bike party in Sturgis, S.D., this week, don't
sweat it.
</P>
<P>
   Boot down the kickstand on your hog and then boot up
SturgisLive.com (www.sturgislive.com).
</P>
<P>
   This year, biker enthusiasts can check the event's official site
for live images, event photos, event history, the Chew the Fat chat
room, an online store and archived concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Sturgis Rally and Race, sponsor of the site, plans to post
edited highlights of the rally on its final two days, Saturday and
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU DIG TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Library and Archives Commission has found a way
for those interested in state history to get a closer look at
fragile artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's Texas Treasures site
(www.tsl.state.tx.us/lobby/treasures) features digitally scanned
images of resources from the State Archives' holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts include William B. Travis' letter from the Alamo;
county-by-county vote totals from the 1845 Texas referendum on
annexation; and a collection of flags from the Texas Revolution and
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   State archivist Christopher LaPlante said the site will remain a
work in progress. ``We've just begun to scratch the surface,'' he
said. _ Tommy Cummings, (817) 390-7397 dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/
</P>
