<HEADLINE>
SIX FLAGS SITE IS QUITE A RIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By TOMMY CUMMINGS  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Reynolds of Austin had a dream. It might not have been a
noble civil rights dream, but it was a dream nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up with the feeling that it was very important that I
put a site \R(www.jump.net/\Palanr)\S together that would help
former employees of Six Flags Over Texas find each other,''
Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason unknown to me, I have dreams of returning to
work at Six Flags.''
</P>
<P>
   GIven the raging heat that has enveloped Texas this summer, that
dream sounds more like a nightmare, but Reynolds is passionate
about the amusement park he worked for more than 20 years ago. His
Six Flags Over Texas Employee Contact Page is a log ride down
memory lane for those who have visited the Arlington park, and
especially for those who have worked there.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has collected old pictures of the park, employee
stories, trivia, gone-but-not-forgotten rides and attraction pages,
old park maps and trip reports. He also includes a petition calling
on park officials to bring back the eerie but popular Spee-Lunkers,
who were replaced by Warner Bros. characters at the park's cave
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Writes one petitioner: ``We all want \Rthe Spee-Lunkers back\S
... the Looney Tunes characters scare me worse than they did.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Earth and space science site (observe.ivv.nasa.gov) is
taking a look at impact craters and tsunamis in articles coinciding
with this summer's disaster movies, ``Armageddon'' and ``Deep
Impact.'' In a news release, NASA is promoting two online articles
about the possible aftereffects of a celestial collision.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been to the doctor in a while, you might find
MSNBC's new health area (www.msnbc.com) worth a visit. The site's
``Virtual Checkup'' is a series of quizzes to help you decide
whether you're at risk for various disorders. Articles include an
``Interactive Calculator,'' which gives users an estimate on how
long they will live given their current health, habits and
lifestyle. _ Tommy Cummings, (817) 390-7397
dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
