<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER-SPRAY (San Francisco) _ A Humboldt County sheriff's
deputy testified that pepper spray was so safe that people could
use it instead of horseradish on a dinner steak. The testimony came
at a trial in federal court on whether deputies used excessive
force in wiping pepper spray directly around the eyes of
protesters. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   HARRELSON-JUDGE (San Antonio) _ A one-on-one basketball faceoff
between a federal judge and actor Woody Harrelson has raised the
issue of whether the judge committed an ethics violation. U.S.
District Judge Fred Biery is presiding over a hearing on the appeal
of two life sentences by the actor's father, convicted hit man
Charles Harrelson. By JACQUE CROUSE.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FUNDRAISING (San Francisco) _ With President Clinton's
motorcade waiting outside the St. Francis Hotel, a half dozen
protesters carrying signs reading ``Impeach Clinton Now!'' faced
off against a Clinton die-hard. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-POLLUTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ A federal appeals court has
blocked a New York state regulation mandating that 2 percent of all
vehicles sold in New York beginning this year be non-polluting. The
decision ends New York's bid to lead the country in the number of
zero-emission vehicles, or ZEVs, sold. Most ZEVs are electric cars.
By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-MAIL (San Francisco) _ Pacific Bell allegedly rung up
millions of dollars in unfair billings by charging hundreds of
thousands of customers a ``hidden'' fee for every message on their
voice mail service, a lawsuit says. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-TRAFFIC (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
had another real world experience, one that had him ranting and
vowing to keep the city's commute traffic flowing. By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   LUEDECKE-OBIT (San Antonio) _ Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Alvin
R. Luedecke, who distinguished himself in the military, as an
educator, acting president of Texas A&AMP;M University and manager of
the Atomic Energy Commission, has died in San Antonio at the age of
87. By CYNTHIA KLEKAR.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOW-O'HIGGINS (Colonie, N.Y.) _ When Michael B. O'Higgins is
losing a round of golf, he tries to persuade opponents to settle
their scores and start the betting anew at the next hole. If the
well-known financial adviser times it right, he can play worse than
his competitors, but come out a winner. His contrarian style has
also made him a winner in the financial markets. By CLAIRE HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-O'HIGGINS-SUIT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nationally, Michael B.
O'Higgins' name is no doubt most associated with the investment
strategy known as the ``Dogs of the Dow.'' But in Albany, he has
most recently received attention for a multimillion-dollar lawsuit
brought against him by the Capital District Physicians' Health Plan
in 1994 and settled this year. By CLAIRE HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-COMPUTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Apple Computer boasts that its
new computer, the friendly $1,299 all-in-one iMac aimed at the
education and home consumer market, is so easy to set up that it
literally takes less than eight minutes for even a child to open
the box, plug in everything and get onto the Net. By MIKE SPAIN
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARTIST'S-HOME (Catskill, N.Y.) _ The local historical society
has signed a contract to purchase the long-neglected home of Thomas
Cole, the American artist who founded the Hudson River School of
painting. The home and Cole's earliest studio had been owned by a
struggling foundation in Catskill. By MIKE HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN-COFFEE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The season's hottest drink is
frozen. Not frozen solid, of course. It's a blended beverage mixing
ice, coffee and any number of flavors. Confused? Frozen coffee
drinks, unheard of just two years ago, are suddenly as popular as a
winning Powerball ticket. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
