<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEB-MEDICINE-BOS &LR;      08-12 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-MEDICINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERMEDICINE: AN UNHEALTHY ALTERNATIVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AARON ZITNER   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Patients come from all over the world for treatment
by Dr. Steven Kohler, an emergency room physician at Salem (Mass.)
Hospital. It is a very speedy trip. All they have to do is log on
and tell the doctor where it hurts _ by electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   From their office on the Internet, Kohler and fellow Salem
Hospital physician Kerry Archer have been diagnosing ailments and
prescribing medication for two years to people around the globe.
Now, a host of doctors are rushing on-line, prompting questions
about whether Internet medicine is good medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, a lot of doctors said this is heresy,''
Kohler said. ``But as time goes on, doctors and more of the public
will see this as a significant aspect of the practice of
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohler calls it the ``virtual housecall.'' A woman on vacation
contracts a urinary tract infection, and she needs an antibiotic. A
man on a business trip has a relapse of asthma, and he wants an
inhaler. Kohler says these are typical, minor ailments that can be
evaluated in the live, person-to-person electronic exchanges
offered for $50 by his Internet site, called CyberDocs
(www.cyberdocs.com).
</P>
<P>
   The potential for ``cybermedicine'' could be huge. It is a
low-cost way to match doctors with patients, 24 hours a day,
whether the patient lives in remotest Alaska or crowded Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   At the Physician Insurers Association of America, which
represents malpractice insurers, an official says she has received
at least a dozen inquiries from doctors in the last six months
about setting up sites like Cyberdocs. Relatively low overhead
costs make it an attractive business prospect: Kohler says he and
Archer have spent about $80,000 on their site, and that it has
begun to break even. They claim 20 to 30 consultations weekly, with
about 90 percent involving a request for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But cybermedicine also raises a thicket of red flags. Can
doctors really treat patients they have never seen? Will patients
try to obtain drugs they do not need? Will doctors practice in
areas where they have no expertise?
</P>
<P>
   And, given that patients sometimes misreport their own symptoms,
how can Kohler and Archer trust what a patient is saying?
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, people are putting themselves at risk to access
health care this way,'' said Dr. Thomas Reardon, president-elect of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This service would definitely raise an eyebrow,'' said
Jonathan Linkous, executive director of the American Telemedicine
Association, which promotes greater access to health care through
phones and computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something here that could be very, very great, or it
could be terribly misused, and this needs to be sorted out,'' said
Dr. Nancy Auer, president of the American College of Emergency
Physicians. ``In the meantime, I think it's a case of `let the
buyer beware.'''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been mixing medicine and telecommunications for
years. A patient in California can have his heart monitored or his
X-rays read by a doctor in Boston, with the data moving in real
time over the phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies often ask clients to take their after-hours
questions to 800-lines staffed by nurses, creating the new field of
``tele-nursing.'' And Web sites offer information on every
imaginable medical problem.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, doctors are using the Internet to extend their
practices. At Cyberspace Telemedical Office (www.telemedical.com),
computer users can tap into a medical library, shop for health
products or arrange a conference with a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   From his group practice in Beverly Hills, Calif., cardiologist
Ronald Karlsberg and his colleagues use a Web page (www.cvmg.com)
to advertise their service of offering case reviews for patients
with heart ailments. Unlike CyberDocs, Karlsberg talks to patients
by phone and obtains their medical records on paper.
</P>
<P>
   At CyberDocs, a patient who requests a ``virtual housecall''
automatically pages one of the site's doctors on call, telling the
doctor to log on for a consultation.
</P>
<P>
   The patient describes his or her symptoms and provides a medical
history. The doctor asks questions to make sure that the ailment is
not something serious, which might require in-person care. If
necessary, Kohler and Archer prescribe medication, using a separate
Internet service to arrange for quick delivery to almost anywhere
on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   They offer prescriptions for baldness. They offer the ``morning
after pill'' for women who may have become pregnant. They have
written about 50 prescription for Viagra, but only for patients
located outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There are many things that Kohler says CyberDocs will not do: It
will not prescribe narcotics, Valium or diet pills. He said it
offers only short-term prescriptions for drugs that require close
monitoring, like blood-pressure medication. And because CyberDocs
doctors are only licensed to practice in Massachusetts, they work
only with people who say they are checking in from Massachusetts or
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at several medical trade groups said the future of
CyberDocs and related sites will hinge on how regulators and
insurance companies handle several key issues, such as whether
special licenses will be needed to provide service.
</P>
<P>
   Malpractice insurance could become another issue. Kohler said
that after walking his insurer through his Web service, the company
said his current malpractice policy would cover his on-line
doctoring, with no additional premium. But other insurers may fear
that they are taking on greater risks in tele-medicine, and they
may demand higher premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers set different malpractice premiums for each medical
specialty based on its history of pay-outs. ``But with this kind of
tele-medicine, there is no experience from a claims standpoint to
know how safe or risky this is,'' said Lori Bartholomew of the
Physician Insurers Association of America, the insurers trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   Also complicating matters, malpractice premiums vary by region.
Insurers charge twice as much for a policy in Philadelphia than in
Pittsburgh, even though both are large cities in the same state,
with comparable medical schools and hospitals. ``Maybe Philadelphia
has tougher juries or a more litigious clientelle, but insurers
have a different experience of losses in one city than the other,''
Bartholomew said.
</P>
<P>
   With cybermedicine and similar services, insurers are being
asked to cover physicians who are practicing by Internet not only
across the country, but around the world. Setting premiums could be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CyberDocs has some people asking whether a doctor
can treat a patient he has never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are short of breath, I can see if your fingernails or
lips are turning blue,'' said Auer of the American College of
Emergency Physicians. ``I can see if you're breaking out in a
sweat. This helps me decide how serious your case is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohler responds that CyberDocs does not want to treat patients
who have acute problems or need ongoing care, and that it tells
those clients to see a doctor in person. But at the same time,
there are many medical problems that doctors and patients tackle
together over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Kohler plans to expand his roster of doctors to all 50 states,
and to add a videoconferencing service so that patients and doctors
can see each other. A psychiatrist will soon come on board for
on-line counseling, though CyberDocs is wary so far of prescribing
Prozac or other anti-depression medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential here is enormous,'' Kohler said by phone. He
then interrupted himself. ``I see another patient signing on,'' he
said. It was a regular client who obtains hair-loss medication from
CyberDocs. ``Luckily,'' Kohler said, ``it's Dr. Archer who is on
call tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-06-98 1332EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
