<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT PITCHING TENT IN SILICON VALLEY  
 HOUSE E-MAIL EFFORT RAISES CENSORSHIP ISSUE  
 DIRECTV AND THOMSON PLAN SET-TOP BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven A. Ballmer, who has more often cast a dark shadow over
Silicon Valley, arrived there last week offering peace, love and
local tax payments. Ballmer, newly elevated to the job of president
of Microsoft Corp., announced that his company, based in Redmond,
Wash., would set up a satellite headquarters in a 32-acre corporate
campus in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer is renowned for being the field marshal of Microsoft's
aggressive and highly effective marketing efforts, which have often
left Silicon Valley littered with casualties. And not lost on
anyone is the fact that Microsoft is moving into the hometown of
Netscape Communications Corp., whose David-and-Goliath struggle
with Microsoft is at the heart of the government's antitrust suit
against Ballmer's company.
</P>
<P>
   But Ballmer declared that the campus, with five buildings,
``underscores Microsoft's ongoing commitment to its employees,
partners and customers in the valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which already has 800 employees scattered in
offices throughout Silicon Valley, will move those people into the
Mountain View campus. Yet much more than merely a matter of real
estate consolidation, the step is also clearly meant to raise the
company's profile in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A larger presence in Silicon Valley, industry executives said,
could help Microsoft recruit people from the region's talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft competes for engineering talent, but only the talent
that is willing to move from here to Seattle,'' said Roger McNamee,
general partner of Integral Capital Partners, an investment firm in
Menlo Park, Calif. ``And a lot of people who live in the valley are
religious about the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Others wonder what took Microsoft so long, saying the company's
relations with Silicon Valley might be better now if such a move
had been made years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real reason for the valley's ambivalence toward Microsoft is
that Microsoft didn't show its face around the valley and didn't
make an effort to understand valley culture,'' said Paul Saffo, a
director of the Institute for the Future, a research group in Menlo
Park. ``Microsoft is late to everything, even moving to the
valley.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE E-MAIL EFFORT RAISES CENSORSHIP ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   A congressional committee has endorsed a bill to control junk
e-mail by requiring the senders of unsolicited marketing material
to identify themselves in the body of their messages _ a provision
that opponents said would give Internet service providers the new,
undesirable task of weeding through private communications.
</P>
<P>
   The measure to regulate junk e-mail, or ``spam'' as it is called
by Internet users, was approved by the House Commerce Committee's
telecommunications subcommittee on Thursday as part of a bill
intended to prohibit another communications annoyance:
``slamming,'' or the practice by some telephone companies of
changing their customers' long-distance carriers without prior
approval. A similar anti-spam measure is part of the phone-slamming
bill already passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the House and Senate spam-buster measures
involves the spot in the message where the senders must identify
themselves. Under the Senate bill, a message must be identified as
unsolicited commercial e-mail in the subject header, which would
enable Internet service providers and individuals to filter out
such messages. But the House bill would require such identification
in the body of the message itself, making automatic filtering
difficult or impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Everett-Church, a lobbyist for the Coalition Against
Unsolicited Commercial e-mail, a group that is pushing a bill to
ban spam, called the House bill ``disastrous for consumers and
Internet service providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett-Church said that to filter mail through a notice in the
body of a message, as opposed to the subject header, is much more
labor-intensive because each message would have to be opened. Not
only would that add a further burden to network operators already
struggling to cope with heavy messaging traffic, he said, ``it is
disturbing to Internet service providers who don't want to get in
the practice of sifting through people's private e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We fear that will open up a new realm of censorship based on
content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JERI CLAUSING
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTV AND THOMSON PLAN SET-TOP BOX
</P>
<P>
   The way the makers of television sets see it, the cable industry
stands squarely in the way of the successful introduction of
digital, high-definition television. Most of the major cable
companies say they will not carry the digital programs that the
broadcast networks plan to being offering in November. And since
two-thirds of the nation's homes subscribe to cable, it is little
wonder that the manufacturers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   So Thomson Multimedia, the nation's largest maker of television
sets, is teaming up with DirecTV, the largest direct-broadcast
satellite company, to work around the cable obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV, part of the Hughes Electronics unit of General Motors
Corp., was one of four companies that bought minority stakes in
Thomson Multimedia late last month. As part of that deal, the
companies agreed to build a set-top box for use with
high-definition television sets.
</P>
<P>
   The box will include a decoder for the DirecTV satellite signal
_ as well as a tuner for over-the-air television signals, both
digital and analog. The boxes should sell for about $400 and enable
DirecTV subscribers with television antennas to get cable channels
from DirecTV, and local television stations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, direct-broadcast satellite services, which beam the same
programming to the entire country, have been unable to carry local
television stations, and that has been a large barrier to mass
acceptance. DirecTV and Thomson Multimedia hope the hybrid box will
solve some of the marketing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Of course all of this may remain academic as long as
high-definition televisions are selling, on average, for $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOEL BRINKLEY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-09-98 2122EDT &QL;
</P>
