<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-BUG-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BRITISH CAMPAIGN FOCUSES ON YEAR 2000 COMPUTER 
PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Get your business ready for the bug,'' a gigantic
yellow-and-black billboard screams in the heavily trafficked
Leicester Square subway station near London's West End theater
district.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bug'' in question is the millennium bug, the technological
apocalypse that may wreak havoc on computers at the end of the
century if they have not been upgraded to understand when the year
changes from 1999 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The gigantic billboard is just one of 3,175 posted in and around
London as part of an ambitious $17 million advertising campaign
that seeks to make small and mid-sized businesses aware of the
potential heart attack their computers may suffer without a visit
from a digital doctor, or ``bug buster,'' as Prime Minister Tony
Blair has referred to the technological experts who are in short
supply to re-code Britain's computers.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is sponsored by Action 2000, a government agency
that was set up last fall to help prepare Britain's businesses for
the potential computer problems at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although awareness of the millennium bug is high,'' said
Gwynneth Flower, managing director of Action 2000, ``too many small
and medium-sized businesses have yet to implement a plan of
action.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the agency, only one in four British businesses has
``taken realistic measures to tackle the bug within their own
organizations.'' The campaign, which began several weeks ago in
print and on billboards, aims to provoke computer users to call
Action 2000's telephone hot line or go on line to the
organization's Web site (http://www.bug2000.co.uk) to get detailed
information on the year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the ads have appeared as double-page spreads in The
Times of London, The Daily Telegraph, The Independent and The
Guardian, as well as others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this many companies think they're ready when in fact
they're not, then the small-business sector of U.K. PLC as a whole
is suffering a worrying perception vacuum,'' said Don Cruickshank,
chairman of Action 2000, referring to the low number of companies
that are prepared for the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry experts seem to be doing some worrying of
their own about the effectiveness of the new campaign. ``I don't
want to knock it because it's better than nothing,'' said Andy
Kyte, an analyst at Gartner Group in London. ``But it's
questionable whether the material they are providing is
comprehensive enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The danger is you get everyone aware of the problem
without the resources to support everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising campaign, which was created by the London-based
agency FCA, a unit of Publicis SA, and is also scheduled to include
television and radio spots in early fall, is part of a larger
government-sponsored initiative to support small and medium-sized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Blair announced that the government would spend $160
million to help eradicate the bug, in part, by providing grants to
train 20,000 people throughout Britain to understand the
technological complexities of the problem. The government hopes to
use young people as well as older unemployed or retired people to
help small and mid-sized businesses recode their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without careful preparation, there could be major disruption
to essential services such as benefit payments, or even to
emergency services such as hospitals, the fire and the police,''
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium bug results from a computer's inability to
recognize the year 2000 because it recognizes only the last two
digits of any given year, making many computers interpret the year
2000 as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   One consulting company that has been very critical of the
British government's handling of the year 2000 problem conceded
that the new campaign might be helpful. ``The campaign is the first
positive step the government has made,'' said Richard Coppel, chief
executive of Prove It 2000. ``Other governments ought to take a
look.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coppel still finds fault with the campaign. ``We have a
problem when we keep telling them about the issue but not providing
an adequate solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that with less than a year and a half to go
before January 2000, any information is beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is you need awareness and education,'' Kyte of the
Gartner Group said, ``even if it is at this late stage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-09-98 2044EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
