<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ALASKA-MAN-MEDIA-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENDANGERED LIST OF BACHELORS GOES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Susie Carter divorced her husband four years ago because he
was unhappy about how much time she was spending at work, she knew
what she should do next. She put him on the cover of her magazine,
Alaska Men, whose mission is to advertise the state's plentiful
supply of bachelors to eager, spouse-seeking women around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked. Soon her ex-husband was happily remarried
and living in Britain, and Ms. Carter, unfettered, was able to
direct her energies entirely into being a professional matchmaker
in print.
</P>
<P>
   Issues of Alaska Men usually feature up to 100 men who pay a
``nominal fee'' of $499 to have their picture and biography
published on a half-page. In return, ``they receive hundreds of
letters,'' Ms. Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter, whose ex-husband did not have to pay the fee,
contends that Alaska Men has brought about ``three to five
marriages'' a month, although she acknowledges that it is difficult
to keep a running count.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, the guys meet a girl and just disappear,'' she
said. ``We're the last thing on their minds after they meet their
soul mate.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, Ms. Carter's romance with her magazine is
troubled. Because of a legal battle over its control, publication
has been suspended since winter and bachelors are going unclaimed.
But thanks to the Internet, Ms. Carter has not been completely
stymied. She has set up a World Wide Web site for the magazine and
hopes to resume publication soon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the single fathers she met while she operated a day-care
center in her home that piqued Ms. Carter's interest in starting
the magazine. Many of them, she said, seemed as if they could
benefit from the companionship and support of women.
</P>
<P>
   But women are in somewhat short supply in Alaska, making up only
48 percent of the population, vs. 51 percent nationwide. Moreover,
at least anecdotal evidence suggests that single men far outnumber
single women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter is eager to get back to the business of promoting her
local bachelors in print, sounding responsible for their fate _ as
well as that of the brides-to-be. ``I get mail from women in
communist China,'' she said. ``In Japan, they've done three
television shows. We fly men to Germany _ three of the guys found
mates there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter describes Alaska Men as ``not a huge moneymaker, but
a labor of love.'' She said the magazine, which she started in her
kitchen in 1987, had built up a subscriber base of 25,000, with a
$5.95 cover price. Last year, the magazine signed an agreement with
Media Mix Marketing of Hollywood to take charge of its business and
marketing side. But Media Mix then moved to take control of the
editorial content as well, filing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marriage didn't work,'' said Terry Gross, the magazine's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter, 55, filed a countersuit and argues that Media Mix
would have changed the magazine radically. ``They wanted to glitz
it up so it's more like Cosmopolitan, with model-type guys,'' she
said. ``They don't want rough-looking guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality, she said, is what her readers have come to expect.
``Women want to know what their husbands look like,'' she said.
``Sometimes they're short and fat and wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Media Mix would not comment on the litigation,
but Gross said he hoped a settlement could be reached soon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though the dispute has stalled production of the magazine, a
quarterly, a new issue is stuck in a warehouse while Ms. Carter
tries to raise cash to distribute it. Among her businesses is a
``900'' telephone number that enables readers to hear the
bachelors' voices and to leave messages.
</P>
<P>
   Her foray onto the Web has provided Ms. Carter with a way to
keep Alaska Men, and the men of Alaska, in the spotlight. Though
her matchmaking potential has been limited by the legal dispute,
she herself managed to be brushed by love while interviewing
candidates to serve as Webmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and it was love at first sight,'' she said of
Patrick Smutz, who is now both the magazine's Web expert and her
fiance. ``I saw this man and thought, `What a hunk.' I don't think
that very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic publishing has opened new possibilities for Ms.
Carter, who said that once the print magazine came back, ``we'll
probably be doing both.'' Already, she has added a section called
``Alaska Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Though dismayed by the legal battle, she is still committed to
one prevailing maxim: ``Women all over the world want to find
men.'' All the better, she feels, if they find them in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-09-98 1907EDT &QL;
</P>
