<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Search engines of old jazzed up as portals 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've probably been hearing a lot about portals on
the Internet lately. People buying portals, selling portals,
analysts predicting portals are the future.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, portal is a new name for Web sites that
used to be called ``search engines.'' The difference is that now
these search engines offer much more than just lists of sites: They
have everything from e-mail to free Web pages to stock quotes and
horoscopes. Furthermore, they are all betting the farm their
content will be so compelling and useful you will be willing to
change your browser settings just to look at them before you look
at anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But do these sites have what it takes to keep you coming back
every day? Take a look at the following portals and decide for
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! (http://www.yahoo.com) is winner and still champion of
portal sites, a start page chock-full of goods and services. And if
you want to search the Web, you can do that, too. Some of the
services it offers include travel arrangements, phone service,
Web-based instant messaging service, free e-mail, celebrity chats,
continuous news updates, special news sections and a variety of
other services too numerous to list here.
</P>
<P>
   But what pushes Yahoo! ahead of any and all competition is that
even your grandmother has probably seen ``chief Yahoos'' David Filo
and Jerry Yang counting their money on the cover of Time magazine.
And when it comes to the dizzying array of choices on the Web, to
borrow from Vince Lombardi, branding isn't everything, it's the
only thing.
</P>
<P>
   And although it seems like only yesterday NBC announced its
partnership in CNet's Snap! (http://www.snap.com), the site
unveiled its new look last week. While anything is an improvement
over the old Snap!, it's still impressive how far they've come.
</P>
<P>
   Snap!, like most portal sites, offers users the ability to
customize the site, but here all you have to do is punch in your
ZIP code and _ voila! _ you've got a personalized weather report
and other links every time you visit.
</P>
<P>
   Its special sections are as good as, if not better, than those
at Yahoo!. The section on the Monica Lewinsky scandal features
links to headlines from newspapers around the country as well as TV
and cable outlets not owned by NBC, giving the site bonus points
for truly trying to offer users the best of the Web. Snap! also has
a fun design scheme that's easy to look at and navigate.
</P>
<P>
   With a vast promotional campaign from NBC planned to coincide
with the new fall TV season, Snap! has a shot at becoming a major
portal player and leapfrogging over its competition.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the wonders of Yahoo! and the novelty of Snap!,
there are still some 35 million Netscape users who can't or won't
change their browser's default page from Netscape's Netcenter
(http://www.netscape.com). Netcenter's much-publicized face lift
this year has certainly spruced up the site, but there's still a
long way to go. You can search the Web, read the news from
ABCNews.com or download the newest version of Netscape and
corresponding plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike Yahoo!, Netcenter's category listings don't
provide comprehensive lists of Web sites but instead offer a
selected ``best of breed'' list of sites that is rather short. What
portal you use may come down to how you like your searches, long
and comprehensive or short and sweet. Netcenter also has an
interesting take on branding, using Netscape's green, blue and
yellow color scheme. It's not real pretty, but you never forget
where you are.
</P>
<P>
   With its nifty slogan, ``Get Lycos or Get Lost,''
Massachusetts-based Lycos (http://www.lycos.com) pioneered the idea
of returning only top-rated sites to users, although users can
still search the Web for a broader search. Lycos is well-organized,
but it's hard to tell what services are available.
</P>
<P>
   The areas Lycos trumpets include its free e-mail service and
links to other search services such as CDNow, Barnes &AMP; Noble,
PeopleFind and CityGuide. Lycos also has a targeted news area
similar to Yahoo! and Snap!, but the links aren't as specific or as
focused as the other two. Through Lycos' sister company, Tripod,
users can build their own Web pages through a link on the site.
It's fun but not a reason in and of itself to push Lycos ahead of
the increasingly stiff competition.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
