<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Making A Toolbar Permanent  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  Sometimes when ``replying to author'' of an e-mail message,
I will get a toolbar between the header and the body of the message
that allows me to select fonts and formatting. I can change the
text of my reply to boldface, underline or italicize it _ even
change the color.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the toolbar appear, and is there a way to make it a
permanent feature of my computer? I use Windows 95 with Outlook
Express.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  By default, the formatting toolbar appears whenever you
reply to a message that was composed in HTML _ Internet programming
language that allows for the kind of formatting you described. You
also can use HTML for new messages. To display the toolbar for an
individual message, click the Format menu in the New Message
window, then choose Rich Text (HTML). To display the toolbar in all
new messages, click the Tools menu in the main Outlook Express
window, then choose Options. Click the Send tab, then select the
HTML option for the Mail Sending Format.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I have AOL but have not used it for several months because
I got better service via a local ISP. I have tried in vain to
figure out how to cancel AOL. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; America Online didn't get nearly 13 million subscribers by
making it easy to cancel. There is no way to do it online even
though it's a piece of cake to sign up online. Anyway, you can view
a complete list of ways to cancel by going to the keyword
``cancel.'' In the words of country singer Jo Dee Messina, ``Send a
fax or send me a letter or give me a call, that would even be
better.'' The phone number is (888) 265-8008.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I keep hearing about what a great deal shareware is. But
I'm not really sure what it is. Can you throw some light on the
subject and also tell me where I can find some shareware?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Shareware is software that you can download and try out for
free. If you like it, you're expected to buy it. Shareware includes
utilities to help manage your PC, games and programs such as image
editors.
</P>
<P>
   Most shareware costs less than regular commercial software. For
instance, I've obtained programs for my PalmPilot for as little as
$12. But just because they're inexpensive doesn't mean they're not
good. Winzip, for instance, is a $29 shareware program that many
consider the best data-compression program available.
</P>
<P>
   Good places to look for shareware include www.shareware.com and
www.hotfiles.com. If you're an AOL user, you also can go to the
keyword ``shareware.'' Note that many top shareware programs can be
found in all of the shareware libraries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I've got a problem with my mouse. It keeps freezing, so I
can't even shut down Windows properly. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  It could be one of several problems, says Don Miller,
product specialist for mouse-maker Logitech. But the first thing
you should do is try using the keyboard next time the mouse
freezes. If you can't, it means that your whole system is frozen
and the mouse probably isn't responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely reasons for a frozen mouse, says Miller, are a
problem with the electronic circuits inside the mouse, or a
messed-up driver (a software file that tells the computer how to
use a mouse, printer or other component).
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether the mouse is defective, see if your
computer will work with a different mouse. Or see if your mouse
will work with a different computer.
</P>
<P>
   If the mouse isn't the problem, it's probably the driver _ which
in many cases has been designed specifically for the brand of mouse
you have. Try changing the driver to a generic one that comes with
Windows. You can do this by going to the Mouse icon in the Control
Panel and selecting the General tab.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't solve your problem, it could be that you have a
problem with your video driver or a port-conflict issue _ which you
may need a trained technician to solve.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK &QC; Windows 98 lets you make use of the empty space
on the taskbar that resides at the bottom of the display. You can
put your Internet Explorer links there, or a URL address space for
fast access to the Web. You also can have a Quick Launch area for
icons of programs you use a lot. To explore the possibilities,
right-click any blank area on taskbar, then choose Toolbars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question on computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-98 0039EDT &QL;
</P>
