<SLUG> BC-CPT-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Apple's iMac Is Already a Big Hit  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Apple Computer, it's beginning to feel a lot like 1984 all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's iMac, an eye-catching new home computer that resembles
the original 1984 Macintosh in its breakthrough design and ease of
use, has already shattered the company's record for first-week
orders, with 150,000. The $1,299 computer, which sports a gently
curved aquamarine plastic case, is scheduled to ship Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our single biggest product launch since 1984,'' interim
Apple CEO Steve Jobs said in a telephone interview yesterday. ``The
feedback retailers are getting for this product is the most
exciting they've seen in years.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer dealers also noted a steep run-up in advance orders of
the ``Internet-ready'' computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen this type of excitement from our customers
surrounding a new PC,'' CompUSA CEO Jim Halpin said in a statement.
``We think (iMac) has the potential to become one of (our)
best-selling consumer computers of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1,299 computer is targeted at the 10 million consumers who
own Macs, but have been slowly defecting to cheaper Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   While the sleek Internet terminal has won high marks for its
speed and ease of use, detractors contend it is too simple. They
criticize the iMac for lacking basic connections for printers and
other peripherals, omitting a standard floppy drive and being
difficult to customize.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its shortcomings, an estimated 400,000 units are
expected to ship by the end of September, fueling a sales spike
over the next six months and feeding a recent resurgence at Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Apple intends to stoke the flames of consumers' interest in iMac
with a major radio campaign, beginning yesterday, in which 20
stations nationwide are giving away an iMac daily until its
Saturday debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fun week,'' Jobs said. ``We intend on putting tens
of thousands of these on shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The iMac is the high-tech equivalent of the New Beetle, but it
is reasonably priced,'' said Matthew Rothenberg, director of online
content for Mac Publishing, which yesterday launched iMacworld, a
Web site devoted to the new computer. ``By wedding solid
performance and a groundbreaking design, (iMac) could be a dynamite
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's turnaround _ punctuated by three straight profitable
quarters and a rising stock price _ hasn't gone unnoticed on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the Boston-based mutual fund giant, has
given Apple a big vote of confidence in recent months by scooping
up millions of company shares. The company last month raised its
stake to 12.29 percent, or 16.7 million shares, from 5.75 percent
(7.6 million shares) on March 31, making it the largest Apple
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Apple shares yesterday improved $1.44,to $37.94 _ nearly triple
its trading price at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-98 0037EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
