<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      08-12 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Aug. 12, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle is planning a three-day sports series on
creatine, a controversial dietary supplement that is being used by
middle school, high school, college and professional athletes to
build muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, creatine sales are booming _ from $50 million
in 1996 to $100 million last year. Sales of $300 million are
expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is not an anabolic steroid. But whether it's safe is a
matter of ongoing debate among sports medicine doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie Shilstone, conditioning consultant for the San Francisco
Giants, has steered players toward creatine, but he has misgivings:
``The one question that hangs out there is, what effect does it
have on the heart?''
</P>
<P>
   Photos for these stories, written by the Chronicle's Alex Truex,
are available on the New York Times photo service. For questions,
call Anthony Trowbridge at (713) 220-6845 or the Chronicle Sports
Department at (713) 220-7891.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are for weekend release.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 1
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-ATHLETES (Undated) _ Mark McGwire swears by it. Jeff
Bagwell and Craig Biggio both use it regularly. Creatine has
emerged as the latest magic potion among professional athletes _
and among the younger athletes who watch their every move. But is
the muscle supplement safe?
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-DOCTORS (Houston) _ Dr. John Nash, a Houston
chiropractor who has worked with college athletes and the U.S.
women's Olympic volleyball team, says, ``Creatine per se may not be
a problem, but the lack of fluids can be a major problem. And we
don't know much about how it reacts with whatever other supplements
are being used.''
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Ten questions and answers about
creatine.
</P>
<P>
   DAY 2
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-EDGE (Houston) _ Athletes who are seeking an extra edge
are turning to diet supplements. Phil Garner, manager of the
Milwaukee Brewers, has seen attitudes on nutrition change
drastically since he played baseball in the 1970s and '80s. ``When
I got into baseball,'' he said, ``if you didn't drink a six-pack
and puke before a day game, you weren't a man. Now, a lot of guys
don't drink, but you wonder about all these other things that make
you feel good and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   DAY 3
</P>
<P>
   CREATINE-STEROIDS (Houston) _ Dr. Bill Bryan of the Baylor
Sports Medicine Institute believes steroid use has declined in the
past decade. But he said, ``Once you get into the elite levels of
athletics, the least bit of performance enhancement becomes
important, and those people will try all the tricks.'' Last month,
Olympic shot-put champion Randy Barnes and Olympic sprinter Dennis
Mitchell tested positive for performance-enhancing banned
substances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
