A9971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-12 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE ADVICE FOR THE FIRST STUD 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hey, Bill, don't sweat it. You can be
interrogated on closed-circuit television and make special
prosecutor Ken Starr look like Marcia Clark after going through the
Johnnie Cochran Carwash in a convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, like Mayor Willie Brown of San Francisco suggests, you'll
let the testimony be broadcast nationwide. So Starr wants leaks?
Pay him back with a tsunami of sincerity. Like Brown says, you're a
star, our Mick Jagger.
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 1: Don't emulate Brown and say you have no
ex-girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   No, just get Starr off your cloud, and don't sweat it. Take it
from me, a guy who walked blocks to a deposition in Washington in
an Internet free-speech lawsuit and arrived soaked and wrinkled.
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 2: Make like Letterman and keep the air
conditioning dialed down to 55. It's OK for Mick to sweat, but not
you. Don't ever let them see your makeup run.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, I was dismayed to read that the entire
White House inner circle is meticulously preparing our president
for his TV appearance before the grand jury. It's a multiple first
in American politics and show business, and they're advising him on
everything from the color of his suit to his enunciation of ``I
don't recall.''
</P>
<P>
   This is very disillusioning. I always thought Clinton was the
Laurence Olivier of presidents and could get high poll ratings by
reading the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   It's like finding out that Willie Brown has to have a personal
shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 3: Don't talk too much. Look, I know it's hard,
Bill, and you have a speech handicap called glib-o-mania.
</P>
<P>
   Some words and phrases to avoid: Don't say ``that woman.'' Don't
say oral sex isn't sex. Don't say ``stain'' unless it's part of ``I
abstain.''
</P>
<P>
   Say ``I don't know,'' ``could be'' or ``I don't remember'' with
an air of authority.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I can understand the difficulties of a president's giving
a one-man show as himself after a career of playing everything to
everybody. It's especially hard when an impeachment panel may be
doing the reviewing instead of theater or TV critics.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Clinton is undergoing numerous ``mock
interrogations'' on his alleged affair with Monica Lewinsky by his
lawyers, and among those lawyers is his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Why do I get the idea those interrogations aren't particularly
mock? Why do I worry about White House lamps flying at taxpayers'
expense? Maybe the president is being over-coached. Maybe he should
try method acting.
</P>
<P>
   Let me put it like an acting coach. What is your motivation for
this scene, Bill? To keep from being drummed out of office, and
finding that the Clinton Library is an 18-and-over Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 4: Don't wear a blue dot over your face. If
Starr gives you gloves to try on, think latex undergloves. No
glove, no love.
</P>
<P>
   May I suggest a conservative blue suit, fresh from the cleaners,
like the one you wore before the American people in January when
you denied having ``sexual relations'' with ``that woman''?
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 5: In that January TV appearance, your advisers
took down the pictures on the wall behind you, so as not to detract
from you, the very handsome president. Maybe you want some pictures
up there this time.
</P>
<P>
   Some ideas, depending on the thrust of your testimony: George
Washington with the cherry tree, Alfred E. Neuman or Steve Martin.
It all depends on whether you say ``I cannot tell a lie,'' ``What,
me worry?'' or ``I forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 6: Don't let the camera show the kneehole under
your desk in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Free Advice No. 7: Have you given any thought to playing
background music? Try your friend Barbra Streisand singing verses
like ``People, people who need people many times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would be part of the unlimited,
let-it-all-hang-out strategy. This also would involve bringing a
note from Dr. Ruth, wearing the gold chains of a sad old swinger
and pledging to take the Sexaholics Anonymous 12-step program.
</P>
<P>
   First step: Recognize a higher power, namely Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   If you broadcast your testimony to the American people, they may
be most sympathetic to that strategy. Think of all the sex addicts
and compulsive liars who go on talk shows and confess, all to great
acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, you may want to provide a studio audience to
whoop, cheer and say ``Aw'' on cue. Bolt their chairs down, though,
in case Republican ringers try to throw them, a la Springer.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to use the unlimited, let-it-all-hang-out approach
(also known as ULIAHO _ yell it loud at moments of joy), forget
Free Advice 1 through 4.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, sweat like a revivalist preacher, World Wrestling
Federation star or, yes, Mick Jagger doing the rooster dance.
</P>
<P>
   Make it sincere sweat, though, and let Oprah clutch your sweaty
paw. ``Ah have sinned, Amurrica, but mah wife lets me.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't need any coaching on that. We'll feel your pain. Just
don't come to me for advice on your impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
