</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-STADIUM13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT seating plan riles students
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas graduates and students have
always claimed to have a special relationship with God. They say
the burnt orange sunset is proof positive that the Almighty is a
proud Longhorn.
</P>
<P>
   But some students aren't praising UT athletics officials' plan
to put them closer to the heavens by elevating about 2,000 student
seats to the new upper deck on the east side of Royal-Memorial
Stadium. They say the reassignment unfairly separates student fans
from the action on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a good view of the entire field, but the players look
like ants,'' said Daniel Knight, president of Beta Alpha Rho, a
pre-law fraternity whose members usually buy football tickets
through block seating reserved for student groups. ``You lose the
feeling of being right there in the game. You can't get that in the
upper deck. It ruins the whole atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   UT student David Bain said he won't be buying tickets to
football games this year, because he'd have to move up for alumni
and student recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students provide the pageantry of what the entire
experience of going to the game is about,'' said Bain, a
22-year-old accounting student. ``I have a number of friends who
are football players, and they say that the greatest motivation is
to look over and see us cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   But athletics' officials say the student uproar is overblown.
There are still about 11,000 student seats in the lower deck. Chris
Plonsky, UT associate athletic director for external services, said
the new seating arrangement gives most students better views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they see the upper deck, I wish they'd reserve
judgment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are on the east side's lower deck in the first six
rows and the last 10 rows between the north 30-yard line and the
field's southern end line. Some of the lower deck seating will be
converted to chair-back seats for alumni and donors, costing almost
$1,500 for season tickets to home games this year. Other seats will
be reserved for athletic recruits and certain university athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The seat switch is part of a $93million stadium renovation that
includes the new upper deck, 66 skyboxes, a stadium country club,
chair-back seats and other improvements. The upper deck is expected
to open just days before the first home football game Sept.
5against New Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for students to be assigned to the upper
sections.
</P>
<P>
   Although as many as 5,000 Texas A&AMP;M University student tickets
are available on Kyle Field's lower deck, the majority sit in the
upper deck, said Jim Kotch, A&AMP;M's athletic ticket manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, two recent university stadium renovationshad
different effects on student seating. University of Notre Dame
officials added 22,000 seats to their football stadium last year,
but didn't change the traditional student section _ seniors at
midfield and freshmen in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But when Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., renovated
its stadium last year, students objected to a plan to shift about
1,800 seats toward the goal line, said Mark Wesoloski ,
Northwestern's assistant ticket manager. Officials and students
agreed to shift only 746 seats, he said.
</P>
<P>
   UT Student Government President Annie Holand cq said she also
hopes to broker a compromise with athletics officials in Austin.
She suggested some tweaking of the luck-of-the draw ticket-buying
system. She suggests allowing students to decide whether they want
to sit in the upper deck or the horseshoe area of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Student spirit groups, such as the 360-member UT marching band,
also rely on students to excite spectators, said Paula Crider,
director of UT's Longhorn Bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current student body is definitely our strongest voice in
the stadium,'' Crider said. ``But, hopefully, spreading them around
will electrify (the rest of) the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, students such as Matt Stevenson, a 20-year-old
economics major, are weighing whether sitting in the upper deck is
worth the price of season tickets for students, which run as high
as $276 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it's a matter of money'' for the athletics
department, he said. ``But it's getting expensive . . . to pretty
much sit up there and bake.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wilson, a 1972 UT business school graduate and Austin
attorney, spends nearly $1,000 each year on football tickets and
has attended every home game since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the students get over it: ``If they're worried about
where they're sitting,'' he said, ``they're entirely too sober.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Shah writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
