<HEADLINE>
OUT OF BRICKS AND MORTAR, A NEW ORLEANS TALE EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ There are long waiting lists for apartments in the
Pontalba buildings, two red-brick symbols of antebellum grandeur
that face each other across Jackson Square in the French Quarter.
And since the city of New Orleans controls the ``Upper Pontalba''
and the state owns the ``Lower'' there have long been suspicions
that politics helps pick the tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Framing a daily scene of street artists, musicians, tarot seers,
magicians, and mimes, the buildings seem steeped in prestige and
romance, yet few people knew the strange history behind the
properties until the recent publication of the book ``Intimate
Enemies,'' an account of an arranged marriage in the 19th century,
a bloody family feud over money, and a strong-willed woman, the
Baroness Micaela Almonester de Pontalba.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on 20 years of research in New Orleans and Paris, author
Christina Vella, a history professor at Tulane University, has
written a narrative of Micaela's troubled life that also describes
old New Orleans and the class rivalries that persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Orleans is full of colonial records,'' Vella said over
lunch the other day. ``Property settlements, wills. In every record
you open you'll find a compendium of nonsense'' in which earthly
possessions are listed down to the cheapest hairpin. It enabled her
to restore a forgotten past to the iron-laced facade of the
Pontalba buildings.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when New Orleans was under Spanish control and the
central square was known as ``Plaza de Armas,'' a nobleman named
Don Andres Almonester financed the construction of St. Louis
Cathedral, its presbytery, and the Cabildo, the seat of city
government, on the west side of the block. By 1782, he had also
bought all of the lots flanking the square on its north and south
sides, and the row of apartments became a source of substantial
rental income for the Almonester family. ``It was a Spanish custom
to have residences close to the center of power,'' Vella said.
</P>
<P>
   After Almonester's death, a marriage was arranged in 1810
between his 15-year-old daughter, Micaela, and Celestin Delfau de
Pontalba, the son of French aristocrats. She moved to France, and
almost immediately her husband and in-laws set off an epic struggle
over her dowry and control of her family's property in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Because Micaela's mother had upgraded the cottages on the
square, later renamed to honor Andrew Jackson following his victory
in the Battle of New Orleans, she clung to the lots. After a
petition by the Pontalbas, Almonester's widow grudgingly added part
of the property to her daughter's dowry with the stipulation that
Celestin could not collect the rent without Micaela's permission _
``a provision,'' the author noted, ``that would be unhesitatingly
ignored as soon as the blotter was lifted from the document's last
signature.''
</P>
<P>
   In scenes out of a 19th century marriage from hell, Micaela
acceded to a pact with the Pontalbas following her mother's death,
giving her husband administrative control over the property. In
1827, Celestin moved quickly to plunder it. ``He lost no time
getting to New Orleans, making improvements to the houses ... and
raising the rents,'' Vella wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Micaela traveled to New Orleans to reclaim
the property through American courts. Back in France, her
father-in-law, Joseph Xavier Delfau de Pontalba, seethed over the
loss of income. After Micaela felt obligated to move back to the
Pontalba estate outside Paris, her father-in-law shot and gravely
wounded her, then killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 1839 that Micaela finally won property rights.
By this time, Vella wrote, the quarrel had ``destroyed the family
and shattered the happiness'' of the three children born to Micaela
and Celestin. But the story was not complete.
</P>
<P>
   Micaela returned to New Orleans for a few years at midcentury.
Although the land on Jackson Square was ``the third most valuable
property in the Vieux Carre,'' Vella wrote, ``she did not realize a
great profit from it because her tenants were notoriously
delinquent.'' And the 21 apartments were dilapidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, filth of every kind characterized New Orleans,''
according to the book. Offal was exposed everywhere, turkeys were
``commonplace pedestrians,'' and dogs roamed the streets.
``Bounties were offered for dead dogs until it was found that
policemen were capturing dogs for a reward instead of chasing
unremunerative criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was far worse than the modern scenes of filth in New Orleans
described last month by Mike Ditka, the coach of the New Orleans
Saints, in a Sports Illustrated interview that created an uproar in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who think New Orleans is filthy have never been
elsewhere,'' said Vella, who grew up in the city. Because New
Orleans is below sea level, it was subject to ``wet filth,'' she
said, but it was really no worse than conditions in East Coast
cities.
</P>
<P>
   To improve the square in 1849, Micaela underwrote the
construction of a pair of four-story buildings with luxurious
apartments. ``No one knows who designed the Pontalba buildings,''
Vella wrote, but the spirit of French architect Henri Labrouste
``haunts the New Orleans buildings'' where brick, iron, and curved
space were ``used to create a feeling both of airiness and
solidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Micaela transformed the neighborhood, Vella said. ``She made it
into a prestige address, the most desirable place in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Lind, an American theater star, was one of the first
residents. But Union forces bivouacked in the buildings for the
occupation of New Orleans during the Civil War, and the property
became ``an unspeakable slum,'' Vella said.
</P>
<P>
   When Micaela died in 1874, annual rents from the Pontalba
buildings totaled only $3,402 and tenants owed $4,929. The property
was eventually sold.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 20th century, a prominent New Orleanian bequeathed
the Lower Pontalba to the state and the building was renovated. A
few years later, a group of businessmen bought the Upper Pontalba
and gave it to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Property managers of the two buildings deny that any favoritism
is involved in leasing the apartments, though confidants of Mayor
Marc Morial and Edwin W. Edwards, the former governor, wound up
with places there.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hand, director of the French Market Corp. that manages the
Upper side, said there are two waiting lists, an internal file of
current residents who want a more desirable apartment and another
with 60 names of those who hope someday to find a spot there.
Turnover is fairly rapid for fourth-floor walkups, he said, priced
at roughly $400 a month, but there are lengthy waits for more
expensive apartments.
</P>
<P>
   At the other building, applicants sometimes wait years for a
choice apartment with balcony views of the Mississippi River, the
cathedral, and the activity on Jackson Square. Despite the noise,
``some people think it's the greatest thing this side of the
Waldorf-Astoria,'' said James Sefcik, director of the Louisiana
State Museum and manager of the Lower Pontalba. ``They are the only
homes built on the psychological heart of New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a century and a half, the buildings coexist
peacefully on Jackson Square, while in France, Micaela's body lies
in a crypt beside her husband and her vengeful father-in-law. No
members of the family are left in New Orleans. The only vestiges of
Micaela's legacy are her initials, A.P. for Almonester and
Pontalba, cut into the iron grillwork on the Pontalba balconies.
</P>
</TEXT>
