<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC AUTHOR WARNS OF THE DANGERS OF RELIGIOUS RELATIVISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago Pope Paul VI's encyclical condemning artificial
birth control sent shock waves through the Roman Catholic world.
</P>
<P>
   Humanae Vitae dashed the hopes of many Catholics who believed
church fathers might be willing to amend religious teachings on
certain thorny contemporary issues. Instead, the pope stood firm.
The repercussions of Paul's encyclical still reverberate.
Fundamentally, Humanae Vitae made the question of authority the
root of all tensions in Roman Catholicism today.
</P>
<P>
   In a new book, author Roger LeBlanc argues that the spread of
dissent throughout the church on issues ranging from the role of
women to human sexuality is eroding papal authority and endangering
the church's future.
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc, who holds a pontifical certificate to teach Catholic
catechism, believes the single biggest threat to the papacy is the
rise of religious relativism _ the rejection that there is one true
set of beliefs that emanate from the Holy See, whose authority can
be traced directly to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious relativism is a denial that there is one true faith
that is valid, the same for all people at all times and places,''
LeBlanc writes in ``Relativism As Religion: Tracing its Historical
Roots to the Modern Day Crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in fact the very cause of religious division in the
world,'' he writes. ``In His eternal wisdom, Christ left something
among us by which we can say: `This is indeed the true faith.' He
left us a guide, a true rule of faith. It is the papacy, the
companion of sound reason.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc's book is sure to raise the hackles of non-Roman
Catholic Christians who bristle at any suggestion that the Vatican
possesses the sole copyright on how to be a proper Christian. After
all, it was fierce disagreements over the role of the pope that led
to the many schisms in Christianity over the centuries. And it is
questions over the papacy that present some of the biggest
stumbling blocks to Christian unity.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting under a statue of the Virgin Mary in the living room of
his mother's Natick, Mass. home, LeBlanc said he doesn't want to
antagonize other Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book is not a call to arms,'' he said. ``I'm not raising
the swords. I would simply ask people to look at the question of
what gave birth to thousands of Christian denominations. And look
at the reason for the Catholic Church's claim to absolute truth and
the pope's claim to absolute authority. These are things that need
to be discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc said a main motivation behind the book is to lay down a
challenge to all Catholics to examine what it is that makes them
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite various polls suggesting that most American Catholics
oppose the Vatican on numerous controversial topics ranging from
homosexuality to a married clergy, Le-Blanc said there is a growing
cadre of younger Catholics whose views are more in line with Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a Catholic, but you if you are going to
call yourself one at least accept what that means,'' LeBlanc says.
``If you look at the story of Adam and Eve, you realize that
religious relativism is what caused man to lose grace with God. How
do people expect to embrace religious relativism and still find
their way to God? And Christ gave back to man what he lost in Eden
by giving him the papacy.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc's book comes at a crucial moment for the church. Vatican
officials say Pope John Paul II is expected to release a major
encyclical attacking relativism in the fall. Angered by what he
sees as unjustified assaults on church teaching and authority, John
Paul has issued edicts that attempt to dampen dissent and increase
the power of the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Recent pronouncements have been aimed at curbing theologians who
challenge church dogma, and limiting the role of lay people in
local churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the pope is afraid of losing his authority,''
LeBlanc says. ``He's trying to defend the faith. If you don't have
ultimate authority rest in the papacy, you reduce religion to
something of man's own invention _ and then there is no more reason
to discuss matters of faith because it's all purely subjective.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _In its first comments on the investigation involving President
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky, the official newspaper of the
Archdiocese of Boston says the president's private actions are a
public concern.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial in this week's Pilot takes issue with observations
by some political pundits that many Americans believe whatever may
have occurred between Clinton and Lewinsky is a private matter
between consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without speaking from an Olympian perch of self-righteousness
... such talk is moral nonsense,'' the Pilot argues. ``Marriage
vows are public vows. And to those who are quick to call sexual
misconduct something `private' _ tell that with a straight face to
Chelsea Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   _Apparently seeking to increase its involvement in the highly
charged debate over homosexuality, a prominent conservative
Christian organization has hired two people who say they are former
practicing homosexuals to work on public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the Family has hired Amy Tracy, former press secretary
for the National Organization for Women, and John Faulk, a former
male prostitute, to be active players in the organization's
campaign to combat gay activism.
</P>
<P>
   _Providing evidence of some softening in relations between the
United States and Cuba, the National Council of Churches has sent
its first direct relief flight to Cuba in two years. The flight
contained $143,200 in medical and other supplies bound for two
medical clinics in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   After Pope John Paul II's historic trip to Cuba in January,
President Clinton bowed to intense pressure and lifted restrictions
on direct humanitarian flights between the United States and the
Caribbean island nation earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   _The Salvation Army, in a campaign to emphasize the
organization's religious foundation, has announced plans to begin
publishing a semi-annual academic journal this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of ``Word and Deed: A Journal of the Salvation
Army and Ministry'' will include articles by Salvationist
theologians on such topics as ``Biblical Foundations for the
Doctrine of Holiness'' and ``Wesleyanism and Holiness Teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   The journal is intended to link the the Army's many social
ministries to its theological roots, according to Jeff McDonald,
managing editor of the War Cry, the Salvation Army's official
national magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
