<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S IDEA OF BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. -- No false advertising greets the customer
here. The headline on the 1998 season schedule proclaims, ``There's
a brand new theme park in Anaheim.'' Captioning an overview of
water fountains, fireworks, and baseball, the Anaheim Angels
present ``Edison Field ... the ultimate playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is just one element in this theme park, which competes
with other Orange County attractions like Knott's Berry Farm,
Ripley's Believe It or Not, the Movieland Wax Museum, the Crystal
Cathedral, and the Richard Nixon Presidential Library and
Birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest draw is Disneyland, owned by the Walt Disney Co.,
which bought the Angels from the singing cowboy, Gene Autry, in
1996. The team once struggled against football for dominance in a
concrete 1960s stadium. Now it faces a slugger's lineup of ace
marketers, pitchmen, and avatars of family fun. Baseball may be
pure, but the Disney bullpen is deep.
</P>
<P>
   After two years and $117 million, a ballpark emerged from the
one-size-fits-all fever that expanded many stadiums for football.
The Los Angeles Rams are now in St. Louis, and the football seats
are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Identity is a sometime thing in cloverleaf heaven. The team was
the Los Angeles Angels, then the California Angels. Now they are
named after Anaheim, baptized by German settlers in 1857 after the
Santa Ana River and the Teutonic word for ``home.'' This place was
home to orange groves until Walt Disney built his theme park in
1955 with subthemes like Fantasyland and Adventureland. Now his
company has added what seems like ``Baseball-land.''
</P>
<P>
   The hype begins with the national anthem, when the ``rocket's
red glare'' produces real fireworks and waterspouts, blending
Francis Scott Key and MTV. The pyrotechnics emerge from a rockpile
beyond center field, a backdrop lacking the verisimilitude of the
Baltimore warehouse in Camden Yards or the Citgo sign behind Fenway
Park. This theme looks as authentic as Fred Flintstone's miniature
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The public address system announces each batter with thundering
resonance, whether it be Babe Ruth or a banjo hitter just called up
from Vancouver. It is all unmodulated, all robotic, a cartoon
version of Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   The concourses are wide and handsome, with dessert carts
groaning with goodies like ``Chocolate Success Cake.'' The
restaurants are busy, and the souvenir store moves product, and
only one product. Fans seeking a Red Sox or Yankee cap must shop
elsewhere, because this marketing is pinpoint-targeted.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels kept their pre-Disney colors of red and blue but,
according to the media guide, ``a periwinkle blue was added as a
main third color. The Angels logos were designed by Disney Consumer
Products and approved by Major League Baseball Properties. The team
lettering marries an angel's wing with a speeding ball. Together
they create a logo that immediately says `Angels' and gives the
feeling of fluidity and motion of the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   This prose shimmers with the wan defeatism of a marketer who
wanted to name the acquisition the Anaheim Lion Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Defeatism is a problem on the field, too. The Angels were atop
the American League West for a while, although they would not be
near first place in any other division in baseball. A summer swoon
makes postseason play unlikely. The trading deadline passed with no
fireworks, and many fans think the team is run by Doc, Sleepy,
Grumpy, and Dopey.
</P>
<P>
   Disney hired the New York architect, Robert A.M. Stern, to
provide some sophistication. Some of his touches, like green and
copper colors for usher's uniforms and concourses, mitigate the
zeal with which Anaheim resists sophistication in its postgame rush
to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball as in real estate, it's location, location,
location. People may enjoy the game at Edison Field, but the
revamped ballpark works better as a vast Disney billboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
