<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      08-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST PEEK AT MOL; BREAKING SILENCE OF SALINGER AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a famous episode of ``Seinfeld,'' Elaine is appalled to
discover a nipple peeking out from her shirt in the photo of
herself she used on her Christmas cards. But somehow I don't think
actress Gretchen Mol is particularly upset or surprised by the
spiky revelations she shares on the cover of the thick new Vanity
Fair for September. (Observers will need to decide for themselves
whether photographer Annie Leibovitz turned the heat way up, or way
down.) An unknown actress whom VF is trying to ``break'' in the
manner of Matthew McConaughey and Matt Damon, both of whom won VF
covers before they met with success, Mol stars in two forthcoming
movies that are rating high on the advance buzz-o-meter: Woody
Allen's ``Celebrity,'' with Leonardo DiCaprio, and ``Rounders,''
with Damon. In the meantime, she really doesn't have much to say
about her last days of anonymity, or her rogue of a pet rabbit.
We'll have to wait and see if Mol's Pre-Celebrity Moment evolves
into a Damon-like year or, alas, fame of the McConaughey
Woulda-Coulda-Been variety.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbing piece in VF is an excerpt from Joyce Maynard's
forthcoming memoir about her relationship with J.D. Salinger. When
she was 18, and he was 53, the two had an unlikely nine-month
affair that Maynard has been unwilling to chronicle out of respect
for the press-phobic author's privacy. But now she tells their
story with a vengeance, portraying Salinger as a bitter, eccentric
loner obsessed with homeopathy who would force himself to vomit
unhealthy food. At the beginning of the relationship, he treats her
like his favorite daughter, writing letters to her with creepy
lines like ``I haven't had a pal like you before, you know,
kiddo.'' In the middle, Maynard moves in with Salinger and they
unsuccessfully explore a sexual rapport, as Maynard finds she can't
physically relax in bed. And at the end, he becomes an icy stranger
who despises her willingness to promote herself as a writer and
asks her to leave his house. (We never learn where her parents
stood on all of this.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard story to read, partly because of the age-power
imbalance in their affair, partly because of unaddressed questions
about Maynard's motivation in telling all. Is she using us to get
back at him, revealing the secrets of a man who at one point says
to her, ``A writer's face should never be known''? Is she crusading
against the potential harmfulness of extreme May-December
relationships? Is she simply cashing in on her experience? In any
case, we probably wouldn't care much about Salinger's dietary
habits if information about his life weren't so famously withheld.
</P>
<P>
   For a small bit of irreverence, check out the Tommy Hilfiger ads
near the front of the issue, a White House motif featuring a
barefoot young woman lounging on a desk that could only belong to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's hard to resist terribly dramatic cover lines
designed to get you into a magazine fast _ the glossy equivalent of
those ultra-italicized movie-trailer voice-overs. On its September
cover, Details promises us that its profile of Matt Damon will
expose us to ``The Dark Side of Oscar's Golden Boy,'' truly a big
promise since Damon and his 1,000-watt smile seem quite immune to
darkness. But the article doesn't even pretend to dig in the dirt,
serving as little more than yet another addition to the thousands
of stories already chronicling Damon's happy rise to stardom, his
friendship with Ben Affleck, his respect for idols like Tom Hanks,
his closeness to his mother, etc., etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker for Aug. 17 includes a Talk of the Town piece by
William Styron, who served on the editorial board that compiled the
Modern Library's controversial list of the 100 best novels written
in English this century. Styron confesses that he felt ``a little
shocked at what the ten of us had wrought, not only in respect to
the list's glaring omissions (no Toni Morrison, no Patrick White,
only eight women in the lot) but in respect to its generally
oppressive stodginess.'' He says the problem was the voting
process, which, as he describes it, sounds seriously inadequate, as
well as the absence of an in-person meeting of the board to debate
the results. Meanwhile, Entertainment Weekly, the magazine that
loves nothing better than a good list, has a story, ``Listomania,''
that explores the cultural need to compile lists like the top 100
novels or movies. Here's the list of reasons we like lists,
abbreviated: 1) to make the information overload of modern life
more manageable; 2) to counteract the temporary nature of modern
life by building lasting structures; and 3) We dig numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
