<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-STRESSED-BOS &LR;      08-12 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STRESSED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRESSED ERIC': A GUY WHO NEVER GETS A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
STRESSED ERIC 
On: NBC, Wednesday nights 
With the voice of: Hank Azaria 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Stressed Eric'' is Eric Feeble, a man whose life is always on
the verge of explosion. He is a single father raising a daughter
allergic to everything she loves, including her dolls, and a son
who won't utter a word but insists on shoving everything into his
mouth. He and his wife are divorced _ ``I'm going for a swim in the
lake of me,'' she tells him _ and he has replaced her with a
mumbling, alcoholic au pair who vomits every time she opens her
mouth. His job as a numbers cruncher is hanging on by a thread, no
thanks to his hostile secretary, who spends her days chatting about
boyfriends on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Modern life, in other words, has a contract out on poor
beleagured Eric Feeble. And if that vein in his forehead doesn't
stop its rabid pulsing, modern life just might land the guy in an
emergency room, or, more likely, an asylum. An animated series
imported from Britain for a six-week run on NBC, ``Stressed Eric''
is a brash, relentless half-hour of TV that captures the insanity
we've all felt when time is definitely not on our side. As his
daughter's lips swell from eating the wrong cereal, and his son
refuses to say ``baaaah'' for his role as Sheep No.6 in the school
nativity, and his au pair regurgitates last night's spirits down
the drain, and his boss waits impatiently for a report he dropped
outside his house, Eric Feeble does not manage to find even a
moment's peace. And it doesn't help that he lives next door to the
Perfects, a family whose luck seems to improve with every laurel
laid on their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Ads for ``Stressed Eric'' proclaim that the show is ``spicier
than `South Park.''' The ads, of course, are overstated: ``Stressed
Eric'' doesn't use political incorrectness and cultural irony as
its stock in trade, relying instead on the more familiar comedy of
good intentions foiled _ sometimes violently _ by circumstances.
The show is edgy in its unwillingness to give Eric a break, and in
its resistance to sentimental resolutions, but it is nonetheless a
classic example of animatated slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the voice of Hank Azaria has been dubbed over the
original dialogue voiced by English actor Mark Heap for American
audiences. For NBC, Eric has been made into an American dad living
in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
