<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-12 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST THE TICKET IF YOUR HEART'S IN THE HEARTLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There used to be a professor at the Harvard Business School who
famously asked corporate chieftains, ``What business are you really
in?'' He convinced a struggling railroad company that it was really
in the booming transportation business. They invested millions in
the trucking and airline industries and lost their shirts. A stern
lesson for the client; however, at $10,000 a day, our B-School man
came out all right.
</P>
<P>
   But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   We here in the media often wonder: What business are we really
in? And the answer is: We are in the business of teaching you how
to live. Just look around you: Country Life, Vermont Life, Southern
Living, Coastal Living, or my current favorite, Midwest Living.
</P>
<P>
   The title took me aback when I first spotted ML on the newstand.
There was a time when I might have cavalierly dismissed life
``between the mountains'' as dull and devoid of content. But during
the past two summers, I crossed the continent twice, and each time
I spent a full week in the heartland. So now, when I dismiss the
Midwest as dull and devoid of content, I do so from a position of
authority.
</P>
<P>
   But of course this vibrant magazine, which has doubled its
circulation in the past decade, and bulges with advertising for
wholesome foods and roomy, American-made cars, puts paid to my
callous Eastern snobbery. Unlike Arizona Highways or New England's
Yankee magazine, which have more subscribers outside their
territory than in, 90 percent of ML readers still hail from the 12
Midwestern states. A cynic might suggest that people who've put the
Freeman, S.D., Schmeckfest in their rearview mirror don't want to
be reminded of it. But I am not a cynic.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to do in the Midwest? What could I have been thinking?
The Strategic Air Command has just opened up a new museum on
Interstate 80. What about the Ashland, Wis., Smelt Run? (You run;
the smelt frolic in Lake Superior.) Or what about Buzzard Day in
Hinckley, Ohio? ``Join in this welcome-back party for the thousands
of migrating turkey vultures that have come home to nest,'' ML
suggests. Why not? How about that Tibetan restaurant in
Indianapolis? India-no-place no more!
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere to eat in the Midwest? What could I have been thinking?
They're serving gourmet dishes that stick to your ribs, not to
mention your arteries. Jasper, Ind., boasts the Schnitzelbank,
where ``entrees range from goulash to sauerbraten.'' Or how about a
table for two at Little Eva's Dumpling Factory of Medford, Wis.?
I'm looking forward to the St. Urho's Day festival in Finland,
Minn. ``You'll feel Finnish when you eat a steaming bowlful of kala
moijakka (fish soup),'' the ML critic informs me. Either that, or
you'll be Russian to get out of there.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere to stay? Rest your bones at the Nordic Inn Medieval Bed
Breakfast in Crosby, Minn. ``Odin's Loft has a king-size bed tucked
inside a dragon-headed Viking ship,'' we learn. Or at Ohio's
all-stone Ravenwood Castle, with Rapunzel's tower and cottages
boasting ``jolly old English themes.'' Here in New England, those
would be ``jolly olde English themes.'' The Midwest can only aspire
to our heights of Anglo-phoniness.
</P>
<P>
   Here to say something nice about the featureless cradle of
American civilization is Dan Kaercher, the founding editor of
Midwest Living. ``I would be glad to defend flyover country,'' says
Kaercher, who sounds corn-fed but in fact comes from upstate New
York. He's heard all the gibes. ``Midwest Living _ isn't that an
oxymoron?'' Or after he published his first issue, friends joshed
that he would never come up with enough material to fill a second
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone in the Midwest, with the possible exception of
James McDougal and Web Hubbell, Kaercher comes off as
straightforward and likable. He's certainly got his finger on the
regional pulse. ``As we speak, there's a lady inside a refrigerated
barn carving a life-size butter cow that will be the prize
attraction at the Iowa State Fair. Do you have anything like that
in New England?''
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, we do not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
