<HEADER>
A0030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BOXING-BOS &LR;      08-12 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BOXING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LA CLUB, BOXERS, CELEBS ALL SEE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some of the world's best boxers work the bags at
Freddie Roach's small, steamy gym in a Hollywood strip mall.
Heavyweight contender Michael Moorer. Lucia Rijker, the female
champion. O.J. Simpson defense attorney Robert Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   Roach, a Massachusetts native, will take on anyone gutsy enough
to step into his ring, located right above the Wash 'n' Fold
laundromat. Of course, Roach doesn't fight them himself anymore.
The former featherweight turned trainer 10 years ago, after 150
amateur bouts and 54 professional matches.
</P>
<P>
   Now he trains 14 professional fighters at his Wild Card Boxing
Club and dozens of ``executive'' boxers, more accustomed to taking
meetings than punches. Side by side, they work the rope, glove up
and hit the mitts. Sometimes they even spar together. This is not
the sort of aerobic fisticuffs offered at health clubs. This is
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's controlled,'' emphasized Roach, 38. ``It's fun for them
to say they got in there with a world champion. But they're not
delusional.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who every so often asks to go jab-to-uppercut with one
of the club's resident pros, successfully defended Simpson against
double-murder charges, and he says he can defend himself in the
ring against an opponent his size: 160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie wouldn't allow me to be in jeopardy,'' said Shapiro,
who has been boxing with Roach for five years. ``If I was sparring
with a middleweight or a superweight, I would be killed. But if
it's a lower weight, I try to hold my own and I usually can.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are fighting words to Roach's real boxers, who say only
their good graces allow the ``white-collar'' boxers to survive.
Six-time world champion James Toney, imposing even when wearing
street clothes and a smile, simply smirked when asked about taking
on Shapiro or Mickey Rourke, who went from acting in movies like
``Diner'' to boxing professionally under Roach's tutelage and back
to acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting?'' Toney said. ``Nah, I'm just messing around with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Yvonne Trevino, a pro with an impressive word of mouth,
says she toys with the boys, especially newcomers who forget to
move their heads out of the way of her fist. Mostly, though, she's
not allowed to take a swing and instead works on her defense by
dancing around punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My real sparring partners, the guys, can make me see stars,''
said Trevino, who comes from a family of fighters and has a 7-2-1
record. ``The other guys? Ha.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Simon, a Hollywood producer who was one of the co-creators
of ``The Simpsons'' and now directs ``The Drew Carey Show,''
understands who is at whose mercy in the ring. Simon began boxing
four years ago, sick of daily runs and serious about slimming down.
Now he can bob and weave like a pro _ almost. He broke his nose
when it connected with the sharp side of the padded mitts that
trainers hold while boxers practice throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pros don't hit me hard unless, for some reason, I get
lucky and hit them,'' said Simon. ``And then they hit me as hard as
they can until I fall down. ... But it doesn't make me nervous or
afraid because I feel like I should get knocked out, and if I don't
I'm doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Roach says he admires the would-be fighters, both
for their heart and their willingness to face fists the size of
hams. Roach, the son of a fighter, triumphed over his first
opponent at age 8, winning the Junior Olympics in New England,
where his mother, Barbara, is still secretary of the boxing
commission. At the time, he weighed 50 pounds, the smallest
weight &UR;  &LR; class, and then kept fighting for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to train Rourke got him to Los Angeles, where the
pair opened a gym together, then later closed it on what Roach says
was the advice of Rourke's accountant. But he was already a
sought-after trainer by boxers who wear suits to their real jobs,
and those whose jobs call for nothing more than a mouthpiece and
satin shorts. Two-and-a-half years ago he opened the Wild Card.
</P>
<P>
   Today the gym has about 75 members, a third of them professional
fighters, two-thirds of them secretaries, actors, and studio
executives who pay $50 a month for gym access, plus $20 or so an
hour for private sessions with Roach or one of his four trainers.
Anyone with a pro or amateur license pays $25 monthly, although
Roach also takes 10 percent of his pros' winning purses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides connecting fists to faces, boxers can also make
post-career connections at the club. For instance, champion Troy
Baudoin, who fought professionally from 1985 to 1993 and then
became a trainer, now also acts in movies and music videos. The
upside is a pain-free career for a change. The downside is he
suddenly has to worry about his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people I go in the ring with are people who can't do
me no harm,'' Baudoin said. ``Every now and then they'll touch me
and I'll tap them to show I'm letting them get away with it. ... I
like playing with them. I don't try to kill them even if I could.
That would be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Maniquis, a film editor at Miramax, says he can't believe
how much longer three rounds, or nine minutes, feels in real life
than on TV. Like most of the non-fighters who are in it for the
workout, he usually does only drills. But sometimes he can't resist
the real ring. So far, he's had his nose bloodied and felt dizzy
and nauseated for an entire day _ despite donning the head gear
that all sparring partners wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're easy on me, because I stink,'' said Maniquis.
``They'll smack me once or twice in the head to let me know who's
boss. But they'll also say, `Go easy on the kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Shannon L. McIntosh, a senior vice president at Miramax,
says she doesn't want anyone going easy on her, male or female.
Now, after a year of working out with Roach, she is considering
going amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spar with girls, whoever will get in the ring with me,''
McIntosh said. ``I've been hit in the head by guys. It keeps you
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach worked McIntosh's corner during the local white-collar
fights last August, and she calls him a ``calming force'' with
flawless technique. Shapiro cites his ``knowledge and dedication,''
saying he trains lawyers the same as a world champion. Rourke once
publicly admitted that Roach had made him cry.
</P>
<P>
   With his baggy shorts, slight but tight frame and wiry red
goatee, Roach doesn't look fierce. But inside the gym _ walls
covered with autographed pictures of boxers and posters advertising
their bouts _ his word is law. The New England featherweight
champion of 1980 _ a title his father, Paul, held in 1947 _ earned
him a name as a trainer in the boxing capital of the world, Las
Vegas. Now movie stars such as Mira Sorvino, who hasn't been at the
Wild Card for a while, know his name, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't treat anyone special,'' said Roach, surrounded by
sweat-covered fighters all focusing on the bag or body in front of
them. ``Everyone here's the same, except maybe in the ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
