<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-GINGRICH-0813     08-12 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-GINGRICH-0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS WITH PAST U.S. LEADERS, FOR GINGRICH, IRISH EYES ARE SMILING
DURING VISIT
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Newt Gingrich grips a 10-pound
concrete block, hoists it from the stack in his work-gloved hands,
walks briskly 10 feet and plunks it neatly in the cast frame of a
house foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The house, a project of Georgia-based Habitat for Humanity, will
sit in the Glencairn housing project on a hillside overlooking
Belfast. It will be dubbed ``The House that Congress Built,'' and
indeed six House members from both parties and their spouses joined
Gingrich in the labor Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   His face a little flushed with exertion, the Speaker of the U.S.
House of Representatives grabs another block and places it at the
end of the last one. A half-dozen TV cameras and a few still
photographers catch it all, the symbolically potent images of a
prominent American politician helping to lay the foundation for
Northern Ireland's future. Through it all, Gingrich sustains a
broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to escape the sense that the speaker is laying
another foundation on this sunny Irish hillside: One that would
support grander ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was coy when Irish reporters asked playfully about his
presidential aspirations, yet it is becoming increasingly clear
that Ireland is becoming an important stop on the 2000 election
stump. Massachusetts Gov. George Weld, a potential rival if
Gingrich chooses to run, visited last year. New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, another prospective Republican candidate, is said to be
planning a trip soon.
</P>
<P>
   The political stature Ireland -- not to mention 46 million
American voters of Irish descent -- on the American political
landscape did not escape Gingrich, who noted that about a third of
U.S. politicians claims some Irish heritage. ``It's always been
there,'' the speaker said Wednesday in front of the elegant
Culloden Hotel, where his party of nearly 30 had been staying.
``You go back to President Kennedy's visit in '63. Tip O'Neil
coming here regularly in the '80s. Reagan's trip in '84. President
Clinton had a remarkably successful trip here in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker stressed that this trip was unrelated to
domestic politics. Instead, the seven-day tour was intended to
underscore the strength of U.S. support for the fragile Irish peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he had conferred with President Clinton about the
goals of the trip. ``We wanted to communicate strongly that there
is bipartisan support, both from the legislative as well as
executive branch, and in talking with the president, he thought
this would be a helpful time,'' the speaker said. ``They get us
here at the beginning at the month and him here at the end of the
month.'' Clinton is scheduled to visit Ireland Sept. 3, following a
trip to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and his delegation of six House members have met
privately with both sides of the conflict that has plagued this
country for 30 years. With the speaker are Reps. John Dingell
(D-Mich.), Jerry Lewis (R-Calif.), Jim Walsh (R-N.Y.), Anna Eshoo
(D-Calif.), Ray LaHood (R-Ill.) and Ken Bentsen (D-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   The group has met with representatives of Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army, as well as the Ulster
Democratic Unionist Party. The Catholic IRA for years has fought to
unite Northern Ireland with the Irish Republic, while the
Protestant Unionists have fought to keep Northern Ireland part of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've communicated pretty successfully the intensity and depth
of our support for the process,'' he said. ``We also learned some
things that will make the president's trip better.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and British governments are placing much of their hopes
on the success of a new Belfast-based assembly, a central part of
the political settlement struck between Protestant Unionists and
Catholic Republicans last April.
</P>
<P>
   In the meetings, Unionists expressed concerns about forming a
government with members of Sinn Fein without adequate safeguards
that the IRA has renounced violence. The Unionist leaders equated
this to the United States entering into a partnership with the
Oklahoma City bomber.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from a meeting with Unionist leaders, Gingrich
acknowledged that this issue remains an obstacle. ``It's very clear
that you have a real concern about the authenticity of the
renunciation of violence by the various groups that have used
terrorism,'' he said. ``We have a much better sense of how
important it is to focus on genuine decommissioning and to focus on
a genuine transition to a political process and away from violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things take time. You've had 30 years or longer of
no one trusting anybody, so everybody starts every morning from a
position of distrust, so it takes everyone a long time to get
through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's assessment of the situation has been reported widely
across Ireland and Britain, where he was routinely portrayed as the
third most powerful man in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim here.)
</P>
<P>
   And Gingrich's political ambitions also have been noted in the
media here. ``The U.S. presidential election is two years away, but
Glencairn, a loyalist estate overlooking Belfast, was as good a
place as any to canvass,'' wrote The Guardian Newspaper under the
headline ``Newt hopes that a touch of blarney will boost his
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The images at the Habitat for Humanity event seemed to have been
considered carefully. Unlike all the other workers, Gingrich worked
bareheaded, reducing the prospect of goofy photos of him with a
bright yellow hardhat perched on his head. Unlike the rest,
Gingrich opted for a flattering dark blue denim workshirt rather
than a white commemorative T-shirt that could have accentuated his
girth. He worked deliberately for a 55-year-old man unused to heavy
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, he surveyed the pale gray foundation with a look
of satisfaction, a drop of sweat dangling from the end of his nose.
When the work was done, he posed with a sweet-faced little boy
named Michael Moore, who had shadowed the speaker as he worked.
</P>
<P>
   As other boys who had been hanging around joined Michael and the
speaker, Gingrich seized the opportunity. ``Our visit is really
about these boys' future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim here.)
</P>
<P>
   While here, Gingrich often has taken the tone of a statesman,
using carefully measured words to describe his talks with leaders
here and even speaking respectfully of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He also has associated himself with John Hume, a friend and
Northern Ireland's most respected Roman Catholic political leader.
At a St. Patrick's Day luncheon hosted by the speaker in
Washington, Gingrich said that he and Hume determined that they
were distantly related.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was scheduled to have dinner Thursday with Hume, an
architect of the peace plan and a Nobel Peace Prize nominee, in
Donegal. Thursday morning, he was scheduled to visit the O'Doherty
Genealogy Center to help trace his family roots. The O'Dohertys are
the ancestors of his mother, Kathleen Daugherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that sense there's a certain amount of personal fun
involved in this trip,'' said Gingrich, who is scheduled to return
home to the United States on Saturday. ``Like all Americans, I'm
curious about my background.''
</P>
<P>
   And given the attention American presidents have received by
visiting their ancient Irish homesteads, the speaker also may be
gathering information for some future visit under very different
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
