<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE-ATHLETES-2TA     08-12 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-ATHLETES-2TAKES-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWDER KEG: 
DOUBTS, FEARS GROW AS USE OF MUSCLE-BUILDING CREATINE INCREASES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, Aug. 15) 
(Eds.: This is the first of a three-day series.) 
(Photo available on NYT photo service) 
(Also with Creatine-doctor, Creatine-Q&AMP;A) 
 
By ALAN TRUEX 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Garner, the Milwaukee Brewers' manager, faced a problem
last summer that many other parents are confronting: a teen-age son
wanting to use a controversial dietary supplement called creatine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my son, Ty, who's a senior playing baseball, was going
to use it,'' Garner said. ``So I wanted to try it first-hand, but
in a controlled way.''
</P>
<P>
   For three months, the former player and coach for the Houston
Astros took the recommended doses of creatine monohydrate, a
laboratory replication of the muscle-building compound formed from
amino acids in the liver, kidneys and pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief exposure to creatine, Garner was impressed. ``You
definitely feel energized,'' he said. ``You get a good workout with
it. You're stronger and you look better.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar testimonials have come from major league sluggers Jeff
Bagwell, Dante Bichette, Harold Baines, Ken Caminiti, Eric Karros,
Ryan Klesko, Mike Piazza and Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to push more weight for a longer period, which
will make you stronger in the long run,'' said Bagwell, the Astros'
first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bill Bryan, team physician for the Astros, has conducted a
poll of major-league players that indicates at least 200 are
supplementing the body's natural supply of creatine with the
manufactured variety.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, who is assaulting the hallowed record of 61 home
runs in a season by Roger Maris, claims creatine has ``helped a lot
with strength and endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike anabolic steroids, the muscle-pumping but potentially
fatal hormones that raged in the 1970s, creatine is legal, and it
can be purchased without a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, creatine sales are booming _ from $50 million
in 1996 to $100 million last year to an expected $300 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Americans are buying creatine, and even horses are
taking it. Never mind that some doctors warn that its use _ or
misuse _ can lead to torn and cramped muscles, gastrointestinal
distress, kidney malfunction, high blood pressure, dehydration and
heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Although Garner, 49, noticed no ill effects from his brief
creatine trial, he said, ``There is a downside. It leads to some
strange injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say creatine drastically alters the body's hydraulics
as it shifts water from the bloodstream to the skeletal muscles.
And since the substance acts on muscles, and the heart is a
creatine-containing muscle, some doctors fear supplementation could
lead to cardiovascular troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie Shilstone, conditioning consultant for the San Francisco
Giants, has steered players toward creatine, but he has misgivings:
``The one question that hangs out there is, what effect does it
have on the heart?``
</P>
<P>
   Greg Hoover, a Houston physician specializing in sports
medicine, said: ``The cardiac muscle is somewhat different from
skeletal muscles, but there could be potential that you're
enlarging the heart as well as other muscles. This is something we
really don't know. It's too early to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Since athletes have been training with creatine for only six to
seven years, its long-term effects cannot be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lon Castle of the Baylor Sports Medicine Institute in
Houston lamented that creatine use is widespread among high school
students and has made its way into junior high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of parents are bringing kids in for school physicals and
asking me about creatine, wondering if their sons will be hurt by
it,'' Castle said. ``These kids are 13, 14 years old and they're
taking this stuff. This is where the emulation of athletes starts
to get dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUESTIONS ON LONG-TERM USE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Creatine was investigated by the Food and Drug Administration
last year following the fatal heart attacks of three college
wrestlers who were thought to have used the supplement.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA attributed the deaths to training in rubber suits in
heated rooms, in dehydrated condition. Even so, the agency issued a
warning in April that anyone using creatine first should consult a
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, creatine has been subjected to what Bryan calls ``a
witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever somebody pulls a muscle or dies, we're going to blame
creatine. One guy e-mailed me the other day who said he has a fatal
heart condition, and he swears it's due to creatine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's right. On the other hand, you do have to
be concerned about risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Ainsley, former Astros prospect who now works for
Houston's Department of Parks and Recreation, said he knows of a
teen-ager in south Houston who died recently after he and some
friends bought into a bottle of creatine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he didn't drink enough water after he took it,''
Ainsley said. ``He went out and played basketball, and he died that
night in his sleep when his whole body cramped up.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's family declined to be interviewed, so it's not known
what other factors might have contributed to the death.
</P>
<P>
   With a withering summer producing more than 100 fatal heat
strokes in Texas, Bryan frets about high-school football players
going through two-a-day workouts while creatine supplements course
through their veins.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we launch into Texas football,'' he said, ``our biggest
concern is that young athletes may be at jeopardy for dehydration
and heat stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle consults with the University of Houston football program
and has advised the athletes to cycle off creatine during
two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when more players were taking creatine than in the
past, we put in a lot more IVs than we did in the past,'' he said.
``My supposition is the people taking creatine got dehydrated
working out twice a day under that hot Texas sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros second baseman Craig Biggio, who bulked up with creatine
last year but has sworn off it for this baseball season, feels it
should be avoided in hot weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into St. Louis to play a game in the middle of the
summer,'' he said, ``there's just not enough fluids you can
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   And he disapproves of high school students using creatine at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For below-20 guys, I don't see a need for it,'' he said.
``When you're 18 years old, you can work out hard and your body's
gonna bounce back without any supplements.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jenna Anding, a registered dietician and assistant professor
of nutrition at UH, agreed with Biggio. ``No one has studied the
effects of creatine in teen-agers,'' she said. ``I question whether
we need to be using these types of products at that young an age.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bryan is aware that many high school coaches are
recommending creatine and in some cases supplying it themselves to
football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``With creatine now being used so widely in high school
football,'' he said, ``this will be the first year we find out if
our fears are valid. I think coaches nowadays know to force water
down these guys, especially when they're outside doing two-a-days.
But are they going to keep them hydrated enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`I WON'T LOOK AT IT AGAIN' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main knock on creatine is that it induces dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who take supplements,'' Castle said, ``should drink
lots of water _ 10 to 12 eight-ounce cups a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' Derek Bell said his failure to drink enough water
with his creatine led to two off-season trips to a hospital, first
with kidney stones and later with dehydration. After those
incidents, he said he ``threw the creatine in the garbage'' and
added: ``I won't look at it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight major league teams, including McGwire's St. Louis
Cardinals, are on record as opposing creatine because they believe
it damages as many muscles as it builds.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire, who was called ``The Big Always Hurt,'' swings on
into history, as healthy as crabgrass. Every upper-deck launch is a
sales boost for creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Bagwell and Biggio could be poster boys for creatine.
Biggio, a seven-time All-Star, played 494 consecutive games before
taking a day off last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, the Astros' perennial home run leader, has used
creatine for three years, and he played all 162 games in 1996 and
'97, missing action this season only because of a lacerated knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Kraemer of the Penn State University Center for
Sports Medicine believes that when athletes in their 20s and 30s
use creatine in proper dosage and with appropriate amount of
liquids, they are not endangering their health.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If creatine causes cramping, he said, the 1996 Atlanta Olympics
``would have been the Cramping Games; about 80 percent of the
athletes were on creatine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Biggio admitted that while using creatine he ``did have some
cramping. It helped me with training, but I stayed on it way too
long last year. This year, I've been able to maintain without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover said that when conducting physical examinations of Texas
A&AMP;M football players, he found ``a lot of them were getting
abdominal cramps. They weren't hydrating well with the use of
creatine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Coleman, the Astros' strength coach, said the ``three or
four'' players on the team who take creatine reduce the risk of
muscle pulls by abstaining from it during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell limits his creatine to the off-season, but not because
it's dangerous to do otherwise. ``The only reason I don't take it
during the season,'' he said, ``is that my schedule is too busy for
me to get involved in the load-up phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he fears adverse side effects from creatine, he said:
``All I know is that creatine hasn't done anything to my body to
make me say, `Oh, my God, this is scary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, 49, had a scare after taking creatine last spring while
training for his hobby of bicycle racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was judicious with it,'' he said. ``Then we had a
bicycle race in Austin and I developed the most atypical cramps in
both my legs; I thought I was going to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it was because of creatine and getting dehydrated and
pushing too hard. You tend to do that with creatine. We saw that
all the time with anabolic steroids. Torn tendons, torn muscles,
torn ligaments. The stuff was driving the system too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover also has seen gruesome muscle damage: ``three men who had
ruptures of the pectoral muscles and two biceps tendon muscles
after using creatine for an extended period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting muscles that are so much stronger than the
tendons we have,'' Hoover said. ``That's why they're being ripped
off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IT'S A MUSCLE SENSATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harrowing tales of muscles popping loose have not kept the
National Football League from embracing creatine. In a sport where
strength is critical to success at most positions, creatine is
almost as popular as steak.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent poll by USA Today, the New York Giants, Tennessee
Oilers, Chicago Bears and Oakland Raiders reported more than 50
percent of their players take creatine.
</P>
<P>
   And the substance has won a following in the college ranks. The
University of Nebraska, always on the leading edge of muscle
training, has supplied its football players with creatine for the
last four years. Three of those seasons ended in national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why creatine is a sensation. ``When researchers
give people creatine and give another group a placebo,'' Bryan
said, ``the creatine users do better at lifting weights.''
</P>
<P>
   If creatine doesn't bring the muscle accumulation steroids can
do, it's far less frightening, because it is not hormonal in
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given my choice between creatine and anabolic steroids,''
Hoover said, ``I'd pick creatine in a second.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said the Astros have ``no official club policy on
creatine, because we don't know what it does long-term. The players
who take it get their own creatine and use it at their own risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Sean Berry tried creatine before the 1996 season,
during which he had a career-high 95 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it for three months, but when I started hearing a few
bad things about it, I stopped,'' Berry said. ``I really have heard
more positive about it than negative. Maybe I should have stayed
with it. I had my best year after I used the creatine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel the gain is dramatic enough to make a big
difference in your performance. With some people, I think the
effect is more mental than physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Effects vary among athletes, depending on how much they work out
and how much creatine they produce naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with a higher baseline level of creatine in the body do
not respond particularly well to supplementation,'' Castle said.
``You can get that baseline level determined, but it's very
expensive to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio said that before using creatine, people ``should educate
themselves about it. You have to do your homework to determine when
to take it and how long to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see how mistakes are made. Creatine often comes in
packaging that provides no warnings about the need for extra
liquids.
</P>
<P>
   The directions that accompany the creatine sold at Bally's
health clubs in Houston advise only to take the substance ``with
several ounces of cool water.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the labels of several brands of creatine recently
examined at a GNC store contained no references to hydration risk.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said: ``The creatine label should state that once you're
outside in a dehydrating environment, away from that
air-conditioned gym, you'd better be careful to have plenty of
fluids in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, some consumers are learning that the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT'S BUYER BEWARE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act of 1994,
creatine is classified not as a drug but as a nutrient. As such, it
was admitted to the marketplace without having to undergo
scientific testing. The FDA has no authority to regulate it unless
it's first proved to be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   And the FDA hasn't found the evidence against it to be
conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Anding said: ``It's buyer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is not marketed by the major drug companies. It can be
ordered by mail, and some magazine advertisements contain veiled
references to competitors pushing impure products.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say whatever you want to market it and you can put
anything you want into the product,'' Castle said. ``How much
filler are they using and what kind? How much actual creatine is in
there? Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover cited a recent study by the American Academy of Sports
Medicine: ``They tested several commercial preparations of
supplements, including creatine, and there were unidentifiable
impurities found in four of six samples.''
</P>
<P>
   Anding advises against ordering any dietary supplement by mail.
``Major health-food stores are big enough that they can demand
quality products,'' she said. ``But some of these mail-order
companies, you don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers might consider a tragedy involving the mail-order sale
of the amino acid supplement tryptophan in the late 1980s. Some 30
deaths were attributed to a contaminated batch produced in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the creatine buyer has obtained a product that meets
the ``99.9 percent'' purity standard that many labels promise, the
next issue becomes dosage.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers recommend taking 15 to 25 grams of creatine per
day for the ``loading phase'' of the training program, which lasts
five to seven days. After that, the daily dosage is supposed to
drop to three to five grams for ``maintenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some users double or triple the suggested dosage. Such a
practice produces no additional muscle, Bryan said, while greatly
increasing the risk of health damage.
</P>
<P>
   A 400-gram bottle _ a one-month supply _ of powdered creatine
(the product also is available as a gel, candy bar, chewing gum and
liquid form) _ typically costs $30 to $70, with prices trending
downward.
</P>
<P>
   Castle feels that for some athletes, it may be worth the
expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the University of Houston we have some pro football
prospects,'' he said. ``Creatine may give them just enough strength
gain that they do a little better on their bench press at the
combine, and they get drafted. So you're talking about their career
and a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a 10-year-old, a 12-year-old, they can all go buy creatine
in stores, and we don't know what the long-term effects of using
this will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about long-term risk, Bagwell said: ``I don't worry about
that. There's a lot of things people put in their bodies that give
them long-term effects they don't worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing for Bagwell, a 30-year-old professional
ballplayer who works out zealously with medical supervision, to
take that position. It's another situation when teen-agers looking
for a better physique are plunging into a substance they know
nothing about.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan noted that teen-agers ``tend to forgo good eating habits.
I worry about kids taking a couple of scoops of creatine and a
Snickers bar and thinking that's all they need. We've observed this
problem at the collegiate level, which is disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle said: ``You've got to wonder what problems someone may
have 10 years from now because he took creatine when he was 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner has those same concerns. ``We don't need to be going
hog-wild on this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it looks like, for better or worse, that's already
happening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
