u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE-Q&AMP;A-$ADV15-H     08-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-Q&AMP;A-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS ON CREATINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, Aug. 15) 
(Also with Creatine-athletes, Creatine-doctor) 
 
By ALAN TRUEX 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ten questions and answers about creatine:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ What's the difference between creatine and anabolic steroids?
</P>
<P>
   They are completely different biochemically. Unlike steroids,
which are taken to increase testosterone production, creatine has
nothing to do with hormones; it is a product of the metabolism of
amino acids and acts only on the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   _ How does creatine compare with steroids in building muscle?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Yesalis, who has conducted research on creatine at
Penn State University, estimates it is only 15 percent to 20
percent as effective as anabolic steroids in adding muscle. Dr. Lon
Castle of the Baylor Sports Medicine Institute emphasizes that
those who take creatine without working out will not benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With anabolic steroids, you don't have to work out very hard
to look good,'' Castle said. ``With creatine, you have to put a lot
of energy into it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Is creatine damaging to the liver?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, but there is concern about long-term damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do blood work on athletes who use creatine,'' Castle
observes, ``we notice their liver functions are up a little bit.
But they go right back to normal when they stop cycling the
creatine. So maybe it does make the liver work harder. But so far
we haven't seen any signs of damage to the liver.''
</P>
<P>
   _ How long does creatine monohydrate stay in the body?
</P>
<P>
   A dose of creatine is believed to remain in the body for about
four weeks, but Castle says, ``I don't know of any studies that
show exactly how long the external creatine stays in the body. You
can test the creatine level, but it won't distinguish the synthetic
from the natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if someone is taking a lot of creatine, blood tests won't
show it because the body dumps it when it gets beyond a certain
level. At that point the body, which produces about a gram of
creatine a day, shuts down its production.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Does creatine make athletes faster?
</P>
<P>
   British sprinter Linford Christie said it brought him Olympic
gold in 1992, but creatine doesn't necessarily increase speed. Any
gain in leg muscle is likely to be offset by an equal gain in water
weight. Studies have shown that swimmers have slower times after
loading on creatine than before.
</P>
<P>
   However, some football players report increases in speed after
taking creatine for a month, building leg muscles, and then cycling
off it for a month to allow the water to recede from the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is creatine useful for pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. ``Pitching is mostly flexibility and mechanics,''
Castle says. ``If you get bigger you change your mechanics, and
that can throw everything out of whack. You don't see pitchers who
look like Mark McGwire.'' McGwire does use creatine.
</P>
<P>
   _ How do you choose which brand of creatine to use?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jenna Anding, licensed dietician and assistant professor of
nutrition at the University of Houston, advises: ``Look at the
research studies on that certain supplement and the brand of
products those studies used. Researchers use the purest creatine
they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also wise to choose creatine powder that's fine-grain; a
coarse, granular powder may be more difficult to digest and more
likely to cause diarrhea and stomach cramping.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does creatine give people energy?
</P>
<P>
   Some creatine users claim it does, but Dr. Bill Bryan of the
Baylor Sports Medicine Institute insists otherwise. He finds no
reason to take creatine a few minutes prior to competition.
``That's absurd,'' he says. ``It has to get in your body, and it
has to build up and you have to take advantage of it by working
out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Is liquid creatine better than powder?
</P>
<P>
   For people who might not be drinking enough water, it's better.
But people who aren't drinking plenty of water shouldn't be in a
creatine program in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Greg Hoover, a Houston sports medicine specialist, said that
while ``liquid creatine is advertised as being more efficient than
the powder, there's no evidence this is true. But it is more
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Where can more information be obtained about creatine and
other sports supplements?
</P>
<P>
   The Internet. You can reach the Medline Web site at
www4.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/medline.html. Then type in the name of
any supplement you wish to research. You also can read medical
reports and studies at the Texas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
