<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0049 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMFORTABLE-BAT-ART-B     08-12 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMFORTABLE-BAT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BAT TAKES THE STING OUT OF HITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenneth B. Lazarus has a high-tech solution to an age-old
problem: stopping baseball players' hands from stinging when they
hit a ball off the wrong part of the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus' company, Active Control Experts Inc., has designed a
system, embedded in an aluminium bat, that turns the bat's natural
vibrations into energy _ energy that is not felt by the batter.
</P>
<P>
   The result: the $290 bat Copperhead ACX bat, which retails for
about $100 more than other high-end aluminum bats. ACX officials
say the Copperhead decreases player discomfort when batting,
boosting ballplayers' confidence in their hitting ability. Batters
feel as if they have hit the ``sweet spot,'' the ideal contact
point on the bat, even when they haven't, Lazarus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of contact sports, getting that solid feel of hitting
the object is a reinforcing feeling that does give players more
confidence,'' Lazarus said. ``If you're not nervous about it
hurting and you have more confidence, that psychologically impacts
you to be a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed the Smart Bat, the high-tech piece of equipment is
made and marketed by Worth Inc. of Tullahoma, Tenn.. Worth plans to
focus on younger and amateur players in leagues with less stringent
rules about qualifying bats.
</P>
<P>
   While Major League Baseball uses only wooden bats, aluminum bats
are standard equipment in college, high school, and Little League
play, and increasingly used in unofficial recreation. The Smart
Bat's special piezoelectric components don't make it illegal for
National Collegiate Athletic Association teams, as long as the bat
fits weight, height, diameter, and performance regulations,
according to an NCAA spokesman, Wallace I. Renfro.
</P>
<P>
   ACX and Worth officials say piezoelectrics are an improvement
over older, more low-tech methods of damping vibrations, including
what Lazarus calls ``rubber and goo.'' And coaches and
retail &UR;  &LR; chain buyers are taking notice: Although Worth just started
producing the bats on July 20, each day the Tennessee firm turns
out 20 bats and takes 15 orders for more.
</P>
<P>
   The bats should be in retail stores by the end of August, and
currently can be ordered from Worth. According to Derrick Olsen,
Worth's baseball marketing manager, July is the industry's selling
season for baseball bats, giving coaches time to buy before the
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. company has optimistic projections for the
bat's sales. This year, Worth expects to sell 12,000 to 24,000
Copperheads, netting 15 to 18 percent of the aluminum-bat market,
Olsen said. Currently, Worth's most expensive bat after the
Copperhead ACX is the regular Copperhead, selling at about $190.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising will be secondary to personal experience and word of
mouth in Worth's campaign to sell Copperheads; the company has
provided free test bats to 25 high school baseball coaches who
serve on the firm's baseball advisory board. ``Word of mouth
typically works extremely well in this industry,'' said the
Copperhead's developer, Worth research and development vice
president Dan S. Pitsenberger.
</P>
<P>
   The Smart Bat is not ACX's first foray into solving the problem
of sports equipment vibrations and turning it into profit. The
100-employee company, founded in 1992 by president and chief
executive Lazarus and chairman Edward Crawley, is a relative
veteran in the applied piezoelectric products market. The privately
held firm focuses on sports gear, with piezoelectric skis,
snowboards, and a suspension mountain bike, all already on the
market from Los Angeles-based K2 Inc.
</P>
<P>
   After developing the company's core piezoelectric technology in
1992 and 1993, ACX found that skiers would pay to reduce vibration
in their skis as they barreled down a mountain. ACX canvassed a
short &UR;  &LR; list of top ski companies and selected K2, which agreed to
buy the credit-card-sized smart components.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting K2 Four model, known as the Smart Ski, became the
best-selling ski in the United States, according to Stuart N.
Rempel, vice president and general manager for K2 skis. The
sporting-goods manufacturer has since come out with the Merlin line
of skis, which use more advanced ACX technology, including a
piezoelectric coil embedded in the ski.
</P>
<P>
   K2 says that its Smart Skis are allowed in professional
competition, and that many pros use them.
</P>
<P>
   ACX's management comes from the technical side of its product.
Both founders are Massachusetts Institute of Technology engineers
by training; Lazarus earned his doctorate at MIT, and Crawley still
heads its aeronautics and astronautics department. Their idea
centered on the use of piezoelectric ceramic materials to cut down
on vibrations, allowing moving parts to function without
disruption. The firm makes only the piezoelectric system, selling
the components to other companies for use in products.
</P>
<P>
   To finance development of the core piezoelectric components, ACX
generated $300,000 from selling stakes in the company, which now
has about 100 investors. In 1995, the company raised $1.5 million
in its second round of financing; the company has now raised $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   While the company won't disclose its revenues, it is growing at
a rate of 100 percent each year and recently reached the break-even
point, according to the chief financial officer, Scott B. Taitel.
He says ACX is considering going public in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The company foresees several key applications for the
technology, which ACX manufactures in its Cambridge facility. While
ACX officials would not disclose specific plans for pipeline
products or potential manufacturing partners, Taitel says the firm
plans to expand its piezoelectric components into different types
of sports equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer electronics also offer a potentially large market for
the company, with products including piezoelectric disk drives,
pagers, and cell phones slated to come to market in the next one to
two years. In addition, the company plans to market automotive
applications within two to five years, Taitel says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Smart Bat, its profitability will rest on customers'
willingness to shell out more money for a bat with mostly
psychological benefits.
</P>
<P>
   At Brine's Sporting Goods in Cambridge, for example, its
top-of-the-line aluminum bat, the Louisville Slugger TPX
Megabarrel, goes for $189; the Cadillac of bats, made from
titanium, can cost as much as $600.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus says he's confident ballplayers will see beyond the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that's changed with the advent of the metal
bat is they last longer,'' Lazarus said. ``You can spend a little
more money on a bat and it will last you a whole season, instead of
a dozen (wooden bats) each season.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he says, ACX is counting on batters' attraction to
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to have the best equipment,'' he said. ``They want
to really enjoy themselves, and that means being their best.''
</P>
<P>
   The view from the trenches at this point is uncertain. Few
people have had the chance to play with the bat. But at least one
coach has already become a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids loved it,'' said Ken R. Kezer, head baseball coach at
New Britain High School in New Britain, Conn., a Worth advisory
panel member who received a free bat from the company and plans to
order six Copperheads for his players. ``It was nice and light.
Contact was good on any part of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all sports fans think a high-priced damper system is
worth the money. ``I wouldn't buy it,'' said Joseph T. Bennett, a
salesman at Adams Sporting Goods Inc. in Dorchester, Mass., whose
top-of-the-line aluminum bat is the Louisville Slugger Air Attack,
selling for $115. ``It's just too expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
