<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE-DOCTORS-$ADV     08-12 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-DOCTORS-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMICAL HELPS `FUEL' MUSCLES TO CONTRACT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, Aug. 15) 
(Also with Creatine-athletes, Creatine-Q&AMP;A) 
 
By ALAN TRUEX 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For all the controversy it has created, creatine
monohydrate looks harmless. In its most common form, it's an
odorless, virtually tasteless powder that's dissolved into water or
fruit juices and then swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   This is the laboratory-produced version of a chemical compound
synthesized in the liver, kidneys and pancreas from the breakdown
of the amino acids argenine, glycine and methionine.
</P>
<P>
   It's sold in nutrition stores and gyms, through the mail and on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So what does it do?
</P>
<P>
   When combined with phosphate, creatine helps the body replenish
its supply of adenosine triphosphate, the ``fuel'' that drives the
muscles to contract. With a shot of supplemental creatine, the
theory goes, the muscles pump longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`MORE ENERGY' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you more energy for anything that's aerobic in
nature,'' said Gene Coleman, strength coach of the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Creatine's role in muscle development has been known since the
mid-19th century, but it was not used as a performance enhancer
until the 1992 British Olympians trained with it. When Linford
Christie proceeded to win the gold medal in the 100-meter run, he
credited creatine for adding spring in his leg muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the creatine craze. It soon became the favored
muscle-building supplement of athletes around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The ``legal, safe steroid,'' it's called, and its use is
described in terminology that mimics steroids: During a five- to
seven-day ``loading'' period, the athlete takes 20 to 25 grams of
creatine per day; then the dosage drops to three to five grams
daily for a ``maintenance'' period, to be followed by ``cycling
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Creatine is actually not a steroid. It has nothing to do with
the production of hormones. But whether it's safe is a matter of
ongoing debate among sports medicine doctors.
</P>
<P>
   By the completion of a monthlong creatine cycle, the athlete
typically adds six to 10 pounds of body weight. But about half that
gain is water, not muscle tissue.
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Bill Bryan of the Baylor Sports Medicine Institute in
Houston explained it, ``You may look better, but you're
water-logged. With creatine in them, the cells suck up water.''
</P>
<P>
   And a muscle cramp or strain may develop, Bryan said, ``if the
water goes into the muscles and stretches the fibers. People on
creatine have experienced an increase in the number of sprains and
muscle pulls. Whether that's because they're driving the muscle too
hard or whether it's because it's swollen with water, we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HAMSTRING PULLS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Nash, a Houston chiropractor who has worked with
college athletes and the U.S. women's Olympic volleyball team,
blames creatine for causing hamstring pulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletes coming in with that injury are, to a really high
degree, ones using creatine,'' he said. ``We were sitting in the
stands at a Rice baseball game one day, and somebody mentioned that
a player had a hamstring injury. Almost in unison, a group of
scouts said, `Creatine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The creatine per se may not be a problem,'' Nash said, ``but
the lack of fluids can be a major problem. And we don't know much
about how it reacts with whatever other supplements are being
used.''
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that creatine, when combined with proper diet
and vigorous workouts, can contribute to gains in strength.
</P>
<P>
   In controlled studies at three universities, athletes using
creatine showed significantly more improvement in weightlifting
performance than did placebo groups in identical training programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Penn State University Center for Sports Medicine, the
gains were noticeable one week after athletes had consumed 25 grams
a day of creatine monohydrate.
</P>
<P>
   These findings were supported by a similar study at the
University of Nottingham in England, where athletes used 20 grams
per day.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study at Truman State University in Missouri showed
that weightlifters taking only five grams of creatine per day
increased their bench press by an average of 20 pounds over a
six-week period.
</P>
<P>
   All these studies lead back to the question of how much creatine
the body needs.
</P>
<P>
   The human body typically produces one or two grams of creatine
each day. Five grams of the synthetic creatine monohydrate is equal
to the amount of creatine obtainable from eating 2.2 pounds of
uncooked beef or salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors think this may be an appropriate amount of creatine for
a full-time athlete, but it's far more than the average citizen
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan notes that research on creatine has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not looked at racial differences; they haven't
looked at age factors,'' he said. ``Maybe an 18-year-old can get
away with it and middle-aged men can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be careful as you get older, because your body
metabolism tends to change. If you're over 40, you should have some
blood work done to make sure your kidney is functioning well before
you get into this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jenna Anding, a registered licensed dietician and assistant
professor of nutrition at the University of Houston, said, ``I
don't know if I can recommend it for women, because the studies
have not shown conclusively that it's safe for women.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PHYSICAL CONDITION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, the Astros' team physician, believes athletes who benefit
from creatine are already in excellent physical condition. He and
trainer Dave Labossiere discourage its use by players who are prone
to muscle strains or dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryan: ``We're telling those guys, `You probably don't want
to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Greg Hoover, a Houston sports medicine specialist,
emphasized that whoever uses creatine ``should not stay on it
continuously. Even if you take a lot of water, you can get problems
with the kidneys being overstressed and not having a chance to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover also theorizes that the muscles need periodic relief from
creatine supplementation, so they can return to their normal state
of hydration.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors all urge caution in using creatine. But they agree
that it does what it's supposed to do: It helps people acquire more
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
