<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-EDGE-2TAKES-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ATHLETES SEEKING EXTRA EDGE TURN TO DIET SUPPLEMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, Aug. 15) 
(Eds.: Day 2 of three-part series) 
 
By ALAN TRUEX 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As batting practice was about to begin, Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell rushed to his locker, pulled a plastic bottle
of ``zinc stresstabs'' off a shelf and swallowed a pill.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many nutritional supplements stocked in the
clubhouse by Bagwell and second baseman Craig Biggio, who total
nine All-Star appearances between them.
</P>
<P>
   Their success may or may not be attributable in part to diet
supplementation. But like elite athletes in any sport, the best
baseball players tend to do whatever they can to increase their
strength and durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a million things you can take,'' Bagwell said during a
break from his ongoing training mission. ``There are all these
things that are supposed to be the new drug that will do wonders _
build you up like steroids but be good to the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell grinned.
</P>
<P>
   He doubts anything healthful can make it easy to acquire a
sculpted physique. He is the most muscular of the Astros _ a shade
under 6 feet and 200 pounds _ because he has worked out almost
daily (pumping iron as soon as the game ends) for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell is not one of the home-run mashers rumored on the
baseball circuit to partake of anabolic steroids, which were deemed
to be potentially lethal and made illegal in 1990 (except by
doctor's prescription).
</P>
<P>
   But going the legal route, Bagwell has taken androstenedione,
which is a close neighbor in the hormone chain to the illegal
steroids. So close, in fact, that the International Olympic
Committee banned it. Shot-putter Randy Barnes recently was
suspended for using this substance.
</P>
<P>
   While Bagwell has had impressive results with creatine, a muscle
energizer approved by the IOC, he said, ``I took Andro-6 for a
while, and I thought it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say Andro-6 works because two of its main ingredients
are tribulus and androstenedione _ hot items on the gray market of
``hormone precursors'' that are legal, but tenuously so.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lon Castle of the Baylor Sports Medicine Institute in
Houston said Andro-6 ``is definitely a little more worrisome than
creatine. Androstene is a steroid, and it does make people
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione and its ``mother hormone'' of DHEA
(dehydroepiandrosterone) are advertised on the Internet, as are
tribulus and chrysin (another ingredient of Andro-6) as ``legal
steroids'' and ``growth hormones.''
</P>
<P>
   QFAC, a supplement distributor with a Web site called ``Dirty
Dieting,'' warns that these steroid precursors ``may soon become
restricted and/or banned.''
</P>
<P>
   The underlying message: ``Buy them while you can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have the potency of the illegal steroids,'' Castle
said. ``But when people take a lot of them, as they tend to do if
they want to add significant strength, then they're dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   They're under scrutiny from the Food and Drug Administration
because they are advertised to double or triple the production of
testosterone, the male hormone and primary muscle-building steroid.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA banned the selling of DHEA in 1996. Upon further review,
it was reinstated to legal status, but that could change again.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Greg Hoover, a Houston specialist in sports medicine, said,
``We haven't yet seen the abuse and side effects with these
precursors that we saw with anabolic steroids. But when that does
happen, we may have some more banned substances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HUMAN GUINEA PIGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Step into a nutrition store, and you see dozens of products _
androstene and DHEA among them _ that are supposed to transform you
into Arnold Schwarzenegger. Dietary supplementation is a
multibillion-dollar industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more money spent last year on alternative medicine
and nutritional products than on medicine itself,'' Hoover
observed. ``With the money involved in sports, everyone looks for
that little edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, 32, said, ``When you're 28, 29, 35 and you're doing the
things we do in the gym, your body doesn't bounce back so well. As
you get older you have to look at supplements, not just creatine
but a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, human beings are guinea pigs for many of these
products. Thanks to the Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act
of 1994, a broad range of ``nutrients'' do not have to pass
scientific testing before being admitted to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Before outlawing them, the FDA must prove through scientific
testing that the substances are harmful.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement industry vigorously lobbied for this legislation,
which excluded from FDA control amino acids, vitamins, minerals,
botanicals, metabolites (such as creatine) and _ giant loophole _
``dietary substances for use by man to supplement the diet to
increase the total dietary intake.''
</P>
<P>
   Androstene is a botanical, found in wild yams in Mexico.
Likewise, tribulus and chrysin are botanically based and assumed to
be harmless. Never mind that some plants _ poison ivy, poison oak,
coca leaves, opium poppy and certain strains of California
mushrooms _ pose obvious health risks.
</P>
<P>
   DHEA has been allowed back into circulation because it may be
safe at 50 milligrams per day. Nutritionist Beth M. Ley writes in
``DHEA: Unlocking the Secrets to the Fountain of Youth'' that
studies with mice indicate supplementation of this hormone extends
life span.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Bill Bryan, team physician for the Astros, calls
DHEA ``the fountain of prostate cancer.'' Other doctors say it
causes not only prostate cancer in men but ovarian cancer in women.
And Ley notes that using DHEA in amounts large enough to promote
substantial muscle gain entails risk of liver disease.
</P>
<P>
   Castle believes there may be a certain amount of androstene or
DHEA that can increase muscle mass without inducing alarming
side-effects, such as shrinking testicles and soft-tissue breasts
in men, and beards and deepening voices in women.
</P>
<P>
   A shrewd body-builder, such as Bagwell, tries to determine the
dosage at which the anabolic product enhances strength without
posing a health threat.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors worry about such powerful chemicals being used by
the public _ especially teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
