<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHLETES-CHARITY-ART-     08-12 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETES-CHARITY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FUND TURNS ATHLETES' DOLLARS INTO CHARITY WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a small third floor office in downtown Boston, Marc Pollick
presides over a charity that could help make it far easier for
professional athletes to overcome a tarnished public image.
</P>
<P>
   The Giving Back Fund, started by Pollick one year ago, is
offering athletes a one-stop service for establishing and
administering foundations, and the opportunity to turn their
lucrative salaries into philanthropic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Many athletes try to establish charitable foundations, but the
funds often fail to achieve their promise when they are improperly
administered or poorly financed. Few young athletes get the
technical aid to sustain philanthropies from their agents,
franchise owners or players' unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some horror stories of foundations that
weren't funded adequately, or the athlete is letting their brother
or uncle run things, and it just turns out badly,'' Pollick said.
``If it was managed properly and well-financed _ like a good
business _ it could be one of the very best things an athlete can
do. Our point is to try to provide a service to these truly wealthy
individuals who want to do good works.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of a wealthy, selfish athlete who flouts the mores of
society is increasingly well-established. With free agency in the
four major sports, athletes' salaries are now often well beyond the
imagination of he average fan. When athletes run afoul of the law
or of commonly accepted social behavior, even their good deeds are
greeted with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports crises are clearly more frequent today than ever
before,'' said Kathleen Hessert, president of Sports Media
Challenge, a consultancy in North Carolina. ``One result is that
the public is actually getting numb to sports crises, even
expecting them.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Sports Media Challenge found that 70 percent
of professional sports teams and 74 percent of collegiate athletic
programs had experienced a crisis related to athletes' mistakes off
the playing field within the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers, and athletes themselves, believe that a perfect
antedote is philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much negative stuff going on, this is one way they
can look good,'' said Myron Finkbeiner, head of the World Sports
Humanitarian Hall of Fame in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relative no-brainer,'' said Richard Lapchick, founder
of Northeastern University's Center for the Study of Sport in
Society, who is also an adviser to The Giving Back Fund. ``It's a
triple win situation. The community benefits from the players'
money and time, the player is less likely to fall into a
megalomaniacal posture and, if you get into that habit of
charitable giving and works, there is a better chance of being a
successful player because there are going to be fewer problems with
the team or their personal lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollick says he came to the idea of The Giving Back Fund ``very
circuitously.'' He was immersed in Holocaust studies at Boston
University, striving for a doctorate while working with Elie
Wiesel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea for a humanitarian studies institute came to mind,
and Elie really liked the idea,'' Pollick said. ``As we began
putting it together the Elie Wiesel Foundation for Humanitarian
Studies I found that he, with his celebrity, was able to make a lot
of contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Pollick founded The Giving Back Fund, a national
nonprofit organization to encourage giving by athletes and
entertainers. The fund has been granted tax-exempt status as a
full-service public charity in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   It is composed of individually identified donor-advised funds
and foundations, each with donor-appointed trustees. While each of
the foundations appears to stand alone, Pollick said, they all
benefit from the financial buying power of the pooled assets,
including the expertise of the fund's strategic partners and the
grant-making guidance of the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Among the advisers to the fund are the NBC broadcaster Bob
Costas, the retired track star Florence Griffith Joyner and her
husband and coach Al Joyner, the author Jonathan Kozol, Rabbi
Harold Kushner, Harvard Law School professor Charles Ogletree and
the retired basketball star Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the fund is receiving services on a reduced
fee or pro bono basis from BankBoston, the law firm of Hale And
Dorr, the accounting firm of Ernst &AMP; Young, the grant-making
services of Grants Management Associates, public relations from
Silverman Media and Marketing and the New England Sports Network is
developing and managing a web site.
</P>
<P>
   The former Boston College football star Doug Flutie has used The
Giving Back fund to start a foundation to fight autism, which
afflicts his son, Doug Jr. Former Celtics star Dee Brown and his
wife Tammy also have started a foundation to support groups that
teach parenting skills and to provide needy schools with teaching
and sports equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Pollick said The Giving Back Fund was started with $250,000 in
seed money from various organizations, and now has about $500,000
of money under management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a long way from our goal of $20 million in assets by
2002,'' Pollick said, ``but it is a start. I really do see it on a
grand scale. In five years, I see this as a major source for
philanthropy in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``By putting all of this together, you're really, really
bringing some power and attention to bear on these various
causes,'' he said. ``If in the process it shows that not all
athletes are greedy and selfish as portrayed in the media, that's
good too.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is plenty of anecdotal evidence that athletes are
aware of the appropriateness or potential power of their charitable
donations or work. All four major sports teams in Boston do
considerable charitable work.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Celtics Charitable Foundation and the Red Auerbach
Youth Foundation both rely on extensive public appearances by
Celtics players at golf tournaments and other events to raise
money. The New England Patriots Foundation was established in 1994,
and has contibuted more than $1 million to help support youth
groups like the Boys and Girls Clubs of Boston and the ROSE
(Regaining One's Self Esteem) Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Bruins contibute to the Failure to Thrive Clinic and
the Anthony Spinazzola Foundation. And the Red Sox, of course, have
their Jimmy Fund and other community charities.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, Pedro Martinez, Drew Bledsoe, Tebucky Jones and
Raymond Bourque are among the players in Boston who have
established separate foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there are many examples. But among the most striking
are the attempts by the National Basketball Association star
Dikembe Mutombo to contribute his own money and raise additional
funds to finance a $2 million hospital in his native Congo, and the
former National Hockey League player and professed sexual abuse
victim Sheldon Kennedy attempting to raise $15 million for other
victims, in part by in-line skating across Canada.
</P>
<P>
   No attempt has been made to tally how many such efforts exist,
or how much money they have raised, according to several sources,
including the Council on Foundations in Washington and The
Chronicle of Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one agent, Leigh Steinberg. I have to give him credit
that when he signs up a client, the first thing he tells them is
that, `If you're my client, you're going to give back,'''
Finkbeiner said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of oversight and guidance, however, has led to some
disasters involving even the most well-intentioned athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball star Michael Jordan was forced to close down his
children's foundation in 1996, seven years after he started it,
when the admnistration of it became ungainly, expensive trips were
financed for overseers, and it was revealed that Jordan had
contributed less than $10,000 over six years.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball star Juwan Howard announced a foundation, with
considerable notice, in 1995, only to admit two years later that it
had yet to register in the District of Columbia, where he plays for
the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the athletes are dedicated, but not skilled in
creating a foundation,'' said Larry Moulter, of Woolf Associates in
Boston. &UR;  &LR; ``It's one thing to commit to doing a foundation, but does
that translate to the dedication that can pull the business aspects
of it off?''
</P>
<P>
   Pollick's answer is that The Giving Back Fund can pick up where
the athlete's good intentions end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think we can provide a full service that is going to
cut down on some of the problems, and provide the athletes with a
really stable foundation, whether they are really hands-on or
content to sit back and watch,'' Pollick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
