</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0064 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREATINE-EDGE-2NDTAKE     08-12 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREATINE-EDGE-2NDTAKE-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
HOUSTON: especially teen-agers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When several sales clerks at General Nutrition Center outlets in
the Houston area were questioned, they said they would not sell
creatine, Andro-6 or DHEA to anyone under 18. But if high-schoolers
and younger can't buy them in stores or obtain them from older
friends, they can order these substances by mail or via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   GNC is a Pittsburgh-based chain of outlets that sells
nutritional supplements nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jenna Anding, a licensed dietician and assistant professor
of nutrition at the University of Houston, said many supplements
are not bought for athletic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a population, we're getting older, and we want to do
everything we can to stay young and healthy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some controversial supplements are popular with office workers
and executives who sense an energizing effect from them. ``DHEA and
androstene give men sort of a euphoric feeling,'' Castle said.
``They make them feel like they're getting stronger, whether or not
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`PSEUDO-SCIENCE GETS THROWN IN' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays there are so many supplements available that nutrition
experts cannot keep up with them, let alone evaluate their health
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know everything that's on the market, because it
changes so rapidly,'' Anding said. ``It could be a full-time job
just to keep track of all the supplements coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   While creatine is the biggest-selling sports supplement _ GNC
salesmen estimate it represents about 50 percent of their business
_ the second-trendiest item might be chromium picolinate, which
assists in blood sugar regulation and helps curb cravings for
carbohydrates and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're training for a marathon, it makes sense to use it,
because your body might get low on chromium,'' Bryan said. ``But
it's expensive, and for those of us working out for an hour or two
every other day, it's a waste of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Most supplements are recommended not by doctors or scientists,
Bryan said, but by personal fitness trainers ``who take a few
courses in nutrition and all of a sudden they're experts. A lot of
pseudo-science gets thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been going on for 200 years. You can go back through
history and find people using magnets and all kinds of stuff to try
to get stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   You can even go back to the ancient Greeks, who stuffed
themselves with fish (which are high in creatine) prior to Olympic
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The early Olympians knew that protein-loaded meats would help
them add muscle. In modern times, athletes buy powdered protein
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one area we probably are neglecting in nutrition,''
Hoover said, ``it's protein. We're getting too much carbohydrate
and not enough protein.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bryan cautioned that protein ``in heavy concentrations
is difficult to digest and can trigger gout. If you're a football
player beating up your body every day, it probably makes sense to
take extra protein. But it would be cheaper to go to Whataburger.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, protein in a hamburger is accompanied by
considerable fat, whereas whey protein, extracted from goat's milk,
has little fat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the promising new supplements is
beta-hydroxy-beta-methylbutyrate _ HMB for short. Bagwell said, ``I
don't think it helped me much.'' But Castle said it has been shown
in studies to improve muscle strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem to have any side effects,'' Castle said. ``It
will be the next hot supplement after creatine runs its course.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover agreed that HMB in moderate amounts is probably effective
and safe. But he said, ``What concerns me is, I'm seeing people
`stacking' _ taking creatine and growth hormone and HMB to promote
breakdown of protein.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're stacking all these things together. Who knows what
effect that will have?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOME SUPPLEMENTS ARE WORTHLESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of GNC's supplements, Bryan contends, are worthless; for
example, shark cartilage is bought by athletes who expect it to
strengthen their own cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absurd,'' Bryan said, ``because when it gets into the
stomach, acids break it down, and it doesn't get past the
intestines.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Bryan said chondroitin sulfate, glucosamine and copper
sebacate are unable to do what they're advertised to do: make
ligaments stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there's nothing you can do to strengthen
ligaments,'' he said. ``As you get older, they get weaker. When
they break, it's just a mechanical thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is one group of supplements that sports medicine
doctors seem to like: antioxidants, which neutralize the free
radicals that accelerate the aging of cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think antioxidants are helpful in athletic training,''
Hoover said. ``Coenzyme Q10 seems to have some scientific basis,
but it's not as effective as selenium, beta-carotine, vitamin C and
vitamin E.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinc, one of Bagwell's favored supplements, is one of these
antioxidants that is believed to help the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoover said, ``If you're going to take one thing, I think
vitamin E is the one thing to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover also said that caffeine, a major component of coffee, is
a stimulus not only for the brain but also for the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It increases metabolism and may make the muscle fibers more
ready for exercise,'' he said. ``One study showed that moderate
doses of caffeine, taken an hour before exercise, enhanced
endurance performance. When that study came out, tons of athletes
started taking caffeine.''
</P>
<P>
   While some doctors believe a person can obtain all the vitamins
and minerals needed by eating proper foods, others insist that's no
longer the case in a world of nutrient-depleted, pollution-tainted
soil and air.
</P>
<P>
   So the marketplace is inundated with enough supplements to
overwhelm an athletic trainer or strength coach.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Coleman, Astros strength coach, said: ``We look at
everything that comes down the pike. The players will ask about
this product and that, and you'd better have an answer and not blow
it off and say, `That doesn't work.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, people would go to doctors and ask about steroids
and they'd say, `They don't work.' But the athletes could look
around them and see they did work _ if they were taken in doses
that were not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman distributes only one product to the Astros: Ultra-Met, a
protein-rich powder made by Champion Nutrition Co. that's mixed
with water or juice and ice and taken before games. Beer is no
longer the beverage of choice among ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, manager of the Milwaukee Brewers, has seen
attitudes on nutrition change drastically since he played baseball
in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got into baseball,'' he said, ``if you didn't drink a
six-pack and puke before a day game, you weren't a man. Now, a lot
of guys don't drink, but you wonder about all these other things
that make you feel good and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
