<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS OF PATRIOTS' OFFENSE MISS THE POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ A day off, a couple of film sessions, and
it's amazing what kind of spin you can put on a 28-0 loss, even if
it came in an exhibition game that was best forgotten the instant
it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Drew Bledsoe what went wrong in Sunday's loss to the
Vikings, ask him about progress in an offense that has yet to make
it from practice to game day with any kind of efficiency, and you
will hear an explanation that makes sense only in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot closer than we were a week ago,'' said the
Patriots quarterback Tuesday. ``I feel we made some strides in the
game. We obviously are not where we need to be, but we made some
strides in the game, offensively and in our passing game. The
timing is starting to come. We've started to feel that happening
for us a little bit. Obviously, it wasn't exact, but we're making
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree of progress is what's being questioned. Sunday's game
does not count for anything, just as Monday night's game against
the Dallas Cowboys will not mean a whole lot in the grand scheme of
a season that is still three weeks from opening.
</P>
<P>
   And the Patriots do have a built-in excuse, particularly on
offense. Bledsoe and his teammates are absorbing their third
offensive system in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe says that change is a way of life in the National
Football League, that staffs seem to turn over as often as players
move around in free agency. So he urges caution against making
premature judgments and asks for patience from fans who are growing
restless after two listless offensive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between having an excellent offense and not
scoring any points in this league is so minute,'' he said, pointing
out that against the Vikings, a few inches' difference would have
produced a touchdown pass to Vincent Brisby and a lucky bounce
would have resulted in an incomplete pass to Terry Glenn rather
than an interception return for a touchdown. ``It's still
preseason. When we're done with this, it all gets thrown out. It's
by no means time to panic.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are some worry lines around the eyes of the coaches
that weren't there a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Pete Carroll saw the same films that Bledsoe saw and
had almost the same frustrations. While he remains optimistic that
progress can be made in bigger leaps, he is also concerned about
what happens when the Patriots go from practice to game situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not carrying over the things we did in practice to
games, and that's an area of concern,'' said Carroll, who felt
Sunday's offensive inefficiency was attributable more to what the
Patriots didn't do than to what the Vikings did do.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever reason you choose, the Patriots are not producing. Zero
points and 180 yards in total offense against the Vikings is not a
formula for winning football. Bledsoe, in his limited first-half
stint, was 7 of 15 for 74 yards with an interception. He has been
forced to make a constant series of adjustments, ranging from
acquainting himself with new offensive schemes to changing the way
he drops back to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the biggest change from a timing standpoint and from
a mechanical standpoint for me and the receivers,'' Bledsoe said
when asked if this has been the most difficult of the passing
offenses to learn. ``That's taking a little bit of time, but when
we start to click in the offense, which I feel we're going to do
very soon, it'll be very productive.''
</P>
<P>
   What worries Carroll _ and right now it is only a worry, not
panic _ is that the Patriots are having what he calls ``clean
practices,'' in which the offense is working. But in two games, the
offensive schemes have been littered with mistakes and inefficiency
both passing and running (66 yards against Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to generate some movement of the football,'' said
Carroll, who watched his team run 14 offensive series against the
Vikings with only one net gain of more than 25 yards, while six
series lasted three or fewer plays. ``I thought we'd be cleaner
than this.''
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't been, and while it's still only midway through
the preseason, it is clear that the Patriots need to make a quantum
offensive leap in the next three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
