<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-12 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUNGING MARKET TAKES FUNDS ALONG FOR THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Check your mutual funds lately?
</P>
<P>
   It's no suprise that stock funds have taken a beating in the
last month as the market's leading indexes slumped. But it's one
thing to watch abstract market measures slide and quite another to
see real money disappear out of your shareholder account.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the general stock funds at Fidelity Investments are
still outperforming their market index benchmarks, but the gaudy
returns of just a month ago have been slashed since stocks peaked
July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's Retirement Growth fund, up 31 percent for the year on
July 17, was ahead by only 19.6 percent by Monday. Contrafund's
1998 gain was cut from 25.4 percent to 15.3 percent during the same
period, and returns for Magellan, the world's biggest mutual fund,
were trimmed from 24.9 percent to 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, up 23.3 percent at its July 17
peak, had earned 14.2 percent as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's funds have lots of company. The performance of
practically every general stock fund managed from Boston and
elsewhere has slipped by 10 percentage points or more.
</P>
<P>
   Even funds that lean toward big ``Nifty Fifty'' stocks have been
stung in the last month. Massachusetts Investors Growth, which
usually invests in large stocks, saw its gains trimmed from 32
percent to 18.2 percent between July 17 and Monday. Pioneer Growth,
another strong performer in the big-stock category, has trimmed its
1998 return from 30.4 percent to 19.6 percent over the same time
period.
</P>
<P>
   But small-stock funds, which already trailed the performance of
funds that invest in big companies, have gotten hit even harder at
practically every turn in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Managers said the adverse investor sentiment toward small stocks
give them no choice but to buy attractive companies at cheap prices
and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not making up ground,'' said Russ Kinnel, equity
editor at Morningstar Inc., the mutual fund research firm. ``Even
before (Tuesday), small-capitalization funds were in the red when
the average large-cap fund was up 10 percent or so. There's a
tremendous gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam OTC &AMP; Emerging Growth was up 18.2 percent on July 17, a
gain that had shrunk to about 1.5 percent after another tough day
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What continues to amaze me is negativity'' toward small
stocks, said Mike Mufson, a co-manager of the fund. ``The glass
isn't half empty, people just think it's empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam OTC is hardly alone. John Hancock Special Equities, a
concentrated portfolio of small stocks, was already struggling on
July 17, up 4.8 percent for the year. But it's been hit hard since
and posted a year-to-date loss of about 12 percent by the end of
the day Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time now that small stocks have
underperformed,'' said Robert Freedman, chief investment officer at
John Hancock Mutual Funds. ``At the moment, there's not much light
at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Fund managers like Bart Geer, who invests in midsize companies
for the State Street Research Alpha fund, said they can't do much
in sharp market declines except to spot stocks that briefly fall
even harder for no apparent reason. But most of their time is still
spent in the normal process of analyzing companies for their
longer-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes on,'' said Geer. ``You can't spend your life in
front of a (computer) screen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _From the personnel file: Karen Schwartzman, the chief
spokeswoman of BankBoston Corp., is leaving after seven years with
the bank. Effective Sept. 8, Schwartzman becomes a senior vice
president with Fleishman Hillard, the St. Louis-based public
relations firm that opened a Boston office six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   _On the move: Stock in Zoll Medical Corp. is up 40 percent in
the last two days although there has been no news on the
Burlington, Mass. maker of heart defibrillators. As we reported
last week, Zoll is facing a possible proxy fight lead by Elliott
Associates, an aggressive New York hedge fund. The stock closed
Tuesday at 10, up from 7 1/8 on Friday on about four times normal
volume.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
