<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERGONOMIC-FURNITURE-B     08-12 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERGONOMIC-FURNITURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DESK JOB, MINUS A BIT OF THE STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For two Iranian refugees, the American dream has a concrete
form: an ergonomic computer desk. And it comes in black, gray, or
cherry wood, with reversible maple paneling.
</P>
<P>
   Max Ladjevardi and Bibi Kasrai, who are married, have built a
business far from the revolution that sent them fleeing Iran in the
late 1970s. While Soho Inc., based in Milford, Mass., has only four
employees and annual sales of about $4 million, the furniture
start-up ships computer desks to retailing heavyweights like Office
Max and major catalogs like Global. Banking on the growing demand
for ergonomic furniture, designed to reduce fatigue and stress in
users, Soho aims to grab a piece of the $13.7 billion domestic
office furniture market as a virtual manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the company is an adjustable computer desk, a
matte metal piece of office furniture with shelves that can move up
and down. Soho's most valuable asset may be the patent for the
adjustable mechanism, which allows a user to reposition the shelves
by turning two knobs. The 5-year-old company has already won a
patent-infringement suit against a ``big fish'' competitor,
according to Kasrai, the firm's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Customers buy Soho's desks for offices, home or corporate, and
for home computer use. Once purchased, a Soho desk takes 30 minutes
to assemble using only a screwdriver. Soho's three- and four-shelf
desks can accommodate a computer, printer, monitor, and keyboard,
and retail from about $199 to $249, said Ladjevardi, the firm's
founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still in start-up mode, with little money for
advertising. Kasrai, a veteran of the New York management
consulting firm McKinsey &AMP; Co., has had to scramble to get the firm
noticed. Her marketing strategy focuses primarily on value and
quality, branding Soho as ``the Volkswagen of ergonomics.'' (The
couple drive a Jeep.)
</P>
<P>
   Value is a clarion call in the ready-to-assemble office
furniture market. ``People are very value-conscious in that
category,'' said Douglas S. Bush, vice president of merchandising
at Bush Industries in Jamestown, N.Y., a Soho competitor. Bush
Industries did $325 million in sales last year, and several large
companies that have staked claims to the market are competing in
prices and quality.
</P>
<P>
   Soho doesn't have to worry about pleasing its investors. The
privately-held company gets its financing from Ladjevardi, the
scion of a family that owned the largest conglomerate in the Middle
East, Behshahr Industrial Group, before the Iranian revolution.
Ladjevardi's entire supply of capital comes from his savings and
personal funds. Part of his financing also came from money he
earned during a stint as a brand manager for New York-based
Colgate-Palmolive Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ladjevardi, who is a US citizen, did not reveal how well the
company is doing, but he said revenues are in the neighborhood of
$4 million annually. He attributed the company's success to an
innovative corporate structure that lets him run his firm by
managing relationships between other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The small firm operates as a virtual manufacturer, or middleman,
between furniture factories, which make desk components, and
retailers, which sell them to consumers. Soho, whose name is an
acronym for the small office-home office market, does not own a
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Its employees work out of three offices: in Milford, where the
company is based; San Diego, where Ladjevardi, 34, and Kasrai, 32,
live with their 3-month-old son; and Chicago, where the company has
a warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Running a manufacturing company without a factory means relying
entirely on computers. Retailers transmit orders electronically to
Soho; a logistics and warehousing firm working for Ladjevardi's
company ships the desks directly to individual retail stores, or,
in the case of catalog orders, to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (corporate) model is designed for a small company that
wants to really go fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The process is streamlined, with a backup supplier waiting in
the wings should any of Soho's suppliers fail to deliver,
Ladjevardi said. It's a formula designed to use the marketing and
management skills Ladjevardi and Kasrai acquired at Harvard
Business School, where both received MBA degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we structured the company was to focus all my
resources on what it was that I did very well, product development
and marketing,'' said Ladjevardi, who learned about virtual
manufacturing in business school.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual manufacturing has caught on in other industries, such as
apparel, but has yet to make a splash in the office furniture
business. Industry analysts and Soho's competitors, several of whom
said they hadn't heard of Ladjevardi's firm, expressed doubt that
Soho's strategy will be competitive in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are companies out there that are doing it, but in my
mind they are just adding cost,'' said Bush, whose firm owns its
own factories. ``Maybe it's not more expensive initially, but down
the road, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the model might make sense for a firm Soho's size,
but not for a larger company dealing with merchants who want
just-in-time delivery without any hitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is probably a pretty good business model for a smaller
business to adopt,'' said Michael L. Franks, director of marketing
at O'Sullivan Industries Inc., a Missouri-based Soho competitor
that owns two factories.
</P>
<P>
   Ladjevardi defended his approach, noting Soho holds suppliers
financially responsible for delays. The virtual manufacturing model
may be relatively new, he said, but it's worked for Soho so far.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is confident enough in Soho's suppliers to plan the
launch of a new desk, slated to reach the market early next year.
And he said he is certain Soho's reputation will lure more
customers to the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to customer service,'' Ladjevardi said. ``The
real proof is, how do people who see my product think of it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
