<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RAISES BIG BUCKS, BUT VISIT STIRS MIXED FEELINGS IN SAN
FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With President Clinton's motorcade waiting
outside the St. Francis Hotel, a half-dozen protesters carrying
signs reading ``Impeach Clinton Now!'' faced off against a Clinton
die-hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best president we've ever had,'' a man in a business
suit said, his arm around his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a liar and a crook,'' a man in a T-shirt responded.
Another protester added, ``This man has brought disrepute on the
office of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit to San Francisco Tuesday stirred Clinton
supporters and his detractors. He was in the area to promote new
regulations on the safety of drinking water and to raise money for
Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to testify Monday for a grand jury investigating an
alleged sexual affair and cover-up involving a former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, a staunch Clinton defender who
spoke at the fund-raiser at the St. Francis Hotel, said he thought
Clinton should have his testimony televised live nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should not allow spin doctors to interpret what he
testified to in that secret proceeding,'' Brown said. ``Of course,
I'm not a great aficionado of the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he believed Clinton had told the truth when he
denied having a sexual affair with the intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should not talk in that secret chamber,'' Brown said. ``He
should speak directly to the American people and not those 23
people in secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the glitzy Grand Ballroom of the St. Francis, Clinton was
welcomed by a friendly lunchtime crowd of union leaders,
politicians and deep-pocketed Democratic contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the beneficiary of the $1,000-a-plate event, praised
Clinton for making life better for Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the crowd the outcome of the governor's race would
determine how his administration's programs, such as the effort to
provide health care coverage to 5 million uninsured children, were
carried out in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need somebody who believes in the potential of government
to alleviate problems and strengthen our common life,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his sharpest remark, Clinton blasted Senate Republican
leaders for blocking his nomination of San Francisco philanthropist
James Hormel as the next ambassador to Luxembourg. Hormel, who is
gay, has been denied a hearing by Republicans who claim he will
promote a gay agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting sick and tired of coming to San Francisco and
saying, as I must say one more time, Jim Hormel should have a
hearing,'' he said to strong applause.
</P>
<P>
   The president also urged Democrats to get out the vote for
Davis, warning that the only thing that could defeat the Democrat
would be a low turnout in November.
</P>
<P>
   Davis faces the state's Republican attorney general, Dan
Lungren, in the Nov. 3 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the featured guest at two more fund-raisers for
Davis in Los Angeles Tuesday night, one hosted by Bruce Karatz,
chief executive of Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home Corp., and another staged
by movie executive Jeffrey Katzenberg of DreamWorks SKG.
</P>
<P>
   All together, the three events raised $3 million for the Davis
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To Clinton loyalists at the St. Francis, the investigation led
by independent counsel Kenneth Starr was little more than a
partisan jab at the president and his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's just another tactic to keep them from doing the
job they should be doing,'' said Sandra Carter, a retired Pacific
Bell technician. ``I have every confidence the president will
prevail because the American people want him to prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
