<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING STEAMROLLED BY BUREAUCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The longer I live in this town, the more appalled
I am by the way the bureaucracy thinks and operates. Bureaucracy in
Albany defends the status quo even when the quo has no status
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Most recent example: a hapless working stiff named Jim Helin.
</P>
<P>
   He's a 35-year-old electrician who lives in the Albany suburb of
Saratoga Springs. Until recently, he worked for the New York State
Department of Transportation. He earned about 29 grand a year when
the overtime was good. When George Pataki and his hatchet moved
into the governor's office, overtime dried up, and Jim Helin went
looking for a job in the private sector. He has three kids. They
get hungry. Every day, that happens.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out the door, Jim Helin's boss in state government
warned him that he couldn't work on any department contract for two
years. Doing that would violate the state's ethics law.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Helin was aghast. This law was aimed at government big shots
_ at legislators and top honchos in executive departments. It was
especially aimed at lawyers. The law says that former state
employees have to wait two years to ``appear or practice'' before
their former agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Helin wrote a letter to Pataki saying that this struck him
as asinine. Pataki wrote back, saying that he couldn't do anything
about it.
</P>
<P>
   So Jim Helin essentially went to work for the electrical workers
union, which supplies electricians to contractors. He ended up
working on a transportation department job, installing electrical
car counters.
</P>
<P>
   He figured he was cool on this job. The company the union had
assigned him to wasn't a state contractor. Instead, it had a
subcontract with the company that actually held the state contract.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of this job, Jim Helin dealt with engineers and
other state transportation department employees. Next thing he
knew, the State Ethics Commission was charging him with violating
the ethics law.
</P>
<P>
   There was a hearing. The hearing officer could have stuck Jim
Helin for 10 grand. Instead, the hearing officer recommended a
$1,000 fine. The full ethics commission, in its bureaucratic
benevolence, accepted the hearing officer's recommendation. Now Jim
Helin has to come up with a grand or find some judge to overturn
the commission ruling. That'll probably cost considerably more than
a grand.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Helin can't believe it. A law designed to prevent former
lawmakers and state government movers and shakers from influence
peddling is instead used to punish a blue-collar guy who made 600
bucks in a good week as a state employee.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because he'd actually talked to state department of
transportation employees during the installation of these traffic
counters. According to the ethics commission, that constituted an
``appearance'' before a state agency.
</P>
<P>
   Ethics commissions are good things, not bad ones. The idea is to
keep powerful people in government from profiting improperly from
their government service at your expense and mine. Their purpose is
not to stick it to ordinary working guys like Jim Helin, who have
no influence whatever over state policy and for whom a thousand
bucks is not an insignificant sum. The commission says it doesn't
like the law and would like it changed to exclude small fry like
Jim Helin. Richard Rivkin, the commission's executive director,
admitted that ``this is not the greatest case in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raises this question: why bring it, then? Who was going to
raise hell if the ethics commission simply decided not to bust this
poor guy's chops? Where was the huge public outcry to hang poor Jim
Helin?
</P>
<P>
   A century and a half ago, the French novelist, Honore de Balzac,
wrote: ``Bureaucracy is a giant mechanism operated by pygmies.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much has changed, Mr. Balzac.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
