A0113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-POLLUTION-HNS &LR;      08-12 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT THROWS OUT NEW YORK REQUIREMENT ON ELECTRIC CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA GRACE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A federal appeals court threw a roadblock in
front of a state regulation mandating that 2 percent of all
vehicles sold in New York beginning this year be non-polluting.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, made Tuesday, ends New York's bid to lead the
country in the number of zero-emission vehicles, or ZEVs, sold.
Most ZEVs are electric cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the state Department of Environmental Conservation
adopted a policy requiring automobile manufacturers to produce 2
percent of their fleets as ZEVs by this year. That number was to
increase until 2003, when the mandate topped out at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan held that the New
York standard was out of step with the national standard and was a
burden to car makers. It also said the state regulation did not
conform with the exception that is allowed, the so-called
``California standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased because this is a decision which is actually to
the benefit of New York state consumers,'' said Lois R. Phillips,
an Albany attorney representing automobile dealers opposed to the
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Car manufacturers argued that the development of ZEVs should be
left to market forces and not to ``artificial sales quotas'' and
that battery technology is not sufficiently advanced to make ZEVs a
``commercial and practical reality,'' said Phillip A. Lacovara, a
New York City attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare political marriage, Republican Gov. George Pataki and
several state environmental groups supported the regulations, and
the state attorney general went to court to defend them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulations adopted by (the Department of Environmental
Conservation) were meant to push the technology, to encourage the
sale of electric vehicles in New York state in hopes of meeting our
transportation needs and addressing out air quality problems,''
said Gary Sheffer, spokesman for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the program has worked, it has pushed the
technology,'' he added, ``and we hope that regardless of what
happens in the courts, that the progress made by the auto makers
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said New York, especially New York City, already has problems
meeting federal air quality standards and that those standards are
going to get tougher in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Automobiles contribute half of the ozone-smog-causing
pollutants and virtually all the carbon monoxide,'' Sheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   The state can appeal the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court.
Last year, U.S. District Judge Lawrence E. Kahn in Albany held that
the New York standards were a way of achieving the goals of the
Clean Air Act and ruled that they could stand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reversing his decision on a strict interpretation of the law,
the appeals panel wrote, ``The language here seems plain enough ...
States must adopt and enforce standards that are `identical' to the
California standards.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's standard was identical to California's until 1993,
when that state shifted its regulation of alternate-fuel vehicles,
voiding the 2 percent goal by 1998, but maintaining the 10 percent
requirement by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental department argued that it was not out of line
with federal law because it was essentially following California,
``albeit by a slightly different standard,'' Sheffer said. ``We are
doing the same thing. It's just that California postponed their
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan-based appeals court disagreed, finding that if the
New York regulations were allowed to stand that could lead other
states to create individual standards.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling favored car makers, some environmentalists
were somewhat optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it isn't going to make a huge difference, and
the reason is they weren't complying with it,'' said Valerie
Washington, executive director of Environmental Advocates in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   She said that because there is ``a future in alternative fuel
vehicles'' manufacturers will look at them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
