<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Africa bombings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Developments in the attack on
the U.S. Embassy: The U.S. ambassador to Kenya goes on national
television. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ENVOY (Nairobi) _ Feature on Prudence Bushnell, the
popular ambassador who has become the focus of some criticism. By
James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-INQUIRY (Nairobi) _ A look at how hard it is to find the
culprits in this sort of terrorism investigation. The success rate
is always low and the investigations always lengthy. But this case
is especially complicated because of the near-simultaneous
explosions that are suspected to have been the product of highly
organized groups who may have been working together with no
knowledge of one another. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TANZANIA (Dar es Salaam) _ Developments in the terrorist
attack on the U.S. Embassy in Tanzania. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DEAD (Ramstein Air Base, Germany) _ Secretary of State
Albright goes to Ramstein to escort the American dead back to Dover
and to visit with those who are being treated for their injuries
from the bomb blasts. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Iraqis play hardball: According to
letters to the Security Council from the head of the IAEA and the
head of the special commission to disarm Iraq, not only are
inspections of Iraqi weapons paralyzed, but the whole long-term
monitoring system has been reduced to unacceptable levels. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N.-BUTLER (United Nations) _ The Iraqis have filmed their
last three meetings with the chief U.N. arms inspector Richard
Butler. On Tuesday, breaking a promise to keep the film
confidential and archival, Iraq showed hours of it on TV and
peddled it around the networks. The culminating scene was of Tariq
Aziz haranguing Butler, and Butler storming out of the room. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ A news analysis on the ruling
Taliban militia's sweep of northern Afghanistan and what it means
to the country. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   BURMA-DISSIDENT (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Pro-democracy leader Aung
San Suu Kyi was blocked Wednesday when she left her home to meet
members of her political party outside the capital, defying
Myanmar's military regime. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OBSTRUCT (Washington) _ The problems, and opportunities,
of an obstruction of justice accusation against Clinton. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING (Washington) _ The lawyer and family of the
accused Capitol killer hold a press conference. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-QUAKE (San Francisco) _ An 5.4 earthquake enlivens the
morning rush hour in the San Francisco Bay area. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-BOTTLERS (Kinston, N.C.) _ Pepsico's independent bottlers
have been fighting an uphill battle against Coca-Cola Consolidated,
the second-largest Coke bottler in the U.S., which can afford big
marketing campaigns and price wars in the fight over shelf space
and vending machines. Now, 12 years after Coke moved to a
centralized ``anchor bottling'' model, Pepsico is considering a
spinoff of its company-owned bottling operations, which might then
acquire independent bottlers _ which are already consolidating. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The dollar falls and stocks rise. Comments
by officials in Tokyo give the Japanese currency some support, and
at midday, the dollar stood at 146.03 yen, down from 147.35 yen in
late New York trading Tuesday afternoon. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 82 points at 1:30 p.m. Overseas, shares eased 0.2
percent in Tokyo but rose 1.2 percent in Hong Kong. They rose 1.9
percent in Frankfurt and were flat in London. In this country, the
long bond was off 6/32 point, with the yield at 5.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   Other market stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHER-TRIAL (Chicago) _ Developments at the Archer Daniels
Midland price-fixing trial. By Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Microsoft asks for a stay of
Tuesday's ruling that opened to the public the deposition by
Microsoft chief Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ In his farewell performance, the NYT
columnist Peter Passell laments the fact that, while the American
system is doing many things right, it is doing one big thing wrong:
For the last quarter century, virtually all of economic growth's
bounty has gone to the educated, enterprising and already-affluent.
</P>
