<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0127 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     08-12 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-NUDITY HUFF DESERVES A REBUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Maybe you've seen Laetitia Casta posing nude on the
``Rolling Stone'' cover currently on newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Or, depending on where you shop, maybe you haven't. The usual
paragons of moral superiority _ Wal-Mart, Kmart, Target, etc. _
have banned the issue from their newsstand shelves.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. I doubt whether these stores even sell the
nude shade of pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. In my selfless role as a crusading journalist and
in an attempt to both shed light on controversial issues and
protect the public from dangers real and perceived, I have studied
the cover carefully. Many, many times.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The cover shows Casta in a pose somewhat reminiscent of Marilyn
Monroe in the photo that was used as the centerfold in the first
issue of ``Playboy,'' only Casta is less revealing.
</P>
<P>
   True, the view from behind is pretty complete. But without
getting into details fit only for men's magazines and front-page
newspaper stories describing the Bill Clinton-Monica Lewinksy
controversy, let's just say someone in the art department at
``Rolling Stone'' must be armed with an airbrush and he isn't
afraid to use it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always momentarily boggled when someone gets upset over
something like this. So some beautiful model type flashes a little
skin on a magazine cover. And we're supposed to care? It's like
getting upset over a dog sniffing people in inappropriate places:
It's what they do. If you don't like it, don't look (and ``Rolling
Stone'' made that easy, by putting a removable card across the
cover for newsstand copies that hides Casta's, ahem, assets). &QL; 
 &QL; 
HECK, HECK, DARN, DARN
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But then I recall that every time I quote someone who uses the
words ``hell'' or ``damn,'' I hear from people outraged by such
shocking language.
</P>
<P>
   More power to you. I sincerely hope you enjoy the rest of 1927.
And by the way, your ankle is showing.
</P>
<P>
   It all goes back to the age-old debate: Is the human body in its
natural state beautiful or pornographic? Depends on the context.
And the body.
</P>
<P>
   Nudity in general doesn't offend me. It's not necessarily a
selling point _ I didn't buy Prince's ``Lovesexy'' CD way back when
just because he was sitting there naked on a leaf on the cover _
but it won't stop me from making a purchase or using a product. I
didn't boycott ``NYPD Blue'' when they showed Sipowicz's butt
(though I did skip my midnight snack).
</P>
<P>
   Those who know about such things say ``Rolling Stone's''
circulation has been slipping of late, that its motivation for
putting Casta on the cover in her birthday suit was to sell more
copies of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Noooo! Next thing you know, they'll be saying American Express
hired Jerry Seinfeld for its commercials because it wanted more
customers. There is no end to perceptive analysis, especially now
that Matt Drudge has his own television show. &QL; 
G,WHAT ABOUT ME?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm surprised more magazines haven't tried nude covers _ it's a
guaranteed attention-getter. Remember the pregnant Demi Moore on
the cover of ``Vanity Fair``? Why not put a stripped-down Drew
Carey on the cover of ``TV Guide``? He's an Everyman sort of
fellow, a beer-and-a-shot kind of guy. Pour him into one of those
thongs that rides way up high, pose him so as to keep things legal,
and every Schlitz drinker on the planet will feel better about
himself. Or worse about Drew anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of solidarity with Casta, I considered switching the
usual picture that runs atop this column with a full-body nude shot
of myself. But I realized that any picture _ clothed or not _ that
doesn't reveal your waistline is the one you want to go with.
</P>
<P>
   Casta's body shape lends itself to nudity. Mine lends itself to
having the ``G'' in a human ``G-O S-U-N-S'' banner painted on it.
</P>
<P>
   Teenage smoking offends me. Pro sports salaries offend me. Sam
Donaldson offends me.
</P>
<P>
   A nude ``Rolling Stone'' cover just doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the naked truth. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
