<HEADLINE>
FORMER SOVIET ATHLETE REDISCOVERS STARDOM IN THE USA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GAGE HARTER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As one of the best modern pentathletes in the
world, Vaho Iagorachvili remembers the days he lived like a king.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the Soviet Union's top 10 athletes, Iagorachvili had
the money, the fame and most importantly, he had the respect.
</P>
<P>
   He had won the bronze medal at the 1988 Seoul Olympics and the
gold at the 1986 Goodwill Games. Iagorachvili held the Soviet
national title three times and was European champion in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was well-known,'' Iagorachvili, 34, said. ``I had
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   When when the old communist state began to unravel, Iagorachvili
was forced to return to his native Georgia, a former Soviet
republic.
</P>
<P>
   There he found life without heat, running water and food. Where
there was so much hope, Iagorachvili encountered despair.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991, a chance meeting with American pentathlete Rob
Stull rejuvenated Iagorachvili. Stull offered Iagorachvili a chance
to go to the United States and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Iagorachvili jumped at the opportunity and seven years later,
he's representing the United States in international competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here a long time,'' Iagorachvili said. ``It does
feel a little different. But this is my home now.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Aug. 2, Iagorachvili brought back a silver medal for the
United States from the World Championships in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this maybe was my last chance to win a medal,'' said
Iagorachvili, who now lives in Austin, Texas. ``I wanted to make
sure I did my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Iagorachvili's silver was the first U.S. individual men's medal
since 1979, when Bob Nieman won the gold at the world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Modern pentathlon is a creation of Baron Pierre de Coubertin,
the Frenchman largely responsible for the modern Olympics. He
patterned the sport after the duties of a Napoleonic courier,
making the competition the ultimate challenge for a soldier ordered
to deliver a message.
</P>
<P>
   At its highest level, the sport consists of 20 air-pistol shots
from 10 meters, a 200-meter swim, a round-robin fencing tournament,
equestrian show-jumping and a 3-kilometer run.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised many people about Iagorachvili's performance was
that he retired in March to pursue other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to work to pay my bills,'' Iagorachvili said. ``It's
hard to earn a living and train. But (U.S. national team) coach
(Victor Svatenko) asked me to come back so I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Iagorachvili went to Colorado Springs, Colo., to train for four
weeks before the championships.
</P>
<P>
   Iagorachvili said he would retire again and go back to work as a
physical education instructor at Austin Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no other choice,'' he said. ``I have two children and a
family to think about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
