<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIST'S-HOME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GROUP ACQUIRES HOME OF ARTIST THOMAS COLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CATSKILL, N.Y. _ Major brush strokes have been added to the
work-in-progress of restoring the home of Thomas Cole, who founded
the Hudson River School of painting.
</P>
<P>
   The Greene County Historical Society has signed a contract to
purchase the long-neglected building in Catskill from a struggling
foundation that has owned it for roughly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The development comes as President Clinton last month designated
the Hudson as one of 14 American Heritage Rivers, a move that
spotlights the Hudson Valley region and can serve as a catalyst to
generate additional funding for projects like the Cole house.
</P>
<P>
   Activists pushing to refurbish Cole's earliest studio and home
see it as crucial to the growth of eco-tourism in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Cole is credited with spawning an American art movement famous
for its ethereal beams of light illuminating the rugged landscape,
not as wilderness to be conquered but as an inspirational work of
God. One of his pupils was Frederic Church, whose beautifully
restored Moorish-inspired house, Olana, across the river in
Greenport, is now a state historic site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Cole's historic value,'' said Darlene Downing,
executive director of the Catskill Center for Conservation and
Development. ``But frankly, it's also a keystone eco-tourism venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can come across the river from Olana in Columbia
County, visit the Cole house and then travel up the Catskill
escarpment to the mountains the Hudson River School artists
painted, and even go on to Cooperstown. James Fenimore Cooper was a
friend of Cole and part of that whole intellectual genre of looking
to the wilderness for inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans to construct a new museum and visitor center at Olana
received a major boost in June when Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y.,
tucked $1 million for the project into a transportation bill.
Preliminary plans call for the 18,000-square-foot complex to be
built on a site adjacent to the historic property on a bluff
overlooking the river.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Rip Van Winkle Bridge, the Catskill
Center has had a conservation easement on the Cole property that
ensures its preservation for public use and architectural
integrity. The Arkville-based center helped arrange the recent
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Cole site has been purchased by the Greene County Historical
Society from the Thomas Cole Foundation for $87,500. The final
transfer awaits cutting through some red tape governing the
handling of assets by nonprofit groups, but those close to the
project said no major problems are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition was financed in large part by a roughly $100,000
donation made by Raymond Beecher, former president of the local
historical society, which already oversees the historic Bronck
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Beecher said plans call for the house to be refurnished with
historic pieces from Cole's time, including some botanical
specimens and paintings donated by a Cole family descendant.
</P>
<P>
   The site and setting will be invaluable to understanding the art
and philosophy of the young American democracy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose, like everything else, you could read about it in a
book,'' said Beecher, 81. ``But there's nothing like seeing the
site and the studio and the gallery exhibits and then going to see
one of the nearby areas he painted like Kaaterskill Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the state matched Beecher's generosity with a
$192,000 grant from the state Environmental Bond Act to be
allocated for restoration of building exteriors on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to have it opened to the public by the millennium,
and then have a major retrospective of Cole's work,'' Downing said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
