<P>
   BOMBING-INSIDER _ Working as a Foreign Service Officer at the
U.S. Embassy in Paris during a time of heightened tension in the
mi-'80s, Mark Sherman distinctly remembers the first time security
guards blew up a suspicious parcel. It wasn't a bomb. And neither
was the tin of cookies _ a Christmas gift _ that the Marine guards
refused to accept. But the threats are always there, and they
affect the mindset of the people who daily represent the U.S.
government on foreign soil. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GINGRICH _ BELFAST, Ireland _ What has House Speaker
Newt Gingrich gleaned from his trip to Ireland? Today, he tries
tracing his maternal ancestors in Donegal. But the Georgia
Republican has also met with leaders of Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), and other Catholic and
Protestant leaders. He also helped build two houses with Habitat
for Humanity. Has the trip affected him at all? Did he back
President Clinton here, unlike his trip to the Middle East earlier
this year? Does he have a message for the Irish people? What's left
on the trip agenda? (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CASTRO _ MIAMI _ Every summer, Castro's birthday unleashes
a fresh round of feverish speculation concerning the health of the
Communist dictator, much of it kindled by wishful thinking. And
this birthday's no exception. Castro turns 72 on Thursday. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CASTRO-BOX _ MIAMI _ Fidel Castro's recent wide-ranging
