<P>
   JOURNAL-ISRAEL _ JERUSALEM _ The waitress could see that my
parents and I were novices. Huddled with a few Israelis in the
bathroom corridor of a downtown sandwich shop, we waited for word
that the suspicious object down the street was harmless. ``Is this
your first time?'' asked our server. Such friendly smiles might be
a rarity in this tense city, but bomb scares are not. Minutes
later, we were allowed back to our table. After a year as Cox
Newspapers' Middle East correspondent, I realized, during this
visit from my parents, that I'm getting used to conditions that
most Americans would find unnerving and most Israelis barely
notice. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
