<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   US-ADULTERY _ WASHINGTON - Despite President Clinton's high
approval ratings in the face of allegations of marital infidelity,
a huge majority of Americans still believe adultery is wrong,
according to polling data. And adultery among the average American
couple is far less common than the flurry of recent allegations
against Clinton and other public figures would suggest, say
sociologists, marriage counselors and clergy. But in cases of
divorce, adultery plays a much larger role. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-CLERGY _ WASHINGTON _ The Family Research Council sponsors
a forum with a panel of clergy members and teachers who discuss
what the Bible and the Koran say about homosexuality. Other topics
for discussion include the role of religious views on homosexuality
in the making of public policy and recent print ads that question
whether or not homosexuality is an immutable identity. (Shook, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _A Nebraska attorney who has pledged to represent Eric
Robert Rudolph once he is found alive, said he doubts the
Birmingham bombing suspect would ever be executed under existing
federal law. He wouldn't say this week on whether he would coach
his potential client to turn in others who may have been involved
in the bombing or bomings if Rudolph is charged in the Atlanta
cases. Decamp will be in the state of North Caroina at a convention
and a phone call a way when Patriot leader Bo Gritz goes into the
woods of Western North Carolina to hopefully negotiate Rudolph from
his hiding place. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
