<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROZEN-COFFEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARISTAS FIND HOT COMMODITY IN FROZEN COFFEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The season's hottest drink is frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Not frozen solid, of course. It's a blended beverage mixing ice,
coffee and any number of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Then you haven't set foot in a donut shop or coffee
bar on a sultry summer afternoon and waited impatiently for the
drink that refreshes.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen coffee drinks, relatively unheard of just two years ago,
are suddenly as popular as a winning Powerball ticket. Well, maybe
not that the odds on being able to enjoy one are far better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The daily consumption of frozen coffee has almost doubled in
the past year,'' said Gary Goldstein, spokesman for the National
Coffee Association in New York. ``It's almost an entirely new
coffee beverage that appeals to non-coffee drinkers as well as the
regular coffee consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunkin' Donuts has done some market research and 20 to 25
percent of its Coolatta buyers are non-coffee drinkers. These
drinks are introducing some people to coffee as a beverage through
a category that hadn't been thought of before, the cold category.''
</P>
<P>
   Some coffee shops, such as Starbucks, make their frozen drinks
with shots of espresso, while others rely on fresh-brewed coffee
(Dunkin' Donuts). Either way, it seems to be a recipe for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's craziness. Cold drinks are becoming just as popular as
hot drinks,'' said Beth Wood-Leidt, president of Connecticut-based
Nancy's Coffee Cafe. Her stores offer frozen cappuccinos and frozen
mochas, as well as mocha shakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, people have never thought of coffeehouses as a
place that offers cold products,'' Wood-Leidt added, ``but that's
changed completely in the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Iced coffee has been with us for ages, but frozen coffee made
its debut in the Northeast just last year.
</P>
<P>
   A chain in California, Coffee Bean &AMP; Tea Leaf, claims to be the
first retailer to have added frozen coffee drinks to its menu, but
industry experts can't agree on which company first took the
concept of a caffeine-laced smoothie or frappe and began marketing
the heck out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Starbucks gets credit for popularizing this
beverage, however. Last summer, the ubiquitous chain started
offering coffee, mocha, chocolate, vanilla and decaf Frappuccinos
in three different sizes, and has advertised its drinks heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks officials declined to provide sales figures for frozen
drinks, which as of this summer includes a non-coffee drink as
well, the Tiazzi, a blend of tea, juice and ice. But Dunkin'
Donuts, which introduced the coffee Coolatta last summer, is not
shy about sharing the impact of its frozen coffee drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee Coolatta sales reached $65 million last year and are
expected to top $90 million this year, according to a spokesman for
Dunkin' Donuts, which this summer has added fruit Coolattas to its
repertoire. Most Dunkin' Donuts shops experienced a 20 percent to
30 percent increase in sales last summer, due to the introduction
of the coffee Coolatta, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of its competitors, Dunkin' Donuts charges more than
twice the cost of a cup of coffee for one of its frozen drinks. The
Coolattas come in three sizes (16, 24 and 32 ounces) and have a
recommended retail price of $1.99 to $3.99, depending on the size
and flavor. The price range at Starbucks is from $2.35 to $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a good comparison for the frozen coffee drinks is
microbeers, another rage item for the '90s. Both sell for about
$3.50 each, and there doesn't seem to be much price resistance from
people,'' said Bruce Mullins, director of new products and
education at Coffee Bean International in Portland, Ore. ``We're
talking about a drink that's really fresh and I think that's a hot
button right now for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coffee shops themselves are evolving. The only option a few
years ago was for decaf, or possibly an espresso or cappuccino.
Many coffee bars now offer dozens of flavors of coffee, and frozen
drinks are but another way they have found to diversify their menu.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Torrence, owner of Stagecoach Coffee, headquartered in
Cooperstown, N.Y., compares today's coffee shops to the bar
industry two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frozen coffee drinks are really like smoothies, which were
a big deal in California five or six years ago,'' Torrence
observed. ``This is part of an overall trend. Coffee bars are
following the pattern of real bars, where the number of drinks
proliferated with frozen margaritas and other specialty drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where this is going is anyone's guess, but today's coffee bars
remind me of the fern bars of the '70s and '80s. Consumers are
steadily becoming more savvy about what they want, and the coffee
bars are trying to stay one step ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
