u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-RESILIENCY-HNS &LR;      08-12 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RESILIENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T COUNT THE JAPANESE OUT DESPITE THEIR TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Japan's new prime minister conceded this week that his
country's economy is in a bad way and is facing a long, hard slump.
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazingly frank confession for a Japanese official to
make. In Japan it's considered poor manners to be that blunt. The
Japanese much prefer to speak elliptically. So when Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi referred to a ``severe situation,'' it meant things
must be pretty rough _ rougher, in fact, than most foreign experts
previously realized.
</P>
<P>
   But although Japan is down, don't count it out.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese are a highly resilient people, as they demonstrated
when they emerged _ literally _ from the ashes of their
catastrophic wartime defeat in 1945 to soon build one of the
world's most powerful economies, even challenging that of their
conqueror, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When I first went to Japan in the early 1950s, the scars of the
war were everywhere. The cities had been largely burned out. The
highway from the port of Yokohama to Tokyo was a trail of
incinerated factories. Yet Japan already had the feel of a nation
on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese optical firms had begun turning out world-class
cameras. High-quality steel alloys matched the best the United
States and Europe had to offer. The startling aspect of this was
that these were products that pre-war Japan, which specialized in
cheap imitations of Western goods, had not manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and business executives had already made the key
strategic decision to become an industrial power in the full sense,
recognizing that the old Japanese economy would never provide the
prosperity they sought.
</P>
<P>
   The embryonic auto industry churned out flimsy models that
looked as if they were held together with rubber bands and glue.
Indeed, the bodies of these early Toyotas and Datsuns were hammered
out by hand. Foreigners laughed and said no one had to worry about
competition from the Japanese car industry. But the Japanese
weren't laughing. Within a decade or so, they acquired a hefty
slice of the global auto market from the western car makers who had
sneered at them.
</P>
<P>
   This is all an old story by now. Still, it is worth recalling.
Most of Japan's problems are of its own making, the result of too
much power residing in too few hands especially in the top
government bureaucracy and the big banks.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Japanese drew the appropriate lessons from their
disastrous misadventure in militarism in the 1930s and '40s, they
are likely to make the required changes to get themselves back on
their feet now.
</P>
<P>
   It could take time. In some ways, the Japanese are extremely
cautious and conservative. But eventually they do move. That's the
moment to watch out for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
