<P>
   BED-DESIGN (Undated) _ The bed has gone to its head. The
traditional, boat-like bed that saw you through life's journey _
from birth to death, from stem to stern, from side to side _ is
becoming a more minimal platform for modern living. It is now
basically a flat barge for layered bed linens. But, ready to seize
the moment, the headboard is grabbing the spotlight and going solo.
From couture-end home furnishing designers to mass-market
retailers, the headboard alone is being sold as an option for the
bed and making itself widely available. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BEACH-HOUSE (Undated) _ Michael Jantzen, a California
designer and conceptual artist, was driving down the Pacific Coast
Highway in Malibu one day when he had an unusual vision. ``I was
looking at all the ugly houses blocking the view of the ocean,'' he
said, ``and I thought, wouldn't it be nice to see the ocean on the
facade?'' The result _ a millennial flight of fantasy yet to be
built _ is the world's first video beach house. In what is perhaps
an architectural critic's dream, a ho-hum building could seem to
disappear. In this case, video monitors pointing toward the ocean
in the back of the house project waves and sky onto the facade. By
Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LIBRARY (Los Angeles) _ The Clinton mystery that
consumes an elite slice of America's architectural and
entertainment establishment these days has nothing to do with DNA
and everything to do with bricks and mortar. Or glass and steel. Or
granite and marble. So far, only the scene is known: 26 acres of
warehouses and vacant lots on the banks of the Arkansas River in
Little Rock have now been set aside as the future home of the
William J. Clinton Presidential Library. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS-SHRINE (Holly Springs, Miss.) _ ``I guess I know more
about Elvis than Elvis knew about himself,'' said Paul MacLeod, who
over the last few years has turned the antebellum house he
inherited here into Graceland Too, a shrine run by the
self-described ``universe's, the galaxy's, the planet's, the
world's No. 1 Elvis fan.'' By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   FORMICA-LANDMARK (Undatd) _ Everyone knows what decorative
laminate is. That's the plastic stuff, often called Formica, that
renovators rip out when they restore a historic house. But take
note. It's none other than those garish old plastic laminates,
circa 1959, that have just qualified the Ralph Sr. and Sunny Wilson
House, in Temple, Texas, for a plaque from the National Park
Service. By Barbara Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   BACKYARD-BARBECUE (Undated) _ Smoke gets in their eyes _ and
that's only part of the attraction. Once man cooked over an open
fire in a cave. Some time later came the 1950s backyard grill, a
mammoth creation etched on the landscape in brick or stone. In the
'60s more mobile chefs, or those without backyards, swore by their
portable hibachis and Weber kettle grills. And then came the '80s
and the portable gas-fired grills that turned summer cookery into
something as romantic as, say, lighting the kitchen range. And now?
After two decades of growth, the American economy has brought a
return to the backyard barbecue. By Donna Paul.
</P>
<P>
   RUG-BUSINES (New York) _ The intimate world of oriental rug
dealers is about to get even cosier. As of Sept. 1, ABC Carpet of
Manhattan is taking over the 3rd-floor rug department at Harrods of
Knightsbridge in London. This late-blooming marriage between two
centenarian retail giants appears to be a far from impulsive union
born of mutual admiration and canny business savvy.
</P>
<P>
   HARRELL-DESIGN (New York) _ Five years ago in Harlem, Andre
Harrell, then the president of Uptown Entertainment, a record
label, had a design epiphany. He went to a cocktail party at Graham
Court, at 116th Street and Adam Clayton Powell Jr. Boulevard;
walked into the apartment of Warner Johnson, the managing director
of Axicom Online.com, a Web-based telephone company, and found the
look that had been eluding him. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
