<SLUG> BC-APPLE-COMPUTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE'S NEW MAC NO GUARANTEE OF COMPANY'S SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE SPAIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Coming soon to a store near you is Apple
Computer's much ballyhooed iMac, the friendly $1,299 all-in-one
computer aimed at the education and home consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Pronounced EYE-MAC, the ``i'' stands for the Internet. The
company boasts it takes less than eight minutes for even a child to
open the box, plug in everything and get onto the Net.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mac World Expo in New York last month, the company
displayed dozens of blue-green, translucent plastic-cowled iMacs to
play a mini-infomercial called ``Simplicity Shootout,'' which sums
up Apple's iMac marketing approach.
</P>
<P>
   The video features a 7-year-old boy setting up an iMac, squaring
off against a 26-year-old Stanford MBA doing the same with a PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good computer, for a Wintel PC,'' the pleasant sounding
but patronizing narrator says. Wintel refers to the Microsoft
Windows Operating System running with a processor made by microchip
giant Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In split screen, the two open their boxes and assemble the
computer systems. Naturally, the simplicity of the iMac setup is
emphasized. In eight minutes, 15 seconds, the youngster turns his
iMac on and is on his way to setting up his Internet browser.
Meanwhile, the MBA fumbles through the directions and has to unpack
several boxes, compared with one iMac carton.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngster successfully gets onto the Internet and checks
his stocks portfolio, the MBA appears to struggle, typing in serial
numbers in a complicated setup. Long after the kid and his dog take
off _ about 20 minutes later _ the MBA finally enters the Net. The
fact is that after the initial setup _ and it really does take
longer for a PC _ the PC is nearly as simple to use as the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question the iMac will be welcomed by Macintosh
enthusiasts. It offers a competitively priced path to upgrade their
older Macs and, for the list price of $1,299, packs a lot of power.
Indeed, it has a faster microprocessor and a bigger hard drive than
most of the Macs (and PCs, too, for that matter).
</P>
<P>
   Apple also has announced more than 150 software companies are
producing new and updated software on the Mac OS platform. Some
colleges, such as Dartmouth, have embraced the iMac, recommending
it for incoming freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Those already devoted to the Macintosh platform are applauding
loudly. The real question is, can cool new iMac win over PC users?
Many people who use Windows PCs at work or have had their own PCs
for a couple of years want faster and bigger units so they can
cruise the Internet and run their current programs faster. Does it
make sense for these folks to consider the iMac?
</P>
<P>
   Apple thinks so, but catchy commercials, competitive pricing and
a neat looking computer may not be enough. Apple has to offer
something the potential customer cannot have with his or her PC
(while making sure the customer doesn't lose something by moving to
the Mac.)
</P>
<P>
   This, many have speculated, was one of the biggest reasons for
Apple's alliance with Microsoft last year. Microsoft Office 98 for
the Macintosh runs elegantly, and its Word documents, Excel
spreadsheets and Powerpoint presentations are interchangeable with
their counterparts on the PC version of Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have some PC programs they don't want to give
up, there are Windows emulators such as SoftWindows and Virtual PC
that allow Windows or DOS programs to run on the Mac. These
programs really work and give comfort to those who may be afraid to
move to a Mac. The iMac includes the new G3 processors, which test
up to twice as fast as the Intel Pentium counterparts, but it also
has some new features.
</P>
<P>
   A Universal Serial Bus (USB) port will make hooking up mice,
printers, scanners and digital cameras much easier. Now, all a
manufacturer of a peripheral device for PCs needs to do is write a
relatively simple piece of software, a ``driver,'' for the device
to also be Mac compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Another Apple ``innovation'' on the iMac is that there is no
floppy disk drive. It just comes with a 24X CD-ROM drive. You can
add an external floppy drive, but Apple says small files that fit
on the 1.4 megabyte floppy disks can be e-mailed or put onto the
SuperDisks and Zip Drives, external disk drives that cram 100
megabytes onto a single disk.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the big test will be whether Apple can deliver the
actual product. It is notorious for introducing products, raising
demand, only to disappoint by delaying delivery by months.
</P>
<P>
   Apple promises it will have adequate inventory on iMacs on hand
by Saturday so there will not be an instant shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is part of the process whereby Apple has returned to
profitability. It just completed its third quarter in the black,
gaining lots of praise on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is the third of a four-block matrix of products the
company has been rolling out. The first was the
``Pentium-toasting'' G3 chip Macs for the professional market. Then
there was the release of high-end Powerbook laptops running with
the speedy G3 chips, aimed at the professional market.
</P>
<P>
   Following the iMac, Apple says it will introduce one more
component to the matrix _ a low-cost portable computer aimed at the
home/student market by 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
