<SLUG> BC-SF-POET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO LITERARY FIXTURE NAMES CITY'S POET LAUREATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internationally acclaimed writer, book seller
and publisher Lawrence Ferlinghetti has been named San Francisco's
first poet laureate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our greatest poet, but he's so much more _ he's the
quintessential San Franciscan,'' Mayor Willie Brown said Tuesday in
conferring the honor.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti, 79, will serve in the role for one year beginning
on Oct. 13, when he will deliver the first of what will become an
annual poet laureate's address at the New Main Library.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the annual address, the poet laureate's duties
include participating in cultural events, visiting branch libraries
and meeting and greeting dignitaries visiting the city.
</P>
<P>
   The title will come with a $5,000 annual honorarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as we call upon the ballet, the symphony, and the opera,
we will call upon the poet laureate,'' Brown said, to show off San
Francisco's culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti said he would use his new title as ``a soap box to
promote ideas'' and proceeded to announce two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Poet's House on Treasure Island or the Presidio,'' he said.
``I presented that idea 20 years ago to the Board of Supervisors
and three months ago to Mayor Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   His second idea is to designate North Beach, because of its rich
literary history, a federal historic site.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti said the neighborhood, made famous by the so-called
Beat poets who made San Francisco a hipster poet destination in the
1950s, also attracted writers such as Mark Twain and George
Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti's business, City Lights Bookshop, has been a North
Beach landmark since 1953. It was the nation's first all-paperback
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti launched a publishing career from there in 1955 but
his 1958 book of poetry ``A Coney Island of the Mind'' along with
the late Allen Ginsberg's ``Howl'' were the most popular poetry
books of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   A 1961 compendium, ``Starting from San Francisco,'' took its
title from Walt Whitman and arguably established Ferlinghetti as
this century's Whitmanesque American bard.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our ageless radicals and true bards'' is how Booklist
described Ferlinghetti, the author of 14 books of poetry, four
works of prose, two plays and two works of translation. His most
recent collection of poetry, ``A Far Rockaway of the Heart'' was
published in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferlinghetti's publication of Ginsburg's ``Howl'' in 1956,
which led to his arrest on federal obscenity charges, drew national
attention to the Beat movement and helped establish broader free
speech interpretations. He was acquitted of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Brown announced last November the establishment of a San
Francisco poet laureate during a speech at Seoul University in
South Korea. Last month he formed a seven-member committee, headed
by City Librarian Regina Minudri. The panel provided Brown with a
short list of recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he believed it was necessary to establish the
program because San Franciscans benefit from the cultural
perspective of artists and writers, whom he described as the
``thinkers, dreamers and image constructors'' in society.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti noted proudly that ``Plato in `The Republic' called
the poet subversive to the public and a gadfly to the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
