<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUEDECKE-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ATOMIC ENERGY COMMISSION OFFICIAL DIES AT 87 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA KLEKAR  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Alvin R. Luedecke, who
distinguished himself in the military, as an educator, acting
president of Texas A&AMP;M University and Atomic Energy Commission
official, died Sunday in San Antonio at the age of 87.
</P>
<P>
   The credits to his life are long: He served in World War II and
when he became a brigadier general at age 33, he was the youngest
ranking general in all the armed forces. He later was promoted to
major general, his rank at retirement in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Following his military career, Luedecke became general manager
of the U.S. Atomic Energy Commission for almost five years,
participating in the successful launches of the Voyager and
Surveyor spacecraft missions. The agency eventually became the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Luedecke returned to his alma mater _ Texas A&AMP;M
University, where he received a degree in chemical engineering in
1932 _ as acting president following the death of Gen. Earl Rudder.
He stayed on as an administrator for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Luedecke retired to San Antonio two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a masterful job of leading A&AMP;M. He was an effective and
quiet leader who led by example,'' said Lane Stephenson, deputy
director of university relations at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved A&AMP;M. He didn't need the job; he just wanted to come
back,'' Stephenson added.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin R. Luedecke Jr. of Austin admired his father for the way
the achieved his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to realize that he started in West
Texas, the son of a ranch-farmer and had a pretty rough time with
some lean years,'' the son said. ``He was the eldest of eight
children. He had to learn a lot on his own because there were so
many people around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a true leader of men. The integrity and work ethic of
his parents was passed on to him,'' his son added.
</P>
<P>
   Luedecke said he remembers most the respect his father garnered
in the numerous careers he undertook. ``Whatever job he had, the
one consistency was that all those who worked for him respected
him.''
</P>
<P>
   This earned the general the motto ``Man of patience made of
steel,'' which his son coined after years of witnessing what he
called his father's ``gentleness and strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Luedecke spent the last years of his retirement in San
Antonio, struggling with the loss of his sight and hearing. ``It
was frustrating for him, but he was alert and sharp, and full of
life,'' the son said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the son, the general is survived by his wife
Isabelle; two daughters, Jan Lee Maynard of Littleton, Colo., and
Miriam Luedecke of Loveland, Colo.; six sisters; three
grandchildren and one great-grandchild; three step-children and two
step-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Services are scheduled Friday at Fort Sam Houston National
Cemetery in San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
