<SLUG> BC-VOICE-MAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT ACCUSES PHONE COMPANY OF `HIDING' VOICE MAIL FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pacific Bell allegedly charged hundreds of
thousands of customers a hidden fee for every message on their
voice mail service, a lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action complaint, filed Tuesday in San Francisco
Superior Court, accuses the telephone company of deceptively
advertising the Voice Mail service it sells small business
customers by failing to explain that they are charged the price of
a local call each time they get a message.
</P>
<P>
   The local charges are disguised on the bill, the lawsuit says,
because they are not listed under Voice Mail services but merged
with regular local calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hidden charge here,'' said Terry Gross, a San
Francisco lawyer who specializes in bringing class-action lawsuits.
``Pac Bell has led customers to believe there is one all-inclusive
charge for the Voice Mail service, hiding the fact that there is a
per-call charge for each message received.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross said the average business customer easily could be
``overcharged'' hundreds of dollars a year in such costs.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cohen, a Pacific Bell spokesman, declined to comment on the
lawsuit. He said the Voice Mail service has about 500,000 customers
statewide, and ``it's one of our hottest selling products.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is marketed at $21.95 per month. It is separate from
Pacific Bell's Message Center, a voice mail service sold to home
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses San Francisco-based Pacific Bell of engaging
in false advertising, unfair competition and violations of consumer
protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   The class action was brought by three plaintiffs _ from
Berkeley, Oakland and San Diego _ who filed it on behalf of all
``similarly situated'' Pacific Bell Voice Mail customers.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint asks the court to bar the telephone company from
engaging in the allegedly improper advertising practices and to
order the company to repay any hidden charges.
</P>
<P>
   Local telephone companies around the country recently have come
under pressure from the Federal Communications Commission to stem
unauthorized billings, a practice known as ``cramming.''
</P>
<P>
   In most of these cases, however, the issue was not phone company
charges but ones from third parties _ like call waiting or Internet
access companies _ that are included on the phone bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1541EDT &QL; 
