<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLKS WHO LOVE TO EAT, LIVE TO WRITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the introduction to ``Stirring Prose, Cooking With Texas
Authors'' ($19.95, Texas A&AMP;M Press), author Deborah Douglas
basically explains that she has no business writing the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I don't enjoy eating all that much,'' she writes. ``I
eat mainly because I don't like to go hungry. If someone would only
invent them, I would gladly swallow pills labeled `Breakfast,'
`Dinner' and `Supper.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, no one has. To fill the pages of this book she had
no business writing, Douglas (who is a pathologist, I guess it
should be noted, although I'm not sure why) went to a host of
writers around the state and asked them for a few of their favorite
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can't ask a bunch of writers for a simple recipe.
What Douglas got is a book full of essays. It is what she hoped for
all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``By asking authors to write about something as familiar as
their favorite recipes, they were freed from the big toe-digging
constraints of having to talk directly about themselves,'' she
writes. ``The resulting off-center reflections are brilliant slices
of their personalities and their writing styles.''
</P>
<P>
   One more small note: Douglas knows that it was her
responsibility to test the recipes, to make sure the ingredients
and their amounts were correct. She didn't. She's not much of a
proofreader, she acknowledges, so the numbers might not be all that
accurate. And she tried only one finished product.
</P>
<P>
   It was Larry L. King's remedy for Asian flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did it not cure the flu, but I woke up with a
horrendous headache, trembling hands, bloodshot eyes, churning
stomach and a surly outlook,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the end of her testing. She warns: ``Eat and drink at
your own risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine writers contributed to ``Stirring Prose,'' and not
all of their recipes are debilitating. Some aren't even for food _
such as King's _ and some are for foods you aren't likely to fix.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Flores offers a recipe for a 2-pound buffalo tenderloin.
Robert Flynn has a stew that calls for 2 pounds of diced lion.
</P>
<P>
   John Graves presents an ideal sandwich. It calls for peanut
butter on one slice of the bread and mayonnaise on the other. Add
fresh buttercrunch lettuce, slices of Big Boy or Better Boy
tomatoes and several thick slices of the ``old, true, dry-cured,
smokehouse kind'' of bacon. The sandwich can be embellished, he
says, with a hard-fried egg, or slivers of fresh green jalapeno,
seeds attached.
</P>
<P>
   James Ward Lee begins his recipe for neck bones and liver with:
``Kill a hog and take the liver on in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee warns, unnecessarily, that we won't find a can of mushroom
soup or a ``ten-ounce package of frozen broccoli,'' in any of his
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious in ``Stirring Prose'' that good, everyday recipes
are somewhat accidental, although there are quite a few. What
Douglas was looking for was how people felt about cooking; what
kind of emotions cooking evoked from them.
</P>
<P>
   She got a lot of history, a lot of folklore and a lot of special
remembrances. Sunny Nash remembered her grandmother, Bigmama, and
Bigmama's mysterious rose-water splash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother told me, `No matter how awkwardly your features
are arranged on your face or what color the skin on your face may
be, if the skin on your face is flawless, then your face is
divine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nash remembered that about once a month in the spring and
summer, her family kitchen became a laboratory for ``rose-water
splashes, sudsy complexion bars and herbal treatments for problem
skin, nails, and scalps.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigmama's recipe for rose-water splash: Take the petals of one
medium to large rose, 2 cups tap water, and 1/4 cup of clear
rubbing alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, bring water to a boil. Drop rose petals
into boiling water. Reduce heat, cover and simmer for 10 minutes.
Remove from heat. Allow to cool before stirring in the alcohol.
Store in a cool place in glass bottles with lids, stoppers or
corks.
</P>
<P>
   Nash says that the recipe can be doubled, tripled or quadrupled.
She suggests placing a rosebud or a fresh petal in the bottle to
indicate what color flower the rose water was extracted from.
</P>
<P>
   Nash writes that no one she knew, growing up in Bryan, could
afford to buy cosmetics; they made their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women who lived along the narrow dirt roads of my
neighborhood did their laundry in the back yard by hand in a tub
with a rub-board and homemade soap. These women, though, had a
soft, sultry beauty that was matched only by the grace with which
they went about their unfortunate lives.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0321 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PGA-TEMPERS-SPI &LR;      08-12 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-TEMPERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEED OFF: HOW GOLFERS CAN KEEP THEIR COOL WHEN TEMPERS FLARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sudden death in golf may not always mean a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wozeniak, head pro at Interbay Family Golf Center in
Seattle, has heard tales of players who have died after angrily
breaking their clubs, only to have a jagged shaft snap back and
pierce an artery.
</P>
<P>
   While that might be merely a chilling bit of golf lore, there's
little question that many players are mad about golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had clients destroy tee markers _ just smash 'em _ break
clubs over their knees, stomp their putters,'' said Deborah Graham,
a Texas sports psychologist who works with more than 100 touring
pros, including some playing in this week's PGA Championship at
Redmond's Sahalee Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen that commercial where a player heaves his whole
bag into the lake? That's happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping everyone from weekend hackers to the world's best
golfers to tee off without being teed off is part of the job of
instructors and sports psychologists, who say emotional stability
is a key to a successful game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is a sport where there's very little release of tension
and emotion,'' said Graham, whose clients play on the PGA, LPGA,
Senior PGA and Nike tours. ``Those things have an outlet in contact
sports or in sports where you're moving at an active pace or
reacting to a moving ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``In golf, you have a lot of time to think. And the ball is just
sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond pro golfer Rick Fehr, who is considered to be a
gentleman on and off the PGA Tour, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players can bang bodies as they battle for a rebound or
basket, he said, and frustrated athletes in team sports kick water
coolers. But outbursts stand out in golf, a game of decorum and
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there before,'' Fehr said sheepishly. ``Sometimes
you do something childish and immature. I'm not sure golfers are
more guilty of this than others. But maybe we're more visible.''
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, a long hitter with a short temper, broke his 5-iron
en route to one of his three double bogies during the third round
of the St. Jude Classic in Memphis earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   While the tales Wozeniak has heard about golfers accidentally
killing themselves may be more myth than fact _ a computer search
of newspaper files across the country found no cases of such
self-inflicted deaths or injuries _ stories of literal weekend
warriors abound.
</P>
<P>
   They include the reported death of a Wisconsin golfer in 1996
after a fight triggered by accusations of slow play.
</P>
<P>
   And the time in 1994 when an Ohio golfer fractured the skull of
a player with a club after a disagreement over whose group was to
tee off first. Two years later, another Ohio golfer broke the nose
of a player in a slow-moving foursome, which included a pregnant
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Pennsylvania golfer was convicted of punching a
tournament official in the face after shooting a quadruple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   The violent outbursts suggest that the aggressors may have
problems dealing with anger anywhere, not just on the course. But
even more typical expressions of frustration, such as tossing
clubs, may not be directly linked to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, the anger you see on the golf course has other
roots,'' Graham said. ``Very often it's suppressed anger about a
frustrating work situation, financial problems, family problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other individual sports, golf tends to attract those who
``may be a little more competitive and self-reliant, but it also
puts players in the position of being very critical of
themselves,'' said Jim Bauman, a sports psychologist at Washington
State University.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is getting players not to dwell on past mistakes
or look too far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell golfers, you never play the last shot. You never play
the next shot. You play one shot at a time, period,'' Bauman said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who evaluates the personalities of her clients and tries
to help them emulate the mental traits of champions, says those who
are used to being in command often find themselves at the mercy of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out and try to control golf, you get into trouble,
because you can't,'' she said. ``Perfectionists can go berserk out
there. The harder he tries, the worse it gets. Golf is a game where
you've got to let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wozeniak likewise strives to induce steady play from his
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get across to people that even the best golfers in
the world don't hit the shots that they want to all day long,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you play best is at an even keel. If you hit a bad
shot, well, you just go from there. That's hard to do. That's why
there are so few great golfers. You can't tell if they're shooting
good or an 80.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Krueger, associate chaplain for the Tour Bible Study, a
Christian ministry to the PGA Tour, said pro golfers are marked by
an intense drive to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they fall short _ and this applies to the weekend golfer
as well _ they throw clubs, get sullen, withdraw,'' he said. ``I
find that the guys who are better able to handle the crisis moment
are the guys who excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realize they're going to hit some bad shots. They don't
let that tank them mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the average golfer who gets ticked off after topping the
third ball in a row, dealing with failure on the course is part of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia sports psychologist Bob Rotella, a consultant to PGA
golfers and other athletes, said the most frustrated players are
amateurs ``who never practice, play once a week, don't have any
skills and should not have any business expecting to play par golf.
They miss a shot and go ballistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing an extreme case, Graham recalled her horror as an
amateur client, upset over his play, bloodied himself by striking
his head with his club. She also heard of a Southwest golfer who
punished himself by plunging into a cactus.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are bordering on self-destructive tendencies,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   To help the typical golfers deal with stress, instructors and
sports psychologists prescribe mental exercises or visual
reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Bauman tells college players to jot down positive thoughts on
cards and tote them in their golf bags. A card might describe a
special place or victory, a reminder of a time when the player was
in control.
</P>
<P>
   He also uses humor as a ``positive distraction,'' suggesting
that players carry a favorite cartoon or look at smiley faces that
they've drawn on the toes of their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's clients might shred a leaf when under duress,
visualizing the release of anger.
</P>
<P>
   Wozeniak advises students to ``take a step back and breathe
deeply a few times before you get to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotella put the issue of dealing with adversity in perspective
in his 1995 book, ``Golf is Not a Game of Perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Golfers must learn to love the challenge when they hit a ball
into the rough, trees or sand,'' Rotella wrote. ``The alternatives
_ anger, fear, whining and cheating _ do no good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
