<HEADLINE>
SEN. GORTON PERSONALLY GOES FISHING FOR A POLLOCK AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Next Tuesday, U.S. Sen. Slade Gorton will preside over
a peace conference among the entrepreneurs of pollock. Fisher men
and women, owners of factory trawlers, catcher boats, mother ships
and shore plants in Alaska will crowd into a room at Davis Wright
Tremaine law offices and have at it. No environmentalists are
invited _ and no media.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, R-Wash., hopes to find some formula to reduce the number
of boats, especially the factory trawlers. One imagines something
like the London Naval Treaty of 1921, which called for the
scrapping of dreadnoughts and set the ratio of capital ships in the
British, American and Japanese navies at 5:5:3. No one disputes
that a similar disarmament is needed in America's highest volume
fishery, in which seasons have shrunk to just 70 days a year. The
question is how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, fired the opening salvo a year ago
with his American Fisheries Act (S. 1221). His bill targets 18 big
boats rebuilt a decade ago in Norwegian yards or that are owned by
Norwegians. It declares its intent to ``Americanize'' the fishery,
and ejects the boats without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton took umbrage at this, which is not surprising in that the
boats are based in Washington state. When Stevens, who chairs the
Appropriations Committee, said he would attach S. 1221 to a money
bill, Gorton threatened to filibuster it. Talking a bill to death
is not a usual Gorton tactic. Stevens agreed to let Gorton try to
work out a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides cheered. The American Fisheries Act Coalition
(www.usafish.org) was happy that Gorton had agreed to the idea of
retiring boats. The companies targeted by Stevens
(www.fairfishlaws.org) were happy that Gorton had insisted that all
sides agree that ``all present participants in the fishery are in
it legally'' and that any reduction in boats ``be done in a manner
that recognizes the economic interests of all.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Stevens side may try to sell Gorton on a boat buyback.
Some compensation might be possible to owners of kicked-out boats,
said maritime attorney Terry Leitzell, vice president of Victor
Seafoods. But he said the foreign-built boats have to go. That, he
said, ``is clearly Sen. Stevens' issue, and we're not in a position
to negotiate it away.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a buyback is who pays. ``I don't think the
government is going to put down money to buy factory trawlers,''
said one boat company boss.
</P>
<P>
   The At-sea Processors Association, which represents most of the
factory trawlers, is pushing for a co-op. The fish are now
allocated among three groups _ at-sea processors, on-shore
processors and Alaskan villages. The association's proposal would
split off the mother ships, leaving just seven factory-trawler
companies _ few enough to divvy up the fish by private agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The result would be a system of individual fishing quotas
(IFQs), which boat owners have been lobbying for since the early
'90s. A formal quota is virtually a property right on the fish.
This would be something less than that, an informal quota. But in a
common-property world, even an informal drawing of fences can pay
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Four companies _ American Seafoods, Tyson, Alaska Ocean and
Glacier Fish _ have done it already in the whiting fishery off the
Oregon coast. The result, said Glacier's manager, John Bundy, has
been that skippers have slowed down, reduced the catch of unwanted
species, increased the quality of the product and stayed in the
black. And because there was no race for fish, the harvest was done
by seven boats instead of 10.
</P>
<P>
   That's a 30 percent reduction in boats. The same plan could cut
the number of factory trawlers in the Bering Sea by 20 percent, the
At-sea Processors Association says.
</P>
<P>
   How about that? Not likely, says Leitzell: ``They get all the
operational benefits of an IFQ, and we don't. We're sitting at the
back of the truck.'' Leitzell likes individual quotas, though some
in his coalition don't. But he says: Reduce the number of boats
first.
</P>
<P>
   How to entice boats to leave? ``I don't know,'' he says. The
Stevens approach has not been to entice them to leave; it has been
to force them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a miracle for Gorton to fashion a consensus from
this. A deal is possible on one issue, though: nationality. ``We
wouldn't oppose a U.S. ownership requirement,'' said Bernt Bodal,
chief executive of American Seafoods, which is owned by Aker/RGI
Group of Oslo, Norway. ``We are willing to work practically to get
something in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodal's boss, Hjell Rokke, was in Seattle a few weeks ago. Bodal
would not confirm it, but several sources said Rokke talked with
representatives of Alaskan villages, which have bought interests in
other factory trawlers. They don't have the cash to buy American's
fleet, but politically they would be unassailable.
</P>
<P>
   And in fish, politics counts for a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a P-I reporter and columnist. His e-mail address
is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
