<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-WINNING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJORS WIN ENSURES A PLACE IN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It can be a major burden or a major relief.
</P>
<P>
   Winning one of golf's four coveted major titles can validate and
enhance an entire career or make every other regular PGA Tour event
and life in general seem slightly less significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather win two majors and no other tournaments,'' said
Fred Couples, who won the 1992 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The victory at Augusta earned Couples superstar status, but then
there are those whom Couples says ``fell off the turnip truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Corey Pavin, who won the 1995 U.S. Open but has
only one other tournament victory since. Last year, his best finish
on the Tour was a tie for eighth at the Mercedes Championships, his
only top 10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing can take away the importance of winning a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a major championship is a very big deal,'' Pavin said.
``I knew I was capable of doing it and it would have been a missed
opportunity if I didn't get one. I wouldn't mind getting a few
more. I feel there is more out there for me to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But winning a major creates undue expectations from fans and the
media that the feat can be accomplished more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't go into them expecting that you are going to
win them,'' Pavin said. ``There is a lot of luck involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the first major is the key, even if it is the only one.
It gives players a sense that they have etched their name in the
history books.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Mark O'Meara is the latest to make history, winning
the Masters and the British Open after playing on the tour for 18
years _ 56 majors _ before breaking through. Up until this year, he
always had been known as one of the top performers on the PGA Tour
to have never won a major event.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a major championship was a dream come true for me,''
O'Meara said upon winning the Masters. ``Hopefully (the win), put a
lot of that stuff to rest. When I come in the press room, people
won't say how you haven't won a major championship. I've got that
under my belt.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of top golfers to have never won a major title includes
David Duval, who is the winningest player on the PGA Tour over the
past year, with victories in five regular tour events. He finished
second at the Masters, seventh at the U.S. Open and 11th at the
British Open. He feels that he's close to a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be extremely special,'' Duval said of the possibility
that he could win his first major at the PGA Championship this week
at Sahalee Country Club in Redmond. ``It would certainly put a nice
asterisk next to what has been a good year for me and build on last
year, which was a very good year as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the same category are Phil Mickelson (28 years old, 12
tour wins but no majors) and Jim Furyk (28 years old, two Tour
wins, no majors). Then there are those who feel that time is
catching up with them, such as Scotland's Colin Montgomerie (35
years old, 17 tournament wins and no majors).
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, Duval believes that time is on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly feel any additional pressure right now,''
he said. ``If I have a couple more close calls where it doesn't
quite work out my way, then I might start to feel a little more
pressure. This is certainly one of the four events that you aim for
through the course of the year ... so it certainly would be a great
crowning moment of the year and probably for my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, a native of South Africa, has worn that crown three
times in the past seven years, winning the 1992 and 1994 PGA
Championships, along with the 1994 British Open. It took him nearly
a decade of toiling on the PGA and European tours before he broke
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me at the age of 35, it did take a little bit of a monkey
off of my back,'' he said of his first PGA win. ``But let's look at
it in another light; it enhanced my career. The second one did a
little more and the third one even made it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Price believes the PGA Championships are as important as any of
the other three major tournaments because the PGA draws the best
and toughest field of golfers from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the fact that the PGA moves its tournament to
different courses across the country, and feels proud to have won
the event at two vastly different courses: Bellerive Country Club
in St. Louis and Southern Hills Country Club in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to the PGA for being adventurous and trying new
golf courses,'' he said. ``If we didn't, we'd just be playing the
same courses year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   When he won last year's PGA Championship at Winged Foot in New
York, his first major after 11 years on the Tour, Davis Love III
called it the most important moment of his life. Even though he's
struggled this year because of back spasms, he'll never have to
answer questions about why he can't win a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every time I play, I have a little more confidence
because of my win at Winged Foot,'' Love said. ``. . . I'll always
enjoy being called the PGA champion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
