<HEADLINE>
GOLFER JOHN DALY IS A MAN FOR THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It was Davis Love's turn, but John Daly wanted
to hit one more ball. After walloping drives in conventional
fashion with his unorthodox swing, Daly decided to tee up another,
this time on top of an Aquafina water bottle.
</P>
<P>
   There he stood, John Daly in front of the world again at
Tuesday's PGA champions clinic, showing his playful side. With a
loud thwack, Daly's steel-headed Callaway driver simultaneously
smacked the plastic bottle and balata ball, the impact sending
every dimple over the driving-range fence.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be when Daly wanted to take another shot, he would
ask the bartender to pour him one.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a year and a half, in his second courtship with
sobriety, Daly has been dry. His life, as errant as some of his
drives, now revolves around the ordinary. Daly has found that the
purest pleasures come from his two daughters and a reunion with his
third ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   With Daly you rarely get the mundane snippets of his everyday
existence because he continues to pack more shrill than monotone.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets an 18 on a hole at Bay Hill, you can't figure it
out. When he rolls a 10 on the final hole at the British Open to
miss the cut, you wonder. When he busts his 5-iron and doesn't sign
his scorecard in Memphis, you hear the whispers like the ones from
a Sahalee volunteer: ``Is he back on the sauce?''
</P>
<P>
   No he's not. But Daly admitted Tuesday he still has the urge,
fighting the obsessive tendencies, realizing the glitches will be
perceived as setbacks, hoping everyone understands.
</P>
<P>
   The incident in Memphis disturbs him. It was typical John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a lot of things with John, it was one step back, two
steps forward,'' said Donnie Crabtree, one of his longtime friends.
``He doesn't want to get back into the thing of: `It's the same old
John again.'''
</P>
<P>
   The temporary lapse could lead to long-term implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good example of what he shouldn't do,'' said Ely
Callaway.
</P>
<P>
   Daly used to walk out of Las Vegas casinos $250,000 up or
$250,000 down before Callaway gambled on him. During Daly's days of
liquor-fueled mishaps, Wilson dropped its $10 million contract with
him. Ely Callaway, who heads the Big Bertha club-making giant,
decided to take a flyer on a volatile investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided he wanted to live and capitalize on his talent in
golf,'' Callaway said. ``We knew if he could do that and stop
drinking, he would be a tremendous attraction because of his
appeal. Fans have a basic empathy for him, a connection even though
they don't know him. He's a very lovable character because of his
problems. We weren't gambling. He was the one gambling _ with his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Daly is the straight and Sahalee is the narrow. There
is evidence he has changed. He grinded it out at the Bob Hope
Classic, firing a 67 on Friday even when he had no hope of making
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour is not the cocktail circuit anymore. His saying
used to be: ``One's too many and 100 ain't enough.'' He will attend
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings while he is here.
</P>
<P>
   His difficulties with alcohol, his publicized nut-outs, his
numerous divorces have somehow endeared him to galleries who first
embraced Daly when he was the nobody who won the PGA Championship
in 1991 at Crooked Stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of who he is, the average person can relate to him,''
said Crabtree. ``He's not as far removed from some of the fans as
other professional golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of them,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   In every way but one. Daly routinely launches 300-yard drives
and on one occasion reached the 630-yard uphill 17th hole at
Baltusrol in two with a driver and 1-iron.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's clinic, he wound up and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit it hard,'' said Lanny Wadkins, the clinic's emcee. ``They
want to see the big boy one time. These people are not concerned
with accuracy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly obliged with shots that skied as high as a 9-iron but went
so far they disappeared in the distance, right where he hopes his
past will go.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently _ because you never know with him _ a new Daly has
emerged, one who is rekindling his relationship with Paulette, his
former wife, and enjoying fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Shynah, his 6-year-old daughter from a previous marriage, lives
in Orlando, but Daly spent Monday with her in New York at a
tournament raising money for breast cancer. Daly made some
left-handed clubs for her, and she tagged along, hitting shots and
hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wonderful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then when he is home with Paulette, he likes to take their
3-year-old daughter Sierra to Chuck E. Cheese. ``She just loves
that place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, a family man who seems to be ordering off the menu
instead of sampling the whole buffet. Even his appetite is
suppressed, Daly having lost 20 pounds, substituting Diet Coke for
Coke and evidently reducing those cravings for chocolate frozen
yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in my life is perfect now,'' Daly said. ``But life
is a struggle. Every day is not always a great day. I'm learning
you can turn a bad day into a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he has no hope at Sahalee, given the confined surroundings
and his occasionally wayward game. It bothers the competitor in him
that he has not won since 1995 at the British Open. The frustration
shows despite encouragement from his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he forgets that drive he took one night in Colorado
when Crabtree had to talk him out of careening off a cliff,
speeding along at 140 mph, contemplating suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Daly has finally slowed down and is trying to catch up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm so used to adversity that my game has gone to
crap,'' Daly said. ``I don't know, maybe my life's too good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
