<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN: NO. 11 HOLE AT SAHALEE IS `BRUTAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ If Sahalee Country Club was an otherwise
spotless windshield, the 11th hole would be its small crack. Or
bug.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred and forty-six yards of real estate. Turns to the
left. Finishes in a forest. Looks like a slalom course.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours from teeing it up for real, Sahalee largely
has passed inspection as host of the PGA Championship. The weather
and setting have drawn raves. The greens and enthusiasm have rated
a thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   Compliments stop once players journey down No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 17 great holes and one brutal one,'' Tom Lehman says.
``I wouldn't even call it average _ because that hole is brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   Two maple trees guard the green to the right, two fir trees
shadow it to the left. The par-5 has a goalpost look on final
approach. Making matters worse, there's yet another wide-bodied
tree stuck in the middle of the fairway, 90 yards out. Somewhere in
the middle of all this flora and fauna, a flag sticks out.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite ricocheted a shot off a greenside limb on No. 11
Tuesday and dropped another ball in the fairway. He hit the trees
again. Duffy Waldorf sent two into wooded oblivion. Steve Jones
plunked one off the natural barricade. As did Fred Couples the day
before. As did nearly every other golfer brave enough _ or
foolhardy _ to try and reach the putting surface in the minimum
number of shots.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th is the first thing fans see when they jump off their
shuttle bus and enter the grounds; it's the last thing the golfers
want to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Roll an 11 in craps, and everybody's a winner. Do it at Sahalee,
and everybody ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Sindelar was one of the few players who landed a second
shot on the 11th green Tuesday. You wouldn't know it by talking to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little confused,'' he said. ``I have to have another
look at it.'' Finally, Sindelar concluded, ``It's not what I would
do if it was my hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Haas diplomatically called the 11th unique. Jim Furyk
described it as interesting. Ask any pro about the hole, and a slow
smile creeps across his face. Let us play through unimpeded, these
guys plead.
</P>
<P>
   Trees smack in the middle of fairways are fairly unique at
upscale golf layouts. Stanford Golf Club has one. Los Angeles
Country Club has one. Preston Trails in the Dallas area has one.
Sahalee is the leader in this clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking one, we're talking four,'' Sindelar said.
``You can play around one, strategize around two. But you have a
bunch of them. We'll try to birdie it somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   To obtain the PGA Championship, Sahalee agreed to remove 400
trees from the course, including a couple stuck inside bunkers.
Apparently there was a strong enough argument to save the trees
bordering No. 11, particularly the proud, leafy one blanketing the
right side of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would cry if they cut down that maple tree on that hole,''
said Carl Taylor, Sahalee grounds crew member. ``It's a par-5. They
don't have to get there in two.''
</P>
<P>
   On the tour, there is always the occasional maverick who breaks
from popular opinion. Heading the committee supporting Initiative
11 is Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   He actually likes the testy par-5. He reached it in two shots
the first time he tried it, using a driver and 2-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great hole,'' Els said. ``It's not easy. But
that's just design. We don't play on golf courses with these kind
of trees. I wouldn't want to take any of these trees out. They're
too nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Payne Stewart: ``I don't mind the 11th hole at all. But as
I say that, it might jump up and bite me.''
</P>
<P>
   Do I go for it in two or lay up?
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of obstacle, not conservative play, that has the
tour players grumbling. They're used to avoiding lakes and creeks
with half swings. Backing off from trees is not their nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to me,'' Lehman said, ``I'd take a chain saw to
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
