<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALES-MAKAHS-HISTORY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHALING RIGHT CLAMIED, PROVOKING OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (WITH WHALES-MAKAHS)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash. _ To Wayne Johnson, whaling is not just a legal
right; it is his birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the rifleman who hopes to kill the first whale, says
that what protesters forget is Makah history _ and what his
ancestors fought to save almost 150 years ago in treaty talks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1855, a tribal chief, Tse-Kauwtl, spoke plainly to U.S.
government negotiators who had come to strike a deal with the
tribe: ``I want the sea; that is my country.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting treaty between the two sovereign nations spells
out the Makah's right to whale. Though some Alaska natives have
been allowed to hunt whales, the Makah is the only tribe in the
country with such a treaty right.
</P>
<P>
   Most Makah believe they need not ask anyone's permission to take
to the sea in canoes and return with a whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view the importance our treaty signers placed on whaling as
a last will and testament of a sacred way of life,'' said Micah
McCarty, a Makah who hopes to harpoon a whale this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge confronting the Makah was to get the world to
agree.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the tribe asked the United States to represent it
before the International Whaling Commission in its quest to resume
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move became possible the year before when the gray whale,
which had been pushed to extinction, largely by non-Indian hunters,
was removed from the federal endangered species list. The tribe
wanted a quota of whales that could be taken for subsistence and
ceremonial use.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Whaling Commission meeting in Monaco last
year, the assembled nations approved a deal by which the United
States for the first time received a quota of gray whales taken
from the stock that has been hunted by Siberian natives. And the
Russian government received a quota of bowhead whales taken from
the stock that had been hunted by Alaskan Inuit. The gray whales
were allocated by the U.S. government to the Makah and the bowheads
were allocated by the Russian government to the Siberian natives.
</P>
<P>
   National Marine Fisheries chief counsel Margaret Hayes said the
nations didn't swap whale quotas, but that's what opponents allege,
calling it a backroom deal.
</P>
<P>
   After the Monaco commission meeting, U.S. negotiators publicly
declared that the IWC had approved a Makah whale hunt. But some IWC
member nations said the commission never formally gave its stamp of
approval to the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. IWC Commissioner James Baker said the commission works by
granting quotas for subsistence hunts to member nations and leaves
it up to those nations to chose which native people qualify for
whale hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission grants quotas; it does not identify people,''
said Baker, who is the U.S. Department of Commerce undersecretary
for oceans and atmosphere. After hearing of the Makah's nutritional
and cultural need to hunt, the IWC granted the quota. That, said
Baker ``is sufficient legal support for the Makahs to do their
whaling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Makahs claim a legal right to hunt gray whales,
international opposition continues to build from those who say the
claim is bogus. More than 350 groups from around the world posted
an open letter to the Makah on the Internet asking the tribe to
withdraw its plans for a hunt. The groups that signed include the
Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals from the
United Kingdom, Dutch Society for the Protection of Animals and the
European Federation for Nature and Animals based in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs
said: ``We would argue that the IWC has not recognized a cultural
and subsistence need by the Makah to hunt those whales. A lot of
other delegations expressed similar views.''
</P>
<P>
   An animal rights group called Australians for Animals is helping
to finance a lawsuit by U.S. Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash., that seeks
to halt the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Arnold, the group's founder, said in a telephone interview
from Australia that she decided to become involved when she heard
how some U.S. animal rights groups were reluctant to take on the
issue because of a sensitivity to Indian rights.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, who plans to be here to protest, said the Makah hunt is
raising concern around the world. ``European groups are deeply
concerned. People in Australia and New Zealand are boiling with
rage. I think you can expect there will be a migration from this
country to Neah Bay to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If America goes whaling in her waters, then we've lost the
whale,'' Arnold said. ``There are so many indigenous tribes waiting
for the outcome of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
