<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPERS-ADVERTISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER TRADE GROUP ANNOUNCES NEW ADVERTISING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Va. _ The Newspaper Association of America (NAA)
announced Wednesday that it will start a clearinghouse for
advertisers, ad agencies and newspapers to simplify the planning
and placement of newspaper advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The new organization _ called the Newspaper Industry
Communications Center _ will cost about $5 million and will take at
least a year to develop, according to John F. Sturm, president and
chief executive officer of NAA, the 1,700-member trade association
for the newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make life easier for our customers in the ad
world _ and make newspapers more competitive in the multi-market
arena,'' Sturm told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The new center will collect data on circulation, readership,
demographics and rates and serve ``as a single source for all
information'' about particular advertising campaigns, Sturm said.
The center's fee will amount to 1/2 of 1 percent of any ad buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, that fee would be lowered over time,'' Sturm said.
</P>
<P>
   He said no decision had been made about where the staff of 10 to
12 people will be based.
</P>
<P>
   ``NICC will not replace existing service providers and it will
not negotiate rates,'' Sturm said. ``The NICC will streamline the
existing ad-buying process and tie together a number of
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Another NAA subsidiary, the New York-based Newspaper National
Network, focuses on actually selling newspaper ads. Sturm said the
network is aiming for more than $100 million in sales this year,
with ads in over 600 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the NICC concept was developed by the consulting firm of
Booz-Allen and Hamilton. The firm of KPMG-Peat Marwick will put it
together, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most NAA members are daily newspapers, accounting for 87 percent
of the U.S. daily newspaper circulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
