<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0352 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MAC-WINDOWS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAC-WINDOWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MAC REBOUNDS, PRICKLY FANS MELLOW (A LITTLE) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the Macworld exposition held in New York last month,
thousands of Macintosh devotees milled about, as content as cows in
sweet grass. They were ogling the new G3s and 50 or so
preproduction models of Apple's soon-to-be-shipped iMac, a
translucent gumdrop of a home computer that seems to have lifted
the spirits of Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   And it's about time. With the iMac and a few other recent
developments, life along the fault line that separates millions of
Mac true believers from those who put their trust in Windows
computers has become a whole lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I'm a longtime, avid user of Windows-based personal
computers, a PC guy through and through. But I have plenty of Mac
friends. As difficult as it might be to accept, Mac users _ famous
for their touchiness at perceived slights against their precious
computers _ are mellowing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, last year an issue of Mac Addict, a monthly magazine
dedicated to Mac junkies, published a half-dozen articles that
offered help for coping in an overwhelmingly PC world. The chief
strategies were to relax and tone down the attacks on the dark
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Escalating the warfare only reinforces a new popular notion
that Mac owners are irrational fanatics,'' Kathy Tafel wrote in the
article, titled ``The Gentle Art of Verbal Mac Defense.''
``Fanatics, maybe. Irrational, never.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Apple evangelists still won't punch you
a parallel port in your forehead if you rib them too roughly.
</P>
<P>
   The difference may be that Apple has scored points with its
latest computer offerings _ the iMac and the G3 line _ and is also
getting reacquainted with profit, an old friend that proved elusive
for the company at this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   So Mac users, never more proud of their computers of choice,
seem less defensive and less compelled to prove anything to PC
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the company has helped us out,'' an old friend of
mine who is a Mac man told me recently.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users really get a thrill, he said, ``when they see that
commercial with the steam roller.'' He was referring to an Apple
television commercial that shows a steamroller crushing a
Pentium-class laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of newfound Apple peace of mind is an aggressive
advertising campaign that says simply: ``Think Different.'' That
directive is always tucked into a corner of a photograph of an icon
of originality, like Albert Einstein or Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is, of course, that anyone who would purchase a
Mac is daring to challenge the PC lemmings' dive over the cliff.
Hamilton Cloud, a Hollywood television producer, is a good example
of the recent change.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran Mac user, Cloud said that all the talk about Apple's
troubles in recent years was making him hesitant, ``scared,
really,'' about buying another Mac.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is proud to Think Different, he said. He just bought
a new G3 Power Mac, and he couldn't be happier _ or more mellow
about his decision. ``It's so-o-o fast,'' Cloud said, without once
uttering a disparaging word about PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But some suggest that Mac people's growing sense of serenity is
not solely rooted in Apple's recent improvements in its computers,
management and marketing. Instead, they point to the fact that
Microsoft, which builds the software, and Intel, which builds most
of the computing brains for PCs, have taken some sharp hits lately
from antimonopoly forces in Congress and state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that the invulnerability of the other side
has been wounded,'' my friend said recently. ``Mac people don't
feel so threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, these so-called platform battles between Mac and PC
users have raged, melting down some friendships faster than unpaid
bets.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Thomas Wagner, 16, a 10th grader who lives in Troy,
Pa., found his e-mail overwhelmed with pro-Mac newsletters after he
created a pro-Windows home page on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone signed me up for some mailing list I couldn't get
off,'' recalled Thomas, the exasperated creator of the Proudly Made
With Windows site (www.epix.net/tjwagner/win95.html).
</P>
<P>
   But in this new dawn of Mac-PC detente, such shenanigans might
become as laughable a relic of an emerging computer age as
2400-baud modems.
</P>
<P>
   At least, I hope so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
