<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOATCHEESE1-AZR &LR;      08-12 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOATCHEESE1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWESTERN CUISINE LENDS ITSELF TO CHEVRE  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS ARE BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Most Americans are wimps when it comes to goat cheese,
preferring mild versions akin to softened cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the preference is for more robust varieties. By
varieties, we mean as many as 50 or 60 kinds, any of which might be
served as a savory course between the boeuf bourguignon and the
chocolate mousse.
</P>
<P>
   At his Phoenix restaurant, Vincent's on Camelback, chef Vincent
Guerithault hews to American tastes, serving goat-cheese dishes
that aren't exactly wimpish but aren't the strong, room-clearing
specimens a French customer might demand.
</P>
<P>
   However, he does magic with them. In his self-named cookbook,
Guerithault offers such treats as Goat Cheese Nachos, Black Bean
Soup with Goat Cheese and Grilled Avocado with Goat Cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Eaten for centuries in Europe, goat cheese, or the French term
chevre, has become popular in America. Little blobs of the white,
fluffy cheese are turning up in appetizers, salads, soups and main
dishes where other cheeses traditionally might be used.
</P>
<P>
   Its properties are different from those of cheese made from
cow's milk. It does not melt, but rather softens and ``puffs up.''
</P>
<P>
   When Guerithault uses chevre in some of his famous quesadillas,
he often combines it with mozzarella, which does melt and becomes
deliciously gooey.
</P>
<P>
   It is a versatile product, combining well with herbs and garlic.
It nicely accompanies such meats as salmon and duck _ as in two of
Guerithault's signature quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phoenix area, he says, goat cheese ``has been part of the
Southwestern influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other cheeses, it is pliable, allowing it to be molded
and shaped.
</P>
<P>
   Chevre varies widely in taste and aroma. In America as well as
in Europe, true cheese connoisseurs prefer strong, dry varieties,
Guerithault says. He puts himself in that category.
</P>
<P>
   What wine to serve with goat cheese?
</P>
<P>
   Because the cheese is so versatile, appropriate wines also favor
a wide range of tastes, says Christie Dufault, sommelier at
Vincent's.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends primarily reds _ a French burgundy or Bordeaux,
or something from Provence or the Rhone Valley. A California wine
such as a Pinot Noir would be a nice pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Dufault warns against serving the milder goat cheeses with too
hearty a wine, as the cheese could be overpowered. A rose could be
a fine accompaniment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Goat Cheese Nachos &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Vincent's Cookbook'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Fried corn tortilla chips (you can make fresh ones from two
whole corn tortillas, cut into wedges and deep-fried)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 275 degrees. Mix together cheeses, sour cream,
parsley and jalapeno. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Put a
small spoonful of the mixture on each chip and bake them in the
oven for 5 minutes or until the cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 236 calories, 16 g fat, 32 mg
cholesterol, 14 g carbohydrates, 209 mg sodium, 62 percent calories
from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Black Bean Soup with Goat Cheese
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Vincent's Cookbook``)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound black beans (dry)
</P>
<P>
   1 quart (4 cups) chicken stock or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 medium yellow onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 whole bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 serrano chile (peeled and seeded if less spiciness is desired)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces mild California goat cheese, cut into 6 slices, for
garnish
</P>
<P>
   Wash and pick over the beans and soak them overnight in water.
The following day, put the soaked beans into a large stockpot with
1 quart water, the chicken stock or broth, onion, carrot, bay leaf
and serrano chile. Bring the mixture to a boil, then simmer it for
approximately 45 minutes. Remove the carrot and bay leaf.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, puree the soup mixture on low until the
consistency is smooth. (Work in batches if necessary.) Pour back
into stockpot and add the cream. Bring the mixture to a boil. Add
salt and pepper to taste. Serve hot with a slice of goat cheese on
top.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 567 calories, 27 g fat, 84 mg
cholesterol, 54 g carbohydrates, 731 mg sodium, 42 percent calories
from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Avocado with Goat Cheese
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Vincent's Cookbook'')
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 avocados, halved, pitted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Bell Pepper Salsa (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces soft goat cheese, cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro sprigs, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees and prepare a hot grill.
Julienne the bell peppers and saute them in 1/4 cup olive oil over
medium heat for about 10 minutes. Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the avocados with the remaining olive oil and season them
with salt and pepper. Grill the avocados about 4 minutes, 2 minutes
each side.
</P>
<P>
   Remove avocados carefully from the grill and place them on a
baking sheet. Fill the center of each avocado with Bell Pepper
Salsa and place a slice of goat cheese on top of the salsa. Place
the avocados in the oven for approximately 5 minutes, or until the
cheese is softened. Divide the julienned bell peppers among 8
serving plates, place the avocados on top, and garnish with
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Pepper Salsa
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow hot chile
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon walnut oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Core the bell peppers and dice them and the tomato, chile, green
onions and garlic very fine and combine all the vegetables. Add the
cilantro. Stir in the vinegar and oil and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 to 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving of a half avocado: 420 calories,
34 g fat, 35 mg cholesterol, 21 g carbohydrates, 286 mg sodium, 69
percent calories from fat. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
