<SLUG> BC-GOATCHEESE2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL KIDDING ASIDE, DOES DELIVER THE DAIRY GOODS  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS ARE BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEEN CREEK, Ariz. - If you are friends with Rosanna Lippe and
her daughter, Joy, you know what you're getting for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Goat products.
</P>
<P>
   Goat cheese. Goat yogurt. Goat ice cream. And a nice, cold jug
of goat's milk.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in some goat chops and shredded meat for burros and you've
gone whole hog into goat cuisine. It's a healthful diet. The
``other'' other white meat is low in fat and cholesterol. The milk
is digested more easily than cow's milk.
</P>
<P>
   But these women aren't in the business for the products. They're
in love with goats.
</P>
<P>
   As they enter the pen behind their Queen Creek home, Lippe and
Joy are swarmed instantly by a curious herd that bleats
plaintively, nuzzles and nibbles. Spry young goats deftly leap onto
wooden cable spools, mimicking the climbing prowess of their alpine
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they playfully gnaw through the shirts of visitors,
which makes them only more endearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're loving, they're kind,`` Lippe says. ``They're the
sweetest animals I've ever known, and I've been around a lot of
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing midherd with little goat feet eagerly pawing and soft
black noses twitching like bunnies, it's easy to lose your heart to
these gentle animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the personalities,'' Joy, 13, says. ``They're
forgiving. You've never really lived till you've been kissed by a
goat.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a kiss on the lips, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   Guarding the herd from predators are two titans of the dog
world: Toledo, a Great Pyrenees; and Pippi, an Anatolian shepherd.
The Lippes' rural neighborhood sometimes is plagued by roving bands
of coyotes and feral dogs. Toledo and Pippi, mild-mannered when
their masters are about, are ferociously protective when left to
perform their sentry duties.
</P>
<P>
   They bond with the kids from birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dogs know they're going to protect the goats,'' Lippe
says.
</P>
<P>
   Lippe, a first-grade teacher at Sousa Elementary School in
Apache Junction, began raising goats as a hobby about nine years
ago, after the parents of one of her students gave her a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``No family is complete without a goat,'' the parent said.
</P>
<P>
   Joy was just 4.
</P>
<P>
   Lippe, widowed soon after, now tends a small herd ranging in age
from 4 months to 8 years. Most are Oberhaslis, an attractive
reddish goat with black markings. She began raising the breed seven
or eight years ago in an effort to improve the line as a dairy
animal.
</P>
<P>
   She also raises LaManchas and Alpines.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is illegal in Arizona to sell goat products from a
hobby farm, Lippe and Joy enjoy the foods themselves and bestow
them on friends. They manufacture such items as hard and soft
cheeses (Cajun, dill, garlic-herb, onion, caraway, jalapeno, green
chiles and plain); ricotta, cottage and cream cheese; yogurt; fresh
milk, milkshakes and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   They eat goat cheese on sandwiches. They put it on pizza. They
fold it into omelets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every goat product I've ever tasted is delicious,'' Joy says.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lippe is a vegetarian, Joy eats some meat, including
the goats she has raised. But because several goats are sent to the
butcher, she doesn't know who comes back in her burros.
</P>
<P>
   December to June is kidding season. For the first week after
birth, newborns live in the family house with Lippe, Joy, Lippe's
parents and her grandfather. Lippe bottle-feeds them, helping them
to bond with her and making weaning easier.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's off to the kid pen for three months until they're
ready for the adult pen.
</P>
<P>
   Does can kid at a year, but the Lippes wait until they are 2
years old, then breed them every other year. They are milked for 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   Lippe also has three bucks that perform stud duties. Most males
are wethered, or neutered, and used for meat.
</P>
<P>
   Every goat has a name: Honey, Patchouli, Gayla Dawn, Eagle,
Rainbow, Herb. Herb's the one who favors the flavor of shirts.
</P>
<P>
   They all come when called.
</P>
<P>
   Joy plans to become a conservation biologist. But like Heidi,
the goat-herding heroine of one of her first books, she always will
keep goats.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, who was raised with horses and cherishes the cats
and dogs she now keeps as pets, says she never will live a
goat-free life.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles. ``Once you've had goats, I don't think you can live
without them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
