<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTFARE-SUMMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT FARE SUITS BLAZING SUMMER DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Little Something'' by Susan Epstein (Morrow, $15) is just
the ticket for folks who nosh their way through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good course to take, particularly when the weather is as
torturous as it has been this summer. Several small somethings are
easier to stomach in this heat than a full, hungry-man-style meal.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein offers up snacks, hors d'oeuvres and appetizers ranging
from the savory (turkey cranberry rollwich) to the sweet (white
chocolate-covered dried fruit). And because the servings are small,
you'll have room to try more than one.
</P>
<P>
   MARINATED GOAT CHEESE WITH CRUMB CRUST
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh oregano, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound goat cheese, sliced into 1-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Combine olive oil and oregano in small bowl. Season generously
with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil mixture onto cheese slices, cover and refrigerate for
at least 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cheese from oil and dredge in bread crumbs. Place on
foil-covered baking sheet and bake about 5 minutes, until cheese
begins to bubble around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 177 calories, 14 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 30 milligrams cholesterol,
228 milligrams sodium, 70 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   HORSERADISH TUNA ON CUCUMBER ROUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 48
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (7 1/2 ounces each) tuna, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons prepared white horseradish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   4 cucumbers, peeled and cut into 3/4-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   Fresh dill for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop tuna in large bowl. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine mayonnaise, horseradish, lemon and dill in small bowl
and then add to tuna. Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using a melon-baller, scoop out center of each cucumber round,
leaving bottom intact and a 1/4-inch border.
</P>
<P>
   Using a spoon or melon baller, fill each cucumber cavity with
the tuna mixture. Garnish with a fresh dill sprig if desired. Serve
chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per round: 17 calories, trace fat, 1 gram
carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 29
milligrams sodium, 23 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ROMAINE BURRITOS WITH BLUE CHEESE, CHICKEN, APPLES AND PECANS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces cooked chicken, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces blue cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 apple, peeled, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared Dijon mustard salad dressing or
vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   8 romaine lettuce leaves, hard stem removed
</P>
<P>
   Combine chicken, blue cheese, apple and pecans in small bowl,
and toss with dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Place romaine on flat work surface. Place tablespoon of filling
about 1/4 inch from wide end of each leaf. Roll up burrito-style,
completely enclosing filling.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 89 calories, 5 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 18 milligrams cholesterol,
163 milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
