<HEADLINE>
THE NITTY-GRITTY OF GOAT OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By EDYTHE JENSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - My milk suppliers look back at me through the kitchen
window.
</P>
<P>
   For 19 years, our family's source of milk, yogurt and cheese has
been a hobby herd of dairy goats.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for a commitment to feed and milk them twice a day,
these creatures provide food, companionship and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Goats are credits to agricultural efficiency. The size of a
large dog, an average doe (female goat) can produce 5 to 10 percent
of her body weight every day in naturally homogenized, easily
digested milk.
</P>
<P>
   The fat globules in goat milk are much smaller than those in cow
milk. That enhances its digestion and allows it to blend easily
with other ingredients _ sauces are smoother, puddings and fillings
creamier.
</P>
<P>
   People sometimes buy their first goat because they're allergic
to cow's milk, their children want a 4-H project, or they
encountered one at a petting zoo and thought it was cute.
</P>
<P>
   Mine was an attempt to be more self-sufficient. Vegetable
gardening and fruit trees were the first step; I was eager to
expand the backyard grocery inventory without investing in a farm
animal that weighed as much as my car.
</P>
<P>
   Goat ownership is not for everyone. Their twice-daily milking
schedule must become their owners' schedule, and kennels don't
accept herds of goats when owners want to go on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who wants goats, here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   - Check local zoning ordinances and deed restrictions to be sure
they're allowed.
</P>
<P>
   - Go to the library and read books about goats, what to feed
them, how to fence them, and proper milk-handling practices.
</P>
<P>
   - If yogurt and cheese are on your personal menu, one of the
most complete mail-order inventory of cultures, cheese molds,
cheese presses and classes for hobbyists is available from the New
England Cheesemaking Supply Co., Box 85, Ashfield, MA 01330-0085 or
at www.cheesemaking.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   - Rural fairs, livestock shows and 4-H clubs for children are
among the social perks of goat ownership.
</P>
<P>
   - Discuss the pros and cons of goat ownership with family
members. If frequent vacations and sleeping in on weekends are
priorities, buy your goat milk and cheese in the store. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
