<HEADLINE>
GOAT CHEESE TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED -
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRE: The French word for goat. Domestically, it is a generic
term that applies to all goat cheeses; specifically, the milk-fresh
cheese. &QL; 
CABECOU: Small medallions of goat cheese aged in olive oil. &QL; 
CHABIS: Mild young cheeses aged 1 to 2 weeks. Semisoft and moist. &QL; 
FROMAGE BLANC: Literally, white cheese. Extremely young and mild.
Goat milk contains no carotene, so pure goat milk products are fine
textured and very white. &QL; 
CENDRE: A vegetable ash used on goat cheese to create a dusty,
gray-black surface. The ash tends to mellow the acidity of the
fresh goat cheese and contributes to a drier, chalkier texture. &QL; 
TOMME: A generic term for ``round,'' this is the word used to
describe hard or semihard goat cheese aged from 6 weeks to 6
months. These cheeses vary in texture and flavor from mild and
nutty to piquant and robust. &QL; 
PASTA FILATA: A category of Mediterranean-style cheeses. The curd
often is immersed in hot whey, pulled into long threads and
reworked into a variety of shapes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
