<HEADLINE>
RECIPE ADDS ALL-AMERICAN INGREDIENT TO ORANGE BLOSSOM MUFFINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our request for the orange muffins served at the Peninsula Hotel
in Hong Kong brought several responses _ most of them with the
orange blossom muffin recipe served at the Jefferson Hotel in
Jefferson, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This is a perfectly nice recipe, but I'm sure the chefs in Hong
Kong don't use Bisquick. So, while I wait for the hotel to e-mail
me their recipe, here's that one to try.
</P>
<P>
   And Donna Arnold of Fort Worth sends a variation on the theme
with the second recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE BLOSSOM MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Combine egg, sugar, orange juice and salad oil. Mix in Bisquick
and beat vigorously for 30 seconds. Stir in marmalade and pecans.
Grease muffin tins and fill two-thirds full with mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients and mix until you have a crumbly mixture.
Sprinkle over batter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in 400-degree oven for 20 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per muffin: 212 calories, 9 grams fat, 32
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 27 milligrams cholesterol,
243 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   MARMALADE MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Combine egg, juice, sugar and oil.
Add Bisquick and beat 30 seconds. Stir in marmalade. Fill greased
muffin tins two-thirds full and bake for 15-20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per muffin: 126 calories, 4 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 27 milligrams cholesterol,
184 milligrams sodium, 31 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Flash from the past: Sharon Norcross of Stephenville, Texas,
found the requested recipe for ginger cookies in an old Imperial
sugar recipe brochure.
</P>
<P>
   GINGER COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 4 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda, dissolved in about 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   Boil together sugar, molasses and butter. Let cool, then add
yolks of eggs, spices and the baking soda dissolved in water. Add
flour. Roll thin on sugar-coated board. Cut and bake on greased
cookie sheet at 400 degrees for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 80 calories, 2 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 13 milligrams cholesterol, 46
milligrams sodium, 26 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
