<HEADER>
A0403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIREVIEWS13-C     08-12 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIREVIEWS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Kathy Janich, Bo Emerson, Nick Tate, and
Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- FOLK
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell Among the Yearlings''
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Welch. Almo Sounds.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Musically, this Nashville singer-songwriter's second effort
strays little from the meticulous country-folk and bluegrass sounds
of her Grammy-nominated 1996 debut, ``Revival.'' Indeed, her
adherence to tradition may be a bit too strict _ some songs have a
hermetically sealed, museum-piece feel. It's in the lyrics that
Welch gets adventurous, delving into the dark side of human nature.
``Caleb Meyer'' deals with the attempted rape of a mountain woman,
while the heartbreaking ``One Morning'' observes a Kentucky mother
as she watches her long-gone son ride up on horseback. As he draws
near, she discovers that he's dead from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Myself''
</P>
<P>
   Lena Horne. Blue Note Records.
</P>
<P>
   10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Lena Horne has lost a few notes through the years, but it
doesn't matter on ``Being Myself,'' a disc on which she's clearly
having fun. And yet emotions run deep in this mixture of pop
standards and blues tunes. Horne is sassy on ``As Long as I Live,''
melancholy on ``Autumn in New York'' and reflective on
``Imagination.'' And don't miss her ``Sleepin' Bee,'' which begins
with a hum and builds to an all-out buzz. Horne, now 81, has
decades of tales to tell from her years as a recording artist and
stage and screen actress. They're all here, a burbling subtext that
gives each phrase, each lyric waves of meaning. Our only regret? We
get just 38 minutes of that old Horne magic.
</P>
<P>
   -- VARIETY
</P>
<P>
   ``Legends of Ukulele''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Rhino. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, looking at this homely little instrument,
but once upon a time the ukulele ruled. Starting with the Hawaiian
music boom of the early 1900s, the instrument crested in the 1940s
with Arthur Godfrey, who eventually sold 9 million of his plastic
ukes. This disc has plenty to argue its case, from virtuoso jazz to
humble folk to aromatic old chestnuts such as ``Do I Love You? Yes
I Do!'' Skip the obligatory Tiny Tim track and go right to the
ineffable Ohta San and ``Little Grass Shack.'' The production and
selection are impeccable, and the way overresearched liner notes
are from Jim Beloff, author of ``The Ukulele: A Visual History''
and contributor of the noirishly cute ``For the Love of Uke.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoom''
</P>
<P>
   The Knack. Rhino. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   They're back. The West Coast crew that gave us ``My Sharona''
returns with a new set of slick, formulaic Cheap Trick imitations.
And somehow they manage the impossible: ``Zoom'' makes ``Sharona''
sound like a rock masterpiece. Just a click short of self-parody,
the Knack's keg-party mix of scattershot-fuzz guitar, sing-song
melodies and brick-handed drumming are as cliche-laden as ever.
Even the lyrics on ``Zoom'' are stone-dumb. Sample: ``Can I borrow
a kiss? I'll pay it back with interest.'' Sheesh. It's almost
enough to make you wonder what Toni ``Mickey (You're So Fine)''
Basil's up to these days. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eve 6''
</P>
<P>
   Eve 6. RCA/BMG. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   This L.A. power rock trio is getting a lot of mileage from its
omnipresent MTV video for ``Inside Out,'' but, unlike a lot of the
bands on the video channel, Eve 6 has legs. The group of
18-year-olds, fronted by vocalist-bassist-lyricist Max Collins,
could be labeled Hanson with distortion guitar pedals. Collins and
crew show amazing musical maturity and tightness that demonstrate
they've been studying. The memorable melodies coupled with witty,
insightful, angst-riddled lyrics prove once again that there's
nothing like the experience of being a high school outcast to
produce great rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
