<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phair stretches beyond scruffy
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, no one's going to accuse her of being Stevie Nicks, even if
she toyed with the pose on the cover of her infamous first album.
But Liz Phair is no longer the ``exile in Guyville'' singing with
the same explicit candor about boy-girl chemistry and tossing off
sexual provocations with lo-fi glee. She got married. Had a kid.
Played Lilith Fair. And now, with her third album, is sounding
awfully slick and professional; mellow, even, compared to the
four-letter-word/scruffy-guitar quotient that previously paced her
songs.
</P>
<P>
   It's Phair's trademark audacity, though, that could have bound
her to dirty-flirty cliches. The rewarding quality of
``whitechocolatespaceegg,'' a title that would look even worse
translated into German, is the way Phair stretches herself as a
songwriter (even if she lets the multitracking get annoyingly out
of hand). Her best stuff has an introspective clarity (``Only
Son,'' ``Go On Ahead'') about life's fundamental relationships or
uses irony and narrative voice (``Big Tall Man,'' ``Johnny
Feelgood'') to break through the confessional ``I'' mode that makes
you assume a piece is autobiographical.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be lying if I said this is remotely as fun as ``Exile in
Guyville,'' though Phair's reliance on nursery rhymes, '60s garage,
bubble gum and girl-group pop, and a few guys from R.E.M. here and
there suggests that she hasn't strayed too far from her musical
roots. This is a smart record, though, almost a dose of reality in
the current climate of triviality. As Phair declares, ``I'm a
complicated communicator,'' which sure beats the daylights out of
carbonated sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``whitechocolatespaceegg''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Phair. Matador/Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Lo-fi queen puts on some lip gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-RAP13-COX     08-12 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogg missing `Doggy' and more
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before this album hit the stores, it was a big record.
Master P's signing of Snoop Doggy Dogg, probably the most popular
artist in gangster rap, elevated P's independent and successful No
Limit Records label to a higher level. And Dogg's departure from
the notorious Death Row Records was the final nail in the coffin of
what was one of the most successful purveyors of violent, graphic
and drug-laced rap.
</P>
<P>
   But a big record isn't always a great record, as evidenced by
``Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told.''
</P>
<P>
   Dogg's teaming with No Limit's in-house production team, Beats
by the Pound, is too often the lulling and unmemorable experience
you'd expect when you match Dogg's languid delivery with equally
lazy rhythms. Not that Dogg rapped any differently on Death Row.
But when Dr. Dre was on the production boards, his keyboard-based
``G-Funk'' always had the kind of power that insisted you listen to
the low-key rapper. And that, coupled with hooks such as those on
``Gin and Juice,'' made even menacing lyrics easy to sing along to.
</P>
<P>
   Here, ``Gin and Juice II'' is an orchestrated yawner complete
with timpani rolls. Dogg's labelmate Mystikal proves more imposing
on ``Tru Tank Dogs,'' and his other new labelmate, Mia X, is as
compelling on the cautionary tale ``Slow Down.'' Dogg finds his
stride only when he's reminiscing, as on the muscular ``Woof!''
That's also true for the well-written reworking of Boogie Down
Productions' ``Love's Gonna Get'cha,'' titled ``Doggz Gonna Get
Ya,'' and on ``DP Gangsta,'' a take on NWA's ``Gangsta, Gangsta.''
</P>
<P>
   NWA, remember, included Dr. Dre. Are you starting to notice the
connection _ or, better yet, what's missing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told''
</P>
<P>
   Snoop Dogg. No Limit Records. 21 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: He may have dropped the Doggy, but on occasion
Snoop Dogg still has bite.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
