<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-LEBOWSKI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A comedy of errors results when one Lebowski is mistaken for
another.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Big Lebowski'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A shaggy ode to beer, bowling and bunging, this Coen brothers
comedy seems almost defiantly inconsequential after their
mesmerizing ``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bridges plays a stoned bit of 1960s flotsam called the
Dude, though his real name is Jeff Lebowski. That's the problem.
There's another Jeff Lebowski, a rich old man whose gambling wife's
creditors crash the Dude's place by mistake ... and pee on his rug.
Demanding restitution from the big Lebowski, the Dude gets mixed up
with the tycoon's performance-artist daughter (Julianne Moore, with
a German accent), a gang of German nihilists with an attack ferret,
and, well, other things.
</P>
<P>
   The Coens seem to improvise the plot scene by scene, but their
hang-loose approach yields hilarious non sequiturs, bits of comic
bewilderment and a Busby Berkeley-style tribute to ninepins.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes John Goodman as a 'Nam-vet pal who nudges the
Dude ever deeper into trouble; Steve Buscemi as a bowling buddy who
never gets to complete a sentence; and John Turturro in one of the
most bizarre cameos of the year. He plays a Latin, hairnetted,
purple-jumpsuit-wearing pedophile named Jesus. The peculiarity of
that one character alone should give you a sense of the movie's
wacky spirit. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
