<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIREVIEWS13-C     08-12 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIREVIEWS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews: The word on the latest video releases
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Man in the Iron Mask''(PG-13) _ Swooning teenagers might
rent it to see a double dose of Leonardo DiCaprio, playing royal
twins and wearing the worst fake whiskers Hollywood has to offer.
But the real, odd treat of this pleasant version of the Dumas tale
is the mix of actors playing the aging Three Musketeers: Jeremy
Irons, John Malkovich and Gerard Depardieu. How a Brit and an
American managed to get jobs working for King Louis is never
answered, but you'll be sufficiently distracted by the retro
swashbuckling. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   ``Niagara Niagara'' (R) _ Blame it on the Oscars. Robin Tunney
won an acting award at the Venice Film Festival for her turn as a
young woman with Tourette's syndrome. It's the latest example of
the confusion between acting and savvy displays of behavioral tics.
Tunney meets shy, awkward Henry Thomas, and they head toward
Toronto on a barely motivated road trip. Tragedy looms. While
Tunney throws herself impressively into the role, the movie falsely
suggests that Tourette's is somehow linked to mental illness.
Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   ``An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn'' (R) _ Eric Idle
plays a director named Alan Smithee, which happens to be the
pseudonym used by filmmakers who disown their own work. That's what
Smithee wants to do with his ``Trio,'' an action film starring
Whoopi Goldberg, Sylvester Stallone and Jackie Chan (who show up as
themselves). That movie is supposed to be so bad that Smithee wants
to burn it, but anything would have to be better than this
gratingly lame satire of Hollywood, written by Joe Eszterhas, who
has given us such fine art films as ``Jade'' and ``Showgirls.'' In
one last jolt of irony, director Arthur Hiller removed his name
from this ``Player'' wannabe, so this really is an Alan Smithee
movie. Grade: F
</P>
<P>
   ``Senseless'' (R) _ Score one for truth in advertising. In this
sloppy, crude and, yes, senseless comedy, Marlon Wayans plays a
struggling college student who enrolls in an experimental drug
program to score some quick cash. The drugs give him supersensory
powers, but an overdose has the opposite result. The movie's
offensiveness _ it frequently stoops to bathroom humor _ would be
tolerable were it made with flair. But director Penelope Spheeris,
who brought a dash of panache to ``Wayne's World,'' is in
hack-for-hire mode here. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
