<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secession: do they mean it?
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The League of the South describes itself as
``paleo-conservative,'' with a states' rights fundamentalism that
makes members almost as contemptuous of Newt Gingrich as Bill
Clinton. If it were up the states of the former Confederacy, says
league president Michael Hill, there would be no abortion, no
income tax, no gun control, no gay rights, no affirmative action
and no restrictions on prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   As controversial as those stands are, the league position that
has attracted the most attention is the call for secession. Are
these people serious?
</P>
<P>
   Yes ... but no one's unstacking arms.
</P>
<P>
   Different members interpret secession differently. Some take it
literally, foreseeing a Southern nation. Others see it as a tool to
pressure Washington into restoring power to the states in keeping
with the original sense of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central authority is devolving around the world,'' says Donald
Livingston, an Emory University(Ga.) philosophy professor who heads
the league's educational committee. ``Why should the United States,
the last 19th-century empire, be an exception?''
</P>
<P>
   The league does not advocate rebellion or civil disobedience,
Hill says. ``We're not so foolish as to believe we can run out on
the street and yell, `Secession!' and have people fall in line.
What we're really about now is to articulate a good defense of
secession. To educate people and recruit candidates to run for
local office. We think the South would be better off as an
independent nation, but we realize it's not likely to happen
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Not judging from the poll numbers, anyway. For the past six
years, the University of North Carolina's Institute for Research in
Social Science has surveyed Southerners on whether they think their
region should be a separate nation. Secessionist sentiment has
ranged from 5 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Shelton Reed, the institute's director, points out that the
league wasn't organized until the rise of attacks on Confederate
heroes and the Confederate battle flag _ symbols that had gone more
or less unchallenged for a century. ``I think this is as much about
defending a version of history,'' he says, ``as about attaining
Southern independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
