<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pearls of wisdom
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're classy little numbers that can come in white, cream,
even black. And while they're not known as a girl's best friend,
the right set of pearls can make all the difference in the world
when paired with a smart black dress, dangled from a Cartier
pendant or pinned on a Bill Blass jacket lapel.
</P>
<P>
   But these lustrous gems are going through rough waters.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, something has been killing up to 70
percent of the pearl oysters in Japan, the world's largest
pearl-producing country. Pearl dealers cite a number of culprits _
climate changes, chemical pollutants, viruses and red tide (a
discoloration of sea waters caused by microscopic organisms). Those
affected are the classic round white pearls between 3 and 9
millimeters.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is so severe that cultivators and importers
recently held a conference in New York to discuss the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortage is in high-quality Akoya pearls,'' says Frank
Mastoloni, a New York pearl wholesaler. ``Just getting enough is a
problem. Smaller, less expensive Akoyas cultured in China are not
affected. Neither are South Sea pearls.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does this mean for prospective pearl buyers?
</P>
<P>
   There's no time like the present to make the mother of all pearl
purchases for a bride, a graduate or, dare we say, for that special
someone for the holidays?
</P>
<P>
   As for prices, Devin Macnow, executive director of the Cultured
Pearl Information Center, says consumers can expect about a $300 to
$800 increase for cultured pearl necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ross of H. Stern Jewelers in New York reports that their
stores are not raising pearl prices at this time. ``We have plenty
of pearl necklaces and bracelets, from $300 to over $1 million,''
he says. ``But if the supply does get worse, this could affect the
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Maier &AMP; Berkele jewelers is also not raising prices of
pearls in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything new that comes in probably will be at a higher
price,'' says Eric Tyree, jewelry manager.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Carroll of Tiffany &AMP; Co. in Atlanta, the
jewelry store raised pearl items earlier in the year less than 10
percent and does not anticipate any more price increases this year.
</P>
<P>
   Says Ross, ``Now might be the time to buy that significant other
that strand of pearls or head to the attic and unearth Granny's
pearls.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
