<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0417 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE16-COX     08-12 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Unflinching Dubus reveals hardship's redemptive power
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name Andre Dubus rings fewer bells than it should. There are
those for whom it elicits reverence, both for his nine works of
short fiction and his passionate, unpitying essays. But he is not a
brand name in the bookstore, as predictable as he is recyclable.
There are writers who are read because they have become
well-marketed commodities, and others because they have something
to say. Dubus is the latter.
</P>
<P>
   His prose is intensely personal but makes no concessions to
fashion. He writes of the physical and spiritual, and how the one
feeds on the other; about the futility, sometimes, of a faith he
has not lost; about drawing bad cards in life.
</P>
<P>
   His own luck changed one night in July of 1986, and his life
changed with it. He was driving home from Boston when he came upon
a car broken down on the road, a young man and a woman with a
bloodied forehead standing beside it. ``He had a habit of stopping
when he saw people in trouble,'' his friend Tobias Wolff wrote in
the introduction to ``Broken Vessels,'' Dubus' collection of
nonfiction that was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping, Dubus got the young man to help him push the car onto
the shoulder of the road. Moments later another car came around a
curve, hitting Dubus and killing the other man. Dubus was struck as
he was shoving the woman out of the way. To save another's life he
lost a leg.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in a wheelchair ever since, an amputee who insists
on calling himself a cripple. For Dubus, there is no honor in
euphemisms or in evasions of hard truth. There is honor, as Wolff
writes, only in ``facing his situation honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   Real people, surmounting obstacles
</P>
<P>
   Dubus' new collection of essays, ``Meditations From a Movable
Chair'' (Knopf, $23), extends many of the themes that gave ``Broken
Vessels'' its emotional power. These are stories of real people,
sometimes of Dubus himself, struggling to live, to surmount one
obstacle after another, to succeed knowing there is every chance of
failure. In most of these pieces, religion _ or rather God _ looms
in the background. Dubus believes in God and he believes in ghosts,
and sees no contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   Life, after all, is contradictory, evil often canceling out good
in spite of priests and prayers. He has no patience with
sentimentality. Neither does he flinch from the horrors we
customarily mask with discretion. In the first of these 25 essays
he tells of his sister being raped. She has called from South
Louisiana, where Dubus grew up:
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, I sit in my wheelchair and listen; I see her
face as though she is in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ```I said ``God bless you'' to him,' she says. `While it was
going on.' I think of Christ nailed to wood, my sister spiked to
the earth on her lawn. `I prayed for him Sunday, at Mass.'''
</P>
<P>
   She prayed for him but would also have castrated him. Would have
killed him. While he was raping her, he asked where her daughter
was, and said he might rape her too:
</P>
<P>
   ``She says if he had raped her daughter, she would have killed
him. I try to imagine her killing a big man. I can. I know a woman
whose small son was sinking in mud at the beach. Wooden pallets
were stacked on the wharf; she laid them in a line to her son,
crawled out on them, and saved him. When she tried to return the
pallets, she could not lift one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning to take nothing for granted
</P>
<P>
   Grace does more than sanctify; it can also transform, making the
weak strong. From his wheelchair, Dubus observes even more acutely
than in his fiction, most of it written when he was swaggeringly
physical. In his late 50s, he no longer takes anything for granted,
least of all life. In even the most casual of these pieces _ on
encountering Kurt Vonnegut, Ralph Ellison and Norman Mailer while
he was still a young writer, or one on writing workshops _ there is
an undertone of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose wells up sometimes into a galvanizing demand that
something tangible come from all those prayers. In ``Broken
Vessels,'' he tells of his daughter crying inconsolably and his
inability to help her. It was shortly after he lost his leg, his
wife is in the hospital with a new baby and he's in his wheelchair.
The daughter, sick with chickenpox, cannot visit the hospital, and
help from above is not forthcoming:
</P>
<P>
   ``I lay helpless on my back, wanting to rise, and hold her in my
arms, and walk with her, and I yelled at the ceiling, the night sky
above it: You come down from that cross and give this child some
peace!''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Meditations From a Movable Chair,'' Dubus has found a
measure of peace himself, but no one would call it tranquillity. In
Dubus' life, every situation _ physical and spiritual _ presents
hardship, not only because he is an amputee but also because it's
his nature to butt his head against hard walls. Facing reality
doesn't mean you accept it meekly. Andre Dubus confronts it
squarely and makes the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
