<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DICKEY-COX     08-12 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In a wrenching memoir, the son of poet James Dickey comes to
terms with his dad's flawed genius
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been easy for Christopher Dickey to write a
mean-spirited ``Daddy Dearest'' memoir of his famous father, the
poet and novelist James Dickey. All the horror stories were there:
the alcoholism, the womanizing, the emotional abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dickey had lived through the glory years of the 1960s,
when his father barnstormed the country as a prize-winning poet.
And he had lived through the depressing years of his father's
destructive second marriage, when every conversation seemed to be
filtered through an alcoholic haze.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a great poet, a famous novelist, a powerful
intellect, and a son of a bitch I hated,'' Dickey says in ``Summer
of Deliverance: A Memoir of Father and Son'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$24). The younger Dickey became a foreign correspondent so he could
get as far away from his father as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 20 years, he filed dispatches for The Washington
Post and Newsweek from Egypt, Iran and El Salvador, wrote three
books, and kept his meetings with his father brief and on neutral
ground.
</P>
<P>
   What disturbed him, more than the anger, was that he still loved
his father at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept finding that everything, no matter what project I
undertook, tended to turn itself toward the question of fathers and
sons,'' says Dickey, who now runs Newsweek's Paris bureau. ``I
figured somebody was trying to tell me something. Then my wife told
me that I had to go back home and quit having those painful little
encounters that lasted only a few minutes sometimes. So we went to
South Carolina in the summer of '94 and spent a few days. It was
painful, but we got the momentum going.''
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the future, especially about how important
James Dickey's daughter Bronwen (Chris' half sister) was to him.
And they talked about the past, including that summer nearly 25
years earlier when ``Deliverance,'' the elder Dickey's best-selling
novel, was made into a movie and all the pent-up forces of
self-destruction within him were unleashed like the waters of the
Chattooga River.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Deliverance,' it was no longer enough for him to write
muscular, virile poetry,'' Dickey says by telephone from Paris.
``There was an expectation that he would live it.''
</P>
<P>
   James Dickey, who died in 1997, became as much a part of legend
as his compelling tale of four suburbanites who plunge into a
nightmare on a North Georgia canoe trip. The Atlanta native
exaggerated his college athletic feats, lied about having been a
pilot (he was a navigator), and created a macho facade to match
Hemingway's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no respect for the journalistic sense of the truth,''
says Dickey, 46. ``If you're telling a story, and you tell someone,
`I was a pilot over the Pacific,' it's easier than saying you were
the second guy in the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   The lying and boasting escalated when director John Boorman
invaded Rabun County with a film crew and actors Burt Reynolds, Jon
Voight, Ned Beatty and Ronny Cox. Invited at first to act as an
adviser, the author was soon banished from the set because he made
Boorman and Reynolds nervous. Eventually, he was given a bit part
as the local sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, when the film was released, Dickey had slipped
into a permanent role as macho outdoorsman. ``He wore his
purple-fringed leather jacket and his big Stetson hat with the
pheasant-feather band,'' the younger Dickey recalls in his book.
``Sometimes long strands of hair that he combed over the top of his
balding head would come loose and drop down over one ear, giving
him the look of a cowboy who had been half scalped.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Braselton, a longtime friend of the poet-novelist's, agrees
that the success of the movie changed James Dickey: ``After
`Deliverance,' he quit listening. Up until then, he took everything
in and used it in his writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Braselton, a Rome writer who was one of the poet's companions on
the canoe trip that was the inspiration for ``Deliverance,'' says
Chris Dickey's portrait of his father is not exaggerated. ``He did
drink a lot, and in his later years his stories got repetitive and
boring, but he was the smartest man I ever met,'' Braselton says.
``There were so many facets of Jim Dickey. He was like Stone
Mountain: Your impression of it depends on which side you approach
it from.''
</P>
<P>
   Braselton says his friend was always worried about not
fulfilling his fate. ``As for his drinking, he told me, `Alcohol
may be an artificial joy, but an artificial joy is better than no
joy at all.'''
</P>
<P>
   The drinking increased when James' wife, Maxine, died and he
married one of his students. Rumors of the new Mrs. Dickey's
cocaine addiction and physical abuse of her husband made their way
across the Atlantic. By the time the son decided to attempt a
reconciliation in 1994, the father was dying of liver disease and
other complications of a hard life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write the book while he was still alive,'' Dickey
says. ``I got into this white heat of writing and we taped hours
and hours and days of interviews, and then he died. Originally, I
wanted to write it because I thought it would bring us together. I
kept on writing it because I wanted to bring him back. It was
frightening because I could feel all those memories of him slipping
away.''
</P>
<P>
   And not all the memories were bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I went to school in Atlanta as a little boy, our
lives weren't exactly like everybody else's. We'd gone to Europe,
and we'd lived on the Riviera. My father took me hunting with a bow
and arrow when I was 8. We met famous people.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chris was 16, the family made a final move to Columbia,
S.C. His father took a writing post at the University of South
Carolina and hit the road doing poetry readings around the country.
``He was loving and being loved by people we did not know,'' Dickey
writes in his memoir.
</P>
<P>
   As his father approached his 40s, Dickey says, fear of middle
age haunted him and the cumulative effects of drinking changed him:
``He feared he would lose his physical powers, his sexual powers,
his creative powers. If you tie everything up in a bundle that's
based on being big and macho and larger than life, you don't leave
yourself much room when you reach middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   Now middle-aged himself with a grown son, Chris Dickey better
understands some of the demons his father faced. He admits that he
was not a good father to his son, James, 28, but they are close now
that he's grown. ``I was too busy trying to save myself,'' Dickey
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bronwen, meanwhile, is attending a private school in
Connecticut; Chris Dickey's younger brother, Kevin, is a
radiologist at Yale Medical School; and his stepmother, Deborah,
reportedly has overcome her drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deborah did not want to read the book,'' Dickey says. ``She
doesn't want to relive those times, but she wanted me to emphasize
the fact that she has straightened out her life completely in the
last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he says, he came to know his father and himself
better than he had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to put the good and bad memories into some kind of
context. When he wasn't drinking, he was so inspiring, so wonderful
to be around. If he were a neutral personality, he wouldn't have
been a poet. And he wouldn't have been a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
