<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-KEBAB-COX     08-12 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-KEBAB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With a universal appeal, kebabs come in countless meaty
combinations_ limited only by taste and imagination
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You started grilling hamburgers before Memorial Day. Father's
Day, it was steaks. On the Fourth, you smoked ribs for hours.
</P>
<P>
   But you ain't grilled nothing yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to take a stab at the most universal of barbecue
dishes _ the kebab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meat on a stick is probably one of the oldest food concepts in
the world,'' says Steven Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue!
Bible'' (Workman Publishing, $18.95). ``And every country has some
version of a kebab, whether it's the sate lalat in Indonesia, with
bits of meat no bigger than a fly, or the giant kebabs of
Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen traveled to 25 countries over three years to research
how different cultures grill and barbecue food. He included more
than 60 recipes for kebabs and sates in his book because he found
``meat on a stick'' everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   They go by names like yakitori (chicken marinated in soy sauce
and sake in Japan), suya (fiery skewered beef in Nigeria) and kofta
(ground meat in North Africa.) They call for skewering everything
from beef heart to quail's eggs, though most involve less
intimidating meats, poultry and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Some skewered meat traditions are spare, such as the Madeira
tradition of cooking chunks of meat on the branches of bay leaf
trees (we've included a modified recipe for this inside.)
</P>
<P>
   Others are complex, such as the sate lilit in Bali, a spicy fish
mousse flavored with kaffir lime leaves and grilled on fresh lemon
grass stalks. And there's as much variety among the skewers as in
what can be skewered, from simple metal batons to sugar cane stalks
to bamboo sticks to upscale skewers with adornments on the handles.
</P>
<P>
   Many kebab recipes are related. Persian-style kebabs, with an
emphasis on yogurt-based marinades and lamb (usually ground) turn
up as far west as the Balkans and as far east as Bangladesh,
Raichlen's research shows. They are thought to have inspired the
Greek souvlaki and the Indian tandoori. ``Ground lamb kebabs are
popular on a huge swath of the world barbecue trail,'' Raichlen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of our family favorites are more likely inspired by global
traditions rather than authentic, which is probably how kebabs have
endured over the centuries. From the essentials _ humans, fire,
meat, sticks _ have come countless combinations limited only by
imagination and taste. So twisting tradition is a tradition when it
comes to kebabs.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we include directions for skewering beef, shrimp, pork,
chicken, vegetables and ground lamb using ideas from Greece,
Turkey, India and Thailand, among other places. We've even included
the directions for the saffron chicken kebabs that are the
favorites at Cornucopia, a restaurant on Roswell Road, where owner
Ben Keshmirian specializes in Mediterranean-inspired kebabs.
</P>
<P>
   So while the grilling season is still in full swing, sharpen up
those skewers and sample the world a few bites at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEBAB-RECIPES-COX     08-12 2891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEBAB-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kebabs: Stick 'em up
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time to take summertime global and experiment with the
grilling traditions of the world. And there's no better way to do
it than with a kebab sampling.
</P>
<P>
   You can make the portions on each kebab as small or as large as
you'd like. And feel free to create your own combinations, pairing
favorite meats with preferred veggies or even fruits, like prunes,
figs, apricots and peaches.
</P>
<P>
   There are really only a few rules to keep in mind. It's good if
you can intersperse lean meat cubes with fatty, and cut pieces
about the same size so they will cook evenly. When using different
vegetables on the same skewer, make sure they have similar cooking
times; longer-cooking vegetables may be blanched first to start the
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Experiment with different skewers, metal or wood. You can
usually find economical versions at grocery and discount stores.
The latest Williams-Sonoma catalog offers stainless steel skewers
adorned with brass handles in the shape of animals. A set of six is
$15.
</P>
<P>
   If you use wood skewers, soak them in water for about an hour
before using to keep them from burning while on the grill. You can
also wrap the ends in foil. It's also a good idea to grease the
grilling grate generously to prevent sticking.
</P>
<P>
   One trick: Use a kebab rack. These stand about 2 inches high,
and you place the skewers on top so they are just above the grate,
but not touching it. We spotted one at Stein Mart for $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the last trick to kebabs is the unskewering. As he
traveled the world sampling kebabs, cookbook author Steven Raichlen
discovered the best way to handle this dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests holding a skewer with one hand, and then, with a
piece of thick bread in the other, pull the meat toward you a bit
to loosen; everything should just slide off.
</P>
<P>
   Below, we give you a few of the international recipes Raichlen
discovered while working on ``The Barbecue! Bible'' (Workman
Publishing, $18.95) plus some others we tried.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Madeira Beef and Bay Leaf Kebabs (Espetada)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Marinating time:
4-6 hours Cooking time: 8-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Grilled beef is popular throughout Portugal, but on the island
of Madeira, this kebab is the favorite. It used to be cooked
directly on branches from bay leaf trees. Here, we stick with the
leaves. Steven Raichlen recommends serving with crusty bread for
soaking up the juices as shown below.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds beef tenderloin or boneless sirloin
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped fresh Italian (flat-leaf) parsley
</P>
<P>
   4cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   12bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Trim any sinews and excess fat off the beef, then cut the meat
into 1 1/2-inch cubes. Combine the olive oil, vinegar, onion,
parsley, garlic, salt and pepper in a large nonreactive baking
dish. Add the beef and toss thoroughly to coat. Cover and let
marinate in the refrigerator for 4 to 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the grill to high. Remove the beef and bay leaves from
the marinade and thread onto the skewers, dividing the bay leaves
among the kebabs. When ready to cook, oil the grill grate. Arrange
the kebabs on the hot grate and grill, turning with tongs, until
the meat is cooked to taste, 2 to 3 minutes per side (8 to 12
minutes in all) for medium-rare. Baste the espetadas with any
excess marinade, but not during the last 3 minutes. Serve the
espetadas on or off the skewers on slices or chunks of Portuguese
bread for soaking up the juices.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 273 calories, 32 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49) , 1 grams carbohydrate, 95
milligrams cholesterol, 371 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Oriental Chicken Kabobs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here is a light, flavorful kebab infused with some of our
favorite Asian tastes _ hoisin and ginger. The whole baby corns are
a nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds skinned and boned chicken breast halves, cut into
1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1medium-size yellow bell pepper, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1medium-size red bell pepper, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1(15-ounce) can whole baby corn, drained and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup hoisin or teriyaki sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1garlic clove, pressed
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle chicken with salt and pepper. Alternate chicken, pepper
pieces and corn on skewers. Combine hoisin or teriyaki sauce and
the honey, garlic and ginger; brush on kabobs. Grill, covered with
grill lid, over medium-high heat (350 to 400 degrees) about 12
minutes, turning and basting with hoisin sauce mixture. _ From:
www.
</P>
<P>
   cookinglight.com.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 348 calories, 39 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 13), 39 grams carbohydrates, 96
milligrams cholesterol, 1,197 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Latin Quarter
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp Kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Steven Raichlen found these kebabs in the Latin Quarter of
Paris, though they are believed to be Greek in origin. Here are his
specific directions for these kebabs, which are as beautiful as
they are delicious.
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon coarse (kosher or sea) salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   12jumbo shrimp or spot prawns
</P>
<P>
   2medium onions, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1large green bell pepper, stemmed, seeded, and quartered
lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   1lemon, cut into 8 wedges
</P>
<P>
   12large cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil, for brushing kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salt, pepper, oregano, rosemary and thyme in a bowl
and set aside. Rinse the shrimp under cold running water, then
drain and blot dry with paper towels. Traditionally, the heads and
shells are left on, but the shrimp are deveined. (To devein shrimp
with shells on, cut with kitchen scissors along back of shell.
Scrape out exposed vein with tip of knife.) You may choose the more
traditional, American approach without shells and heads if you
like. Cut each onion into 4 wedges and cut each wedge crosswise in
half. Cut each pepper quarter crosswise into 4 equal pieces.
Preheat the grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the ingredients for the kebabs on a cutting board.
Here's a sequence I like (but feel free to follow any you desire):
a lemon wedge (cut edge toward you), a piece of bell pepper, a
piece of onion, a shrimp (underside facing you) with a cherry
tomato placed in the hollow space formed by the curve, another
piece of pepper and onion, another shrimp with a tomato, more
pepper and onion and, finally, another lemon wedge (cut edge away
from you). Run a skewer through these ingredients to make an
attractive kebab, then thread the remaining kebabs the same way.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, brush the kebabs on both sides with oil and
sprinkle with the herb mixture. Arrange the kebabs on the hot grate
and grill until the shrimp flesh is firm and pink and the tomatoes
and onions are lightly charred, 3 to 6 minutes per side. Brush the
kebabs once or twice with additional oil and season liberally with
the herb mixture as they cook. Unskewer the kebabs onto serving
plates.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 250 calories, 26 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 18 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 1,368 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cornucopia's Lime-Saffron Chicken Kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 2 hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ben Keshmirian of Cornucopia's Mediterranean Restaurant shares
this chicken kebab, which he says is a best seller. It's no wonder;
the tangy lime juice and aromatic saffron combine to penetrate the
chicken with powerful flavor, especially if you can it marinate
overnight. We used the large holes of a regular food grater for the
onion.
</P>
<P>
   2limes, juiced
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground saffron
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3pounds boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   Combine lime juice, onion, olive oil, saffron, salt and black
pepper in a bowl and set aside. Cut the chicken breasts into large
cubes, place them in a shallow dish and pour marinade over them.
Cover and allow to marinate in refrigerator 2 to 24 hours. Skewer
and cook over medium heat on grill, turning occasionally, until
chicken is done, about 8-10 minutes depending on heat.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 212 calories, 34 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 2 grams carbohydrates, 92
milligrams cholesterol, 318 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Lamb and Eggplant Kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-16 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ground lamb is one of the most popular kebab ingredients in the
world but not that common here. If you can't find some already
packaged at the grocery, ask the butcher. Most likely, he will be
willing to grind up a cut of lamb, such as the shoulder, for you.
Be sure and grease the cooking grate very well or use a rack,
because ground meats stick more than cubed.
</P>
<P>
   1pound ground lamb
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup minced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons finely chopped fresh Italian (flat-leaf) parsley
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   8Asian or other long slender eggplants (each 6 to 7 inches long
and 1 1/2 inches wide)
</P>
<P>
   Lavash or pita bread, for serving
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a generously oiled grill to high. Place the lamb in a
large bowl and mix in the onion, garlic, parsley, 1 teaspoon salt,
cumin and 1/2 teaspoon pepper. Knead and squeeze the mixture with
your hands until thoroughly blended, 3 to 4 minutes. To test the
mixture for seasoning, saute a small amount in a nonstick skillet
until cooked through, then taste, adding salt or pepper to the
remaining mixture as necessary; it should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the ends off the eggplants and discard; cut each eggplant
crosswise into 1 1/2-inch rounds. Thread each round, through the
cut sides, on a skewer, 4 to a skewer, spacing about 1 1/2 inches
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Line a baking sheet with plastic wrap. Divide the meat mixture
into 24 equal portions. Lightly wet your hands with cold water,
then take one of the portions of meat and mold it around a skewer,
between 2 eggplant rounds, making it as much as possible the same
size and shape as the eggplant. Repeat with the remaining portions
of meat so each skewer contains 4 eggplant rounds alternating with
3 portions of meat. Place each kebab as it is made on the prepared
baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, arrange the kebabs on the grate and grill,
turning with tongs, until nicely browned and cooked through, 12 to
16 minutes in all. Use a lavash or pita bread to protect your hand
as you slide the meat and eggplant off their skewers onto serving
plates. If desired, trim away the charred eggplant skin before
eating. Serve accompanied by lavash and pita. _ From ``The
Barbecue! Bible'' by Steven Raichlen (Workman, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 287 calories, 6 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 11 grams carbohydrates, 82 milligrams
cholesterol, 668 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tandoori-Style
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable Kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 16 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When I think grill, I don't think cauliflower. But this recipe
produced the best cauliflower I've ever put in my mouth. The
marinade can be used for almost anything, meat or vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   1pound new potatoes, halved, quartered or cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   1/2head cauliflower, broken into florets
</P>
<P>
   2medium-size carrots, sliced 2 inches thick
</P>
<P>
   1medium-size onion, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1recipe Tandoori Marinade (see below)
</P>
<P>
   Raita sauce (plain yogurt with chopped cucumber, cilantro, mint
and salt and pepper to taste) for dipping, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium-size pot of lightly salted water to a boil. Add
the potatoes and boil for 3 minutes. Add the cauliflower to the
potatoes and boil for 3 minutes. Add the carrots to the potatoes
and cauliflower and boil for 2 minutes more. Drain immediately,
plunge into cold water to stop the cooking, and drain again.
</P>
<P>
   Place the vegetables, including the onion, in a large bowl. Add
the marinade and toss to coat. Let stand at room temperature while
you prepare the fire. (Alternately, the marinating vegetables can
be refrigerated for up to 12 hours.) Prepare a medium-hot fire in
the grill. Thread the vegetables onto skewers. Grill the
vegetables, turning occasionally, until browned and tender, about 8
minutes. Serve hot, with raita on the side if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 198 calories, 6 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 10), 39 grams carbohydrates, 7 milligrams
cholesterol, 657 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Tandoori Marinade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon garam masala (available at Indian groceries and
farmers markets)
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine the yogurt, garlic, ginger, cumin, coriander, salt,
garam masala and red pepper in a small bowl. Use this marinade with
any vegetable or combination of vegetables. _ From ``The Vegetarian
Grill'' by Andrea Chesman (Harvard Common Press, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 9 calories, less than 1 gram protein, less than
1 gram fat (percent calories from fat, 46), 1 gram carbohydrate, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 146 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Moo Satay (Grilled Pork on Skewers With
</P>
<P>
   Cucumber Salad and Spicy Peanut Sauce)
</P>
<P>
   A favorite street food of Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand,
these morsels make delicious finger food and work well as a main
dish accompanied by rice and tangy-sweet marinated cucumbers. If
you prefer, chicken, beef or shrimp can substitute for the pork;
adjust cooking time accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 appetizer or 4 main-course servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 4-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   MEAT:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1pound lean pork, sliced in 3-by-1-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   16to 20 6-inch bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   SPICY PEANUT SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons Thai red curry paste or Vindaloo curry paste (we
used Rajah brand from DeKalb Farmers Market)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chunky-style peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons palm sugar or brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons freshly squeezed lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER PICKLES:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6small (Kirby) cucumbers or 1 large hothouse cucumber or
Japanese cucumber
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons coarsely chopped shallot or purple onion
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon finely chopped fresh hot chiles
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon finely chopped dry-roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   A few fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the meat: Combine coconut milk, fish sauce, sugar,
cumin, coriander and turmeric in a bowl and stir well. Add the pork
slices, mix well, cover and refrigerate for 1-2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the sauce: Warm the coconut milk in a small saucepan
over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until it reaches a gentle
boil, about 5 minutes. Add curry paste and stir occasionally until
it dissolves into the coconut milk, about 3 minutes. Add peanut
butter, stock and sugar and cook gently until the sauce is smooth,
about 5 minutes. Remove from heat and season with lime juice, fish
sauce and salt. Taste and adjust seasonings. Cool to room
temperature. (May be made ahead and refrigerated up to 1 day.)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the cucumbers: Combine the vinegar, water, sugar and
salt in a small saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a gentle boil,
stirring to dissolve sugar and salt. Remove from heat and cool to
room temperature. Just before serving time, peel the cucumbers,
slice them crosswise about 1/4 inch thick and cut the slices in
half. Combine cucumber slices with the vinegar dressing, shallot
and chiles. Divide between two serving bowls. Sprinkle with chopped
peanuts and a few cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the meat: Generously oil the grates of a charcoal or gas
grill. Prepare fire or preheat on high setting. Thread a slice of
the marinated meat onto each soaked bamboo skewer and grill until
cooked, 4-8 minutes total. Arrange on a serving platter. Set on
table along with the peanut sauce and the cucumber pickles. _
Adapted from ``Real Thai'' by Nancie McDermott (Chronicle Books,
$9.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per appetizer serving: (2 skewers), 345 calories, 19 grams
protein, 21 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 21), 25 grams
carbohydrates, 36 milligrams cholesterol, 251 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
