<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-ROAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADSIDE AMERICA WEB SITE ROAD TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sage who came up with ``The journey is the reward,''
obviously never took a long road trip with his family. And he
probably never got to see the World's Largest Replica Cheese,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you remember that post-war American rite of passage: The
whole crew wedged into the family's wood-paneled station wagon on
the way to someplace grand. Mom and Dad are meditatively counting
the mile markers to the next rest stop or tourist trap as the kids
wage territorial wars over the backseat while pelting each other
with Stuckey's pecan logs.
</P>
<P>
   If all this has you pining for the good old days, steer your
browser to the Roadside America Web site (www.roadsideamerica.com)
and enjoy a fun-filled trip that may take you not only down memory
lane, but to more than 6,000 of the most popular highway
attractions from all 50 states. Yes, here you can finally see Rock
City, right on your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   A thoroughly enchanting guided tour of American goofiness, the
site is an interactive multimedia companion piece to the books,
``Roadside America,'' published in 1986, and ``New Roadside
America,'' in 1992 (both Simon &AMP; Shuster).
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Doug Kirby, Ken Smith and Mike Wilkins, continue to
add new attractions to their database, which also includes pages on
tourism news and travel tips. The Electric Map page in the Roadside
Rotunda has links to each state's memorable landmarks, and special
sections devoted to favorite road-themed film clips.
</P>
<P>
   It even has a Pet Cemetery area that counts the ``Noble Dog
Mausoleum'' and ``Elephant Burial Ground'' among its treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Other sights on the site include a page called Big Bovines,
devoted to the American preoccupation with building enormous cow
statues, the largest of which _ the 38-foot-tall Salem Sue _
overlooks Interstate 94 in North Dakota. Sue's not alone: When it
comes to tourist attractions, many celebrate humongous objects:
giant chairs, balls of twine and chicken sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   For those overwhelmed by the vast wealth and quality of the
kitsch here, and unsure where to begin, Roadside America offers a
guided tour. Users with at least a 28.8 modem connection can opt
for a Trans Orbital Tour on a specific theme (the ``Wiener Fever
Dream'' was recently offered).
</P>
<P>
   The host, the Travel Brain also offers a tour called ``Probe My
Lobes'' that opens a new browser window and rotates through some
possible destinations, allowing the user to click on whatever looks
good.
</P>
<P>
   If the virtual visit through Roadside America inspires you to do
some more sightseeing on the Web, you can get your clicks on Route
66 (route66.netvision.be). That site is devoted to the legendary
stretch of well-traveled asphalt that once spanned Illinois to
California. Billed as ``Where the Mother Road Meets the Information
Superhighway,'' the Route 66 site offers a trunk load of nostalgia,
links and lore.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as evidence of the international appeal of the American
road, the site comes to you from Belgium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1624EDT &QL; 
