<HEADER>
A0427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE13-COX     08-12 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Sierra Nevada, Red Brick are summer standouts
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people I know are ready to kiss summer goodbye if not, in
fact, kick it out the door. Who says the livin' is easy? Not when
it's this hot, not when it's this muggy and buggy. Alas, there's
another month or more left, and there are also all those summer
beers competing for attention.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is a summer beer anyway?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough to see why a crackling fire and the cold of
winter turn the mind toward thoughts of hearty stouts and porters.
Even a Scottish ale, more malty than hoppy, is suited to the snow
season.
</P>
<P>
   But many people _ myself included _ drink the same beers in
summer that they drink in winter. With a certain kind of meal, I
want a certain kind of beer. One evening calls for an India Pale
Ale (quite a few evenings call for IPAs, frankly), another for a
Vienna lager. None of them will say ``Summer Brew'' on the label.
</P>
<P>
   But seasonal beers are in, and are likely to stay in. They add
variety and interest. With summer beers, you have to imagine
yourself on the deck. Or at Turner Field. Think ballgames and
barbecues. That's what these beers are made for, and it's to be
expected that some would do it better than others.
</P>
<P>
   A late-summer sample of eight such beers illustrated how varied
they can be. The eight, in no particular order, were Dogwood Summer
Brew, Samuel Adams Summer Ale, Sierra Nevada Summerfest, Sierra
Nevada Wheat beer, Pete's Summer Brew, Red Brick Summer Brew, Bert
Grant's Summer Ale and Redhook Blonde Ale.
</P>
<P>
   A minor masterpiece
</P>
<P>
   Seven of those are ales _ ironic when you consider that if
``summer beer'' suggests anything, it's crispness.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not surprising, then, that the one lager in the
group, Sierra Nevada Summerfest, stood out. This is a minor
masterpiece of brewing, a light (but not Lite) lager, soft on the
palate and yet firm enough to stand up to spicier summer foods. The
Saaz hops give it a faintly floral aroma, entirely different from
the citrusy, Cascades character that most people associate with
Sierra Nevada Pale Ale.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a beer that would make me forget Sierra Nevada Pale
Ale. But the person who's not ventured much beyond mass-market
lagers can see just how well that style can be made. It's beer, not
barley pop. And it's an example of a pioneering craft brewery in
Chico, Calif., one whose reputation was built on pale ales, showing
Bud-Miller-Coors how to do it right.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to think everything Sierra Nevada attempts comes off
as a masterpiece. But the Sierra Nevada Wheat, for the aficionado,
falls a tad short of expectations _ which is to say it's likely to
suit most people just fine. It's a clean-tasting, unfiltered beer,
made from 50 percent wheat malt and 50 percent malted barley, and
its slightly tangy taste comes partly from the Strissel Spaltz
hops. ``I came across them a few years ago in the Alsace _ in
France _ when I was looking for a replacement for Saaz,'' says
Steve Dresler, head brewer at Sierra Nevada. ``I don't think
they're that, though. They have a character all their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing how well Sierra Nevada can turn out a lager or a
lighter-bodied wheat beer only confirms its stature as a
world-class brewery. But the real surprise was seeing how well Red
Brick Summer Brew stood up to the competition. Along with last
year's Christmas ale, this is the best beer the Atlanta brewery has
produced. One of the reasons is the Ahtanum hop that Brian
Buckowski, head brewer at Red Brick, found last year in Washington
state. The Ahtanum gives this light-to-medium-bodied beer a
subtlety found in few other beers.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Redhook Blonde Ale brings more to the palate, but
there's nothing obviously seasonal about it. A person not into
hoppy ales can enjoy this well-made beer anytime. And if you're
going to buy the Blonde, why not buy the far more interesting
Redhook Rye, a year-round beer I call The Perfect Deck Beer?
</P>
<P>
   More than lemonade
</P>
<P>
   The same problem arises with Samuel Adams Summer Ale. It's
spiced with lemon and Grains of Paradise, leading some to think
it's a Belgian White Ale. It's not, and it's not as complex or
spicy as Samuel Adams White Ale, introduced as a seasonal last
winter and now offered year-round.
</P>
<P>
   A Belgian White can accompany light lunches on a patio perfectly
(fruit and shrimp salads especially), and Samuel Adams' White Ale
is a good one. But so, too, is the locally made Dogwood Summer
Brew. The Samuel Adams has more bite; the Dogwood is a touch
sweeter and maybe more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to a couple of beers that are neither
interesting nor summery. Pete's Summer Ale has a hint of lemon, but
so what? Like most of the beers under the Pete's label, it's
ordinary _ neither bad nor good.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Grant's Summer Ale, the fourth in this Yakima, Wash.,
brewer's seasonal offerings, is made with Chinook hops, which are
meant to impart a certain zestiness. What's most noticeable,
unfortunately, is the well-known flavor of Bert Grant's house
yeast. Grant is a deservedly laureled pioneer in hop development,
and his best beers _ the Imperial Stout and the excellent Scottish
Ale _ are the ones with enough hops to override that flavor. Call
it ``house character,'' if you want, but it's not for me.
</P>
<P>
   And that's as it should be. Not every kind of cheese satisfies
everyone equally, and neither should every kind of beer. For every
Sierra Nevada, there are three others that are just something to
drink on a hot afternoon. When that's the case, lemonade does it
just as well. A beer has to do something more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
