u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LIBRARY-ART-N     08-12 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LIBRARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH ARCHITECT WILL CLINTON HUG? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clinton mystery that consumes an elite slice
of America's architectural and entertainment establishment these
days has nothing to do with DNA and everything to do with bricks
and mortar. Or glass and steel. Or granite and marble.
</P>
<P>
   The list of suspects is impressive. Will it be Charles Gwathmey
with the girder? Or Frank Gehry with the facade? Or I.M. Pei with
the pyramid?
</P>
<P>
   So far, only the scene is known: 26 acres of warehouses and
vacant lots on the banks of the Arkansas River in Little Rock have
now been set aside for the home of the William J. Clinton
Presidential Library.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not stopped the buzz about who will win Clinton's
commission to design the complex, which will one day hold his
presidential papers, a museum, offices and an ``educational and
outreach'' program to preserve the legacy of the 42nd president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal of interest, a great deal of
excitement,'' said Skip Rutherford, an old Friend of Bill, who is
the local coordinator for the library project in Little Rock. He
has been besieged with proposals from architects famous and
anonymous. ``Because, you know, these are signature pieces, and
they come along rarely.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trail of clues in this who'll-do-it starts just
north of here, at the Malibu beachfront home of Jeffrey Katzenberg,
the Dreamworks movie mogul. It was designed by Gwathmey, and White
House aides say the president was captivated by it when he stayed
there last fall, especially by the way it embraces the waterfront,
since the library is to be built along a river.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in February, the president, his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, and their daughter Chelsea, spent a weekend in another
Katzenberg house designed by Gwathmey in Park City, Utah, and 10
days ago, the Clintons put up in a third Gwathmey house, Steven
Spielberg's on Georgica Pond in East Hampton, N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   But the architectural world really went atwitter when Gwathmey
was seated at the president's table at a White House dinner June 17
for the presentation of the Pritzker Architecture Prize to Renzo
Piano, the Italian architect, whose best-known works include the
Pompidou Center in Paris. Gwathmey has never won the prize, widely
considered the profession's most prestigious, but was seated with
the president and Piano all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of obvious,'' said Gehry, the Los Angeles-based
creator of the wavy titanium steel facade of the new Guggenheim
Museum in Bilbao, Spain, a Pritzker winner who was also at the
dinner, along with Pei, who designed the John F. Kennedy Library in
Boston. ``Everybody said, `Oh, he's doing the library!'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with his trademark easy empathy, the president gave Gehry
some reason for hope, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me and waved his arms like he was describing
Bilbao and said, `I can see it all now in Arkansas,''' Gehry
recalled with a chuckle. ``I think he's probably gone from
architect to architect.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gwathmey, 60, a principal in the New York firm of
Gwathmey, Siegel &AMP; Associates, which learned last week that it had
won the commission to build the U.S. mission to the United Nations,
professes puzzlement at the origins of the buzz. He has not even
seen the proposed site, though he readily acknowledges that it
would be ``a fantastic commission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea where it came from,'' he said by telephone from
New York. ``I know that the president stayed in three of our
houses. I know for a fact that he loved the Katzenberg house in
Malibu. I've met him once, at the Pritzker Prize dinner. And that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not quite all. Since Katzenberg, Spielberg and the third
Dreamworks partner, David Geffen, are all expected to play a role
in giving and raising money to build and endow the $100 million
privately financed library, their architectural patronage is seen
as carrying special weight, and they arranged for Gwathmey to meet
the president. Geffen has offered to give a party to help start the
campaign for the library next winter at his newly renovated house
in Beverly Hills, the old Jack Warner estate, which he bought for
$47 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these guys are going to be paying a lot of the cost, they
sure ought to have a say,'' said one White House aide, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Katzenberg beach house that Clinton liked is a collection of
pavilions, with a cylindrical, glassed two-and-a-half-story living
room, which opens onto the Pacific. A Gwathmey, Siegel monograph
describes it as ``eroding a traditional courtyard house and
exposing its cut edge to the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said that the final decision rests with and Mrs.
Clinton, and that they have been poring over books and portfolios,
and talking architecture with almost anyone they meet. Rutherford
declined to discuss the names of architects who have sent
proposals, but Gwathmey confirmed that he had sent a portfolio to
Rutherford, and so did Gehry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is, subject to change, that ultimately a small number
will be invited to come to Little Rock and tour the site, to meet
with local officials and look at surrounding areas, then have an
opportunity to present their thoughts and ideas to the president
and the first lady,'' Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford, who happily confessed that ``I know absolutely
nothing about architects,'' is getting lots of calls from them
these days. In fact, moments after the writer telephoned Gwathmey
to ask about the library, Rutherford called to ask, ``What was the
name of that architect you said you were writing about?'' When told
it was Gwathmey, Rutherford just laughed and said, ``You've started
quite a buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People call me and say, `Am I on the list?''' Rutherford said.
``I say, `What list?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gwathmey and Gehry both said they were impressed by Clinton's
remarks at the Pritzker dinner, in which the president recalled
that it was Thomas Jefferson, the designer of Monticello, who also
designed the American creed that ``we are all created equal,
endowed by God with the right to life, liberty and the pursuit of
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, we dedicate ourselves to an act of creating
and building that will never be finished,'' Clinton added. ``An
architect conceived of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To have somebody as brilliant as Clinton to play with, and
somebody who'd devour information as he apparently does, would be
an amazing experience,'' Gehry said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Gwathmey said, ``I just hope he picks a modern
architect and not a traditional architect, to be a patron of modern
architecture and not to go backward and do a replicative
building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
