<HEADLINE>
AN AUDIO EXTRA FOR SPORTS CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sports trading card collector who examines a trading card
series featuring a star athlete like Michael Jordan may be startled
to find a metallic surface where printed scoring statistics are
expected. And the collector would probably be even more surprised
to hear the voice of the athlete when the card is placed inside a
compact disk player.
</P>
<P>
   Power Deck sports cards, manufactured by the sports memorabilia
company Upper Deck, are believed to be the only audio trading cards
on the market that approximate the size and look of traditional
sports cards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to images of professional athletes, the cards
include recorded interviews, trivia questions, commentary and
live-action sound from athletic competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to take trading cards into the 21st century,''
said Howard Farfel, senior director of marketing at Upper Deck,
based in Carlsbad, Calif. ``People tend to put regular trading
cards in their closet and leave them alone. The idea here is to
interact with the cards and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverse side of the cards contains digital sound data that
can be scanned by a compact disk player. But because the cards are
rectangular and pliable, they work only when placed on a compact
disk adapter, available free at trading-card shops.
</P>
<P>
   After pushing the play button, card owners can listen to
commentators breathlessly recount the accomplishments of the
athlete featured on the card. They can also hear interviews with
such athletes as Troy Aikman, quarterback for the Dallas Cowboys,
who, on the card featuring his image, said at one point during the
five minutes of audio, ``I think my strengths are probably my
competitiveness and my desire to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck, which is a privately held company, first released
these cards in 1997. The company declined to say how many cards it
has made. The digital cards are not sold separately, but rather are
included randomly _ with no indication on the packaging that one is
inside _ in packs of traditional sports cards produced by Upper
Deck.
</P>
<P>
   The company said a customer's chances of getting a digital card
in a traditional-card pack are about 1 in 22 for the common cards,
and 1 in 120 for rare versions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cards for Jordan and Aikman, there are cards
featuring Ken Griffey Jr., outfielder for the Seattle Mariners, and
Rusty Wallace, a leading Nascar driver.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other companies produce high-technology sports
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Donruss, a sports memorabilia manufacturer in Texas, sells
CD-ROM baseball cards featuring video highlights, player statistics
and personal profiles. Cyberaction, an Internet company, offers
downloadable sports cards with video and sound
(www.cyberaction.com).
</P>
<P>
   But are high-tech sports cards necessary when paper-based
trading cards have been popular for so long? If the market is any
indicator, the answer may be yes and no for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids certainly like them,'' said Fred Engelhaupt, a clerk
at the Beverly Hills Baseball Card Shop in Beverly Hills, Calif.,
who checked a collectibles guide book and found that the most
valuable Power Deck card, Michael Jordan, sells for a minimum of
$12. ``But I haven't had a big adult response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
