<SLUG> BC-GAYS-CLERGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIGIOUS LEADERS DECRY HOMOSEXUALITY
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing the Bible, religious leaders from several
faiths Wednesday said homosexuality is a sin and declared
``homosexuals should become straight and get married.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not homophobic,'' said Bishop Harold Ray of the
non-denominational Redemptive Life Fellowship in West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to promote the biblical alternative, which is
male-female marriage. We are not attempting to condemn people,''
Ray said at a news conference sponsored by the Family Research
Council, headed by conservative activist Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting Ray's view were two panelists _ Yvette Cantu, a
policy analyst for the council, and Anthony Falzarano of the
Transformation Ex-Gay Ministries _ who spoke of their own
conversions.
</P>
<P>
   A former lesbian activist, Cantu said she was ``concerned about
my many gay male friends who were dying of AIDS, yet still
maintaining active sex lives. I was concerned about the fact that
many of my gay and lesbian friends were involved in heavy
recreational drug and alcohol use. It concerned me that many of my
lesbian friends were involved in obsessive-compulsive behavior in
their relationships, that some were violent with each other, and
that some were seducing their friends' girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantu said her ``turning point'' came when she was a nursemaid
to two dying gay friends and took a hard look at her lifestyle.
``Only much later did I come to realize that the moral law as
expressed in almost every major religion is to protect us, not
repress us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Falzarano described a similar transformation after maintaining a
gay lifestyle for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``God did not want me to be gay. I could no longer participate
in such an act, and I never looked back,'' said Falzarano, who has
been straight for nine years, is married, and has a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Other panelists were: Rabbi Yehuda Levin of the Union of
Orthodox Rabbis of the U.S. and Canada, Brooklyn, N.Y.; Victor
Stanley of Calvary Baptist Church, Woodbridge, Va.; the Rev. Robert
McFarland of Excel Ministries, Washington, D.C.; the Rev. Thomas
Morrow, Catholic Archdiocese of Washington, D.C.; and the Rev. J.
Philip (CQ)Ashey (CQ) of the Church of the Apostles Episcopal
Church, Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who said she was a member of a gay and lesbian group was
denied an opportunity at the press conference to respond to the
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold your own press conference,'' Rabbi Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
