<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-GOLD-ART     08-12 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-GOLD-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Aug. 16)  
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (JT)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humans have lived in what is now California for at least 7,000
years, and the land they live on was formed over a few million
years of geologic time. But modern California _ the boisterous,
roiling, polyglot place of dreams that so fills the American
imagination _ was born on the morning of Jan. 24, 1848, at a
sawmill on the South Fork of the American River in the foothills of
the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``This day some kind of mettle was found in the tail race that
looks like goald,'' Henry Bigler, a Mormon worker at the mill,
wrote in his diary. And from the moment that Bigler's boss, an
itinerant carpenter named James Marshall, found two tiny nuggets,
the first one about half the size and shape of a pea, in the water
channel of the mill owned by John Sutter, nothing was ever the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, more than a quarter million migrants from
all over the world had come to seek their fortune, and though much
of the boom went bust within a decade and population centers moved
west and south, the settlers never really stopped coming. Today,
the Marshall Gold Discovery State Historic Park in Coloma, a tiny
village 50 miles east of Sacramento, readily recaptures the
excitement of Marshall's find, with a reconstruction of the mill _
now run by electricity _ and a small museum with blown-up
reproductions of Bigler's journal and other documents. It is as
good a place as any to begin a sesquicentennial tour of the
territory that made California the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   The patient _ or the merely romantic _ can still pan for placer,
or particle, gold along the riverbank with wide, flat pans
available at shops throughout the region, and the weary can swim in
the Sierra-fed stream at a small campground across the way from the
mill site. But Coloma is only the chronological starting point for
visiting a region that, like the Cotswolds or Tuscan hill towns,
best yields its treasures to unhurried exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching for more than 300 miles along California Route 49,
the Golden Chain Highway, the Gold Country today is a collection of
well-preserved Victorian frontier towns, historic museums, pristine
parks and rivers for hikes and whitewater rafting _ and even a
growing wine country _ all within easy reach of the grander
splendors of Lake Tahoe and Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent long weekend, my wife, Dee Dee, and I barreled north
from Los Angeles in our own private stagecoach, a trusty Ford
Explorer, racing across the vast agricultural expanse of the Great
Central Valley into the rolling foothills northeast of Fresno. We
drove almost the whole of Highway 49 over three and a half days,
but confined our official wanderings to the northern half of the
territory, the stretch from the town of Angels Camp north to Nevada
City, with frequent stops in between.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Angels Camp, in Calaveras County, that a young
prospector with a literary bent first heard the tale of a
celebrated jumping frog. A monument across the street from the old
Angels Hotel on Main Street commemorates Mark Twain's inspiration,
and an annual May Jumping Frog Jubilee at the county fairgrounds
draws competitors from all over to re-enact the legend. Just south
of town, atop a rise called Jackass Hill, a well-marked road off
Highway 49 leads to a reconstructed cabin that may or may not be
where Twain wrote the story that helped begin his career.
</P>
<P>
   A short drive east on Route 4 lies the picturesque town of
Murphys, where we stayed on an earlier trip to the region, with its
old Main Street shaded by giant elms and locusts and looking
unchanged from its heyday. There, the Murphys Historic Hotel, which
once played host to Twain, Ulysses S. Grant, J.P. Morgan and
others, still functions, and though guidebooks often cite its
charm, it seemed a bit musty to us, and a steak and salad dinner in
its restaurant was only passable. A far better redoubt is the
Dunbar House 1880 bed-and-breakfast, a white frame Italianate
cottage lovingly restored by Bob and Barbara Costa, who serve a
delicious breakfast of home-baked goods in a peaceful garden.
</P>
<P>
   Route 4, which heads up into the Sierras and in summer can be a
delightful back-country route to Tahoe, with cattle wandering
across the road in the high reaches of Ebbetts Pass, is a diverting
detour, with at least one truly spectacular sight: the Calaveras
Big Trees State Park. This stand of giant sequoias has neither the
tallest nor the most-visited examples of this tree, but in the
1850s they were the first to be discovered by white settlers and
for a time thought to be the only such specimens in the world.
There are two groves in the park, one in the north with 150 trees,
easily accessible from a parking lot; the other, in the south, with
more than 1,000 trees, is reachable only by an easy milelong walk
through an old-growth forest.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Highway 49, the road continues north to the pretty,
unspoiled town of Sutter Creek, named for the Swiss emigre whose
sawmill started it all, but whose own efforts at mining here ended
in dismal failure. A local merchant named Leland Stanford was
luckier: he took a share of a nearby mine as payment for a
customer's debt, and it ultimately became the basis of a fortune in
railroading that propelled Stanford to the governorship and to the
founding of Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sutter Creek's Main Street is abuzz with a four-block
stretch of gift shops, bed-and-breakfasts and antiques shops, and
is home to what may be the finest luncheonette in North America,
the Chatterbox Cafe. Sharing the name of Garrison Keillor's
fictional restaurant but founded in 1946, long before ``Lake
Wobegon'' was invented, it was taken over in 1991 by Mike Gill and
his wife, Michele, longtime Keillor fans from the Los Angeles area
who spied it on a visit and couldn't resist the name. It serves
breakfast and lunch only, slowly, has just 14 stools and 5 tables,
closes at 3 p.m. (4 p.m. weekends) and is practically perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gill presides over an old-fashioned soda fountain that
still pumps out syrup and seltzer in separate streams, requiring
hand-dashing with a long spoon over crushed ice. In the kitchen,
Gill grills fresh-made hamburgers on homemade buns with skinny,
hand-cut fries from a bin of russet potatoes that juts out into the
only passage to the tiny, immaculate bathroom. The waitresses are
agreeably jaded and lippy, and virtually everything is homemade,
from the iced tea to the cinnamon buns and biscuits, and after a
lunch of two ``Prospector'' burgers (with thick locally smoked
bacon and Jarlsberg cheese), and fresh blackberry and coconut-cream
pie, we rolled out the door in a state of purest bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed and sleepy after our indulgence, where did we go next?
To a wine-tasting, of course, in the no-nonsense metal barn of
Domaine de la Terre Rouge, just outside the haunting remains of
Fiddletown, near Plymouth, in neighboring Amador County. Along with
Calaveras and El Dorado Counties, Amador constitutes a growing
local wine-producing region that dates back at least to the 1860s,
when some of the immigrants _ Basques and Italians, for example _
brought grape cuttings with them; today it makes award-winning
zinfandels, syrahs and other varietals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
