<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-VIDEO-LADN     08-12 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POCAHONTAS II' COMING SOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NANCY HEWITT and ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Disney has another winner on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pocahontas II: Journey to a New World,'' arriving on video
Aug. 25, continues the story of the American Indian princess who
fell in love with a white man.
</P>
<P>
   Now home in England, John Smith has been accused of treason and
faces death, but after he escapes, the king turns to the matter of
defeating the Americans and claiming the land for England. But it
is John Rolfe who convinces him not to battle the savages until he
meets with their chief.
</P>
<P>
   The king dispatches Rolfe to bring the chief back to Britain but
it is Pocahontas who decides to go to England in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Bedard reprises her role of the spirited teen, Russell
Means is back as Chief Powhaten, David Ogden Stiers again plays
Gov. Ratliffe, Michelle St. John returns as Nakoma, along with
Flit, Meeko and Percy.
</P>
<P>
   Several new characters are introduced in this sequel including
Billy Zane as the dashing British diplomat Rolfe, Jean Stapleton as
his kindly housekeeper Mrs. Jenkins and Donal Gibson, real-life
brother of Mel Gibson, in the role of Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Five new songs are introduced including ``Where Do I Go From
Here?'' and ``What a Day in London!''
</P>
<P>
   And Disney has spared no expense in re-creating a breathtaking
1600s England, complete with cobblestone streets, lush greenery and
colorful costumes.
</P>
<P>
   This sequel to the 1995 film completes the Pocahontas story.
Viewers will enjoy the young woman's English adventures, her new
love interest and the appearance of a friend from the past.
</P>
<P>
   STIRRING THE POT: Disney has also released its 1985 animated
feature ``The Black Cauldron'' ($26.99; one hour, 20 minutes) whose
failure at the box office put the chill on animation projects until
it heated up in 1989 with ``The Little Mermaid.'' This sword and
sorcery tale was aimed at kids who were gaga over ``Star Wars,''
complete with a farm boy, actually a pig boy in this case, who's
called upon to save the world. The plot's a little confusing, and
there are no catchy songs, but some of the animation is quite
lively. (Director Tim Burton was one of the animators). ``The Black
Cauldron'' isn't for the little ones, but the 8-and-older crowd
should enjoy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0451 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-GOLD-ART     08-12 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-GOLD-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: other varietals.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fact, the growing conditions are not unlike the long, hot
days of Provence, and Terre Rouge specializes in Rhone varietals
like grenache, syrah and mourvedre. We were inspired to visit after
tasting its Vin Gris d'Amador, a delightfully crisp dry rose. The
winery is owned by Bill Easton and Jane O'Riordan, former wine
merchants in Berkeley. The afternoon we visited, a friendly, though
not especially knowledgeable, employee happily poured a half-dozen
samples, and we went home with a case and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to make our Friday night's destination in Nevada City, we
sped up the road, breezing through famous towns like Placerville
(originally named Hangtown, for its rough justice), where my
great-great-grandfather sought his fortune in vain in the Gold Rush
but saw the money-making potential of the dry-goods business and
returned to rural Illinois where he eventually opened a store of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Having made our reservations on short notice for a crowded
summer weekend, we had little choice of accommodations in Nevada
City, a picture-book Old West town whose main thoroughfare, Broad
Street, rises sharply up a steep hill. We stayed at a
bed-and-breakfast called The Parsonage, and it was adequate, but we
envied the inviting look of another, Grandmere's, in a sprawling
house just up the street that was full that weekend, and decided it
would be the preferred destination on our next trip.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada City is best seen by walking its hilly streets, and there
is plenty to see, from the small brick Nevada Theater, at 401 Broad
St., which dates from 1865 and is the oldest operating theater in
the state, to the National Hotel, at 211 Broad, said to be the
oldest continuously operating hotel west of the Rockies, with a
broad upstairs porch. The Nevada County Historical Society Museum
in Firehouse No. 1, at 214 Main St., has a charming collection of
old photographs and pioneer relics.
</P>
<P>
   But by far the most interesting attraction in the area _ and one
of the most compelling in all of the Gold Country _ is the Empire
Mine State Historic Park down the road in nearby Grass Valley. This
splendid 800-acre park is the site of the state's oldest, richest
hard-rock gold mine, which operated from 1850 to 1956, when the
price of gold made mining unprofitable. Here visitors can see what
a big industrial business mining became after the era of the early
49ers, when technology made it possible to dig deep into
underground quartz deposits, out of which gold was then laboriously
``stamped'' with giant smashing machines. We spent a fascinating
half-day here, with an enthusiastic and articulate state park
ranger as our guide, peering down a shaft of the abandoned mine.
The mine, stretching 11,000 feet below ground, contains 367 miles
of shafts, most of which are now flooded with groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans for a ride that would carry visitors through
part of the underground labyrinth, but even a tour of the mineyard
is enough to sense the hardship of the miners, most of them emigres
from the tin and copper mines of Cornwall, England. They brought
with them their beloved meat pie, the pastie, which is still a
staple in Grass Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the mineyard, in a class juxtaposition worthy of
Shavian drama, a gate leads to the lushly landscaped grounds and
stone-and-brick cottage of the Bourn family, which owned the mine
for much of its life. The family stayed here in Gilded Age luxury
during their periodic visits to the mine, ensconced in gardens and
a grove of trees but, even so, unable to escape the round-the-clock
pounding of the giant stamping machines. Today there are tours and
perpetual quiet.
</P>
<P>
   After a quick lunch of delicious hot pasties at Mrs. Dubblebee's
in Grass Valley, we headed off to Coloma, and then to a refreshing
dip in the canyons of the North and Middle Forks of the American
River at the Auburn State Recreation Area just east of Auburn on
Route 49.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, we wandered the winding streets of Nevada City, and
then took one last stroll through natural beauty in the South Yuba
River State Park at Bridgeport, a quick drive north of town on
Pleasant Valley Road off Highway 49. Bridgeport is home to a
beautiful 252-foot covered wooden bridge from 1862, one of the
longest single-span covered bridges in the country, and offers a
series of hikes and swimming holes in cool pools set back from the
bubbling rapids of the South Fork of the Yuba River.
</P>
<P>
   As we paddled from boulder to boulder in the soothing stream, we
could feel the powerful tug of the current and couldn't help
wondering if it still carried flecks of treasure. Reluctantly, we
dried off with spare T-shirts and turned south to Sacramento for
the long drive home down Interstate 5, the Golden State Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall Gold Discovery State Historic Park, &LR;  Highway 49, Post
Office Box 265, Coloma, Calif. 95613; (530) 622-3470. Day-use fee,
$5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Calaveras Big Trees State Park,  &LR; Route 4, Post Office Box 120,
Arnold, Calif. 95223; (209) 795-2334. Six thousand-acre woodland
with giant sequoias, self-guiding trails and camping and picnic
sites. Day-use fee, $5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Domaine de la Terre Rouge Winery, &LR;  10801 Dickson Rd., Plymouth,
Calif.; (209) 245-3117. Tastings Friday to Sunday, 11 a.m. to 4
p.m.; free. The small shop carries cookbooks and local history
books.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Empire  &LR;   &UR; Mine State Historic Park,  &LR; 10791 East Empire St.,
Grass Valley, Calif. 95945; (530) 273-8522. Hours vary seasonally;
call for schedule. Admission: $3, $1 children 6 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; South Yuba River State Park,  &LR;  17760 Pleasant Valley Rd., Penn
Valley, Calif. 95946; (530) 432-2546. Gold panning demonstrations
at 1 p.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dunbar House, 1880,  &LR;  271 Jones St., Murphys; (209) 728-2897 or
(800) 692-6006, fax (209) 728-1451. Three double rooms and one
suite, each with Norwegian stove, in a restored house. Excellent
home-baked breakfasts. Rates: $125 to $175.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Grandmere's Inn, &LR;  449 Broad St., Nevada City; (530) 265-4660,
fax (530) 265-4416. Five double rooms and two suites in a 1856
Colonial Revival house in the heart of town. Landscaped gardens and
broad front veranda. Rates: $100 to $165.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chatterbox Cafe, &LR;  39 Main St., Sutter Creek; (209) 267-5935.
Classic luncheonette, with homemade pies, fries and burgers,
fountain drinks and ice cream. Decorated with vintage Army
recruiting posters and '40s sheet music. Breakfast and lunch only.
Lunch for two with huge servings of pie, $20. Closed thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mrs. Dubblebee's, &LR;  251C South Auburn, Grass Valley; (530)
272-7700. No-frill bakery and cafe in an old white clapboard house,
specializing in Cornish pasties, savory individual half-moon meat
pies with buttery, crimped crusts. The beef is the house specialty
and more flavorful than chicken, but both are delicious. Takeout
pies available in two sizes, lunch and dinner. Lunch for two with
soft drinks, about $8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Citronee Bistro and Wine Bar, &LR;  320 Broad St., Nevada City;
(530) 265-5697. California cuisine, with dishes like cold tomato
and roasted garlic soup, sauteed sea bass with wasabe mashed
potatoes, and grilled meats and fish. Dinner for two: $100.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Broad Street Books and Espresso Bar,  &LR;  426 Broad St., Nevada
City; (530) 265-4204. Bookstore-cafe, with breakfast specialties
like scrambled eggs with dill and cheese, baked goods, espresso
drinks and lunchtime sandwiches. Indoor and outdoor tables. Big
breakfast for two, under $20.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
