<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKYARD-BARBECUE-ART     08-12 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKYARD-BARBECUE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBECUE PITS FOR THOSE WITH MONEY TO BURN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I., Texas, N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DONNA PAUL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smoke gets in their eyes _ and that's only part of the
attraction. Once man cooked over an open fire in a cave. Some time
later came the 1950s backyard grill, a mammoth creation etched on
the landscape in brick or stone. In the '60s, more mobile chefs, or
those without backyards, swore by their portable hibachis and Weber
kettle grills. And then came the '80s and the portable gas-fired
grills that turned summer cookery into something as romantic as,
say, lighting the kitchen range.
</P>
<P>
   And now? After two decades of growth, the U.S. economy has
brought a return to the backyard barbecue. Fire-hungry homeowners
who want to keep up with the Dow Joneses are moving beyond rusty
iron grills to a new generation of built-ins. They want fish
baskets, wood-fired pizza and bread ovens, smokers and rotisseries.
They may even want a designer fire pit.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the experience of cooking over wood or charcoal
is powerful. ``The mingling of the fragrances with the air, the
unique quality of the smoke and the aroma of charcoal is very
healing and purifying,'' said Barrie Kavasch, a Native American
food historian who maintains that fire is ``emotionally magnetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's done in a primitive oven in a hole in the ground or
in a rooted-in-stone artisanal outdoor command post of the sort
that is becoming popular today, cooking over fire is in fact
booming. Steven Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue! Bible''
(Workman, 1998), says he believes that the ``grill mania'' sweeping
the country is a reaction to the high-tech lives people are living.
``Grilling has a timelessness about it,'' he said. ``It appeals to
a primal yearning for fire-cooked food.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hamilton, Mass., a seaside town north of Boston, a tall stone
fireplace has a shiny stainless-steel grill and a fancy rotisserie.
Its owner, Boston chef Frank McClelland, lives in a year-old house
built with an outdoor hearth. ``I wanted to experience the great
pleasure of cooking outside during the spring, summer and fall
months,'' McClelland said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Martin, the owner of Martin Grill and Oven Works, in
Providence, R.I., recently made a fish basket for McClelland that
attaches to the rotisserie. Martin said that the demand for
expensive outdoor cooking areas is increasing and that outdoor
ovens for the home have risen to 20 percent of his business, from 5
percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Ross, a food historian who has taught courses in
historical cookery in Smithtown, N.Y., for 20 years, noticed the
change about two years ago. ``All of a sudden there was an interest
specifically in building brick ovens and learning how to bake and
cook in them,'' Ms. Ross said. The demand was so great that she has
added a course on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   When McClelland and his family moved to Hamilton from an
apartment above his Boston restaurant, L'Espalier, he hired Peter
Giordano, who describes himself as a muratore. (The word is Italian
for mason.) Giordano, born in Palermo, Sicily, has been building
with stone since he was 14. Now 53, he and his son Peter Jr., 26,
built a fireplace for McClelland that is an update of a traditional
design.
</P>
<P>
   The fireplace is made primarily of local field stone. The stone
chimney and grill area are built on a brick base; counters and the
grill are standard height, 36 inches. High-quality iron spot
bricks, which cost $1.35 apiece as against 40 cents for standard
bricks, was chosen. The top of the chimney is made of the same
bluestone as the surrounding terrace, and a food preparation area
is also made of bluestone.
</P>
<P>
   Although the design is simple and timeless, it includes modern
modifications, particularly inside the fireplace. For the walls,
the masons used cement blocks rather than solid stone. ``If we
would have built this using the ancient method, we would have had
12- to 16-inch solid walls on both sides,'' said Giordano Sr.
Instead they determined that stone veneer over cement blocks would
be more efficient and less expensive. Yet, the cost for the
fireplace still ran about $5,000, or $35 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Worth it, McClelland said. ``When I cook at home, I love to let
my hair down,'' he said. ``The idea of coming out here when the
weather is cool and roasting game or meat is fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, June and Mark Chandler purchased a house four
years ago and found a crumbling outdoor fireplace held together by
little more than ivy. They hired Gardens, a local landscape design
and construction concern, to recreate and embellish an outdoor
cooking area where one had been built 70 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bauer, an architectural designer at Gardens, was inspired
by traditional Italian stone techniques to create a new oven,
entertainment area, grill and terrace. He said his emphasis was on
using stone the way it is supposed to be used. ``There is nothing
fancy here,'' he said. ``We used the simplest materials: limestone,
galvanized metal and pea gravel. What this is really about it is
how it is executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Using blocks of white Texas limestone measuring 24 by 12 by 6
inches, Bauer made the walls of the oven tower 12 inches thick.
``Stone is meant to be heavy and big and support itself,'' he said.
``In today's world, stone is often used as a veneer. In our
construction, all of our stone becomes load-bearing walls.''
</P>
<P>
   When the quarry stone arrived, it was in a rough rectangular
shape; stonemasons reworked each block by hand to make certain the
corners were crisp and straight.
</P>
<P>
   The limestone blocks in the Chandlers' original terrace had been
pushed up by tree roots. The masons were able to recycle the blocks
for the new terrace; pea gravel was used to fill in where the roots
were intruding.
</P>
<P>
   The $2,500 wood-fired pizza oven the Chandlers selected came
from Italy in terra-cotta sections. Although they fit together
tightly, Bauer had stonemasons seal the oven entirely with a layer
of cement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The tower that houses the oven looks like a folly sitting in a
Tuscan garden. It is 10 feet high with a standing-seam metal roof.
Ivy climbs its walls, and the whole thing looks as if it had been
on this spot for years.
</P>
<P>
   The terrace is 30 feet square, including the area for the
barbecue grill, storage cabinets and galvanized metal counter tops,
which won't rust, set along a 19-foot-long limestone wall. Cabinet
doors are made of teak and wire mesh. The total cost was about
$38,000.
</P>
<P>
   When Donald and Virginia Sohn were renovating a 60-foot-long
terrace behind their home in Beverly Farms, Mass., ``it seemed to
need a fireplace,'' Mrs. Sohn said. What she had in mind was quite
different from what her architect, John Pears, drew for her. Pears,
who was born in South Africa, presented a hybrid of several
different fireplaces he had seen in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in Malawi, they don't do structures,'' he said.
``They make a pit in the ground. Here the sunken terrace that
already existed became like the pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone walls surrounded the area, and would provide seating. It
was the congeniality of a circle around a fire that inspired Pears.
``Everyone faces inward and looks at each other across this event,
while people cook together,'' he explained. In the end, he adapted
an African concept to fit an American life style.
</P>
<P>
   The fireplace consists of a 48-inch circular drum, built with
bricks recycled from a chimney in a nearby carriage house. Firewood
is stored on a bluestone cap above the drum. The firebox is a
conical steel structure that contains the fire. Topping that is a
42-inch rotating steel grill. The grill gently spirals up and down,
so food can be raised high when the fire is hot and lowered as it
cools. Pears also designed a circular steel ledge, at counter
height, to hold implements, plates and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Custom fabrication added to the costs. With the architect's
design fee, the tab for the Sohns' grill was nearly $15,000. But it
was an instant success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first party we had was in October, and the night was
brisk,'' Ms. Sohn said. ``As the evening drew on, the crowd sat on
the walls around the fireplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a fire pit, a pizza oven or a fish basket added to a
fireplace well anchored to the land, the new accouterments have
attracted fans of entertaining outdoors. ``If you are cooking your
very chic buffalo burgers on a very chic outdoor grill,'' said Ms.
Kavasch, the food historian, ``they do taste better.''
</P>
<P>
   An outdoor oven is usually dome-shaped and gets as hot as 600 to
700 degrees. Wood is set inside and fired up, and afterward the
coals are raked out. Baking is done directly on the oven floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correct dimensions when building an oven are critical,'' said
Frank Martin, owner of Martin Grill &AMP; Oven Works in Providence,
R.I. ``The door height should be no more than 65 percent of the
height to the top of the oven.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor ovens begin at $5,000. Sources for them include Martin's
company, at (401) 724-1491; Peter Giordano of Gloucester, Mass.,
(508) 283-2793, and Gardens in Austin, Texas, (512) 467-9934.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE     08-12 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (Take 1 -- in two takes)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that Monica Lewinsky was given
``transactional immunity'' to testify about her relationship with
President Clinton in Kenneth Starr's investigation. What does that
mean, and how does it differ from immunity in general?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Transactional immunity'' is a form of blanket protection so
comprehensive it is rarely granted by prosecutors. Basically, it
means that there can be no prosecution under any circumstances in
connection with events coming out of the entire ``transaction'' _
hence the term. For her part, Lewinsky promised her full and
truthful testimony and must answer any and all questions Starr
might raise before the grand jury. She will not have the option of
invoking the Fifth Amendment, which protects citizens from
self-incrimination, because with no prospect of being prosecuted
there's no possibility of self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A more limited and more widely used immunity, known as ``use
immunity,'' is not an absolute guarantee. Under that form of
protection, prosecutors cannot use anything witnesses say to
prosecute them or to seek evidence to prosecute them. But the
witnesses can still be prosecuted if other evidence surfaces
independently that they have committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   So, the former White House intern will not go to jail as long as
she tells the truth, regardless of any evidence against her.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the five states with the lowest number of prison
inmates per 1,000 population, and the five with the highest?
</P>
<P>
   A: The highest rates per 100,000, ac-- ording to 1997 figures
from the U.S. Department of Justice, are the District of Columbia
at 1,682; Louisiana, 672; South Carolina, 636; Nevada, 618; and
Oklahoma, 617. The lowest rates are North Dakota, 112; Minnesota,
113; Maine, 124; Vermont, 140; and West Virginia, 174.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have scientists discovered the cause of the huge upwelling of
cold water in the Gulf of Mexico along the Florida Panhandle? After
only one news report a few days ago, nothing has been mentioned in
the media.
</P>
<P>
   A: In the words of one researcher, ``In a nutshell, no.'' Both
Beverly Roberts of the Florida Marine Research Institute and Sneed
Collard, a biologist at the University of West Florida in
Pensacola, agree that as yet there is no hard scientific data
supporting a theory of what caused the 15-to-20-mile-wide band of
cold water that stretched along the coast for nearly 200 miles in
June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Collard, who has been charged by the federal government with
investigating the phenomenon, says remnants of the cold water _
which may have come from the 10,000-foot deep DeSoto Canyon _ are
still hanging around, but not in the concentrations seen earlier.
He cautions that news reports may have made the event seem more
ominous than it was. He fielded calls from dozens of reporters and
heard possible explanations ranging from pollution to a giant hole
in the bottom of the Gulf of Mexico. His best guess? ``There are no
coherent theories out there at this time. It's an anomalous cold
water event. I've got to leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Iraqi flag, which I see often on CNN, has three stripes,
and in the center there are stars and what I imagine are Arabic
words. What do the words mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: The inscription, on the white (middle) stripe, means ``God is
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: On Vice President Al Gore's recent trip to Ukraine, it was
reported that Chernobyl was the world's third-largest nuclear
reactor before the explosion there in 1986. What are the world's
largest reactors now?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the world's top 15 reactors in terms of energy
generation (measured in magawatts heat), as reported in the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission's 1997 Information Digest: Phillipsburg-2, in
Germany; Neckar-2, Germany; Palo Verde-3, Arizona; Emsland,
Germany; Grondhe, Germany; Brokdorf, Germany; South Texas-2, United
States; Isar-2, Germany; South Texas-1, United States; Unterweser,
Germany; Ohi-3, Japan; Seabrook, New Hampshire; Penly-2, France;
Ohi-2, Japan; and Gralenrheinfeld, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me if ``Lord of the Dance'' is playing now?
Anywhere I could see it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Better rent the videotape, or plan on taking a trip. The
closest place to see it currently is Las Vegas, where one of the
troupes has set up shop in the Broadway Theatre of the New York-New
York Hotel/Casino. It's a ``permanent'' run, meaning it will play
there as long as audiences come. Two other troupes tour worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Flatley, who created ``Lord of the Dance'' after
splitting with ``Riverdance,'' doesn't perform in the Las Vegas
show, but he remains artistic director. The Las Vegas cast includes
Conor James Smith as the Lord of the Dance; Geraldine Bergin as
Saorise, the Irish colleen; Decklan Bucke as the Dark Lord;
Catriona Hale as Morrighan, the Temptress; Ashling Dunney as the
Little Spirit; and Rosemary Collier as Erin the Goddess.
Information: 702-740-6815.
</P>
<P>
   Other troupes are on tour. Here are some of the places you can
fly off to and see ``Lord'' this year: Cardiff, Wales, Sept. 7-8;
Glasgow, Scotland, Sept. 11-12; Sheffield, England, Sept. 15-16;
Newcastle, England, Sept. 18-19; Hamburg, Germany, Oct. 1-2;
Stuttgart, Germany, Oct. 6-7; Munich, Oct. 9-11; back to Hamburg,
Oct. 13-17; Berlin, Oct. 19-21; Brussels, Belgium, Oct. 23-24;
Frankfurt, Oct. 26-27; Vienna, Oct. 29-30; Innsbruck, Austria, Nov.
1-2; Cologne, Germany, Nov. 4-6; Ghent, Belgium, Nov. 10-11; Paris,
Nov. 24-25; Oslo, Norway, Nov. 27-29; Gothenburg, Sweden, Dec. 1-2;
Stockholm, Dec. 4-6; Copenhagen, Dec. 8-9; and Helsinki, Finland,
Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Flatley, meanwhile, is busy with a film project under the
working title ``Dream Dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Inside Edition'' recently featured a woman who had lost a
good bit of weight. She started her own business with a cookbook
and menus for overweight people. I didn't see all the program, so
could you provide any details? How can I get her book?
</P>
<P>
   A: The woman you saw is JoAnna M. Lund, author of a series of
cookbooks under the Healthy Exchanges banner. At one time she
tipped the scales at 300 pounds, and when three of her children
were called to active duty during Operation Desert Storm in the
Persian Gulf, Lund resolved to make a drastic change. She devised a
method of what she called ``exchanges'' to enable her to eat all
the food that she loved, while exchanging the fats and sugars with
healthier choices, thus reducing the calorie intake. She lost 130
pounds, and the idea for her Healthy Exchanges cookbook was born.
</P>
<P>
   Lund now has written eight books and a series of booklets,
writes a syndicated newspaper column, has a radio show, has
produced two inspirational audio tapes, and operates several
businesses. Her latest book, ``Dessert Every Night,'' will be
published in September. She plans a book-signing visit to Atlanta
in October, her publicist said.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Healthy Exchanges, P.O. Box 124, DeWitt, IA 52742;
or call 1-800-766-8961 or 319-659-8234.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been an official inquiry into the fire last month
on the Carnival Cruise Lines ship Ecstasy?
</P>
<P>
   A: The National Transportation Safety Board is continuing to
investigate the July 13 fire, which caused no deaths but left 78
people, mainly crew members, complaining of various trauma-related
ailments. A formal report is nine months to a year away, said James
Scheffer, a NTSB marine investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel, which remained afloat after the fire broke out just
2 miles offshore after leaving Miami, was taken to Newport News,
Va., for repairs. Cruises have been canceled through Sept. 11.
Authorities initially discounted, but did not exclude, speculation
by the ship's owners that the fire was started by a welder in a
lower laundry area and spread upward through vents to an open-air
deck where flammable mooring ropes were stored.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB also is checking into the ship's firefighting
procedures and passenger communications. Jim Garrett of the Coast
Guard, which helped Carnival crew members fight the fire, said the
Ecstasy's mechanical protections appear to have performed well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address to write Senate Majority LeaderTrent
Lott? A newspaper editorial suggested that we inundate his office
with letters imploring him to allow a vote on the Shays-Meehan bill
concerning campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write: Sen. Trent Lott, Russell Building/487, 1st and C
streets N.E., Washington, D.C. 20510.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
