<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE     08-12 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (Take 2 -- in two takes)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Russell Building/487, 1st and C streets N.E.,
Washington, D.C. 20510.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the American Heritage Rivers program. What
is it all about? How are rivers selected?
</P>
<P>
   A: The idea, according to Environmental Protection Agency and
other government officials involved, is to channel federal
resources to local communities ``to help them preserve the
historic, cultural, recreational, economic and environmental
values'' of their rivers. The initiative was announced Feb. 4,
1997, by President Clinton. Communities nominate their areas to the
program; if their rivers receive the designation, the communities
will receive streamlined, focused support to access existing
programs and services. It's not a ``land grab'' for rivers,
according to the EPA, and no foreign governments or international
organizations are involved.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Internet access, check this site _
www.epa.gov/OWOW/heritage/rivers.html _ for complete information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it ever revealed what brand of golf ball astronaut Alan
Shepard hit on the moon? He had always kept it secret.
</P>
<P>
   A: It wasn't your ordinary Wilson or Maxfli. The three balls
Shepard used Feb. 6, 1971, when he made his shot heard 'round the
universe, were not identified by NASA, but described by only as
``special and heat-resistant. We can tell you some other things
about the feat, however. He missed the first shot, connected on the
second and third, and estimated that the balls went ``miles and
miles and miles'' in the moon's weak gravitational pull. Scientists
later said possibly a half-mile,at most.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the club? The secretly prepared, customized
Wilson 6-iron Shepard used was created by Jack Harden, head pro at
a Houston country club frequented by National Aeronautics and Space
Administration personnel. He was approached by a NASA engineer who
said Shepard was toying with the idea of hitting a golf ball, but
the problem was how to smuggle a golf club along. Harden was given
the end portion of a utility tool similar to the one Shepard would
be carrying on the moon. Cutting off a small shovel from its end,
Harden was able to grind the stem so it would fit into the socket
of the club head.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shepard wasn't the first man in space (that was Soviet
cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin), he was the first American, and he was
always proud of his golfing exploit. ``Probably I'm a hell of a lot
more famous for being the guy who hit the golf ball on the moon
than the first guy in space,'' Shepard said in a 1996 interview.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Buffalo Bob'' Smith, the creator of ``Howdy Doody,'' died
recently. Can you print the words to his program's theme song?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's set to the tune of ``Ta-ra-ra-boom-de-ay'':
</P>
<P>
   It's Howdy Doody time,
</P>
<P>
   It's Howdy Doody time.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Smith and Howdy, too,
</P>
<P>
   Say howdy doo to you.
</P>
<P>
   Let's give a rousing cheer,
</P>
<P>
   'Cause Howdy Doody's here.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to start the show,
</P>
<P>
   So kids, let's go!
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been a change in entry requirements for a U.S.
citizen traveling to Canada? My wife recently was denied boarding
for a flight to Canada from Atlanta because she didn't have proof
of citizenship, although she had flown there in previous years
without it.
</P>
<P>
   A: The requirement for proof of citizenship has always been in
effect, according to the Canadian Consulate General. Passports are
recommended, because they verify citizenship and have a photo, but
citizens or permanent residents of the United States aren't
required to have passports. If a passport is not available, some
sort of original identification papers or certified copies proving
citizenship (birth, baptismal or naturalization certificates) are
required, along with an ID card containing a photo. Permanent
residents of the United States are advised to carry their Resident
Alien Card (U.S. form 1-151 or form 1-551).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was told that Monica Lewinsky gained access to the White
House because of the government shutdown. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lewinsky already was a White House intern at the time, but
the story goes _ and President Clinton confirmed it in a deposition
in January _ that Lewinsky and other interns once brought him pizza
in the Oval Office during the federal government shutdown in 1995.
This was before she was transferred to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press in March, Monica
Lewinsky's father, Dr. Bernard Lewinsky, said he believes his
daughter moved from her internship to a full-paying job because she
received accolades for volunteering during the shutdown to answer
phones inside the White House in then-Chief of Staff Leon Panetta's
office. ``She was commended not only by Mr. Panetta but by
everybody on the staff for the outstanding job that she did
answering over 1,000 telephone calls that day correctly,'' he said.
``On the basis of that, I believe, she was able to apply (for) and
receive the position that she got.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to visit Althorp, in England, next year to see
Princess Diana's burial site. When will tickets for next summer go
on sale?
</P>
<P>
   A: Details for 1999 haven't yet been announced. A spokesman for
Althorp House told Q&AMP;A that the site probably will be open again in
July and August, as it was this year, but he wasn't sure. He
advised those interested to call in January or afterward to inquire
about specific details, including ticket arrangements. The number:
011-44-1604-592020. Another option is to call the British Tourist
Authority in New York: 800-462-2748.
</P>
<P>
   When you make your travel arrangements, you need to know that
Althorp House is 100 miles from the little village of Althorp, so
don't get them confused.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What states are involved in Powerball?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're printed it before, but since Powerball hysteria breaks
out every so often when jackpots rise to astronomical heights,
here's the list again. In the most recent jackpot frenzy, it was
documented that many players drove long distances and even bought
airline tickets to states where they could buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The states are: Arizona; Connecticut; Delaware; Idaho; Indiana;
Iowa; Kansas; Kentucky; Louisiana; Minnesota; Missouri; Montana;
Nebraska; New Hampshire; New Mexico; Oregon; Rhode Island; South
Dakota; West Virginia; and Wisconsin. Plus, the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Rezulin, a diabetes drug, has been banned
in Europe, and liver problems have been reported in the United
States. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was widely reported recently that consumer advocates in
the United States, including Public Citizen, had urged the
government to ban Rezulin, citing 26 deaths worldwide from liver
failure. The call to ban the drug, which has been widely touted as
a way to help some patients reduce their need for insulin, came
seven months after Britain banned it because of liver risks.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration strengthened its testing and
labeling requirements in an advisory Dec. 1, saying patients taking
Rezulin (troglitazone) should be monitored more frequently for
signs of injury to the liver. It also issued a requirement for
warning information about potential liver toxicity to be more
prominently displayed in the drug's labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer Parke-Davis, which insists the drug is safe when
used properly, sent letters in late July to 500,000 doctors saying
the FDA had upgraded its warning for doctors to test patients'
livers for signs of toxicity for the first eight months of Rezulin
use. The tests need to be made monthly, according to the
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
