<HEADER>
A0468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     08-12 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: PROS AND CONS OF DIFFERENT HOUSE DESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Art is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new house is a major investment. All home buyers are concerned
that their money will be well spent. They dread the prospect of
discovering major flaws or defects after they buy and move in. The
problem is that most people don't really know what to look for when
buying a house.
</P>
<P>
   Start by considering the style of house. It is important to
understand that even though a house looks elegant, it may not fit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch houses, for example, are the most popular houses in
America, but they do have some drawbacks. Since the entire house is
on one level, it has a larger roof area than a two-story house. The
big expanse of roof allows more heat to escape in the winter and
absorbs more sunlight in the summer, so heating and cooling bills
can be higher than for other houses. These costs may not be
excessive, however, if the attic has adequate ventilation and
insulation. Also keep in mind that if you have to replace the roof,
it can be a costly proposition
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, ranch houses are easy to maintain because all
the rooms are on one level. Exterior painting, roof repair and
gutter cleaner can be done from a step ladder. Ranch houses are a
good choice for older people or those individuals who find stair
climbing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate agents call any two-story house a ''colonial''
as long as both floors are the same size, with the bedrooms on the
upper floor. Two-story houses are cheaper to heat and cool than
large one-story houses.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the exterior of the house can be a lot of work. You
will have to raise an extension ladder to paint the upper story or
clean the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   Bi-level houses are essentially ranch houses raised so the
basement/lower level is largely above ground. The lower level may
also include a garage and storage area that, although convenient,
cuts into the living space. Bi-levels are ideally suited to sloping
lots, where the upper level opens directly onto the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Cod house is a one-and-a-half story structure. The top
half story is the attic, which may or may not be finished. If the
attic is converted into living quarters, the rooms will be small
because part of the sloping roof serves as the walls. These top
rooms may be difficult to heat or cool if the roof is not properly
insulated. Cape Cods are attractive to first-time home buyers
because they are less expensive than larger houses. A large family,
however, will probably feel cramped in one.
</P>
<P>
   Many home buyers love the elegance of Tudor-style houses. The
stucco and wood trim, leaded-glass windows, roof gables and angular
chimneys create a romantic facade, but these features also make
Tudors expensive. Take time to carefully inspect a low-priced Tudor
that seems like an exceptional bargain. Often the stucco surfaces
are made of thin layers of metal lath and cement that may
deteriorate in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   Most Tudors have slate roofs that are extremely durable, but the
valley flashing between the many gables and dormers is not as
rugged and is subject to leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Today many home buyers are rediscovering the architectural
beauty of older Victorian houses. The problem with many Victorians
is that the plumbing and electrical installations may not be
adequate to meet today's needs. Larger Victorians may be difficult
to heat, especially if they are inadequately insulated.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it can be expensive to match or replace the elaborate
fixtures and ornamentation throughout the house if you have to make
major repairs or renovations. Another problem with older period
homes is that it is difficult to upgrade them with new
low-maintenance materials. Tudors, for example, do not look good
with vinyl siding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0491 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-O'HIGGINS-HNS &LR;      08-12 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-O'HIGGINS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOGS OF DOW' GURU SWITCHES HIS INVESTMENT STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With DOW-O'HIGGINS-SUIT)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ When Michael B. O'Higgins is losing a round of
golf, he tries to persuade opponents to settle their scores and
start the betting anew at the next hole.
</P>
<P>
   If the well-known financial adviser times it right, he can play
worse than his competitors, but come out a winner _ at least
monetarily.
</P>
<P>
   It's how a contrarian financial strategist plays the fairways,
the 51-year-old O'Higgins explained recently at Schuyler Meadows
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the cyclicality of golf, as is the case with
(financial) markets, as in life in general,'' O'Higgins said. ``You
don't have too many straight lines in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins, a native of Venezuela who lived in Cuba and the Far
East before settling in Loudonville, N.Y., and then Miami, has a
preference for the squiggly route.
</P>
<P>
   The approach has won him plenty of attention _ both bullish and
bearish _ and has him poised for the spotlight again.
</P>
<P>
   His new book, detailing an updated twist on his contrarian
investment strategies, is scheduled to hit bookstores this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, O'Higgins became well-known in financial circles in
the early 1990s, when his book ``Beating the Dow'' spawned a
multibillion-dollar industry based on strategies called ``Dogs of
the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   His ideas have brought him supporters and detractors in the
Albany area, where he once lived and worked.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Apkarian remembers O'Higgins attending annual meetings of
Mechanical Technology Inc., which Apkarian formerly headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's evaluating a particular investment, he does a
thorough analysis of it, and he's bright enough to understand what
he sees and hears,'' Apkarian said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Madarasz, a spokesman for the New York Civil Service
Employees Association, extols O'Higgins' abilities, saying the
adviser has done well by the public employee union's funds.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Capital District Physicians' Health Plan
won a $2.7 million judgment against O'Higgins last year. The HMO
claimed he improperly invested the health maintenance
organization's money.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins and the HMO reached a confidential settlement
agreement this year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins said it was not news to him that people either love
him or hate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are like that _ they have strong personalities,
and they bring out strong reactions,'' he said about himself.
``I've never been a shrinking violet.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps controversy is to be expected when the subject is a
contrarian.
</P>
<P>
   What's almost certain is that he'll be a conversation topic if
``Beating the Dow with T-Bonds, T-Bills and Stocks'' does as well
as the first book, which has sold more than 200,000 copies. For the
new one, HarperCollins paid him an advance of nearly $500,000, the
New York Post has reported.
</P>
<P>
   This time, O'Higgins said, anyone using the new strategy with
clients will owe him a fee. While O'Higgins earned much attention
from ``Beating the Dow,'' he earned no money from financial
managers who used it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm patenting this one. ... They're going to get sued next
time,'' O'Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't patent the first book, he said, because it never
occurred to him it would become so popular.
</P>
<P>
   The idea began gestating in the 1970s, when O'Higgins lived in
Loudonville. He had arrived in 1965 to attend Siena College,
founded by Franciscans, at the recommendation of two uncles who
were Franciscan monks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the most serious student,'' O'Higgins said. ``Chasing
money and chasing women were my interests then. Now it's just
making money.''
</P>
<P>
   He stayed after graduation, he said, because he liked the region
and met his wife here. His wife, Donna, graduated from the State
University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins started his career in 1971 at investment research firm
Spencer Trask &AMP; Co. During 1973 and 1974, when a bear market hit
and stocks plummeted, O'Higgins began questioning the firm's
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   He opened his own firm in 1978 and began using the contrarian
ideas that were published later in ``Beating the Dow.''
Essentially, O'Higgins purchased stocks he calculated to be
momentarily out of favor, with the thought of buying low and
selling high.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased with the results. He was sued twice in
federal court for investments he managed in the 1980s, accused by a
physician and two dentists for breaching his fiduciary duties in
connection with their pension and profit-sharing funds.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, O'Higgins was accused of not following his
clients' wishes, which resulted in big declines in the funds'
value.
</P>
<P>
   Also in both cases, federal judges decided in O'Higgins' favor.
In a 1992 decision, Judge Frederick J. Scullin Jr. wrote, ``The
plaintiffs were well aware of the risks. They were well aware of
the defendant's investment philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Higgins had published some of that contrarian
philosophy in ``Beating the Dow,'' igniting an entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of large brokerage firms offer funds called unit
investment trusts tied to the `Dogs' method. O'Higgins helped
market Merrill Lynch's funds initially, said Roberta Hess, vice
president of defined asset funds in the company's Princeton, N.J.,
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have almost $20 billion following the `Dogs of the Dow'
strategy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry King, associate vice president of investment at Prudential
Securities in Albany, said it's easy to understand why the ``Dogs''
method took off running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple concept, the fees are extremely reasonable, and
it's easy to explain and it works,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Dogs'' strategy began slipping in 1993 as the stock
market headed upward, according to a Wall Street Journal report.
Merrill's so-called ``Select 10'' strategy saw returns over the
last year and the five-year period ended Dec. 31, 1997, of 27
percent and 21 percent, below the Dow's return of nearly 30 percent
in 1997 and nearly 28 percent in the five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins not only is the first to concede this, he also said he
sent a letter to his clients last August _ when the Dow hit 8,200 _
urging them to dump the ``Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of reasons the ``Dogs'' bark has outpaced
their bite, O'Higgins said. First, the stock market overall has
become overvalued, due to a flood of investments from retirement
plans and amateur speculators. Second, too many people are
following some form of the strategy he set out in ``Beating the
Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea behind this is to buy things that are cheap,''
O'Higgins says. ``But if something becomes too popular ... it
usually rises in price to a point where it's no longer cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not revealing much about the new book before it hits the
stores. But he said the new strategy considers investments in bonds
and Treasury bills as well as stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Valley Forge Management Corp. of Wayne, Pa., has
signed a contract with O'Higgins to establish the The O'Higgins
Fund Inc. using the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins points out that this is a way for investors who can't
afford his own $1 million minimum to use his method.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are undecided, among them Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked to him about it. ... But at this point there's
just been discussions,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sivy, Wall Street editor for Money magazine, said
variations on O'Higgins' ``Beating the Dow'' remain a good
long-term investment method, even if they're not doing as well as
the Dow right now. The relative downturn, he believes, is due not
to the strategy's popularity but the current dominance of
big-growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Sivy is not convinced a new strategy that includes bonds and
T-bills will necessarily be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of doesn't matter how you draw up the rules, as long
as they give you a universe of big established companies and they
give you a way of selecting the ones that are the cheapest,'' Sivy
said. ``I'm not sure that adding more wrinkles and more
complications makes it better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
