<SLUG> BC-DOW-O'HIGGINS-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO NO FAN OF `DOGS' THEORIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nationally, Michael B. O'Higgins' name is no
doubt most associated with the investment strategy known as the
Dogs of the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Albany area, he has most recently received attention
for a lawsuit brought against him by the Capital District
Physicians' Health Plan in 1994 and settled this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany-based health maintenance organization ended up
selling $2.4 million securities it had bought for $5.1 million
under O'Higgins' management. In January 1997, a federal judge
ordered O'Higgins to pay up to the tune of $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was not within what we told him our policy was,''
said Dan Colacino, the HMO's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Though that charge was similar to two previous lawsuits brought
against O'Higgins in federal court, in this case a judge ruled
against O'Higgins based on a separate issue: The investment adviser
had neglected to reveal that he was using his brother, James
O'Higgins, then a First Albany Corp. vice president, as the
commissioned broker-dealer for the purchases. The judge determined
Michael O'Higgins breached his duty in not revealing the potential
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins appealed, and a confidential settlement was reached
earlier this year. O'Higgins would offer no information, but said
the HMO would have prospered if its administrators didn't get
scared when the bonds he invested in were down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sold at bottom, and then sued ... which is incredible to
me,'' O'Higgins said. ``And then this bond subsequently
skyrocketed.''
</P>
<P>
   The HMO sold, Colacino said, because it was concerned about an
outside-its-policy expenditure of its members' money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw the performance of the investment, we sought
outside financial advice, and their advice was to sell, and we just
took their advice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E. Stewart Jones, a lawyer who knows O'Higgins socially, said
lawsuits are part of the game when your job is investing clients'
money at some risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the nature of that business; people become
dissatisfied,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   .MDSU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1639EDT &QL; 
