<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-HEIRLOOM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING OLD IS NEW AGAIN FOR GREAT-GRANDDAUGHTER'S WEDDING DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Even in a time when wearing hand-me-downs is
trendy, the item of clothing that Jeniffer Todd received from her
great-grandmother is extra-special.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wedding dress made for Loretta Pavero in 1932, when she
married in upstate New York at age 15. Pavero's granddaughter,
Darlene Todd, wore it for her ``simple backyard wedding.'' And on
Aug. 8, Pavero's great-granddaughter Jeniffer wore it in a larger
wedding at Genesis United Methodist Church in southwest Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Pavero's daughter, Joyce Anthony, opted not to wear the dress
because her wedding happened too quickly. She was also too tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore the dress because we didn't know if she'd ever get to
see someone else in it,'' Darlene said. ``Now she gets to see her
great-granddaughter as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeniffer, 23, has wanted to wear the dress since she was a
little girl. ``I saw the picture, and she looked absolutely
gorgeous. I knew then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just lucky enough to have the same build.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple and straight-lined, the dress remains almost entirely in
its original state. The lace, imported from Italy, is a little
brown around the seams. The satin trim and slip are in mint
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's the stain on the front from the stuffed
mushrooms that Darlene ate at her reception. (Jeniffer also had
stuffed mushrooms at her reception.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't stored under proper conditions,'' Darlene said. ``We
found it in a cedar chest in (Pavero's) house. No cleaner would
touch the dress. They didn't want to take the risk.'' One cleaner
wanted $75 for the insurance alone.
</P>
<P>
   When Darlene resurrected it for her wedding, it had a small hole
in the front, which she quickly repaired by sewing lace from the
train in its place.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeniffer's wedding, Darlene revived the veil, which hadn't
been worn since 1932. About 10 feet long, it was reconstructed with
new netting and the original lace around the edges. Darlene spent
10 hours getting the dress ready for her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 months of planning, the Big Day came. Unnerved,
Jeniffer sat in the dressing room with her bridesmaids and maid of
honor, who wore purple floral dresses in the same style the
bridesmaids wore at her great-grandmother's wedding. About 15
minutes before the wedding, Pavero and her daughter arrived and
were taken to see Jeniffer.
</P>
<P>
   Pavero, 81, has trouble speaking, but she brightened up when she
saw her great-granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember looking like that?'' Darlene asked.
</P>
<P>
   Softly touching the dress, a glimmer of nostalgia in her eye,
all Pavero could manage was a drawn-out, ``Nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't have to say even that much. Her smile did all the
talking.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0532 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FESTIVAL-LADN     08-12 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FESTIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILM FESTIVAL'S HOMETOWN FEEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What do Toronto, Telluride and Tinseltown have in
common?
</P>
<P>
   Each has a film festival, though it might come as a surprise
that Tinseltown's is the baby of the bunch. The 2-year-old
Hollywood Film Festival closed its showcase of fresh filmmakers,
new productions and tributes to industry icons at an awards gala
Monday night at the Beverly Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And the winners were:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sugar Factory,'' written and directed by Australian
filmmaker Robert Carter, and director Nick Pearcy's ``Paradise
Falls'' took home the honors for best features over $1 million and
under $1 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Penelope Ann Miller, who plays a sister caring for her widowed
brother's family in ``Rhapsody in Bloom,'' earned a special jury
award for best acting in a feature. ``Rhapsody'' was directed by
Craig Saavedra and written by Eric Tuchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goreville U.S.A.'' was named best documentary, with ``Holiday
Romance'' by English filmmaker JJ Keith chosen best short film, and
director Steven Ayromlooi's ``Return of the Sun Devil'' best
animated film. The 24-year-old Ayromlooi also was chosen best young
filmmaker for his short ``Nathan Grimm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Independent Filmmaker Award was presented to
director-writer L. Alan Fraser for ``Next Time.'' Special-effects
duo Rob Legato and Crystal Dowd received a Hollywood Digital Award
for ``Titanic,'' while Entertainment Tonight Online was named best
entertainment Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Academy Award-winning actress Shelley Winters accepted a
Lifetime Achievement Award, saying, ``It's about time Hollywood
started to pay less attention to special effects and violence, and
more attention to human beings and relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Zanuck and David Brown each received awards for
outstanding achievement by motion-picture producers. Brown returned
the pat on the back, saying ``It's about time Hollywood would
produce its own major film festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Honorary awards also went to director Norman Jewison and
award-winning film composers Dave Grusin and Stewart Copeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
