<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0533 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MAC-SOFTWARE-NYT &LR;      08-12 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAC-SOFTWARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALKING THE MAC THRILL OF YESTERYEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used in the Web address
at the end of the story instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly two years, my friend Nancy Bendit has blamed me for
persuading her to buy a Macintosh Performa. Her complaints fall
into three categories:
</P>
<P>
   1. There is not enough cool software to run on the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   2. Not enough software.
</P>
<P>
   3. Software! Software! Where is the software?
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Ms. Bendit brings this up _ to be fair, no more than
three or four times a day _ I flash back to my own very different
experience with my first Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Day 1992, stuck in a motel near the Phoenix
airport, I passed the grim time playing a game called Glider on my
brand-new Powerbook 160.
</P>
<P>
   Deceptively simple, Glider required the player to pilot a paper
airplane through a house, avoiding such dangers as electric fans
and burning candles. In some rooms, you had to figure out how to
turn on a light switch; in the kitchen, you had to avoid the
certain death of a sizzling toaster.
</P>
<P>
   Glider embodied all the charms of the first-generation
Powerbook: Quirky and adorable, it sneaked up and hooked you on its
elegant simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Bendit needed, I reasoned, was to find a program like
Glider, one that would allow her to undergo a similar communion
with her Macintosh machine. Would that be possible, given the
ferociously anti-Mac climate of software development today? I went
in search of more recent Mac programs whose lure might be powerful
enough to invoke such an epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   Online stores were the obvious place to start. While retail
stores have become notoriously parsimonious about allocating shelf
space to Mac ware, big shareware archives like those at Tucows
(www.tucows.com) and at ZD Net (www.macdownload.com) do not suffer
from space constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Gralla, the editor of ZD Net's software library,
acknowledged that ``the amount of Macintosh shareware has been
dwindling,'' but the site still has more than 5,000 titles. I asked
ZD Net's resident Macintosh expert, Richard Curtis, about his
favorite programs, and then downloaded and tested three on my old
Power Macintosh 7100/66.
</P>
<P>
   One program that stood out was Spell Tools 1.2.1, which creates
a floating window on screen. Click on the window to check spelling
in any application on your computer. If you highlight text, Spell
Tools will read it out loud in a tone that sounds vaguely like
Marlon Brando in ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: an enjoyable tool, certainly, but not enough to
alter anyone's world view. I needed something quirkier.
</P>
<P>
   I visited two smaller shareware sites maintained by die-hard
Macintosh boosters, www.macupdate.com and www.ualberta.ca/mmalowan.
I downloaded Debt Wizard to analyze and find suggestions for
eliminating pesky credit-card debt, a 401(k) planner only too happy
to predict retirement income based on wild guesses about future
returns on investments, and My Precious Baby, for recording
milestones like the first tooth.
</P>
<P>
   But these programs were teases. Until a user paid a registration
fee, the programs were hobbled. A window shopper could sample only
a portion of their features. Disregarding the shareware tradition
of allowing users to fully test software free seemed to me to be a
very non-Mac attitude.
</P>
<P>
   On www.trickfx.demon.co.uk, I did find a very quirky freeware
program called Ivolution. A snapshot of an abstract image appears
on screen and then automatically mutates in five ways. Each
mutation includes different colors and patterns. Click on one, and
it will evolve in five more directions. This cycle continues for as
long as your attention span holds.
</P>
<P>
   I applauded the purely useless but amusing nature of Ivolution.
But in the end, it wasn't enough. Perhaps the only kind of program
that would have truly transformative properties would be a really
good game.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this Wintel-centric world, there remain a few software
companies known for their Macintosh games. Freeverse Software, at
www.freeverse.com, sells bizarrely offbeat versions of such
standard card games as hearts and solitaire. But although I have
spent hundreds of hours playing Hearts Deluxe over the years, I
didn't think the concept was original enough to qualify as Ms.
Bendit's software Rosebud.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosia Software, at www.ambrosiasw.com, sells arcade-style
games guaranteed to provoke nostalgia in anyone who ever pumped
quarters into a Galaga machine. But after I downloaded and became
addicted to two of Ambrosia's longtime best sellers, Swoop (think
of Space Invaders) and Bubble Trouble (Pac-Man), my only question
was: Where is the new stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five we're working on,'' the company's spokesman,
Jason Whong, assured me in a phone interview. ``We have a
role-playing game called Cythera that's going to be a lot of fun.
And we've got Smithereens, where you're a snake and you have to eat
other snakes and you can eat eggs and other stuff, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That game sounded as if it could be just what I was looking for
_ a product that melded Ambrosia's high-quality programming with a
totally weird premise. When would it be available?
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope they both will be out in 1998,'' Whong said. ``But
then, Cythera was announced by the company back when I was still a
junior in college, so ....''
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, I found the creator of Glider, John Calhoun.
In an e-mail message, I asked Calhoun, who is now a programmer at
Apple Computer, if he had written any other Mac games that I could
offer to Ms. Bendit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scads,'' he wrote back. ``Most of it was not very interesting.
But there you are _ Glider looks dated to me now, too. I think
games are really for the moment, like bad sitcoms you grew up
watching as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dated or not, at least Glider is still available, distributed by
Casady &AMP; Greene (www.casadyg.com). A new CD-ROM version for the Mac
costs $34.95, plus shipping and handling. I will order it for Ms.
Bendit. Will it be enough to keep her from replacing her Performa
with a Windows machine?
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
