<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUKE-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE OLD NEIGHBORHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Luke Perry insists that his ``Beverly Hills,
90210'' character does not have an evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   So the actor's return to the series that made him a matinee idol
can mean only one thing: The Hills will be chillin' with Dylan
again.
</P>
<P>
   Perry signed an overall deal with Fox that will bring the often
brooding Dylan McKay back to the series, allow him to develop his
own show and lead to television and theatrical movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as surprised as everybody else, let me tell you,'' Perry
joked about his return to the show. ``I was pretty clear never to
say never. (Fox entertainment president) Peter Roth extended
himself in a major way here. He showed me loyalty and that's all I
ever wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who left ``90210'' in 1995 to pursue a feature-film
career, didn't exactly blow up into the next Tom Hanks, but he
didn't bomb like David Caruso, either. Perry was in pictures such
as ``The Fifth Element,'' ``Normal Life,'' just finished filming
``Florentine,'' and is working on ``Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best thing for me,'' Perry said about his return
to the ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Aaron Spelling apparently has not given Perry
much information on the circumstances surrounding Dylan's return.
</P>
<P>
   When we last saw McKay, the show's moral center, he was driving
away from his bungalow in England with a cat on board after his new
bride (played by Noxzema girl Rebecca Gayheart) was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   In Perry's estimation, McKay didn't stay long in England (``with
Amsterdam that close?'') and he traded the cat off while in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Perry would not divulge the terms of his deal other than to say,
``I'm still gonna call Anthony Edwards and ask to borrow some
money. It ain't all about the money, bro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``90210'' will need Perry and the buzz surrounding his return to
hold off its direct competition at 8 p.m. Wednesdays, especially
``Dawson's Creek,'' the latest in teen dramas that is helping the
WB network build quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Priestley, the show's star, will leave the show early this
season before Perry's comeback and Shannen Doherty turned down a
spot on the show to start up a new Spelling drama, ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a day since I left that at least one person
has said to me, `When are you coming back'?'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   When he and Spelling started talking a few weeks ago, ``It was
music to my ears. He said, `Hey, pal, wanna saddle up again?' I
said, `Hey, boss, when do I start?' We have had our ups and downs,
both personally and professionally, but at the end of the day, he
is someone I have a lot of respect for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
