u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUG-BUSINESS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUG-BUSINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE THIRD FLOOR AT HARRODS: ABC CARPET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The intimate world of Oriental rug dealers is about
to get even cozier. As of Aug. 31, ABC Carpet &AMP; Home of Manhattan
is taking over the rug department at Harrods in London. This
late-blooming marriage between centenarian retail giants seems to
be far from impulsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This signals that Europe wants to buy the American home
furnishings look,'' said Leslie Stroh, editor of Rug News, an
industry newsletter. ``Where the rugs are actually made doesn't
matter anymore; it's where they are designed and packaged.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the American retailer's first venture beyond
familiar turf. ABC, a purveyor of carpets, furniture and
housewares, has been cautiously expanding from its anchor on lower
Broadway, opening stores in Delray Beach, Fla., in 1997 and
Westbury, N.Y., this year. And while the legendary Harrods seems
more packed with tourists than ever, its Persian rug department had
been losing luster because of the upheavals in Iran, where most of
its rugs came from, and the recent disintegration of a wholesale
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have over 330 departments,'' said Peter Willasey, a Harrods
spokesman, ``And history dictates that with some specialties, it is
better to bring in an outside company rather than buying yourself.
ABC will offer a wider selection of Oriental rugs, carpets and
accessories to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The new department will be called ABC Carpet at Harrods. It will
comprise 8,000 square feet on the third floor, offering more than
20,000 handmade rugs. ``Harrods is the third-most-visited site in
London,'' said Jerome Weinrib, the chairman of ABC Carpet and Home.
``We're going to cover the world in carpets.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Oakley, a third-generation rug manufacturer in India,
said that in recent years consumer attitudes have changed, with
Oriental rugs now being perceived as precious collectibles rather
than cheap and ubiquitous goods. ``Harrods Oriental rug department
used to have a reputation second to none,'' Oakley said, ``but as
the years have gone by, the Orientals have looked rather boring and
ordinary. ABC coming into Harrods should create waves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
