<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYSLEXIC-ADVOCATE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Dyslexic children have a friend in Joe Griffith 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Griffith says he got through school by cramming and cheating
and feeling stupid. He figures he missed out on a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good memory, and I came up with unbelievable ways to
cheat. We dyslexics are very creative,'' Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls how angry he became at age 9 or 10 when his mother
gave him a copy of the book ``Black Beauty'' as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never read a complete book for pleasure. Reading was
drudgery. I had to read aloud to myself, and start over and read
the same thing 10 times before I could get through it. I crammed
for tests all night,'' Griffith said. ``Teachers passed me for
trying hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The learning disability went undiagnosed until 12 years ago.
Despite that, Griffith, 57, has worked as an actor and TV talk-show
host. He recalls co-hosting America's first business program
offering stock market advice on Channel 39.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day they asked me to read the noon news, and I was out of
a job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith is still not a good reader.
</P>
<P>
   But he is a professional motivational speaker from Dallas, who
recently published his third book, ``How Dyslexic Benny Became a
Star'' (Yorktown Press, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   A previous book, ``Speakers Library of Business Stories,''
published by Prentice-Hall, is in its seventh printing. The book is
dedicated to dyslexics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a relief, to have one of the largest publishers in the
world publish your book when you can't read,'' Griffith said.
``That's when I came out of the closet and admitted I was dyslexic.
It's amazing how many people still don't admit it. I'll give a
talk, and people come up to me afterward and whisper that they too
are dyslexic.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said that dyslexia practically ruined his life _ all
those fears and insecurities _ but that he has been successful
despite all. That's the message he gives to children with dyslexia:
They can succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the book came out in January, he has been speaking at
schools, talking with children and explaining to teachers what
dyslexia is like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers think they understand, and the kids know they don't,
so they don't trust the teachers,'' he said. ``Most school systems
today fail to recognize and help dyslexics. If you can catch it in
kindergarten or first grade, it doesn't have to be a problem, but
teachers aren't trained to recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 12 to 15 percent of the population has some degree
of dyslexia, an inability to process written material. Those who
are most severely affected are the most likely to get help. Those
with mild to moderate problems just start dragging slowly behind,
Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they are twice as likely to become juvenile
delinquents, drug addicts and school dropouts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Griffith began working as a consultant to the Texas
Department of Corrections' program to deal with illiteracy in the
prison system. An estimated 80 percent of the people in Texas
prisons are illiterate, and Griffith said 60 to 70 percent of
illiterates are dyslexic.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith heads an organization known as CODE, or Concern Over
Dyslexic Education. CODE works with school systems to help them
comply with the federal Individuals With Learning Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   His book is available through most bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
