<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-WEATHER-1STLD     08-12 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-WEATHER-1STLD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN IN TUNIS? ON WEB, A WORLD OF WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ala.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Please use this version)  
 (af)  
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every morning, Doug Liu rises at 6 and checks on the Internet to
find out about the surf near his home in Northern California. About
three times a week, the news is good enough for a 25-minute trip to
the beach to catch a set of waves. The rest of the time, it saves
him a trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it shows there's no swell coming in, I'll just sleep in,''
said Liu, a system administrator for a technology company.
</P>
<P>
   The round-the-clock availability of information on the Internet
has spurred the success of Web sites that offer books, music, news
and the like. And it's also creating a demand for weather
information without the polish and marketing of weather forecasters
goofing off on local news shows.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of weather news appeals to Jimmy Bradley, 34, a
grocery stock clerk who participated in a recent discussion in a
weather chat room. (Of course there are chat rooms about the
weather.) Unlike the television broadcasts, Bradley said, Web
weather information has ``no opinions of meteorologists and talking
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Web was providing users with weather
information as soon as it was available, circumventing the wait for
a newscaster to make a radio or television announcement.
</P>
<P>
   In Bradley's home city, Mobile, Ala., where Hurricane Danny
dumped 43 inches of rain last year, time for storm preparation is
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, he got word of an approaching storm on line a
half-hour before he heard about it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to do what I had to do outside to get ready for it,
stuff like getting the dog in and the boat tied down and the
computer shut down,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Most weather pages offer a national overview of weather,
articles on places where weather is making news, local forecasts
and more detailed information for those who need it. Many sites now
offer personalized weather pages, proving that like politics, all
weather is local.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites are more oriented toward consumers, offering pages
with easy-to-use graphics and an eye on what the average user
wants. With others, you are expected to understand weather data
without the help of lengthy explanations. Weather news is also
cropping up on general interest sites, like news services and start
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The number of hits on weather sites puts most popular sites and
Web portals to shame. The National Weather Service said its page
got one million visits a day. Disney.com, by way of contrast, said
its site got 600,000 visits a day. The Weather Channel said its
site got 87 million ``page views'' a month, which means about 20
million visitors, and about 300,000 surfers have opted for
customized pages.
</P>
<P>
   There are 250,000 personal subscribers to the Accuweather Web
site, though the company says some 25 million get their weather
from additional Accuweather displays on Snap, CNN Interactive and
The Wall Street Journal's online edition.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is going beyond traditional media by offering weather
information for users with specific needs _ for storm warnings,
crop reports and forecasts for travel destinations _ that cannot be
met by television.
</P>
<P>
   More serious weather-heads are using that information to do
their own forecasting. Their efforts can be met with mixed results:
amateurs can sometimes draw the wrong conclusions from the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's not all good,'' a user identified as
DisasterWX said in a chat room. ``Now a lot of people are doing
individual forecasting. Some know what they are doing, but many
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The average weather hunter on the Web is most likely looking for
a temperature and conditions forecast, something to help determine
whether to carry an umbrella to the office. Here are a few Web
sites that offer that kind of information, plus some other places
to stop for additional features.
</P>
<P>
   If predictions and graphics aren't enough and you want to see
what the weather is like in a certain place, try weatherimages.org
or tvweather. com (soon to become weathercast. com). Both offer
``live'' images of weather cameras from around the globe, which are
actually still shots that are updated every so often. It's a nice
touch, though they tend toward the banal because the view usually
does not include twisters or hurricanes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Best Part of Accuweather Site Is Its Forecasting Accuracy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WWW.ACCUWEATHER.COM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This site, probably the most layman-oriented of the bunch, is
for people who want a thorough and easy-to-understand weather
report without a lot of frills.
</P>
<P>
   Accuweather.com offers an overview of regional, national and
world weather, graphics and maps of temperature and weather
patterns as well as personalized services like local and
travel-destination forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   You can create a personal weather page, allowing you to get the
forecast by entering your city's name or ZIP code, though
predictions won't necessarily be for what is over your house: you
can get only as close as the weather center nearest you.
</P>
<P>
   Local weather forecasts on Accuweather are much like what you
might see on local television: the sun shining or shrinking behind
clouds, sunrise and sunset, moon phases, high and low temperatures,
extended forecasts, and hour-by-hour forecasts. In addition, there
are jet-stream and precipitation maps.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are spending the next five days in Ouagadougou,
Burkina Faso, for example, you can find out that there will be
highs in the mid- and upper 90s and lows in the upper 70s. If
logging on to your personalweather page every day is too
cumbersome, Accuweather will send a forecast to your e-mail address
free.
</P>
<P>
   If you would prefer to search by weather ``product'' _ where the
hurricanes will be touching down next or where a particular storm
is _ you can do that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Accuweather site provides updates on specific storms and
conditions, as well as archive roundups of, say, how many people
Hurricane Bertha killed in 1996 (answer: at least nine).
</P>
<P>
   There are also fee-based services like tailored aviation weather
pages and, for those who fear twisters, National Weather Service
warnings sent directly to pagers.
</P>
<P>
   The site occasionally lurches toward the technical. For
instance, it offers a measure of ``base reflectivity'' on its radar
chart, though it offers a help section if you need to understand
that. For fun, check out Weather Facts, which offers a weather
trivia question and Today's Worst Weather; on a recent day, that
prize went to Magic City, Idaho, experiencing its 14th consecutive
day hotter than 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising on Accuweather is restricted to a few banners, at
least for now, so loading pages does not take too long. And more
important, the site has been, as the name implies, accurate: a
glance out the window confirmed that it was indeed sunny on a
recent afternoon in Los Angeles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lots of News and Lots of Ads &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WWW.WEATHER.COM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The home page of the Weather Channel, Weather.com is, like the
24-hour cable station that preceded it, oriented toward breaking
weather news from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   (``More heat,'' the site recently reported. ``The heat continues
in Oklahoma and Texas. It's now 23 days in a row for triple-digit
heat in Dallas.'') The news options let you click to read a feature
article on weather or to peruse headlines and summaries.
</P>
<P>
   Weather.com also offers a Dow Jones-style scrolling ticker of
forecasts and conditions in cities; you can scroll back if your
city zips by too quickly. As with the Accuweather page, you can
type in a city name to find out the weather there.
</P>
<P>
   When you do, you get a five-day forecast of temperatures and
conditions. You can also get a video report on ``this day in
weather history.'' The site occasionally displays computer-command
gibberish on its pages after loading, though it disappears when you
click on Reload.
</P>
<P>
   In its feature section, the Weather Channel mixes news (well,
features, anyway) with what the weather will be like at events like
the current PGA Championship. It's not the most elegantly designed
page, although it blends in some interesting analyses of how high
temperatures and humidity will affect events. It also offers a
selection of weather-related tips on topics like gardening, golfing
and boating.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising is considerable, making the site a bit slow to
load.
</P>
<P>
   Weather.com offers a personalized weather page, and a revised
version is due in the fall. The new version will let you customize
the report to show the current weather in five cities of your
choice, as well as a five-day forecast and a blend of the usual
cloud and temperature maps for your local area and the whole
country. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service Web Site Takes Itself Seriously &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WWW.NWS.NOAA.GOV &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE is probably the most trusted and
well-known source of weather information in the country. So
naturally, its home page is focused on ... good government?
</P>
<P>
   The top of the page is emblazoned with the insignias of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the National
Weather Service. In between is an American flag and a weather vane.
</P>
<P>
   The first link is not weather maps, forecasts or conditions, but
Our Mission _ a solemn promise to provide weather information and
warnings ``for the protection of life and property and the
enhancement of the national economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Just below that is the agency's ``reinvention'' goals to be
accomplished by 2000, a response to a Clinton Administration
initiative called the National Partnership for Reinventing
government.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, and then there's the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service site gets good marks for
explaining, unlike any other site, how weather information is
actually recorded. And users can select weather observations from
individual locations, not just cities, which gives a context for
understanding how close or far the observed conditions are to you
(for instance, you can check Los Angeles International Airport, not
just Los Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   You get wind, visibility, maximum and minimum temperatures and
24-hour summaries in addition to the conditions and current
temperature (updated every hour). The National Weather Service also
provides crop summaries, earthquake and tsunami reports and
ultraviolet indexes for those who want more detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   It also issues official weather warnings. It summarizes severe
weather warnings by state, so if you are looking for a flash flood,
you will know if there is one on the way. The site offers videos of
inclement weather, but they take a long time to download.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to forecasts, the National Weather Service site
offers an ``enhanced graphics'' version, which worked with mixed
results: a page for local weather would not load because the server
was down.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, graphics on the site are nonexistent to
rudimentary. That make the pages quick to load, but they lack the
consumer-oriented bells and whistles that the average
weather-hunting Web surfer might be looking for. As far as overall
presentation goes, the site also requires looking at multiple pages
and thus consumes more time than the other sites. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-COX     08-12 1468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elton John, Disney, and Alliance Theatre start the creative
juices flowing for ``Aida''
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York
</P>
<P>
   Crammed into the corner of Studio 4-3 _ the same
turn-of-the-century loft where Michael Bennett created
``Dreamgirls'' _ a rehearsal pianist bangs some rocking, chiming
chords on a scuffed upright. The sound may not be Steinway, but it
is unmistakably Elton. A brand-new, never-performed-in-public Elton
John song is struggling to compete with the old A/C window units
that labor on this wickedly humid day and dribble water four
stories onto lower Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Gyrating across the smudgy wooden floor, stealing glances in the
mirrored wall that stands in for the audience, are singer-dancers
in tank tops, cutoffs, sweats, sneakers and soft boots that look
thick enough for a mountain hike. They represent the people of
Egypt in grim excitement about the upcoming execution of Radames,
the white Egyptian soldier, and Aida, the black Nubian slave girl
best known from her namesake Verdi opera, whose forbidden love is a
betrayal to their nations and families.
</P>
<P>
   It's Week 4 of rehearsals. ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of
Aida,'' the new pop-rock musical co-produced by Walt Disney
Theatrical Productions and Atlanta's Alliance Theatre Company, is
in full creative heat.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Georgia, the sets (glittering obelisks, a multi-use
pyramid) are being assembled on the Alliance stage, where the show
begins previews Sept. 17. The dancers are kept steadily aware of
that destination by the thin red line of tape that angles across
the floor, mirroring the precise outline of the Alliance stage. The
stand-in obelisks are cardboard; a folding chair is labeled
``Throne.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a stripped-down, make-believe version of the dazzling
make-believe world to come. And Act 2 is literally taking shape in
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we're working on different approaches to the
ending,'' says director Robert Jess Roth, who at a boyish 35 may be
the youngest director with a long-running Broadway hit (``Beauty
and the Beast'') in production. ``So everyone's still involved,
still putting in ideas, from Linda (Woolverton, the book writer,
also from `Beauty') to the designers, to (lyricist) Tim Rice, to
Elton. I e-mail him every other day and it's wild not being quite
sure where he is; once it was Nice (France) and once it was Austin,
I know that. For a man who's never written directly for the stage
his theatrical instincts are astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The late) Michael Bennett owned this building and this is the
way he worked: wide-open collaboration, hectic but stimulating,''
continues Roth, a longtime director for Disney theme parks still
looking to make his artistic mark in the New York theater world.
Sweeping his hand toward the T-shirted dancers who look as if they
stepped right out of Bennett's `A Chorus Line','' he added, ``I get
inspired just being in Michael's room.''
</P>
<P>
   Another strong unseen presence is John, who has said he wanted
the premiere in Atlanta, his adopted hometown _ `So that I can keep
an eye on it'' _ a remark that didn't amuse Disney producers. (John
reportedly will watch rehearsals when they move to the Alliance
next month.) Judging by portions of three songs, John's ``Lives''
score is more reminiscent of his classic 1970s sound, both in the
uptempo rockers and love ballads, than the family-oriented numbers
he wrote with Rice for ``The Lion King.'' There is a tender duet
for Radames (played by Hank Stratton, 30, who appeared in the
Alliance's ``Angels in America'') and Aida (Heather Headley, 27,
the original Nala in ``The Lion King''), sung as they are about to
be sealed in the tomb, which seems destined to melt teen hearts.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly melts Woolverton's. As Roth instructs the lovers to
``Hold hands, so that's the last thing we see'' as the tomb is
closed, the 45-year-old author lets out a cry/sigh/laugh that shows
she's both moved and amused at herself for getting teary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with Elton's music, I'm such a fan,'' says
Woolverton, who worked on ``Beauty and the Beast,'' and who keeps
her 7-year-old daughter, Keaton, at her side during rehearsals and
then asks her artistic counsel at home. ``When my father died,
(John's hit song) `Daniel' was playing on the radio, and to this
day if I hear that song I have to pull over to the side of the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   When work on ``Lives'' began in earnest two years ago,
Woolverton was summoned to John's Buckhead apartment _ ``Or his
floor of the building, I guess would be more accurate!'' _ to meet
the British rocker and hear him play the songs he'd just composed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so excited and nervous,'' recalls Woolverton
delightedly. ``So now, it's not just his music, it's Elton's voice
I'm hearing. Even though he's not here, it's an intimate
partnership for me.''
</P>
<P>
   How does ``Lives'' stand apart from ``Aida,'' Verdi's grand 1871
opera?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to contemporize the story, and popularize it,''
Woolverton says. ``Now, is that a bad thing? No, I don't think so.
Even if people know the title `Aida,' not many know just how
powerful and timeless a love story is at the center of it. My
version is a truer love triangle . I'm interested in the
relationship between Aida and Amneris (the Egyptian princess,
played by Sherie Scott, a veteran of ``Rent''), not just as slave
and master, or rivals for Radames, but as women who were both born
into the role of princess, who are equals. I've developed their
bond to raise the stakes of the situation even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolverton added that Disney chairman Michael Eisner _ who will
see the show at the Alliance and rule on its Broadway-readiness _
has been faxing script suggestions as the project unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance artistic director Kenny Leon is also on the scene in
his role as co-producer _ offering the occasional comment or two
from the line of folding chairs along the mirrored wall, softly
humming a catchy John refrain. Woolverton accepted his critique
that the script repeated the word ``slave'' too often. ``That will
have a harsh ring to many people in my audience,'' Leon says. Three
Alliance stage managers are also posted on the line, recording the
lighting, sound and set-change cues.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the extent of the Atlanta presence. The only
Atlanta-based performers are three children who will join the cast
later. At first, Leon claims to have no problem with this ``best
cast we could have found.'' A moment later he concedes he's
disappointed that two Atlantans turned down offers to join the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, ``Lives'' is a Disney endeavor, pulling equipment and
manpower from corporate outposts in New York, Los Angeles, Toronto
and Orlando. The Mouse is footing most of the bill, which is
top-secret but will obviously run over $1 million. Director Roth
was impressed by the Alliance-bred production of Alfred Uhry's
``The Last Night of Ballyhoo'' on Broadway and refers to the
oft-maligned Alliance stage as ``a fantasyland _ a combination of
stage depth and relatively intimate house that's hard to find. I
jumped up and down when I saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate destination for ``Elaborate Lives'' is Broadway _
it closes Nov. 8 at the Alliance _ but the timetable is up in the
air. Disney's line producer in Atlanta, Marshall Purdy, said last
weekend that the company is circling, ``vulture-like'' around the
few Broadway stages that are deep enough to handle ``Lives,''
hoping that one will become available after the new year.
</P>
<P>
   But a spring transfer to the Great White Way, ``Would be the
ideal scenario, only if the show works ideally,'' says Stuart Oken,
Disney vice-president for creative development. ``Only when we get
the show on its feet in Atlanta will we know what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   -- WHAT IT'S ABOUT: Based on the 1871 Verdi opera of the same
name, ``Aida'' tells the story of a black Nubian slave girl and her
forbidden love for a white Egyptian soldier, Radames
</P>
<P>
   -- BEHIND THE SCENES: Elton John and lyracist Tim Rice _
partners in ``The Lion King'' _ collaborated on the music for
``Aida,'' with the book written by Linda Woolverton, who also wrote
the stage version of ``Beauty and the Beast.'' It is being directed
by ``Beauty'' director Robert Jess Roth. Heather Headley, the
original Nala in ``The Lion King,'' plays Aida; Hank Stratton, who
appeared in ``Angels in America'' at the Alliance, plays Radames.
</P>
<P>
   -- THE PRODUCTION'S COST: A closely guarded secret, but likely
more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- F YOU WANT TO GO: For single tickets to ``Elaborate Lives:
The Legend of Aida,'' call 404-733-5000. Single tickets $17-$35.
You can also order tickets online at www.alliancetheatre.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
