<SLUG> BC-REALITY-BYTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNIPPETS FROM CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A WIRED WOODSTOCK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time, Woodstock fans probably won't be worrying about
getting slowed down in the mud on Max Yasgur's farm in upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it might be on the bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tomorrow, Infoseek Corp. should expect plenty of
fiftysomethings to log on to its simulcast of the 29th anniversary
concerts for the original Woodstock music festival in Bethel, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The ``A Day in the Garden'' (actually three days) is the first
concert to appear on the site of the original Woodstock in nearly
30 years. Back when the original took place, some computers were
the size of school buses.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock buffs can access pre-festival information from
Infoseek (concert.infoseek.com), the search-engine people. The site
includes diaries of Woodstock stories, artist profiles, a chat
room, links to artist and fan sites, and retrospectives on the
original Woodstock. Fans can also buy tickets or purchase CDs by
the performing artists on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The coolest feature is the Shockwave-powered game designed to
get Woodstock fans in the mood. Using the arrow keys on the
keyboard, players must move a guy wearing a Rasta hat from the back
of the crowd to the front of the stage before time runs out.
Pushing and shoving are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   It's far out. It is like Woodstock _ without the mud.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE POPE, LIVE FROM THE VATICAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II will go online Sunday to recite his Angelus
prayers as the Vatican begins cybercasting from its site
(www.vatican.va) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Vatican site is an interesting visit. Its
Holy Father option gives visitors images of John Paul II, John Paul
I, Paul VI and John XXIII.
</P>
<P>
   The site, designed with a parchment theme, also examines the
Vatican Museums, the Jubilee 2000 celebration and historic Vatican
documents.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU AN INTERNET ADDICT? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before you call up that next Web site, consider the findings of
Kimberly Young, assistant professor at the University of Pittsburgh
and co-founder of the Center for Online Addiction
(www.netaddiction.com).
</P>
<P>
   Young promotes her book, Caught in the Net, on her extensive
site. In her book, Young points out that middle-aged homemakers and
college students are likely to become addicted to the Internet,
which she says has become as serious a problem as alcoholism and
compulsive gambling. Young also reports that nearly 14 percent of
college students meet the criteria for addiction.
</P>
<P>
   On her site, Young offers counseling and seminar information.
Visitors can also take tests to determine whether they are addicted
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings reviews Web sites for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call him at (817) 390-7397, or e-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
