<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-US-ADULTERY     08-12 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-US-ADULTERY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST AMERICANS SAY ADULTERY IS WRONG UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite President Clinton's high approval ratings
in the face of alleged marital infidelity in the White House, a
huge majority of Americans have been telling pollsters for years
that they believe adultery is wrong under any circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   And among average American couples, adultery appears to occur
far less than might be suggested by the flurry of recent news
accounts about the president and such other public figures as Bill
Cosby, Frank Gifford and Bruce Willis, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear to be all that common,'' said Dave Murray,
director of the non-profit Statistical Assessment Service in
Washington and an anthropologist whose speciality is family
structure. ``If anything, attitudes toward adultery in the 1990s
have hardened, possibly as a backlash to the sexual revolution of
the 1960s,'' added Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable data on adultery in the United States are limited.
Probably more than any other human behavior, adultery is cloaked in
secrecy and, therefore, researchers can hardly count on complete
candor from subjects. In addition, much of the research that has
been done in recent years has been colored by ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a 1994 survey by the National Opinion Research Center at
the University of Chicago, and a host of public opinion polls
conducted since, portray Americans as moralistic and conventional
in sexual matters _ ''essentially monogamous,'' as the University
of Chicago researchers summarized their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, recent research by sociologist Judith Treas of the
University of California in Irvine found that
</P>
<P>
   American attitudes about adultery are closely aligned with those
of Ireland, Northern Ireland and Poland, three nations with
conservative Catholic populations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The much-hyped sexual revolution apparently failed to loosen
American adults' non-permissive attitudes toward sex outside
marriage,'' Treas said.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''The general population seems to say, 'Oh, no, adultery is not
the right thing to do,' but a lot of the people saying that are
engaged in extra-marital relationships,'' said Albert Watson, a
University of Cincinnati professor who teaches family counseling.
</P>
<P>
   How many Americans commit adultery is difficult to quantify. But
a frequently used starting point is the 1994 National Opinion
Research Center survey.
</P>
<P>
   In a face-to-face survey of 3,432 adults who were born between
1933 and 1974, the center asked: ''Have you ever had sex with
someone other than your husband or wife while you were married?''
About 24 percent of men and 11 percent of women answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   Those percentages, if applied to the current population of
adults in the United States, would mean that about 19 million men
and 12 million women have committed adultery at least once in their
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures may be low, however, since polls of any kind do
not always elicit the truth. ''If your wife is in the next room,
you're not going to be completely candid,'' said Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the University of Chicago survey findings are similar to
those of public opinion polls conducted since. For instance, about
80 percent of those surveyed by the University of Chicago for its
1994 report agreed that adultery was ''always wrong'' while 10
percent said it was ''almost always wrong.'' A Gallup Poll last
December, before the Monica Lewinsky investigation of Clinton
began, found that 79 percent of Americans believe adultery is
''always wrong,'' 11 percent believe it is ''almost always wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Pew Research Center for The People and The Press,
found recently that 85 percent of Americans ''agree'' or ''mostly
agree'' that they have ''old-fashioned values about family and
marriage'' _ a figure that has been remarkably constant since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But Father James Heft, chancellor and a professor of faith and
culture at the University of Dayton, notes that there is nothing
old-fashioned in the way Americans speak of adultery today.
Consequently, he believes, there is little public outrage arising
from the allegations that Clinton had an affair with Lewinsky, and
tried to conceal the affair from Whitewater investigators and
lawyers representing former Arkansas state employee Paula Jones in
a sexual harassment suit against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We usually don't speak of adultery or fornication anymore,''
he said. ''We use more neutral terms like extra- and pre-marital
sex _ clinically descriptive and morally contentless. (CQ) That's
been part of our problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Ellen Balchunis, a professor at LaSalle University in
Philadelphia, said, ''Americans can and do separate their attitudes
toward infidelity and their politicians.'' Their attitude is ''they
didn't vote for Clinton to be pope,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for Clinton's continued high standings in the
polls may be the growing importance of privacy to most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a twist on the concept that we Americans hold our leaders
to a higher standard _ that Americans are afraid that the same
standards will be applied to them,'' said Nate Lenow, a private
investigator in Memphis, Tenn., with experience in adultery-related
divorce cases.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, for the past 30 years, American society has been
moving away from what University of Chicago sociologist Edward O.
Laumann calls the ''public guarantee of morality through law.''
With that movement has come a secularization of adultery laws, most
notably the no-fault divorce statutes of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who did what to whom no longer plays a part in the finances of
a divorce settlement,'' said
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schatz, a nationally known divorce attorney with the
Chicago firm of Kalcheim, Schatz &AMP; Berger. ''It may be an issue in
terms of emotions and it can set the tone for a case, but not the
finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Schatz said most divorces are not brought on by adultery, but by
the decay of relationships, which sometimes leads to adultery.
</P>
<P>
   ''If spouses work at being friends and supporters, respect each
other and have some common interests, they can sustain some of that
early romance,'' he said. ''They won't need extra lovers, and they
won't have to come see me.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
