<HEADLINE>
STOCKTON ROLLS OUT THE RED CARPET FOR 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ It didn't matter to the 30,000 cheering fans
who showed up that they were paying good money to see a mere
football practice.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did they mind that what they got Tuesday night was a World
Wrestling Federation match with a little football thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   What was important was that this was the event in town _ and it
involved the San Francisco 49ers, the team all of Stockton has been
nuts over since it opened its first training camp here 21 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   In what was billed as the ``Stockton Super Bowl,'' the 49ers and
San Diego Chargers met Tuesday night for a joint practice session
at sold-out Amos Alonzo Stagg Memorial Stadium and, at least
briefly, gave the fans, paying $10 each, their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Roman circus with a little practice mixed in,''
said Berkeley sociologist and 49ers consultant Harry Edwards as he
watched the action. ``The people here being as community minded as
they are, to have 30,000 people out here for a practice, yeah, it
was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have gotten into the spirit of the thing. They're
battling. This is basically the Roman Coliseum. Let's not fool
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco tackle Derrick Deese and San Diego defensive end
William Fuller turned a pass-blocking drill into a tussle that
developed into a mass scrum as players on both sides joined in
support of their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed that we aren't going to take any mess going into the
season,'' the feisty Deese said. ``He pushed me over on my back and
tried to drive me into the ground. I turned him over and we went to
work. I thought it was cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, 49ers tight end Shonn Bell and Chargers defensive end Van
Tuinei went at it at the end of a drill. Each man took a swing at
the other, always a futile gesture since the advent of the helmet
and face mask.
</P>
<P>
   More players joined in on this one, nearly enough to qualify as
a brawl. San Francisco tackle Chris Ruhman had his helmet ripped
off. Missing were bodies flying out the swinging doors of a saloon
and balsa-wood chairs being smashed over heads _ another milieu,
perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, 49ers rookie guard Phil Ostrowski tangled with Chargers
defensive tackle Henry Taylor, but by then, the spirit waned and
fewer players joined in.
</P>
<P>
   After each pointless skirmish, the fans cheered wildly. Death to
the infidels, they seemed to be saying.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the practice was mundane, but typical by football
training camp standards. The teams worked on running plays, passing
plays and punts.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the evening was a special one for some of the
approximately 120,000 fans who showed up at 38 practice sessions
spread over 21 days at the University of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Retired linebacker and new radio analyst Gary Plummer handled
the public address system and, at one point, exhorted 49ers coach
Steve Mariucci to let wide receiver Jerry Rice participate in a
team drill. Rice, rehabilitating from major surgery on his left
knee, was limited Tuesday night to individual drills only.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment manager Kevin Lartigue sang the national anthem _
perhaps a first for an NFL training camp practice _ as a
parachutist descended into the stadium. Planes flew over Stagg
stadium airspace, though not the Blue Angels as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   The entire evening was the culmination of a month of good will
flowing freely from the people of Stockton to the 49ers'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we developed was a rapport and a relationship with
the city of Stockton and the University of Pacific,'' Mariucci
said. ``Everybody here is bending over backwards to make it work.
The hospitality here has been second to none.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
