<HEADLINE>
AT THE NEW KIDS CAFE, THERE IS SUCH AS THING AS A FREE DINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In news footage, the children stare back at you, naked, with the
inevitability of death hovering around them like bees around
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   You are at once saddened and relieved that hunger's haunting
face sits in some faraway country with a name like Bosnia or
Somalia, places distant and unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that hunger also lives here. It is next door
and down the street and around the corner. Its face _ although
sunken _ looks a lot like that snapshot of you when you were a
little girl or boy making mud pies, climbing trees or both. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It feels like a dull, blunt needle in your stomach, that pang
you get just before a late breakfast or lunch. Only it is much
worse and lasts much, much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Sonjia Dickerson knows that pang and sees that face with
shocking regularity. It is no worse than a Bosnia or Somalia, she
says, but it's not a whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, hungry children live in communities all over the United
States. More than 12 million, according to estimates by the Second
Harvest National Network of Food Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the former coordinator of business operations for the Fort
Worth school district's nutritional services, I got to see it
firsthand,'' Dickerson says. ``Children were much hungrier on
Monday because they hadn't had food, or very little food, over the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids are heading back to school lunch programs, but even then,
it's a long time between lunch one day and breakfast the next.
</P>
<P>
   And it gets even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunger in children is not just about an empty stomach,''
Dickerson says. ``It also means not reaching the appropriate
heights and weights, and it leads to poor school performance.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Dickerson hopes the Tarrant Area Food Bank's Kids
Cafe can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Launched nationally in 1993 by the food bank's parent company,
Second Harvest, Kids Cafe provides meals exclusively to children at
risk of malnutrition. In the Morningside community, where the first
cafe opened in May, that's 77 percent of all children.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the reasons why the food bank chose the area to
begin its work, Dickerson said. The other reason is HOPE Farm, a
mentoring program for African-American boys ages 5 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we had to do was go in and add a food component to a
program that was already making a difference in the lives of
children,'' she said. ``Before we came there, they were giving them
a snack. We'll add to that a nutritional meal.''
</P>
<P>
   The local cafe will provide dinner to about 50 children a day.
The food bank will celebrate its grand opening at 4:30 p.m. Aug.
18. At that time, sites for two additional cafes in North Texas
will be announced. Those are scheduled to open in September.
</P>
<P>
   The food bank will supply food, administrative support and
salary for the kitchen coordinator at each site. But none of it
could be done, Dickerson said, without the $100,000 grant it
received from Capital One, a financial services company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have a one-year commitment,'' she said. ``And so
we've budgeted ourselves so we can maintain these programs for one
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But surely there are others like Capital One who can guarantee a
longer run. There must be, because it IS a long time between lunch
one day and breakfast the next.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send e-mail to gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV09     08-12 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV09-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADJUSTING A 401(K) FOR RETIREMENT DRAWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Long Beach and all needing)  
 (For release Sunday, August 09, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 69 years old and will be retiring next January. I will
receive Social Security and a company pension, I would like to know
the approximate maximum that I could expect to receive from my
401(k) each month without drawing from the principal. I attach a
statement, and a breakdown of the investment alternatives that are
available.
</P>
<P>
   F.H., Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if you wanted to get a strong income stream from your
401(k) with very little prospect of a reduction in principal, you'd
have to rearrange the portfolio fairly substantially. It s pretty
well positioned right now for a person in your situation -- just
approaching retirement. You have 59 percent of the money in stock
funds, with the largest stock position in Fidelity Equity Income
fund. On the fixed-income side, you have a total of 41 percent --
most of it in an Interest Income fund, but I also counted 37
percent of your holdings in Fidelity Puritan as fixed-income
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   To get the highest prudent income stream, you might put all of
the money in offerings such as the Interest Income fund and the
GNMA offering, (which I assume, like most of the offerings, is
Fidelity s,) and Fidelity U.S. Bond Index. Such a portfolio ought
to produce a yield of about 6.5 percent, which would mean $21,981,
or $1,832 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with doing that is that while good bond funds
should retain their value over the long haul (although some
short-term periods can be very bumpy) there s very small prospect
for principal growth, and growth of principal is what you need when
inflation starts digging into the buying power of your income
stream.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason I hope you can work out a budget that calls for
only about $1,500 monthly withdrawals from the fixed-income side.
This would allow you to leave about $50,000 of your 401(k) savings
in a solid fund such as Fidelity Equity Income, and should make
your situation more solid in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are 55 years old and my husband will probably work 10 more
years. We have $110,000 in IRAs in American Century-Benham Target
Maturity 2005, $15,000 in Vanguard Wellington fund, $27,000 in
Vanguard High-Yield Municipal Bond fund, $10,000 in Vanguard Asset
Allocation fund, and $25,000 in a CD. My husband has $13,000 in a
401(k) program at his place of employment.
</P>
<P>
   As you can tell, our investments are very conservative because
we have little investment knowledge. Do you suggest any changes? We
have $30,000 in a savings account we would like to invest now. We
feel we have waited too long to prepare for retirement. Please
help.
</P>
<P>
   How much do we need to have invested to receive $25,000 a year
to supplement my husband s pension and our Social Security?
</P>
<P>
   R.H., Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, since the answer to your last question is a little less
than $385,000, and since your current portfolio is likely to take
you well beyond that point during the course of the next 10 years,
you haven t done so poorly. To get that figure, I presumed that you
could achieve average 6.5 percent returns from a fixed-income
portfolio with a mild smattering of stocks -- a portfolio very much
like the one you now hold.
</P>
<P>
   Let s suppose your current savings of $226,000 achieves that 6.5
percent target over the next decade; its value would then be
$428,011, nicely above the target figure. Moreover, that figure
doesn t include the effect of any ongoing savings you might make,
or of continuing contributions to your husband s 401(k) program.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do those figures it include that $30,000 that you re
thinking of investing more aggressively. I have long noticed a
frequent common denominator in my mailbag -- that people who feel,
correctly or not, that they ve waited too long to focus directly on
retirement are most prone to make mistakes; just at the time they
should be beginning to reduce risk they want to crank it up in
hopes of catching up.
</P>
<P>
   As I outlined above, you are in a good position to meet your
target of having $25,000 income to supplement your pension and
Social Security. So what remains for you to worry about is the
effect of inflation on your income stream after retirement. For
that reason I suggest this: Treat your current portfolio (plus the
401(k) as your primary retirement pool, and keep it invested
substantially as it is. Then take that $30,000 account and treat
that as your inflation-fighting account. Given your current
portfolio, I m not going to suggest anything more aggressive than
you now have. The most volatile (and most potentially rewarding)
segment of your current portfolio is the holding in Vanguard
Wellington, a balanced fund that has a little more than 62 percent
of its portfolio in stocks and the rest in bonds and other
fixed-income issues. This fund has a long and excellent record,
easily demonstrating the summary of Morningstar Mutual Funds --
above-average, with average returns and below-average risk. But don
t jump in all at once. If you ve read this column very often, you
know I m very jumpy about the current market. Therefore I suggest
you employ a discipline called dollar cost averaging. For example,
you might initially put $833 of the money into Wellington, moving
the balance to Vanguard s Prime Money Market fund. You could then
instruct Vanguard to move a similar amount into Wellington each
month. If we presume average 5 percent returns from the money
market, this would spread the investment period out over the course
of 36 months, and the slow process of establishing your investment
would reduce the carnage if the market took a spill at some point
during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if all goes according to schedule, you won t have to think
about that money when you retire. You ll have your other funds to
supplement your pension and Social Security. It s another 10 years
down the road that you re worried about -- when inflation will have
cut the buying power of the pension, and when that $25,000
supplement isn t doing so well either. That s when you can look to
the pool you established in Wellington for help. And if you
achieved average 10 percent returns from this pool over those 20
years (and I think this is a reasonable expectation, even counting
in the current markets and the dollar-cost- averaging hedge at the
beginning) it would amount to $201,824 -- a nice present for
yourselves on the tin anniversary of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What suggestion do you have for someone 38 years old who is
inheriting $10,000 and who wants to retire well? Where to put the
money to keep it multiplying fast but safely?
</P>
<P>
   S.D., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. When you re 25 years or so away from retirement, the question
of safety becomes relative; it s such a long investment time frame
that what would seem like a fairly risky vehicle over any four- or
five-year period becomes a great deal less risky. I m speaking, of
course, about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But before we get into considering the thousands of possible
market investments, it s better to begin by thinking about taxes.
If you simply bought a stock, or shares of a mutual fund, you would
face potential tax bills during each of those 25 or so years --
every time you got a dividend, or swapped stock holdings, or got a
capital gains distributions (if you chose a mutual fund), Uncle
would have his hand out. If you qualify for to open an IRA, I
suggest you put $8,000 of the money into a money market mutual fund
and the other $2,000 into a Roth IRA invested in Vanguard Index 500
portfolio -- a mutual fund which seeks to duplicate the results of
the Standard and Poor s 500 Index, which tracks the nation s
largest 500 companies. Each year as you become eligible to do so,
move another $2,000 into the Roth IRA. The result? By the time you
re 65 years old you should have $109,365, a calculation that
presumes 5 percent returns from the money market fund for the six
years during which you will have the account in existence, and 10
percent average annual returns from the Index 500 fund. Obviously,
$109,365 isn t enough to allow anybody to retire well, but it sure
wouldn t hurt, would it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
