<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-12 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET CAN HELP INFLATION-PROOF A RETIREMENT FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Long Beach and all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 57 and 53. I make $77,000 a year and she
earns $100,000. We would like to retire in three years and have a
retirement income of $6,000 per month. We have checked with Social
Security and both of us will be qualified for benefits at nearly
the highest level. With the information below, how close can we
come to achieving our goal? We own three houses, worth $315,000,
$95,000 and $82,000; we have four mutual fund accounts totaling
$159,500. We have two late-model cars worth $30,000, and I own
$200,000 worth of S stock in the small company where I work, which
can take out over a 10-year-period.
</P>
<P>
   N.B., Beaverton, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is going to be a little iffy, since some of the values
appear (at least to me) to be imprecise. But one things does seems
clear to me -- you re pretty far away from a comfortable retirement
along the lines you propose. If we add up all of your assets
(except the cars, which as you know represent a fast- depreciating
asset,) I come up with a grand total of $851,500. Since you wouldn
t be eligible for Social Security until two years after you retire,
and your wife not until three years after that, let s start with
what it takes to generate a $72,000 annual income stream. If we
presume a 6.5 percent income stream from a retirement portfolio,
the number would be a little more than $1.1 million. Now of course
you might decide that you wouldn t need quite that much, since you
could dip into principal in the early years of retirement and then
begin rebuilding your savings after Social Security kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   But there s also the question of that S corporation stock. Does
the stock pay dividends? Or would your sale simply represent a
contract under which you were entitled to $20,000 a year for 10
years, or perhaps $1,666 a month. If such is the case you might,
with the sale of some of the real estate, be able to work out a
plan to take you through those 10 years -- but at that point your
finances would fall off the table.
</P>
<P>
   Here s where I end up: If you were to sell the two lesser-valued
real estate parcels and add the proceeds to your current mutual
fund portfolio, the total would be $336,500 -- enough, if invested
in a fixed-income portfolio, to produce $1,822 a month. If you were
to use your $1,666 a month from your company stock for living
expenses during the first two years, that would mean withdrawals of
$4,333 a month from that pool, and your principal would fall to
$271,115 by the time your Social Security kicked in. Let s suppose
that during the next three years you were to then cut withdrawals
to $2,733 a month. The result is that by the time your wife s
Social Security eligibility begins you would be down to $219,449 in
principal and you would have used up half of the money from your
company stock. It s a position from which you would not recover.
You might manage to stay near that $6,000 monthly level for the
next five years, but when the last payment from the company stkck
arrived, you d be cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Blacker still, none of these calculations take inflation into
consideration. A rough rule of thumb is that a people have a nice
degree of financial security in retirement if they have two sides
ing expenses, and a $275,000 growth portfolio designed to protect
you from inflation in later years.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to be such a grouch, but at bottom the only advice I can
propose is, first, to save like mad until you do retire, and
second, consider whether you might not be better off in the long
run if you deferred retirement a few more years than you now plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I m 64, single, and retired last year. I have pensions from
two companies totaling $23,000 a year and $12,000 from Social
Security. My IRAs consist of $100,000 in Fidelity Growth and Income
fund, $50,000 in a Fidelity money market fund,, and $50,000 in a CD
currently paying 5.75 percent. Non-IRA investments consist of
$25,000 in AARP Capital Growth fund $50,000 in AARP Growth and
Income, and $25,000 in a CD paying 6.08 percent. The pension and
Social Security money currently provides for all my needs, and
income from investments is reinvested, with the occasional
withdrawal for overseas travel.
</P>
<P>
   However, the pensions are fixed, and buying power will suffer in
the event of inflation. Further, I have reservations about the bull
market continuing. I had consisted selling Fidelity Growth and
Income and the AARP funds and buying bond funds, but this would
leave me paying capital gains taxes on the AARP funds. What do you
suggest?
</P>
<P>
   B.H., Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can understand your nervousness about the market, but I
think you may be going too far. As a recent retiree, one of your
major concerns should be protecting yourself against the ravages of
inflation in the later years of your retirement, and unless you
have a terrific amount of money, the stock market is certainly the
best bet. If you were to move most of the $100,000 of IRA money
that s now in Fidelity Growth and Income fund to the fixed- income
side, the two AARP stock funds would represent only 25 percent of
your retirement savings, and especially since you re not counting
on any of these savings for a day-to-day income stream, I suggest
you stay put with them. One reason for this is that it s almost
impossible to time the market; if you get out now and you re like
most investors, you ll probably mis-time your re-entry, and the
worst part of such mis-timing is that people tend to come in too
late, missing the first few heady days or weeks of the next bull
market.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason, of course, is that I assume you hate paying
taxes as much as the rest of us do, and there s no way to exit from
the two AARP holdings without tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that I suggested you move most of the money from Fidelity
Growth and Income. As I m sure you know, that excellent fund is now
closed to new investors; therefore I suggest you leave the door
ajar, leaving the minimum required to hold your account open. This
would allow you to restore your investment in this fund should you
become more comfortable with the market in the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My grandchildren have shares of Lindner Growth Investors fund
in trust accounts. The results have been poor, with changes of
managers, etc. Should we wait for a hopeful improvement or sell? If
we sell, where should we put the proceeds?
</P>
<P>
   M.K., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the last management change at Lindner Growth Investors
came late last year, and it s hard to see any improvement since.
Entering this week, year-to-date figures for the fund showed an 8.1
percent loss, which puts it in the bottom quartile of the small-cap
value fund arena. The average small-cap value fund had a 3.3
percent loss year-to-date, and even the top quartile wasn t getting
anywhere, showing an average return of precisely -- nothing. Do you
blame it on a tough market sector and wait a little longer of do
you head for the doors?
</P>
<P>
   Let s look at the longer record. Over three years the fund had
average annual gains of 8.1 percent, comparing unfavorably to a
peer average of 17.5 percent. Its last above- average performance,
according to Morningstar Mutual funds, came in 1994 (and it lost
money that year, albeit losing a bit less than its peers).
Mornignstar rates it below average overall -- above-average for
risk, low for performance. Yes -- that s enough; I d dump it.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative investment, if you want to stay in the
small-cap arena (and if your grandchildren are at least 10 years
away from college age) I d suggest Vanguard Small-Cap Index. If
they re older than that, I d look at a balanced fund such as
Vanguard Balanced Index. And if you want to stay within the Lindner
family, Lindner Dividend Investor seems to me to be its strongest
offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
