<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORMICA-LANDMARK-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHRINE TO PLASTIC LAMINATES _ WHO'D HAVE THOUGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (lb) 
 By BARBARA FLANAGAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows what decorative laminate is. That's the plastic
stuff renovators rip out when they restore a historic house.
</P>
<P>
   But take note. It's none other than those garish old plastic
laminates, circa 1959, that have just qualified the Ralph Sr. and
Sunny Wilson House, in Texas, for a plaque from the National Park
Service. At this rate, today's aqua vanity is destined to become
tomorrow's Victorian mantel: a period piece invariably trashed by
insensitive modernizers, and then painstakingly rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the National Register of Historic Places _ the
official federal list of districts, buildings and objects that best
exemplify American culture _ bestowed landmark status on the Wilson
house, a local shrine to the heritage of high-pressure plastic
laminate, often called Formica.
</P>
<P>
   But Formica this house is not. Ralph Wilson Sr., the late
founder of Wilsonart International, now the United States' largest
producer of decorative laminates, built the 3,000-square-foot model
home in Temple, Texas, about 100 miles northeast of Austin, as an
experimental showcase for Ralph Wilson Plastics.
</P>
<P>
   Together with his daughter, Bonnie, he drew up the plans and
masterminded the extensive use of pink, turquoise, lemon, pumpkin,
glitter, marble and maple laminates as alternatives to conventional
building materials: drywall, wallpaper, paint, wood, ceramic tile
and linoleum.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, laminates were used mostly on horizontal surfaces _
tables and counters. Wilson plastic-laminated most of the rest of
his house: the kitchen and bath cabinets, the shower stalls and
most of the walls, which were made of a special grade of plastic
that replaced the standard Sheetrock.
</P>
<P>
   The doorless garage of the Wilson house served as lab within a
lab. There Wilson covered the walls with new grades of laminate,
using the open garage to test his products' ability to withstand
the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most model houses, which are built for marketing and then
dismantled, Wilson actually lived in the house, monitoring the
laminates until his death. His widow, Sunny, lived there until she
sold the house to the company two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   How did preservationists discover this anomaly _ a trove of
historic laminate gone ungutted for 40 years? During demolition, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Wilsonart had hired Grace Jeffers, a New York art historian and
Formica expert (and the daughter of a Formica salesman), to help
build its corporate archives. Ms. Jeffers visited the house by
chance, and then avidly pursued its preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was in Texas, some company people were making fun of
the house,'' she said. ``They told me, `For a hoot, let's go over
to the founder's house because they're gutting the interior today.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into the house,'' she continued, ``I couldn't
breathe. I've been looking at laminates forever, and this was the
most stellar example. My eyes were all glassy and blinky, and I
said, `You can't hurt this!'''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some scholars, Ms. Jeffers believes it is the Wilson
house _ not the Formica House at the 1964 World's Fair _ that
pioneered the lavish use of plastic laminates. After being turned
down by the Brooklyn Museum of Art to add part of the Wilson house
to its collection of period rooms, Ms. Jeffers finally asked
Wilsonart, ``Why don't you just let me save the whole house?''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that the house was a superb example of midcentury
modern architecture, with its open floor plan directly inspired by
the experimental Case Study Houses of California, Ms. Jeffers
persuaded the company to buy, renovate and furnish the house, to
turn the bedrooms into the company archives and to open the house
to public tours.
</P>
<P>
   Tours, by appointment only, are to start in November;
information will be available after Oct. 15 at (254) 773-9898.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Through her documentation, Ms. Jeffers convinced the National
Register that the house was nationally significant. Working with
horticultural consultants, she restored the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifties landscaping had a lot in common with '50s interiors,''
she said. ``All the textures and the nubbiness of things like
grasses and Scandinavian rugs.'' The period landscape includes
yucca, pampas, liriope, mimosa, Chinese holly, irises and calla
lilies, plus peach and pecan trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house has become the company mascot,'' Ms. Jeffers said.
``We had no idea the project would take on these proportions. But
the company sees itself as a family, and the house has become a
symbol of community for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Wilde, an office worker at Wilsonart whose father has been
with the company for 40 years, thinks the house inspires pride in
the products. (The retro ``Brady Bunch'' style, she noted, is
``already coming back.'') Ms. Wilde said that the Wilson house
embodied a truism: ``What's ugly to one person is beautiful to
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
