<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAW-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW FESTIVAL: RECONSTRUCTING A BYGONE ELITE AND ITS FOLLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIAGARA-ON-THE-LAKE, Ontario _ Swelter-as-you-stroll season has
descended on the muggy streets of this unlikely summer theater
mecca on Lake Ontario, just over the Canadian border. Yet inside
the town's playhouses, a perennial chilliness prevails, and it has
nothing to do with the efficiency of the climate control.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's the plays occupying the theaters of the Shaw Festival,
an ambitious operation that has been presenting the works of George
Bernard Shaw and his contemporaries for 36 years, that are
responsible for a certain pervasive coolness.
</P>
<P>
   Bound by a singular mission _ producing only plays written
during Shaw's long (1856-1950) lifetime _ the festival, with eight
major shows in repertory on three stages, specializes in a style of
well-upholstered drama, primarily British in origin, that was a
mainstay of the theatrical times in which Shaw lived.
</P>
<P>
   These plays, by Shaw and Wilde, John Galsworthy and Christopher
Fry, are well-suited to the gold-plated settings the festival
favors, lavish, impeccably designed affairs that unfold with
everything but a royal warrant: tea services that would not look
out of place in the display windows of Asprey, fur-ruffed overcoats
inspired by the likes of Cecil Beaton.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reassurance in the plushness _ all the trouble
they've gone to! _ and a danger of irrelevance, too. For as you sit
through your third drawing room comedy or well-made social drama in
as many days, waiting for a tertiary character named Morrison or
Rose or Parker to announce the duchess or clear the silver or light
his lordship's cigar, your patience with the theater of the
absurdly wealthy can wear a little thin. You find yourself caring
less and less whether Lady Pompom runs off with Sir Brylcreem. You
long for a clear view out the gleaming mansion windows, for a
glimpse of what else might be going on in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Shaw does not limit itself to the British upper crust _
Kaufman and Hart's ``You Can't Take It With You,'' for instance, is
among the season's mainstage offerings _ but it's clear in the
sheer volume of depictions of the leisure classes (in Wilde's
``Lady Windermere's Fan,'' Shaw's ``Major Barbara,'' Galsworthy's
``Joy'' and Fry's ``The Lady's Not for Burning'') that the
festival's designers and directors enjoy standing on ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   And in its best presentations, like a lyrical, ravishing version
of ``Lady's Windermere's Fan,'' distinguished by Fiona Reid's
fascinating Mrs. Erlynne and an ornate carousel of a set by William
Schmuck that spins in two directions, the company succeeds in
adding beguiling new flavors to a genre that at times is as hard to
swallow as week-old oysters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Windermere's Fan,'' in the skillful hands of the Shaw's
English-born artistic director, Christopher Newton, reveals itself
as more than a showcase for droll repartee. The 1892 comedy,
Wilde's first London triumph, can seem a rather severe yet
rewarding morality play, as it reflects on the scandalous choices
made by Mrs. Erlynne, who abandoned an illegitimate daughter at
birth, a character and incident based, incidentally, on the
playwright's great friend, the socialite and actress Lillie
Langtry.
</P>
<P>
   It also skims the surface of tragedy: Newton's production
positions Lady Windermere (the lovely Colombe Demers) and her
husband (Ben Carlson) as the rich, stately partners in an enchanted
marriage whose spell is broken with the arrival of the mysterious
Mrs. Erlynne and her legacy of desertion.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the play grows more rueful with the piling up of
secrets and suspicions that define its emotional fault lines and a
rigid moral and social code that Wilde deplores. ``Between men and
women there is no friendship possible,'' declares Lady Windermere's
suitor-in-waiting, Lord Darlington (the persuasive Gordon Rand).
``There is passion, enmity, worship, love, but no friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reid's portrayal of the play's pivotal character _ whether
she will disclose her identity to her daughter, and what the
decision reveals about her, are the evening's most intriguing
questions _ proves to be the play's bridge to that world outside
the mansion windows.
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial because of all the fancy people who waltz across
Wilde's marbled foyers, only Mrs. Erlynne speaks with true
authority, a conviction forged in a real world of risk and loss.
With the casual, careworn bearing of one who fully grasps but does
not necessarily regret her youthful folly, Ms. Reid is, as Wilde
intended, a breath of fresh air, a self-possessed (and Ibsen-esque)
harbinger of modernity, blowing through the musty aristocratic
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Windermere's Fan'' is the best reason for the trip to
Niagara-on-the-Lake, where the Shaw entertains about 300,000
theatergoers each year from April to November. Its focus on 100
years of plays, from mid-century to mid-century, gives it a unique
raison d'etre and helps to distinguish it from its better-known
rival, the Shakespeare-centric Stratford Festival in Stratford,
Ontario. And if a smooth and sumptuous version of the Wilde play
shows the Shaw off to best advantage, a few of its other offerings,
though solidly produced, underline some of the pitfalls in the
constraints imposed on play selection.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the well-known works it presents at its large house,
the Festival Theater, the Shaw Festival offers an assortment of
obscurer plays in two smaller theaters, across from each other on
the town's main thoroughfare of 1950s charm, Picton Street.
</P>
<P>
   While some are neglected mini-classics and other curiosities,
they are all lovingly attended to: ``Waterloo,'' Sir Arthur Conan
Doyle's one-act play, now in previews, about an elderly veteran of
the famous battle in which Napoleon was defeated, is notable both
for its author and its performances. Still, in some instances, the
productions only cement the plays' less-than-stellar reputations.
There's a reason, it turns out, many of these plays are not revived
more often.
</P>
<P>
   The works of the period do not lend themselves easily to
reinterpretation; what you are left with in plays like ``Joy,''
Galsworthy's arcadian slice of upper-class life, circa 1907, are
earnest reconstructions, with recordings of birdsong added. It's
theater of the mildest sort, not deadly theater, but not completely
alive either. ``Joy'' concerns the sexual and emotional awakening
of an 18-year-old girl, convincingly played by Severn Thompson, on
an afternoon of faint intrigue in a, yes, sumptuous English garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy'' may have been jarringly realistic 90-odd years ago. But
today, regardless of how astute its character studies seem, the
genteel pacing turns it into a dreamplay, a trivial exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lady's Not for Burning,'' while set in the year 1400, was
written in the 1940s, and at the Shaw Festival plays like another
drawing-room comedy. It's easy to see how London audiences,
benumbed by decades of a compulsion to chronicle the private lives
of the privileged, would have been shocked out of their seats by
the plays of John Osborne and the other angry young men who burst
on the scene in the 1950s. From gentlemen in starched collars to a
lout in his underwear!
</P>
<P>
   The Shaw Festival could not exist without the plays of its
namesake; this season, the presentation is ``Major Barbara,'' which
receives a beautifully designed if workmanlike revival under the
direction of Helena Kaut-Howson. No performance is unfortunate, and
Joel Hechter, as the effete son of an amoral arms maker, and Bill
Walker, as a downtrodden bully who challenges Major Barbara (Kelli
Fox) to a Salvation Army showdown, bring an active creative force
to their supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   But as demonstrated by Schmuck's zanily effective sci-fi
rendering of Undershaft's munitions works, there's a lot more
scenery happening here than anything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
