<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORRISON WOULD BE RIGHT AT HOME HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday Aug. 14)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I read in Time magazine that officials at Pere-Lachaise cemetery
in Paris (France, not Texas), tired of picking up beer cans and
condoms left behind by mourners, have decided to disinter the
remains of Jim Morrison, the late lead singer of the Doors, when
the 30-year lease on his grave expires on July 6, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made as to where the Lizard King should be
reburied, which is why I am putting in my nomination early for
Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota has a lot of things going for it as a final resting
place for drugged-out rock stars, not the least of which is an
abundance of cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the all-important local connection. Morrison was
born in Melbourne, a Sarasota-wannabe city located on Florida's
dreary East Coast, and he spent a year in junior college in St.
Petersburg, a suburb of Sarasota and home of the Sarasota Devil
Rays. (Morrison was preoccupied with the themes of evil and death,
so the ``devil'' part is another selling point for Sarasota.)
</P>
<P>
   Morrison was the son of a military officer, an occupation that
is heavily represented among Sarasota's retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison is currently buried in France. For several years,
Sarasota hosted the French Film Festival. Coincidence? I hardly
think so.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Morrison's Cafeteria in Sarasota Square Mall.
</P>
<P>
   There are 67 listings under the name ``Morrison'' in the
Sarasota phone directory.
</P>
<P>
   Several copies of books written by Toni Morrison can be found in
the new Selby Library in downtown Sarasota, assuming they haven't
been stolen, checked out or banned.
</P>
<P>
   A quick check of some random quotes and song lyrics by Jim
Morrison further convinces me that Sarasota deserves to be his
final resting place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning and I got myself a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   This lyric should resonate among Sarasota's retirees, some of
whom nip at a rate well above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may eat your chicken
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat your pork and beans
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat more chicken
</P>
<P>
   ``Than any man ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if Sarasotans have one of the highest per capita
chicken-consumption rates of anyplace in the country, but I do know
that we eat a heck of a lot of chicken. At least I do, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a killer on the road
</P>
<P>
   ``His brain is squirmin' like a toad.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the driving habits of Sarasotans, many have brains
that squirm like toads once they get behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of myself as an intelligent, sensitive human with the
soul of a clown.''
</P>
<P>
   This sentiment fits in nicely with Sarasota's circus heritage,
though Morrison's behavior, which included exposing himself
onstage, the symbolic slaughter of a sheep and jumping drunk out of
windows, diverges rather sharply from traditional clown acts, which
consist mostly of squirting flowers and goofy unicycle riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of hooked to the game of art and literature; my
heroes were artists and writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota is lousy with artists and writers to the point that you
can hardly throw your morning beer can out the window without
smacking one upside the head. In short, it is Jim Morrison's kind
of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of us as erotic politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota could certainly use some erotic politicians. After all,
why should Washington, D.C., have all the fun?
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
