<HEADLINE>
SCORCHING TEXAS SUMMER FRIES OUTDOOR ENTERTAINMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In terms of quality and vitality, Fort Worth's Shakespeare in
the Park was hot this year. Its stagings of ``Henry V'' and ``As
You Like It'' earned high numbers artistically.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the weather was also hot. Higher numbers on the
thermometer meant that fewer people ventured out to Trinity Park to
see the plays.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth actors did not scorch alone. With the exception of
Waxahachie's Scarborough Faire _ whose closing date of June 14
enabled it to avoid the heat wave _ outdoor entertainment entities
in most parts of Texas suffered from this summer's onslaught of
three-digit temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Some fought back. Water misters and electric fans have been
installed at Hip Pocket Theatre _ where, in her welcoming talk,
producer Diane Simons reminds audiences that they'll be wearing
coats and jackets when they attend the October season finale.
</P>
<P>
   The Tablerock Festival in Salado passed out fans and sold ``cool
collars'' for audience members to wear around their necks. Concerts
in the Garden in Fort Worth cooled off symphony players by waiving
the dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Most just toughed it out.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Shakespeare season that ran from June 10 to July
12 drew 9,200 people, compared with 11,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a devastating year,'' said executive director
Robert Fass. ``But we did take a beating from the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Brothers in the Bard, the Shakespeare Festival of Dallas, played
to a season total of 71,500 in Samuell-Grand Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was down about 22,000 from last year,'' said Sandra
Greenway, acting director of marketing and development.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Shakespeare does not charge admission. But it still took
a hit financially, because smaller crowds meant lower sales of
refreshments and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much cooler when the sun went down,'' said Greenway.
``But it was hard to convince people of that when the `Dallas
Morning News' had the heat death toll on the front page every
morning, and TV stations led off with the heat wave every
evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance was down at the Fort Worth Symphony's Concerts in the
Garden. This series of 16 performances, over four long weekends
between June 11 and July 5 in the Fort Worth Botanic Garden,
featured music ranging from the ``nuclear polka'' of Brave Combo to
Beethoven's Ninth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody is wearing black armbands at the symphony office _
perhaps because in a time of potential disaster, survival is a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Koonsman, executive director of the symphony, uses terms
such as ``extremely fortunate'' and ``great success'' when
assessing the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got this loyal group of patrons who turn out _ rain or
shine, sleet, hail, whatever,'' Koonsman said. ``Our numbers were
down. We had over 45,000 last year, and we had 38,000 this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One visible casualty of the heat was the symphony players'
normally dapper attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything in our power to combat the heat for
musicians on stage,'' said Koonsman. ``We brought in electric fans,
we put coolers of bottled water on stage, and we pretty much tossed
aside our normal dress code _ which is black slacks and skirts and
white shirts and blouses. This summer, many of the musicians wore
shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   At least these organizations' heat troubles are over. Some
performance venues are still watching the thermometer nervously.
</P>
<P>
   On July 10, Hip Pocket Theatre opened ``Fatty in Babylon'' in
the 175-seat Oak Acres amphitheater at 1620 Las Vegas Trail N.
Attendance at the previous show _ Eugene Ionesco's absurdist
classic ``The Rhinoceros'' _ caught the brunt of the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ran July 10 through Aug. 2,'' said producer Simons.
``That's pretty much the time frame of the worst heat. Our crowds
were down. But, strangely, not every night. We had some very good
houses late in the run. Our director, John Moore, thinks they just
got cabin fever and wanted to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new to Hip Pocket, which has staged plays
outdoors in the summer for more than two decades. In the benchmark
broiling summer of 1980, for example, the hardy Hipsters performed
``Captive Wild Women,'' which featured a campfire on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Godly subject matter does not guarantee heavenly weather. The
religious pageant ``The Promise,'' which runs through October at
the Texas Amphitheatre outside Glen Rose, has watched its crowds
diminish during the summer. David Sanders, president of Promise
Productions, wasn't available at press time. But an unidentified
staffer, when asked if ``The Promise'' had experienced lower
attendance due to the extreme heat, said: ``Common sense will tell
you that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smith/Ritch Point Theatre near Ingram, in the Texas Hill
Country, is currently featuring ``The Music Man'' on its open-air
stage along the Guadalupe River bank. The show runs through Aug.
29, with former Fort Worth actor/composer Douglas Balentine in the
title role. Crowds are good, but they probably would be better
under normal weather circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling about 60 percent of our seats,'' said Bruce
Bicknell, executive director of the Hill Country Arts Foundation,
parent organization of the theater. ``Without this heat, we'd be
selling 70 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tablerock Festival performs the historical musical drama
``Salado Legends'' every year in Salado _ south of Fort Worth
between Waco and Austin. This year's shows were July 18, July 25
and Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have three performances,'' said playwright and board
President Jackie Mills. ``So we were very conscious of how the heat
affected our attendance. Crowds were down the first two shows.
People were saying they wanted to wait and see if it got cooler. It
didn't. So they all came to the last show. We can seat 450 in our
amphitheater, but somehow we got 494 in for that performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we're not the only ones affected by the heat. I
spoke with the Institute of Outdoor Drama. They say theaters are
complaining about the heat all over Texas _ except in El Paso,
where they say: `What else is new?' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Perry Stewart is the Star-Telegram theater critic. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/
</P>
</TEXT>
