<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN LAWMAKERS CONSIDER EXCEPTIONS FOR TOUGH GUN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican lawmakers are poised to relax strict laws
on the importation of firearms that could mean the early release of
dozens of Americans now held in prisons on gun charges.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, part of a wide-ranging package of reforms to
Mexico's firearms law proposed by President Ernesto Zedillo, has
already passed the Senate, and congressional sources say it stands
a good chance in the Chamber of Deputies, which is expected to
begin negotiations on it next month.
</P>
<P>
   While the package of reforms would not repeal the stringent
gun-control laws, it would grant a one-time exception to those who
live outside Mexico and who inadvertently bring a gun or ammunition
into the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the exception would not apply when the gun or ammunition
involved is specifically reserved for the use of the Mexican police
or military.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than facing a stiff prison sentence, those found with a
weapon or ammunition would pay an administrative fine of less than
$1,000 and be allowed to return to the United States with the gun
and/or ammunition, said Sen. Alvaro Vallarta Cecena, of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about people who have committed an error rather
than a crime,'' Vallarta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should understand that we should not allow injustices
to occur with someone who inadvertently leaves his gun under his
seat or a couple of boxes of ammunition in his trunk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial sources say that, if passed, such a law would apply
retroactively, allowing many of the more than 80 Americans now
jailed here on gun charges to apply for early release.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush raised the subject with his Mexican
counterparts at the Border Governors' Conference in Brownsville
last month. Bush urged the Mexican governors to support a lessening
of the penalty for those who were forgetful or ignorant of Mexican
law.
</P>
<P>
   The federal firearms law of 1972 permits civilians licensed by
the Mexican military to carry semi-automatic pistols and ammunition
up to 9mm, ``with the exception of .38 caliber Super ..., .38
caliber Comando ... and 9mm Mauser, Luger, Parabellum and Comando,
and similar models manufactured by other makers.''
</P>
<P>
   It also permits licensed civilians to carry revolvers up to
.38-caliber Special and ammunition, ``with the exception of .357
Magnum.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who live in rural areas are permitted to carry .22-caliber
rifles and up to .12-gauge shotguns with normal barrels, the law
states. Licensed hunters also are allowed semi-automatic rifles and
ammunition up to 7.62mm or .30 caliber
</P>
<P>
   All other weapons are reserved for the police or the military.
</P>
<P>
   Those carrying a .45 caliber or 9mm pistol or an M-16 rifle
would not be eligible for the one-time exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Under present law, unless importation permits are presented at
the time a foreign resident crosses the border, anyone found
carrying any firearm or ammunition by Mexican Customs officials can
be charged with smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities have tightened the application of such laws
with the rise of violent drug-smuggling cartels and the advent of
guerrilla movements in several states since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, including at least one Texas law enforcement
officer, have been arrested crossing the Mexican border and charged
with carrying guns and ammunition they are legally permitted to
carry in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, jail sentences of more than 5 years have been
imposed for as little as one or two boxes of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The reform package sailed through the Senate, dominated by
Zedillo's PRI.
</P>
<P>
   But certain aspects of the whole package face opposition in the
Chamber of Deputies, controlled by a majority of opposition
parties, said Juan Carlos Gutierrez Fragoso, from the conservative
National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we will have to call in (Zedillo's)
representatives to negotiate out certain points,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think that there is anyone who is opposed
specifically to that part of the initiative,'' he said of the
one-time forgiveness provision.
</P>
<P>
   If the law is passed, those already serving sentences would have
to petition the Interior Ministry for early release, an official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
