<SLUG> BC-BED-DESIGN-ART-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEADBOARD COMES OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bed has gone to its head.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional, boatlike bed that saw you through life's
journey _ from birth to death, from stem to stern, from side to
side _ is becoming a more minimal platform for modern living. It is
now basically a flat barge for layered bed linens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no trend more dominant right now than the clean,
casual lifestyle collections _ modern, midcentury furnishings _
that lend themselves to trimmer, leaner beds,'' said Brian Carroll,
an editor of Furniture Today, an industry journal, who covers the
case-goods market, which includes beds. ``The duvet dresses the
bed. If you want a design statement, it's the headboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready to seize the moment, the headboard is grabbing the
spotlight and going solo. From couture-end home-furnishing
designers like Dakota Jackson, Vicente Wolf for Casa Bique and
Christian Liaigre for Holly Hunt to mass-market retailers like
Pottery Barn and Spiegel, the headboard is being sold on its own,
as an option for the bed, and making itself widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Independent of the bedding, the headboard has become its own
piece of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bilhuber, a New York decorator, designed a large
three-panel lacquered wood headboard for a young New York architect
and his wife. It stands freely like a low, monumental wall at the
head of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the bed the ability to float in the room,'' Bilhuber
said. ``In New York there often isn't even a headboard wall
available, or there's a radiator under the window.'' Bilhuber's
headboard, which he now sells by special order, hides the radiator
in the bedroom it was designed for.
</P>
<P>
   With the headboard's new popularity, the choices of materials
are proliferating stylishly _ from John Hutton's wrapped wicker
Merbau for Donghia to Barbara Barry's cream-colored leather for
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Large furniture manufacturers like Ethan Allen and Stickley
offer headboards without beds, as do smaller companies like John
Kelly Furniture Design, Park Furniture and Ted Boerner Furniture
Design. Purchased separately, headboards are less expensive _
generally 50 percent to 60 percent of the cost of full beds.
</P>
<P>
   Artists like Stephen Whisler, a New York sculptor, are
investigating the headboard as billboard, with furniture works like
his ``Thought and Speech'' headboard _ a maple plywood panel with
cartoon cut-outs of a thought bubble and a speech bubble, each
above its respective side of a bed _ a different kind of design
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems in a relationship that one does the talking
and the other one does the thinking,'' Whisler said.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the headboard is as much of a bed as is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to use a headboard than find the right bed,'' said
Christopher Coleman, a New York decorator. ``Nobody uses a
footboard anymore. Most mattress companies give you a frame; you
just screw it on. It takes up less room, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend for statement headboards has been given a healthy push
by recent ``boutique hotel'' designs. William Sofield of Studio
Sofield has, by his estimate, designed more than 50, including
headboards for the SoHo Grand in New York and a woven leather and
gun-metal headboard for the Hard Rock Cafe Hotel in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels know that headboards work well in tight spaces, to
enhance decor and enable the bed to be used as a sitting surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the back of a sofa,'' said Christian Liaigre. ``The
feeling that one can sit and watch television or take breakfast.''
Liaigre designed two models for a recent project, the Mercer Hotel
in New York, including a low, linen-upholstered headboard based on
an English wing chair, that gently embraces the head of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It protects people when they sleep,'' he said. ``It's very
psychological.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Murphy, the vice president of Parish-Hadley Associates in
New York, found a more pragmatic reason for the popularity of
headboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The king-size mania,'' he said. ``Even single people want a
king-size bed, which is really an ungainly shape. To do a
four-poster bed, for instance, you have to have a very high ceiling
to make it look at all elegant. Instead, you do a beautifully
shaped headboard, in a beautiful fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   King-size beds also complicate the issue for those who would
wish for a handsome antique. There aren't a lot of wonderful
antique beds that are large. ``I personally prefer sleeping in a
king-size bed,'' William Sofield said. ``But you're faced with few
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Sofield designed a headboard for himself. ``An extremely
built-in one,'' he explained, with compartments ``like `In' and
`Out' boxes, to organize myself. The bed is where I spend my few
waking hours at home _ taking notes for the next day, last-minute
ideas before I go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the headboard is a straightforward solution to
stylistic confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at all these different beds; I wanted something clean
and peaceful,'' recalled Martha McCully, the beauty director of
Allure magazine, of shopping for furniture for her house in East
Hampton, N.Y. ``A lot of older beds are fantasy-oriented. I got
sick of seeing carved, painted wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCully designed her own headboard instead _ a simple slab
of polished mahogany, which she had made at Richomme, a custom
furniture fabricator on Vestry Street in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. McCully, the 47-inch high, queen-size headboard is also
a kind of vertical desk. She sits against it, with a laptop
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm writing a book,'' she said. ``This is how I've worked for
the last six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Custom headboards are not news to decorators; they are an
important tool of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``By designing a headboard, the bed can become a continuation of
the architecture of the room,'' said Christine Cain, a senior
associate at Jed Johnson and Associates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
