<SLUG> BC-BEANIEBOWL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves latest team to undertake Beanie Baby craze
 &HT;    Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the craziest buzz around the Atlanta Braves since Andruw
Jones got a bad haircut.
</P>
<P>
   And it's all about Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The switchboard has been ringing off the hook, and we've been
getting hit pretty hard with e-mails,'' said Miles McRea, the
team's senior director of promotions.
</P>
<P>
   It all started three weeks ago when the team announced it would
be giving away the Beanie Baby ``Chip the Cat'' to the first 12,000
youngsters who attend Wednesday's Braves game with the San
Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the team has sold another 10,000 tickets. On
Wednesday, the game was about 5,000 seats short of a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise to Braves and league officials, who have seen
Beanie Babies become one of the biggest draws in Major League
Baseball this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen teams have had Beanie Baby giveaways, and they've
been a phenomenal success,'' said Mark Gorris, MLB's vice president
of team services.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average they've boosted attendance between 10,000 and
12,000 a game.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure they'd get into games before all the dolls were
snapped up, Beanie-crazed fans have camped overnight at stadium
gates. ``I was at a Texas Rangers game last week, and people were
in a line that went around the stadium three times,'' said Lori
Tomnitz, spokeswoman for Ty Inc., the maker of Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Braves officials say fans need not camp out by Turner Field. If
the 12,000 dolls are taken, they can tap an extra supply.
</P>
<P>
   The clamor for Chip the Cat comes despite the fact that the same
doll has been on sale for about $5 in stores for two years. Braves
officials are keeping their stash in ``safekeeping'' at an
undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will limit the giveaways of Chip to youths 14 or
younger. ``They're not for adults,'' said McRae. ``This is a
promotion to get kids to come to games.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the dolls, kids will get an enlarged baseball
card of Braves's First Baseman Andres ``Big Cat'' Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   The team has scheduled a second Beanie Baby night for Sept. 2,
when the Braves play the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
