<HEADER>
A0705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BED-DESIGN-ART-2NDTAK     08-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BED-DESIGN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and Associates.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition to strengthening decorative motifs or composition,
upholstered headboards are an opportunity to introduce fabrics or
unusual materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love things that are soft behind the head,'' said Keller
Donovan, a New York decorator who uses upholstered headboards
almost exclusively. ``Headboard fabric is another way of bringing
color and pattern into a room; it creates a focal point.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Mindel, a New York architect with Shelton, Mindel and
Associates, has used chenille on a custom headboard for a client,
and suede on a headboard for a guest bed in his own loft.
</P>
<P>
   Nice work, if you can get it done. The best headboard resources
for designers and decorators are largely to-the-trade only.
Businesses like Charles H. Beckley, Avery Boardman and Sanderson,
based in the Design and Decoration Building in New York, offer
dozens of standard, upholstered shapes, and wood beds with
headboard options _ if you are working with a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Waverly, a fabric company, makes custom headboards available to
the trade and several standard shapes are available at retail,
through its Waverly Home stores.
</P>
<P>
   Many furniture upholsterers also make headboards, as a part of
their service. Prices vary according to the amount of detail. A
modest queen-size design should be about $700; a king-size, $900.
The cost of the fabric, which the client supplies, is additional.
(In comparison, Spiegel's slip-covered velveteen headboard is $299
complete for a queen or king size. Barbara Barry's leather
headboard for Baker is $3,127 for a queen size; $3,896 for a king.)
</P>
<P>
   What should one know about having a headboard custom made?
</P>
<P>
   ``Use a hardwood frame; the most common is ash,'' said Claude
Mailloux, a fabricator at Ernest Studio in New York. ``For an
upholstered headboard, use a Dacron or foam fill _ not down; it
settles.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Melkun, the general manager of Bielecky Bros., a
furniture manufacturer, stressed one of a headboard design's most
important points: getting the height right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedding height is not standard anymore,'' Melkun said.
``Measure at least 20 inches from the top of the bedding to the top
of the headboard.'' Total height will typically be about 42 inches.
``Remember, you're going to be losing some of that height with bed
linens,'' Melkun said. ``Forty-two inches isn't that excessive. It
tends to be the best level for reading or watching television. It
gives you the best back support. Your shoulders hit a comfortable
spot, not the top of the headboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Melkun recommended about 4 inches of padding in an upholstered
headboard. Bielecky Bros. will also sew an additional panel of
matching fabric to the top of a headboard, to hang behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can flip it forward to the front, to protect the
upholstered fabric,'' Melkun explained. ``As a antimacassar of
sorts. If the fabric is expensive _ and your husband's hair is
oily.''
</P>
<P>
   Resources
</P>
