<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIS-STRAW-HAT-THEATER     08-12 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIS-STRAW-HAT-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PART COMMUNE, PART CAMP, SUMMER THEATER CLINGS TO TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Ill., N.Y.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(nk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FISH CREEK, Wis. _ It came swooping across the stage just as the
police inspector made his entrance, a little black bat, wheeling
past the secret bookshelf compartment where the dead body was
stashed, paying no attention at all to the fact that there was a
murder investigation going on.
</P>
<P>
   An Agatha Christie murder investigation at that, the kind where
the actors must memorize rivers of rapid dialogue and quicksilver
twists of plot.
</P>
<P>
   The impromptu bat cameo was absorbed without a hitch, though, as
the inspector briskly ad-libbed ``Oh, I see you have a window
open,'' and turned back to the bloody deed at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody understands that bats are part of the package here on
the rustic pinky of land that is Wisconsin's Door Peninsula, bathed
by Green Bay on one side and Lake Michigan on the other. And
Peninsula Players, which calls itself the country's oldest
residential summer theater, has not survived for two-thirds of a
century by flouting the nature around it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the theater insists on ingratiating itself physically,
artistically, even spiritually, with the shimmering water and the
velvet canopy of cedars sheathing its little promontory of land.
That approach is part of what has made Peninsula Players a thriving
stalwart in a genre that is fading from the American landscape: the
summer theater as part commune, part camp, where the cast and crew
spend every moment living, eating, working together.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago there were more than 100 summer stock theaters.
Many had their entire casts living on site for the summer, doing a
different show each week; some, particularly in the Northeast,
hired a star who played the leading role and who then moved on to
another resident theater company on what was known as the straw hat
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But over the decades, theater changed. The big, splashy Broadway
musicals that became so popular were a tough fit for many summer
theaters _ too expensive and logistically untenable with their huge
choruses, multiple sets and costume changes, said Robert Bruyr,
executive assistant for member communication and education at
Actors Equity. Summer theaters found it hard to compete, especially
as production costs skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Some summer theaters started playing year-round to accommodate
new audiences and save the cost of closing up for the winter. Some
scrapped their resident companies and played host to more transient
casts. Nowadays, while there are nearly 400 places to see a show in
the summertime, said Jill Charles, editor of the Summer Theater
Directory, there are only about a dozen places like Peninsula
Players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature works very well with art,'' said Amy McKenzie, an
actress and director who grew up with Peninsula Players as the
daughter of one of the group's star actresses and the man who has
been its executive producer for nearly 30 years, James B. McKenzie.
``My commute to work is a half-mile old Indian path along Green
Bay. How can you be in a bad mood, whatever you might be obsessing
about? This whole place has been endowed like a prop, just like you
endow a prop as an actress on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Atmosphere and attitude are so important here that actors,
directors, costume designers and others are chosen partly by how
well they can handle the rhythm and temperament of the place.
Everyone is expected at the dining hall when the breakfast, lunch
and dinner bells ring. Until recently no one had a private
bathroom. Some sleeping quarters are squeezed above the box office,
the set design workshop and the prop rooms. And telephones,
televisions and other bells and whistles are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only theater that I know of where talent is really
second to who you are,'' said Ms. McKenzie. ``You can be brilliant,
but if you don't know how to interact with people, then this isn't
the place for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, after auditions for the summer season, Greg Vinkler,
the artistic director, decides which actors would be best for the
parts and then talks to people who know them, trying to find out
whether they are affable and easygoing enough to fit in in Fish
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call a lot of people and really grill them,'' Vinkler said.
``A few years ago, we had a fabulous actress up here. No problems
with her work onstage. But she had no interaction with people here.
She'd come get her meal and go back to her room. It's a fine line.
We try to let everyone be themselves, but they have to get along
with people. It's a huge part of our decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet with unusual consistency for a summer theater, Peninsula
Players has also managed to pull together exceptionally talented
casts, including some of the top actors in Chicago, one of the most
exuberant theater towns in the country. Auditions, held each year
in Chicago, a good five-hour drive from Fish Creek, always brim
with about 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 11-member cast includes three winners of Joseph
Jefferson awards, Chicago's version of the Tony, and actors who
have starred in or directed productions at the city's best
theaters, Steppenwolf, the Goodman, Shakespeare Repertory. The star
of the first two plays of the season, Sarah Underwood, 34, had a
major role in the national touring company of ``Angels in
America.'' Another actor, Howard Platt, 59, has had regular roles
in sitcoms like ``The Bob Newhart Show,'' ``Sanford and Son'' and
``Evening Shade,'' and will be producing and directing a revival in
New York of ``A Couple of Blaguards,'' written by Frank and Malachy
McCourt.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Peninsula Players' production of the London hit
``The Woman in Black'' was so well received that it was brought to
Chicago for a winter run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Gold, 40, an actress and New Yorker who knew nothing about
Peninsula Players, having moved to Chicago this year to teach
acting at Northwestern University, was expecting what she called a
typical summer stock experience: ``20-year-olds having all these
crises. One big gland.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, offering a visitor the bug spray she carries
with her here, while she is ``not a nature gal,'' she has delighted
in the ``tremendous opportunities for acting'' and ``people who
know what timing is.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any theater, Peninsula Players has to please its audience,
in this case the summer vacation crowd that surges into Fish Creek
(which has a year-round population of about 300) to take advantage
of the Door Peninsula's charming combination of rugged seacoast,
family farms, lush wooded trails and a vibrant artistic community
that has sprung up around the Peninsula Players over the last few
decades. Audiences expect a certain amount of tradition from a
theater that began in 1935 in a small Fish Creek motel and has been
on this 15-acre site, a former boys' camp, since 1937.
</P>
<P>
   The performances don't start until dark, so as not to interrupt
the pleasure of some of the regular patrons, who come before the
show to picnic, stroll through the day lilies and trilliums in the
garden and lazily watch the kaleidoscopic sunsets over the bay from
Adirondack chairs. As the audience files into the open-sided
auditorium, with its sagging canvas director's chairs for seats,
bug spray is as readily available as programs for the night's show.
Even the posters have stayed the same _ yellow and green on white _
after an attempt at a splashy four-color number proved too dramatic
a change for patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, audiences have seen a few famous names _ Sam
Wanamaker, Harvey Korman _ before they were famous. But they also
have lesser-known favorites, like Bob Thompson, now 81, who has
acted with the theater since 1938, appearing in everything from the
1957 production of ``Inherit the Wind'' (when monkeys in the play
escaped from their cages) to the recent performance of ``On Golden
Pond.'' Thompson routinely gets applause when he walks on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shows are calibrated for a common-denominator
audience, like this year's musical, ``The Fantasticks,'' and under
the theory that any Agatha Christie play packs them in, ``Spider's
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   But the theater also has to please its high-caliber cast, which
rehearses one play during the day while performing another at
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we couldn't get the good-quality actors to come
up here if they came up and did one silly British sex farce after
another,'' said Todd Schmidt, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   This season, there is only one British farce, ``Tons of Money,''
about a man who fakes his death and pretends to be his cousin so he
can inherit his own fortune.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always an actors' favorite. This season, it is
``Rain,'' a drama based on the W. Somerset Maugham story about the
relationship between a strait-laced minister and a vamp on a
tropical island. While playing loopy British blue-bloods in
``Spider's Web'' at night, the actors rehearsed Maugham's lush tale
of lust and sin in Polynesia during the day. The company wasn't
able to perform ``Rain'' for more than two weeks because, Schmidt
said, ``financially, we know we couldn't sustain it. It just
wouldn't draw the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater also tries to do new plays, often scheduling them
for the last four weeks of the season, the sleepier post-summertime
stretch from September to October. This year's will be ``Romance in
D,'' a new romantic comedy by James Sherman, who wrote ``Beau
Jest.''
</P>
<P>
   And Peninsula Players often gets an early crack at the rights to
Broadway shows because it is so far off the beaten track that
there's no chance of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people,'' said Ms. McKenzie, ``say Fish Hook, where?''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, Peninsula Players has felt the inexorable
pull of the modern age tugging at its barnlike buildings and
rough-hewn setting. This year, the theater invested in
walkie-talkies so that staff members could communicate without
standing next to each other. More significantly, the theater
recently built new housing for the actors, simple wooden apartments
with private bathrooms. A new septic system was added, along with
new public restrooms and expanded rehearsal and storage space.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways, Peninsula Players is sticking to tradition.
With ``Rain,'' for example, Vinkler, the director, considered ways
to simulate the constant precipitation of the rainy season in Pago
Pago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have rigged it up so the rain came gushing down over
a trough,'' Vinkler said. ``But then I said, `Let's not have real
rain at all. Let's have sound instead.' It was more important to
get the set up rather than kill ourselves over a special effect.''
</P>
<P>
   And after a couple of seasons of performing big, popular
Broadway shows _ ``Guys and Dolls,'' ``Amadeus,'' ``Crazy for You''
_ with multiple sets and huge casts, the Peninsula Players has
returned to more bite-size productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Let's do what they do in New York,''' Vinkler
said. ``But I've come to realize that we can't do that. We don't
have the set, the resources or the time. So this year the biggest
cast is 11, and it's all one set. We should do the kinds of things
we do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt chimed in: ``For the sanity of everybody here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
