<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Following Jesus Without Embarrassing God''
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Campolo
</P>
<P>
   Word, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   Here's the trouble with ``Following Jesus Without Embarrassing
God:'' For every time that you want to cock an eyebrow and say to
Tony Campolo, ``Maybe we better think that one over again'' (and
there are indeed such instances), he can say the same thing to you
about six times on half a dozen topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which of us can deny that, even as we are trying to follow
Jesus, we sometimes behave in ways which must make God and
Christianity seem ridiculous to those outside the faith?'' the
Eastern College sociologist asks. What follows is advice on how to
(among other things) talk about prayer without making God look bad,
be politically involved without losing your soul, and be sexually
attractive without being obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have heard this intense Italian-American speak know
that his words can be entertaining and pointed, and ``Following
Jesus Without Embarrassing God'' only furthers that reputation.
Agree with his arguments or don't _ either way, Campolo will make
readers think twice, and maybe even thrice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``When God's Children Get Together''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Children's Choir
</P>
<P>
   Malaco Records
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Children's Choir was formed in 1990 to open for
the world-famous Mississippi Mass Choir _ then flourished on its
own. Since 1992, the choir has released three CDs, the first two of
which have done very well on the national gospel charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When God's Children Get Together'' is the third, and it should
do at least as well as the second effort, 1994's ``A New
Creation,'' which sold nearly 100,000 copies. Once again, the MCC
(which has more than 200 members, all ages 7 to 17), has a strong
selection of mainly traditional-sounding songs, and once again,
there's a nice balance of tempos and old-sounding and more modern
instrumentation.
</P>
<P>
   What is most impressive, though, is the variety of strong
soloists, and how smartly the songs are arranged to show off their
talents and the choir's power. Felicia Brister, for example, powers
the group through the quietly building ``All We Have;'' the more
modern-sounding, funk-oriented ``I'm Blessed'' features an assured
vocal from Onitsha Shaw and, near the end, a rap from Dathan
Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it is extremely hard to believe that these are high
school kids, so assured are their vocals. But that is often the joy
of hearing young people perform: They don't know they're not
supposed to be as good as they are, so they just go ahead and do it
anyway. That's certainly the case here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
