<HEADLINE>
TECHNO COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Different Way to Look At the Browser Wars
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom says Netscape is the rabbit and
Microsoft is the tortoise in the race to create the dominant
browser, albeit a large, extremely powerful tortoise that is
gaining rapidly. But a new survey puts the browser race into a
different light.
</P>
<P>
   Positive Support Review, a Web design and consulting company in
Los Angeles, has found that, by one measure anyway, Microsoft
Internet Explorer has a greater share of the browser market and
that Netscape's Navigator browser is now the one playing catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Positive Support Review's atypical conclusion is based on
measuring market share in a different way: instead of looking at
the absolute number of people who use a given browser, looking at
how much time they spend using the respective browsers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which looked at 450,000 hits a month at a broad
range of Web sites, found that visitors used Microsoft 55 percent
of the time in July, up from 42 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Microsoft has taken the lead in usage patterns, there is
a recent bit of good news for Netscape, said Victor Janulaitis,
chief executive of Positive Support Review. Janulaitis said
Netscape had been gaining, which he attributed to people
gravitating to the latest release of its browser.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in July, usage of Microsoft dropped from a peak of 62
percent. ``Up until last month, it had been a steady climb,'' he
said. ``Microsoft won't be happy about the last month.''
</P>
<P>
   Janulaitis said Positive Support Review (www.psrinc.com)
undertook the project so it could tell its Web design customers
whether to focus on features for Netscape Navigator or Internet
Explorer. The company also plans to charge $299 for the complete
survey results. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Search Engine Is Placing Its Focus Outside U.S. Borders &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may be the World Wide Web, but more than half of the activity
and traffic on the Web is based in the United States. A growing
number of search engines are emerging that emphasize regions
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One such engine comes from Black Box (www.theblackbox.com),
based in Hong Kong, which is the creator of the Orientation Asia
and Orientation search engines for Africa, Central and Eastern
Europe, Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, it went live with Orientation Middle East, which
offers news updates, discussion groups and hot links pertaining to
15 nations in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Orientation's creators say their search engines differ
fundamentally from most search engines based in the United States
because they search for Web sites with a regional bias. The engine
weights its response to search inquiries in favor of Web pages that
originate from a given region, said Phil Ingram, marketing manager
for Black Box.
</P>
<P>
   The site culls its news from local sources and employs local
stringers to search for and rate sites of regional interest in the
hopes of becoming a regional portal, or point-of-entry, to the Web.
The site is also capable of searching in native languages, even if
the characters are not derived from the Roman alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Black Box is not alone. A growing number of region-centric
search engines and traditional search engines, like Yahoo, are also
expanding their regional news and Web offerings. Black Box says one
of the advantages offered by its Orientation sites is a particular
sensitivity to local cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the front page of Orientation Africa offered
a less-than-sensitive reader poll that asked visitors whether they
thought the Hutu rebels in Rwanda should be forgiven, hanged or
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram, when informed of the poll, said it would be immediately
removed. ``The polls are meant to be a little tongue-in-cheek,'' he
said. ``But that one has to come down right away.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Textbooks for Sale Online Are Aimed at College Students &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College students will soon be able to order their textbooks from
the warm confines of their dorm rooms. On Monday, Varsity Books
(www2.varsitybooks.com/textbookclub/index.asp) went live with a
site that permits students to order textbooks on line in an
academic version of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the site has reading lists for specific courses only
for colleges in the Washington area, but the company plans to add
schools nationwide for the spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   Varsity Books, a start-up backed by private investors, said it
would get the class reading lists from schools nationwide so
students with credit cards could just log on and click on their
colleges to find out what books they needed to read. For now,
students can search the site for individual books.
</P>
<P>
   The company is marketing its service as a way to avoid lines at
the campus book store while saving money. It says it can deliver
textbooks in as few as two days. Now, if the company could figure
out how to send along pizza. ... &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Offering Old-Fashioned Values For Teen-Agers Using the Web &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No sex? No violence? No computer hackers?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not, says Ira Kaufman of Legacy International, a
nonprofit organization that develops leadership skills among
promising teen-agers. Kaufman is director of a new Web-based
project at Legacy that is scheduled to go live on the Internet
today.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman wants the site (www.legacyintl.org) to use the latest
technology to promote old-fashioned values and to help teen-agers
on line develop a sense of community. The site has several facets:
free Web design for teen-agers, global chat rooms, a program that
helps visitors volunteer in their local communities and an
entertainment area that lets visitors download rock, jazz and other
music.
</P>
<P>
   A more unusual component is yet to come. The site will soon
start a life-simulation game
(www.globalrewards.org/ggame/index.html) designed to show
teen-agers how their lives might turn out, based choices they make.
Four teen-agers, who won a contest on Yahoo, will help design the
simulation with consulting help from the Rand Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, Hewlett Packard and Earth Link were among those
companies that donated $80,000 in cash and equipment to help get
the Legacy site up and running. Kaufman said the general idea was
to give teen-agers an alternative to nefarious influences on the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the alternatives cater to the darker side of things,''
Kaufman said. ``We're trying to give them a lighter side _ we want
them to be conscious that there are choices.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You Can Let Your Smile Be Your Security Password &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your password can be stolen, but only you have access to your
body.
</P>
<P>
   That's the general philosophy behind the technology that uses
fingerprints, facial features and other physical markers as a basis
for entry or access. Now a new application of this technology has
come to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Miros (www.Miros.com), a biometrics company in
Wellesley, Mass., is shipping the first copies of True Face Web
($199 each for 1 to 25 users). The software is intended to permit
access to secure Web servers only to those who have registered
their faces on the server.
</P>
<P>
   The software works in conjunction with a camera, measuring the
shapes of a person's facial features and, more significant, the
relationships between those shapes, said Michael Kuperstein, chief
executive of Miros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works the same way babies recognize faces,'' he said. ``It
looks at the gestalt, the holistic pattern of the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuperstein knows a thing or two about measuring people's mugs.
Face-recognition software made by Miros is already used to guard
transactions at 150 automatic teller machines in the South and
West. Several companies are testing Miros face-recognition software
as a way to protect access to internal company networks.
</P>
<P>
   The process has several steps. A camera on top of _ or inside _
a monitor takes your picture, which the software loaded on your
computer analyzes and sends to a secure server at, for example, an
online brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   When you want access to your personal account, you sit in front
of the monitor for another picture. That image is then matched
against the already stored record.
</P>
<P>
   Kuperstein, who has a PhD in neuroscience from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, said that the software could not be fooled
by a photograph and would be unlikely to mistake one person for
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't differentiate between twins,'' he said. ``But how
many evil twins are out there who are going to perpetrate a crime
against their twin?''
</P>
</TEXT>
