<HEADLINE>
TREASURY SECURITIES GAIN AS INVESTORS SEEK HAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities turned slightly lower Wednesday,
as the dollar fell against the yen before steadying itself, making
dollar-denominated investments like government securities less
attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Also putting some pressure on bonds was the Treasury's $11
billion auction of new 10-year notes, which followed a
disappointing auction of five-year notes on Tuesday. Wednesday's
auction results turned out to be not as good as hoped.
</P>
<P>
   A third factor was that the stock market showed signs of
recovery, easing the flight to bonds. Still, bonds held fast after
a manufacturing report from the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta
suggested that the nation's economic growth was slowing and
inflation was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, the 30-year bond was down a half-point to a
price of 107 1/32, while the yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose to 5.63 percent, from 5.60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers and traders expect the market to remain uncertain
through the Treasury auctions this week as investors may be wary
not only of the 10-year note Wednesday but also the 30-year bond
Thursday, since everything is currently at the high side of the
recent price range.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even though many people believe the dollar will
strengthen again and the Asian markets will get worse before they
get better, the 10-year issue was awarded at a price to yield 5.428
percent, a little behind what was hoped for, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Burtnick, managing analyst with Thomson Global Markets,
said Wednesday's auction, because it was a reopening of an existing
issue of 10-year notes, was considered a dealer-driven event,
rather than one for smaller investors. ``It was better for those
wanting to buy large amounts without moving the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market behaved well late in day because of a rumor that
the Russian ruble might be devalued, which spurred a late flight to
quality into Treasuries,'' he said. ``Regarding tomorrow's auction
of 30-year bonds, the closer we get to a yield of 5.50 percent on
the long bond, the harder it is to sell. Dealers might have to
cheapen the issue to make it more attractive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
