<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MTV MUSIC AWARDS HEAD WEST; JAZZ ON THE ROCKS;
DEFINING A MOUSE POTATO; ALTAR ALTERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., France, Germany)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MTV wants to reassure the city of New York that it
doesn't have anything against it. When the cable network announced
its annual Video Music Awards on Tuesday, some eyebrows were raised
by word that the awards, which have been held in New York for the
last four years, are being shifted to Los Angeles. The decision had
particular resonance because of the transfer of next year's Grammy
Awards from New York to Los Angeles after the event's organizers
squabbled with Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But Marnie Jakubowski-Malter, a spokeswoman for MTV, said that
the network simply decided ``to switch things around'' to keep the
event fresh. ``We made our decision well before that Grammy
thing,'' she said, adding, ``We love New York.'' The awards will be
held Sept. 10 at the Universal Amphitheater. The actor Ben Stiller
will be the host.
</P>
<P>
   Marsalis Immemorial
</P>
<P>
   He's had hit albums and won a Pulitzer Prize, but the latest
honor bestowed on the jazz trumpeter Wynton Marsalis may top the
lot: His music is being set in stone. Thursday, in the small town
of Marciac in the south of France, officials are expected to unveil
14 stone engravings, each etched with a page of Marsalis' ``Marciac
Suite,'' which he composed last year in honor of the town's annual
jazz festival. Marsalis, who will perform there Thursday, said he
had attended the festival for the last 18 years. ``I love it,'' he
said. ``I like the food, the sunshine, the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Philologically Fertile
</P>
<P>
   It may be a hippy-dippy attempt at spin by a bunch of Blairite
mouse potatoes, but the editors of the New Oxford Dictionary of
English are calling the edition to be published Thursday the most
important in years. The dictionary includes some 2,000 new words
and phrases _ including those used above _ and took six years to
compile.
</P>
<P>
   Helen McManners, a spokeswoman for Oxford University Press, told
Agence France-Presse that the project cost $4.8 million and was the
first edition written from scratch in more than 70 years. In
addition to Blairite (of Tony Blair, the English prime minister)
and mouse potato (a consistent computer user), the dictionary
includes new definitions for some of the old words. It weighs over
six pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered, Again
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, visitors to the Pergamon Museum in
Berlin have found one of the museum's principal attractions, the
Pergamon Altar, under an unsightly scaffold. But on Tuesday, a
newly renovated altar began to emerge, as museum officials unveiled
a third of the ancient Hellenic frieze. The altar, which stands 7
feet high and dates to 180 B.C., was excavated in Asia Minor by
German archeologists in the late 19th century and transported to
Berlin in 1902. The renovation is expected to take three more
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
