<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the steering winds of the jet stream almost completely
locked over Canada, the lethargy of the current weather pattern
across the contiguous states will persist.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will bubble up along and
south of a stalled front spanning east from the southern Plains to
the Carolina seaboard. Near the western edge of the front,
temperatures at Dallas will likely stay below 100 degrees as clouds
and perhaps sluggish showers develop. Farther east, slow-moving
storms will raise the risk of flash flooding in a few areas over
the Deep South as lethargic winds aloft promote slow-moving
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the absence of energetic high-altitude winds,
thunderstorms will generally stay below severe limits, except for a
single renegade storm or two that will produce large hail and gusty
surface winds. Over Florida, isolated strong storms will erupt,
mainly in association with sea breeze fronts forging inland from
the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Late-afternoon and evening thunderstorms will flare over the
high ground of the Southwest as tropical moisture holds steady.
Storms will then drift westward from mountains over Arizona and
southern California. Farther north, heat will continue to build
across the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Generally low humidity will prevail across the Northeast as
Canadian high pressure ridges south from Quebec. Temperatures will
average near or slightly below seasonal levels. Meanwhile, clouds
and a few showers will gather in the western Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Memorable Trace
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics of a popular song proclaim that it never rains in
southern California. At Bakersfield in the San Joaquin Valley,
these lyrics have long rung true on August 11. On Tuesday evening,
however, a trace of rain was observed, marking Bakersfield's first
rainfall on August 11 since weather records began in 1938. Earlier
on Tuesday, moist air resting atop the high Sierra was heated,
becoming buoyant compared to surrounding cool air. In turn, heated
air rose rapidly, forming thunderstorms. As the decaying remnants
of one storm drifted west, it brought a trace of rain to
Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast Text for Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday: The Northeast will be seasonably warm with
some afternoon thunderstorms as a weak cool front moves across the
region. The Southeast will stay very warm and humid with scattered
afternoon thunder. Clusters of thunderstorms will bring locally
heavy rain to parts of the southern Plains while northern areas
stay very warm with isolated thunder. Most of the West will stay
hot, but the Northwest will turn much cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday: Dry and seasonal conditions will be followed by
a warming trend in the Northeast. The Southeast will be sultry with
clusters of slow-moving thunderstorms. Potent thunder will develop
in the hot air over the northern Plains, while southern sections
have seasonable heat. The Rockies will stay very warm with isolated
mountain thunderstorms. The Pacific Northwest will be cool and
mainly dry. The Southwest will stay hot.
</P>
</TEXT>
