<HEADLINE>
GRILLING IN THE GLOBAL VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ ... Honey sesame shrimp ``on the barbie'' (from
Australia) Makes 4 servings 1 1/2 pounds jumbo shrimp, peeled and
deveined
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons Asian (dark) sesame oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice wine, sake or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Thai sweet chile sauce (optional, see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed with the side of a cleaver
</P>
<P>
   2 slices (1/4 inch-thick) fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, trimmed, white part flattened with the side of a
cleaver, green part finely chopped and set aside for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Rinse shrimp under cold running water, then drain and blot dry
with paper towels. Set aside while you prepare the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Combine 3 tablespoons sesame oil, rice wine, soy sauce, honey,
sesame seeds, chile sauce (if using) and five-spice powder in a
large bowl and whisk to blend. Stir in garlic, ginger, green onions
and shrimp to coat, then cover and let marinate in the refrigerator
30 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Using a slotted spoon, remove shrimp from the marinade to a bowl
and toss with remaining 2 tablespoons sesame oil. Pour marinade
into a saucepan; remove and discard garlic, ginger and green
onions, using the slotted spoon. Bring the marinade to a boil over
medium-high heat and cook, uncovered, to a thick, syrupy glaze,
about 3 minutes. Remove from the heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, oil grill grate. Arrange shrimp on the hot
grate and grill, turning with tongs, until nicely browned on the
outside and firm and pink inside, about 2 minutes per side. Brush
shrimp with glaze as they cook.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer shrimp to serving plates or a platter and sprinkle with
green onions and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Sweet chile sauce, popular in Thai and Vietnamese cooking,
is the Asian version of ketchup. One good brand to look for is
Sriracha. If not available, simply omit.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 423 calories (48 percent from fat), 22 grams total
fat (3 grams saturated), 260 milligrams cholesterol, 17 grams
carbohydrates, 37 grams protein, 1,038 milligrams sodium, 2 grams
dietary fiber.
Catalan tomato bread (from Spain) Makes 8 servings 4 fresh, very
ripe tomatoes, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, cut in half (optional)
</P>
<P>
   8 slices country-style bread, cut 1/2-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Cruet of extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Small bowl of coarse kosher or sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to medium-high.
</P>
<P>
   Place half tomato and half garlic clove (if using) on each
serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, arrange bread slices on a hot grate and
grill until nicely browned, 2 to 4 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Place a piece of grilled bread on each plate. To eat, rub a
bread slice with cut garlic (if using), then with cut tomato.
Drizzle each slice with oil and sprinkle with salt and pepper, if
desired. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 126 calories (37 percent from fat), 6 grams total
fat (1 gram saturated), no cholesterol, 17 grams carbohydrates, 3
grams protein, 367 milligrams sodium, 1 gram dietary fiber.
Grilled sugar-dipped pineapple (from U.S.A) Makes 8 to 10 servings
1 ripe pineapple (see note)
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon gloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark rum, to flambe (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the leafy top off the pineapple then cut off the rind. Slice
fruit into 8 to 10 even rounds. Using a pineapple corer or paring
knife, remove core from each round.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, place melted butter in shallow bowl; combine
the sugar, lime zest, cinnamon and cloves in a separate bowl. Bring
both bowls to grill side. Oil the grill grate. Dip each slice of
pineapple first into melted butter, then in the sugar mixture,
shaking off the excess. Arrange pineapple slices on hot grate and
grill, turning with tongs, until browned and sizzling, 5 to 8
minutes per side. Transfer pineapple slices to plates or a platter,
arrange slices in an overlapping fashion.
</P>
<P>
   If using rum, warm it in a small flameproof saucepan on one side
of the grill; do not let it boil or even become hot. Remove from
heat and then, making sure your sleeves are rolled up and hair is
tied back, light a long match and use it to ignite the rum,
averting your face as you do so. Very carefully pour the flaming
rum over the pineapple and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Look for fruit with a golden rind. It will be juicier and
sweeter than the usual green-rind pineapples.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving, based on 8: 262 calories (47 percent from fat), 13
grams total fat (8 grams saturated), 33 milligrams cholesterol, 31
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 3 milligrams sodium, 1 gram
dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
