<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BBQ-KANSAS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRILLING IN THE GLOBAL VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Shortly after moving from Boston to Miami, Steven
Raichlen was lounging in an Adirondack chair next to his grill when
he had ``one of those little moments of epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not, he thought, ``see the world through grilling?''
</P>
<P>
   An award-winning author of 16 cookbooks, Raichlen had long been
fascinated by the world's oldest, simplest and most primal method
of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years he traveled the ``global barbecue
belt,'' logging 150,000 miles and visiting 25 countries on five
continents. He spent another year testing recipes for The Barbecue!
Bible (Workman, $18.95), a hefty collection of more than 500 global
grilling recipes that transports readers from the steak houses of
Buenos Aires to the satay stalls of Bali.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen's brush with live-fire cooking included eating shrimp
cooked on ember-filled hubcaps in Vietnam and vegetables seared on
infrared gas grills in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   He still swoons at the memory of picanha, a prime cut of sirloin
served at churrascarias in Brazil, or Caribbean jerk pork seasoned
with hot Scotch bonnet peppers and allspice.
</P>
<P>
   To re-create the global grilling recipes he sampled, Raichlen
takes notes, makes sketches and tries to ``fix a taste, flavor and
preparation in my mind, then figure out how to get the same
results.''
</P>
<P>
   After tasting the haunting, smoky grilled escargot at L'Hostal
in Castellnou, France, Raichlen could have sworn he tasted curry.
But when he interviewed the chef he discovered the snails were fed
bunches of thyme before being cooked over grapevine trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   Although cooks can't buy live snails in the United States,
Raichlen was indeed able to duplicate the flavor using curry, a bit
of lard and a sprinkling of shallots, garlic and thyme chopped so
finely they would blow away if you breathed too hard.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop on his tour Raichlen relied on local cooking
experts, embassy officials and taxi drivers to steer him to the
best restaurants. From there he would branch out to the central
markets, stalls and street vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love street culture, street food and that kind of
in-your-face experience,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But in countries where social and political unrest made travel
impossible, such as Afghanistan, Iran and Iraq, Raichlen relied on
interviews and recipes with expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks I took were of the gastronomic sort,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One of his riskier meals was at an Esarn (northeastern Thai)
restaurant. He began to worry when he realized the fly-infested
kitchen overlooked a stagnant canal. Still, he ate with the gusto
befitting the guest of honor and was pleasantly surprised when he
didn't get sick.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen speaks French and Spanish with a smattering of Italian,
Portuguese and German thrown in. In countries where he didn't speak
the language he hired local interpreters. When no interpreter was
available he used his past cookbooks and a bit of pantomime to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in Korea a cook wrote down a recipe and the
concierge at the hotel translated it into English. In Brazil, a
butcher pulled out a diagram of a steer to illustrate exactly where
the picanha came from.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen's culinary travels also included pit stops throughout
the U.S., and his book includes a section on Kansas City-style
barbecue. There's a recipe for Lil' Jake's wings and mention of not
one but two Kansas City restaurants on his top 25 grilling
emporiums and barbecue joints list (Arthur Bryant's and Lil'
Jakes).
</P>
<P>
   But there were a few editing glitches that local barbecue buffs
will find hard to swallow. Raichlen places Kansas City on the
Mississippi rather than the Missouri River, and he ignores the
state line, referring to ``Kansans.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals may also bristle at Raichlen's use of the words
``barbecue'' and ``grilling'' as if interchangeable. (Grilling is a
quick-cooking method done over direct heat. Barbecue is a
slow-cooking method over indirect heat.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of true barbecue in other countries, except
the Caribbean and Mexico,'' Raichlen says. ``It's only in the U.S.
that you'll find (barbecue) purists. What's interesting about the
U.S. is that we have the tradition of both grilling and barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``barbecue'' in the title was the publisher's decision.
But Raichlen acknowledges the title has probably helped sales.
</P>
<P>
   And whether you call it grilling or barbecue, ``it's a religion
for a lot of people,'' he says. ``They really approach it with
religious fervor, and that's what I love about it.''
</P>
<P>
   -MORE-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
