<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SILVA-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A simple onion sandwich has its virtues
</P>
<P>
   It was the sheer simplicity of the sandwich that caught our
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Gather members of the Association of Food Journalists for an
annual conference and the eating can become, well, lavish.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of research, we often end up sharing one rich meal
... after another ... after another.
</P>
<P>
   Treadmill, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   But a tribute to James Beard luncheon at the Red Star Tavern and
Roast House in downtown Portland, Ore., proved a welcome respite
from our sometimes overzealous consumption of salmon, hazelnuts and
fresh Marionberries (a cross between the Chehalem and Olallieberry
blackberries, not to be confused with a certain Washington, D.C.,
mayor).
</P>
<P>
   For lunch executive chef Rob Pando served fresh-squeezed
lemonade sipped from frosty, sugar-lipped glass tumblers; a salad
of heirloom tomatoes and baby greens; Dungeness crab salad with
avocado, dressed in a light, lemon vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   And a basket of Walla Walla Sweet onion sandwiches served with
housemade mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   An onion sandwich?
</P>
<P>
   On the menu it did sound suspiciously like Depression-era fare,
but it was a favorite of the late, great culinarian James Beard.
</P>
<P>
   The sandwiches so-adored by one of Portland's native sons won
the table over.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are wonderfully simple, simply wonderful little
sandwiches...'' Marion Cunningham writes in The Fannie Farmer
Cookbook. ``James Beard used to make them with a rich brioche
dough....''
</P>
<P>
   You hardly need a recipe to re-create Pando's sweet onion
sandwiches at home. Simply slice the onions thin and serve with a
healthy slathering of high-quality mayonnaise on sturdy,
country-style bread.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Jan Roberts Dominguez of Corvalis, Ore., also is
captivated by the simple sweet onion sandwich. But the author of
The Onion Cookbook offers a slightly jazzier variation on the Beard
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts Dominguez uses pumpernickel bread and a sour
cream//mustard mixture to offset the sweet, crisp onion slices and
adds Swiss cheese and arugula. Both are thoughtful additions, to be
sure. But you could just as easily go without. In this case,
simplicity is, indeed, a virtue. Sweet onion sandwich Makes 4
servings 1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   8 slices dark, dense-textured pumpernickel bread
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces thin-sliced Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   12 to 16 tender arugula leaves, rinsed and crisped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium (about 8 ounces) fresh Walla Walla Sweet onion (or
another sweet onion, such as Vidalia), sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a cup, combine sour cream and mustard. Slather 4 slices of
the bread with half of the sour cream mixture. Equally distribute
the cheese, arugula and onion slices over the sauce, then season to
taste with salt and pepper. Spread the other 4 slices of bread with
the remainder of the sour cream mixture and complete the
sandwiches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
