<HEADER>
A0774 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-12 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST IMAGINE CECIL VAN TUYL IN ROYAL BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ How about this as a way to liven up the
dullest days of summer? How about Cecil Van Tuyl offers to kick in
whatever financial help Miles Prentice needs to buy the Kansas City
Royals in return for voter approval of Van Tuyl's Brush Creek Plaza
redevelopment proposal?
</P>
<P>
   If Van Tuyl's bid for a $78-million redo west of Country Club
Plaza gets the go-ahead at the polls Nov. 3, it will be worth
nearly $20 million in taxpayer subsidies. If Van Tuyl becomes a
Royals part-owner, it's a good possibility he'll get to share in at
least that much public largess over the next decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Major league franchises are, after all, as good a way to
generate taxpayer subsidies as economic redevelopment. The bonus is
that the public relations potential has a lot more upside in sports
than it does in bricks and mortar. This is an aspect of the deal
that shouldn't be lost on Van Tuyl.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has public relations problems, it's Van Tuyl. His
controversial redevelopment proposal has been kicking around for
nearly three years. As far as can be told, there's never been any
spirited public support for the project. Except for those in Van
Tuyl's employ and project beneficiaries, enthusiastic proponents
seem few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposition side, however, the fight to stop the
development has been intense. The opposition's numbers aren't all
that many, relatively speaking, but they are committed. One
objection is that it would create a traffic zoo in the area and
otherwise diminish the quality of life thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   That's the practical objection. The esthetic objection is that
all those ancient apartment heaps Van Tuyl wants to supplant with a
brand new mixed-use commercial-residential neighborhood are too
precious to destroy. To paraphrase, hell hath no fury like
preservationists faced with proposed demolishment of something they
see as charming.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has evolved into such a hot political potato that
the Kansas City, Mo., Council last week decided not to decide and
dropped the issue into the hands of voters. The people will
determine the project's fate, which would appear dubious. Those not
strongly opposed are apparently indifferent to it, which doesn't
bode well for Van Tuyl.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Van Tuyl creates image problems for himself by
choosing to maintain a nonexistent public profile. Van Tuyl's
visibility is nil in the community, which is a critical drawback
now that he's faced with the challenge of persuading Kansas Citians
to join him in radically changing the face of a beloved piece of
local real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Van Tuyl, however, can solve all his PR problems in one fell
swoop by mounting a white horse and becoming the biggest local
backer in the effort to save the beloved big-league baseball
franchise. Not only would he create a public persona, but also
would gain a rep as a guy who wants to give something back to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Any effort to link his Royals financial support to voter
approval of his redevelopment project might be tricky from a public
relations standpoint, because some would equate it with a polite
form of blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   This hurdle is negotiable, though, because so many Kansas
Citians are desperate to retain the Royals. Thus, sufficient
numbers of voters likely would be able to overlook the /{quid pro
quo/} nature of his offer in return for the promise keeping the
Royals in Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
