A0779 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALL-PLAN-KAN &LR;      08-12 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-PLAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE MALL PROPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The tidal wave of development sweeping south
Johnson County, Kan., has inspired plans to bring another regional
mall to the metropolitan area's shopping mix.
</P>
<P>
   Developers Copaken, White &AMP; Blitt on Tuesday confirmed they were
working on plans to build a mall at 135th Street and Metcalf
Avenue, in one of the region's most affluent, fastest-growing
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The developers, who are the main owners of Oak Park Mall, also
in the Kansas City area, are proposing a retail strip center and a
regional mall on about 90 acres. Members of the firm are working
with apartment developer A.G. Spanos, which plans to build an
apartment complex on 50 acres southeast of the mall, buffering it
from nearby residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing that plans are preliminary, Jon Copaken said the
company believes there is demand now for a retail strip center on
the site that would accommodate four or five large stores and
numerous smaller retailers and restaurants. He acknowledged that
plans for an enclosed mall were more speculative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mall component will be dictated by the demand of
department stores,'' said Copaken. ``There are department stores
here that might want to be in the center and retailers outside of
Kansas City that might want to be in this market. If none of the
department stores are interested, then it wouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the mall plan comes only a week after it was announced
that May Department Stores Co. is buying six Kansas City area Jones
stores and one in Topeka, Kan. The entrance of May, one of the most
successful department store retailers in the country, is leading
some retail observers to suggest that the Kansas City retail market
is in for some changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is due to break out of the second-tier status it's held,''
said David Levine, whose Dallas company Real Estate F//X has done
consulting for the Country Club Plaza and the proposed downtown
Power &AMP; Light retail project. ``Kansas City is not a major retail
market in the eyes of many retailers but it has the potential to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said Kansas City has some predictable shopping and
restaurant venues and could use a mall if it were exciting enough
to attract some of the new retailers and themed restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City has the horsepower for a Neiman Marcus or a
Bloomingdale's,'' Levine said of two of the more upscale national
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   He said May also owns chains such as Lord &AMP; Taylor that it might
want to bring to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the strip center could begin in the spring, if the city
grants appropriate zoning. The mall could take three to five years
to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Copaken, White &AMP; Blitt and A.G. Spanos would have to get zoning
for their specific plans, said John Petersen, attorney for the
project, but the site was zoned for a regional mall and apartment
project in 1990. A Michigan developer, Forbes-Cohen Properties,
proposed a mall of about 1.3 million square feet on the site, but
the project never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The demographics in what is known as the Blue Valley area are
considered phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has high, real high, disposable income,'' said Dennis
McKee, president of the County Economic Research Institute, which
develops statistics about the county. ``It is a hot retail location
and growing at almost double digit rates. It is competitive,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of households in the three-mile trade area
surrounding the proposed mall site area has grown 8 percent a year
over the last five years. And according to a report the research
institute did in March, the average price of houses in the area is
more than $206,000 and annual household disposable income is almost
$94,000.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said the Kansas City area has about 10 percent more
retail space per capita than the national average. Even so, he
believes the area could support another mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you would see a real severe shakeout,'' Levine
said. ``You would see an adjustment but some of that would be due
to changing preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that adjustment would be in Johnson County, which last
year surpassed $5 billion in retail sales. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
