</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-SHOT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-YEAR-OLD BOY SHOT AND KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 1-year-old boy was shot and killed Tuesday
in a midtown Kansas City apartment, and police said the boy's
6-year-old cousin told them he had fired the fatal shot with a gun
he had found in a bag.
</P>
<P>
   The bag also contained video game controls. Police were trying
to determine who took the gun into the Kansas City house.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Darian D. Hinds was shot about 2:35 p.m. at a
three-story house converted to apartments at 4001 Warwick Blvd. The
older boy's name was not released because of his age. It was his
birthday Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just traumatized,'' said Donald Richards, a family
member. ``I don't know if he knows what is going on. I'm sure he
just saw the gun in the bag and was curious about it. He didn't
know. It was just an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old boy's sister, 16, and their mother were also in
the first-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The girl and woman were in a different room from the children
when the child was shot. The gun apparently had been in a bag that
was on the floor in front of a television set, said Detective Jeff
Cowdrey.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the boy told them he grabbed the handgun, pointed it
at a wall and pulled the trigger. A bullet struck the 1-year-old,
who was climbing onto a chair, in the torso.
</P>
<P>
   The mother called 911, and the boy was taken to the hospital,
where he was pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   No one who lived at the home claimed the handgun or knew how it
got into the house, said Detective Kevin Kilkenny.
</P>
<P>
   The mother told police the gun was not in the bag earlier in the
day, so police were investigating whether someone stopped by the
house Tuesday and put it there.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the shooting, family members gathered at the home. A
half-dozen pink roses in a vase had been placed on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   About 6:30 p.m., an argument that could be heard on the street
broke out among family members. The teen-age girl stepped out of
the house and asked for police to intervene because the argument
was turning into threats. Police said later the argument was over
who was at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Police escorted several relatives to the curb and talked with
them. Family members then took the 6-year-old boy to get something
to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors told police they had seen someone carrying a gun in
and out of the house in recent days. Another family member told
police that was a BB gun and was not related to the shooting.
Police were still investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The family had lived in the home about four months, said
Richards, a brother-in-law of the woman who lives there.
</P>
<P>
   A similar shooting occurred July 15, when Chris Hollowell, 4,
was shot in the head as his 10-year-old brother looked at a
handgun. The brothers had gone to their 10-year-old cousin's house
in Grandview and found the handgun on a closet shelf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
