A0796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS &LR;      08-12 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE TELEVISION REPORTS HIGHER EARNINGS FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc. on Wednesday reported
second-quarter revenues rose 401 percent and operating cash flow
for the quarter grew 484 percent over last year's second quarter,
reflecting the combined results of the Hearst and Argyle operations
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter totaled $109.7 million, up from $21.9
million a year earlier. Operating cash flow for the quarter totaled
$54.3 million, compared with $9.3 million in the year-earlier
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 results reflect operations only of the former Argyle
Television Inc. that merged, effective Aug. 29, 1997, with the
broadcasting group of The Hearst Corporation. Argyle owned six
stations and Hearst owned eight stations.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half, revenue rose 395 percent to $197 million
from $39.8 million, while operating cash flow jumped 497 percent to
$84.5 million from year-earlier $14.2 million. Earnings per share
came to 49 cents, compared with a year-earlier loss of 79 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle also announced pro forma results as if
Hearst-Argyle's acquisition of the broadcasting group of Pulitzer
Publishing were complete. That acquisition, announced in May, is
expected to close by year-end, pending regulatory and shareholder
approval.
</P>
<P>
   On that basis, revenue for the quarter rose 6.7 percent, to
$178.4 million from $167.2 million, while operating cash flow was
up 11.4 percent to $89.5 million from $80.3 million. Pro forma
earnings per share rose 23 percent, to 27 cents from 22 cents a
share a year-earlier.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half, pro forma revenue was up 6.5 percent to
$320.9 million from $301.2 million. Operating cash flow rose 10.2
percent, to $142.4 million from $129.2 million a year earlier.
Earnings per share were up 38 percent, to 29 cents from 21 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marbut, chairman and co-chief executive officer, said the
Pulitzer acquisition ``was a defining transaction for our
company.'' He said the deal puts Hearst-Argyle in more high-growth
southern markets and provides greater geographic and network
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The pro forma company, with TV stations in 20 states, will reach
16.5 percent of U.S. households and will be one of the top three
independent TV station groups, Marbut said. The company will be the
largest ABC affiliate group and the second largest NBC affiliate
group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John G. Conomikes, president and co-chief executive officer,
said the rate of growth of third-quarter ad sales has slowed ``to
about 3 percent'' as the result of the UAW strike against General
Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   However, Conomikes predicted that Hearst-Argyle will benefit in
the latter part of the quarter from the strike's settlement and
from political advertising. He said the earlier 8 p.m. starting
time for ``Monday Night Football'' would benefit Hearst-Argyle's
nine ABC-affiliated stations by allowing them to put their
late-night news program on earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football'' is ``undeniably primetime TV's single
biggest draw for male viewers across all demographic
categories,''according to David J. Barrett, executive vice
president and chief operating officer of Hearst-Argyle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
