<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MOTHERBOARDS-ART-     08-12 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MOTHERBOARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOTHERBOARD: HEAD OF THE COMPUTER HOUSEHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has an evocative name, the motherboard, and rightly so: It is
the computer's main circuit board, so all the smaller assemblies
are plugged or wired into it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the motherboard (which is, of course, bigger and
smarter than a daughterboard) has had other names. For a time, IBM
referred to motherboards as planar cards, part of its practice of
having its own terms for everything. But it's not surprising that a
word like ``motherboard'' beat out ``planar card'' _ the hand that
rocks the cradle rules the world.
</P>
<P>
   A motherboard binds chips together. The board usually holds all
the processing power and moves signals back and forth among the
various chips responsible for doing computations, putting images on
the screen or sending data to modems or disk drives. The
motherboard is the Grand Central Terminal for all the data.
</P>
<P>
   Motherboards are generally made of a hard plastic and have
circuit traces made of copper etched onto them. In many cases, the
board has multiple layers because the traces are so complex that
they must cross one another many times. The chips, resistors,
capacitors and other components are generally attached to the top
and sometimes the bottom with solder.
</P>
<P>
   The art of designing a motherboard is complex and involves many
design decisions. One of the most basic is whether to solder a
component directly to a board or connect it with a socket.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, almost all parts were attached with sockets so new
parts could be swapped in when the old ones went bad. That practice
is largely history because the sockets never gave as good
connections as pure solder. Further, if repairs are needed, finding
which of the many components is bad and then replacing it is often
more expensive than buying a new motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only the processor chip and the memory boards are
routinely attached with a socket instead of solder. The processor
is the most important part of the computer and is generally the
most expensive. The speed of the chips varies, and sometimes people
upgrade their computers by putting in more powerful processors.
</P>
<P>
   The RAM is usually connected in small cards, memory modules that
are sometimes known as daughterboards or daughtercards; among the
more common are those known as SIMMs (single in-line memory
modules) or DIMMs (dual in-line memory modules). More memory is
generally better; huge amounts are generally needed by graphics
designers, scientists, programmers, medical diagnosticians and many
others, who can add more memory if they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes manufacturers may leave parts off the motherboard to
give the user some flexibility. The circuitry for putting images on
the screen, for instance, is often put on a separate card that
plugs into the motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   That lets some people choose whether they want a high-end
graphics card capable of supporting a big monitor or whether they
would rather save some money by getting a lower-end card. Modems,
fast disk controllers, network access circuits and sound processing
are some of the typical functions put on separate cards to leave
the user some options.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers are starting to bundle as many of these
options as they can together on the board. They are trying to
choose a collection of options that should fit the average user's
needs and locking them into the board.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon to find circuits that used to be on a
separate sound card soldered onto the main motherboard. They are so
standard that this is the cheapest way to deliver the features. For
example, graphics processing on the motherboard is more common
these days.
</P>
<P>
   While motherboards have usually contained many chips, each for
different functions, chip manufacturers are now bundling more and
more features on the same chip. Manufacturers love to do that
because it reduces the chip count on the motherboard and makes
assembly cheaper. In time, it is possible that there will be only
one chip on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who want better computers, and feel adept enough,
may put in faster processors, while others buy whole new computers.
For some people, a smart move is to upgrade by buying a new
motherboard but keeping the old box, power supply and disk drives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1824EDT &QL; 
