<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS FOR READING ON SUMMER VACATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Byu PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Point of Origin''
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Cornwell
</P>
<P>
   356 pages, Putnam, $25.95
</P>
<P>
   THE AUTHOR: Before writing her first crime novel eight books
ago, Patricia Cornwell worked as a police reporter, an employee of
the Virginia chief medical examiner's office and a volunteer police
officer. She lives in Richmond, Va., and speaks with a subtle
Southern accent.
</P>
<P>
   BACKGROUND FOR FIRST-TIMERS: Quincy is a wimp. So is Mark Sloan
of ``Diagnosis Murder.'' Neither of those crime-solving physicians
is fit to pass a scalpel to Kay Scarpetta, the state of Virginia's
chief medical examiner.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLOT: Dr. Scarpetta reluctantly delays her beach vacation
with Benton, her FBI agent lover. A horse farm owned by a media
wheel has been torched, and it doesn't look as though a frayed
extension cord is the culprit. Worse: Carrie Grethen, Scarpetta's
nemesis from earlier novels, may somehow be manipulating these and
other misdeeds _ even though she is locked in a psychiatric
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie's toxic ploys inflict new pain on Scarpetta's niece,
Lucy, who is Carrie's former lover. And subsequent events bring
even deeper emotional hurt to Scarpetta.
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE DELIGHTS: Cornwell's crime-scene portraits are
exhaustively detailed. You can feel the muck, smell the
flame-charred flooring. There are lengthy descriptions of a motel,
a motel clerk, a motel room, a motel bath. Then, by way of
intoxicating contrast, there is the lean economy of allocating
snide subtext to the merest of attributions (''... my niece inanely
said'').
</P>
<P>
   CAVEAT FOR THE SQUEAMISH: Cornwell also provides detailed
descriptions of charred, parboiled, bludgeoned and otherwise
foul-played-with bodies.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
