<SLUG> BC-SA-SYMPHONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED SAN ANTONIO SYMPHONY SEEKS NEW CONTRACT WITH MUSICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE GREENBERG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Just a month from opening night, the San Antonio
Symphony's 60th season is threatened by a game of brinkmanship
between its governing board and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a ``profound financial crisis,'' the chairman of the San
Antonio Symphony board said Tuesday that the coming season is in
peril unless the musicians agree to renegotiate their contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the musicians' attorney, Leonard Leibowitz, has resisted
entering into formal contract talks while most of the musicians are
out of town for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board feels very strongly that before we make a decision
to launch our 60th season, we have to deal in a straightforward
manner with the financial crisis we face,'' chairman Charles Lutz
said after a board meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The season is scheduled to begin Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key ingredient of our decision to go forward is a
renegotiated contract with the musicians,'' Lutz said. ``And I
would suggest that a renegotiated contract is essential to our
going to a group of stakeholders and asking them for sustaining
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Another board meeting has been tentatively set for Aug. 25.
Asked if a go-or-no-go decision would have to be made then, Lutz
replied: ``Not necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutist Jean Robinson attended the board meeting as head of the
orchestra committee, which also would be the contract negotiating
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to keeping our orchestra alive, and we are
doing all we can to ensure its survival. We can't talk about any
specifics right now,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract has two years to run. In February, however,
the board declared a state of financial emergency, which allows the
symphony to force the musicians to reopen their contract.
</P>
<P>
   The symphony is asking to freeze the musicians' base weekly
salary at $732, reduce the number of paid weeks from 39 to 36 and
cut pension payments and other benefits, according to a letter from
symphony attorney George P. Parker Jr. to Leibowitz.
</P>
<P>
   The symphony also has filed a complaint against Local 23 of the
American Federation of Musicians. Parker charged that the musicians
union had ``refused to bargain over changes in the parties'
collective bargaining agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The symphony has an accumulated debt of about $1.5 million and
repeatedly was late in making payroll during the second half of the
previous season, which closed at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   A task force, including board members, staff, musicians and
others not associated with the symphony, has spent the summer
studying a wide range of the orchestra's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz said the task force recommendations were reported to the
board Tuesday, but he would not disclose what those recommendations
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we now must do is bring together all the constituencies
... and reach agreement with them that the right thing to do is
move forward with the 60th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of these groups is essential _ the orchestra members, the
corporate community, season subscribers, City Council and the city
leadership, the board, and local and national foundations and
trusts,'' Lutz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HOME-SALES-BOS &LR;      08-12 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HOME-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE HOME SALES SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A brisk spring real estate market pushed sales of
detached single-family homes in Massachusetts to their highest
level in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   During the second quarter of 1998, between April and June, more
than 14,304 single-family homes were sold in the state, a 11.5
percent increase from the second quarter of 1997, the Massachusetts
Association of Realtors reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mild weather and continued low interest rates pushed the number
of closings for the first six months of 1998 to an all-time
mid-year high of 22,528.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in Greater Boston dipped 4.9 percent in the second quarter
of 1998 as compared to the second quarter of 1997, a decline
attributed to a shortage of inventory and a new statewide listing
system that many agents had difficulty mastering.
</P>
<P>
   The average state-wide sales price for a home also climbed 10.2
percent to $217,281 during that period. In Greater Boston, where
sales tend to be driven by the higher end of the market, the
average price of a single-family home rose 15.4 percent to
$284,289.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the median home price increased by 6 percent to
$131,100 during the second quarter of 1998, the National
Association of Realtors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Condominium sales in Massachusetts increased by 14.3 percent
during this time period, while the average price of a condo rose to
$135,640. In Greater Boston, the average price of a condo is now
$168,079 _ a 12.7 percent increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said sustained economic growth was the main ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the second quarter, consumer confidence was at
an all-time high, interest rates were low, and the stock market was
up,'' said Karl Case, an economics professor at Wellesley College.
</P>
<P>
   Case predicted that the market will slow in the third quarter,
in part because of volatility on Wall Street and the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is still strong, there is still no reason to
expect things are going to collapse, but it's going to be probably
a healthy cooling,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are many first-time home buyers now shopping for
homes, many who already own are opting to trade in their existing
homes for more expensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can sell that first home and buy a larger home with
more amenities and that is reflected in the percentage changes.''
said MAR president Mary Crowley. ``The trade-up market is really
moving and that was a segment of the market that was very depressed
for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
