A0819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-QUAKE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-12 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-QUAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE EARTHQUAKE SHAKES NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A moderate earthquake shook parts of northern
California Wednesday morning, rattling more nerves than buildings.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Centered about 85 miles southeast of San Francisco near the San
Andreas fault, the quake struck at 7:10 a.m. PT and registered 5.4
on the Richter scale of ground motion, according to the U.S.
Geological Survey office in Menlo Park, Calif. The effects were
felt over 116 miles, from Sausalito, just north of San Francisco,
down to Big Sur.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco metropolitan area, the quake prompted
officials to shut down commuter train service while they checked
tracks for damage, and it caused some downtown skyscrapers to sway,
which frightened at least a few office workers.
</P>
<P>
   Seismologists at the University of California at Berkeley said
the earthquake was followed by dozens of small aftershocks in the
same area that registered 2.0 or greater, which is typical for a
quake of this size. One reached 3.0. But they also said the history
of earthquake activity in northern California over the last 20
years suggests a 5 to 10 percent probability that Thursday's large
quake could be a warning, known as a foreshock, of an earthquake
equal in size or larger within the next seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Near the epicenter of Thursday's quake, seven miles
south-southeast of San Juan Bautista, a bedroom community of 1,500,
state officials found small cracks in Highway 101, a major
north-south corridor. But they were not found to be serious enough
to close the road. `'Cars are still driving over them,'' Sheriff
Harvey Nyland of San Juan Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
   But the quake caused enough superficial damage at the town's
most famous landmark, the 186-year-old Mission San Juan Bautista,
that church officials summoned engineers to determine if there were
structural problems, as well. The Rev. Edward Fitz-Henry said
plaster fell from a wall that faces the mission cemetery, which
faces the fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since 1906 that the mission has been
damaged by an earthquake,'' Fitz-Henry said, referring to the most
devastating earthquake ever recorded in northern California, with a
magnitude of 8.25. In addition to its historical importance, the
mission was the setting for the climax and several other critical
scenes in ``Vertigo,'' Alfred Hitchcock's 1958 thriller.
</P>
<P>
   In case any fans of the film were wondering, Fitz-Henry said,
the bell tower in the final scene of ``Vertigo'' was not damaged.
That is because the mission has no bell tower. Hitchcock,
Fitz-Henry said, shot the scene on a sound stage in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
