<SLUG> BC-BURMA-CAPTIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURMESE HOLD AMERICAN STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted early as Myanmar-Captive; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman from Portsmouth, N.H., detained in Burma along with
several other American university students, is doing well and may
be released shortly, her mother says.
</P>
<P>
   Anjanette Hamilton, 20, was taken into police custody along with
17 companions Sunday for distributing antigovernment leaflets in
Burma, the southeast Asian nation also known as Myanmar. Though the
group is being held, they have not been arrested or charged with
any crime, a U.S. State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   The six Americans being detained have communicated with their
families through the US embassy in the Burmese capital of Rangoon.
Five of the students attend American University in Washington,
D.C., and one attends Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to hang in there,'' said Anjanette's mother,
Alison Hamilton. ``We are hopeful that things will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton received a fax from her daughter, known as Angie, on
Tuesday in which she said she is ``absolutely fine.'' The fax
continued: ``We are still making corny jokes, so I still have my
sense of humor. I LOVE YOU GUYS SO MUCH.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was relieved to hear from a US embassy official
Wednesday that the embassy was able to visit the students on
Tuesday and give them food, towels, and clean underwear. The
embassy also told Hamilton that they gave her daughter some
batteries she had requested for her Sony Walkman.
</P>
<P>
   The students were distributing the leaflets Saturday, the 10th
anniversary of a nationwide uprising against Burma's military
government that left 3,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Angie, who will be a sophomore at American, left Washington for
Thailand on July 28, her mother said. Along with the other
students, she had planned to visit refugee camps in Thailand near
the Burma border. Hamilton had taken two suitcases with her _ one
with her clothes and the other with dental supplies for the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's mother said her daughter was participating in the
trip through the Free Burma Coalition, a group active on college
campuses that works to promote democracy in Burma. The group is not
affiliated with American University.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more humanitarian than political,'' Hamilton said.
``We're puzzled as to how she got into Burma and mixed up in all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Angie has been fighting poverty and injustive overseas for
several years, her mother said. In 1994, she spent time in India,
where she visited an orphanage. She was so inspired to help that
she raised $6,000 for medical equipment for the orphanage. Two
years later, she spent a summer building latrines in a Brazilian
village.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department official said it was a good sign that US
embassy officials were able to visit the detained students, but
added that Burma has not detained Americans in the past, so it is
tough to predict what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Hamilton, who says she has lost sleep over her daughter's
ordeal, maintains hope that Angie will be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do feel they're being treated well, and we heard from the
embassy that the mood has changed for the better, so all of these
things make us hopeful, but we still don't know when they will be
released,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
