<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0826 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORTWORTH-EXHIBIT-TEX     08-12 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH EXHIBIT SHOWS WHAT'S IMPORTANT _ AND WHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to say that certain artworks are important. Any
museum worth its salt makes that claim every time it hangs
something on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   It's another thing, though, to communicate WHY an artist or a
painting or print or an apparently simple lump of lead is
important, without smothering viewers in data and dogma.
</P>
<P>
   Take the two Andy Warhol paintings recently purchased by the
Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth. We all know who Andy Warhol is and
what his art looks like.
</P>
<P>
   But art and artist both have enjoyed far more than 15 minutes'
worth of fame _ and we can see why when we look at the pictures at
the Modern. Not only are the individual pictures horrific _ a
self-portrait as a death mask and a cannon-sized gun _ they are
installed with other artworks that amplify the themes of death and
the need for spiritual reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing artworks with related subject matter, similar
compositions and other affinities isn't a new practice. But, new or
not, it helps us get inside artworks that otherwise might seem
inaccessible. It even helps build a mood _ edgy seriousness in this
case _ that lingers well after visitors leave the museum to go
home, grab some coffee or, just maybe, look at more art.
</P>
<P>
   Assembled by Michael Auping, the Modern's chief curator,
``Recent Acquisitions and Selections From the Permanent
Collection'' features about 60 artworks by 33 artists. It includes
paintings, photographs, drawings and one video installation _ Bill
Viola's ``The Greeting'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the work will be familiar to visitors who have been to
the Modern during the past year or two. Along with the two Warhols,
conspicuous new acquisitions include an important new painting by
Anselm Kiefer and a classic montage by those rude Brits, Gilbert &AMP;
George. Then there are golden oldies such as Picasso and Jackson
Pollock, hung side-by-side to suggest new ideas about both.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paintings, the show includes several photographs.
Most are segregated into photo-only installations, although Cindy
Sherman's self-portrait as a pope is placed with the Warhols and
new Kiefer, with the Gilbert &AMP; George piece (which combines
photography and mixed media) nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greeting'' is placed in a darkened gallery all its own. A
monumental projection, Viola's work is on the scale of a
16th-century altarpiece _ quite fittingly, considering that it is
based on Jacopo Pontormo's post-Renaissance painting of the Virgin
Mary's visit to her cousin Elizabeth. Viola's work is more general
and secular, but the monumental female figures, the fluttering
drape of their clothing and the dramatic lighting in his work all
hark back to Pontormo, as does the video's overall sense of
something uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greeting'' is a major, majestic work by Viola and, for
now, the only video piece the Modern owns. Any number of artists,
including the quietly complex Ann Hamilton and trendy Tony Oursler,
work in that medium. But the Modern has yet to buy more video. This
tells us that Viola is special and that video is going to be around
long enough that there's no need to hurry up and buy.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other things this show wants to tell us:
</P>
<P>
   Warhol truly is great. He is not just the seer of surface
appearance, but a profound ponderer on eternal truths _ one of
which, the brevity of earthly existence, is mirrored by the
phenomenon of modern celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol's ``Self-Portrait'' (1986) and ``Pistol'' (1982) join the
Modern's extremely important ``Twenty-five Colored Marilyns''
(1962), along with several Warhol works on paper. ``Twenty-Five
Colored Marilyns'' is placed in a Pop room with paintings by Roy
Lichtenstein, Gerhard Richter and Jess. Placement of the new
Warhols _ in the ``death'' gallery _ casts a shadow on the entire
pop assemblage, though.
</P>
<P>
   Painted in black and putrid green, Warhol's ``Self-Portrait''
immediately brings to mind representations of severed heads _ of
Goliath, Medusa and others _ held suspended by their hair. As to
``Pistol,'' Auping has installed it so that the gun's barrel points
directly at Warhol's skull-like self-image. (As an aside, Auping
notes that the gun in ``Pistol'' is similar to the one Valerie
Solana used to shoot the artist in 1968, nearly killing him.)
</P>
<P>
   German artist Anselm Kiefer's importance exceeds the reputation
he enjoyed in the late 1980s as an apologist, of sorts, for the
Holocaust. The Modern's recent purchase of ``Pope Alexander VI: The
Golden Bull'' (1996), which measures almost 12-by-20 feet, makes
this clear.
</P>
<P>
   But not just size counts here. What really matters is that the
Modern has purchased not only Kiefer, but a new Kiefer. For, as
high as Kiefer was flying in the United States a decade ago, he
fell hard in the early '90s: About that time, several of his most
vocal American fans decided that Kiefer and his new art lacked
relevance _ that he, and it, were simply bombastic.
</P>
<P>
   Auping thinks otherwise. Not only did he steer the Modern to
purchase an early Kiefer last year _ the artist's ``Quaternity''
(1973) _ but he is planning a survey of Kiefer's new works,
featuring ``Pope Alexander VI,'' for the Modern's new building,
which opens in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Auping says, Kiefer's art addresses the
co-existence of life and death, good and evil, and other universal
dualities. In ``Pope Alexander VI,'' an immense pyramid symbolizes
humanity's yearning for a transcendent good, while evil and
futility are expressed in the trails and smudges of gold leaf and
blood-red paint on its steps.
</P>
<P>
   All-American, abstract expressionist Jackson Pollock _ who with
his cohorts stole the flame of progressive art from Paris and
brought it to New York _ was more European than we might think.
Pollock was greatly influenced by Picasso, this show says, flanking
Picasso's ``Reclining Woman Reading'' (1960) with two early, subtly
figural Pollocks.
</P>
<P>
   This grouping also casts a favorable light on Picasso's late
work, which can take self-satire to an almost buffoonish extreme:
Here, though, he soberly reprises one of his major themes _ the
female model as an object of the artist's gaze.
</P>
<P>
   What else can we learn by looking?
</P>
<P>
   That photography is becoming more important, not less so, as a
fine art medium with its own message. Auping makes this point by
putting several photographs on view and by addressing interactions
between painting and photography. The Cindy Sherman, for example,
refers to Old Master paintings of ecclesiastic figures. Too, Andres
Serrano's large, richly hued and lighted photographs emulate
painting _ just as they are rooted in traditional photojournalism.
</P>
<P>
   That realist paintings of familiar-seeming subjects by artists
like Julie Bozzi, Scott Gentling and Robert Bechtle are far from
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gentling paints naturalist Jane Goodall surrounded
by oddly threatening objects, including an ape's skull. Even Dennis
Blagg's relatively tranquil landscape painting _ recently
purchased, along with four graphite drawings _ underscores the
anxiousness of these other works.
</P>
<P>
   But, enough already. We're not trying to tell you what to think
_ any more than the Modern is. Go and see for yourself. Art is
about ideas, but it's also about the pure pleasure of looking.
``Recent Acquisitions and Selections From the Permanent
Collection''
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 18: Museum hours are 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesday-Friday,
11 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday and noon-5 p.m. Sunday at the Modern Art
Museum of Fort Worth, 1309 Montgomery St.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
