<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OBSTRUCT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSTRUCTION OF JUSTICE IS MOST SERIOUS OF ALLEGATIONS ABOUT
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first article of impeachment against President
Richard Nixon that the House Judiciary Committee approved 24
summers ago charged Nixon with obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of actions the committee placed in that
category were Nixon's instructions to the CIA to block an FBI
investigation, his approval of hush-money payments to the Watergate
burglars, and his obtaining information from a federal prosecutor
in order to pass it along to aides who were under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky is in a different realm. But the prevailing view in
political circles is that the most serious accusations against the
president involve obstruction of justice and that these are the
matters Congress is most likely to focus on if it begins
consideration of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was just a question of perjury in a civil trial so that
he could protect his wife and daughter from embarrassment, that's
one thing,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said last week. ``But if, in
fact, there is obstruction of justice or he did counsel others to
lie under oath or if he conspired to do these things, these are all
felonies and they're very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr has been investigating a
number of questions about Clinton's conduct that could fall into
the category of obstruction of justice. These are apparently the
main ones:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did the president urge Ms. Lewinsky to lie about their
relationship in her testimony in the Paula Jones lawsuit?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did he tell Ms. Lewinsky to give presents he had given her _ a
dress, a brooch and a hatpin _ to his secretary, Betty Currie, to
keep them out of the hands of Ms. Jones' lawyers?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was he instrumental in preparing the ``talking points'' meant
to coach former White House secretary Linda Tripp in preparation
for her testimony about the president in the Jones lawsuit?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did he try to shape Mrs. Currie's testimony about his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did he have his friend Vernon Jordan arrange for a job for Ms.
Lewinsky in return for her false testimony?
</P>
<P>
   In the Nixon case, much of the evidence of obstruction of
justice was on tape, in Nixon's own words. The evidence against
Clinton is much less clear.
</P>
<P>
   For example, lawyers familiar with Ms. Lewinsky's account have
said she testified that she and Clinton discussed possible cover
stories but that he never asked her to lie. Ms. Lewinsky also
testified that she alone was the author of the ``talking points,''
the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the gifts, the lawyers report that Ms. Lewinsky has said
that Clinton told her: ``If you don't have them, you can't turn
them over.'' It is unclear whether this was an idle observation, a
command or something in between.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers said that Mrs. Currie told investigators last
winter that the president walked her through an account of his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky by asking leading questions like,
``We were never alone, right?'' But there has been no indication
that Mrs. Currie said the president asked her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has said publicly that he helped Ms. Lewinsky find a job
at Mrs. Currie's request, not the president's.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law against obstruction of justice is unusually
broad. It applies, in one section, to someone who ``knowingly uses
intimidation . . . threatens or corruptly persuades another person
. . . with intent to influence, delay or prevent the testimony of
any person in an official proceeding.'' The maximum penalty is 10
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes obstruction cases are cut and dried, involving, say,
destroying documents, coercing jurors or paying witnesses to change
their testimony. This was the situation in Watergate, when former
White House aides H.R. Haldeman and John Ehrlichman and former
Attorney General John Mitchell were convicted of trying to buy the
silence of the Watergate burglars.
</P>
<P>
   In another prominent case, Teamsters president Jimmy Hoffa went
to prison for obstruction of justice, in his case for jury
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases like Clinton's can be more subtle, and may depend,
for instance, on how one interprets a conversation a defendant had
with a potential witness.
</P>
<P>
   Obstruction is often difficult to prove, lawyers say, but it is
often easier to prove than some other crimes, including perjury,
where the prosecutor must show not only that defendants
specifically lied but that they meant to lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obstruction of justice turns more on the global assessment of
the acts that were done _ whether the person was trying to
interfere with the process of finding facts,'' said Gerard Lynch, a
former prosecutor who now teaches criminal law at Columbia Law
School.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction need not succeed. All the prosecutor has to
prove is that an attempt was made. People are rarely charged with
obstruction of justice alone, Lynch said. Usually, he said, the
charge is added to other criminal charges to improve the prospects
of a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The law applies to civil as well as criminal cases, but
prosecutions are rarely brought for obstructing a civil lawsuit
like the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Washington trial lawyer Robert Luskin explained why. ``In civil
cases,'' he said, ``the trial process is almost always perfectly
well suited to protect the system. You don't need to have a
prosecutor involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never tried a civil case where someone wasn't lying about
something, but you don't say, `I'm going to call in a U.S. attorney
now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But in criminal cases, obstruction of justice is a defense
lawyer's nightmare. At their first meeting with clients, defense
lawyers say, they invariably warn the clients not to talk to anyone
in any circumstance about the case. Prosecutors, the lawyers
caution, might use the conversation, even if it seems innocuous, to
bring an obstruction of justice charge.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Silbert, who was the first Watergate prosecutor and who is
now a criminal defense lawyer in Washington, described his approach
this way: ``I will tell my client, `Look, they're investigating you
for X. Based on what I know, I don't think they have a very good
case. You can do something stupid and illegal and you can destroy
documents and get someone to lie, and you will give the government
a very easy case. If you don't do that, there may not be a case
against you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Luskin said that Clinton's personal lawyers must have warned the
president not to talk about the case. But based on reports of their
accounts, Clinton seems to have ignored the advice when he met with
Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs. Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Luskin recalled several instances when his clients had been
charged with obstruction after they disregarded his warning to keep
their mouths shut. ``It's very hard advice for people to take,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
