<P>
   BOEING-LAYOFFS (Seattle) After two years of building up
employment, The Boeing Co. is beginning its plan to cut up to
28,000 jobs by the end of next year with the first round of layoffs
scheduled to become effective in early December, according to
company documents. The first major round of federally mandated
60-day warn notices are scheduled to be issued to workers in
Boeing's commercial aircraft division Oct. 2, with the layoff
becoming effective Dec. 4. Also, wrap in that Boeing will announce
737 assembly line in California Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West and James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f''
category)
</P>
<P>
   WHALES-MAKAHS (Undated) Week after week, Will Anderson camped on
Baja beaches, lulled to sleep by the sound of gray whales spouting
and the rhythm of the tides. Each morning, he awoke to the
breathing of the great beasts. Now Anderson and activists like him
around the world have joined a passionate battle to stop the
Makah's whale hunt this fall off Washington's remote Olympic
Peninsula. It doesn't make a difference to Anderson, an organizer
with the Progressive Animal Welfare Society, that the Makah are an
indigenous people whose culture is defined by thousands of years of
hunting whales. To Anderson, hunting gray whales _ animals he calls
friendly and intelligent _ is just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Shukovsky. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GORTON (Washington) Sen. Slade Gorton's advocacy for
Microsoft is being rewarded with campaign contributions from
company executives. During the first six months of this year, 23
Microsoft executives have contributed to Gorton, even though the
state's 70-year-old senior senator isn't currently a candidate for
anything and hasn't announced whether he plans to seek re-election
in 2000. The contributions are far more numerous than ever received
by Gorton from the Redmond-based software giant. In 1997, he
received contributions from eight Microsoft executives, in 1996
none, and in 1995 he received just one contribution, from the
company chairman and chief executive officer, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Washington) Microsoft Corp. asked a U.S.
appeals court to block a judge's order that the public and press
may attend pretrial questioning of its billionaire Chief Executive
Bill Gates and other witnesses in the antitrust case against the
software giant. Summary from wires.
</P>
