<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYANMAR-COX     08-12 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYANMAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young U.S. activist in custody in Myanmar
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young idealists, they simply wanted to make a quiet statement in
support of democracy. But the simple act of handing out leaflets
has landed 18 foreign activists, including Atlantan Nisha Anand, in
police custody in Myanmar, the Asian nation formerly known as
Burma.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have yet been filed, but the democracy advocates _
six of them Americans and four, like Anand, students at American
University in Washington _ could be sentenced to as long as 10
years in jail if convicted of violating the censorship laws
enforced by Myanmar's military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were going, but I didn't know they were doing
this,'' said Doug Steele, spokesman for the Washington-based
nonprofit The Burma Fund. The group initially traveled to Southeast
Asia to visit a Burmese refugee camp just inside Thailand. The
students from American University had raised several thousand
dollars for the refugees with a dinner earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets they later handed out in Myanmar's capital, Yangon,
carried the message ``Don't forget _ Don't give up'' and the date
8-8-88, a reference to Aug. 8, 1988, when soldiers fired on a
pro-democracy demonstration, killing many civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Anand graduated from American University this spring, and is
scheduled to begin graduate study there this fall. She and others
in the group were described by friends and family as ``very
idealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very much into peace and love,'' said her mother, Ginny
Guzman of Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were handing out pamphlets. That's all they were doing,''
said Matt McMillan, a friend of Anand who works for her father,
Vijay, at Canterbury Engineering in Chamblee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   But that can be dangerous in Myanmar, where police arrested the
activists Sunday and then held them for questioning without
allowing them access to their governments' embassies until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State television showed pictures of the group Wednesday and
reported that all were being treated well. Anand, who suffers from
asthma, has been allowed to receive medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The government could opt to deport the detainees _ including
three Thais, three Malaysians, three Indonesians, two Filipinos and
one Australian _ but officials said they are still investigating
the incident. The Agence France-Presse news agency quoted state
television as reporting Tuesday that the activists had been trained
in sabotage and were intent on destablizing the country. The charge
was characterized as ludicrous by supporters of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Anand said his daughter believes in civil disobedience but
is firmly committed to nonviolent methods. ``Obviously, as parents,
we support her. But (this situation) is very tough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Smith (R-N.J.), chairman of the House International
Relations Subcommittee on International Operations and Human
Rights, is attempting to gain entry into Myanmar to verify the
group's safety. Smith left Washington for Thailand Wednesday to
press Burmese officials to grant him a visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``A denial of my visa will only raise the specter that the
Burmese military government does not want a speedy resolution of
this crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Steele said the situation is very tense because Myanmar's
national economy is in collapse and pro-democracy groups have
called for a mass campaign of civil disobedience if the military
does not allow a parliament, elected in 1990, to be seated by Aug.
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking on this. They could end up as hostages,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Samar Abulhassan of the Cox Washington Bureau contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
