<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL     08-12 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGLEWOOD INNOVATION, MUSICAL AND OTHERWISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ The administrative battles at the Tanglewood
Music Center during the last 18 months seem to have had little
effect on the center's annual Festival of Contemporary Music, held
here this past week. That's not to say that the festival has
proceeded without change; and clearly there is more change to come.
But this festival has evolved steadily over decades, and few of
this year's changes seem to be echoes of the broader skirmish over
control of the center.
</P>
<P>
   One change that clearly is linked to the shake-up is Seiji
Ozawa's involvement. His conducting the student orchestra in
Takemitsu's ``November Steps'' in the final concert was regarded as
emblematic of the Boston Symphony Orchestra's assertion of dominion
over its summer music school, and the consensus here is that this
is a change for the better.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser change is that the festival, once a week long, has been
compressed to five days. But by offering concerts in the afternoons
and evenings _ and on Sunday at 10:30 a.m. _ it offered the same
number of performances as in recent years: six concerts and three
preconcert recitals, plus a partly related Boston Symphony
performance.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, a troubling paucity of student works. In
past years, a few were heard on the main programs, including an
annually commissioned orchestral work. No commission was made last
year, and at this year's festival the only work by a recent
Tanglewood student was the String Quartet No. 3 by Shih-Hui Chen (a
1996 alumna), performed by the Arditti String Quartet in the
opening concert.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of the Arditti and Reinbert de Leeuw, the Dutch
conductor who has directed the festival since 1994, argues that it
has not lost its credibility in new-music circles, as did an
appearance by Peter Serkin and the presiding presences of two
composers in residence, Henri Dutilleux and Mauricio Kagel, and
several other composers, among them Elliott Carter, Charles
Wuorinen and George Perle.
</P>
<P>
   This was de Leeuw's final festival; although he described the
recent administrative upheaval as saddening, he said that he had
always intended to hand over the reins after five years.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he has used this year's festival to restate an
inclusive view of contemporary music in which abstraction and
programmatic writing, intellectual severity and inviting populism,
soulfulness and mechanical intricacy, and sobriety and pranks
intermingle freely and draw on one another's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One of Kagel's works, ``General Bass,'' for solo accordion,
moved slowly; used easy, repeated intervals, and sounded like a
merciless parody of Minimalism. Yet Minimalism also had an honored
place at the table. de Leeuw led the orchestra in an account of
John Adams' ``Shaker Loops'' (1978, revised 1982) that brought out
the work's shifting chromatic nuances beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' newer piano duet, ``Hallelujah Junction'' (1998), though,
seemed oddly plodding; it could be that the student pianists were
unable to create the rhythmically pointed barrelhouse effect that
Adams was seeking, and ended up pounding instead.
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation of composers has grafted Minimalist
practices onto other styles: ``Song X,'' a piano work by Kenneth
Lampl, brought together Minimalist figuration and chordal melodies
that would be at home on a Dave Brubeck album. Jazz with an early
Miles Davis accent, as well as stylized references to flamenco,
made fleeting incursions by way of Thomas Ades' programmatic
dreamscape, ``Living Toys.''
</P>
<P>
   And rock found a back door into the festival through Matthew
Guerrieri's String Quartet (1998), a gorgeous, harmonically
ambiguous work in which the central movement is based on the chord
progression from the Beach Boys' ``God Only Knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Kagel's ``General Bass'' was unlike any of his other works at
the festival, yet a quirky sense of humor came through virtually
all of them. Often he amuses through harmonic surprises and
peculiar juxtapositions. In Quartet No. 4 (1993), which the Arditti
gave a tightly polished reading, the clever dissection of a
folklike melody was among the tricks in his arsenal. ``Westen,''
which Kagel conducted, hints at a cultural exchange gone haywire:
percussion instruments evoke African rhythms, and the rest of the
orchestra brings a European perspective. But while the interplay
suggests curiosity on both sides, the two styles never find common
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Kagel's works, ``Fuerst Igor, Stravinsky'' (1982),
memorializes Stravinsky by way of a laconic, almost spoken
resetting of an aria from Borodin's ``Prince Igor.'' And his
``Etudes for Large Orchestra'' (1992-96) _ the final works played
at the festival, on Monday evening _ traded in big gestures and
strange combinations: a slow tuba melody, for example, overlaid
with a flurry of flutes. Kagel's ``Etudes,'' conducted by de Leeuw,
was also the most vivid display of how finely polished the
Tanglewood Music Center orchestra is.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the evidence was otherwise lacking. All through the
festival, the young musicians gave mostly stunning performances of
a demanding slate of chamber works, and when they came together for
the finale, they communicated freshness, excitement and a sense of
occasion. They supplied all the color and energy Peter Lieberson
demands in his ``Fire'' (1995), conducted by Stefan Asbury.
</P>
<P>
   And in Dutilleux's violin concerto, ``L'Arbre des Songes''
(1983-85), conducted by de Leeuw, they supplied the gossamer
textures necessary to support Irvine Arditti's eloquent reading of
the angular yet melodic solo line.
</P>
<P>
   In Takemitsu's ``November Steps,'' the players at first seemed
slightly at sea, but after a tentative start, Ozawa was able to
draw a confident performance from them. Like Kagel's ``Westen,''
this is a cross-cultural work in which assimilation proves
impossible. The Japanese instruments _ the lutelike biwa, played by
Kakujo Nakamura, and the shakuhachi flute, played by Katsuya
Yokoyama, both flown in from Japan for the performances _ hold the
spotlight so thoroughly that the orchestral music seems almost an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Dutilleux's music was plentifully represented, and argued that
he should have a higher profile in the standard repertory. In works
like ``Ainsi la Nuit'' (1976), played by the Arditti, or ``Les
Citations'' (1985-90), a chamber piece with a supremely beautiful
oboe line, rendered with graceful virtuosity by Carolyn Banham, one
had to admire Dutilleux's magically shifting textures.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath his appealing surfaces though, Dutilleux speaks of
troubling issues: the second movement of ``Les Citations'' and
``The Shadows of Time,'' in which Ozawa led the Boston Symphony on
Sunday afternoon, come to terms with the dark side of the soul
through allusions to war and death.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights are too numerous to discuss, but a few that
should be noted are Serkin's impassioned reading of Messiaen's
``Couleurs de la Cite Celeste'' (1963), with de Leeuw conducting;
Robert Zuidam's ``Nella Citta Dolente'' (1998), with its
magnificent eight-part vocal counterpoint; Wuorinen's ``River of
Light'' (1997), a shimmering, dramatically propulsive dance work,
and Carter's tough-edged and surprisingly lyrical Clarinet Concerto
(1996), played with vibrant virtuosity by Thomas Martin, with
Asbury conducting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
