<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSIES-RISK-BOS &LR;      08-12 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-RISK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE `GARDEN SPOTS' AMONG US EMBASSIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS   AND ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When bombs ripped apart two US embassies last week,
the losses were not limited to people and property. A way of life
disappeared, too.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats, secretaries and accountants who work at America's
288 embassies and consulates around the world have long divided
foreign postings into high-risk and low-risk assignments. But
Friday's bombings showed that even safer countries bring an
unexpected hazard: They have accessible, minimally protected
embassies that make inviting targets for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there really is the sense that no place is safe, not
even the so-called garden spots,'' said Myles Frechette, who has
served as an embassy official and ambassador in Latin America and
Africa during a 35-year career the Foreign Service.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department employee who has served in turbulent
countries in the former Soviet Union and elsewhere, put it this
way: ``It's hard to know where you can go and work without
endangering your family. ... This is a topic a lot of people are
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other employees interviewed, he is not authorized to
talk to the press and did not want to jeopardize his chances of
getting a desireable post the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the embassy bombings in Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam, young Foreign Service officers with children and officers
nearing retirement say they are reconsidering where they want to be
assigned, and even whether they should leave the professional
diplomatic corps.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat stationed in Central America during the civil wars
there of the 1980s and Colombia during the drug cartel bombings of
the early 1990s was considering a posting in east Africa to
decompress at the end of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. ``I had been telling my daughter, `We'll go on
safaris,''' she said, ``but after Friday's attacks, she was reading
the newspaper and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Miller, vice president of the American Foreign Service
Association, an organization of 23,000 active and retired members,
said those heading overseas consider everything from E-coli
outbreaks and blood supplies tainted by AIDS to air pollution and
threats from international terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're putting your health at risk, you're family's health at
risk, and sometimes your life at risk,'' he said. ``It scares a lot
of people. The risks seem to be growing.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, US government agencies find it increasingly
difficult to fill jobs overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many veteran diplomats, Miller bristles at the image of
``striped-suit'' American envoys sipping wine at plush receptions.
In his 30 year-career, he has endured a police uprising in Cairo, a
threat of a coup in the Dominican Republic and tear gas wafting
through the air during a student rebellion in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Foreign Service and civil service employees who
work in US posts overseas have long realized that some countries
have unstable governments, poor hygiene and assorted hazards. The
State Department ranks assignments by threats from terrorism,
street crime and counterintelligence spying.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings include critical (such as Lebanon), high (Colombia,
Israel and Egypt), medium (Brazil) and low (France). The toughest
assignments come with salary bonuses of up to 40 percent for
hardship and danger duty.
</P>
<P>
   Five US ambassadors have been killed in the past three decades,
all in countries considered unstable or dangerous: Guatemala,
Sudan, Cyprus, Lebanon and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Nairobi, a large embassy that serves as a regional hub for the
State Department and other US agencies in east Africa, was
considered a desirable, low-risk assignment, aside from pervasive
street crime. As Frechette put it, ``The living is good, the food
is good and the disease level is good.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the US embassy hugged a downtown street clogged
with trucks and vendors. It did not have the high walls and small
windows that the US government has required of embassies built
since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's powerful bomb killed 12 Americans working at the
embassy _ more than any attack on a ``high-risk'' US embassy this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Pfaltzgraff, professor at Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University, said the bombings prove that
terrorism hits beyond those places traditionally considered
dangerous. ``If the goal is to strike at United States property,
United States citizens, it doesn't matter where you do it,'' he
said. ``You could do it in Tanzania, Kenya, or the very smallest
country with which we have diplomatic relations.''
</P>
<P>
   At the United States Information Agency, an employee who has
worked in Africa said the US government's rankings of threats tend
to be misleading. Argentina, for example, is rated as one of the
safest places and even the name of its capital, ``Buenos Aires,''
means ``good air.'' Yet in 1992, a bomb exploded at the Israeli
embassy in Buenos Aires, killing 30 people inside and next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last week, a lot of us have been wondering how to define
a safe post,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Wednesday that it is putting together
a proposal to increase embassy security around the world and will
soon release an estimate of the cost. But spokesman P.J. Crowley
said Washington does not want to isolate its diplomats abroad.
``We're not going to create a 'fortress America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Frechette said the irony for American
diplomats is that hostile Communist countries were often the safest
places to live. State security operations, which closely watched
foreign diplomats, ensured that the Americans were not robbed,
killed or kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   The new threats started to emerge with the end of the Cold War,
not the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, Frechette added. He knows.
When he began his careeer in the Foreign Service in 1963, terrorism
was a new threat. Since then, he has endured uprisings and a storm
of locusts in Chad as well as a Libyan plot to kill him in
Camaroon, where he was ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   While serving as ambassador to Colombia, he rode in a helicopter
that was shot at by drug traffickers. Because of constant death
threats from guerrillas, he drove in a bulletproof car escorted by
vehicles filled with bodyguards everywhere he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always avoided assignments in Europe because I thought they
were too boring,'' he said. ``I would have fallen asleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
