<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-710&AMP;A     08-12 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO REBELLION A WAR OF WORDS AS WELL AS BULLETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ In this capital struck with war fever, the day
began with a breathless government announcement that made the
improbable claim that it had retaken the eastern provincial capital
of Bukavu and was building up for a knockout punch against rebel
positions throughout eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels are eager not to lose the edge in a war that
seems to have become as much a battle of the airwaves as one of
enemies captured and body counts. A mutinous commander who was
regaling foreign journalists in the eastern regions quickly issued
a statement that the rebels who were leading a week-old uprising
against President Laurent Kabila were using their own DC-10
jetliner to ferry troops and weapons several times a day to a
fallen military base not far from this city.
</P>
<P>
   Even the normally reserved foreign diplomats who concede that
they are largely at a loss to know what is occurring felt the urge
to guffaw at that. ``Really,'' one diplomat asked, ``I think that
is a bit much, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   While agreed-on facts are about as slim as they come, what is
well established is that a sporadically violent conflict is under
way. On one side is the man whom foreign diplomats and many
Congolese consider a novice and a politically maladroit president.
On the other side are many of the people who helped put him in
power just over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For Kabila the conflict is an outright invasion from his former
sponsors to the east, Rwanda and Uganda. Once again, he says, those
countries have allied with the community of Congolese Tutsi,
long-ago immigrants from Rwanda, who provided the backbone for
Kabila's own rebellion two years ago. This time, he contends
however, their aim is to annex territory.
</P>
<P>
   One form that revenge has taken is the old-fashioned witch hunt.
Thousands of Tutsi and people suspected of being Tutsi by virtue of
their appearance have been rounded up, and some have been beaten.
They are held at a military base for what the government now calls
``protective custody.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents say theirs is an authentic uprising of soldiers
and people thoroughly fed up with a leader whom they had hoped
would transform the country, but has instead turned out to be a
poor-man's copy of Mobutu Sese Seko, the dictator whom Kabila
overthrew.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say it is certain that Rwanda has supported the
rebels, providing logistical help in the east and lending at least
some officers who seem to have carefully planned and executed the
effort to oust Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   That drive has included a quick seizure of the border cities in
the east and a stunning move by hijacked plane to capture a
military base in the far west, from which the rebels might strangle
or capture the capital. Whatever the claims on both sides, there
has been little action since.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the western base at Kitona, the rebels are known to
have scattered thousands of soldiers, both recent recruits and
members of Mobutu's disgraced army who were being ``re-educated.''
Congolese familiar with the army say where they have gone and where
their loyalties lie is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Just as uncertain is the fate of the 15,000 or more young
Congolese who are said to have volunteered for the war in the week
that the government has been pressing for volunteers who can be
rushed into service. The hate for Rwandans is so strong here that
young men can be seen sleeping overnight near the stadium that is
the recruiting site be sure they will enroll first thing in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Little else is clear, either, except that those who can afford
to flee have been taking the threat of generalized violence
seriously enough to begin leaving in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Lebanon have chartered jets for
evacuations. On Tuesday, South Africa Airways used a Boeing 747
jumbo jet for its regular run here rather than a much smaller
Airbus because of the huge number of people who had bought one-way
tickets out. At last count the waiting list for the flight on
Thursday stood at 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just plain weary of all the trouble,'' one
departing businessman said. ``But what has made it even worse is
that nobody seems to have any idea of what is going on or what is
about to happen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rumors eagerly propagated by both sides stoke that uncertainty.
In a representative hour Wednesday one visitor heard these claims:
The Mozambican air force is flying sorties in support of Kabila,
Cuba and Libya have begun supplying the government troops and arms,
the rebels have cut the oil pipeline for the capital and the sole
seaport, Matadi, is in the process of falling to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the disinformation is that in Kabila's
seven-month rebellion against Mobutu, wild propaganda by the
invaders proved to be an even better weapon than infantry assault.
By merely announcing the arrival of his troops days before they
appeared, Kabila's public relations representatives, many of whom
are now working for the rebels, often managed to send the enemy
fleeing westward.
</P>
<P>
   The problem this time, however, is that both sides are engaging
in the same tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the government felt that it needed to say it had
retaken Bukavu, 1,000 miles northeast of Kinshasa on the Rwandan
border, one government official here said sheepishly, ``Because the
enemy keeps saying how close it is to Kinshasa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
