<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TEACHING-TEST-BOS &LR;      08-12 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHING-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2D CERTIFICATION TEST STUMPS HALF OF TEACHING CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Almost half of aspiring teachers failed the second
certification test in July, according to results released
Wednesday, just as the outrage was subsiding over the 59 percent of
would-be teachers who failed Massachusetts' first test in April.
</P>
<P>
   Although the results are slightly better than those from the
April test, they are still not acceptable, state education
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 47 percent of 2,500 teaching candidates failed the July
test. About 700 of the July candidates were retaking all or part of
the test they failed the first time. Of the 148 who failed the
entire test the first time, only 6 percent -- nine people -- passed
it this time. All candidates can take the test again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the handwriting is on the wall. Those people need to
consider another career,'' said Interim Education Commissioner
David Driscoll. ``I think the focus needs to be on attracting the
best and brightest, and then a 100 percent (pass rate) won't sound
so unattainable. That's a reasonable goal for basic literacy and
subject matter tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improvement in the passing rate, no one in the
state's educational hierarchy was celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly doesn't do any good for the morale of teachers
that are already in the classroom,'' said Stephen Gorrie, president
of the Massachusetts Teachers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci again blamed the low scores on the
colleges and universities that train future teachers. ``The problem
is not with the test,'' he said. ``The problem is with people
coming out of the teacher colleges who are not prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci reiterated his proposal to require all schools of
education to have 80 percent of their graduating prospective
teachers pass the test to retain state accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, testing experts Wednesday said no inferences can be
made about why the second batch of test-takers did better than the
first, particularly on the writing portion, because the Department
of Education and the testing company have yet to release
information about how the test was put together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know enough about the test,'' said George Madaus, a
Boston College education professor whose speciality is testing and
assessment. ``They say they equated these two tests, which is a
technical term. But I would like to know how they did that. Until I
know that, it is impossible to know whether the two tests weren't
comparable.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the April and July tests were both reviewed
for fairness, and found to be equally challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The exam comprises three parts: Basic comprehension skills,
divided into reading and writing, as well as a teacher candidate's
speciality, such as math or art.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight percent of those who took the test in July for the
first time passed the writing portion, compared to only 59 percent
in April. And 80 percent passed the reading portion, compared to 70
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe part of the answer is that the extraordinary public
attention to the April results led July candidates to take the
tests more seriously,'' Driscoll said. He said a report on how
students from different universities performed on the test will be
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sophi Sagall, an Emerson College student seeking to become a
drama teacher, said she failed the reading portion of the July test
by four points and will have to retake that portion at the next
test Oct. 3. She is slated to begin teaching drama at Wellesley
High School in September, but does not know how the school will
react to her failing the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous going in because of the attention,'' Sagall said
Wednesday. ``I knew no matter what score I got, I would be under
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was probably more prepared than the April
test-takers because she was able to talk with friends about the
questions, finding out for example that some questions required
definitions of such terms as ``preposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many state lawmakers were on vacation this week and
not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Harold Lane Jr. (D-Holden), a former school
principal and co-chairman of the Legislature's education committee,
said he was pleased the pass rate had inched up, ``but it is not
enough. We have to be more attentive to how we prepare students.
And the deans of education schools are committed to doing something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
