Friday's bombings showed that even safer countries bring an
unexpected hazard: They have accessible, minimally protected
embassies that make inviting targets for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there really is the sense that no place is safe, not
even the so-called garden spots,'' said Myles Frechette, who has
served as an embassy official and ambassador in Latin America and
Africa during a 35-year career the Foreign Service.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department employee who has served in turbulent
