Diplomacy at Tufts University, said the bombings prove that
terrorism hits beyond those places traditionally considered
dangerous. ``If the goal is to strike at United States property,
United States citizens, it doesn't matter where you do it,'' he
said. ``You could do it in Tanzania, Kenya, or the very smallest
country with which we have diplomatic relations.''
</P>
<P>
   At the United States Information Agency, an employee who has
worked in Africa said the US government's rankings of threats tend
to be misleading. Argentina, for example, is rated as one of the
safest places and even the name of its capital, ``Buenos Aires,''
means ``good air.'' Yet in 1992, a bomb exploded at the Israeli
embassy in Buenos Aires, killing 30 people inside and next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last week, a lot of us have been wondering how to define
a safe post,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Wednesday that it is putting together
a proposal to increase embassy security around the world and will
soon release an estimate of the cost. But spokesman P.J. Crowley
said Washington does not want to isolate its diplomats abroad.
``We're not going to create a 'fortress America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Frechette said the irony for American
diplomats is that hostile Communist countries were often the safest
places to live. State security operations, which closely watched
foreign diplomats, ensured that the Americans were not robbed,
killed or kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   The new threats started to emerge with the end of the Cold War,
not the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, Frechette added. He knows.
When he began his careeer in the Foreign Service in 1963, terrorism
was a new threat. Since then, he has endured uprisings and a storm
of locusts in Chad as well as a Libyan plot to kill him in
Camaroon, where he was ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   While serving as ambassador to Colombia, he rode in a helicopter
that was shot at by drug traffickers. Because of constant death
threats from guerrillas, he drove in a bulletproof car escorted by
vehicles filled with bodyguards everywhere he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always avoided assignments in Europe because I thought they
were too boring,'' he said. ``I would have fallen asleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
