</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Iraq is not only freezing all
current U.N. weapons inspections but is also threatening the
long-term monitoring that is crucial to preventing the country from
producing weapons of mass destruction in the future, U.N. officials
say. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With: IRAQ-U.N.-BUTLER.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET-EXPLOSION (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ A giant Titan 4 Air
Force rocket carrying a classified military spy satellite exploded
shortly after liftoff. It was hoisting a secret satellite for the
National Reconnaissance Office that reportedly cost $1 billion.
With graphic and photo.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ A news analysis on the ruling
Taliban militia's sweep of northern Afghanistan and what it means
to the country. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-POLITICS (Boston) _ This has got to be the most fun you can
have in Massachusetts politics without a Kennedy. Precisely because
a Kennedy is leaving the 8th Congressional District, suddenly
candidates without the best brand name in American politics have a
shot at hallowed ground: the kingmaker district that gave John F.
Kennedy his start in national politics and long served as home base
to the late leonine speaker of the House, Tip O'Neill. Vying for
the seat is a sharp-elbowed, capacious-pocketed field of 10 _ count
them, 10 _ strong Democrats. By Carey Goldberg. With graphic and
photo. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS BANKS-NAZIS (Undated) _ A Swiss fund to help needy
Holocaust survivors will make payments to some 2,000 Gypsies in
Germany, a fund spokesman say. (early summary)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Once again, the bargain hunters tiptoe back
into the stock market, picking up some of the issues battered in
the previous day's downdraft. This buying of small-company, oil,
semi-conductor and other beleaguered stocks repeats the pattern
that led the stock market to rebound at the end of last week, after
the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 299.43 points on Aug. 4,
its third worst point decline in history. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
With graphic.
