<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN AGAINST ROYALS ALL PART OF GORDON'S SCHOOLING AS CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lesson 42 in the ongoing education of Tom Gordon as a
closer came Tuesday night against the Royals. ``That was big what
happened,'' he said. ``I learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon was called into a tie game by Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams after a rain delay with two outs in the eighth, he didn't
feel right. He has been a closer for all of one season now, and all
those years of starting have not been erased from his psyche. As
Gordon learned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that he didn't trust his fastball or was worried about
his specialty, the killer curveball. The problem was his mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why,'' said Gordon, ``but I felt as if I were
starting the game instead of coming in to relieve. I found myself
pacing myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A starter paces himself. A starter can pick his spots to throw
this pitch or that. A starter thinks of the long term, five or six
or seven innings down the road. A reliever can do none of the
above. A reliever must produce immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a different feel when I got out on the mound,'' said
Gordon. ``I felt like a starter, so it took me a while to get
myself motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gordon surrendered the go-ahead run in the top of
the ninth before the Red Sox took him off the hook with a run in
the bottom of the inning and made him a winner with Nomar
Garciaparra's three-run homer in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that glitch, Gordon has made a remarkable transformation
from starter to one of baseball's best closers. He has 32 saves,
including 29 in a row, and has blown only one save opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In adapting to his new role, Gordon has had to alter his
pitching rhythm. Intsead of being ready every fifth day, for
instance, he must be ready on call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feeling I had (Tuesday) is not a kind of feeling that I
want to have,'' he said. ``But later in the game when they had
runners on base, that's when I started to pick it up (mentally).''
</P>
<P>
   It's an old problem for closers. Bring a closer in to close a
game and he's ready. Bring a closer in with a huge lead or deficit
(just to get work, for instance) or into a tie game, then a
closer's focus is not always as sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come into a game and you know the game's on the
line,'' said Gordon, ``you can pretty much get yourself into that
frame of mind right away. But right now it's still very new to me,
and that's why I felt the way I felt (Tuesday). If it had been a
save situation and I knew I was coming into the game to save it or
maybe we had a couple of more runs, I probably wouldn't have felt
like I was starting the game. I might have been sharper earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he felt confident he could be a closer when he was
given the word a year ago this month ``because I've always had an
aggressive attitude even when I was a starter. What I remember is
that I used to give everything I had early in a game and then if I
got into a tough situation, I was almost out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a closer, he doesn't have to worry about saving himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a starter, there was a lot of thinking,'' said
Gordon. ``But now ... it's just `bam!' Don't think, go out there
with your stuff, and get three outs. Get your outs, finish this
game, and go home. I don't have a lot of time to think out there
and I don't want to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, old habits die hard. Gordon pointed toward the locker of
Dennis Eckersley, another starter turned closer, and said, ``Those
guys who've been doing it for years know how to snap mentally into
it. But me? I'm still learning. There've been times when I've
gotten up (to warm up) and I didn't have good stuff, but I've been
able to focus and still get myself ready. But to say what exactly I
did to pinpoint my mind, I can't say. When I don't feel as pumped
up right away, I try to think of something to get me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, getting the save is enough to pump up any closer.
Gordon conceded he had problems earlier in the season coming into
non-save situations but has found a way to get into focus hours
before he takes the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell myself I'm pitching every day. That helps me out,''
said Gordon. ``I say to myself, `I'm pitching today,' and I keep
repeating that to myself. When I walk out to the bullpen in the
sixth, that's what I'm telling myself: `I'm coming in.' But what I
learned (Tuesday) is that I sometimes still have that attitude as a
starter.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gordon still didn't feel right when he took the
mound, even though he got Mike Sweeney to pop up to end the eighth.
``I had my good curveball,'' he said, ``but I didn't have my good
spot fastball.'' And the Royals took advantage in the ninth before
Gordon settled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud,'' he said. ``I didn't feel right and I didn't
have my (best) stuff, but I came back and I learned something new.
After all, I'm still pretty new at this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
