<HEADLINE>
SONY FACES UP TO NAKED TRUTH, STOPS SHIPPING VIDEO CAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY AND HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was Candid Camera. Now there is Naked Camera.
</P>
<P>
   Under ideal conditions and with a special filter, a new Sony
video camera can see through some bikinis and T-shirts, turning a
bathing beauty's day at the beach into a birthday-suit peep show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 14-year-old boy is going to want one of these,'' said
Bob Moisan, general manager of a camera and video store near
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The video cameras are from a new line made by Sony Corp., and
several models include an infrared option called NightShot that
allows videophiles to take footage in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   But much to the embarrassment of the consumer-electronics king,
a Japanese magazine reported that the X-ray like properties of
NightShot gave it the potential to qualify as the one of the
biggest advances in softcore pornography since Hugh Hefner invented
the Playboy centerfold.
</P>
<P>
   When used by day, a NightShot-equipped camera can make the
Spandex of a swimsuit seem as diaphanous as cellophane, the
magazine reported.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Sony said it was halting shipment of the original
models of the camera, which can retail from about $600 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Sony insists that NightShot was designed with purely innocent
intentions. With the ``NightShot'' feature, nature buffs can study
the nocturnal habits of the coyote and the owl, and parents can
record their children's hijinks after dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intended for such night-time activities as a baby
sleeping, or children out on a Halloween night, or carollers at
Christmas time,'' said Sony spokeswoman Dulcie Neiman.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something else ``NightShot'' could do. When used
with one of the camera's filters in bright sunlight, NightShot &UR;  &LR; can
sometimes yield images that make flimsily clad people appear to be
naked. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen all the time,'' acknowledged Sony spokesman
Rick Clancy. ``But it does happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though 400,000 cameras with the NightShot feature &UR;  &LR; have
been shipped to North America, few people in the United States
seemed to have been aware of NightShot's voyeuristic powers until
wire stories began to move out of Tokyo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my!'' said product specialist Shameem Siddiqui of Best
Buy, an electronics chain about to open stores near Boston, when he
was told of the camera's X-ray capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Circuit City was equally surprised.
</P>
<P>
   While the NightShot in its original form might appeal to some
consumers, Sony has moved quickly to modify the camera. Newer
versions will produce only a blank screen when the NightShot
feature is activated during daylight, Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Once radio reports began airing Wednesday about cameras that
could eye-pop a peeping Tom, inquiries started flooding Newtonville
Camera &AMP; Video.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had phone calls galore,'' said manager Moisan, adding,
``Everybody wanted to know about the naked camera.''
</P>
<P>
   But try as he might, Moisan couldn't get any of the NightShot
-equipped Sony cameras in his store to ``see through'' clothing.
The images that appeared in the cameras' viewers were more
reminiscent of the ``X-Files'' than an X-rated movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of surrealistic and eerie looking,'' Moisan said.
``Everything had a washed-out look, but you had the illusion of
seeing flesh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
