<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO APPEAL ORDER OPENING DEPOSITIONS TO PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. will appeal a federal judge's order
that pretrial questioning of its chairman, Bill Gates, and 16
employees in the government's antitrust action be opened to the
public and the news media, the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District Court refused
Wednesday to postpone the order he issued Tuesday that the
depositions of Gates and others take place soon so that the Sept. 8
trial date he has set is not delayed.
</P>
<P>
   With obvious reluctance, Jackson told a Microsoft lawyer, John
Warden, ``I am going to deny your motion for a stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's initial ruling to open the depositions came in
response to a motion from The New York Times, The Seattle Times and
the cable-television and online news units of Ziff-Davis, a
computer trade publisher. Their filing was joined by Reuters and
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The news organizations based their requests on a federal
antitrust law that says depositions taken in civil antitrust cases
``shall be open to the public as freely as are trials in open
court.''
</P>
<P>
   In hearings Wednesday and on Tuesday, Jackson made it clear that
he did not like the provision but felt bound to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department joined the news organizations Wednesday
in opposing Microsoft's request to postpone the depositions,
apparently out of fear that a postponement would delay the start of
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   In its court filing, the government said it had asked Congress
last year to repeal the 1913 act requiring open deposition taking,
but stated that Congress had failed to act, leaving the provision
``the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed. But even as he ordered the parties to work out
details for taking the depositions in public, he warned that the
process was likely to be complex and asked the two sides to come up
with answers to these questions, among others:
</P>
<P>
   _ How will the public be notified of the time and place of the
depositions?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the questioning be televised?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will reporters or others be allowed to bring cameras, cellular
phones or laptop computers into the room?
</P>
<P>
   _ How will seating be allocated among members of the news media
and the public?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the proceeding be closed when Gates or any of the other
16 Microsoft employees giving depositions discuss trade secrets?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a partial list of things that could be potential
problems,'' Jackson said after he had read a list of 20 or more
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Microsoft prepared to appeal, lawyers representing the
company and the government remained in the courtroom after
Wednesday's hearing and began trying to devise answers to the
judge's questions.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Microsoft has made it clear that it wanted
much longer to prepare for the trial. Last spring, the company
asked for a seven-month delay, but Jackson said he wanted to try
the case in September, and he has worked assiduously to push the
parties toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge had agreed Wednesday to Microsoft's request for a
postponement in the depositions, the trial date would almost
certainly have been pushed back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1935EDT &QL; 
