<SLUG> BC-BELL-IBEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC SETTLES WITH IBEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after reaching an agreement with its largest union, Bell
Atlantic Corp. announced Wednesday a tentative two-year pact with
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers that guarantees
union access to future jobs and prohibits layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached at 3:15 a.m., came hours after Bell
Atlantic and the Communications Workers of America announced a pact
with similar provisions. The agreement with CWA ended a two-day
strike by 73,000 telephone workers in 13 states and Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW, with 13,000 technicians, installers, repair workers
and operators in New England, is the largest telephone company
union in the region. The new contract will cover workers in
Massachusetts, Vermont, New Hampshire, Maine, and Rhode Island. The
two unions negotiated similar agreements that offer wage increases
of up to 3.8 percent the first year, and 4 percent the second year
of the pacts. Both agreements prohibit layoffs, limit the use of
outside contractors, and ensure union members will secure future
jobs involving Internet, multimedia communications and data
networking technologies _ jobs that are expected to be among the
fastest growing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Myles Calvey, business manager for IBEW Local 2222 in Boston,
said the new contract would be submitted to workers for a vote
within 20 days. The local has 3,700 members in greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest issue was contracting,'' said Calvey, who chaired
negotiations for 10 regional locals. ``We had a clause in the
former contract that prevented Bell Atlantic from using outside
contractors to install poles and cables. That language remained in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement ensures that we will continue to care for our
customers by providing them with outstanding service,'' Donald J.
Sacco, executive vice president of human resources, at Bell
Atlantic, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company also agreed to increase by 15 percent payments to
workers who resign from the company rather than be transferred to
another city or state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, IBEW officials will be allowed to initiate
organizing campaigns at newly created nonunion subsidiaries without
company interference.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sacco, pensions will increase by a minimum of 20
percent over the life of the agreement. Additionally, IBEW workers
will receive cash bonuses for maintaining service standards.
</P>
<P>
   James Green, a labor expert at the University of Massachusetts
in Boston, said the new contracts suggest that unions are
developing more expertise in forecasting and bargaining on future
changes in industry that could affect their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We are now seeing a trend on the part of unions to bargain
over the future direction of an industry,'' said Green. ``In the
past, unions were behind the curve in terms of understanding new
technological changes and re-engineering. They were simply in a
reactive position. That appears to be changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-AGRITOURISM-AR     08-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-AGRITOURISM-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TACHING, Germany: farm products.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   European Union officials acknowledge that since 1991, about $2.3
billion has been spent on programs to promote rural business
activities as alternatives to farming, about 40 percent of it for
farm vacations. Since most of those funds are distributed as grants
to match local government aid, the total figure Europe spent in the
period to promote farm vacations could be double that, or close to
$2 billion, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Yves Champetier, director of the European Association for
Information on Local Development, defended the spending, saying the
goal was to ``get away from direct subsidies to farmers and create
new viable activities.'' European funds, he said, go to restoring
dilapidated buildings, training farmers in hotel skills, promoting
traditional products and trades, and helping to market farm
holidays through travel agencies or Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Though they may not realize it, American tourists in Provence or
Tuscany are often the beneficiaries of European government aid to
farmers to restore old farm buildings and so prevent their gradual
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Thaller's family provides an example.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, after tractors replaced horses, the Thallers converted
an unused horse barn into guest rooms, then finished the attic of
their 137-year-old farmhouse, creating total accommodations for
about 20 guests. Now, on sunny August days, the Thallers' guests,
who pay about $13 a night for a room, poke around the barn or
descend a meadow to the Tachinger See, a pond for swimming, boating
and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Leafing through dog-eared guest books, Thaller's mother, Rosi,
points to names of families, mostly German, that have returned
again and again, providing 5 percent to 10 percent of the farm's
total income. ``It's more a little side thing,'' she said, adding
that it ``allows you to get nicer furniture, allow yourself things
you might not otherwise be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Thallers built a new cow barn with
subsidized loans from the Bavarian government, and Martin Thaller
wants to create a wine bar in the low stone vaults of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Bavaria is among Europe's most generous regions for farmers. A
five-year program begun in 1994 will provide a total of $1.2
billion, including funds from the regional government matched by
the European Union, to promote rural businesses as alternatives to
farming.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Reitzlein, an official in the Bavarian agriculture ministry
in Munich, says that about 7,000 of Bavaria's 185,000 working farms
take in paying guests, accounting for one-third the total number of
farms offering agritourism in Germany. This year, she said, to
better market the farms abroad, Germany's regional governments will
begin ranking them with a star system like that used for hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Europe continues, under international pressure, to
dismantle price supports for farm products, which will cut into
farm profits for farmers like Thaller and Lenzi. Under a government
plan called Agenda 2000, Bavaria will order farmers to cut milk
production by 15 percent to 20 percent so that the milk price will
rise, Thaller said.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, he said, not even tourism receipts will suffice
to keep his farm alive, and he will be forced to take outside work
as an electrician, a trade he learned before turning to farming.
Yet his optimism is unbroken. ``I like to assume things will get
better,'' Thaller said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuscany, Lenzi, 37, faces a similar struggle. He restored his
farm with grants from the regional government in Siena, matched by
European Union funds, and guests arrive in steady streams. But
wading through European farm policy complexities, a maze of price
supports and production quotas, is taxing, and the white Vernaccia
wine that is his specialty now commands a price of $98 per 100
liters, compared with $285 a decade ago. ``You won't get rich,'' he
said, then added with a wave of the hand at his cluster of small
stone buildings: ``But you're preserving what's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite government subsidies, Ms. Reitzlein of the Bavarian
agriculture ministry acknowledged that farm incomes in Bavaria ``do
not keep step'' with urban incomes and ``remain very depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giovanni Pacini, who is responsible for rural tourism in the
province of Siena, where more than 3,000 farms, including Lenzi's,
take in guests, points to thousands of ancient villages, churches
and farm buildings that have been saved from sure destruction. ``An
enormous patrimony has been rescued,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosi Thaller says there is yet another benefit _ that farmhouse
guests have introduced her six children, including Martin Thaller,
to a world they otherwise would not have known. ``Our kids visited
with the guests' kids, and our kids benefited,'' she said. ``They
went along to museums, saw things they otherwise wouldn't have
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous enrichment for us and for our children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
