<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-Q&AMP;A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons Q&AMP;A with Bob Whitfield
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes it's difficult to figure Atlanta's Bob
Whitfield, one of the top young offensive tackles in the NFL. He's
sometimes quiet, occasionally irritated, frequently funny and
almost always thinking. Sometimes he's dominant on the field;
sometimes he seems indifferent. He first played in the NFL in 1992,
at age 20, and became a full-time starter the next season. He has
started every game for the Falcons for five-straight years, the
last four years at left tackle. He also owns his own studio,
PatchWerk Recordings, in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: There has been quite a bit of fuss over the importance of
quarterback Chris Chandler staying healthy. Does it make any
difference to you whether you're blocking for a quarterback with a
track record for injury or if you're blocking for a guy who clearly
makes such a difference in how the team fares?
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield: He's a good quarterback and a leader. We all rallied
around him (last year), and we knew if we kept him healthy it said
a lot about us. If we keep the hits off him, we know we can win.
Our whole thing was to move the ball and keep Chandler healthy. It
will be again.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What do your peers think of you? What do you think of
yourself?
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield: I think everyone around the league respects my
athletic ability, my awareness and my pass-blocking. I look at
myself and there are a lot of shortcomings. Maybe I haven't applied
myself or haven't done certain things (coaches) want to see,
especially with my run-blocking. Until I do that, I won't see
myself as the complete package. I'm trying to show some different
things, improve my run-blocking because I've been in the league
going on seven years, and I've only had a sniff of the Pro Bowl, as
an alternate. I'm trying to get there as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Is the assessment that you're inconsistent, or even
sometimes lackadaisical, accurate?
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield: I watch myself slack off. I can watch film and tell
you if I'm slacking off or if I'm not into it. Maybe it's practice,
and I don't feel like doing it. This year, though, I'm trying to
stay in tune more, work harder, want to be here more, and I've
found out that concentrating and focusing, it goes by faster and
you don't have as many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: The Falcons were 19th in the NFL in rushing last year, and
in the first preseason game, the running game struggled (with 67
yards on 23 carries). Three of five projected line starters were
here in '96, the last of seven straight years of run-and-shoot
offense. Is there a difference blocking now versus then?
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield: It's a transition. A lot of the run-blocking is way
different. In the run-and-shoot, you spread everybody out, and
there are a lot of cutback lanes, so you might not have to get a
great block, just good position on a guy where he can't get to the
ballcarrier. This is more straight-ahead blocking with eight or
nine (defenders) in the box (near the line of scrimmage). In the
run-and-shoot, you might have four or five guys in the box. Here,
you need to create space to running lanes. Everybody has to come
off with good leverage and power.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Why are fans in Atlanta so indifferent to the Falcons? Do
they have a right to be?
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield: We've got the image of maybe not winning many games
but showing a little excitement, so we'll keep a small group of
(core) fans. But to sell out that big arena, you got to put some
points on the board and some wins. I never knock somebody for what
they feel about sports. If they don't want to watch, they don't
have to watch. But it helps us play better when there are a bunch
of fans in the Georgia Dome. We got to do some impressive stuff to
get them to come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
