<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLCAMPS-SKINS-CO     08-12 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLCAMPS-SKINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redskins stand good chance to improve
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROSTBURG, Md. _ Norv Turner will have no excuses this time if
his Washington Redskins team, the favorite in the suddenly diluted
NFC East, fails to advance to postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is one of only seven NFL coaches since 1970 to have
survived four years without a playoff appearance. He has plenty of
reasons _ about 16 million of them _ to think the Redskins drought
will end in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Washington paid $16.4 million in signing bonuses and first-year
salaries to acquire veteran defensive tackles Dana Stubblefield and
Dan Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of less than a week this spring, general manager
Charley Casserly coaxed Stubblefield, an unrestricted free agent,
away from San Francisco. Then he dealt first- and third-round draft
choices to the Cincinnati Bengals for Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield got a six-year contract worth $35.88 million.
Wilkinson got $21.4 million over four years. And the Redskins got
the pair of enforcers they desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the brainy Turner again will resemble a character from
``Revenge of the Nerds,'' no one should be able to kick sand in his
face without fear of retribution. The Redskin defense was 28th
against the run in '97, but defensive coordinator Mike Nolan has
cautioned that Stubblefield and Wilkinson ``shouldn't be viewed as
saviors.'' But Wilkinson, who squandered his immense talent for
much of his four seasons in Cincinnati after being the first
overall pick in the 1994 draft, would prefer to toss caution to the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the money they're paying us, it's only natural (that)
people will expect a big change,'' Wilkinson said. ``And that's
fair. But if they turn the two of us loose and let us just beat on
people, I don't see how teams can stop us. You simply can't
double-team two tackles like us. But believe me, teams are going to
think they're seeing double.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last five seasons, the defensive emphasis in the NFL
seems to have moved from the edge to the inside _ away from
upfield-rushing ends, whose quickness has been neutralized by
quarterbacks' three-step drops _ and toward the tackles. No team
reflects that change more than the revamped Washington defense,
which struggled last year with defenders Steve Emtman, Chris Mims,
Keith Rucker and Chris Zorich.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly recently said that if the Redskins had either of their
new tackles in 1996 or '97, they would have been in the playoffs
both years. Now they have both, so expections are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys didn't just wake up one day and say, 'Hey, let's
sign Dana Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson,''' said Stubblefield, the
49ers' first-rounder in 1993. ``They have been planning this for a
long time. They saw the way the game was going, and they reacted to
it. They stepped up for us; now it's time we step up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Casserley blueprint actually called for acquiring one
dominant tackle, and Stubblefield topped the list, as he did for
most clubs. But by landing the tandem, Washington completely
altered the dynamic of their division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division has always been about brute power and being
physical, and we sometimes couldn't hold up,'' middle linebacker
Marvcus Patton said. ``Well, let's see teams try to mess with us
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short time they have been together, Stubblefield and
Wilkinson, who met for the first time at an athletic banquet in
'93, have grown close. They have joked during camp and, defensive
line assistant Earl Leggett noted, are ``beginning to meld.''
Washington will have to smooth out some rough spots as each player
attempts to establish himself as ``The Man'' on the Redskins'
defensive front. But their similar backgrounds should help hasten
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield, the league's defensive MVP in 1998 with 15 sacks,
grew up in Cincinnati and described his neighborhood there as ``one
of the places where, at a certain age, all your friends started
dying.'' His father abandoned the family when Stubblefield was 6
years old, and Dana claimed that his maturity came ``from having to
do all the things he wasn't around to do.'' Stubblefield eventually
moved in with his grandfather, who died midway through Dana's
junior year in high school. Seeking a more stable background in a
rural setting, he went to live with the family of one of his
teachers, Martha Heath, on her 220-acre farm.
</P>
<P>
   The second-youngest of 11 children, Wilkinson grew up in Dayton,
played at Ohio State and then went to Cincinnati after skipping his
senior season with the Buckeyes. He hated it there, calling the
city ``racist.'' His father died of a heart attack in '87, and
Alfred Powell, his freshman coach in high school, recalled that
Wilkinson then developed a lazy streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Dan was saying, 'No matter how hard you work, life
is still going to turn out unfair,''' Powell said. ``His father
didn't make it to many games because he was at work most times,
just trying to make ends meet. (Wilkinson) was always a little bit
backward socially, and he drew in even more after that. Frankly, he
flat-out felt sorry for himself and didn't want to work through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his strength and quickness, the 320-pound Wilkinson has
been an underachiever in the NFL. The Bengals coaches finally
decided he no longer was worth their investment.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Stubblefield has a reputation in some quarters as a
player who doesn't work hard every play. Critics claim that he got
his 15 sacks, after just one the year before, just to increase the
ante on the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive tackles and Turner all know that it's time to
silence the naysayers and restore the credibility of a proud
franchise. With a buttressed line, a trio of solid linebackers and
the NFL's best man-coverage players in Darrell Green and Cris
Dishman, Nolan certainly should have a top-10 unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from San Francisco, I know how things are supposed to
work out,'' Stubblefield said. ``No matter how good the offense
was, the defense won championships. And (it) always does. I feel
like I was brought in here to establish that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
