<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside Motorsports: NASCAR not the only race down South
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To most Southerners, Indy-style race cars, and their
drivers, might be so unfamiliar that they could come from another
planet, but at least one team will have home ties at the Aug. 29
Atlanta Classic 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway. The Kelley Racing
Team, headquartered in Fort Wayne, Ind., just completed a
sponsorship agreement with Norcross, Ga.-based Johnson Industries,
a top wholesale auto-parts distributor. Look for the JI logo on car
No. 8, driven by Scott Sharp and No. 28, Mark Dismore.
</P>
<P>
   Indy-style racing might be No. 2 these days, even at the Indy
Brickyard, but that doesn't mean the hard-core fans have retired.
The IRL Crew, the official fan club of the Indy Racing League, will
be taking two chartered busses to the Atlanta race. The club has
100 seats reserved, with the option for more if demand is great
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Mosport
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's GT1 sweep at Mosport International Raceway left Panoz
drivers in the top four positions of the championship points
series: Eric Bernard of Paris leads with 87, followed by Andy
Wallace, Le Mans, and David Brabham, England, tied at 80 and Raul
Boesel of Key West, Fla. fourth with 63. Another Panoz driver, Doc
Bundy of Atlanta, is seventh with 43 points. Other
Atlanta-connected results at Mosport: sixth place, Toshiba/Lease
Plan Ferrari 333, driven by Wayne Taylor, Altamonte Springs, Fla.,
and Eric van de Poele, Monte Carlo; eighth place, Downing Kudzu
Mazda, driven by Jim Downing of Atlanta and A.J. Smith, Voorhees,
N.J. Taylor and van de Poele are 1-2 in WSC points with 110 and
109, respectively. Downing is seventh with 48. Taylor leads the WSC
series with 110 points, one more than van de Poele.
</P>
<P>
   Formula 1
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Ferrari is next to God. Literally _ the Pope blesses
the team, and church bells ring when the team wins races. When they
lose, they get no more respect than Bear Bryant _ ``we're with you
coach, win or tie.'' The fallout of Ferrari's disappointing weekend
in the German Grand Prix _ Michael Schumacher finished fifth and
Ulsterman teammate Eddie Irvine eighth as the McLaren Mercededs
continued to roll _ has reached the Monza race circuit, where
ticket sales for the Sept. 13 Italian Grand Prix are well down from
last year. Tickets are still available for everywhere except for
the 1,500-seat central stand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
