u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-ENVOY-600&AMP;ADD-     08-12 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-ENVOY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVOY TO A LAND OF BEAUTY NOW RESIGNED TO LIFE IN A FORTRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-RDP, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-INQUIRY,
AFRICA-DEAD) 
(JT) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ This has been an agonizing time for the United
States ambassador to Kenya, Prudence Bushnell.
</P>
<P>
   Her embassy was destroyed in a terrorist bombing on Friday that
injured her and took the lives of three dozen American and Kenyan
colleagues, many of them close friends.
</P>
<P>
   She has had to re-establish her mission in temporary quarters
while overseeing a chaotic rescue operation and arranging to
evacuate dozens of wounded officials and employees.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters harder, she has also become the focus of anger
among many Kenyans who believe the United States did too little to
help save Kenyans trapped under the rubble of a building next door
to the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like that building over there _ devastated,'' she said
Wednesday during a ceremony for rescue workers, pointing at the
demolished Ufundi Co-operative Building where more than 100 Kenyans
died.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials say the bombing was particularly painful for
Bushnell because she had been complaining privately to her
superiors in Washington for more than a year about the poor
security in Nairobi. She had argued that the embassy should be
moved, but a decision was made in Washington to renovate the
existing building instead.
</P>
<P>
   She has a reputation as an effective manager _ indeed, her
background was in administration within the State Department.
Within two hours of the explosion, a bandaged Bushnell walked into
a temporary command center set up at another building housing the
U.S. Agency for International Development and took charge.
</P>
<P>
   She immediately ordered a secretary to take down a list of
priorities: determine who was missing, establish a central control
room, set up communications because the local telephones were
jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Until last Friday, Kenya was considered a safe foreign posting,
a lovely country where diplomats enjoyed safaris and the biggest
threat to security was the occasional political riot by students
downtown or a spate of carjackings.
</P>
<P>
   That changed drastically last week when a pickup truck loaded
with explosives detonated at the entrance of the embassy's
underground parking garage at the rear of the building. The
explosion gutted the mission, demolished the seven-story Ufundi
building next door and killed at least 247 people.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion caught Bushnell on the 18th floor of the
Cooperative Bank Building next door to the Ufundi building, where
she was meeting with the Kenyan trade minister. She was badly cut
by flying glass and had to descend on foot through floor after
floor of destruction and chaos before being led into a scene of
carnage outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was bleeding,'' she recalled at an emotional news
conference on Saturday. ``The banister was wet with blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador has taken the tragedy personally, friends said.
She had prided herself that during a three-year tenure as a deputy
assistant secretary of state for Africa _ a time when there was a
genocide in Rwanda and several other dangerous crises on the
continent _ no Americans were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that really upset her was that the whole time she
was the deputy assistant secretary in Washington she never lost an
American,'' one aide said. ``Today she's saying, `Now look what's
happened, and it's my fault.' That's what's hurting her most.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bushnell was born in Washington to the diplomat's life, the
daughter of a career Foreign Service officer. She was raised
abroad, in Germany, France, Pakistan and Iran. She speaks fluent
French.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Russell Sage College in Troy, N.Y., she
had a career in the private sector as a management consultant in
Texas before deciding to join the Foreign Service in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has served as the general services officer in
Bombay, India, and then as the deputy chief of mission in Dakar,
Senegal, under George Moose, who later became an assistant
secretary of state and took Bushnell with him to Washington in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Like her father, she was on the administrative track in the
State Department, a road that seldom leads to an ambassadorial
appointment. But in 1996, President Clinton nominated her to become
the ambassador to Kenya, with the strong support of Moose.
</P>
<P>
   She is married to a retired lawyer and playwright, Richard
Buckley, and has five stepchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In her two years in Kenya, she has been a persistent critic of
President Daniel arap Moi's government, pushing Kenya to live up to
its 1992 promise to establish a full-fledged Western-style
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   She has also hammered the Moi administration again and again for
being slow to clean up corruption, which is a tremendous drag on
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, she found herself on the defensive, facing
allegations from Kenyan journalists and people in the street that
U.S. Marines should have allowed local rescuers to enter the
embassy in the hours immediately after the bombing to carry out
wounded people. Instead, the Marines turned away crowds of good
samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, Bushnell defended the Marines on state
television, saying they had been trying not only to protect the
crime scene but also to keep self-appointed rescuers from being
hurt. There was a gas tank behind the building that might have
exploded, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort was to keep everybody out because we didn't know if
the gas was going to explode and we didn't know if the building was
sound,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell also tried to defuse public anger in diplomatic terms.
``The fact that there is anger is very, very understandable,'' she
said. ``I feel tremendous anger and frankly it is that anger that
helps me keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, several embassy officials said, Bushnell had been
functioning well on the job, running staff meetings with her usual
mix of humor and intensity. ``She's done remarkably well
considering that she was almost killed in the explosion,'' one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Bushnell says the experience of surviving the bomb
has irrevocably changed her and her view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly my life was changed,'' she said in an interview with
The Associated Press Wednesday. ``Dramatically. And I am having to
adapt to a new life style. One that is full of security people. We
never had armed guards before. We never lived in a fortress before.
We do now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
