<SLUG> BC-MA-BEST-HMOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER MAGAZINE CITES TOP BAY STATE HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumer Reports, the nation's largest consumer magazine,
Wednesday released a report that rated Medicare health maintenance
organization plans sold by Harvard Pilgrim Health Care and Blue
Cross and Blue Shield among the best buys in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine examined 200 Medicare HMOs and 1,200 Medicare
supplemental insurance policies in its September issue, which is
scheduled to hit newsstands Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings compared plans on a ``value index'' that evaluated
benefits and premiums. The index did not take into account
differences in quality among the plans. The magazine will issue a
separate report comparing HMO quality in October, said Trudy
Lieberman, health policy editor for Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   For the Boston market, the magazine evaluated 16 HMOs and one
so-called ``Medigap'' plan that pays for some health care costs not
covered by Medicare, the federal health insurance program for
seniors and disabled citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Among HMOs that do not offer prescription drug benefits,
Harvard's First Seniority ranked at the top, closely followed by
HealthSource of New Hampshire and Blue Cross's BlueCare 65 plan.
Though HealthSource does not sell Medicare HMOs in Massachusetts,
Consumer Reports included the plan because of its proximity to the
Boston market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strive to provide excellent value to our members,'' said
Ellen Offner, vice president for Medicare programs at Harvard
Pilgrim. Offner said Harvard's dental benefits under First
Seniority set it apart from rivals. The plan, among other things,
lets seniors buy dentures for $355, compared to thousands of
dollars charged to uninsured patients.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, Fallon Community Health Plan in Worcester, Mass., and
Blue Cross rated well among plans with drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the largest and fastest-selling Medicare HMO in
Massachusetts, Tufts Health Plan's Secure Horizons trailed its
rivals in both categories. Only Aetna US Healthcare fared worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to think that people are voting for us with their
feet,'' said Michelle Davis, spokeswoman for Tufts. ``We're the
largest Medicare HMO in the state, and we regularly report
extremely high satisfaction among our members.''
</P>
<P>
   On Medigap policies, Consumer Reports reported a 35 percent
average jump in premiums since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The article also projected that seniors will face market turmoil
as HMOs increasingly scale back benefits, hike premiums or bail out
of unprofitable markets in response to lower government
reimbursement and soaring health care costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
