<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-POLITICS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC STRONGHOLD _ SANS KENNEDY _ UP FOR GRABS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This has got to be the most fun you can have in
Massachusetts politics without a Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely because a Kennedy is leaving that the 1st
Congressional District, a Democratic stronghold encompassing parts
of Boston and several suburbs, is up for grabs and considered the
hottest campaign fight in the state these days.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, candidates without the best brand name in American
politics have a shot at hallowed ground: the kingmaker district
that gave President John F. Kennedy his start in national politics
and long served as home base to the late leonine speaker of the
House of Representatives, Thomas P. (Tip) O'Neill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Kennedy to hold the seat, Joseph P. Kennedy 2d,
is about to retire after six terms, and vying for his spot is a
sharp-elbowed, capacious-pocketed field of 10 strong Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, the political junkies who abound here can follow a
phenomenon now exceedingly rare in the center-straddling Democratic
Party of the Clinton era: contenders in this grand old bastion of
blue-collar, lunch-pail liberalism are sparring in part over just
who is the most liberal liberal on the liberal block.
</P>
<P>
   At an evening candidates' forum last week in the working-class
Dorchester neighborhood, one candidate, George Bachrach, a former
state senator, introduced himself to a reporter as ``an unabashed,
unrepentant, unreconstructed liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ray Flynn, the former mayor of Boston who is considered the
current front-runner in the race, who does not hesitate to identify
his brand of politics with the New Deal of Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, there seemed so much liberal consensus at the forum,
which local schoolchildren had helped organize as part of a lesson
in democracy, that one candidate complained it could hardly be
called a debate. Yes to tens of billions more federal dollars for
education, the candidates said; yes to universal free health care;
yes to more government money for child-care and elder-care and
antipoverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's refreshing about this race,'' said a veteran Democratic
political consultant, Daniel Payne, ``is that in an America where
politics have become very bland and Democrats and Republicans sound
very much alike and seem very cautious about positions, virtually
all the candidates in this race are well left of center.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more-liberal-than-thou uniformity hardly makes for a
dull campaign, observers hasten to point out.
</P>
<P>
   First, they note, the stakes are so high. The Eighth is not just
any seat _ in political history, it is practically a throne. It has
been held by James Michael Curley, Boston's ``Rascal King Mayor;''
it was Tip O'Neill's seemingly forever John Francis Fitzgerald, the
Kennedy forebear known as Honey Fitz, and in 1946, he watched his
patrician 29-year-old grandson, John F. Kennedy, win it.
</P>
<P>
   The Eighth ``is a kind of a cherished district in Boston because
so many famous Boston politicians have started their national
careers there,'' said Thomas O'Connor, a historian of the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a geographic and sociological oddity. Roughly
T-shaped and encompassing 40 percent of Boston plus several
suburbs, it includes areas as diverse as the Brahmin country of
Beacon Hill, the predominantly minority section of Roxbury, the
egghead commune of Cambridge and much in between.
</P>
<P>
   And the real suspense in the race is already mounting right now,
in the lead-up to the Sept. 15 primary, for the district is so
overwhelmingly Democratic that the primary is considered the
end-all of the campaign, even though a Republican, Philip Hyde, who
previously competed for the seat, is also running.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So lively is the campaign that analysts say it may end up
surpassing the gubernatorial race in spending, particularly given
the early financial push by three millionaires: Tom Keane, a member
of the Boston City Council who invokes the spirit of former Sen.
Paul Tsongas; Chris Gabrieli, a high-tech venture capitalist with a
fancy campaign Web site and lavish television time, and John
O'Connor, husband to a supermarket heiress and is known as a
campaigner for environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the field of 10, some observers say, is worth
watching as a bellwether for various strains in current Democratic
politics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, said Lou DiNatale, a senior fellow at the McCormack
Institute, a public policy center at the Boston campus of the
University of Massachusetts, there is the female factor. Two women
are running _ Marjorie Clapprood, a former radio talk-show host,
and Susan Tracy, a veteran of city political work and one of four
lesbians running for national office this year who are openly gay.
How the two female candidates fare, DiNatale said, could answer the
question, ``Are gender issues working in the liberal community?''
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach and O'Connor he would call ``great white liberals'' in
the style of perhaps a decade ago, while Gabrieli and Keane lean
more toward Clinton-style moderation.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are two minority candidates, each with solid
bases in their communities but little money: Charles Yancey, a
black City Council member and president-elect of the National Black
Caucus of Local Elected Officials, and Alex Rodriguez, who was
recently assistant deputy secretary of the treasury and is perhaps
the most aggressive oratorian of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to bite this race in the butt,'' he told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities make up about 40 percent of the district, but it also
has a heavy Italian population that could help Michael Capuano, the
mayor of the city of Somerville, who boasts that the working-class
suburb has reduced the average public-school class size to 19.
</P>
<P>
   On issues, the biggest divergence from liberalism-as-usual
appears to be Flynn's opposition to abortion; the other candidates
took pains to point that out at a televised debate on Tuesday
night. Political analysts say they expect Flynn to retain his lead
into the final lap, but the hottest question then will be whether
the candidate in second place can pick up enough anti-Flynn votes
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn remains sanguine. ``I think the people know exactly what
they want.'' he said in a recent telephone interview, ``someone who
will identify with them, work for them, protect Social Security,
the elderly, the poor and education.''
</P>
<P>
   For voters, the plethora of candidates has kept the race
confusing, and many remain undecided. There was no obvious trend
among an unscientific sampling of people asked on the streets in
the neighborhoods of Dorchester and Beacon Hill and in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a crowded field that it is really hard,'' said Steve
Capuccio, a 44-year-old systems analyst from Cambridge who plans to
vote for Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any agreement, it was on the sense of change that
comes when a Kennedy goes. Kennedy announced in March that he would
retire to devote more time to his family and business, the Citizen
Energy Corp., which was founded in 1979 as a nonprofit company to
deliver heating-oil to the poor but has since grown into a partly
profit-making conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish Joe Kennedy were still in,'' said Mike Kelly, a
Cambridge investor. ``Kennedys have an automatic vote in my
house.''
</P>
<P>
   But Donald Wilson, 38, a real estate businessman who lives on
Beacon Hill, had no such regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race is less interesting, but I would not want a Kennedy
in the race,'' Wilson said. ``I've had my fill of Kennedys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
