<HEADLINE>
WORKERS WHO DIED IN COLLAPSE SHARED IRISH BACKGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUINCY, Mass. _ He was his musical father's middle child _ a
smart and quiet kid who told corny jokes, savored science fiction
films and so ached to visit America that when the chance came
unexpectedly last month, he jumped at it.
</P>
<P>
   Gaelic football was Shane Patrick McGettigan's passion in his
native Drumshanbo, Ireland, a village of 700 just 25 miles south of
Northern Ireland. And football was his ticket to Massachusetts,
where he died Tuesday amid a jumble of steel tangled by tons of
brick, working the day job that was his pastime for a sport he took
more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big, strong, gentle type of a lad _ very
happy-go-lucky and very, very popular,'' said Eamonn McGowan, the
manager and trainer of the Allen Gaels, his team in County Leitrim,
Ireland. ``The whole town is totally devastated by this. Nobody can
believe this has happened. He's only been gone from Ireland for
three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A month shy of his 22nd birthday, McGettigan and another Irish
workman, 23-year-old Ronan Stewart from County Louth, were killed
when a construction-site scaffolding collapsed at a Quincy
high-rise condominium.
</P>
<P>
   As federal officials investigate the cause of the collapse, and
families of the dead men prepare for the return home of their
bodies for burial, friends and teammates said McGettigan's grisly
death was cruelly incongruous to his life of laughter, music and
small-town friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss that stupid smile on his face _ his stupid jokes,''
Kieran McWeeney, McGettigan's best friend said in a telephone
interview from Drumshambo. ``He wanted to see the world _ to get
away from here for a little bit. He was so good to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his countrymen, McWeeney was recruited last year to
play Gaelic football for a team in Chicago _ a season he enjoyed
while McGettigan spent the summer of 1997 as a laborer on a
construction site outside of Dublin, building a wall alongside a
highway.
</P>
<P>
   When McGettigan's turn came last month in a telephone call from
a Gaelic football recruiter in Boston, he did not hesitiate.
``We're only a small village here,'' McWeeney explained. ``He
jumped at the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   McGettigan's father, Charlie, had achieved local celebrity in
Ireland 1995 when he won a pan-European song contest, followed by
millions, with his entry, ``Rock and Roll Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But his only son made a name for himself on the football fields,
winning two medals with the Allen Gaels in 1996 and 1997. He was
selected to play for the all-county team, a distinction in a
country where their blend of football is taken as seriously as the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport was a big thing in his life,'' said Enda McGlone, a
long-time family friend. ``He played a little music, but ended up
choosing football over music. He planned on coming back here in
September for what would have been his last year in college.''
</P>
<P>
   McGettigan was enrolled at Dublin City University, where he was
a communications student who was interested in pursuing a
film-making career, perhaps, said McGlone, to satisfy his appetite
for the whiz-bang special-effects films of movie titans like Steven
Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   In its editions Thursday, the Irish Mirror recounts an interview
with McGettigan about his father's local fame and his own
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for my dad being famous, well, he might be to others, but
he's just dad to me,'' he said. ``But hopefully after today (a
championship match) people will be asking him, `Are you Shane
McGettigan's father?' rather than asking me if I'm Charlie's son.
He's fanatical about football and he'll certainly be cheering us on
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie McGettigan was to board a US-bound jetliner late
Wednesday, accompanied by his daughters Ciara, 25, and Tara, 18, on
a journey to bring his son's body home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
