<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-BENZ-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS REJECT CHALLENGE TO DAIMLER STOCK OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A German court rejected a challenge Wednesday to the
way Daimler-Benz AG rewards 1,600 of its executives with stock
options. The ruling, by a court in Stuttgart, allows Daimler
managers to continue to invest in the company by buying convertible
bonds whose price is lower than the company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The decision swept aside objections by a management professor,
Ekkehard Wenger, that the stock-option plan linked management
rewards solely to the stock price rather than considering the stock
price's performance relative to that of the overall market. It also
helped pave the way for Daimler to tackle the problem of pay
differences between its executives and those of Chrysler Corp.,
which it plans to acquire this fall in a stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   The pay differences between the United States and Germany drew
attention last week when a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission disclosed that Chrysler's chairman and chief executive,
Robert Eaton, had received $69 million in bonuses, stock and stock
options in previous years that will be paid in cash and stock when
the deal is completed. He also received a pension sweetener that
could be worth $360,000 annually for life if he stays with the
merged company for three years.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the 10-member management board of Daimler, the
executives who run the group's day-to-day business, together make
less than the salary, bonus and stock options exercised last year
by the No. 2 Chrysler executive, Robert A. Lutz, whose compensation
package totaled more than $13 million. He retired on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Though the salaries of senior German managers are rarely
disclosed, Daimler's chief executive, Jurgen Schrempp, is thought
to earn the equivalent of $1.1 million to $1.5 million a year, plus
the returns on Daimler stock options. But the cumulative payout for
all 10 management board members, if all options are exercised, is
estimated to total about $570,000.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 Daimler executives combined were paid the equivalent
of $12.3 million, slightly below their 1996 pay, the company's
disclosure statements show.
</P>
<P>
   Wenger, who teaches at the University of Wurzburg, views Daimler
with suspicion because the plan will lead to the annual creation of
as many as 22 million shares, diluting others' holdings. He said he
would appeal the decision to Germany's highest court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the acquisition agreement, which was released in Germany this
week, Daimler and Chrysler said they sought executive pay
arrangements that would be competitive on both sides of the
Atlantic ``both with regard to the type and variety of programs as
well as the amount of remuneration.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock-option plans are relatively new in Germany and have come
under the influence of American ideas about motivating executives
to create shareholder value. But other German corporations,
including Lufthansa, link such plans not only to the share price
but also to its performance relative to the overall growth of the
German stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler introduced stock options in 1996, and German law
requires that executives hold the bonds for up to two years. They
may not convert them until the share price on which they are based
increases by at least 15 percent. Though the original plan was
intended for 170 senior executives, Daimler expanded it last year
to include the much broader group.
</P>
<P>
   Experts expect Daimler to gradually adjust its compensation
structure to those in the United States, especially because the
largest bloc of shareholders _ roughly 44 percent _ will be former
Chrysler shareholders. But this will have to be done within the
limits of German law because the merged company, to be known as
DaimlerChrysler, will be a German corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
