u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CDC-TEENAIDS-COX     08-12 0246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-TEENAIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton aide: Conservatives hurt AIDS prevention efforts
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ White House AIDS adviser Sandra Thurman pulled no
punches, as usual, during a Wednesday talk on AIDS prevention in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conservative swing that we have in Congress and school
boards and at the state level is a huge impediment,'' Thurman said
during her hourlong speech, presented at the National Leadership
Conference to Strengthen HIV/AIDS Education and Coordinated Health
School Programs. The conference is sponsored by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman, the former executive director of AID Atlanta and a
Clinton appointee, said ``plain old advocacy'' is the best way to
change U.S. lawmakers' conservative approach toward AIDS education
and prevention programs. She urged AIDS educators and teachers to
speak with legislators at all levels of government and to educate
them about the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to talk about condoms. We have got to talk about
needle exchange,'' Thurman said. ``Our children's future depends on
it. It means we have to do more than we ever planned to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting condom ads on television will be tough, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sensitive issue,'' said Thurman. ``I'm not sure
we're making much progress. But we'll continue to make that push.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
