</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RECORD-HEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN RECALLS DAY OF 120-DEGREE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEYMOUR, Texas _ Long before talk of global warming, this North
Texas farm-and-ranch community experienced what its local history,
``From Salt Pork to Sirloin, Vol. II,'' wryly called ``Seymour's
proudest heat wave.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12, 1936, the temperature climbed to 120 degrees. That
set a state record that remained unchallenged until 1994, when the
far West Texas town of Monahans matched it.
</P>
<P>
   Many a Seymour resident will note that 120 degrees was far less
agreeable in 1936 than in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   There were no air conditioners, central or window-mounted, and
some folks didn't own fans. Johnnie Jackson Miller, who lived on
farms outside of town, was among many people whose homes had no
electricity except for a propeller-driven wind charger that powered
one light and the family radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall exactly what my mother did that day,'' said Miller,
69. ``She poured water in the chicken house to keep the chickens
from dying. Then she brought water into the house and poured it on
the floor to try to cool it down. All day, she'd draw water for the
chickens and pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   It still gets hot in and around the Baylor County seat, 59 miles
southwest of Wichita Falls, although the thermometer at Farmers
National Bank showed a relatively mild 85 degrees shortly after
noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a welding spark ignited pastures, tinder dry from a
month of 100-plus temperatures. The 48-hour blaze blackened 2,000
acres and destroyed a firetruck, despite the best efforts of 60
volunteer firefighters and four airplanes, ``The Baylor County
Banner'' reported.
</P>
<P>
   But that broiling August day smack in the middle of the Great
Depression remains a communal time peg.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat easy for residents to recall because it was the
day of the Old Settlers Reunion and Rodeo picnic during Texas'
centennial year celebration, attracting 800 people by one count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the ground was hot,'' said H.A. Dodd, 71. ``I
remember because I had no shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the rodeo, none of the cowboys and cowgirls suffered heat
exhaustion, and no one among the spectators collapsed, ``From Salt
Pork to Sirloin'' said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Collier, 82, recalls hitchhiking in from Paradise in Wise
County, taking a cooling, clothing-free dip in a stock tank with 20
other boys before making it over to the reunion bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``No girls,'' he said of the summer immersion ritual. ``We were
near a road. But they couldn't see us. Didn't care if they did.''
</P>
<P>
   At the picnic, in the city park along Seymour Creek, more than a
ton of ice was trucked in to chill the lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fancher, then 24, volunteered to help and was fearful
that he would be asked to work the barbecue pit. Luckily, J.W.
Ross, vice president of Farmers National Bank, appointed him to the
drinks stand.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy duty serving a thirsty crowd on one of the
hottest days in Texas history, Fancher recalled Tuesday after a
roast chicken lunch at the Seymour Senior Citizens' Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Hazel Williams and myself served lemonade to every mother
and child,'' he said. ``We don't know how much, but we did it
non-stop for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From Salt Pork to Sirloin'' said it was so hot that day that
10 medical thermometers blew up in a Seymour doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it,'' said Pauline Allen Bradwell, 84. ``I
never heard that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was hot,'' Bradwell acknowledged. ``We fashioned a
home-made `air conditioner' with straw, wire, water and a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymour families tried an assortment of ways to beat the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the daytime, we'd just sit under an old mesquite tree and
fan ourselves,'' recalled Mary Mocek, 90. ``We drank from a
container wrapped in a wet gunny sack. At night, we'd take our
sheets off the beds, wet them down, wring them out good and then
put them back down to sleep on. That was our `air conditioning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oleta Hayley, ]82, said she remembers being ``nearly smothered
to death'' by the heat on Aug. 12, 1936. Her husband insisted that
they sleep outside. Hayley tried it, but moved back inside even
though they didn't own a fan. ``I can't sleep without something
between my head and the way beyond,'' she said, gesturing toward
the skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard days, but happy days,'' Hayley said.
</P>
<P>
   Fancher said he slept on a quilt and a wagon sheet on the ground
outside even though ``mosquitoes went after you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just accepted it,'' he said. ``We didn't know any
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
