<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-BELLS-FCC-NYT     08-12 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-BELLS-FCC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: POLITICS PRODDING FCC TO FAVOR BELL COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: S.D., Ariz., S.C., N.J., Mo.)   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than two years in the regulatory wilderness, the
local Bell telephone companies are finally winning battles of
influence at the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest victory yet came last week when the FCC
recommended that the Bells, along with GTE Corp., be allowed to
keep their local data networks to themselves instead of having to
resell them to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard described the proposal as a bid to
jump-start the deployment of high-speed data services to American
homes. By allowing the Bells to avoid reselling the use of their
systems, the FCC is trying to give them incentives to invest in
advanced data services.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal also reflected a complex and powerful set of
political pressures that have come to bear on the FCC. The Bells'
political influence seems to have combined with Kennard's relative
vulnerability, the impatience on Capitol Hill with the pace of the
communications revolution, and Washington's native partisanship to
push the FCC in its current direction.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are immense, coming as technological change and
corporate consolidation continue to sweep through the
telecommunications industry. Those changes, in fact, have
contributed to labor disputes between several of the Bells and
their union employees represented by the Communications Workers of
America _ some 73,000 of whom walked off the job early Sunday after
failing to reach a new contract with Bell Atlantic. Those employees
returned to work Tuesday, but only after Bell Atlantic agreed to
let the union into two new, fast-growing ventures that it was
trying to develop using nonunion labor.
</P>
<P>
   But all the Bells are locked in a regulatory and financial war
with the big long-distance carriers to dominate the nation's $200
billion telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   That war has two main fronts. One is the $80 billion
long-distance market, with the Bells trying to get in and the
existing long-distance giants trying to keep them out. That battle
is at a standstill, with a key court case yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The other front is the growing market to provide high-speed
Internet access to consumers, who are generally stuck with modems
that make linking to the Internet tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's FCC proposal would give the Bells an important boost
by allowing them to deploy local data networks through subsidiaries
without sharing them, as they must for most of their systems.
</P>
<P>
   That is just fine with many members of Congress because they
want to be able to show voters that something tangible _ and good _
has resulted from the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The law was supposed to usher in an age of broadly lower rates
and broadly better and more advanced services. But that has not
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The specter that hangs over many members of Congress, especially
those on the Senate and House Commerce Committees, which oversee
the FCC, is that of former Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler was the sole incumbent Republican senator to lose in
the 1996 elections. As chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee,
Pressler had been highly identified with the act. He lost his seat
to Rep. Tim Johnson, in part because Johnson convinced voters that
the act was not good for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who succeeded Pressler as the
committee's chairman, is bent on not allowing that to happen to
him. He has railed against the act since its passage and has been a
big proponent of relaxing restrictions on the five remaining Bells:
Ameritech, Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, SBC Communications and U S
West.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. The Bells remain the dominant communications
lobby in Washington. While some powerful members of Congress _
including Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., ranking Democrat on the Senate
Commerce Committee, and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott _ are
generally identified with the long-distance carriers, the Bells
still seem to have more muscle to flex.
</P>
<P>
   That is largely because the Bells have customers and employees _
read voters _ in hundreds of congressional districts nationwide,
while the big long-distance carriers tend to be concentrated
geographically _ AT&AMP;T in New Jersey, for example; MCI
Communications in the Washington, D.C., area and Sprint in the
Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Because Congress controls the FCC's budget, its wishes naturally
carry some weight.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress' influence at the FCC has appeared to grow since
Kennard became chairman, partly because he was not the first choice
of anyone important in the first place. He got the job in a
compromise between Vice President Al Gore, who favored Kathleen
Wallman, a former chief of the FCC's common-carrier bureau, and
Hollings, who favored Ralph Everett, one of his former aides.
</P>
<P>
   So Kennard has not appeared to have the same level of support
from the White House that was enjoyed by his predecessor, Reed
Hundt, who is a close friend of Gore. And he also lacks a solid
power base in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hundt seemed to fight the Bells at every turn with a sharp
tongue and an even sharper pen. Part of Hundt's combativeness
seemed to stem simply from his personality. But he also seemed to
draw confidence from his relationship with the vice president.
Kennard does not have that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not prevented Republicans in Congress from using
the FCC as a political surrogate for Gore, a potential Presidential
candidate in 2000. Gore, after all, is primarily identified with
two issues: the environment and communications.
</P>
<P>
   McCain; Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., a member of the Commerce
Committee; and House Speaker Newt Gingrich have each demonstrated
an interest in communications policy and are each considered
potential presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When a dispute arose over the commission's plan to raise money
to subsidize Internet connections for schools and libraries, the
fees were immediately labeled the ``Gore tax'' on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this is an election year and that the next
presidential election is little more than two years away has
appeared only to increase the congressional pressure on Kennard to
move away from Hundt's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Bells are helped by the very nature of
telecommunications regulation in the United States. The local
telephone industry, especially the Bells, is regulated much more
strictly than is the long-distance industry.
</P>
<P>
   So when anxious members of Congress press the FCC to ``do
something'' to shake up the communications landscape or to ``get
out of the way of the marketplace,'' that often ends up being
translated into relaxing restrictions on the Bells or on local
phone companies generally.
</P>
<P>
   If that dynamic does not change soon, the Bells may be in for
more victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
