<SLUG> BC-MARKET-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS REBOUND, LIFTED BY VALUE-SEEKING BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BEAR-MARKETPLACE, RAT) 
(bl) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bargain hunters again tiptoed back into the stock
market Wednesday, picking up some of the issues battered the
previous day.
</P>
<P>
   This buying of small-company, oil, semiconductor and other
beleaguered stocks repeated the pattern that led the stock market
to rebound at the end of last week, after the Dow Jones industrial
average plunged 299.43 points on Aug. 4, its third-worst point
decline in history.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs of renewed interest in the big-name
stocks that have performed well all year, in part because investors
viewed earnings reliability as a haven in an uncertain market. This
buying helped lift the Dow Jones industrial average by more than
100 points during the day. And it held most of the gains, ending up
90.11 points, or 1.1 percent, at 8,552.96.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, however, do not seem ready to say the market is out of
danger yet. And they point out that much of the market _ especially
small-company stocks _ is already in a bear market, having fallen
more than 20 percent in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too much to expect the market to reach the bottom on
this leg,'' said Byron Wien, U.S. investment strategist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``First you have a frightening downleg, a
recovery from that, a relaxation of investor fears, and then
another downleg.'' That, he concluded, means there could be more
trouble in October, the time of last year's record one-day point
decline in the Dow. His forecast for the Dow at year end is 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Applegate at Lehman Brothers is more optimistic,
forecasting the Dow at 9,900 at year's end, which would give the
Dow an unprecedented four years in a row of double-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the market faces trouble ahead, in part because
Japan has yet to prove that it can get its economy back on track.
``You can't say we are out of this rolling correction yet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks rose 15.24 points, or
1.4 percent, to 1,084.22. Although both the Dow and the S&AMP;P
regained most of their Tuesday losses, they are still down 8.4
percent and 8.6 percent, respectively, from their July highs.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case in the few days of recovery recently, the
Russell index of 2,000 smaller-company stocks and the Nasdaq index,
with many high-technology stocks, outperformed the marquee indexes.
The Russell rose 7.95 points, or 2 percent, to 408.55, while the
Nasdaq climbed 32.83 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,825.53. They are
16.9 percent and 9.4 percent, respectively, below their highs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The buying Wednesday was prompted in part by a reversal in the
Japanese yen, which rallied against the dollar after hitting an
eight-year low on Monday. This lead to a mixed day for stocks in
Asia _ which was better than usual _ and a rally in Europe before
Wall Street opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just any day tell me what the dollar-yen is doing, and I will
tell you what U.S. equities are doing,'' said Applegate of Lehman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But Latin American stocks continued to plunge, despite the yen's
rally. The Bovespa index in Brazil fell 4.4 percent and the Mexican
Bolsa index dropped 1.9 percent. Both markets were rattled by
growing fears that Russia would be forced to devalue the ruble,
adding to the pressure on other emerging market currencies.
</P>
<P>
   World markets have been following the movements of the yen
recently because it is a signal of the continued weakness of the
Japanese economy. U.S. officials say Japan must turn its economy
around to lead Asia out of it year-old economic crisis. Only then
will Asia's drag on the U.S. economy and corporate earnings be
eased.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the weak yen has focused attention on the
possibility of a devaluation by China, a move that would deepen the
Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The yen, which finished in New York at 146.44, rallied after
Japanese officials indicated overnight that the government was
prepared to intervene in the currency market to support the yen if
its decline accelerated. On Tuesday, the yen fell to 147.35 to the
dollar, surpassing the 146.78 low it hit before the surprise
intervention to support the yen by the United States and Japan in
June.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of official jawboning can slow a decline temporarily.
But currency traders do not seem overly concerned. Japan's
intervention alone to support the yen this spring had almost no
lasting impact. And the surprise intervention with the United
States on June 17, while effective at the time, did not support the
yen for long because Japan did not take the policy actions
investors think are needed to deal with the nation's banking
problems and to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric and Wal-Mart Stores led the Dow higher. GE, off
11.6 percent after the Dow hit its record high of 9,337.97 on July
17, rose 2 1/16, to 89]. Wal-Mart, which announced a 30 percent
surge in earnings on Tuesday, jumped 2, to 66.
</P>
<P>
   And then some stocks have just continued to rise, bucking the
market's trend. Apple Computer, whose stock is up 205 percent this
year, rose 1 1/16 Wednesday, to 40 1/16; it had risen 8.6 percent
since the Dow began to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of American Express on Wednesday was another
indication of how hard it is to rebound in the current environment.
It has been one of the best-performing stocks in the Dow this year,
although only a middling performer when included among the stocks
in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   It announced last week that the crisis in Asia would cut into
its revenue in the second half of the year, and the stock dropped
6.8 percent in one day. Since its high for the year of 117~ on July
14, American Express had plunged 16.4 percent through Tuesday.
Wednesday, it jumped as much as 2}, or 2.8 percent, to 101\. But by
the end of the day it had given up most of its gain, rising just [,
to 98|.
</P>
</TEXT>
