<HEADLINE>
TWO INDONESIAN OFFICERS SENTENCED IN STUDENT SLAYINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: name cq in 2nd graf, 2nd Lt. uses only one name, Pariyo.) 
 (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two military officers whose troops killed
four university students in May, setting off a cataclysm of
violence and the resignation of President Suharto, were sentenced
to less than a year in prison on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A military tribunal found 1st Lt. Agus Tri Heryanto, 29, and 2nd
Lt. Pariyo, 30, guilty of violating military orders and not
controlling their troops, who shot at students protesting Suharto
and his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two defendants have been found guilty of taking action
outside of their orders or exceeding the limits of their orders,''
said Col. Saji Suradi, who presided over the two-month trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said that the two officers were taking the blame
for the military and that they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Students gathered outside the courtroom complained of the
leniency of the sentences: 10 months in prison for Heryanto and
four months for Pariyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentence doesn't fit a crime this serious,'' said Rhea
Sutedja, who on the day of the incident was wounded by a rubber
bullet. ``If they only violated orders, then a heavier sentence
should be handed down to those who gave the orders.''
</P>
<P>
   The student killings set off three days of rioting, looting and
arson that left more than 1,000 people dead and sections of the
capital in ruins. Suharto resigned nine days later.
</P>
<P>
   The former commander of an elite unit of special forces, Lieut.
Gen. Prabowo Subianto, is being questioned by a military council
over his role in the kidnappings of Suharto opponents before
presidential elections last March. Prabowo is Suharto's son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the council, Gen. Subagyo Hadisiswoyo, told
reporters Wednesday that Prabowo had misinterpreted orders and
``admitted that he was wrong,'' but it is not established that he
gave the orders to his troops to kidnap the political opponents.
Under the country's new president, B.J. Habibie, the military has
said it will go after officers implicated in rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have arrested 10 members of the special forces,
alleging they were involved in more than two dozen kidnappings.
Fourteen people remain missing.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have been released said they were abducted, tortured
and questioned about their political activities.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the government, under court directive, agreed to lift
a ban on a pro-democracy youth group. The Suharto government had
banned the group, the Democratic People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 parties have formed since Habibie became President
on May 21. Suharto had allowed only three government-sanctioned
parties to operate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ROUT TWINS, 11-2, AFTER CONE SCARE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Defeating the Yankees these days requires more than a
simple combination of good hitting, pitching and defense. Defeating
the Yankees requires a secret weapon, and unwittingly, Minnesota
deployed the size 13{ right foot of LaTroy Hawkins Wednesday _ a
big foot that oddly provided the Twins with their best chance for
victory in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, David Cone recovered from the impact of Hawkins'
right foot and the Yankees covered the Twins with a flood of
late-inning runs to win, 11-2, before 47,841 at Yankee Stadium. The
Yankees once again have a .750 winning percentage, having won 87 of
116 games, including their last seven. At 87-29, they have won 58
games more than they have lost, the first Yankee team to do so
since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting all year to get everyone clicking together
on all cylinders,'' Cone said. ``I think we're starting to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the other games on their current homestand were a lot
easier. The Yankees were in jeopardy Wednesday; Cone was in
trouble. There were moments in the first innings when the Twins
could have broken open the game with one hit, when they could have
knocked out Cone, when they could have finally had the Yankees
reeling, if only for one day.
</P>
<P>
   And Hawkins' big right foot played a major part in creating this
opportunity. In the first inning, Cone, already out of sorts, was
rushing his delivery, his body moving forward with his arm dragging
behind. His control was affected, his fastball sailing high, his
curveball and slider imprecise. Two hits and a hit batsman loaded
the bases for Minnesota, and the Twins scored their first run on a
groundout. Cone returned to the dugout feeling fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins shut out the Yankees in the bottom of the first, and
when Cone returned to the mound, he found that Hawkins had dug an
unusually large hole in front of the rubber, where pitchers plant
their back foot as they drive forward while releasing the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Cone excavated and kicked at the gash, working to fix it to his
liking. But, he would say later, his balance was affected, he felt
awkward. He walked Ron Coomer on four consecutive pitches to lead
off the second; he was unable to throw any of four fastballs over
the plate, and he was missing badly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone tried slowing his delivery, aiming intently at the mitt of
catcher Joe Girardi _ and the more he tried aiming the ball, the
more dysfunctional his delivery became. Javier Valentin stood and
watched Cone throw four more fastballs out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi went to the mound. ``Be patient, I'll figure it out,''
Cone said, digging at the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre watched, and although he says he believes Cone
when the pitcher tells him he feels great, he was seeing the
classic signs of a pitcher with a tired or injured arm: Cone, whose
control has been spectacular, simply could not throw a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jerzembeck began throwing in the Yankees' bullpen, as Cone
fell behind Denny Hocking, Minnesota's No. 9 hitter, three balls
and no strikes. ``I can't remember a time when I threw 11 straight
balls,'' Cone said after the game. He saw Jerzembeck warming up and
assumed that he was in danger of being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   He threw a strike to Hocking, Yankee Stadium erupting with mock
cheers. Cone fired another fastball, and Hocking popped up to short
center field, the runners forced to hold. Later, Hocking and Cone
would point to this as a pivotal moment. ``I was thinking we might
bunt in that situation,'' Hocking said, ``but you've got to make
the guy throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Otis Nixon lined a single to right, but the ball was hit so hard
and reached Paul O'Neill so quickly that Coomer stopped at third.
Bases loaded, one out, infield back, Jerzembeck nearly ready in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Gates hit a bouncer to first baseman Tino Martinez, who
was in position to make the play only because the bases were loaded
and he wasn't holding the runner. Martinez gloved the ball and
threw to second, where Derek Jeter caught the ball for a forceout
and returned a throw to first for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Cone returned to the dugout and with both hands grabbed his
teammate David Wells, joking: ``How are you throwing strikes? Let
it rub off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone said later: ``At that point, I breathed a sigh of relief. I
knew I could settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins scored another run in the third inning, but Cone was
making adjustments on the fly, adjusting to the hole, adjusting his
release, gradually gaining control of his fastball and slider.
Minnesota, only 1 for 6 with runners in scoring position in the
first three innings, would not get any more runs.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, the Yankees came back. Four runs in the fourth,
including two on Girardi's hit-and-run double; three runs in the
seventh, with home runs by Bernie Williams and Scott Brosius; three
more in the eighth, including two on a double by Brosius that gave
him five runs batted in for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' foot had opened a hole, but the Twins couldn't get
through quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
