<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0946 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOTSTEIN-MUSIC-2TAKES     08-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTSTEIN-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING EXPEDITIONS OF MUSICAL ARCHAEOLOGY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who, in musical history, could have guessed that a meddlesome
figure like Leon Botstein would come along?
</P>
<P>
   Not Mendelssohn, obviously. ``In everything I have written down
there is at least as much deleted as there is allowed to stand,''
the composer told a friend around 1842. ``My `St. Paul' originally
had a third more numbers, which shall never see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   But Botstein, the American academic turned conductor and
festival director, has exposed those numbers to the full glare of
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Botstein is gleefully exploring ``Tchaikovsky and
His World'' in performances and discussions filling the first of
two weekends at the Bard Music Festival in Annandale-on-Hudson,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 he devoted similar attention to Mendelssohn at Bard
College, and two years later he conducted the American Symphony
Orchestra and the Pro Arte Chorale in a performance of
Mendelssohn's path-breaking oratorio ``St. Paul,'' or ``Paulus,''
of 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ever the contrarian, he has recorded the work in a new
critical edition from the Carlus publishing house, leading the
Royal Scottish National Orchestra and Chorus, and appending the 11
numbers that Mendelssohn thought would be interred with his bones
(Arabesque Z6705; three CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Another of Botstein's historical straight men was Deryck Cooke,
an English musicologist and the author of an influential essay,
``The Bruckner Problem Simplified,'' of 1975. ``The spurious Schalk
score,'' Cooke wrote there of the first edition of Bruckner's Fifth
Symphony, ``has been abandoned by everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for simplicities. In 1995, Botstein led the American
Symphony in a performance of the Bruckner Fifth in the edition by
Franz Schalk; now he has replicated that performance on disc with
the London Philharmonic Orchestra (Telarc CD-80509).
</P>
<P>
   And in response to no particular historical provocation except
his usual bugaboo, unjust neglect by posterity, Botstein throws in
another recording, of Erno Dohnanyi's First Symphony, which the
conductor unearthed in a Lincoln Center offshoot of the Bard
Festival in 1995 (Telarc CD 80511), here also with the London
Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of Dohnanyi, little deliberation is needed. At his
best, as in the youthful First Piano Quintet, Dohnanyi was a
splendid composer, and he is here working in near-peak form. The
main focus of the festival at which the work was performed was
Bartok, and that composer thought so highly of his compatriot's
symphony that he could play it from memory at the piano.
</P>
<P>
   This work, from 1900, breathes much the same late-Romantic air
as the Zemlinsky symphonies, discussed elsewhere in these pages, a
volatile atmosphere laced with disparate influences: Bruckner,
Brahms and Tchaikovsky; Liszt, Wagner and Busoni.
</P>
<P>
   In the second of the work's five movements, the Molto adagio,
with its languid, sinuous melodies and its lush blend of strings
and woodwinds, you might suspect that Dohnanyi had heard
Rachmaninoff's Second Symphony, if that work had not lain six or
seven years in the future. Dohnanyi's work is, to be sure, an
immediate successor of Glazunov's ``Seasons,'' and in the Scherzo,
sounds it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Hungariana in the middle of the second
movement is vintage Dohnanyi, and the composer speaks throughout in
a distinctive and piquant style. This work certainly deserves an
occasional hearing, and it is good to have it in a fine performance
and in Telarc's excellent sound.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in the other recordings, it is minor curiosity that
although Botstein is the music director of the American Symphony
and has performed the music with it, an American label should
resort to a British orchestra and recording locale.
</P>
<P>
   But Botstein has also maintained a relationship with the London
Philharmonic, including an earlier recording of works by Joseph
Joachim. In any case, the musical results in the Dohnanyi and
Bruckner works make the decision hard to fault.
</P>
<P>
   The fluency and coherence generally accorded these big,
sprawling pieces here speak well, too, for Botstein's continued
growth in sheer technical terms as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruckner performance is especially impressive, since
Botstein has not only to create an interpretation but also to
counter the expectations, orchestra's as well as listeners', raised
by familiarity with the other versions.
</P>
<P>
   Those scores, edited by Leopold Nowak and Robert Haas, are
nearly identical to each other and radically different from the
1894 version (published in 1896) by Bruckner's friend Schalk. The
basic issues are whether, as in other instances, Bruckner approved
of Schalk's cuts and emendations (if in these, his waning, years he
even knew about them), and whether he would have objected in any
event, being, supposedly, an acquiescent sort.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As if there were not enough controversy here, Botstein has
involved himself in recent debates over how much Haas' editorial
work, stressing the ``purity'' of original versions, and how much
the monumental Bruckner performance style since World War II may
owe to the Nazi ideology in Germany and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Haas was cozy with the regime, no question. Pamela M. Potter, in
her new book, ``Most German of the Arts: Musicology and Society
From the Weimar Republic to the End of Hitler's Reich,'' suggests
that he was considered ``victimized'' in Austria before the
Anschluss, deprived of important academic appointments because he
had joined the Nazi party in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had also waged a difficult battle with `Jewish business
interests' for his Bruckner edition,'' Ms. Potter reports, citing
archival documents from the University of Vienna, ``a situation
which `was decided in his favor ... by our Fuhrer Adolf Hitler.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A CD booklet is not even remotely big enough to accommodate such
issues, which were discussed at length in connection with the
concert performance. Botstein merely suggests them here, arguing
chiefly that in the Schalk edition, which is substantially shorter,
the work ``possesses a special power and proportion that reveals a
new _ or, perhaps, simply a forgotten _ dimension of Bruckner's
music.''
</P>
<P>
   And as in the concert, he makes a persuasive case for this
alternative, adding lively tempos into the mix. The work takes on a
mercurial cast, as at the end of the first movement, where the coda
fairly skips toward conclusion. Still, Bruckner would not be
Bruckner without some monumentality and drama, and it was Schalk
who instituted the notion of bringing on a platoon of fresh brass
players for the work's peroration.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how such matters are handled in recordings is never
clear in the listening alone; suffice it to say that the
conclusion, in the London Philharmonic's performance and Telarc's
sound, is truly resplendent.
</P>
<P>
   Again as in the concert, there is no sense of mere demonstration
or didacticism. This is a gritty, committed performance from first
to last.
</P>
<P>
   Less can be said for the Mendelssohn recording, despite much
fine work from Botstein and the Scottish forces. The main problem
is an indifferent cast of vocal soloists (Susan Roberts, Ruby
Philogene, Glenn Siebert and Mark Beesley), especially the men, in
roles that have been well, sometimes superbly, recorded. (Thomas
Hampson's Paul in the Erato recording conducted by Michel Corboz is
a notable example.)
</P>
<P>
   This splendid work, which was inspired in part by Mendelssohn's
historic revival of Bach's ``St. Matthew Passion'' and is
especially rich in its use of chorale tunes, is well worth getting
to know. But Botstein's recording should probably not be anyone's
first or only one.
</P>
<P>
   The supplementary disc, including a few alternative versions of
published numbers as well as items dropped from the final version,
will be of interest principally to specialists.
</P>
<P>
   True, it also holds attractions for the average listener, but
the dislocations in original placement as well as intent between
numbers discourage listening straight through, and the whole thing
ends in mid-modulation, on an agonizingly unresolved chord.
</P>
<P>
   With the classical-recording industry still struggling to emerge
from the chaos caused by a suffocating glut of the overfamiliar,
Botstein's adventurous programming in recent years seems to have
cast him in a modest role of savior, bearing invigorating doses of
the ``new'' and unusual. Indeed, many of his archaeological finds
are likely to wear better on disc than in the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   This impressive trove is a reminder of what a remarkable body of
work Botstein has accumulated over a decade of exploration. It also
shows promise of further development in the technical aspects of
conducting on his part, even though he has chosen roads that will
get him there only the hard way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
