<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-12 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTANGLING A CRASH OF PRIORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Days after the
</P>
<P>
   demolished truck was hauled away and the road cleared, Arizona
state police still were taking angry calls. Gov. Jane Hull even
joined the complainers, releasing a statement saying, ``Disrupting
traffic for five or six hours at a time is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   You probably saw the pictures on TV or in the paper. Interstate
17 was shut down for more than four hours Sunday afternoon. The
backup stretched 30 miles and involved thousands of cars and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   People had fled north for the weekend, away from the terrible
Phoenix heat, and now were heading home.
</P>
<P>
   Going from mountains to desert makes travelers crabby to begin
with. Then, they stopped. There was an accident ahead. They knew
that. But they had to get back to the city, back to their busy
schedules. It wasn't long before they wanted to know _ demanded to
know _ what was holding things up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little girl.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Layne Paulson, and she was 13 years old. Her body
on the road was holding things up.
</P>
<P>
   Layne had gone north for the weekend, too, and was returning
home. She and her father, George, along with his fiancee and her
daughter had been camping. The four of them were in the cab of
George's pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   South of Cordes Junction, where the road drops steeply and winds
along rock walls, a car in front of them suddenly swerved. The
driver told Department of Public Safety investigators he hit a
slick spot in the road, perhaps gas or oil from a big rig. The car
fishtailed, striking a guardrail and careening across the lane.
</P>
<P>
   George veered to avoid hitting him. He went off the road and
onto a narrow patch of dirt only a few feet from the rocks. As he
tried to steer back onto the pavement, his truck flipped over. No
one was wearing a seat belt. Layne was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   The upside-down truck spun wildly, like a second hand on a
clock. Then time and traffic stood still.
</P>
<P>
   There was a doctor in one of the following cars. He rushed to
Layne, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a beautiful girl,'' her grandmother, Shirley Paulson,
told me. ``She was like sunshine walking into a room.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley lives out of state. So does Layne's mother. Her father
and his fiancee remain in the hospital. The other girl was injured
only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen stories about the traffic and what the governor had
to say.'' Shirley said. ``I guess some people don't think about
how, when they have to stop because of a siren, they're the lucky
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokesman Andy Vidaure has listened to complaints since
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand people's frustration,'' he said, ``but the fact
is there was a death.''
</P>
<P>
   Any accident may be a crime scene, he said. What if _ as
sometimes happens _ drugs or alcohol are involved? Or road rage? If
police don't gather all the evidence, there's no hope of making a
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only get one shot at the scene,`` Vidaure said. ``It takes
time. This was a very tough situation. It was a mess out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The road was covered with debris.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup had been loaded with camping gear, and with dreams.
As any parent can tell you, no 13-year-old girl travels without a
truckload of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Layne Paulson was in the school chorus. She worked on the school
newspaper. A friend says she loved the band Hanson and going to the
mall. She was supposed to start high school next week. Her
principal at Desert Shadows Middle School in Phoenix told me, ``She
was a lovely girl. She would have been a spectacular grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, said her grandmother, adding, ``But, sometimes, the
best people are only on this Earth for a little while, and we have
to cherish what we've had, and how precious they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, a traffic accident in which one person is killed
rates a passing mention on the TV news and only an inch or two of
type in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   This one made the front page and was the lead story on all the
evening newscasts. But not because a girl died. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
