u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRELSON-JUDGE-1STLD     08-12 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRELSON-JUDGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE OFFERS TO STEP DOWN IN HARRELSON CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates with judge offering to step down from the case.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACQUE CROUSE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal judge who had a one-on-one basketball
face-off with actor Woody Harrelson has offered to step down from
hearing the high-profile murder appeal of the actor's father.
</P>
<P>
   The offer from U.S. District Judge Fred Biery followed ethical
questions raised about the half-hour game at a time when both men
were in Denver, where Biery was presiding over the latest appeal of
two life sentences given to Charles Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   The judge _ a high school basketball player who went on to the
basketball program at Texas Lutheran College _ said the pick-up
game with Woody Harrelson occurred after a chance meeting with the
actor in the hotel health club.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the San Antonio-based judge freely discussed the
game and the situation that led to it, saying he did not believe it
raised any ethical concern.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Biery offered to step aside. The judge faxed a
letter to lawyers telling them they can request the appeal be
reassigned to another judge if they object to the basketball
encounter _ or to any of Biery's other social relationships with
people in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors and defense attorneys in the case could not be
reached Wednesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all at the same hotel, the FBI agents, the
prosecutors, the defense attorneys and Woody Harrelson,'' Biery
said Tuesday. ``I would have had to lock myself up not to run into
someone involved in the case every day at breakfast, dinner and in
between.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Harrelson is appealing his 1982 conviction and two life
sentences for killing U.S. District Judge John H. Wood on May 29,
1979. Harrelson is an inmate at the federal prison in Florence,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson, whose movie credits include a film about
basketball called ``White Men Can't Jump'' and who played a
bartender on the television comedy ``Cheers,'' acknowledged last
week that he is footing the bill for his father's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Biery said he was getting ready to leave the gym on Aug. 5 when
Woody Harrelson came in.
</P>
<P>
   Biery, who works out several times a week by shooting baskets,
said they began to talk and decided to play a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did say he felt kind of awkward, and I told him we could
play as long as we did not discuss the case,'' Biery said. ``I also
had breakfast twice that week with FBI Special Agent Claude Martin,
who was there to testify. We also did not discuss the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Bohl, a judicial ethics expert and instructor at
Southwestern University School of Law in Los Angeles, said though
no impropriety may have occurred, that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a clear appearance of impropriety, and judges are held
to the standard of avoiding the appearance,'' she said. ``I was
shocked by this. He wasn't trapped in an elevator. He could have
said hello and cordially walked off, but he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas School of Law Professor Charles Silver,
however, said that as long as Biery is telling the truth that they
did not discuss the case, he sees nothing wrong with the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an appearance of impropriety issue for judges, but I
am always reluctant to assume there has been impropriety,'' Silver
said. ``Judge Biery has been around a long time, and he knows the
rules. In principle, there is nothing wrong with him and Woody
Harrelson being on opposite sides in a pick-up game _ or on the
same side, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Code of Conduct for federal judges requires them to avoid
impropriety and the appearance of impropriety in all activities,
but sometimes chance encounters are unavoidable, a federal appeals
court judge said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Circuit Judge Jerry Buchmeyer, who serves on the federal
Committee on Codes of Conduct, said the restrictions require only
that a judge and parties not discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do run into parties in a lawsuit, and I think judges in
small towns have the problem more than others, usually,'' he said.
``You might even go have a drink with a lawyer, but (neither) you
nor the lawyer discusses the case before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Biery said about 20 other people were in the gym while he and
Harrelson played basketball for a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that his law clerk took pictures of the game are false,
Biery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a 13-year-old nephew in Denver, and he came by and had
his picture taken with Woody and his two brothers,'' Biery said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
