<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-COLUMNIST-NYT &LR;      08-12 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-COLUMNIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 GLOBE WORKERS PROTEST BARNICLE REPRIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also tonight's Boston Globe story, GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A burst of anger rolled through the newsroom of The Boston Globe
on Wednesday as at least 50 people signed a petition, which was
presented to the editor and publisher, saying that the reprieve
given columnist Mike Barnicle ``not only cripples the paper's
integrity but undermines the efforts of staff members who work
daily to produce a newspaper that is beyond reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle had teetered on the brink of termination for five days
for writing a column that paralleled the work of the comedian
George Carlin and making apparently contradictory statements about
his familiarity with Carlin's work. After refusing his editor's
request that he resign and mounting a public campaign in his
defense, Barnicle was suspended for two months on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the decision by Editor Matthew Storin and Publisher
Benjamin Taylor offered raw comments in an hourlong staff meeting.
Automotive writer John White, a 33-year employee at the paper who
spoke at the meeting, said afterward: ``There has been a perception
for a long time that Mr. Barnicle answered to a different standard
than the rest of us. On this one, a lot of us are angry.''
</P>
<P>
   According to White, the hostility at the meeting was replaced
briefly with applause when Storin announced that Walter Robinson,
an assistant managing editor and a former metropolitan editor,
would edit Barnicle's future columns. Robinson was the editor who
identified potential problems with the work of another columnist,
Patricia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith was forced to resign earlier this summer after
admitting she fabricated characters in some columns. She is black,
while Barnicle is white. The Boston chapter of the NAACP issued a
statement Wednesday echoing the charges that the paper has employed
a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the news that Barnicle was being asked to resign,
the columnist's many supporters inside and outside the newsroom
urged the paper's management to reconsider. The chief executive of
Staples, Inc., a leading advertiser, wrote a letter to Taylor
saying that losing Barnicle's column, ``would render The Globe a
less attractive advertising vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin said Wednesday that the meeting was ``emotional and
candid and healthy.'' He added that he is ``getting a lot of
sentiment'' from among the paper's 520 editorial employees ``that
it's time to put this behind us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
