<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PROSECUTOR DEFENDS ACTION IN MAFIA BUG ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The former federal prosecutor who got the court order
used to bug a Mafia induction ceremony again defended her legal
strategy Wednesday, insisting she withheld information from the
judge who granted the order because the FBI wanted to protect the
mob source who told them the time and place of the secret ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   As she did last week on the witness stand in a different mob
case, Diane M. Kottmyer, former head of the New England Organized
Crime Strike Force, said she kept details about the ceremony out of
court documents  &UR;  &LR; because the FBI didn't want to expose Mafia
informant Angelo ``Sonny'' Mercurio, who told agents the ceremony
would take place in a Medford house on Oct. 29, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Kottmyer said she was told by the FBI that the details were so
closely-held, so ``singular,'' that mentioning them in the court
affidavit could point to Mercurio as the source of the information.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Kottmyer, who is now a Massachusetts
Superior Court judge, provided US District Judge David S. Nelson
with all the pertinent information he needed to make a decision on
authorizing the bugging.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Kottmyer is being asked to defend the
government's decision to seek a so-called ``roving bug,'' which
doesn't specify the location to be bugged _ even though the FBI
knew hours before Nelson signed the order exactly where and when
the induction ceremony would take place. But Kottmyer said she
wasn't told before she sought authorization from Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The legality of the bugging, which is being challenged in two
separate court cases involving the prosecution of mobsters and
their associates, is at the core of months-long hearings before US
District Judge Mark L. Wolf in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for New England Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme, Winter
Hill Gang leader Stephen Flemmi, Mafia soldier Robert DeLuca and
Winter Hill gangster John Martorano, argue that Nelson was given
incomplete information _ particularly regarding what investigators
knew about the planned induction ceremony. They want the tape
recordings of the ceremony suppressed as evidence in the extortion
and racketeering case against the region's top Italian and Irish
gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, during several hours of questioning by Martorano's
attorney, Martin G. Weinberg, Kottmyer said she was unaware that
the Boston office of the FBI had promised headquarters in
Washington that it would add the time and place of the induction
ceremony to the court affidavit accompanying the bugging
application as soon as agents learned the details.
</P>
<P>
   That was never done, even though then-organized crime supervisor
James A. Ring _ who testified earlier in the hearings _ said
Mercurio told him the time and place of the ceremony on Friday,
Oct. 27, 1989, hours before Kottmyer met with Nelson. Kottmyer
testified that Ring didn't tell her about Mercurio's information
until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she'd known the location, Kottmyer said, she was
precluded from putting it in the affidavit because of the FBI's
concerns about exposing Mercurio. And she had no authority to
convert her request for a roving bug to a more restrictive fixed
one, pegged to the Medford location.
</P>
<P>
   The package of documents seeking a roving bug had been approved
by Justice Department and FBI superiors in Washington, days before
anyone had firm information on where the ceremony would be held,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with prosecutors and Kottmyer in private, Wolf
will decide whether Kottmyer will be required to reveal whether the
FBI had other informants at the induction ceremony, besides
Mercurio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
