<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-BUTLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ BROADCASTS VIDEO OF TALKS WITH U.N. ARMS INSPECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (with IRAQ-U.N.) 
(bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq experimented this week with a television
propaganda blitz intended to court world opinion. The effort is
getting mixed reviews, and could backfire where opinion matters
most: in the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, Iraqi television, and networks around the
world, have been showing video footage of a tense standoff between
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and the United Nations'
chief arms inspector, Richard Butler, in talks that broke down 10
days ago in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   More than four hours of tapes of two days of meetings have been
shown in Iraq. Networks have aired mostly one short clip that
appears to show Butler getting up from his chair and abruptly
ending the meetings Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That never happened,'' Butler said Wednesday in an interview,
recalling his last, admittedly chilly meeting with Aziz. ``The
meeting ended in an orderly way. I walked around the table and
shook his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   For Butler, who had been given an ultimatum by his Iraqi
counterpart _ declare us disarmed first or there is nothing to talk
about _ there were more troubling aspects of the videotaping than
one scene that he suspects may have been edited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been shocked to learn that Iraq has chosen to put into
the public arena videotapes of our private official
consultations,'' Butler said, calling the Iraqi action an attempt
at political theater. ``This was done without any consultation with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, an Australian arms control expert and former diplomat,
said that the videotaping of his meetings began last December, when
one crisis over the expulsion of U.S. inspectors had abated and
another was about to begin. At the first meeting taped, Butler
recalled, Aziz ``announced the existence of presidential sites from
which we would be forbidden forever, and that authored Part II of
the November-to-February crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, here were these cameras and lights in the room,'' he
said. ``I said, `May I ask you a question before we begin? What it
is that we see here?' And he said that they are video cameras. And
I said, What is the purpose of this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz assured him that the films were being made only for the
historical record for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `It's not for the media?''' Butler recalled. ``And he
said, `No!' _ robust assurance _ `No! It's just for the record.'''
</P>
<P>
   Talks in January, March, June and August were also videotaped.
And in June, an extra microphone appeared in front of Butler's
place at the table in Iraq's Foreign Ministry. Its presence made
private consultations with his team virtually impossible. An aide
said his voice in a whispered conversation 20 feet away was picked
up clearly.
</P>
<P>
   But only the August session, when Iraq appeared to have decided
to stop all further cooperation with the arms inspection commission
known as Unscom, was made public on Iraqi television.
</P>
<P>
   But before the public airing, just after the end of the talks,
copies of the video were sent to certain embassies in Baghdad close
to the Iraqi leadership and to selected members of the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, Unscom, have not yet been provided our copies,'' Butler
said. The commission's monitoring center in Baghdad was given a
tape, however, and that is slowly making its way to New York, days
behind the copies circulated to influential Security Council
members _ though not the United States _ by the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person from a permanent member state spent five hours
yesterday reviewing the whole lot,'' Butler said. ``But not us, the
co-participant in the talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and others who have seen the tapes doubt they will
have the effect the Iraqis want. Much of the footage is devoted to
Aziz blustering, badgering and cutting off Butler with repeated
sharp demands for an immediate end to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   This from the Iraqis, who have persuaded some of U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan's aides that Butler's ``Anglo-Saxon'' bluntness
and the ``cowboy'' behavior of his inspectors offends Iraqi
sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Iraq talks about Unscom's behavior, as they sometimes
do, this kind of behavior by them in a diplomatic context is
unheard of,'' Butler said of Iraq's public distribution of the
tapes. ``Diplomacy does have its rules. It would be appropriate for
us to be advised of these things. We are a co-participant with Iraq
in these conversations. It's not a one-way event, a one-way
street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does to the utility of confidential conversations is
a bit worrying,'' he added. ``That's why diplomacy has these
conventions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
