A0963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HEAT-HNS &LR;      08-12 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUC DECIDES RESIDENTIAL ELECTRICITY CANNOT BE CUT OFF DURING HEAT
WAVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Electricity cannot be cut off to residential
users for any reason during a record heat wave expected to last
into September, says an emergency rule adopted Wednesday by the
Texas Public Utility Commission.
</P>
<P>
   PUC Chairman Pat Wood and Commissioner Judy Walsh voted for the
immediate ban on cutoffs through Sept. 30 after hearing reports
that Houston Lighting &AMP; Power and other utilities were still
hanging disconnect notices on customers' doors despite public
promises not to cut people off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were doorhangers passed around in the middle of this
horrible heat,'' Wood said. ``That's what got my Irish up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he objected to seeing panicking Houstonians ``passing
out from the heat on national television'' while seeking help with
bills because they feared their electricity would be turned off.
The commissioners said Texans should not be afraid to run their air
conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a general emergency is escalating into a needless
crisis because people aren't getting the message that we've got
time to work on your payment plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HL&AMP;P had already announced an indefinite suspension of
terminations starting this month, said company spokesman Graham
Painter. But he confirmed the company had continued sending pink
warning notices and distributing the doorhangers.
</P>
<P>
   Those practices stopped Wednesday, Painter added. Newly worded
late notices will explain the ban on disconnections but urge
customers to make arrangements to pay their bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still going to be a lot of people who have difficulty
paying their bills. We agree this is a special year and they need
time to do it,'' he said. ``It seems reasonable to err on the side
of conservatism when human lives are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Texas death toll from the heat wave hit at
least 128 when the U.S. Border Patrol confirmed the death of a man
who was trying to cross into the United States near Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   With July the hottest ever recorded worldwide, Texas utility
bills soared to an average $175 in Dallas, while residential bills
statewide have been running up to 40 percent higher than last year,
said Saralee Tiede, chief of the PUC's customer protection office.
</P>
<P>
   Under the PUC ruling, customers unable to pay soaring electric
bills will have until the end of September to work out deferred
payment plans with their electric companies. Residential customers
must be allowed up to six months to pay the bills but can opt to
pay them sooner. If electric companies approve, customers might
also qualify for 12-month plans in which all of their payments are
averaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This emergency ruling is not what I would call a free lunch,''
said Carol Biedrzycki, executive director of the Texas Ratepayer's
Organization to Save Energy, a consumer advocacy group that sought
the new rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were not aware of the fact that they weren't going to
be disconnected even though they were receiving disconnect
notices,'' she added. ``This was a problem. We've got that settled
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Texas congressmen are seeking another $37.5 million
in emergency heat relief money, just two weeks after a grant of the
same amount was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Sheltering Arms agency has already run out of its
share of the federal money, and other administrators say they have
exhausted at least 60 percent already.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of disconnection notices and the quickly dwindling
aid money likely led hundreds of people to line up at Sheltering
Arms on a day so hot that fire trucks and air conditioned buses
were called in to offer relief, Tiede said. Money shortages in Fort
Worth had hundreds there lined up before dawn awaiting help at the
Will Rogers Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   More money could be on the way, though. Recent fund-raisers at
Sheltering Arms have led to collection of $200,000 from private
foundations, energy companies and even individuals putting up $5 to
$500, said Nieves Lopez, an energy assistance planner at the Texas
Department of Housing and Community Affairs. HL&AMP;P announced an
extra $5 million for low-income ratepayers earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said her agency is also supervising an effort to shift
remaining federal dollars from locations around the state where
they are not being used to those with high need, such as Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous need for energy assistance during this
extended heat wave,'' she said. ``However, it makes it particularly
difficult to assist clients as long as the utilities either
terminate clients or send termination notices to their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez recommends that people be told their power won't be
terminated, they should use air conditioners wisely and they will
have an opportunity to work out a reasonable payment plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is,'' said Commissioner Walsh, ``that people need
to take care of their health first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
