<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-NYT &LR;      08-12 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS RESPOND TO KENYAN CRITICISM OF POST-BOMB CONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-RDP, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-INQUIRY,
AFRICA-DEAD) 
(JT) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The American ambassador to Kenya went on
television Wednesday night to address charges that Americans were
more concerned about protecting their own people and guarding their
embassy than helping Kenyans killed or hurt in an attack presumably
aimed at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editorials and some Kenyans have charged that
Americans concentrated on saving embassy employees after a bomb
attack last Friday but stood by while others worked to rescue
Kenyans. They have also said Americans and embassy employees were
flown out of the country while Kenyans had to make do with
overcrowded hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador, Prudence Bushnell, explained American conduct in
an interview aired Wednesday night on Kenyan television. ``We were
shedding blood. Blood was blood,'' Bushnell said. ``We were
rescuing people. People are people. There was no determination as
to race, religion, ethnic group. We were trying to get as many
people out as we possibly could.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``The fact that there is anger is very, very
understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from the blast in Nairobi stands at 247, the
Kenyan government said Wednesday, including 12 Americans and 24
Kenyan employees who were inside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The American government has rushed support teams, including
doctors, paramedics and specialists in rescue operations, as well
as blood supplies and rescue dogs, to help both Kenyans and
Americans hurt in the explosion. However, many Kenyans still feel
the Kenyan casualty list would have been shorter if the Americans
had been as concerned about them as they were about protecting
American lives and protecting the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not see them first of all saving lives,'' said Charity
Ngilu, a leader of the opposition Social Democratic Party and a
presidential candidate in last December's election. ``They were
more concerned with their building and property.''
</P>
<P>
   An editorial cartoon in the Nation, the country's most widely
read newspaper, showed two beefy men in Marine Corps battle gear
pointing their rifles at a badly wounded Kenyan, wearing a Chicago
Bulls T-shirt and missing his left leg and right arm. ``We can't
take you for some security reasons,'' barks one Marine. Behind him,
a white man is being carried on a stretcher to a plane with the
American flag and label ``American Rescue Force 1'' on the
fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ugly side of Americans,'' read the headline on an
editorial in the Standard, the country's second-largest daily. The
editorial called the U.S. Marines guarding the embassy
``heavy-handed,'' ``insensitive'' and ``looking more suited to a
Rambo movie than the bread and butter role of a guard in a city
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Kenyan anger appeared to reflect a lack of
understanding of the mission of American soldiers in protecting the
embassy, as well as pent-up resentment over Washington's charges of
corruption in the Kenyan government and criticisms of the absence
of a liberal democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kenyans resented the refusal of the Marines to allow anyone
into the embassy after the blast. Kenyans who gathered outside
wanted to rush in and begin digging through the rubble for victims.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that the Marines' role was to protect
the embassy's documents and that no one would be allowed into the
building until a professional search team arrived and it was
determined that the building was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we wanted was for good Samaritans to lose their
lives in our building,'' Bushnell said in her interview with Kenyan
television.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corps Brig. Gen. Steve Johnson, the commander of the
joint task force sent in response to the bombing, defended the
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Marines did exactly what they're required to do,''
General Johnson said at a memorial ceremony Wednesday afternoon.
``Their mission was to protect the United States mission.''
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to judge how deep the resentment runs
beyond the country's leaders and the elite. On the streets
conflicting sentiments were voiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are angry with the Americans,'' said Bismarck Odida, 35, an
electronics repairman who was among several hundred Kenyans who
gathered Wednesday in front of the American embassy, watching the
cleanup. ``They're trouble-makers.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began in 1992, he said, ``when you Americans started
pushing for this multiparty democracy.'' Odida, who is a member of
the ruling Kenya African National Union, added: ``Before that,
Kenya was an island of peace.'' The American ambassador at the
time, Smith Hempstone, was a voluble critic of the lack of
democracy, and is credited by some, and damned by others, for
loudly pushing for multiparty elections.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon Kasina, a 45-year-old trader, interrupted Odida. ``This
has nothing to do with democracy,'' he said. ``This is terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We are not angry with the Americans. We are angry
with the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The division of opinion among the populace was also evident in a
mildly heated discussion between two women working in a camera
shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are angry,'' said one woman, who did not want to be
identified. ``They say the Americans are doing nothing. They didn't
help bring out the bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister-in-law countered: ``No, that's not fair. Of course
they wouldn't let anyone in. They have documents, secrets, they
must protect.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents were CIA files that would presumably include
profiles of Kenyan leaders and perhaps the identities of Kenyans on
the agency's payroll. Some Kenyans who did manage to get in engaged
in looting, Bushnell said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
