<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES13-C     08-12 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons Notebook: Addition of Dutton may give fans hope
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons made a roster move Wednesday
evening, and while it wasn't the one they're hoping to make a
splash with today or Friday, the addition of quarterback John
Dutton to the team is interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 222-pounder was a sixth-round draft choice of the
Dolphins in April, but Miami was _ unlike few teams in the league _
quarterback rich and waived him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In order to remain at the NFL's 80-man roster limit, the Falcons
waived rookie free agent quarterback Brian Brennan of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In some pre-draft hype, Dutton was considered as high as a
possible fourth-round pick after putting up impressive numbers in
two years at Nevada-Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton, 22, didn't throw a pass for three years from 1993-95 as
the native of Newport Beach, Calif., spent two years at Texas, and
redshirted in '95 after transferring.
</P>
<P>
   But he took off at Nevada-Reno, where he was a teammate of
Falcons rookie free agent tackle Michael Edwards. In '96, he
completed 222-of-334 passes (66.5 percent) for 2,750 yards, 22
touchdowns, and just six interceptions. Last year, he completed
222-of-367 (60.5) for 3,526 yards, 20 TDs, and six interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, however, have Dan Marino, Craig Erickson, Damon
Huard, and Stan White at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton is expected in Suwanee today.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are still negotiating with former Minnesota Vikings
defensive end Fernando Smith, who had 13.5 sacks the last two years
despite several injuries last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Durand, the agent for the 6-6, 283-pound Smith, said,
``We'd like to make a decision no later than (today). We're
considering the Falcons, New Orleans, Washington and Jacksonville.
The Falcons have shown great interest in having Fernando join the
team, and we're strongly considering Atlanta although there are no
clear front runners.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will have a brief practice today, probably at 2
p.m., as they make final preparations for Friday night's game in
Detroit. There likely will be a light workout Saturday, an off day
Sunday, and perhaps two practices Monday and/or Tuesday. There will
be no more chance of two-a-day practices after next Wednesday, when
camp breaks. On that date, veterans are allowed to go their homes
in the area. Rookies and veterans who do not have homes in the area
will continue staying at the Falcon Inn motel adjacent to team
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   This is close to a repeat of Tuesday, as the same eight players
missed practice Wednesday. They were DT Mark Campbell (knee
sprain), RT Corey Louchiey (groin), WR Keith Crawford (hamstring),
WR Tim Dwight (back), DT William Gaines (back), WR Jammi German
(groin), DE Barry Mitchell (elbow), and CB Randy Fuller (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   None will play Friday nightat Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   New injuries: CB Lenny McGill (ankle), CB Ronnie Bradford
(thumb), and S Devin Bush (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what's going on with the quarterbacks:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler _ Threw in drills, and worked with the No. 1, No.
2 and No. 3 lines and all offensive skill players.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani _ Threw in drills, and worked with the No. 1 and
No. 2 lines and all offensive skill players. Also had holding
duties while working with placekickers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg _ Threw in drills, and worked with the No. 1 and
No. 2 offensive lines, and all offensive skill players. Also had
holding duties while working with placekickers. Got almost all the
work in hurry-up offense drills at the end of practice. Early, in
11-on-11 drills, he threw a perfect 12-yard out to the left
sideline, caught by Tony Martin with Michael Booker covering.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brennan _ Threw in drills. Was waived after practice.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad, and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: Defensive left end Lester Archambeau, who has been
splitting time with the No. 1 unit this week with third-year man
John Burrough, sniffed out a few bootlegs in different drills
Wednesday, batted down a couple passes at the line of scrimmage and
was involved in a couple stops in a goalline session.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: With DeBerg running the offense against the No. 1 defense
in a hurry-up drill, there were two incompletions, then left guard
Calvin Collins jumped offsides, then several players muffed the
snap count. On third-and-20 from the offensive 20, DeBerg rolled to
his left and threw toward the sideline, and receiver Tony Martin.
Backup strong safety Chris Bayne intercepted. Against the No. 2
defense, DeBerg and the offense moved 35 yards in five plays, into
position for Morten Andersen to kick a 52-yard field goal with two
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Ever seen what happens when dinner is not mandatory at an
NFL training camp, like Wednesday in Suwanee? Stay clear of the
door, brothers and sisters. It's a stampede.
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I've been in the league 10 years, eight as a starter,
last year I was second on the team with (a career-high) 119
tackles, and you guys didn't even do a card on me.'' _ Strong
safety William White, to an Upper Deck photographer who was at
practice photographing players for trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   In one practice, the Falcons typically use about four cases of
tape, with 32 rolls in each case. That's about 128 rolls of tape,
which at 15 feet per, works out to about 1,920 feet, or 640 yards,
or six football fields plus another 40 yards worth. They also use
about 64 rolls of ``spating tape'' per practice, generally on the
outsides of shoes, and 48 rolls of spongy pre-wrap, the stuff that
goes on before the tape so when the tape is torn loose, less hair
comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Hard noses
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons got in more goalline work than in any practice yet.
When the first units were both in there, on the second play, from
the 2, Chandler rolled to his right and hit wide open TE Brian
Kozlowski for a TD as there was some confusion whether outside
linebacker Keith Brooking or a safety should have covered Koz'. On
the third play, from the 1, he hit TD Ed Smith for a TD (SLB Henri
Crockett defending).
</P>
<P>
   When the second units were out there, with DeBerg at
quarterback, the defense stopped the offense the first two times,
but on third down from the 2, Gary Downs followed backup right
guard Scott Adams and backup right tackle Ephraim Salaam into the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   With Graziani running the No. 2 offense, there were three
straight scores. First, he reversed out his right and hit TE Brian
Saxton for a TD (MLB Ruffin Hamilton covering). Next, Ken Oxendine
went up the middle for a TD, and on the third play, Graziani hit TD
O.J. Santiago, who tipped the ball up in the air and caught it for
a TD, over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   In three more plays, with DeBerg at QB, there was a 4-yard TD
pass to FB Bob Christian, a 1-yard run by Harold Green, who was
stopped short of the goalline by S Eugene Robinson, and an
incomplete pass, as Archambeau swatted the ball at the line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
