<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0973 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALES-MAKAHS-SPI &LR;      08-12 1950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALES-MAKAHS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKAH WHALE HUNT BITTERLY OPPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Week after week, Will Anderson camped on Baja beaches, lulled to
sleep by the sound of gray whales spouting and the rhythm of the
tides. Each morning, he awoke to the breathing of the great beasts.
</P>
<P>
   Now Anderson and activists like him around the world have joined
a passionate battle to stop the Makah's whale hunt this fall off
Washington's remote Olympic Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't make a difference to Anderson, an organizer with the
Progressive Animal Welfare Society, that the Makah are an
indigenous people whose culture is defined by thousands of years of
hunting whales. To Anderson, hunting gray whales _ animals he calls
friendly and intelligent _ is just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's judgment of the Makah and their attempt to breathe
new life into their culture by resurrecting the hunt is shared by
hundreds of groups around the globe, including the Humane Society
of the United States, Australians for Animals, Sea Shepherd
Conservation Society, Canadian Federation of Humane Societies,
Korea Animal Protection Society and Swiss League Against
Vivisection.
</P>
<P>
   Some organizations are seeking to stop the hunt by filing a
federal lawsuit. Others have vowed to disrupt the hunt by putting
themselves between whale and whalers.
</P>
<P>
   The debate pits ancient, indigenous rights against modern,
international mores. The conflict has generated worldwide media
coverage, a lawsuit by a Washington congressman and the creation of
an inter-agency police task force designed to provide security
during the hunt, expected to attract demonstrators from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's spiritually and morally wrong to be killing whales,''
said Anderson, who speaks of his time kayaking among the whales in
Baja California, Mexico, as ``a profound, door-opening
experience.'' Anderson makes no bones about his demand that the
Makah conform to what he believes is the prevailing global attitude
against whaling.
</P>
<P>
   As to the Makah's assertion that they have the right to hunt
whales, Anderson said, ``We are all advocates of our own belief
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The polarization could result in more than whale blood being
spilled at sea. Anderson and dozens of other animal rights
activists plan to take to the ocean in ships, inflatable boats and
a two-man submarine painted to look like a killer whale.
Ultra-light aircraft and amphibious planes will circle above. The
goal is to swarm the armed, Makah whalers, making it impossible for
them to carry out their hunt, or at the very least documenting it
on video.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the high seas that sweep the area every fall with the
high emotions of all involved, ``there is a lot of concern on our
part ... that we may end up losing somebody,'' warned Capt. James
Olson, chief of operations for the 13th Coast Guard District,
during a meeting with some of the animal rights activists in May.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to prevent chaos at sea, the Coast Guard recently
proposed establishing a 500-yard exclusion zone around the whaling
vessels. But activists like Paul Watson of the Sea Shepherd
Conservation Society have said they won't let the Coast Guard keep
them away.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is mindful that the hunters will carry a .50-caliber,
armor-piercing rifle to kill the whale after it is struck by a
harpoon.
</P>
<P>
   But despite such dangers, Watson said, ``we will do everything
that is lawful to obstruct and intervene in the hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Watson's exploits are the sinking of two Spanish and two
Icelandic whaling vessels. But he rebuts those who charge he is an
eco-terrorist by saying ``we have never caused an injury to anyone
in our entire history.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson's passion for protecting marine mammals has attracted
followers and funding from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   A co-founder of Greenpeace, Watson split with the group in 1977
and founded Sea Shepherd, which he calls ``more activist'' than
Greenpeace. ``I don't believe there is anybody more radical then
us.''
</P>
<P>
   He justifies his organization's tactics by pointing out that
many whale species are teetering on extinction and that the gray
whale has only recently been removed from the federal endangered
species list.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are not spending all our energy and money and time and
resources on the Makah killing five gray whales,'' said Watson. The
real problem, as Watson sees it, is that the Makah are leading the
way for other nations that want to return to their whaling
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the Makah to hunt based on cultural history instead of
need for food could result in countries making the same claim as a
guise for the resumption of commercial whaling, Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he worried, would undermine the International Whaling
Commission's global moratorium on commercial whaling.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1997 commission meeting, Japan's delegate asked what the
difference is between cultural necessity for the Makah and cultural
necessity for the Japanese, according to Watson.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. IWC Commissioner James Baker said the Makah's case is
far different from the Japanese desire to return to whaling. ``The
Japanese proposal for small, coastal whaling has a heavy commercial
element. They sell the whale. The U.S. has always opposed
commercial whaling. We have a written agreement with the Makah not
to sell whale,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that the Inuit whale hunt in Alaska was presented to
the IWC as primarily cultural and its approval did not open the
floodgates of indigenous whaling. The Alaskan Inuits have been
hunting for years without sparking a wholesale return to indigenous
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But Watson is not mollified. ``What we see is that thousands of
whales will be killed as soon as that first Makah harpoon goes into
a whale,'' he said. ``The moratorium will be destroyed with the
first harpoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not fighting the Makah. We are fighting Japan; we are
fighting Norway. If this moratorium is destroyed, it is a
catastrophe for many species of whale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Makah claim to have a subsistence need to hunt whales, which
Watson asserts is also bogus. In fact, no one is starving at Neah
Bay. And besides, gray whale meat tastes terrible, Watson said.
``Gray whales are bottom feeders.''
</P>
<P>
   For Watson, the Makah hunt is a frightening threat to a beloved
creature. He recalled how in 1975, he piloted a Zodiac inflatable
boat between a 150-foot Soviet harpoon vessel and a sperm whale
``reasoning that they wouldn't risk killing a human being.'' He was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A harpoon flew over the protesters' heads and slammed into the
back of one of the whales. ``The ocean erupted behind us, and
another bull came straight out of the water at the harpooner.'' The
two wounded whales ``were screaming and thrashing, and the ocean
around us was red.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the whales dove, then moments later emerged right next to
Watson's Zodiac, towering over them, raining blood and water onto
their little boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up into this huge eye and that instant changed my
life forever. That whale understood exactly what we were trying to
do. I saw pity in that eye, not for himself, but for us. The
easiest thing for that whale to have done was to come forward and
crush us. Instead, with great effort, the whale slid back into the
sea and I watched him disappear beneath the waves and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson points out that even some members of the Makah tribe want
to stop the whale hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Thompson, 74, is one of about seven Makah elders who
publicly allied themselves with Sea Shepherd. She traveled to the
International Whaling Commission meeting in Scotland in 1996 to
oppose the Makah request for a quota of gray whales. She believes
the time has passed for the tribal whale hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know anything about it,'' she said. ``We don't know
how to cut it, we don't know how to cook it and we don't want to
eat it. The Makahs ate humpback (whales). The gray whale is hot dog
and the humpback is steak.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Makahs preferred eating other whales than
grays, which were commonly used for their oil.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says it is simply not true that the tribe needs whale
meat for dietary reasons. ``Even during the Great Depression, we
didn't know we were poor. We went out to get food from the sea and
the rocks. No one was hungry. We still have the same fish, the same
clams, the same seafood.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also rejects as wishful thinking the hope that whaling
will provide a spiritual and cultural focus for the people and
become an alternative for troubled youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they say that will bring the kids out of violence,
will bring the kids out of liquor, will bring the kids out of
drugs, is done in the home,'' she said. ``The problem is not with
tribal culture, but with what is happening in the homes. It is
happening all over. I don't think my teenagers are any different
than yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a return to the old whale culture, Thompson says the
tribe should conduct whale watching trips and capitalize on
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that appeals to animal rights activists like Will
Anderson of PAWS, who has followed the gray whales on their annual
migration between Baja and the Bering Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's Makah do not know whales,'' said Anderson. ``A lot of
us feel that we do. When a whale comes up to you for a friendly
encounter it changes your perspective. We have been trying to get
the Makah interested in cultural eco-tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Toni Frohoff, a Seattle-area biologist specializing in the
behavioral interactions between whales and people, is concerned
that if whales are accustomed to friendly relations with people,
they will be sitting ducks for Makah hunters. Frohoff, who works as
a consultant to the Humane Society of the United States, said she
fears that the hunt will be a bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these people have hunted whales before and it is rare,
extremely rare, for an experienced hunter to kill a whale with a
single shot,'' Frohoff said. ``We can expect that the whales that
are struck and lost will suffer extensively before they die.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Calvert, a port commissioner in Friday Harbor and vice
chairman of the county Republican party, fears the Makah whale hunt
will repel tourists who visit the San Juan islands for
whale-watching cruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eco-tourism has become the mainstay of the economy of the San
Juans,'' said Calvert. ``This will have a devastating effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvert has been working closely with U.S. Rep. Jack Metcalf,
R.-Wash., who has opposed the Makah hunt through resolutions made
in Congress and by filing a federal lawsuit in the District of
Columbia to stop the hunt. Makah elder Thompson is also a plaintiff
in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing the hunt, the federal government failed to comply
with numerous environmental laws, including the National
Environmental Policy Act and the Endangered Species Act, according
to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf, who lives on Whidbey Island, operates his home as a bed
and breakfast, catering to many guests who come to whale watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think America is ready to step up and authorize
whaling,'' Metcalf said. ``I just don't think it is necessary or
right. There is no way to do it humanely. From the pictures I've
seen, it is just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   So awful, said animal rights activist Anderson, that when it
comes time for the hunt this fall, ``a lot of people will be out
there risking their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like myself are not going to care what the government
says about restrictions and exclusions around the hunt. We want to
document the hunt and bear witness and to put our lives on the
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
