<SLUG> BC-BURMA-DISSIDENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYANMAR AGAIN BLOCKS DEMOCRACY LEADER FROM TRAVELING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Loading a van with food, water and other
supplies, Aung San Suu Kyi embarked again Wednesday on one of the
few means of protest she has: She drove into the countryside as far
as she could until the military authorities who rule Myanmar
stopped her.
</P>
<P>
   The last time she did this, at the end of last month, she spent
six days inside her car, blocked by soldiers from proceeding and
refusing their order to return to the capital, Yangon. This time,
foreign diplomats said, she was better supplied for an even longer
stay.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of the country's pro-democracy leader _ and winner
of the Nobel Peace Prize _ stalled for days inside her car and
surrounded by soldiers seemed an apt symbol for the political dead
end the country has reached.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since Suu Kyi stepped forward as a leader during
a pro-democracy uprising, her main accomplishment has been to
dramatize the human rights abuses and political repression of the
military rulers of the former Burma. She has not succeeded in
easing the lives of her countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after her party, the National League for Democracy,
won a landslide victory in parliamentary elections, its delegates
remain blocked from taking office, powerless, harassed and often
jailed.
</P>
<P>
   In another of the symbolic acts that are her only weapons, Suu
Kyi has demanded that the elected National Assembly convene by Aug.
21, though she has not said what would happen if, as expected, the
military government ignores her demand.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of this date, she has begun traveling to the
countryside to try to meet with her supporters. The first two
times, brief meetings were permitted. The second two times she was
stopped, on the same road and in almost the same place: 15 miles
west of Yangon, heading toward the town of Bessein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of Myanmar regrets that security conditions in
Ayarwaddy division make it unsafe for Ms. Suu Kyi to travel there
at this time, but the government encourages Ms. Suu Kyi to return
home and continue her political activities in a more secure
environment in Yangon,'' the government said in a statement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The military government, for its part, can point to few
accomplishments during its decade of rule since the country's
long-time strongman, U Ne Win, stepped into the background. It
appears to have quieted the ethnic insurgencies that have
challenged the central government for years. But it has failed to
revive the economy of one of the world's poorest nations, or to win
the support either of its people or of most foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is no sign at the moment of the unrest among
students and monks that exploded into street protests _ and then
into military violence _ in August 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The political standoff is being played out in small, tense
gestures. Among these was the arrest on Sunday of 18 foreign
demonstrators who donned T-shirts with pro-democracy slogans and
began handing out tiny leaflets in downtown Yangon.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators remained in detention Wednesday as their home
governments demanded their release and as local authorities said
they were trying to decide whether to put them on trial or expel
them.
</P>
<P>
   The detainees include six Americans, three Thais, three
Malaysians, three Indonesians, two Filipinos and one Australian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
