<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DAVIS-COX     08-12 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DAVIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love III defends his PGA Championship title
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It's probably golf's most familiar scene of
1997 and surely among the most emotional. A rainbow running across
the sky at Winged Foot Golf Club at the conclusion of the PGA
Championship. A rain-soaked, teary Davis Love III flinging his
visor through the air in victory. Davis in weepy embrace with
mother Penta and wife Robin. A son realizing that his father, a
respected PGA pro lost in a plane crash in 1988, watched it all
proudly from above.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win one major or a hundred majors,'' said Love, ``that's
probably going to be the highlight of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the first round of the 90th PGA Championship begins at
Sahalee Country Club and Love becomes an equal to the other 149
players in the field, just another guy trying to negotiate this
narrow area of the Pacific Northwest without too frequently finding
timber. He will try to become the first player in 61 years to
repeat as champion. He will not be the biggest story of the week.
That designation goes to Masters and British Open champion Mark
O'Meara, 41, who attempts to become the first player since Ben
Hogan in 1953 to capture three majors in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Love this week finds himself reflecting on new, once
unattainable experiences that have been part of securing, after 12
years as a PGA Tour player, his first major championship. He
celebrates the end of a label _ the Best Player Not To Win A Major
tag that vanished by winning a Sunday showdown with his good
friend, Justin Leonard, but recalls it as ``a compliment and
annoying at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot more focus on me as a person and as a
player,'' Love said. ``It's probably been 10 times more than I
thought it would be. But then it's also been great to be on that
trophy with those other champions. I enjoy being part of that
group. It is a fun little club to be in and they make you feel a
part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the interesting aspect to the story: While Love's
hunger has not been dashed _ he wants to win all of the majors and
says, ``I'm just getting started'' _ the dream victory was not
followed by an entirely dream season. Although Love won twice after
Winged Foot, coasting to victories at Callaway Gardens last fall
and in April at Harbourtown, a pained back caused curtailment of
his schedule and concern about his future.
</P>
<P>
   Although an exercise and stretching program, as orchestrated by
Columbus, Ga., physical therapist Tom Boers, has greatly healed
Love's back at this stage, he has played only five PGA Tour events
since the MCI Classic at Hilton Head and been, for the most part,
disappointed by his performance in the majors. He tied for 33rd at
the Masters, then missed the cut at the U.S. Open, where his back
was so inflamed he could hardly play. After a three-week rest Love
rallied slightly to finish eighth at the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it stalled me a little bit in the other majors,''
Love said Wednesday. ``I wasn't very comfortable at the U.S. Open.
I probably shouldn't have even gone out there. I started feeling
better before I went and then the trip out there kind of got me. I
hit one shot on Monday and all of a sudden I was back out of it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   While pleased to have moved to No. 2 in the rankings behind
Tiger Woods, Love honestly does not know how it happened. But, then
again, he's not the first player confused by the Official (formerly
Sony) World Rankings, which list Japan's Jumbo Ozaki 11th, ahead of
Phil Mickelson and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Love said. ``Maybe I got some of Jumbo's
points. I still don't how that whole thing works. ... But it's like
a friend of mine said, 'I'm one win away from No. 1 player in the
world,' so I'm hanging in there. If I'd have not done anything the
whole year, I'd have been disappointed, but to have overcome the
distractions and still be able to have a couple good weeks, I feel
pretty good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   His lower back is the main reason. When it went into spasm in
April while in Japan for the Chunichi Crowns, Love still won the
tournament, but wondered if marked the beginning a lifetime war. He
took a month off, returning to the tour at the Memorial for a
surprising fifth-place finish. After the debacle at Olympic, Love
did not feel sufficiently healed and able to swing at 100 percent
strength until the week before the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Two stretching routines a day, about 20 minutes each, are
usually enough to keep his back loose. He avoids lengthy plane
trips on his plane, a small jet, and even flew commercial to
Seattle this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private planes are nice if you've got a big enough area to lay
down or walk around,''' Love said. ``I'm not in that category
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Boers is here this week, supervising his stable of
lumbar-ravaged stars _ Love, Couples and Ernie Els. The latter two
have disks that demand more care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate it was just a hurt and not a bad back,'' Love
said. ``Once I got the swelling and the tightness out, it's gotten
a lot better. So I feel very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Billy Andrade made the field as the eighth alternate
Wednesday when Steve Jones withdrew following the death of a close
friend. ... The ``Isleworth Slam'' is on the line this week as the
members of the posh Orlando club try to sweep the majors. O'Meara
and neighbor Lee Janzen have combined for three so far. Other
Isleworth players in the field are Woods, Scott Hoch, Stuart
Appleby and Grant Waite. ``If we could do that,'' said Woods, ``we
could say we're not going to Hawaii (for the PGA Grand Slam); we're
going to hold it at Isleworth. The PGA would love us.'' ... Woods
has been calling the towering fir and cedar trees at Sahalee
``80-foot rough.'' ... Odd pairing: Al Geiberger, 60, the 1966
champion, who made a pact to enter if son Brent made the field, and
John Daly. ...
</P>
<P>
