<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE'S BARNICLE DECISION BRINGS PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Strong protests from inside and outside The Boston
Globe newsroom Wednesday greeted Tuesday's decision to suspend
rather than terminate veteran Metro columnist Mike Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight day, editor Matthew V. Storin and
publisher Benjamin B. Taylor faced a tough grilling about the
Barnicle decision at a staff meeting. Later in the afternoon, the
publisher and editor were presented with a petition signed by 53
employees stating that ``Barnicle's reprieve gives the appearance
of a double standard that allows one individual to ignore
journalistic principles other reporters must follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Boston chapter of the NAACP and the Urban
League of Eastern Massachusetts criticized the Globe's decision to
retain Barnicle. The NAACP charged that the move reflects ``a
double standard that has both racial and gender implications.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode began when an Aug. 2 Barnicle column was found to
contain eight jokes similar to those in comedian George Carlin's
1997 ``BrainDroppings'' book. On Aug. 5, Storin _ accepting
Barnicle's explanation that he had not read the book and got the
jokes from friends _ initially suspended him for a month without
pay. But later that day, WCVB-Ch.5 in Boston ran a clip of Barnicle
endorsing the book on a June 22 edition of ``Chronicle.'' It was
then that Storin asked for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, who responded that he would not resign, has said that
he did not recall recommending the book on the air.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Storin rescinded his request for the columnist's
resignation and imposed a two-month suspension without pay. In the
meeting at which that decision was announced, Barnicle apologized
to his colleagues, saying, ``We're here today because of my
sloppiness. We're here today because I have caused embarrassment
... to the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   All this comes less than two months after black columnist
Patricia Smith resigned after admitting to fabricating aspects of
four 1998 columns.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the suspension agreement, the Globe announced that
Barnicle will reduce the amount of outside work he does, will work
to repair his frayed relationships with his editors, and will face
closer supervision of his columns. Wednesday, it was announced that
assistant managing editor Walter Robinson would become Barnicle's
supervising editor. It was Robinson's scrutiny of Smith's columns
that triggered the events that culminated in her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's staff meeting was attended by scores of Globe
employees and included tough questions about Barnicle's
transgressions and why he did not face the same fate as Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no holds barred,'' said automotive writer John White.
``And there are a lot of people who are upset with this thing.
White Anglo-Saxons are just as angry about this as our
African-American brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sorry to see how beleaguered Matt (Storin) and Ben
(Taylor) were about the situation in which they'd been trying to do
the right thing,'' said theater critic Ed Siegel. ``But the anger
at Barnicle was real and justified, and I hope it will lead to a
paper with sharper standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin characterized the meeting as ``emotional, forthright,
candid, and healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he ``understands the feelings behind'' the employee
petition, which stated that ``the reversal by Globe management not
only cripples the paper's integrity, but undermines the efforts of
staff members who work daily to produce a newspaper that is beyond
reproach. ... Globe management did the right thing by demanding
Patricia Smith's resignation and publicly airing management's
decision-making process in the newspaper. ... It erred by not
firing Barnicle and by keeping information about his case `a
private matter.'''
</P>
<P>
   The petition was an outgrowth of a Tuesday night meeting of
about a dozen mostly minority employees. But assistant Metro editor
Joseph Williams said that it was signed by white and minority
staffers and doesn't follow racial lines. The 53 signees would
represent about 10 percent of the Globe editorial employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make this an `us versus them' issue. There
are a lot of people out there who are angry and confused,'' he
said. ``It's a protest letter. We made no demands. ... We just want
to make sure they know how strongly we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to that letter, Storin acknowledged that Globe
leadership has ``a difference of opinion'' with the petitioners
over the appropriateness of the two-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision also came under fire Wednesday from the Boston
branch of the NAACP, which expressed its ``discontent'' with the
Barnicle suspension, citing a ``double standard'' in the Smith and
Barnicle cases.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an Aug. 7 letter written by Staples CEO Thomas G.
Stemberg to Taylor hinting that he might withdraw his advertising
from the Globe were Barnicle dismissed, NAACP president Leonard
Alkins said in an interview that his suspension ``is not a decision
based upon ethics. It is a decision based upon economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Storin and Taylor have stated that the Barnicle suspension
was not influenced by advertiser or outside pressure. Storin noted
that in the past the Globe has published articles angering such
major advertisers as Fleet, Fidelity, Bell Atlantic, and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Wallace-Benjamin, president and CEO of the Urban League of
Eastern Massachusetts, also released a statement on the Barnicle
suspension Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times does an employee at the Globe get to bend and
sway the rules before they are dismissed?'' she asked. ``From where
we sit, it depends on who you are and how many people you can get
to cry to the paper about how you are being mistreated. And perhaps
the tolerance for it is influenced by race, gender, and how long
you have been able to break the rules and still remain employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the perception of a double standard, Storin said that
in the past, reporters caught plagiarizing _ a more serious offense
than that for which Barnicle was punished _ received shorter
suspensions than the columnist. He also said that Smith was given a
second chance after evidence surfaced in 1995 that she had been
fabricating information in her columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could argue,'' he added, ``that the Patricia Smith (case)
brought about not only greater scrutiny of Barnicle, but in fact a
greater penalty than what he would have had otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In an additional development Wednesday, the Rev. Eugene F.
Rivers III, pastor of the Azusa Christian Community, who has
characterized the Barnicle suspension as a ``slap on the wrist,''
said he was trying to set up a meeting with Globe personnel to
discuss ``the journalistic sacred trust and the Barnicle affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to listen and understand what happened ... so that our
worst fears are allayed,'' said Rivers. ``We're not interested in
mau-mauing or playing political games.''
</P>
<P>
   Indicating that the Barnicle episode provided a ``legitimate
occasion ... to look at diversity and affirmative action at the
Globe,'' Rivers said he would be asking for more black
representation on the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
