</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-DEAD-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT PREPARES TO ESCORT HOME THE BODIES OF `VERY BRAVE
AMERICANS'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: AFRICA-RDP, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-ENVOY,
AFRICA-INQUIRY) 
(nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSHUT, Germany _ ``I am bringing home 10 very brave
Americans,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said here
Wednesday night as she prepared to fly home with the bodies of 10
of the 12 Americans killed in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Albright spoke after visiting eight Kenyan employees of the
State Department and an American staff member who are in the
American military hospital here for injuries suffered in the
bombing, which killed 250 people and wounded 5,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has flown 12 wounded Kenyans and 10 Americans to
Germany since the bombing, but nine of the Americans were later
flown on to hospitals in the United States. One Kenyan staff
member, identified by German officials as Joash Okindo, is in a
German university clinic in Homburg with serious head injuries.
Officials said not all of those hospitalized here were well enough
to receive visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just been visiting nine patients who are here, and they
are getting better,'' Albright said at the entrance to the Landshut
Regional Medical Center as night fell.
</P>
<P>
   She had spent just short of an hour talking privately with the
injured and with relatives of the one American from Nairobi who is
still here, Carolyn Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expressed President Clinton's best wishes and support to
them and said we would do everything we could, not only for them
but for all Kenyans, Tanzanians and Americans who were hurt,'' she
said. Ten people were killed in an almost simultaneous explosion
near the American Embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be intimidated or pushed off the world stage by
people who do not like what we stand for, and that is freedom,
democracy, and the fight against disease and poverty and
terrorism,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, Albright did not allow photographers or
reporters to follow her through the wards, apparently so as not to
subject the injured to additional trauma.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state will depart nearby Ramstein Air Base
early Thursday morning in a C-17 military transport with the
flag-draped coffins of the 10 dead, whose bodies have been lying in
the medical center mortuary since they arrived here early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to greet the plane after its arrival at
Andrews Air Force Base, Md., according to American officials here.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Air Force Senior Master Sgt. Sherry Lynn Olds, of
Panama City, Fla., was flown to Dover Air Force Base in Delaware on
Wednesday at the request of her family, military officials said.
The 12th American casualty of the bombing, Jean Dalizu, was to be
buried in Kenya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the hospital, Albright did not allow photographers or
reporters to follow her through the wards, apparently so as not to
subject the injured to additional trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the seven Americans medically evacuated to the United
States Wednesday before Albright's arrival went to Walter Reed Army
Medical Center in Washington. They were identified by Army
officials here as Sgt. Daniel Briehl of the Marines, Clyde Hirn,
Gary Lonnquist, Frank Pressley, Lydia Sparks and Gary Spears. The
seventh, Carol Hawley, was transferred to Brooke Army Medical
Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Another, David Robertson, left for a hospital in Phoenix on a
commercial flight on Tuesday, officials of the medical center here
said. One more, Ellen Bomer, was flown to Walter Reed late Sunday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
