<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BOMBINGS-HNS &LR;      08-12 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BOMBINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS WORLDWIDE SECURITY REVIEW OF U.S. EMBASSIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday called for a review
of security at U.S. embassies worldwide and said he will ask
Congress for emergency funding to pay for safety enhancements in
the wake of two embassy bombings in East Africa last week, National
Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the review after meeting with his national
security staff for two hours Wednesday about the investigation into
the attacks. Twelve Americans were killed in the bombing in
Nairobi, Kenya. No Americans were killed in the blast at the
embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. The two blasts killed more than
250 people and injured more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Beirut in 1983 led to
security reviews and more precautions at U.S. embassies under the
1986 Diplomatic Security Act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants this review to include a list of priorities for
improving embassy security, particularly at high-risk facilities,
such as those in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The president asked that the security review be completed within
the next few days, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Appropriations
Committee, indicated he was prepared to increase spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president asks for emergency funds, I will support it
... to assure protection of our personnel and embassies,'' Stevens
told The Associated Press. ``This terrorist threat must be
countered.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be on hand Thursday to offer a eulogy when an Air
Force plane carrying the remains of 10 Americans arrives at Andrews
Air Force Base in Maryland, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two dead Americans not on the plane include one who was
married to a Kenyan and will be buried in that country. The family
of the other wanted a private memorial ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels it's important in his role as the president
to convey a sense of the nation to the families: our sympathies,
our respect and our gratitude for the contribution these people and
their families have made for this country,'' Lockhart said. ``It's
obviously an event that I think weighs heavily on him, but he
believes it's important ... to speak for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven people injured in the blasts arrived Wednesday for
treatment at Walter Reed Army Hospital in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the national security staff meeting, Attorney General Janet
Reno updated Clinton on the status of the FBI's criminal
investigation of the bombings. Undersecretary of State for
Political Affairs Thomas Pickering, standing in for Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, discussed worldwide embassy security,
Crowley said. Defense Secretary William Cohen also attended the
high-level meeting. However, Crowley did not say whether the
subject of military retaliation arose.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was not at the meeting because she went to Germany on
Wednesday to visit injured Americans at Landstuhl Hospital near
Wiesbaden. She plans to be on the plane bringing the bodies of the
victims to the United States, the State Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the president was pleased with the ``outstanding
cooperation'' U.S. investigators have received from Kenyan and
Tanzanian law enforcement. Both countries have permitted FBI agents
access to all suspects who have been detained and questioned, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley refused to provide details of the investigation, saying
such disclosures would assist terrorists trying to elude capture.
He reiterated Clinton's statement that the United States would not
yield to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to create a fortress America,'' Crowley said.
``We are not going to retreat from the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
