</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LOZZANO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S LOZZANO HAPPY TO BE HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Lawrence Lozzano had all but given up hope of
returning home to play soccer when the news he'd been awaiting for
three years finally arrived last week: He'd been traded to the Los
Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   It could hardly have been more welcome: Lozzano, a versatile
veteran from Cerritos, was moving to one of the premier teams in
American soccer, where he was rejoining nearly a half-dozen former
teammates and one of his first professional coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, he was going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good,'' says Lozzano, 28, who won't make his debut
for the Galaxy (18-6, 52 points) when it takes on the Kansas City
Wizards (10-12, 26) tonight at the Rose Bowl because of a nagging
hamstring injury. ``The situation is perfect for me here, being
from here, having a house here in Cerritos, being local, playing
for the hometown team in front of friends and family. ...
Especially with (the Galaxy) being a first-place team, a winning
team, possibly a championship team. That makes everything nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lozzano is happiest for his wife, Dinorah, and three sons, who
finally can live at home rather than going back and forth between
San Jose, where he starred for the Clash, and Cerritos.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any negatives, it would be that the former Gahr
High standout probably won't see much time at his favored position,
forward, instead providing depth to the Galaxy's defense and
midfield. And that's not much of a negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to attack more than defend, but wherever this team
needs me, I will contribute as much as I can,'' he says. ``Winning
the championship is the goal here, and I'll do what I can to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a few weeks before he gets the chance. His hamstring
injury has sidelined him since July 11, and he's been working with
Galaxy trainers Ivan Pierra and Jim Liston this week to get back
into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Lozzano can play anywhere on the field, and he has done so in a
career that started as soon as he was out of high school and
includes stints with the U.S. national team, with whom he's made
seven appearances, and in Mexico, where he led Tampico Madero in
scoring three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's been trying to join the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning (of Major League Soccer), I was supposed to
come here,'' he explains. ``I was supposed to be picked up in the
(1996) draft by the Galaxy on the third round, fourth pick, but
Dallas took me with the third pick. They were going to try to trade
me (to the Galaxy), and when I went to San Jose (after the '96
season), they tried to trade me, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been ongoing for awhile, and so finally I just
concentrated on playing and figured if it happens, it happens. I
kind of thought it would never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dallas, Lozzano played primarily as a defender, making 22
of 31 starts on the back line during MLS's inaugural season. With
the Clash, he was a forward, contributing 10 goals and 10 assists
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy acquired Lozzano for forward Harut Karapetyan, who
had requested a trade after his playing time was severely cut this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an issue of the versatility and polyfunctionality of
Lawrence Lozzano,'' said Octavio Zambrano, who coached Lozzano with
the California Emperors and Los Angeles Salsa. ``When he's played
in defense, he's done well, and in Mexico and San Jose when he was
a forward, he's done quite well. He can play anywhere, and he's a
tough guy, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's a very, very happy guy to be back in his hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   That could pay off, Lozzano suggests. ``Your lifestyle affects
your training habits, and it has a lot to do with with you reaching
your full potential,'' he said. ``In terms of being 100 percent all
the time, (being happy) makes that so much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   So does playing for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell the difference when I walked into the locker room
on Monday,'' he says. ``They're a great group of guys, and they
welcomed me to the team, made me feel comfortable. It's night and
day (compared with San Jose). Over there, it's a losing team,
inconsistent, and at times the guys on the field aren't getting
along. It seems everyone gets along here, respects each other.
That's one of the ingredients to a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   A win tonight, in regulation or shootout, will secure a playoff
berth for the Galaxy. If L.A. falls, it would qualify if Dallas
fails to win in regulation Saturday at Colorado. ... The only way
L.A. misses the playoffs is by losing its last eight games, Dallas
winning its last nine in regulation, and the Burn winning the Sept.
2 meeting in the Rose Bowl by 40 goals. ... The Galaxy has scored
68 goals, two shy of the single-season record set last year by D.C.
United. ... The Wizards are clinging to fourth place in the Western
Conference, one point ahead of Dallas and three in front of San
Jose in the race for the final playoff berth. They have lost in
regulation only once in their last seven games, a 2-0 defeat to the
Galaxy on July 4 at the Rose Bowl, but fell twice in shootouts
before beating Colorado, 3-1, on Saturday. ... Mo Johnston, with
nine goals and two assists in 17 games, is the only K.C. attacker
who has been on form this season, one reason why the Wizards are
struggling so. Preki (4 goals, 7 assists), the '97 MLS MVP, Mark
Chung (0, 5) and Digital Takawira (5, 2) have been disappointing.
... Chung had two of his assists against Colorado. ... Johnston has
a goal or assist in each of the past five games. ... Goalkeeper
Mike Ammann, an Orange native, has been the brightest spot for
Kansas City with five shutouts and a 1.33 goals-against average,
third in the league. ... Kansas City has surrendered the fewest
goals of any MLS team (30) but has only scored 30, second-worst in
the league. ... The Wizards are an MLS-worst 2-9 on the road; last
season, when they won the West regular-season title, they were 9-7
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
