<HEADLINE>
U.S. ROCKET CARRYING SPY SATELLITE EXPLODES AFTER LIFTOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Air Force rocket carrying a spy satellite blew
up shortly after launch Wednesday, creating a $1 billion Roman
candle that showered debris and sparks across a wide swath of ocean
and dealing a setback to the country's space-reconnaissance
program.
</P>
<P>
   The Titan 4A rocket blew up about 40 seconds after its 7:30 a.m.
liftoff from Cape Canaveral, Fla., into a hazy sky. The Air Force
said the rocket's nose dipped slightly just before the craft turned
into a fireball some 20,000 feet up. Seconds later, flight
controllers radioed signals to trigger another explosion and break
the falling debris into smaller, less dangerous chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said they had no idea what caused the
accident. An investigative board will be convened at once, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured, and there appeared to be no property damage,
officials said. Even so, the mood around the cape was one of
dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' the launch announcer muttered as the Titan exploded.
``It appears that we've had a malfunction of the vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The blast could be heard miles away and set off car alarms in
the region. It also reverberated on Wall Street, and its echoes may
be felt in Pentagon planning rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite was intended to monitor air-defense radar networks
and track missile tests, according to an official intimately
familiar with the project, and while its loss is not a catastrophe
it dashes several years' of planning and could delay further
satellite launches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial thought is, `We're hurt,' '' Brig. Gen. Randall
Starbuck, commander of the 45th Space Wing at Cape Canaveral, said
at a somber press conference. ``This is a sad day for the United
States Air Force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
