<SLUG> BC-COLO-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. CAMPBELL CALLS PRIMARY WIN A TRIUMPH FOR GOP MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, who easily defeated a
conservative challenger Tuesday night in his first election since
switching parties, called his victory a triumph for Republican
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends an important message to me, because I am sick to
death of my opponents saying Republicans don't trust me _ they do
trust me in landslide proportions,'' said Campbell, who beat Bill
Eggert, 71 percent to 29 percent. ``It shows the moderate voices
within the Republican Party are dominating.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell switched from the Democratic party three years ago.
Eager to encourage Democratic defectors, the Republican Senatorial
Campaign Committee in Washington made a rare foray into primary
politics, mailing out pro-Campbell postcards to thousands of
Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic opponent will be Dottie Lamm, a women's activist
and wife of former Gov. Richard Lamm. She defeated a more liberal
opponent, state Rep. Gil Romero of Pueblo, 58 to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also chose a woman in the primary for governor,
Lt. Gov. Gail Schoettler, a former banker. She will face state
Treasurer Bill Owens, who won the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's race, Democrats argue that the governorship is
the only barrier keeping Colorado from slipping into ``one party''
status. In neighboring Kansas, Wyoming and Utah, Republicans
control the legislatures and the governors' mansions. In Colorado,
Democrats have held the governor's office since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a Democratic governor to say no to a Republican
legislature when it needs to be said,'' said Gov. Roy Romer, who is
barred from running for a fourth term by Colorado's term limits
law.
</P>
<P>
   In primaries, where moderates generally prevailed, several new
faces emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Udall, son of Morris Udall, the former congressman,
unexpectedly won the Democratic congressional nomination for the
Second District. This area, which includes Boulder, has been in
Democratic hands since 1974, the year President Nixon resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Republicans now have their best chance in years to
regain the seat. On Tuesday, voters nominated Bob Greenlee, a
millionaire radio entrepreneur, who is a moderate and Boulder's
first Republican mayor in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjoining Sixth District, the western suburbs of Denver,
the Republicans nominated Tom Tancredo, an anti-tax activist and
former director of the Independence Institute, a
libertarian-leaning think tank. Although the district has been in
Republican hands since it was created 14 years ago, Tancredo's
arch-conservatism may open the door to the Democratic candidate,
Henry Strauss, a real estate developer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
