<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INCOME-GAP-ECONSCENE-     08-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCOME-GAP-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: CLOSING THE INCOME GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most economists are most comfortable thinking and writing about
what is, or will be. Would cutting the capital gains tax to 15
percent transform couch potatoes into software entrepreneurs? Would
4 percent unemployment lead to inflation? Just ask you friendly,
neighborhood PhD. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, truth be known, most economists have a weakness for clever
fixes that exploit free markets. Want to prevent the overfishing of
coastal waters? Privatize the rights to fish. Want to curb global
warming for a fraction of the cost of conserving energy at home?
Let Western consumers pay the Chinese and Russians to cut their
emissions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But efficiency isn't an end in itself: making more stuff for
less gets you only part of the way to the economist's nirvana. And
maybe, just maybe, economists _ and other Americans _ are worrying
too little about dividing up the spoils. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's economic system does work better than the obvious
alternatives. After all, the socialist utopias collapsed under the
cumulative weight of their internal contradictions. Asia's crony
capitalism has proved that it isn't ready for prime time. Europe's
mixed economies perch on a powder keg of 20 percent youth
unemployment _ and can't think of any way out, save for the risky
strategy of following the advice of Alexander Hamilton and adopting
a common currency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the celebration may be getting out of hand. For while the
American system is doing many things right, most economists would
agree that it is doing one big thing wrong: for the last quarter
century, virtually all the bounty of growth has gone to the
educated, enterprising and already-affluent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, growth was seen as the solution to all
problems. Competitive markets, the not-so-dismal scientists
reminded us, had insured that two-thirds of all income had gone to
wages as far back as the division between capital and labor could
be measured. Hence, a growing, fully employed economy would mean
rising living standards for all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But since the 1970s, economists have learned that a very nasty
devil lurks in the details. While labor still captures about
two-thirds of national income, only skilled workers have benefited.
And even within this elite, the phenomenon of ``winner take all''
has increased the gaps between the successful and the also-rans in
occupations as diverse as law, plumbing and basketball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of business-as-usual argue that the consequences are
less than meet the eye. Inequality of consumption, they note, is
less extreme than inequality of wages or incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Social mobility allows some of the poor to make the leap to the
comfortable middle. The earned-income tax credit _ a negative
income tax for the working poor _ has offset some of the wage
decline of the unskilled. And the elderly, the people traditionally
at greatest risk, are generally shielded from poverty by Social
Security and Medicare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But such rationalizations get you only so far in an economy that
has grown steadily less egalitarian over the last quarter century.
The most comprehensive estimate of income distribution, by Lynn
Karoly of the Rand Corp., shows that the real income of the bottom
10th of American families fell by 13 percent between 1973 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And Brooks Pierce, an economist at the Bureau of Labor
Statistics, has found this growing inequality has been magnified by
the decline of company-wide medical and pension benefits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What could be done to right the imbalance without damaging the
engine of economic growth? Probably plenty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The earned-income tax credit could be expanded. State and
federal tax systems could be tilted, effectively eliminating taxes
on the bottom third of the income distribution and making up the
lost revenue with modest increases on the top third. Government
could take some of the sting out of private income inequality by
increasing outlays for communal services _ day care, early
childhood education, mass transit, recreation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is being done? Precious little. Virtually all recent tax
changes have had the effect of allowing the rich to keep more of
their earnings. President Clinton's acclaimed effort to make
college affordable has funneled the greatest share of the tax
breaks to the middle class. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surprising the skeptics, welfare reform has been successful in
cutting dependence. But it is safe to say that tough love gets you
only so far. Even its most optimistic supporters concede that the
social infrastructure of day care and medical benefits is sorely
lacking _ and that roughly one-third of the welfare caseload is
hopelessly unprepared for gainful employment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A decade hence, will hindsight show that American capitalism,
too, was drifting toward the ashcan of history? Probably not. But
history rarely looks kindly on societies that trumpet their virtues
and ignore their failings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
