<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RATES-CONSUMERS-ART-5     08-12 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATES-CONSUMERS-ART-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISIS IN ASIA LEADS TO LOW INTEREST RATES IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One side effect of the financial crisis in Asia is incredibly
low interest rates for American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the region's malaise, demand for computers and their
components and a variety of other products is dwindling, putting
downward pressure on the earnings of many U.S. companies. But that
very damper on growth has made inflation a distant worry and kept
interest rates attractive to borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates have reached historic lows in recent
days, and consumers can largely expect more of the same, according
to economists and market analysts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond touched 5.55
percent, its lowest level since the Treasury Department began
issuing bonds on a regular basis in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Yields fall when investors clamor for bonds and push up their
prices. That is what happened on Tuesday as fears increased that
Japan's economic recession would worsen and investors fled
worldwide equity markets for the relative safety of bonds backed by
the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the yield on the 30-year bond was down 2/32, to a
price of 107 15/32, while the yield was unchanged at 5.60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general feeling is that interest rates will remain good
and there's not a lot of economic news out there to steer us
otherwise,'' said Greg Lumsden, a managing director of loan
originations at Countrywide Credit Industries, one of the nation's
largest mortgage loan providers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, home mortgage refinancings have hit their highest
levels in years and they are expected to continue at a strong pace.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on a 30-year mortgage, which started
the year at 7.05 percent, is now 6.9 percent, and has been below 7
percent for eight weeks, the longest stretch since 1993, according
to Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage provider. Rates are
expected to remain in that range through the end of the year, said
Robert Barr, a senior economist at Fannie Mae.
</P>
<P>
   If Asia's economic crisis continues to worsen, ``our forecast
may be a little too conservative,'' Barr said, suggesting that
rates could fall even further.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae forecasts that $1.33 trillion in mortgages, for home
purchases and refinancings, will be made in 1998, up from $834
billion last year. The record was $1.2 trillion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 10-year Treasury note, increasingly used as a
gauge for mortgage rates, rose six basis points, to 5.43 percent
Wednesday, but remains near its June low of 5.35 percent, also its
lowest level since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Declines in rates for other types of consumer borrowing are even
more striking.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year new-car loans are now available from banks at an
average rate of 9.05 percent, down from 9.21 percent at the
beginning of the year and 9.36 percent a year ago, according to
Bank Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   And bank-issued credit cards offer fixed rates almost two
percentage points lower than where they were at the beginning of
the year. At this time last year, the average rate was 16.85
percent and it remained at 16.82 at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate of about 15.06 percent, a consumer carrying
a card with a $1,000 balance who switches to the lower rate from
the rate of a year ago could save $200 a year in interest payments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The rates for people with good credit continue to go down,''
Bill Anderson, president of Bank Rate Monitor, said.
</P>
<P>
   A stellar credit history may qualify consumers for a credit card
with a 9.90 percent fixed rate that Capital One Financial began in
April or a similar card at 9.99 percent from First USA Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Declining interest rates and fierce competition have also pushed
some introductory ``teaser'' rates for new cardholders to as low as
zero, from the recent average of about 5.9 percent to 6.9 percent,
said Robert McKinley, president of Cardweb Inc., a Gettysburg, Pa.,
research firm which tracks the card industry.
</P>
<P>
   While rates are unlikely to fall much more, credit-card rates
for consumers with a less than rosy credit history are actually
going higher as lenders become more concerned about their own risks
in a weakening economic environment, McKinley said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card issuers are also imposing more stringent
restrictions on customers. One late payment, for example, can cause
a customer to forfeit a low introductory rate, and late-payment
fees are rising, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In what is known as the subprime card market, which caters to
consumers with low incomes, poor credit or no credit history, rates
now run 18 percent to 21 percent, said Spencer Nilson, publisher of
the Nilson Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Low rates on everything from mortgages to auto loans raise a
note of caution from some economists.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy slows drastically, consumers may find themselves
overextended after taking advantage of today's favorable rates to
borrow, Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities Company
International, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have called this the Goldilocks economy, but maybe
we're getting to the part where Goldilocks meets the three bears,''
Brusca said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
