<HEADLINE>
THE BENEFITS OF A POSTAL CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A calorie-counting guide in the latest issue of Fitness magazine
proclaims that:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; burns 160 calories an hour escorting
visitors through the White House;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Kate Moss  &LR; burns 205 calories an hour runway modeling;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Martha Stewart &LR;  burns 225 calories an hour potting fall
bulbs;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gillian Anderson  &LR; burns 480 calories an hour chasing aliens
on ``The X-Files'';
</P>
<P>
   _ A postal worker delivering mail on foot on a hilly route burns
485 calories an hour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETORT TO THE REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; T.S. Bolton &LR;  sends word of the Drudge Retort, an online
response to  &UR; Matt Drudge &LR; 's notorious online news site. The Report,
which broke the  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  story, has been criticized for
overeagerness in scandal-mongering and undereagerness in
rumor-checking.
</P>
<P>
   The Retort's faux ``editorial board'' includes  &UR; Stephen &LR; 
 &UR; Glass &LR; , the magazine journalist who's admitted making up sources
and quotes;  &UR; Janet Cooke &LR; , the Washington Post Pulitzer Prize
winner who lost her job for making up a story;  &UR; Patricia Smith &LR; ,
who resigned from the Boston Globe for fabricating incidents and
people; and  &UR; Mike Barnicle &LR; , who's in hot water with the Globe for
allegedly stealing jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``report'' on the Retort site describes all White
House staff members being required to become Universal Life Church
ministers, because conversations between the president ``and his
padre'' would then be protected as privileged. ``We considered
making the entire staff into presidential psychologists,'' says an
imaginary White House aide, ``but we just didn't have the time or
money to enroll everyone in med school.''
</P>
<P>
   The Retort's home page lists a Southern California snail-mail
address and an e-mail address that doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE SMALL STEP FOR MURPHY BROWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Although Murphy Brown was a fictional TV journalist, TV truth is
often stranger than fiction. New York magazine reports that
 &UR; Candice Bergen &LR; , who starred in the comedy series, has been
talking with ``60 Minutes'' producer  &UR; Don Hewitt &LR;  about
contributing stories to the TV newsmagazine.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Hewitt told New York, he'd talked with
Bergen, who was at the time interested in a career as a
photojournalist. She decided to try acting instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we make the determination that there is a story worth her
doing,'' said Hewitt, ``we'll give her a chance to do it, and we'll
see how she does. ... She's one of the most intelligent people I've
ever met in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sally Kirkland &LR;  is getting her breast implants removed on
camera, says the New York Post, for an informational video about
women with implant problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scotland Yard has arrested a man and charged him with
extortion for trying to sell a naked portrait of  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 
to  &UR; Mohamed al-Fayed &LR;  for $180,000. The man had claimed _ falsely,
according to police _ that the princess had hired him to create the
work.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bo Derek  &LR; is selling the 31-acre estate in Los Angeles that
she lived in with  &UR; John Derek &LR;  for almost 20 years. It was put on
the market just before he died in May. The asking price is $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THINGS GREAT AND SMALL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Bittner &LR; , publisher of the Flock Report, about the wild
parrots of Telegraph Hill, writes in the latest issue that he has
identified two more groups of birds down the Peninsula, both
roosting in churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palo Alto flock is Episcopalian, the Sunnyvale flock,
Catholic. I've been unable to establish which religion the
Telegraph Hill flock follows,'' writes Bittner.
</P>
<P>
   (In other fauna news, the Berkeley Bark asserts that female dogs
prefer to urinate in the center of a lawn, while male dogs ``water
the edges.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big-budget Hollywood romantic comedies are the genre I loathe.
I try not to ruin it, but I start squirming and fuming, and I can
feel all the people around me loving it, and I almost have to be
taken away on a stretcher.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR;  Director John Waters, whose next movie is ``Pecker,'' in
Details magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
