<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENGALS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steele and Krumrie: Twin sons of different mothers
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Ky. _ The mentor and the student don't look alike on
the outside, but their hearts and mean streaks are identical.
</P>
<P>
   When rookie defensive lineman Glen Steele first joined the
Cincinnati Bengals, line coach Tim Krumrie pointed toward him and
said, ``Steele reminds me of an old saying Paul Brown said about me
when I was being timed in the 40 (yard dash). PB said, `I wish
training camp was here so we could put him in pads and let him hit
somebody.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp is here and the fourth-round draft choice from
Michigan hasn't stopped hitting and reminding people of Krumrie,
the classic overachiever who arrived in Cincinnati as a 10th-round
pick and played 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really critiqued myself when I played,'' Krumrie said.
``I just tried to play hard every down. That's the same thing about
Steele. He's not going to ring your bells and whistles in his
shorts, but when he puts his pads on he's going to hit you in the
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-4 and 295 pounds, Steele is taller and heavier than
Krumrie, but their playing styles and approach to the game are
similar.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's practice at Centerville High School, for example,
Steele was suffering from an intestinal virus, but he kept working
until he was taken to the locker room for two pints of intervenes
fluids. He then participated fully in both of Wednesday's workouts
at the Bengals' Georgetown College training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of moves and I'm not the quickest guy in
the world,'' he said, ``but I'm willing to work and I want to
learn. Whether you're a rookie or a 10-year veteran, you should
learn something every time you go on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele's learning curve has been complicated because he's
playing both end, his position as a four-year starter at Michigan,
and nose tackle. With regular nose tackle Kimo von Oelhoffen out
with a pulled groin, Steele has spent most of this week at that
position and is expected to get considerable playing time there in
Monday night's preseason home opener against Indianapolis. ``The
hardest thing to get used to is the pace,'' Steele said.
``Everything is boom, boom, boom. If you don't know what you're
doing, you can get behind real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   If Steele's name and his new No. 70 aren't familiar, you might
recall what he did against Ohio State last November while wearing
No. 81. In the 20-12 victory that knocked the Buckeyes out of the
Rose Bowl, he had two sacks, three other tackles for lost yardage
and a fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The roster won't be set until Aug. 30, but Krumrie gave every
indication that Steele's name will be on the final list. ``This guy
isn't a project. He's going to play. He's having a good, solid camp
and he keeps getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
