<HEADER>
A1019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COLUMN13-COX     08-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top seed tanks in ATP final
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASON, Ohio _ I don't pretend to know more than a computer but
if Marcelo Rios is the No. 1 player in tennis, the sport should be
fumigated.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, the computer's top man, put up a less-than-valiant effort
Tuesday night, losing in 62 minutes to someone named Daniel Vacek,
whose previous claim to fame was that his mother is named Radmila.
No. 1 players don't lose in 62 minutes to anybody, let alone Daniel
Vacek, who in 10 years on the tour has never won.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the computer's No. 2 player, Pete Sampras,
played his first match Wednesday, and it is my duty to report that
No. 2 looked suspiciously like No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the best player in the world,'' Martin Damm said
after Sampras rolled over him like a truck, 6-4, 6-2, in the Great
American Insurance ATP Championship.
</P>
<P>
   It was quick and workmanlike _ one hour, 13 minutes _ a fitting
27th birthday present from Sampras to himself. But more
importantly, it was the way top players should comport themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you're No. 12 in the world or No. 18 and you need a week off,
it's one thing to show up as a shadow. If you're No. 1, call in
sick and give the spot in the draw to someone who cares.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Rios' pathetic tank on Tuesday night, Sampras was
diplomatic. ``I know nothing about it,'' he said. ``It's hard for
me to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a ringing endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The former and future No. 1 player won by breaking Damm at 4-5
in the first when Damm's serve suddenly went haywire, like a
computer crashing. Damm hit only one first-service in in that game,
and only 36 percent in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras feasted on Damm's second serve like Dom DeLuise at an
all-you-can-eat buffet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play with your second serve against a guy like
Pete,'' the 26-year-old Czech said. ``It was an easy match for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   How would Sampras celebrate his birthday?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go back to my room, have dinner and get ready for
tomorrow,'' he said. ``Have a little dessert. Treat myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is your family here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're all by yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has taken criticism for tennis' fall from grace from the
heady days of McEnroe-Connors and McEnroe-Lendl. No charisma, say
his critics. Too bland. Too robotic, like R2D2 but without the
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   He rejects the charge. ``I'm an athlete,'' he said. ``I'm not a
celebrity. I'm not a big star.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the hammer: ``I'm an anti-celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees himself as a tennis player, which would have sufficed 20
years ago. But this is the '90s and just being good is almost
sinful.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded of Stan Smith, who was No. 1 in the early '70s
when I started covering the sport. Sampras and Smith are very much
alike _ serve and volley specialists with muted personalities _
except Smith was accepted for exactly what he was: a great tennis
player. He wasn't asked to show false emotion on the court or make
headlines off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a showy guy,'' Sampras said. ``I'm not flamboyant.
People know what I'm about. I'm about winning tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike Rios, he is about giving his all.
</P>
<P>
   He said it used to bother him when he read that he was boring
and was ruining the game. Now, he said, he has adopted a line Jack
Nicklaus used when the same nonsense was foisted on him: ``The more
I won, the less I cared,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   He has won plenty, 55 tournaments, including 11 Grand Slam
events.
</P>
<P>
   He is No. 2 with a bullet, and his birthday party Wednesday
night was subdued. As is he.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
