<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNGER-DONATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philanthropist Kantor makes donations to the hungry
 &HT;    By Kavita Kumar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Trucks loaded with 89,700 jars of baby food and
18,432 bottles of salad dressing were on their way Wednesday to
four major Ohio food banks, thanks to a gift from philanthropist
Milton Kantor.
</P>
<P>
   Kantor, chief executive officer of Victory Wholesale Grocers,
contributed the goods valued at more than $50,000 to help feed some
of the 1.6 million Ohioans living below the federal poverty level,
a fourth of whom are children.
</P>
<P>
   The food will be distributed through the Miami Valley Emergency
Food Bank, Cincinnati Free Store, Southeastern Ohio Regional Food
Bank and Shared Harvest Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Dayton), an anti-hunger advocate and
friend of Kantor, helped arrange the distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Kantor had set out to send baby food to aid the starving victims
of civil war in Sudan, but found that helping the needy overseas is
often not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen pictures of the children in Sudan and so we had a
meeting because I knew we had to do something,'' Kantor said.
Problems with logistics, distribution and red tape prevented the
goods from being sent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said cultural differences can also complicate overseas
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, (Sudanese) won't eat the baby food; it's not
indigenous to them. So then we tried to barter it, but that also
proved difficult,'' he said. ``So I suggested the food stay
local.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was especially concerned about Appalachian areas, where
requests for emergency food increased by 43 percent last year. In
March, he had toured the poorest areas of Appalachian Ohio and was
disturbed by the widespread hunger he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Kantor dedicated the gift to the memory of Hall's 15-year-old
son, Matt, who died two years ago of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In Logan, the director of the Southeastern Ohio Regional Food
Bank said Kantor's gift is the largest donation of baby food in the
distribution center's 14-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a rurally depressed part of the state with depreciated
resources,'' said its director, Dick Stevens. ``We have many in our
area who are working just above the minimum wage, which is often
not enough to support their families.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Kumar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
