<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORS-NOTE-NYT     08-12 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORS-NOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EDITOR'S NOTE FOR THURSDAY, AUGUST 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: This editor's note will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on August 19, 1997,
described the operations of the European Union Bank, an offshore
institution based in Antigua. The article said two of the bank's
original directors, Aleksandr P. Konanikhin and Mikhail B.
Khodorovsky, were officers of the Menatep Bank of Moscow. It quoted
unidentified British and American officials who said Menatep had
links to Russian organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, The Times should have sought a response from
Menatep, Mr. Khodorovsky and Mr. Ko-nanikhin.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Khodorovsky has since said the allegations about Menatep
were ``baseless'' and ``entirely false.'' He said last fall that
Menatep had earned a B+ rating from Thomson Bank Watch, an
international rating service, and had recently gained approval from
the Securities and Exchange Commission to sell stock in the United
States. He added that the bank had ties to the World Bank and was a
``respected, reputable financial institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Khodorovsky said he withdrew as a director of the European
Union Bank in 1994, a week after its registration, and played no
role in its operations before then.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Konanikhin said the allegations against him, including an
arrest in the United States, visa violations and Russian charges of
having embezzled $8 million, resulted from ``disinformation'' by
Russian intelligence, which influenced or duped officials at the
United States Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   This editors' note was delayed pending the outcome of a lawsuit
in London against The International Herald Tribune over the
article. The Times was not sued, and the suit has now been settled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
