</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOKESMAN SAYS CLINTON WILL ANSWER EVERY GRAND JURY QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-OBSTRUCT) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will answer every question put to
him when he testifies on Monday in the grand jury investigation
into his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a White House spokesman
indicated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some television commentators and essayists have speculated that
Clinton may choose to invoke Constitutional protections against
self-incrimination or invasion of privacy to prevent prosecutors
from asking specific questions about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky has testified before the grand jury here that she
and Clinton had a sexual affair, according to a lawyer familiar
with her testimony. Clinton denied such an affair in a sworn
deposition during the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   In his only public comments on his prospective testimony,
Clinton said that he would testify ``completely and truthfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that meant that the president would answer every
question put to him, Lockhart said, ``That's what it suggests to
me, yes.'' Asked again if Clinton might duck some questions, he
said, ``The statement I think is pretty straightforward, that he
will testify completely and truthfully.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked specifically if the president would invoke the Fifth
or Fourth Amendments of the Constitution to block questions,
Lockhart referred again to the statement. ``I think that answers
that question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, speaking at the daily press briefing at the White
House, said that he was basing his comments on the president's
remarks, which he made almost two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal strategy is among the best-kept secrets in
Washington, known only to a handful of lawyers. News organizations
and free-lance commentators have compensated for the White House
silence on the details by offering numerous theories about what he
might wind up doing.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement negotiated with the prosecutors, Clinton is
to testify on Monday at the White House. His testimony will be
videotaped and also transmitted live via closed-circuit television
to the grand jurors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
