<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT APPEALS TO KEEP DEPOSITIONS CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Wednesday asked a federal appeals court
to block the public and the news media from witnessing the
depositions of Bill Gates and other company executives.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also began negotiations with lawyers for the
government and the news media to set ground rules for an
unprecedented public questioning of the executives.
</P>
<P>
   The tussle over whether the depositions should be open or closed
_ which began late last week when several news organizations said
they would demand access _ threatens to postpone the start of
Microsoft's anti-trust trial, which had been scheduled to begin
Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been sued by the Department of Justice and the
attorneys general of 20 states and the District of Columbia, all of
whom accuse the company of illegally anti-competitive practices in
violation of the nation's anti-trust laws.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled Tuesday
that a little-known 1913 law allows the public access to
depositions in anti-trust cases. Wednesday, he refused a request by
Microsoft to allow the depositions to proceed in private while his
ruling is appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft suggested to Jackson, and is now suggesting to the
appeals court, that the depositions should be allowed to proceed
behind closed doors, but recorded by a video camera. The company
argues that if it ultimately loses its attempt to block public
access to the depositions, the videotapes could be watched by the
public and news media.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft warned that allowing the public to witness the
depositions will make it difficult to keep the trial on schedule.
The company argued that the depositions, which were supposed to
begin Wednesday with the questioning of Gates, will be delayed by
logistical questions and lengthened by the need to consult with the
judge about excluding the public when trade secrets or other
confidential information are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   A succesful appeal ``may relieve the parties of the onerous
burdens of having to accommodate attendance by members of the press
and general public at the more than 25 remaining depositions in
this case to be held in the next three weeks, and having to resort
constantly to the district court on issues of exclusion when
confidential information is sought by deposition questions _
burdens that are certain to delay the ultimate termination of this
litigation,'' Microsoft argued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Moranville, an associate professor of law at the
University of Washington, said opening the depositions to the
public could dramatically alter the tenor of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of potential for the whole thing being played
to the press, rather than in fact being an information-gathering
process,'' she said. ``What you do in making it public is, you run
the risk of the whole O.J. (Simpson) scene, where there isn't even
a judge to take control. It strikes me as particularly problematic
in a case like this, where everybody and their brother's going to
want to watch Bill get grilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is supposed to respond to Microsoft's
appeal Friday, and Microsoft is entitled to reply to the
government's response on Monday. The appeals court could decide as
soon as Monday whether to let the depositions proceed. In the
meantime, none is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief filed Wednesday, Microsoft said the depositions
should be secret in part because ``it is probable that much of the
information elicited at those depositions will involve the
development and marketing of existing and future software products
_ information that the companies involved regard as extremely
valuable proprietary information.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that at least 16 people have already been deposed in the
case, Microsoft complained that The New York Times Company, ZDTV,
ZDNET and The Seattle Times had waited until just days before the
Gates deposition to seek access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purported `emergency' to which intervenors refer in their
papers is entirely of their own making,'' Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it will argue that the news media and the judge
have misapplied the 1913 law. The company said that the word
``deposition'' had a different meaning when that law was written,
referring to action in a trial-like setting, and not to the
pre-trial discovery that is closed in virtually every type of legal
case.
</P>
<P>
   But the news media, in a brief filed with the district court,
said both ``the unambiguous language of the statute and the
unbroken 85-year history of judicial understanding'' makes it clear
that the public should be allowed into the depositions. The news
media blamed Microsoft for delaying the trial, saying that if the
company simply stopped objecting to opening the depositions, they
could proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft insists that intervenors are entitled to no more
than stale records of the deposition proceedings, to be made
available, if at all, at some uncertain future time,'' the attorney
for the news media argued. ``Each day that the public is denied
access to a judicial proceeding required to be open constitutes a
`separate and cognizable' violation of the First Amendment, and, in
this case, of a federal statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft warned of the delays that could be caused by
opening the depositions to the public, the Justice Department
appeared less concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already had conversations with Microsoft, we've had
conversations with the intervenors, and I think everything's going
to work out smoothly,'' said David Boies, the government's special
trial counsel.
</P>
<P>
   If the depositions are to be public, various ground rules must
be set, including where they will be held, how many people will be
allowed to attend, and what types of technological devices, such as
laptop computers, will be allowed in the room. Recording devices,
such as television cameras and tape recorders, are expected to be
barred as they are in federal courtrooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
