A1035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS13-COX     08-12 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida doctor, non-profit group to offer free drug testing kits
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Parents who want to be sure their
children aren't using illegal drugs could swing by the Sheriff's
Office and pick up a free home drug-testing kit, if a local
doctor's anti-drug crusade succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Douglas R. Smith, an emergency medicine physician at Good
Samaritan Medical Center, is the chairman of Drug Free America, a
Delray Beach, Fla.-based nonprofit group that hopes to put 10,000
testing kits in Palm Beach County law enforcement offices this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent will not pay one single penny,'' Smith promised
Wednesday. ``Not for the kit, the postage or the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The kits, which test a urine sample for marijuana, cocaine,
amphetamines, opium and heroin, will include a list of warning
signs and local counseling resources, along with a plastic cup and
bottle for mailing the sample to a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   After three days, parents would call a toll-free number for the
results, with a physician available to discuss and interpret a
positive result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants one can take one,'' said Smith. ``We don't
take names, addresses or phone numbers. We don't want to know who
you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug Free America _ not to be confused with the Partnership For
A Drug Free America _ has enlisted an impressive roster to support
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of State Alexander Haig is listed as an adviser
on the group's letterhead but could not be reached for confirmation
Wednesday. U.S. Rep. Mark Foley (R-Lake Worth), and Palm Beach
County State Attorney Barry Krischer have lent their names to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very supportive,'' said Foley. ``Sometimes if a child
knows they're going to be tested, they're less likely to engage in
illegal use of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Circuit Judge Walter Colbath, Jr., asked that his name
be removed after learning Wednesday that he was listed as an
advisory board member. Judicial ethics forbid him from lending his
name to any effort that raises money, Colbath said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Bob Neumann has agreed to let his office serve as a
distribution point, said Dawn Guzzetta, his public and governmental
affairs adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really want to make clear that we are not promoting
this,'' Guzzetta said. ``We didn't raise money for it, we're just a
clearinghouse if parents decide they want to use one.''
</P>
<P>
   Each kit will cost Drug Free America about $30, including the
testing charge by SmithKline Laboratories, Smith said. He has
raised about $190,000 of the $300,000 needed to put together 10,000
kits.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 38 and the father of two children, 7 and 12, will begin
testing his older boy next year, he said. But not all teenagers
think he has a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right unless you give your parents a reason,'' said
Tonia Lewis, 17, a junior in high school, when told of the test.
``It's a violation of your space, your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Howard Simon, executive director of the American
Civil Liberties Union of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have a right to test their children for drugs,'' Simon
said, noting that the ACLU is dedicated to monitoring government
instrusion into private lives, not the relationship between parent
and child. ``If you're 15 and your father says you can't read
Penthouse, that doesn't mean your First Amendment rights have been
abridged.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
Post staff writer Mary Warejcka contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
