<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Division Series tickets to go on sale
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Braves announced tickets for the Division Series
will go on public sale Monday (Aug. 17) and Turner Field and via
various TickerMaster outlets. There will be no limit to the size of
ticket orders for the Division Series, though the majority of seats
available are reserved seating in the upper reaches of the park _
Upper level, Upper Pavilion and Skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for the Division Series remains the same as last year _
$30 for Dugout level, $25 for Field level, $20 for Terrace level,
$15 for Field Pavilion and Terrace Pavilion and $10 for others.
These sales are for first-round games only. Dates for NLCS and
World Series sales will be announced at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves win the NL East, they will have home-field
advantage. The Division Series will start either Sept. 29 or 30
and, in a scheduling change, the club with the home field advantage
will host Games 1, 2 and, if necessary, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Orders through TicketMaster may be made via its Charge-By-Phone
service, at various TicketMaster outlets and through TicketMaster
Online. Phone orders may be made at 404-249-6400 or outside the
metro area at 800-326-4000. TicketMaster Online can be accessed at
www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Seats purchased at the Turner Field ticket office may only be
paid for with cash, cashiers check or money order. No checks or
credit cards will be honored.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker rockin'
</P>
<P>
   However the Braves bullpen shapes up for the postseason, rookie
John Rocker thinks he has earned his spot in it. And if he
continues to work like he did Tuesday night, he is right.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think as well as I've pitched since I've been up (May 5), I
think I'll probably be on the postseason roster, unless something
drastic happens in the next three weeks,'' He said. ''I think I've
pitched well enough for long enough that I've earned that''
</P>
<P>
   The staff's lone left-handed reliever for nearly seven weeks,
Rocker suddenly finds himself surrounded by two others, with the
call-ups of Norm Charlton and Adam Butler. Though the Braves
habitually reduced their pitching staff by one to 10 men for the
postseason, manager Bobby Cox would like nothing better than having
two lefties in his bullpen for October.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rocker's penchant for walks (he has yielded 18 in 24-1/3
innings), he has allowed only 16 hits and a .186 average with 27
strikeouts. And he was outstanding working the eighth inning
Tuesday night, striking out Tony Gwynn swinging and then buckling
Ken Caminiti on a check-swing strikeout. Rocker's fastball was
consistently timed in the mid 90s, topping out at 98 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''I changed my strategy back to how I was throwing a couple
weeks ago _ challenging with my fastball then using my slider when
I got ahead,'' he said. ''I think what got me away from that were
those two innings in Cincinnati (July 29), where I think I threw
like one slider the whole time. I started to rely on (the fastball)
too much because I was striking out a lot of guys with it. But the
slider felt good last night. You get ahead in the count and then
out pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Father knows best
</P>
<P>
   Hunter Wendelstedt, the first-year umpire who ejected both John
Smoltz and Bobby Cox in a wild altercation in Cincinnati two weeks
ago, was behind the plate Wednesday, working in the same crew with
his father Harry, the league's senior umpire. League president Len
Coleman had given special approval for the father and son to work
one stretch this season. Hunter was filling in with Ed Montague's
crew when his incident with the Braves occured.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Smoltz or Cox have received notification from the league
about any fine or suspension. Making contact with an umpire is an
automatic suspension and that the matter has gone so long without
league action is leading the Braves to believe the incident is
being dismissed. Wendelstedt ejected Smoltz after turning into him
and stepping on Smoltz's foot and then ejected Cox for putting his
hand on his chest when trying to separate the two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
