<HEADLINE>
THQ DROPS PLAN TO ISSUE NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Citing unfavorable market conditions, video-game
maker THQ Inc. said that it has withdrawn plans for a $60 million
private placement to fund expansion.
</P>
<P>
   THQ, based in Calabasas, Calif., had announced late in July that
it planned to issue the subordinated notes that could be converted
to stock after seven years. The notes would have financed the
purchase of new game titles, expansion of foreign distribution and
possible investments in other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement Wednesday sent THQ shares down as investors
possibly feared a dilution of their stock. Between July 27, when
the announcement was made, and Tuesday, the company's share price
fell from $31 to $26.875.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gysi, THQ's chief financial officer, said recent drops in
the stock market would have made it difficult to place the $60
million in notes. ``In a declining market, it's a challenge to do
new issues,'' Gysi said. ``When stocks are dropping, most fund
managers, who would be buying the notes, are more worried about
surviving than taking on anything new.''
</P>
<P>
   Gysi also acknowledged that the effect the announced placement
had on THQ's price helped scuttle the plan for now.
</P>
<P>
   Investors greeted Wednesday's news enthusiastically, sending THQ
shares up $2.875 to close at $29.75. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
