<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-FANS-700&AMP;     08-12 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-FANS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME OUT TO .... BATTING PRACTICE!  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Ryan Ahlemeyer begged his father, Lon, to leave
early for the 20-minute drive to Busch Stadium on Tuesday, early
enough to be one of the first fans into the park when the gates
opened at 5:10 p.m., to scamper to the outfield seats in Section
385 and to get in position to catch a batting practice homer from
Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Ahlemeyer, 42, a self-employed electronics technician,
rescheduled some job appointments, hopped into his gold Saturn and
drove Ryan, 13, from Cahokia, Ill., to the stadium by 4 p.m. to
wait in line. The father later sat in the steamy stands as his son
stood as rigid as a Marine behind the yellow neon sign that says
Big Mac Land in the upper terrace deck high above the left-field
fence. It would take about a 440-foot homer to reach Ryan's small,
tan glove perched over the front-row railing, a prodigious blast
even for McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan was eerily confident, and so was his father. ``He said
he was going to do it, so I believed him,'' Lon Ahlemeyer said of
his son. ``It's kind of amazing, but I thought he'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people like the Ahlemeyers packed the entrances to
the stadium four hours before the first pitch, some like Ryan who
wanted to catch a ball and many others who simply wanted to watch
McGwire practice swinging a bat in his quest to break Roger Maris'
37-year-old record of 61 homers in a season. There were fathers and
sons and mothers and daughters. It was as easy to find a 5-year-old
with a Cardinals cap as it was to find a 55-year-old with a paunch
and a Cardinals T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, a team with a losing record, are nevertheless on
a pace to set a team attendance record with 3.1 million fans. The
enthusiasm that permeates Busch during batting practice, which is
generally regarded as a mundane warm-up in other stadiums, is the
clearest indication of just how eager fans are to feel close to the
summer's memorable home run race, with McGwire, at 47 entering
Wednesday night's game, leading the Cubs' Sammy Sosa, who has 46.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure I got here and got a chance to get
something from his season,'' said Chad Mulligan, who cruised
through St. Louis on vacation from his home in Pocahontas, Ark.
``He's obviously going to break it. Even if we don't get a ball, we
can say we were here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jane Mehlelman sounded a similar note. ``I haven't seen
this before and it's wonderful,'' she said. ``I've always enjoyed
coming to the games because I'm a big Cardinals fan. Now this makes
it even more exciting. You feel like you're part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Moranville, a former resident of St. Louis who now lives in
Memphis, returned home to see McGwire and felt as if he had been
placed inside a time capsule and was 10 years old again.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, McGwire has brought back a lot of interest in
baseball,'' he said. ``I was a fan of the Cardinals with Stan
Musial and Red Schoendienst. Back then, baseball was everything to
kids. Now, I don't think it's everything. McGwire is bringing that
back. Kids need heroes. He's a hero.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ryan Ahlemeyer, skinny with choppy brown hair, a hesitant smile
and high hopes, was evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come every night to watch him if my parents would let
me,'' Ahlemeyer said. ``This is so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When the park officially opened, the tranquil sounds of batting
practice in an empty stadium were replaced by the rowdy sounds of
fans rushing to get in position to snare a souvenir blast from
McGwire. They burst up the runways in anticipation. There was a
family of five with the father giving instructions for catching the
elusive ball, teen-agers who used hand and eye signals to station
themselves and husbands and wives who separated by 150 feet to
maximize their chance for a ball.
</P>
<P>
   They had gloves, cameras, binoculars and camcorders. Mostly,
they had gloves, causing one stadium employee to lament: ``It used
to be I could get all the balls I wanted if I came down here for a
few minutes. Now, everyone's here.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a calm in the seats as the crowd swelled. Jeff Marsh
wanted his 13-year-old son, Patrick, to feel the type of
exhilaration he did when he once caught a foul ball off a Nolan
Ryan fastball. Chad and Kevin Mulligan, whose combined weight is
about 450 pounds, sat in the front row of one section and spread
out in five seats to store their belongings. Sure. They were boxing
out other fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something gets close to us, my brother's big enough to get
it,'' said Chad, who pointed to his brother, a huge man with logs
for arms.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire took practice swings beside the cage, the fans
cheered as if he had smoked a double. It was time. Ryan peeked down
over the railing and saw so many fans standing below him. Should he
be in the loge section?
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire routinely bunted the first batting practice pitch,
the fans groaned. When he grounded the ball to shortstop and fouled
another off, they moaned some more. But on the fourth toss, McGwire
satisfied the fans in 282 by stroking a ball at them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fletcher saw it all the way. He was sweating through a
purple shirt as the ball flew toward him. Fletcher reached up with
both hands and tried to catch the ball barehanded. It sounded like
a firecracker when it popped off his left hand and bounced softly
into another fan's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost it in the sun,'' a pained Fletcher said. ``If I had a
glove, I would have caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fletcher Jr., a concerned 13-year-old, was still asking
about the apple-red mark on his father's hand when another ball
rocketed toward them. Five pairs of hands lunged for it, and the
fan whose glove reached the farthest was Tim Blan, who seconds
earlier had switched spots from the walkway in front of the section
to the sixth row. He shouted, ``Yeah,'' and closed his eyes after
the grab, but calmed down for the post-catch interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure luck,'' Blan said. ``Any of these guys could have
caught it. I was just telling myself not to drop it. I'm glad I had
the glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after McGwire completed his first practice session with a
homer to center, Ryan did not lose hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he'll hit one up here,'' Ryan told his father. ``He
always does.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire did not go deep on his first three tries in the second
round. But then he lined a bullet into a section in left center,
almost the same spot where he drilled one later Tuesday night off
the Mets' Bobby Jones for his 47th homer.
</P>
<P>
   On the next swing, McGwire's 12th of batting practice, he
unloaded on a fastball and Ryan's brown eyes bulged because the
ball was hurtling toward him. Would the ball be high enough? Would
it make it to the terrace level? Ryan was standing behind a
three-foot railing, which led to a 50-foot drop, so he could not
lean over too far. He waited.
</P>
<P>
   The ball continued soaring. Ryan was standing over the ``d'' in
``Big Mac Land,'' and he squeezed his glove between two railings
awkwardly, yet adeptly. Miraculously, the ball hit the webbing of
Ryan's glove like a cannon ball and popped out like a snow cone
before he coolly gathered it in with his right hand, his arms
wrapped around the railing. Fans did double-takes after the
outstanding grab and then gave Ryan a McGwire-like ovation. The
teen-ager had been right all along. A ball from McGwire's special
and possibly historic season was his.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hit very hard and I didn't know if I was going to catch
it,'' Ryan said. ``I just tried to put my body in front of it. When
I saw it in my glove, it felt like Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
