<HEADLINE>
TOWN THAT DISNEY BUILT IS HIT BY FIRST VIOLENT CRIME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CELEBRATION, Fla. _ This widely publicized planned community
developed by Walt Disney Co. a few miles from Disney World was
abuzz Wednesday with news of the town's first reported violent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   A robber who said he had a gun threatened a family before taking
an undisclosed amount of cash and two credit cards from their home
in Celebration about 6 p.m. on Monday, said a spokeswoman for the
Osceola County Sheriff's office, which provides police protection
for the unincorporated town of about 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The robber approached Terrence Turner in the garage of his home
while Turner's wife, Stephanie, and two small children stood nearby
in the yard. He then threatened to shoot the Turners unless he was
given money, said the spokeswoman, Carole Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept his hand in his pocket,'' Ms. Garcia said. ``The
victim never did see a gun. He was polite and apologetic and he
drove off in a blue Honda after being given the money and credit
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebration is Disney's effort to generate small-town values in
a carefully designed small-town atmosphere. It has attracted
attention as a potential antidote to urban crime and the sprawl and
isolation of traditional suburbs since the first residents moved in
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The houses, which start at $160,000 and go as high as $1
million, are close together. The architecture of the homes is
old-fashioned and many have porches to promote social interaction.
The streets are narrow, tree lined and quiet. Residents often leave
doors unlocked and children rarely use locks on their bicycles at
school or downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the town is expected to have 20,000 residents on
4,900 acres southwest of Orlando, and it has been the
fastest-selling development in Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other planned communities, Celebration is not gated,
and its downtown is a magnet for tourists and other visitors. It is
just off heavily traveled Route 192.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garcia said there had been no previous reports of violent
crime in the town and only a handful of reported thefts of bicycles
or tools and material from construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Conneely, who moved here nearly two years ago from
Connecticut, heard about the robbery over coffee downtown Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was shock and surprise,'' Ms. Conneely said.
``Then I thought that it proves this sort of thing can happen
anywhere. We shouldn't be naive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carl Perkins, who lives near the Turners and moved here with his
wife from a Chicago suburb, did not seem particularly alarmed by
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the feeling that a lot of people moved here looking for
small-town America,'' he said. ``Everyone is looking for that old
sense of community and the security that goes with it. But you're
kidding yourself if you think that this couldn't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Herrington, the community services manager for the
Celebration Co., the Disney subsidiary developing the town, said
residents were not as much concerned Wednesday about security as
about the well-being of the Turners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tight-knit community, and you are going to have
a high level of concern when something like this happens,''
Herrington said. ``We have all the same issues that every other
community in America has, but we feel this is a very safe place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2145EDT &QL; 
