<P>
   EDITORS: Following is a list of stories related to the terrorist
attacks on the U.S. embassies in Africa that moved tonight in the
New York Times News Service report. All stories have moved in the
``i'' category. For more information, call: (888) 346-9867. The
N.Y. Times News Service Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-RDP (Washington) _ The U.S. ambassador to Kenya and the
Defense Department were so alarmed about threats to the embassy in
Kenya that they requested a safer building but were rejected for
budgetary reasons, the State Department said Wednesday night. In
Nairobi, the Kenyan government said it has detained several
suspects in last week's bombing of the embassy. Federal law
enforcement officials said that FBI agents in Nairobi would
question the suspects. By Philip Shenon. 1,000 words. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya _ The American ambassador to
Kenya went on television Wednesday night to address charges that
Americans were more concerned about protecting their own people and
guarding their embassy than helping Kenyans killed or hurt in an
attack presumably aimed at the United States. By Raymond Bonner.
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-INQUIRY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ In the war between the United
States and terrorists since the 1983 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in
Beirut, Lebanon, the score is grim. Today it stands: Americans
killed in bombings and hijackings in the Middle East and Africa _
307. Terrorists convicted for those crimes by American courts, a
bare handful. By Tim Weiner. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ENVOY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ This has been an agonizing time
for the U.S. ambassador to Kenya, Prudence Bushnell. Her embassy
was destroyed in a terrorist bombing on Friday that injured her and
took the lives of three dozen American and Kenyan colleagues. She
has had to re-establish her mission while overseeing a chaotic
rescue operation. To make matters harder, she has also become the
focus of anger among many Kenyans. BY James C. McKinley Jr. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DEAD (Landshut, Germany) _ ``I am bringing home 10 very
brave Americans,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said here
Wednesday night as she prepared to fly home with the bodies of 10
of the 12 Americans killed in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in
Nairobi. By Craig R. WHitney. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
