<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/12/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- AFRICA-RDP, 8-12 --
Unidentified U.S. Embassy employees who were injured in the bombing
in Nairobi last week arriving at Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington on Wednesday. They were on their way to American
hospitals. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) TUSCANY, Italy -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- EUROPE-AGRITOURISM-2,
8-12 -- A room in Umberto Lenzi's Tuscan farm-cum-inn, the Fattoria
San Donato. As prices for farm products dwindle, and with them
rural incomes, European farmers are redesigning their farms to take
in tourists, a practice known as agritourism, and governments are
helping them do so. By rough estimate, the 15 European Union
countries have spent $2 billion since 1991 to subsidize such
programs. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) TUSCANY, Italy -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- EUROPE-AGRITOURISM-1,
8-12 -- Umberto Lenzi uses the World Wide Web to lure vacationers
to the 600-acre Tuscan farm his grandfather bought in 1939.
Europeans, drawn by modest room rates and seeking refuge from noisy
cities, are arriving in droves. ``We just felt a need to get away
from the noise of the television set,'' says Nicola Decaro, 40, a
city employee from Apulia, Italy, who spent a week recently with
his wife and two daughters at the farm. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- GAYS-CHRISTIANS-ADS, 8-12
-- Janet Folger is the national director of the Center for
Reclaiming America and the leader of a controversial new anti-gay
advertising campaign marketing sexual ``conversion.'' Ms. Folger
directed the placement of full-page newspaper advertisements
showing ``former homosexuals'' who ``overcame'' their sexual
orientation through prayer. Gay rights advocates were infuriated.
(Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SAN JUAN BAUTISTA, Calif. -- Aug. 12, 1998 --
CALIF-QUAKE, 8-12 -- The Rev. Edward Fitz-Henry, left, and an
archaeologist, Ruben Mendoza, inspect the Mission San Juan Bautista
after an earthquake, which struck Wednesday. Centered about 85
miles southeast of San Francisco, the quake began at 7:10 a.m. PT
and registered 5.4 on the Richter scale of ground motion, according
to the U.S. Geological Survey office in Menlo Park, Calif. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- LONGTIME-SOAPSTAR, 8-12 --
Helen Wagner has played Nancy Hughes in the soap opera ``As the
World Turns'' for more than 42 years. ``I outlasted Cronkite, I
outlasted the one who wrote those wonderful travel programs - what
was his name? Charles Kuralt,'' Miss Wagner says off camera. She
has also outlived two on-camera husbands and has become, in her
words, ``the longest continually running item on TV.'' (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FISH CREEK, Wis. -- Aug. 12, 1998 --
WIS-STRAW-HAT-THEATER-2, 8-12 -- At the Peninsula Players in Fish
Creek, everyone must fit in and all the members eat three meals a
day together. ``You can be brilliant, but if you don't know how to
interact with people, then this isn't the place for you,'' says Amy
McKenzie, an actress and director who grew up with the troupe as
the daughter of one of its star actresses and the man who has been
its executive producer for nearly 30 years, James McKenzie.
(Jeffrey Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) FISH CREEK, Wis. -- Aug. 12, 1998 --
WIS-STRAW-HAT-THEATER-1, 8-12 -- Members of the Peninsula Players
performing in ``Spider's Web.'' The troupe is a thriving stalwart
in a genre that is fading from the American landscape: the summer
theater as part commune, part camp, where the cast and crew spend
every moment living, eating, working together. (Jeffrey Davis/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NYACK, N.Y. -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- ALDRICH-NUDE, 8-12 --
Karen Finley, whose work will be shown at the Aldrich Museum as
part of a variation on an exhibition of the nude in 20th-century
art that was canceled last month by the Whitney Museum of American
Art. In canceling the exhibition, the Whitney said it was trying to
cut costs so it could devote more resources to its forthcoming
Project of America, a series of shows about the history of American
art in the 20th century. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LENOX, Mass. -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL,
8-12 -- Seiji Ozawa conducting the student orchestra in Takemitsu's
``November Steps'' during the Festival of Contemporary Music at
Tanglewood. His conducting the orchestra was regarded as emblematic
of the Boston Symphony Orchestra's assertion of dominion over its
summer music school, and the consensus here is that this is a
change for the better. (Alan E. Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PHOENIX -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- LAWDOG-AZR, 8-12 --
Stephanie Nichols-Young, an animal rights lawyer, with K.T., a
loving greyhound, saved by Ms. Nichols-Young when she sued on
behalf of greyhound breeders who did not know that their dogs were
being sold to research labs. ``They can't speak out for themselves,
so we have to,'' says Ms. Nichols-Young, 41, who does much of her
non-human legal practice for free. (Suzanne Starr/Arizona Republic
Photo
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- BACKYARD-BARBECUE, 8-12 --
Frank McClelland works up a blaze outside Boston. After two decades
of growth, the U.S. economy has brought a return to the backyard
barbecue. Fire-hungry homeowners who want to keep up with the Dow
Joneses are moving beyond rusty iron grills to a new generation of
built-ins. They want fish baskets, wood-fired pizza and bread
ovens, smokers and rotisseries. They may even want a designer fire
pit. (Donna Paul/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MALIBU, Calif. -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CLINTON-LIBRARY, 8-12
-- The Charles Gwathmey house for Jeffrey Katzenberg, the
Dreamworks movie mogul. White House aides say the president was
captivated by the home when he stayed there last fall; Gwathmey is
a leading contender to win Clinton's commission to design the
William J. Clinton Presidential Library. (Bart Bartholomew/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- BED-DESIGN, 8-12 -- ``It
always seems in a relationship that one does the talking and the
other one does the thinking,'' says Stephen Whisler, a New York
sculptor. Ready to seize the moment, he has designed the ``Thought
and Speech'' maple headboard. It is made of maple plywood panels
with cartoon cut-outs of a thought bubble and a speech bubble, each
above its respective side of a bed. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- ELVIS-SHRINE-B&AMP;W,
8-12 -- The original Graceland in Memphis. ``I guess I know more
about Elvis than Elvis knew about himself,'' says Paul MacLeod, who
over the last few years has turned the antebellum house he
inherited in Holly Springs, Miss., into Graceland Too, a shrine run
by the self-described ``universe's, the galaxy's, the planet's, the
world's No. 1 Elvis fan.'' (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HOUSTON -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CREATINE-ATHLETES-HNS, 8-12
-- Bottles of creatine monohydrate on the shelves of Vitamin Smart.
This is just one of many stores, gyms, mail-order and Internet
services that carry the controversial compound. Though not an
anabolic steroid, its safety is a matter of ongoing debate among
sports medicine doctors. (Smiley N. Pool/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-CLOTHES-ONLINE-2, 8-12 --
Kathryn Chase, at left with her daughter Molly, wants to open a
commercial scanning center in Atlanta. Describing her test of a
body scanner Ms. Chase says, ``It's almost like a carnival ride.
You go in, get down to your underwear, put your feet on the white
marks and press the button. Lights flash, music plays - it only
takes a few seconds - and you have all the data the pattern-making
software needs for a custom fit.'' (Chuck Rogers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) AMES, Iowa -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-CLOTHES-ONLINE-1, 8-12
-- Tracey Nutt being scanned recently at the University of Iowa in
Ames. The process is part of a program called Caesar, for Civilian
American and European Surface Anthropometry Resource - the first
large-scale whole-body three-dimensional scanning project ever
done, measuring a total of 10,800 men and women with a range of
ages and weights. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-TRADING-CARDS, 8-12 --
Power Deck sports cards, manufactured by the sports memorabilia
company Upper Deck, are believed to be the only audio trading cards
on the market that approximate the size and look of traditional
sports cards. In addition to images of professional athletes, the
cards include recorded interviews, trivia questions, commentary and
live-action sound from athletic competitions. (Upper Deck Trading
Cards/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-WEB-WEATHER-2, 8-12 --
Weather.com keeps a close eye on breaking weather news worldwide,
left; Accuweather lets you tailor its services to your needs. Most
weather pages offer a national overview of weather, articles on
places where weather is making news, local forecasts and more
detailed information for those who need it. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-WEB-WEATHER-1, 8-12 --
The round-the-clock availability of information on the Internet has
spurred the success of Web sites that offer books, music, news and
the like. And it's also creating a demand for weather information
without the polish and marketing of weather forecasters goofing off
on local news shows. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WESTLAKE, Ohio -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-WEB-CENSORSHIP,
8-12 -- Sean O'Brien won a dispute with Westlake High School over
his Web page. While the United States Supreme Court issued a
decision in 1988 on the censorship of student newspapers, it has
yet to deal with a case involving school censorship of a Web site
set up by a student outside school. (Roger Mastroianni/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SEATTLE -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- CIR-MICROSPEAK, 8-12 -- Ken
Barnes, compiler of a lexicon of slang that Microsoft built, at
home in Seattle. More than a dozen current and former Microsoft
blue badges (permanent Microsoft employees) and orange badges
(temporary workers and independent contractors) are among the
contributors to the lexicon of Microspeak, which can be seen on the
Web at cinepad.com/mslex.htm. (Robert Sorbo/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Aug. 12, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 8-12 --
Even though a house looks elegant, it may not fit your needs. There
are five basic styles of house. Clockwise from top left, bi-level,
Victorian, Cape-cod, Tudor and two-story, center. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
