<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-NYT &LR;      08-12 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATH TO VICTORY IN A MAJOR MEANDERS THROUGH TALL TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ With 100-foot tall trees and perfectly
manicured grass, Sahalee Country Club hardly resembles midtown
Manhattan. Lee Janzen sees similarities, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best way to prepare for this course would have
been to go to a big city, like New York, and maybe play down Fifth
Avenue,'' said Janzen, the two-time U.S. Open champion. ``With the
trees being so large, and so close to the fairway, you immediately
see the only shot you can possibly hit. And that's straight down
the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   With that game plan in mind, the world's greatest golfers have
prepared to tee off Thursday for the 80th PGA Championship, the
final major championship of the year. Sahalee, which is playing
host to its first major, is a unique course that will test
precision and patience. Those who stay on the fairway consistently
will have a chance to win. Those who venture into the trees may
wish they had a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody heard there were a lot of trees,'' said Justin
Leonard, last year's British Open champion. ``I don't think anybody
imagined this many.''
</P>
<P>
   But through those trees leads the path to a major. And for Mark
O'Meara, it could be a path that leads to history. Having already
won the Masters and the British Open, O'Meara will try to become
the first man since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three majors in the
same year. If O'Meara is in contention this weekend, the tournament
is certain to be memorable. And if O'Meara can reach the back nine
Sunday with a chance to win, he likes his chances as well as
anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have a chance Sunday, I'm going to go for it,'' O'Meara
said. ``There's no reason not to. People remember the people who
win. You don't remember sometimes who finishes second, third,
fourth, or fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has deep respect for Hogan, one of the game's greats,
who died last year. In 1980, after winning the 1979 United States
Amateur Championship, O'Meara actually turned professional in
Hogan's office, signing with the Hogan company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got to know him as well as most other players of our
era, and it was a lot of fun,'' O'Meara said. ``We had a lot of
neat times together. Just to be tossed around in the same light as
a Hogan is a tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   But while O'Meara has already had a memorable season, this
tournament will be the last chance for others to win a major this
year. Those who have never won a major, such as Colin Montgomerie
and Phil Mickelson, would love to silence their critics. And Tiger
Woods, who has only one victory on the PGA Tour this year, but nine
top-10 finishes, could put an entirely different slant on his year
by winning a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is my last chance at a major this year, but I'm
not going to put any more pressure than I normally do,'' said
Woods, the 1997 Masters champion. ``Last year, I was guilty of
being too rambunctious, and not really being as patient as I need
to be. I need to give myself a chance and not shoot myself in the
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to hurt yourself at Sahalee is to toy with the
trees. The 11th hole is certain to be the most controversial of the
tournament, a 546-yard par 5 that features two trees in front of
the green that frame the pin like goal posts. Players who try to
reach the green in two shots will have to work the ball between the
trees like a place-kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be plenty challenging,'' Janzen said. ``You'll
see some eagles, plenty of birdies, and you'll see some shots hit
the trees and end up in not so good spots. If you could be a fly on
the golf bag, you might hear some words you've never heard.''
</P>
<P>
   All the talk about O'Meara's quest has overshadowed Davis Love
III, the defending champion, who won his first major in emotional
fashion last year at Winged Foot Golf Club in Mamaroneck, N.Y. Many
will never forget the scene when Love approached the final green
there and a rainbow appeared in the sky, reminding him of his
father, Davis Love Jr., the renowned golf teacher who died in a
1988 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Love was excited about his chances to repeat, but nobody has won
back-to-back PGA Championships since Denny Shute in 1936 and 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the players here, Love will rarely use his driver,
and instead hit woods and irons off the tee to keep the ball
positioned in the tight fairways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hit two very good iron shots in a row to get on
the green,'' Love said. ``For me, it's probably one or two drivers
the whole golf course. You don't ever really get to a hole where
you can just bomb a driver down there and have an easy shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning a major is not supposed to be easy, however, and Sahalee
should present an interesting test. Nine of the last 10 PGA
champions were first-time major winners, so historically, it has
been a hard tournament to predict. But for the winner, dealing with
the trees, the 4-inch rough and the pressure will be well worth the
reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where we play this, or what you think of the course,
they're going to give that Wanamaker Trophy to somebody on
Sunday,'' David Duval said. ``And that's what we all want.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The weather is expected to be excellent throughout the
tournament, with afternoon temperatures in the 70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE JONES, the 1996 U.S. Open champion, withdrew Wednesday
because of the death of his close friend, Gus Lebsock, a part-owner
of the Phoenix Suns who died Tuesday from a heart attack. Lebsock,
67, had been fishing with Jones in Montana last weekend. Jones was
replaced by BILLY ANDRADE.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN DALY, the tour's leader in driving distance, practiced
Tuesday with a new Callaway Big Bertha Steelhead driver, and he
will use this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
