<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PACIFICCLASSIC-LA     08-12 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PACIFICCLASSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELLA DUO FAVORED IN CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR _ One horse hasn't run his best in precisely a year. The
other hasn't won a stakes in this country, let alone a race of this
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, Gentlemen and Puerto Madero are shaky propositions
in the $1 million Pacific Classic on Saturday. But together,
coupled in the wagering because of common ownership, they are 6-5
favorites for the 1\-mile race, the highlight of the Del Mar
season.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold is so close, at 8-5 all by himself, that the
Kentucky-based 4-year-old really should be considered the favorite.
Free House is 3-1 on the morning line set after post positions were
determined Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as tough as it gets. You have three, maybe four top
horses,'' said Richard Mandella, trainer of Gentlemen and Puerto
Madero, apparently counting the latter as the ``maybe.'' ``Touch
Gold is world-class. Free House is world-class.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen won the Pacific Classic in 1997, when he was the best
older horse on the West Coast. Free House won the '97 Santa Anita
Derby and ran second or third in all of the Triple Crown races.
Touch Gold won the '97 Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Free House's and Touch Gold's rival, the popular Silver Charm,
will miss the Pacific Classic after a last-place finish in the San
Diego Handicap. The handlers of top-ranked Skip Away decided to
keep him in the East. But even without them, this is one of the
strongest runnings of the Pacific Classic, and its nine-horse field
equals the 1994 race won by come-from-behind 7-1 shot Tinner's Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get three horses like this,'' Mandella said, ``people don't
appreciate it (enough). It doesn't happen that often these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Gentlemen has lost back-to-back races for the first
time in a 20-race career. He bled and finished last at 1-20 odds in
the Santa Anita Handicap. He came back 3{ months later to run third
to Skip Away and Puerto Madero in the Hollywood Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile workout in :46 3/5, the fastest Tuesday morning at
Del Mar, raised Mandella's confidence in Gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a sterling year,'' Mandella said. ``We're still
looking to get to the maximum point.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilean-bred 4-year-old Puerto Madero is the equal of Gentlemen
off their recent form. This will be his fourth U.S. race.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero could be one of the early trailers, hoping his
stablemate and Free House kill each other off.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero will be ridden as usual by Kent Desormeaux.
Gentlemen switches to Corey Nakatani, who rode him to two victories
in 1996. Gary Stevens had been riding Gentlemen but committed to
Silver Charm in the spring, and Mandella didn't want to be Stevens'
second choice.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens will be on Lazy Load in the Pacific Classic, taking over
from Desormeaux. Eddie Delahoussaye has Pacificbounty, replacing
injured Laffit Pincay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
