<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONG-DISTANCE-DEGREE-     08-12 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE-DEGREE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SWT to offer online master's degree
 &HT;    By Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Very soon, geography students from Lubbock to
Laredo and beyond will be able to turn on a computer, pop in aCD
and begin working toward a master's degree in applied geography
from Southwest Texas State University in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   SWT, with help from a U.S. Department of Education grant, is now
offering the only online master's degree in applied geography in
the world. For students who normally would not be able to attend
SWT because of, well geography, such as high school teachers in the
Rio Grande Valley, the program offers an alternative way to receive
a degree without having to spend several semesters on campus. With
the program, the university is helping to foster a trend among
colleges and universities of widening their reach through distance
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very innovative way to look at geography,'' said
Lawrence Estaville, chair of the Geography and Planning Department
at SWT. ``This is not a new academic program, but it is a new way
of delivering the current academic program, and we are the very
first ones to have brought it online.''
</P>
<P>
   The university has offered a traditional applied geography
degree since 1983, and was the first institution in the nation to
do so. Since then, the department has grown to become the nation's
largest, with 28 professors, 575 undergraduates, 165 master's
students and about 19 doctoral students. The geography department
also offers the only doctoral program at SWT.
</P>
<P>
   The federal grant _ $208,000 spread over three years _ will help
get the online program started by Jan. 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where student populations are constantly evolving,
distance learning is more than a luxury, it is a necessity, said
state Rep. Ted Kamel, R-Tyler. ``The average student age is going
to continue to grow as people return to school to re-learn things,
for continuing education, to finish degrees or start new ones,''
Kamel said.
</P>
<P>
   This new layer of students often cannot afford to attend a
course that meets three times a week from 3 to 5 p.m., he said.
``The deal with distance learning on the Internet is, you can plug
in your laptop at the airport or wherever you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Kamel sponsored a bill that allows Texas colleges to
offer online courses without having to get state approval, provided
those courses are already being offered traditionally.
</P>
<P>
   For those skeptical about distance learning, Kamel said the
trend will augment but not replace traditional universities and
face-to-face interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it means is that we will have a better-trained work force.
Hopefully, it puts Texas on the same cutting edge of technology and
education that other states are,'' Kamel said. Going electronic
also means spreading the gospel on geography, SWT officials said.
The more people who have access to geography the better, Estaville
said, because contrary to what many think, geography is much more
than looking at maps and memorizing the location of foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In applied geography, we try to give students experience with
real-world problems, like the siting of landfills, modeling the
movement of surface and subsurface water, NAFTA transportation,
air-quality degradation, developing tourism,'' he said. ``All of
these are major issues for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   So is teaching geography, said Brock Brown, an SWT geography
professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geography is now pretty much mandated in the high school
curriculum, but it's a double-edged sword,'' Brown said. ``We've
got geography out there, but we don't have a lot of teachers who
can effectively teach it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Rio Grande Valley, which already suffers from a chronic
shortage of teachers, there are few master's degree programs, and
anyone wanting additional education in geography usually has to
travel to SWT for classes.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an online degree is enticing to Daniel Furmaga,
a geography teacher at Edinburg High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very attractive degree, especially now that people are
recognizing the importance of geography,'' Furmaga said. ``I would
be able to access resources and instruction that, for the most
part, have been out of my reach,'' he said. ``Southwest Texas is
THE geography school. Their geographers are full-blooded. They eat,
drink and sleep geography.''
</P>
<P>
   Furmaga said a master's in geography would help him be a better
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many kids ask 'Why do we need to know this?' `` Furmaga
said. ``What we are trying to show is that in life, you are going
to use this, whether it's math or geography.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that emphasis on using geography in daily life that will
eventually create a cadre of global citizens, one expert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing facts and where things are no more makes you a
geographer than memorizing multiplication tables makes you a
mathematician or knowing how to spell makes you a great writer,''
said Ronald Abler, executive director of the Association of
American Geographers in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the connectedness of places and events in the world that
is the core of geography,'' he said. ``It is hearing of some event
in one particular place and immediately thinking how it is affected
by and, in turn, affects distant places.''
</P>
<P>
   Abler said enrollment in geography programs at all levels _ from
undergraduate through doctorate _ has been increasing a steady 3
percent each year, and there are about 20,000 geography students
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   That means more teachers are being trained to present good
quality geography in primary and secondary schools, Abler said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebeca Rodriguez writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
