<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CLEAR-CUT: CHAN'S PLAN IS PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Can't really say how bad that haircut was
that Michael Irvin threw a fit about a couple of weeks ago, but
after watching the Cowboys struggle through two preseason games and
a couple of scrimmages with teams that might not be able to compete
in the WAC, I'm right there with him.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this training camp has been like a four-week shave with
a dull razor. If the season doesn't start soon, somebody's liable
to bleed to death just to relieve the boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Which means, you understand, that things are right on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Folks are supposed to start getting antsy about now, which is
why the Cowboys will wrap up the Wichita Falls portion of training
camp and pick it up again at Valley Ranch after this weekend's trip
to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   If you're less than enthused about what you've seen of your
heroes so far this summer, join the crowd. They are 0-2 in
preseason games, 1-1 in game-type scrimmages and light years away
from where first-year coach Chan Gailey hopes they'll be when they
open the season against Arizona on Sept. 6 at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   You can't miss Gailey. He's the guy with the barber's clippers
and the straight razor, trying to put a spit shine on a team that
had gotten a little ragged over the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to put too many pre-set standards on 'em,''
Gailey said of his expectations before yesterday afternoon's single
practice at Midwestern University. ``We had an idea of a general
area where we wanted them to be and we are in that general area.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I put it too much up here,'' he added, holding a hand
up high, ``and we don't get there, then I go around staying mad
about it and it might not be their fault. You don't know what all
is going to happen in training camp that will slow you down or set
you back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was wearing the look of a man who had just dodged an
Internal Revenue Service audit after learning that defensive tackle
Leon Lett, by far his best defensive player in the front seven,
will miss only three to four weeks with a sprained knee and should
return in time for the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough game for tough people,'' Gailey said, but just
uttering the cliche seemed to leave his own knees a little wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   His team, Gailey understands better than anyone, must make some
giant strides over the next couple of weeks to be ready to play for
real. To get there, the Cowboys must address the head coach's three
main concerns.
</P>
<P>
   (1.) Somehow, some way, they must apply some defensive pressure
to opposing quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   (2.) The offense, still struggling with Gailey's new system,
must find some consistency.
</P>
<P>
   (3.) Someone must emerge as the No. 2 receiver to take some
pressure off Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the areas I'd say are the chief areas of concern for
me right now,'' Gailey said. ``I have a hard time categorizing what
the biggest problem is and what the least problem is, because if
it's a problem it's a problem. Whatever weak links you have, you
can be attacked there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys knew coming into camp that it would take time for
their two new starters at defensive end _ Kavika Pittman and rookie
Greg Ellis _ to develop, but they'd like to see some progress soon.
Pittman missed Tuesday night's scrimmage against the Saints in
Shreveport with an ankle sprain, and Ellis has yet to find himself
in the same area code as an opposing quarterback, much less record
a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we'd like a better pass rush, but there are ways to
create pressure,'' Gailey said. ``We'll be able to get to that, I
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to create more consistency in the offense. I think
we've got to quit dropping the football, both catching passes and
putting it on the ground with fumbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's like any coach. All he wants is perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we score every time we get the ball we won't be as
consistent as I want us to be,'' Gailey said. ``But at the same
time, we've made progress. We've had good days, we've had bad days.
I would hope we could move rapidly from here on out, but we'll take
it at the pace that we need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   They're on a 24-day clock now, though, and suddenly time, like
the barber's scissors, is snip, snip, snipping away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
