<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-PERELMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERELMAN LIKELY TO GET LARGER STAKE IN SUNBEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunbeam Corp. said Wednesday that it had agreed to give one of
its largest shareholders, a company controlled by Ronald Perelman,
the right to increase its stake for attractive terms in exchange
for guarantees that it will not sue the troubled appliance maker.
Such a suit would have been likely to force Sunbeam into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, Sunbeam granted the Perelman
holding company, MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes Holdings Inc., five-year
warrants to purchase 23 million Sunbeam shares at an exercise price
of $7 per share. MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes already owns 14 percent of
Sunbeam's stock, making it the second-largest shareholder behind
Franklin Mutual Advisers Inc. The new arrangement would give
MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes a 28 percent stake if it exercised the right to
buy the additional shares.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam says the arrangement, which would dilute the value of
current investors' shares, is good for the company because it comes
with certain key guarantees from MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes. But it is
also a way for Perelman to recoup his investment after having sold
Coleman Co. to Sunbeam in March for a large chunk of Sunbeam stock
instead of mostly cash. Had he taken cash, his investment _ then
worth about $560 million _ would not have taken a nose dive when
Sunbeam ran into serious trouble under its former chairman and
chief executive, Albert Dunlap, who has since been ousted.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Coleman deal, shares of Sunbeam were trading
at about $40. But after several disappointing quarters, the stock
has tumbled, losing more than 80 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement was made after the stock market had
closed for the day.
</P>
<P>
   For Perelman, ``the road to breaking even is a lot shorter
now,'' said Constance Maneaty, an analyst who follows the company
for Bear, Stearns. Perelman could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the right to buy the additional shares,
MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes has agreed to release Sunbeam from any legal
claims arising from the Coleman purchase, in light of Sunbeam's
dismal performance, and to keep in place Perelman's hand-picked
management team. Jerry Levin, a turnaround expert associated with
Perelman who is now Sunbeam's chief executive officer, and other
key executives have signed three-year employment contracts to
continue to run the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, such a deal would have required a shareholder vote,
but Sunbeam appointed a special committee to approve the
transaction, saying putting it before investors would have taken
months and ``would inhibit Sunbeam's ability to reach a settlement
with MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes and to retain and hire senior management
essential to Sunbeam's business; and thus would seriously
jeopardize the financial viability of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Gittis, vice chairman of MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes, said in a
statement that the agreement was good for all investors because
``these warrants will only have value if Sunbeam shares appreciate
from current levels.''
</P>
<P>
   What is sweet about the deal that allows Perelman to buy more
stocks at $7 a share, however, is that the stock price does not
have far to go to get there. Shares of Sunbeam closed at $6.875, up
25 cents on the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2216EDT &QL; 
