<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIAN MALAISE BRINGS LOW RATES TO AMERICANS
</P>
<P>
   In the complex chain of global economic events, the malaise that
has brought pain and suffering to Asians has given American
consumers low interest rates _ a trend economists expect to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that home mortgage refinancings have hit their
highest levels in years. The average interest rate on a 30-year
mortgage, which started the year at 7.05 percent, is now 6.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices slipped, as the dollar fell against the yen
before steadying.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING TO BUILD 737s IN CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   Boeing plans to announce Thursday that it will build some of its
single-aisle 737 jets in Long Beach, Calif. _ a decision welcomed
by workers at the former McDonnell Douglas operations there, where
600 jobs will be restored.
</P>
<P>
   BRITONS BUY MCI STAKE IN VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications agreed to acquire MCI's 24.9 percent
stake in Concert, the companies' international joint venture, for
$1 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM IN DEAL WITH SHAREHOLDER
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam granted one of its largest shareholders, Ronald
Perelman's MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes Holdings, the right to increase its
stake for attractive terms in exchange for guarantees not to sue
the troubled appliance maker.
</P>
<P>
   CALENERGY TO BUY A UTILITY
</P>
<P>
   Calenergy, an international developer of power plants based in
Omaha, Neb., said it would buy MidAmerican Energy Holdings, Iowa's
largest utility, for $2.6 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHER EXECUTIVE TESTIFIES
</P>
<P>
   An executive with Archer Daniels Midland testified that he and
another senior executive had participated in a global conspiracy
with competitors to fix the price of citric acid.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER OPTIONS PASS MUSTER
</P>
<P>
   A German court rejected a professor's challenge to the way
Daimler-Benz rewards 1,600 of its executives with stock options.
Now Daimler can tackle the differences between its executives' pay
and executive pay at Chrysler, which it plans to acquire. Daimler's
chief executive, Juergen Schrempp, is thought to receive $1.1
million to $1.5 million a year, plus the returns on Daimler stock
options. An SEC filing showed that Chrysler's chief executive,
Robert J. Eaton, received $69 million in bonuses, stock and stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM MAKES UNEXPECTED PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Seagram reported a slim but unexpected $3 million quarterly
profit as strong results from its television and music businesses
offset lower liquor sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT UP AT NEWS CORP.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. said its fourth-quarter earnings more than doubled,
buoyed by large gains in its U.S. television businesses and a
return to profit of its film division.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TO APPEAL JUDGE'S ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it would appeal a federal judge's order that
pretrial questioning of its chairman, Bill Gates, and 16 employees
in the government's antitrust action be opened to the public and
the news media.
</P>
<P>
   OPENING THE KIMONO ON MICROSPEAK
</P>
<P>
   Detroit gave Americans words like ``tailfin,'' while Hollywood
contributed ``sitcom.'' The latest lingo comes from Redmond, Wash.,
where current and former Microsoft workers have compiled a lexicon
of the company's jargon: ``Opening the kimono'' means to reveal the
inner workings of a project or company to a prospective new
partner, while a ``bitstorm'' causes the digital equivalent of
gridlock.
</P>
</TEXT>
