<SLUG> BC-NAZI-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAZI SUSPECT SAYS HE WAS PRISONER AND UNAWARE OF ATROCITIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jack Reimer, the former Brooklyn businessman accused
of hiding his past as a Nazi war criminal, interrupted his lawyer
at his trial on Wednesday to praise a survivor of the Treblinka
death camp who had testified earlier about escaping a mass
execution of Jewish prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But Reimer, who maintains that he was a prisoner of war in an SS
training camp in Trawniki, Poland, testified in U.S. District Court
in Manhattan that he had been unaware of Nazi atrocities at
Treblinka or anywhere else in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all under the strictest secrecy,'' he said. ``We
didn't know anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as Reimer, a 79-year-old former potato chip
salesman and restaurateur, took the witness stand to defend himself
against charges that he had been a commander in the Trawniki camp,
helped to liquidate the Jewish ghettos in Poland, and assisted in
mass executions of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   And although Reimer continued to maintain Wednesday that he had
been a captured Soviet soldier while in the camp and had never
killed anyone, his testimony included a series of assertions that
appeared likely to bolster the government's case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer was asked about his role in the mass shooting of Jewish
prisoners in a pit outside the Trawniki camp _ an incident about
which he has given many conflicting accounts in recent years to
government lawyers and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Reimer maintained that by the time he arrived at the
pit, all of the victims were dead. He said that they had been
executed by a group of SS men who had arrived earlier. He said that
he took only one shot, on orders from an SS officer, but directed
his rifle away from the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But then he acknowledged that one of the victims might have been
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why it comes into my head that somebody moved or
pointed to his head,'' Reimer said. ``I don't know. It is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The admission may be significant because the Justice Department
has asserted that Reimer should have been ineligible to enter the
United States under a law that, among other things, bars people if
it can be shown that they assisted in the persecution of people on
the basis of race, religion or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer, who was born in Ukraine, told investigators when he
applied to enter the United States in 1952 that he had been a
lieutenant in the Soviet Army who had been captured by the Germans
and held with other prisoners of war at Trawniki.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Reimer's testimony Wednesday focused on his time at
Trawniki, where he says that he was mainly a bookkeeper and
paymaster. He has denied the government's charges that he and other
Trawniki men participated in the mass executions there and the
liquidation of the Jewish ghettos of Warsaw, Lublin and
Czestochowa.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, the government closed its case with testimony
from Simon Friedman, 79, the former prisoner at Treblinka.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, who described a day of mass executions at the death
camp in July 1944, did not identify Reimer or place him at the
scene of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman testified that at one point, he and a group of about 20
others were ordered to lower their pants and underwear and hop
toward a grave dug by other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to try to run through a field, and was shot in the
hand and neck. He lay there for hours, left for dead, as other
groups of prisoners were executed in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer sat impassively throughout Friedman's testimony, but
after he took the witness stand, he issued his compliment to the
Holocaust survivor. ``I have to give Mr. Friedman a lot of credit
at his age,'' Reimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Friedman scoffed at Reimer's assertion, saying that if he
were truly ignorant of what had occurred under the Nazis, ``he
wouldn't be sitting here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
