<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWS-DIVORCE-800&AMP;ADD-     08-12 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-DIVORCE-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBIS STIR FUROR BY HELPING `CHAINED WOMEN' TO OBTAIN DIVORCES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By NADINE BROZAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ At age 88, Rabbi Emanuel Rackman would just as soon be
spending his time writing his memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the rabbi, one of the leading figures in Orthodox Jewry
in New York, is embroiled in a bitter dispute that has pitted him
against virtually the entire spectrum of the Orthodox rabbinate.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the furor is the rabbinical court he and another
Orthodox rabbi, Moshe Morgenstern, established a year and a half
ago to help women whose husbands refuse to grant them a religious
divorce, known as a get. The court, which meets in Rackman's office
in Manhattan and Morgenstern's in Queens, grants the women
annulments instead.
</P>
<P>
   In Orthodox belief, a get is more important than a civil divorce
decree because, without one, a woman is considered to be in chains,
linked forever to her husband. Without a get, such a woman _ known
as an agunah _ remains in limbo: Though she no longer lives with
her husband, she cannot remarry within Orthodoxy, and should she do
so elsewhere, any children she may bear will be considered
illegitimate. In turn, those children cannot marry Orthodox Jews,
nor can their descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Men on the other hand, face no such consequences. They are
entitled to remarry so long as their new wives are not themselves
in need of a get, and their offspring are considered legitimate.
The justification for the discrepancy is that the Bible permitted
polygamy, but did not allow women more than one husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extreme situation where hundreds of women are
suffering, for whom every day is a torture,'' said Rackman, whose
long career has included service as rabbi of the Fifth Avenue
Synagogue, provost of Yeshiva University and most recently,
Chancellor of Bar-Ilan University in Israel. ``So we are using an
extreme remedy: we give a get in such a way that it is not a get
but a dissolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The court, the Bet Din Tzedek Lebayot Agunot _ ``Righteous Court
for the Problems of Chained Women'' _ is made up of Rackman,
Morgenstern and a third member from a small, rotating group of
rabbis, to meet the requirement for three judges. So far, they have
ended 190 marriages _ or as they prefer to phrase it, ``freed 190
women.'' Many are from the New York area, but Morgenstern also
travels occasionally to Israel and Los Angeles, where he and two
other rabbis from the court _ sometimes by telephone _ grant
annulments.
</P>
<P>
   The court's annulments, like those in Roman Catholicism, state
that the marriage technically never existed. The children from the
annulled marriage are considered legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   With civil divorce on the rise even in the family-oriented
Orthodox community, the issue of how to deal with the end of a
marriage has taken on a new urgency in recent years. Increasing
numbers of those men, rabbis involved in such cases say, are trying
to withhold the get in exchange for reducing or eliminating support
payments or winning custody rights. But the annulments are proving
as troublesome an issue in Judaism as they are in Roman
Catholicism, where they have recently been under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some people deem the two rabbis heroes for liberating women who
do not live in a marriage but cannot be released from it. Others,
including admirers of Rackman who fault him more in sorrow than
anger, contend that no matter how well-intentioned he may be, he is
bending immutable laws to fit contemporary cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I always tolerated private disagreement, but for me to
take a public position has been very painful,'' said Rabbi Saul
Berman, a former student of Rackman and former senior rabbi of the
Lincoln Square Synagogue, who spoke in opposition to Rackman at the
recent annual convention of Hadassah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of the most important issues before the
Jewish community,'' he said, ``and its resolution will be crucial
to the integrity of Orthodoxy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWS-DIVORCE-2NDTAKE-     08-12 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-DIVORCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of Orthodoxy. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute is whether annulment conforms to
Halacha, the body of law that governs Jewish life. The majority of
rabbinical authorities say that it does not, or at least, that
Rackman and Morgenstern have not produced the Talmudic or halachic
evidence that it does.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient times, it was acceptable under Jewish law to force a
reluctant husband to grant a get by boycotting his business,
ostracizing him from the community or even flogging him. In Israel,
recalcitrant husbands have been jailed, sometimes for many years.
But with such coercive methods illegal under American civil law,
Rackman said: ``We have found a loophole. If coercion is warranted
by the facts of the case and cannot be exercised because of state
law, then the only means available to help the wife get out of the
marriage is annulment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Morgenstern, an accountant by profession, ``Every
one of the women we have freed has 20 to 30 grounds for annulment:
beatings, threats, verbal abuse, desertion, failure to support her
and her children.'' Both rabbis say there are many references to
annulment in the Talmud and in centuries of rabbinic rulings in
answer to questions raised by Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgenstern does not believe that the availability of the
get ought be limited to brutality or abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman is not a slave,'' he said. ``She is a person in her
own right. She has the right to say I loved you yesterday and if I
change my mind today, the man must let go.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has been intensifying since the creation of the
court. There have been public debates, and articles in the Jewish
press in New York and in Israel have produced barrages of letters
to the editor. In recent days, the coverage has become personal,
with the revelation that as a young man, Morgenstern himself had
refused to give his first wife a get for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern, who is 67, says that experience led him to the
conclusion that ``when a woman does not want to continue a
relationship with a man, no matter how much in love they were
before, the man must let go.''
</P>
<P>
   In his case, he said his wife, who was pregnant at the time,
left him and returned to her parents after she developed colitis.
Her parents had disapproved of his uncertain prospects as a rabbi,
so he returned to school and studied accounting at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give the get because I always hoped that my wife
would return to me then, but to no avail,'' he said. ``In
retrospect, I am convinced I made an error and should have let her
go the minute she wanted out.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponents of the new court pretty much run the ideological
gamut of Orthodox Jewry.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, director of Edah, a group dedicated to the
revitalization of the more liberal wing known as modern Orthodoxy,
said he believed the power to annul should be allocated only to a
central court and not to every bet dinformed by three rabbis.
Instead, he advocated other means of resolution, like prenuptial
agreements with specific provisions for the get, and various forms
of community pressure on the recalcitrant husband.
</P>
<P>
   Another opponent of the new court is Rabbi Yaakov Feitman,
president of the ultra-Orthodox Young Israel Council of Rabbis.
``The overwhelming number of cases of agunot are not eligible for
any kind of annulment,'' he said, explaining that annulment was
only applicable in circumstances that involve fraud that predated
the marriage, such as a disease that was concealed from the bride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts go out to agunot, but freeing them improperly only
transfers them to a worse prison,'' Feitman said. ``The
overwhelming number of rabbis around the world will not marry women
with those annulments and even worse, if they remarry without
rabbinic sanction, they will have children who will be declared
children of incest or adultery. That is a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief criticisms, even among the rabbis' staunchest
supporters, is that they failed to produce evidence that the
annulments issued by their court fully conform to Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sources are there and anyone with a will to find them can,
but they did not circulate their halachic material,'' said Blu
Greenberg, an author and teacher who has written extensively on
feminism and Judaism. ``When you do something that is as unique a
departure as this, you must line up your ducks first.''
</P>
<P>
   But she emphasized, ``If this bet din succeeds, as I hope it
will, then it will be Halacha responding to a contemporary need.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern countered the criticism by citing various scholarly
references to annulment and said: ``I can cite chapter and verse of
evidence and I write a legal brief for every case we adjudicate.
Anyone who wants to see my evidence is welcome to come and see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several women who have had their marriages annulled by the
Rackman-Morgenstern court said they had no doubts about the
validity of the procedure, nor do they fear problems should they
want to marry again.
</P>
<P>
   One woman from Long Island, who like others interviewed declined
to be identified for fear of retribution from their husbands, said:
``They helped me when I needed it, they made me feel there was a
way out. We had been married 20 years and he was using the get as a
monetary leverage. When Columbus said the world was round, everyone
said he was nuts. He proved everyone wrong and they will too.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman from New Jersey, who sought a divorce from her husband
of two and a half years because he became violent, said: ``I went
to all the rabbis I knew, and they said to me, `Isn't it worth your
giving him some money to be free?' I said, `No, I am not buying a
get.' I don't think God wants a woman to suffer just because she
didn't meet a good partner. If a man can't fulfill his duty, I
believe the marriage contract is void and my conscience is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
