<HEADLINE>
SEC FILES SUIT AGAINST COMPANIES ALLEGING FRAUD WITH ONLINE CASINO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Federal officials have rolled out their sequel to
``Risky Business,'' suing Los Angeles-based companies they claim
operated a fraudulent investment scheme via the Internet that cost
investors $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint filed Wednesday by the Securities and Exchange
Commission in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles seeks to halt the
operations of Internet Casino Sports Gaming LLC and Internet Casino
Sports Gaming Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Also named were the companies' principals, Robert Matias, also
know as Robert DuVall, 35, and Alan Lenchner, also known as Alan
Lane, 62, both of Los Angeles, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents have frozen corporate and individual assets, and
seized about $250,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The government alleges that the men used money to be invested in
an online casino to pay salaries to family members and support a
lavish lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The action is part of a nationwide sweep of allegedly bogus
entertainment-related schemes 40 states that cost unwary investors
more than $100million.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Casino's phones were still working Wednesday but
neither of the principals could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Their attorney, Steven B. LeHat of Irvine, Calif., said he did
not want to discuss the issue at length.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite obviously their take on their operation is something
that under the circumstances would not be the subject of a news
report until we see what's coming down here,'' he said. ``We have
not seen any claims the federal government has made so we are
talking in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit is a civil action and claims that from April
1997 to the present the two men and their companies raised about $2
million by selling shares to 152 investors nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But only about 10 percent of the money was used for the
development and licensing of the Web site, said Lisa A. Gok,
assistant regional director in the SEC's office of enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The balance was used to fund a boiler room from which the
businesses were pitched, the paying of salaries for Matias' father-
and mother-in-law and Lenchner's daughter, and automobile
allowances, including a 1998 Mercedes-Benz sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Gok said the men used the Internet to solicit potential
investors, who then sent their money to a mail drop in Studio City,
a Los Angeles suburb.
</P>
<P>
   She cautioned investors to read the SEC's Cyberspace Alert
before sending money to any business being promoted via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It is also available via the investor assistance and complaints
links on the SEC Web site at www.sec.gov. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
