<SLUG> BC-KPMG-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: KPMG AIMS TO STAND APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a firm sells business advice, it may be difficult to
imagine anyone remembering its advertising slogan or considering
its logo hip enough to wear as a fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   And KPMG Peat Marwick LLP is certainly not expecting its image
to become as widely recognizable as McDonald's arches or its logo
as popular the Nike swoosh. But the accounting, tax and consulting
firm has, nonetheless, created a brand campaign intended to set the
firm apart in an industry in which potential clients often view
competing firms as largely one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign comes after a proposed merger with Ernst &AMP;
Young, which last week consolidated its own ad accounts, fell
apart. The two firms planned to unite to create the world's largest
accounting and consulting firm, but abandoned the idea in February
because of growing opposition by foreign antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the firms said the merger was critical to their
business and long-term survival. Now, KPMG wants to reinforce its
strengths in the minds of would-be clients.
</P>
<P>
   Using the tag line ``It's time for clarity,'' the ads are meant
to convey an ability to deliver the attributes clients say they
want from professional firms mired in the complexities of the
information age _ understandable business advice and practical
solutions that can be easily carried out quickly and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   One television commercial shows prim grandmothers doling out
such advice as ``Always make sure you conduct a mass utilization
model before crossing the street.'' A print ad shows a weathered
mailbox and says: ``Remember what it was like before there was
overnight mail, voice mail and e-mail? You actually had time to
think.'' Both the spot and ad include the ``clarity'' tag line.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which will include print, broadcast and billboard
advertising, was created by Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS, in New York, part
of the Lowe Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos. It represents
the initial phase of a $60 million worldwide branding effort for
KPMG, which operates in 155 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing strategy is to deploy a brand advertising
campaign that will significantly increase prospect and client
awareness for KPMG, help us create a place at the table when there
is business to be won _ and help our partners and professionals win
more of that business,'' said Tim Pearson, chief marketing officer
for the company. ``This is advertising that helps articulate KPMG's
strategy and captures who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which began late last month and is being expanded
domestically this month and internationally in the fall, includes
commercials on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and ABC's ``Nightline.'' This
month, KPMG will expand the television advertising to such channels
as CNN, the Discovery Channel, MSNBC, the Learning Channel and
CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also run commercials during golf and tennis
tournaments and NCAA football bowl games. Print advertising will
appear in business newspapers and magazines and special interest
publications. The campaign will also include advertising on
billboards at major airports.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the brand message, a separate national print and
broadcast campaign will emphasize KPMG's services.
</P>
<P>
   One print ad promoting the firm's consulting business shows a
tricycle sitting in the grass. It includes this message: ``It's so
rewarding to watch a youngster fail over and over only to learn
from his mistakes. Just not when it's a consultant who's charging
you $275 an hour. Our consultants average 13.5 years of experience.
We figure you pay them for their business insight, not their
business education.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads will bear a modified KPMG logo since the firm expects to
adopt the shortened KPMG name by the end of this year to support a
consistent and recognizable global identity. In both the brand and
services campaign, the spots use humor and plain speaking to talk
to an audience that is business smart but has little tolerance for
insider lingo that can get lost on even the most seasoned
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarity also works because corporate leaders, the influentials
we're reaching, are charged with bringing clarity to their
shareholders and employees and they are frustrated with the level
of clutter, chatter and `white noise' in the current environment,''
Pearson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
