<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-12 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last chance &QL; 
for a major &QL; 
to remember
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ So we're down to one, the final major, albeit the
one they call the minor major.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The PGA Championship, No. 80 in a series, can still
save the day _ I mean the year. Mark O'Meara's year.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to O'Meara, who happens to be a really nice
guy, a rock-solid family man and, in his own words, ``a very good
golfer, not a great one,'' any year that bears his stamp isn't a
year you're likely to remember for very long.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I've almost forgotten it already.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen winning the U.S. Open most assuredly didn't help
much, either, although we must pump Janzen's hand for at least
preventing O'Meara from daring to think Grand Slam at Sahalee
Country Club this weekend. That would have been too much. As it is,
O'Meara is still attempting a Ben Hogan, the three-fourths Slam.
</P>
<P>
   This lumpy, average Joe of a fellow _ he could pass for a
sportswriter _ was once a National Amateur champion, but he had
trundled through 56 majors without sniffing victory before he
claimed the elusive prize at the Masters. There, almost out of
nowhere, he snuck past both a contemporary who had come to
overshadow him, Fred Couples, and a hot young lion in David Duval
to steal the show from a certain beloved old Bear.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, O'Meara was at it again, beating the field
and the wrath-of-God elements at Royal Birkdale. Tiger Woods should
have been the British Open champion. He was actually tied for the
lead after a spectacular finish on the last two holes. But no. It
would be O'Meara, suddenly a major master, who added the Old Claret
Jug to his new green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't golf now supposed to be child's play? Hadn't the brat
pack pretty much laid siege to the tour in 1997? And the one place
the twentysomethings didn't kick butt, somewhere under a rainbow at
the PGA, Davis Love III did.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's record romp through the '97 Masters seemingly announced
his candidacy for immortality. Ernie Els and Justin Leonard
followed suit, providing a sneak preview of the
Palmer-Nicklaus-Player troika for the next century. Until Duval
reeled off three straight victories at the close of the season to
give us a new Fab Four of the fairways heading toward the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that was just kid stuff compared to seeing Love hurdle his
personal hump at the PGA, the workingman's major. Davis' father,
who died in a plane crash, was a much-loved teaching pro. Anyone
who knew of the dad's affection for the son _ and vice versa _ also
knew exactly who was responsible for that rainbow in the sky above
Winged Foot as Love conquered all.
</P>
<P>
   This year? Blah. For all the drama provided by the Masters and
the two Opens, and indeed the Sunday scripts have been
scintillating stuff at each venue, the wrong blokes keep turning up
on top.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: The stars make the tournament. U.S. Open TV ratings at
Olympic were down 18 points from '97, in no small part because
people didn't tune in by the jillions to see how Tiger was doing.
It has been awhile since his mere presence at an event made him a
safe bet to cash the first-place check.
</P>
<P>
   The Chosen One has exactly that many wins _ one _ to his name in
'98, which ties him with, among many others, Trevor Dodds. Who?
That's my point.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA offers grand possibilities. Hope springs eternal, El
Nio or no El Nio. We can escape these doldrums, although it will
take a Tiger or a John Daly or a Couples or a Tom Watson to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, of course, invented himself at Crooked Stick's PGA, while
Couples, who came so close to claiming a second Masters, is a
Seattle homeboy. Watson, pushing 49, proved at Colonial he still
may have one last major in his yippy grip. Fact: Julius Boros was
only a couple months younger than Watson when he prevailed in the
PGA 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Stuart Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   His is the saddest imaginable story. Appleby decided to play
Sahalee less than three weeks after his wife, Renay _ who also was
his caddie _ was killed in a flukish accident in London. A taxi
backed into her, crushing her.
</P>
<P>
   Why did he come? It's either play golf, he figured, or go into a
shell from which he might never escape. Confronting the horrific
tragedy head-on, he conducted a half-hour news conference, telling
reporters to ask him anything they wanted. He got through it but
not without a lot of tears.
</P>
<P>
   If the compassion of one's peers counts for anything, Appleby is
the overwhelming PGA favorite. Also, oddly, he makes his home in
Isleworth, the gated enclave near Orlando where O'Meara and Janzen
live.
</P>
<P>
   Golf could use another rainbow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
