<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-NAZIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS BANKS AGREE TO PAY HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS $1.25 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: ADDS details on settlement, banks, background, and quotes
throughout; Adds dateline.) 
 (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Representatives of Swiss banks and Holocaust
survivors announced a settlement Wednesday in which the banks
agreed to pay $1.25 billion in reparations to victims of the Nazi
era.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, intended to settle the claims of tens of
thousands of survivors whose families lost assets in World War II,
was hailed by Jewish groups and elected officials as providing
long-delayed justice for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am tremendously pleased and gratified to announce that we've
reached a historic agreement,'' said Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.,
who led the move to pressure the Swiss banks into providing money
for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced in front of U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, where three suits filed over the last two years had been
consolidated into one class-action suit. The suits had accused the
banks of retaining the assets of Holocaust victims, assets that the
plaintiffs' lawyers said had been deposited in the banks by the
victims or that had been looted by the Nazis and stored in Swiss
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The litigation had been part of a growing effort to force the
banks to scour their records to identify dormant accounts and the
proceeds of Nazi plunder and to pressure them to return the assets
to the elderly and frail victims and their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the banks are Union Bank of Switzerland and Credit Suisse,
said Marc Cohen, a lawyer for the banks.
</P>
<P>
   The effort galvanized many of the victims and stirred bitterness
in Switzerland. But animosity was replaced by expressions of good
will Wednesday, as D'Amato spoke before a battery of microphones
and cameras in downtown Brooklyn. The lawyers and representatives
of the two sides were joined by two people who added a moving touch
to the discussions of litigation and vast amounts of money to right
historical injustices.
</P>
<P>
   One was Estelle Sapir, 73, a concentration camp victim who is
among the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy,'' Ms. Sapir said in a barely audible voice.
``I think this should have happened long ago. People need the
money. They're getting very old, and this is not charity.''
</P>
<P>
   The second person was Christoph Meili, 30, a former night
watchman at a Swiss bank who was fired and subjected to death
threats and police interrogation in Switzerland for saving
Holocaust-era bank documents from a shredder. Meili is now living
in New Jersey and working as a guard at an office building in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day,'' he said. ``We move a big step forward. I'm
happy. I'm glad to help the survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   The banks issued a statement saying: ``This development
represents a major milestone in our longstanding efforts to insure
that justice is served.''
</P>
<P>
   Many details of how to pay the money and who would qualify
remain to be worked out. The payments are to be made in four
installments over three years, with the first installment of $250
million not likely for nine months to a year because of the work
needed to implement the deal, according to lawyers for both side.
The work includes devising a plan to distribute the money to
victims with claims against the Swiss banks who live in the United
States and abroad, they said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of states and cities, including New York City and New
York state, had threatened to impose sanctions on the Swiss banks
if they did not agree to an acceptable settlement. The threat had
outraged the Swiss government, and the sanctions were also opposed
by the U.S. government, which feared that the threats could
complicate efforts at a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat said in a statement
Wednesday night that the accord ``represents a major step'' in
achieving justice for Holocaust survivors and strengthening
American-Swiss relations.
</P>
<P>
   One condition of the settlement, Eizenstat said in an interview,
was that the plaintiffs publicly call for all elected officials to
drop their threat of sanctions against the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   The call for sanctions intensified after a settlement agreement
fell apart in June. In subsequent weeks, officials in New York
City, New York state and California said they would impose
sanctions on Sept. 1 against Swiss financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   Another condition of the agreement is that the plaintiffs drop a
separate suit against the Swiss National Bank, which along with the
Swiss government had refused to negotiate with the plaintiffs, and
indemnify the bank and all other Swiss companies against further
monetary claims by the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said the National Bank's role in processing gold that
it knew had been looted was not in contention, but that essentially
taking the bank out of the case was a necessary condition to reach
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make the perfect the enemy of the good,'' he
said. ``I think additional monetary claims by the U.S. government
and by the private sector will not likely be forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   He said neither the Swiss government nor the Swiss National Bank
were contributing to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the pact began decades ago, when thousands of Jews
deposited their money in Swiss banks for safekeeping in the face of
persecution in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2242EDT &QL; 
