u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CUNY-ADMISSIONS-55     08-12 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CUNY-ADMISSIONS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGENTS DEMAND REVIEW OF CUNY'S REMEDIAL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The City University of New York and the New York
state Department of Education are battling over whether CUNY needs
the approval of the Board of Regents before it can enact a
far-reaching plan to bar students needing remedial help from its 11
senior colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department and the Regents maintain that they have
both the right and the responsibility to review any changes that
affect admissions policies at the state's public universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obligated by statute to review the plan, and it is our
intention to do so with as much haste as good sense would permit,''
Carl Hayden, chancellor of the Board of Regents, said in an
interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to the Education Department this week, CUNY's
chairwoman, Anne Paolucci, and its interim chancellor, Christoph
Kimmich, called the proposed review ``an unnecessary and
inappropriate incursion into the right of the Board of Trustees to
operate the City University of New York as set forth in the
education law in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   CUNY intends to enact the tougher standards at four colleges _
Hunter, Queens, Baruch and Brooklyn _ in September 1999. But a
state review could push back that date, because Education
Department officials have told CUNY that such a review is likely to
include public hearings and could take six to seven months.
</P>
<P>
   State officials promised Wednesday to hasten their review,
perhaps by scrutinizing preliminary versions of the plan before it
is formally proposed. But the possibility that the plan could be
delayed or even rejected leaves CUNY unable, in admissions
documents it is preparing now, to tell students applying to Hunter,
Queens, Baruch and Brooklyn Colleges what their admissions policies
will be.
</P>
<P>
   It is also too early to predict how the Regents would vote on
CUNY's policy. Several said Wednesday that they wanted more
information about its potential impact before they made a decision.
Some, like chancellor Hayden, have applauded CUNY's efforts to
toughen its standards. But some have also expressed concerns about
whether students who are turned away from the senior colleges would
be adequately served elsewhere, including at CUNY's community
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there should be stricter entrance requirements,''
said Saul Cohen, a regent and the former president of Queens
College. ``But you should never use a sledgehammer if you can use a
scalpel,'' he said, indicating that he would have preferred a more
moderate policy that allowed students who needed limited remedial
work to enroll at the senior colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``a board has a right to make policy, and our
job is to see if the sky will fall in.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Department officials say that most policies that come
under review _ about 25 a year _ are approved, and that plans to
review the CUNY proposal do not necessarily suggest any opposition
to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an institution changes or alters its mission in any
substantive ways, it is required to get prior approval from the
board of regents,'' said Gerald Patton, the deputy commissioner for
higher education, who is coordinating the planned review. ``We are
not doing this because we want to do this, but because we are
required to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state first notified CUNY in June that it wanted to
scrutinize the remedial policy. But CUNY officials did not become
concerned about the process until last month, when state officials
laid out a long list of questions they would be asking and said
that CUNY's formal plan would have to be submitted by Oct. 1 for
the Regents to make a decision by next April.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials told the department that they probably would not
be able to submit a detailed plan until December. Officials at
CUNY's campuses have until next month to submit their own proposals
to the chancellor's office, which will then develop a master plan.
That plan must then be reviewed by the CUNY board.
</P>
<P>
   Education Department officials had told CUNY that if the master
plan could not be submitted before December, CUNY should not seek
to adopt it until September 2000, since it would be difficult for
the regents to make a decision quickly enough for the policy to be
enacted next year.
</P>
<P>
   A delay would give at least a temporary reprieve to students who
might have been turned away from Hunter, Queens, Baruch and
Brooklyn Colleges next year if they could not pass all three of
CUNY's placement exams in reading, writing and mathematics. More
than a third of Baruch's entering freshmen and roughly half of
those at the other three colleges failed one or more of the exams
when then entered last fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
