<SLUG> BC-BOEING-LONGBEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO SHIFT SOME JET OUTPUT TO LONG BEACH IN '99 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aiming to ease the strain on one of its most troubled production
lines in Seattle, the Boeing company plans to announce Thursday
that it will begin building some of its single-aisle 737 jets in
Long Beach, Calif., beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which has been highly anticipated for months, is
good news for workers at the former McDonnell Douglas operations in
California, who have seen three of the four airplanes currently
built there canceled by Boeing since it bought McDonnell Douglas
last year for $16.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing executives and union officials acknowledged that the
move would only restore about 600 jobs, a fraction of the number
that will be lost when production on the discontinued Douglas jets
stops in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is expected to say that it will start building three of
the best-selling 737's a month in Long Beach starting in the second
half of next year, possibly rising to as many as five a month after
that, said executives who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is part of changes to an overall consolidation
plan that Boeing first announced in March.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also expected to say that it will transfer some
of its satellite operations to California and will make St. Louis
the headquarters of all future production of fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
   Neither move will result in the transfer of many jobs. But the
St. Louis decision could be significant if Boeing wins the
competition to produce the Pentagon's new Joint Strike Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said that it expects to eliminate between 18,000
and 28,000 of its 238,000 jobs by 2000 but Thursday's announcement
is not expected to provide more details on how those targets will
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials declined to comment. The move was reported
Wednesday by The Seattle Times.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 737 move has been opposed by the International Association
of Machinists, who represent 39,000 hourly Boeing workers in the
Puget Sound area. Though Boeing now has more orders for the 737
than it can handle and has paid heavy penalties to airlines for
missing delivery dates, workers fear that they will lose their jobs
if orders dry up in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The machinists' contract is set to expire next year, and Boeing
is eager to avoid a strike like the one it suffered in 1995. The
situation is complicated by the fact that the machinists' union and
the United Automobile Workers union, which represents 7,600 hourly
workers at Long Beach and is just as eager to get the new work as
the machinists are worried about losing it, are set to merge in the
next few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
