<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-BRITISH-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TELECOM TO BUY MCI'S STAKE IN JOINT VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pulling one of the final threads from its tattered relationship
with MCI Communications Corp., British Telecommunications PLC
announced an agreement Wednesday to acquire MCI's 24.9 percent
stake in the companies' international joint venture for $1 billion
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal was the denouement in a five-year relationship
that began with high hopes for a global telecommunications
partnership, blossomed into plans for a merger and then fell apart
amid a fight over money.
</P>
<P>
   With British Telecom's agreement to buy the stake in Concert, as
the venture is known, the British communications giant will be free
to move forward with plans to form a $10 billion joint venture with
MCI's rival, AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Neither MCI nor British Telecom would make any executives
available Wednesday to discuss the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Concert, which British Telecom formed in 1994, is meant to be a
vehicle for serving the global communications needs of
multinational corporations. With service in 52 nations, Concert
tries to allow its customers to use a seamless network that
functions identically in New York or New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   After buying MCI's portion of Concert, British Telecom will own
the entire venture. The British company expects Concert to generate
about $1 billion in revenue and to become profitable this year.
Financial analysts are unlikely to balk at the implicit value of $4
billion that Wednesday's deal placed on the operation.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom's American depository receipts, which trade on
the New York Stock Exchange, rose $2 Wednesday, to $133.375. MCI
rose $1.625, to $61.75, on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, the No. 2 long-distance carrier in the United States, began
its dealings with British Telecom in 1993, when BT bought 20
percent of the U.S. company for $4.3 billion. The companies formed
Concert the next year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they announced that British Telecom had agreed to
acquire the 80 percent of MCI it did not already own for $24
billion, forming a trans-Atlantic communications giant called
Concert PLC.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship soured last summer. Both companies'
shareholders had already approved the deal and the companies were
seeking regulatory approvals when MCI said in July that it could
lose as much as $800 million in its nascent local phone operation.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom reacted to the announcement by essentially
forcing MCI to accept a $5 billion reduction in the value of their
deal, making it worth $19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door for other communications carriers to bid
for MCI, which was not entirely pleased with the latest turn in its
relationship with British Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom Inc., led by Bernard Ebbers, offered $30 billion in
stock for all of MCI early last October. Two weeks later, GTE
jumped into the competition with a $28 billion cash bid.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom did not make a serious attempt to hold on to
MCI. After a flurry of negotiations among MCI, Worldcom and GTE,
MCI agreed to be acquired by Worldcom for $37 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   That deal will probably be completed in the next month. For its
20 percent stake in MCI, British Telecom will receive $7 billion in
cash. As for Concert, AT&AMP;T will become British Telecom's main
partner as soon as the British company finishes buying out MCI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0503 </DOCNO>
