<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-ZURICH-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES KEEPS IT SIMPLE: RUN FAST, JUMP FAR, WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Morocco, Denmark, Kenya)  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland _ Marion Jones has designs on five gold
medals at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, and she
has yet to lose an event this season: not a sprint, not the long
jump, not even the one 400-meter race she ran in April.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night at the Weltklasse, the best known and best
funded of the six stops on track's Golden League circuit, she
started by winning the women's 100 into a slight headwind in 10.77
seconds. That was a bit of a disappointment because she had hoped
to break 10.7 seconds for the first time. She concluded by winning
the long jump with a leap of 23 feet 11} inches, which was a
delight because it matched her personal best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to run faster and jump farther than I have
before,'' said Jones, 22. ``It's not as complicated as you might
think. Obviously world records are in the back of my mind, and you
are always reminding me, even if they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   World records have long been synonymous with Zurich. Since 1959,
23 have been matched or bettered in this meet _ last year, three
were broken in a single, extraordinary evening. But there would be
no such number-crunching on Wednesday night, only nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 10th anniversary of the men's 400 record of 43.29
seconds set here by the American Butch Reynolds. Despite the
considerable efforts of Michael Johnson, the record still stands.
Reynolds was here Wednesday night to watch Johnson make another
unsuccessful run at it, although his time of 43.68 seconds was his
best since his 1996 Olympic season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming together,'' Johnson said. ``But it's not my
objective to be in the same shape as 1996. I just want to win
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan Bailey of Canada, the world record-holder at 100 meters,
is not expected to race for the next three to four weeks after
pulling up midway through the 100-meter final with a strained thigh
muscle. With Bailey out and with Ato Boldon and Maurice Greene
training in Los Angeles because Zurich officials would not meet
their financial demands, the winner in the 100 was Seun Ogunkoya of
Nigeria in 9.96 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The best performance of the night came from Hicham el-Guerrouj,
the Moroccan world record-holder in the 1,500, and as he turned the
final corner, he was on pace to break his own mark of three minutes
26 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But the wall of sound that greeted el-Guerrouj as he pushed
toward the finish could not quite help him break through the
barrier he had created in Rome last month. Instead, he would have
to settle for the second-fastest 1,500 meters in history: 3:26.45.
</P>
<P>
   And though el-Guerrouj missed the $50,000 bonus that is reserved
for those who break world records in a Golden League event, he is
still in the running for a larger payday. Those athletes who win
their events in all six of the Golden League events and the Grand
Prix/Golden League final will split $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   El-Guerrouj has now won the first four legs.
</P>
<P>
   So has Jones. So has the American Bryan Bronson, the winner of
the men's 400 hurdles in 47.70 seconds, and Haile Gebrselassie, the
Ethiopian who fell short of his world record in the men's 5,000,
but still managed to win handily in 12:54.08.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's too difficult to win so many competitions,'' Gebrselassie
said. ``I'm struggling, and there are three more stages to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones sounded more upbeat and much less weary. ``I don't have a
problem with it,'' she said of the new format. ``Obviously when
you're running fast and going fast, everything is hunky-dory.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything wasn't for Wilson Kipketer of Denmark, whose streak
of 28 victories at 800 meters came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Japheth Kimutai, a 19-year-old who like Kipketer was born in
Kenya, is the world junior record-holder and the fastest man over
800 meters this season. And he was the better man Wednesday night
in 1:42.87. Kipketer finished second in 1:43.18, more than two
seconds off the world record he set here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the problems I had, I'm not surprised that I lost,''
said Kipketer, who contracted malaria in January and who missed
months of training and all of the early season. ``The other boys
are far ahead in training.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
