<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECTED-TERRORIST-230&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S SILENCE POSTPONES EX-HUSBAND'S DEPORTATION HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A deportation hearing for a man whom the FBI, in
secret documents, has linked to the terrorists who bombed New
York's World Trade Center was abruptly adjourned Wednesday when the
man's ex-wife refused to disclose what she had told federal agents
about him.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Hany Kiareldeen, a 30-year-old Palestinian, has been
detained for five months while the Immigration and Naturalization
Service has been trying to deport him. He had been waiting to have
his lawyers question his ex-wife, Amal Mohamed, about the secret
information, but the hearing stopped Wednesday, in its second day,
when Ms. Mohamed refused to answer some questions.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen's lawyers said they planned to go to U.S. District
Court here to seek an order compelling her to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Shulman, one of Kiareldeen's lawyers, contends that the
terrorism charges against his client were the creation of Ms.
Mohamed, who he said has a history of vindictiveness toward her
ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning by Shulman, Ms. Mohamed, a native of Egypt, said
she had met with FBI investigators at some point to ``confirm some
answers they had'' about Kiareldeen. But when asked for details,
Ms. Mohamed, who herself faces deportation proceedings later this
month, refused, saying that she had been threatened and that she
was concerned for her safety and the safety of her three children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier in the hearing, a lawyer for the INS, Leo Weber,
expressed concern about opening portions of the hearing, saying
that one of the unnamed informers who provided the secret
information had received death threats. An open hearing, he said,
could jeopardize the informer's anonymity and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules governing the Executive Office of
Immigration Review, the office's 200 administrative law judges
cannot compel witnesses to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Daniel Meisner, after failing to persuade Ms. Mohamed to
answer Shulman's questions, concluded that Kiareldeen's lawyers
would have to seek an order from a federal judge to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   He adjourned the hearings until Sept. 18. In the process, he
left several witnesses who had gone to the federal building here to
testify for Kiareldeen sitting in an adjacent room.
</P>
<P>
   The developments highlighted the problem for immigrants who face
deportation partly because of classified information. Kiareldeen is
one of 30 Arab-Americans who are the subjects of secret FBI
information suggesting that they are terrorists. When such
allegations become part of a deportation proceeding, as they have
in his case, investigators are required to provide only general
summaries of them and do not have to divulge the details or the
source of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen, a manager of an electronics store in Passaic, N.J.,
who has been in the United States since 1990, was picked up by
immigration officials and FBI agents in March for overstaying his
student visa _ a violation of immigration law not normally grounds
for automatic deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The following month, his lawyers learned from summaries of FBI
documents that informers had charged that Kiareldeen had met at his
home in Nutley, N.J., with Nidal A. Ayyad just a week before the
bombing of the World Trade Center on Feb. 26, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ayyad was one of four defendants convicted in March 1994 in the
attack. The secret informers also alleged, according to the
summary, that Kiareldeen had threatened the life of Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
