<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TO STUMP FOR GOP AROUND U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Iowa, N.H., Conn., S.C., Calif., R.I., Ariz., Fla.,
La.)   (bl)  
 By DAN BARRY    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will travel to several
states in the next few weeks to present himself as a Republican
visionary whose ideas about governance and politics have national
applicability. But those visits will not be limited to the exchange
of ideas; he will also be raising money for various Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is tentatively scheduled to attend a fund-raising event
for the Wisconsin Republican Party in Milwaukee on Aug. 25. The
next day, he will swing through Iowa, stopping to help raise money
for Rep. James Leach, the chairman of the House Banking and
Financial Services Committee, deliver a speech to a group of law
enforcement officials, and attend a fund-raising event for Jim Ross
Lightfoot, Iowa's Republican candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Giuliani is to travel to South Carolina for a
``Victory '98'' dinner being held by the Republican State
Committee. In mid-October, he will make several appearances in New
Hampshire, including one before the Nashua Federated Republican
Women's Club.
</P>
<P>
   And his aides are working out details for possible visits to
other states, including California and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Iowa caucus and the New Hampshire primary figure
prominently in presidential races. But aides to the mayor were
quick to say that his visits to those states did not suggest any
presidential ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the trips is to tell people the story of the
successes in New York City and to help influence the Republican
Party to accept his views on economic and social issues,'' said
John Gross, the mayor's longtime campaign treasurer. ``It is also
to try to help those candidates who share the same values that he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Keith Fortmann, the executive director of the
Republican Central Committee of Iowa, said visits by prominent
out-of-state politicians always carry that undercurrent of
ambition. ``I know the assumption is that if someone is coming to
Iowa, it automatically means he's running for president,'' he said,
adding, ``I'm looking forward to seeing what Rudy says, like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The trips will mark the first out-of-state political visits that
the mayor has made since addressing a gathering of Republican
National Committee members in New York City last month, during
which he maintained that the party's future success depended on its
ability to be more inclusive. It was an appeal that many read to be
as much personal as ideological. Giuliani, who is interested in
higher office, favors abortion rights and is for gay rights and gun
control _ positions that are anathema to the party's strong
conservative segment.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's new-found beneficence on behalf of the Republican
Party has not been limited to out-of-state visits. Next week, for
example, he is serving as the host of fund-raising events for Linda
Lingle, a gubernatorial candidate in Hawaii, and J.D. Hayworth, a
conservative congressman from Arizona. He has already held
functions in New York for Jeb Bush, a gubernatorial candidate in
Florida; Gary Franks, a Connecticut candidate for the U.S. Senate,
and Rep. Robert Livingston of Louisiana, the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   All this Republican-related effort by Giuliani comes at a time
when New York City has a shot at becoming the host to the
Republican National Convention in 2000; the city has traditionally
been perceived as too liberal for mainstream Republicans to bless
it with their presence. But the administration's hopes were
bolstered this week when the national committee announced that New
York was one of five finalists. A choice will be made before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Cristyne Lategano, the mayor's communications director, said
some of the reasoning behind Giuliani's peregrinations was to
eliminate any lingering impressions of New York City as
crime-ridden, drug-infested and otherwise unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City is one of the safest large cities in America,''
she said. ``Getting that message around is very helpful for New
York, especially in luring large conventions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
