<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT KEEPS QB OPTIONS OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ There's not exactly a quarterback controversy brewing
at USC's training camp, but, inevitably, coach Paul Hackett faces a
barrage of questions each day regarding the deepest and most
intriguing position on the team.
</P>
<P>
   When Hackett designated sophomore Mike Van Raaphorst the starter
last spring he also left himself some wiggle room, and that means
plenty of chances to speculate on the quarterback derby.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in two of the nation's top freshmen trying to elbow their
way up the depth chart and it's anything but a foregone conclusion
that Van Raaphorst will last the entire season at No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Van Raaphorst certainly has the inside track. He is the
starter,'' Hackett said. ``(But) he will really have to play well
to keep them at bay. Is it possible a freshman could start the
first game? That's very doubtful. Could it happen later in the
season? That's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   It's comments like those, along with some impressive play by
true freshman Carson Palmer during the first few practices, that
has kept any shred of a controversy alive.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word when he recruited Palmer and Jason Thomas last
winter, Hackett is giving the frosh plenty of practice time the
first week of training camp. Hackett, who said finding a backup is
one of the fall's early goals, realizes it's possible that an
injury could force him to juggle his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has been limited by a sore ankle, but Palmer, a 6-foot-4
All-American from Santa Margarita, has been drawing attention with
his accuracy and touch after just three days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play this year. That's always been my goal,'' Palmer
said. ``I felt I've done pretty good so far. It's different.
Everybody's so much bigger and faster; there's so much you need to
know. There's so many little things I'm missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said his goal is to be the No.2 quarterback entering the
season opener against Purdue. Thomas is even more precocious,
believing he, too, will thrust himself into the mix when he
recuperates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I get healthy, I guess the cream will rise to the top,''
Thomas said. ``If I have a chance, I'll be out there on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   First, they have to get by Van Raaphorst. Van Raaphorst began
last year as the backup to John Fox, but by midseason he earned
starts against Washington and Stanford. He was knocked out of the
Stanford game with a sprained ankle, an injury that would keep him
sidelined for the season's last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has the No.1 designation, he's aware the freshmen
are receiving a longer than usual look this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to beat everybody out again,'' Van Raaphorst said.
``Everyone knows (the freshmen) have got talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go out and if I make a mistake, it's not the end of the
world. It's nice going into the season (knowing) I'm the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost forgotten so far have been juniors Fox and Quincy Woods.
A year ago, Fox was the starter. But after seven games of
inconsistent production, Fox found himself the backup and only
started the last two games because of Van Raaphorst's injury.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment to a reserve role has been difficult for Fox, who
threw for 1,940 yards with 12 touchdowns and eight interceptions in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'm at. I don't like that I'm not the
first-string quarterback,'' Fox said. ``I'm where I was a few years
ago. It's tough to let the young guys get reps. You understand they
need to get reps too, but it's tough. That's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to become the starter is if I show them I can
compete every chance in the scrimmages.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who Hackett designated the No.2 quarterback after spring
drills, said he would have transferred if John Robinson had not
been fired. He decided to stay, he said, because he feels like he's
getting a new start.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure he's properly motivated, Woods said he kept every
newspaper article from last season questioning his ability or
chronicling his switch to wide receiver so that he can prove his
critics wrong when _ or if _ he gets on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned from the mistakes I've made, and I've become a
stronger player,'' Woods said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
