r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-ANDYGUMP-LADN     08-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ANDYGUMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDY GUMP, 88, FARM BOY BECAME SOUTHLAND'S KING OF PORTABLE
TOILETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yes, there was a real Andy Gump. In the flesh. A
dirt-poor Oklahoma farm boy who rose to become a millionaire by
bailing out people in need.
</P>
<P>
   Bailing them out in parks, at concerts, sporting events, swap
meets and just about every public event where people gathered
outdoors in Southern California to work or have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Gump, king of the portable toilets, died Monday. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   His life was part Will Rogers, part Horatio Alger. He was a
humble guy who never changed over the years, not even when the big
money started rolling in and his famous name dotted the landscape
all over this town.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you saw a long line of anxious-looking people hopping
from foot to foot, you knew there had to be an Andy Gump nearby.
</P>
<P>
   His name became synonymous with the outdoor sanitation business
in Southern California. It wasn't a portable toilet people went in
search of outside at public events. It was, and still is, an Andy
Gump.
</P>
<P>
   How all this transpired is a heck of a story from another
generation, says Barry Gump, Andy's son. It's the story of a kid
born into poverty back in 1910 in Claremore, Okla., the same town
where Will Rogers was born.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' sister even baby-sat Andy a few times. The people in
Claremore tended to be humble, hard-working and as honest as the
day was long. Andy was no different. He never forgot where he was
from.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was 19 when the Depression hit,'' Barry says. ``He
never knew it hit, though, because his family had nothing before
the Depression, either.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Gumps had moved to Campo, Colo., a tiny farming
town 325 miles southeast of Denver. The family tried to make ends
meet running Gump's service station and cafe out on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   But when the great dust storms blew through the Midwest in the
'30s, devastating crops and businesses alike, Andy and his wife of
two years, Irma, decided to join the migration west in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   They moved close to relatives in the L.A. area and, after a few
stints at odd jobs, Andy got a dump truck and started hauling rock
and gravel to construction sites up and down the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It was after dumping off a load of gravel in Oregon sometime in
the mid-1940s that Andy got the idea to fill his empty truck with
Christmas trees and bring them home to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad met a man in Pacoima who owned a cesspool and sewer
business on San Fernando Road,'' Barry said. ``He let Dad rent out
part of his lot to sell the Christmas trees.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history. The man took a liking to the
nice, personable Andy Gump, and sold him his business when he
retired a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad got a pump truck, and that eventually led to starting his
portable-toilet business in the mid-1950s,'' Barry says. ``He
called it Mission Sanitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy didn't know it, but he would soon catch the business break
of his life. He met a sign painter named Larry Fontana, who
convinced him that Mission Sanitation somehow didn't have the ring
to it that Andy Gump did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business wasn't that good, anyway, so my dad suggested to Andy
that he use his own name on the business instead,'' said Fontana's
son, Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been a popular comic strip with an Andy Gump cartoon
character, and Dad said why not use that? Andy told my dad he
really didn't want his name on portable toilets, but he tried it
anyway, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Mission Sanitation folded and Andy Gump emerged _ from a
garage at the home of Andy and Irma Gump in Mission Hills, a Los
Angeles suburb. There was Andy and his two sons, Barry and Bill,
who passed away in 1980, and Barry's friend, Angelo Pascolla, out
in the garage building five plywood portable toilets.
</P>
<P>
   The group delivered them to construction sites and picking them
up when the jobs were over.
</P>
<P>
   Five portable toilets grew to 50, then 100, and finally 3,000,
as plywood gave way to fiberglass and plastic _ and Andy Gump
became the undisputed common name for portable toilets at public
and private events all over this town.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Gumps served the L.A. area during the 1971 Sylmar
Earthquake when entire neighborhoods had no usable bathrooms. More
than 900 Gumps were scattered throughout venues for the 1984 Summer
Games in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And when then-presidential candidate Ronald Reagan decided to
throw a 1976 barbecue at his Santa Barbara ranch for politicians
and reporters, who got the call to duty?
</P>
<P>
   Andy Gump.
</P>
<P>
   Irma was the only one who called him by his given name _
Massena.
</P>
<P>
   To everyone else, from kindergarten through retirement, he was
Andy.
</P>
<P>
   Still humble and never forgetting where he was from. Still
driving his old Ford pickup truck to work every day well into his
80s _ still living with Irma in the same, modest Mission Hills home
they moved into more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gump is survived by his wife, Irma; daughter, Cherilyn; son,
Barry; three grandchildren; and seven great-grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
