<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUIT HAYES TO JOIN TEAM TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ USC recruit Windrell Hayes is expected to attend
practice today after pleading guilty Wednesday in Stockton to
writing bad checks.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer receiver from San Jose State had to pay $8,490.13
in restitution and was also sentenced to three years of probation
for the misdemeanor offense, according to San Joaquin County deputy
district attorney Patrick Slamon. If necessary, Hayes must also
testify against two other men involved in the scam.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes was scheduled to drive to Los Angeles on Wednesday night.
If he completes the necessary paperwork this morning at USC, he
will join the Trojans for their afternoon practice, coach Paul
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said NCAA rules prohibit Hayes from working out in pads
for three days, and he would probably not participate in a contact
practice until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a position where a young man obviously has been in
error,'' Hackett said. ``He has a second opportunity at USC. I will
be very conscious to watch carefully how he proceeds. I believe he
deserves another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if allowing Hayes on the team was inconsistent with
the one-game suspension levied against R. Jay Soward for poor
academic performance, Hackett said: ``When you become a member of
the team, you come under my rules and the standard of the team.
When you have recruit status, I think it is slightly different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
