A1311 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-TEX     08-12 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETT SIDELINED WITH KNEE SPRAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he will
not be ``scouring the woods,'' for defensive-line help in the
aftermath of Leon Lett's knee injury, which the coach said could
cause Lett to miss the Sept. 6 season opener against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Lett, the Cowboys' best pass rusher, injured his left knee when
Saints quarterback Billy Joe Hobert fell on him during a scrimmage
Tuesday night in Shreveport, La. A magnetic resonance imaging exam
performed on the defensive tackle early yesterday revealed a
sprain.
</P>
<P>
   The injury hurts a pass rush that has made little impact with
new starting ends Kavika Pittman and Greg Ellis. But since Lett is
not expected to be out more than three or four weeks, Gailey and
team owner Jerry Jones have decided not to make any major
acquisitions to beef up the club's depth on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed for Leon. It hurts our team to a certain
degree,'' Gailey said. ``But it's an opportunity for somebody else
to come in and show'' what they can do.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent among those players is fourth-round draft choice
Michael Myers, who Gailey said will assume Lett's starting duties.
And defensive coordinator Dave Campo said he can't wait to see how
tackle Darren Benson performs. Benson was the club's supplemental
draft choice in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel pretty good about our tackles,'' Campo
said. ``We've got three or four who can really help us. Is our
depth better? I feel better right now about our depth at tackle
than I did a year ago. Darren Benson has come a long way. You've
got Antonio Anderson. Michael Myers is a gamer. He plays better in
games than he does in practice. Only time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Lett's injury is the second setback the defense has had in
training camp. Linebacker Broderick Thomas, who was expected to
provide pass-rushing help on long-yardage situations, sustained a
season-ending knee injury last month.
</P>
<P>
   It already has been a hard summer for Pittman and Ellis. Neither
has registered a sack in two preseason games, and Pittman has
missed the past three days of practice after sustaining an ankle
injury in last week's exhibition game against the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey continues to say that he is not concerned with the lack
of pressure and added that the lack of sacks has come, in part,
because the team has not employed any special defensive fronts to
get the defensive ends to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't game-planned anybody,'' Gailey said. ``There are
ways to create pressure. Certainly we'd like a better pass rush,
but like I said, I think we'll be able to develop in time.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff Writer Clarence E. Hill Jr. contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2314EDT &QL; 
