</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-DRUGBUST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE CHASE ENDS IN DRUG FIND BY CUSTOMS FIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LISA MASCARO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A suspect in a drug-smuggling case led U.S.
Customs Service officials on a chase through Southern California
skies before landing at Santa Paula Airport, where he was arrested
with more than 500 pounds of cocaine aboard his craft, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, identified only as 52 and a California resident, was
arrested Wednesday morning on suspicion of drug smuggling, firearms
violations and illegal entry into the country with what officials
said was between $4 million and $5 million worth of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He flew all over the Central Coast, making loops, going low,
going high,'' said John Hensley, customs special agent in charge of
the Los Angeles field division. ``We don't know if he saw the
planes behind him. Maybe that's just the way he operates.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials spotted the suspicious-looking plane at about
7:30 a.m. Wednesday just south of the U.S.-Mexico border operating
without a standard Federal Aviation Administration radar device and
flying low at altitudes of 150 feet.
</P>
<P>
   From their Domestic Air Interdiction Coordinating Center at
March Air Force Base in Riverside County, customs officials began
their pursuit after the plane bypassed a mandatory stop before
crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft, a twin-engine Cessna turboprop with American
markings, then followed a known drug-running route along Laguna
Salada, which Hensley said is a below-sea-level valley bordered by
mountains and was once popular among smugglers because it was out
of radar's reach.
</P>
<P>
   From about 8 a.m. until 10 a.m., the man, described as clean-cut
and a registered pilot, was pursued by customs pilots. They trailed
him in a jet, two planes and a helicopter on what they called a
midspeed chase as the pilot crisscrossed the skies in an ``S''
pattern as he apparently kept looking for signs he was being
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of outgunned,'' Hensley said. ``He wasn't going to
get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials are unsure if the pilot planned to stop at Santa Paula
Airport or simply landed there because he was running low on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Paula Police Department officials were notified of the
incoming plane, said Santa Paula police Cmdr. Bob Gonzales, and
along with customs agents surrounded the aircraft upon landing at
the airport that sits in the midst of citrus groves.
</P>
<P>
   A drug-sniffing dog was brought to the scene and ``did a
pirouette when it got close to the plane, so we knew something was
there,'' Hensley said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials found 14 duffel bags full of cocaine, with wholesale
value of between $4.1million and $5million, a revolver on the pilot
and two automatic pistols in the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was being held in a Ventura County customs facility
and was scheduled to be transferred to a federal detention center
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1996, the plane was last registered to a Wilmington,
Del.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Paula Airport, which was temporarily shut down,
officials had no record of the plane having stopped overnight or
fueled there before, office manager Janice Dickenson said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport sees about 100 planes daily and is more accustomed
to hobby pilots and vintage aircraft than the activity that flew in
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years, I've never seen this happen,'' Dickinson said.
``This isn't a problem we've had here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
