<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1316 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     08-12 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVOY'S REQUESTS FOR SAFER BUILDINGS HAD BEEN DENIED FOR BUDGET
REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(inserts new sentence after 6th grf) (See also: AFRICA-INQUIRY, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-ENVOY,
AFRICA-DEAD) 
(JT) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. ambassador to Kenya and the Defense
Department were so alarmed about threats to the embassy in Kenya
that they requested a safer building, but were rejected for
budgetary reasons, the State Department said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, the Kenyan government said it had detained several
suspects in last week's bombing of the embassy, which killed at
least 247 people, including 12 Americans. Federal law enforcement
officials said that FBI agents in Nairobi would question the
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by requests from news organizations, the State
Department revealed details of the security warnings issued to the
department over the last nine months by the ambassador to Kenya,
Prudence Bushnell, and the U.S. Central Command, the element of the
Pentagon that oversees American military interests in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Senior State Department officials said they did not believe that
Bushnell had cited any particular terrorist threat in her two
requests for a new embassy building _ the first made in a cable
last December, the second in April in a message sent directly to
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``She indicated that resource constraints were endangering
embassy personnel,'' said Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary for
administration, who choked with emotion as he described the
warnings that the ambassador had made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we simply lack the money to respond immediately
to all the needs of embassy construction _ it's just like a family
with limited resources,'' he said at a news conference. ``Look I've
been a foreign service officer for 25 years. And if anybody thinks
that everyone in the department isn't sick about this, they're just
wrong. We did the very best we could, given what we had.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the department had agreed to the request, a new
building could not have been built before last week's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the department had to turn down the requests for a
new embassy because other projects had a higher priority, including
the construction of embassies in the Balkans and the nations of the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli newspaper Haaretz reported Wednesday that Israeli
intelligence officers had advised their American counterparts
shortly before Friday's bombings to disregard a warning that the
Embassy in Kenya might be the target of an attack.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that the man who relayed the warning had
been known to Israeli intelligence, and that American intelligence
officials had asked the Israelis to assess his credibility. The
newspaper said that ``based on their past experience with him, the
Israelis said the man's warning should be taken with a grain of
salt.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper did not provide any further details about the man
or the timing of the warning.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official in Washington said that David Bar-Illan,
Netanyahu's spokesman, denied the report. Bar-Illan had said that
Israel had gone through the last six months of intelligence
exchanges with the United States and found no exchange like the one
Haaretz reported.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Israel and Washington have ``ongoing and
intense exchanges'' of information about intelligence matters and
the East African bombings since they have happened. ``There is a
constant exchange of counter- terrorism information and
fragments,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official of a foreign intelligence service confirmed
earlier this week that his government had learned of a warning that
preceded the attack. But the official did not say at that time
whether the United States had asked other governments to assess the
warning.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials noted Wednesday that even if a new embassy
building in Nairobi had been approved, it would not have been
completed for years. ``We still would have been in that embassy''
when it was bombed, Kennedy reminded reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell, a career foreign service officer who is highly
regarded at the State Department, made her first request for a new
embassy building last December in a cable to the department in
Washington
</P>
<P>
   ``She expressed her concerns on the vulnerability of the embassy
and requested a security assessment,'' Kennedy said. ``Her desire
was to have a new building. The department expressed its agreement
and shared its understanding.'' He described the tone of the memo
as ``concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   While the department declined to make public the ambassador's
message, officials said she had listed several security concerns,
noting that the embassy was close to the street at a busy
intersection, which made it vulnerable to a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were multiple threats at the embassy,'' Kennedy said.
``She talked about crime, she talked about administrative matters,
and she talked about safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But in January, the State Department's Foreign Buildings Office,
which reviews requests for construction and decides how that budget
will be spent, did not include a new embassy for Nairobi on its
priority of new projects. ``This discussion confirmed that other
embassy projects had a higher priority than Embassy Nairobi for our
limited funds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the U.S. Central Command issued a similar warning
to the State Department, recommending that the embassy be housed in
a new building.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the department, Kennedy said, the Central Command
``expressed to the department its concern over the vulnerability of
the Nairobi chancellery, noting that a planned renovation for later
in the year would not change the fact that the embassy was close to
the street.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the guidelines requested by the Inman committee,
the external wall of an embassy should be at least 100 feet from
streets or sidewalks. At the Nairobi embassy, which had been
considered a low-risk post for terrorists, the so-called setback
was only about 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
