<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-GENOVESI-nY     08-12 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-GENOVESI-nYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ALBANY LOSES A PART OF ITS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Genovesi was something of a legend when this columnist
was first assigned to cover Albany nearly a dozen years ago.
Whenever there was talk, as often there was, about what was really
going on behind the scenes _ who owed what to whom and why, or who
hated whom and exactly how much _ his name invariably came up.
``Tony could tell you that,'' people would say, only to add, ``Of
course, he won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Genovesi rose, the way politicians used to, through the machine.
Before he was elected to the state assembly, he was a power broker
in Brooklyn, a macher in the Thomas Jefferson Democratic Club and a
protege of the infamous Meade Esposito. In those years, Genovesi
was the kind of man you turned to if you wanted a judgeship in the
borough, or a spot on the ballot, or if, instead, you just wanted
an opponent's nominating petitions thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   As the political strategist for Assembly Speaker Stanley Fink,
he later became a power player in Albany as well. From his post as
director of the Democratic Assembly Campaign Committee, he
determined who needed help from the party come election time. He
also decided who was loyal enough to the Democratic cause _ or,
more pertinently, to Fink _ actually to get it. The methods weren't
always pretty, but that wasn't what he aspired to.
</P>
<P>
   When he died on a slippery road in Dutchess County late Monday
night, Albany lost, if not a major figure, then an exemplary one,
and one that is not likely to be replaced any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   It has been decades since machine support has, on the national
scene, mattered as much as a telegenic smile, a good media adviser,
cash for television ads and a well-run polling operation. If there
is a symbol of the new age, it is not the smoke-filled room where
seasoned players call the shots.
</P>
<P>
   It is the conference room with the one-way mirror where
housewives, dentists and retirees air their pet peeves in focus
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The discreet knowledge of alliances, debts and lingering
hostilities that was so much a source of power to the
behind-the-scenes professionals of the past is now largely
irrelevant, replaced by a different kind of expertise: the ability
to read a poll or spin a story.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the transformation has been slower in coming, in part
because few outside state government seem to care much about what
happens there. Yet still, inexorably, it has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of district-by-district understanding of the state that
Genovesi spent a lifetime acquiring has less and less utility. In
Albany, as in Washington, the crucial battles are increasingly
fought over the airwaves with attack ads crafted by outside
consultants who would not know how to invoke the Wilson-Pakula rule
if their life depended on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gruff and beefy, Genovesi was in most ways just the opposite of
a slick, focus-grouped politician.
</P>
<P>
   More liberal than the Assembly district in Canarsie he inherited
from Fink in 1986, he was a resolute opponent of the death penalty
even when it was clearly a losing issue. When he did speak to
reporters, he was blunt and unsentimental. And though he was chary
with commentary, what he did say seemed, remarkably enough, to be
what he actually believed.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he took Fink's Assembly seat, it was widely
assumed that his political experience would make Genovesi a strong
contender to become Assembly speaker himself. After all, few in the
chamber knew better than he did the strengths _ and, perhaps more
significantly, the vulnerabilities _ of their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But Genovesi never did succeed in becoming the leader of the
Assembly and, in fact, saw his power wane even in Brooklyn. Twice,
he lost out to become the head of the borough's Democratic
organization. And for the last several years, he had been locked in
a nasty, mostly self-wounding battle with one of the men who beat
him, Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr., over everything from
candidate endorsements to patronage to judgeships.
</P>
<P>
   Among his colleagues, Genovesi's death was mourned mostly in
purely personal terms. But as his former allies and rivals took
turns praising him, they repeatedly invoked the very kind of
virtues that are themselves in the process of passing out of
political life: genuineness, humor and loyalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
