<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-LABOR-N     08-12 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC PACT MAJOR VICTORY FOR UNION, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By reaching a tentative agreement this week that would force
Bell Atlantic to guarantee its union workers job security _ even in
digital technologies only now being developed _ negotiators
representing 73,000 of the company's employees scored a significant
victory, experts in labor relations agreed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no consensus on whether these gains would have
major repercussions in other industries and how they might affect
Bell Atlantic in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced Tuesday, ended a two-day strike that
began after the old contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Sunday. The
company agreed to guarantee that all installation, maintenance and
repair jobs involving advanced data communications, including
access to the Internet, would go to union members.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Bronfenbrenner, the director of labor education research at
Cornell University, said that workers in other industries were
likely to be inspired by Bell Atlantic's agreement to phase out a
nonunion customer service operation in Virginia _ one of the key
provisions in the proposed contract.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bell Atlantic's customer service employees, many workers
deal with the public only over the telephone and are fearful that
their jobs could be reassigned to nonunion personnel in other
states with the flick of a switch, she said. ``This is just going
to add weight to workers who think that this is a fight worth
fighting,'' Bronfenbrenner said. ``Other employers are going to
say, `We have to think twice about whether the secret to corporate
success is eliminating good jobs.'''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Bell Atlantic's management had underestimated the
resolve of the union, the Communications Workers of America. ``The
company realized that if they were going to break the union's
commitment, it was going to take a long time,'' she said, ``and
they couldn't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey Keefe, a professor of labor relations at Rutgers
University, said that Bell Atlantic's situation was complicated
because it merged last year with Nynex, a company with a very
different approach to labor-management relations.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a crippling four-month strike in 1989, Nynex
adopted a conciliatory approach toward its labor force, making
concessions to its employees, like limits on forced overtime, that
were not matched by other telephone companies. After the merger,
other Bell Atlantic employees insisted on having such provisions
extended to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nynex was a pushover,'' said Herbert Northrup, professor
emeritus of management at the University of Pennsylvania, ``so what
you have is a forcing of a foreign culture onto the Bell Atlantic
people.'' He said that extending job protection to workers in new
forms of communications could well put Bell Atlantic at a
disadvantage because most of its competitors in the high-technology
sphere are not unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe pointed out that the proposed contract, which is subject
to ratification by the membership, extends only to the year 2000
and does not give the CWA the rights it sought to make it easier to
bring the 7,100 employees of Bell Atlantic's cellular phone unit
into the union fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a big victory today,'' he said, ``but whether
it really changes the relationship with management _ which is what
the union is after here _ I think that still remains open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
