<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SPEARFISHING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTIST DIVES INTO SPEARFISHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. _ By profession, Gerald Lim is a
mild-mannered dentist. When he isn't filling cavities, he has a
more-or-less secret life as the national spearfishing champion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being gored by his own spear, Lim successfully defended
his individual title recently after two days of competition at the
U.S. National Freediving Spearfishing Championships in the waters
off Kings Beach in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lim, Bill Ernst of Malibu and Rene Rojas of Anaheim _
representing the Great Los Angeles Council of Divers _ fended off
the competition to retain their national team spearfishing crown.
</P>
<P>
   But the understated Lim will tell you the honors are not like
winning other titles. When he lets others know he is the national
spearfishing champion, the response is usually short and succinct:
``The what?'' So Lim usually doesn't talk about it much, but
spearfishing is an abiding passion in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ocean) is the final frontier,'' said the Redlands
recreationist. ``It's as far away from civilization as you can
get.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lim's accomplishments are certainly not lost on the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no financial award and the sport is not widely known,
but among his peers it's a great honor,'' said competitive free
diver Terry Maas of Ventura, author of ``Blue Water Hunting and
Freediving.''
</P>
<P>
   Lim is now among an elite class of repeat winners of the
national title, which includes Maas, himself a four-time winner,
and Bill Ernst's brother, John.
</P>
<P>
   The annual spearfishing championships attracted more than 70 of
the country's best free divers _ anglers who hunt underwater sans
oxygen tanks, with only as much air as their lungs can hold _ to
compete individually and as part of 23 teams. Their dives usually
last from 90 seconds to 2{ minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the first day of the event, July 30, Lim speared seven fish _
four tautog, or blackfish, at about 10 pounds each, two 5-pound
bluefish, and a 13-pound striped bass _ for a total of 67 points.
Each fish speared and weighed in is worth a point, and one point is
awarded for each pound the fish weighs. There is a maximum of 16
points awarded per fish.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, Ernst had collected 66 points and Rojas had earned
65 points. The consistency of the three divers placed them high in
the first round's standings, yet a couple of divers had higher
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The trio relied on advance scouting for the second day of
competition. Prior to the event, the three had flown back early and
had scouted the area extensively. Knowing that most of the diving
pressure would be near shore, the trio focused much of their
scouting on offshore reefs and humps, some as far as 2{ miles from
off the beach. Since all competitors must either swim or kayak to
their hunting areas, most spearfishermen don't travel that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first day, we tried to hit the stuff everyone else was
going to hit and save the outside for the second day. That really
paid off,'' Lim said. ``When you shoot one striper in a school, the
whole school is gone. Most of the stuff near shore gets hammered
very quickly, and things get much tougher the second day.'' The
second day the spearfishers went to their more distant spots, and
on Lim's first dive he shot a 28-pound striper. While bringing it
back to his kayak, he noticed a bluefish was staying with the
speared fish. Lim quickly got another speargun and hit the bluefish
with what what he thought was a kill shot.
</P>
<P>
   While collecting the bluefish, however, it suddenly began
thrashing wildly and Lim soon found his own spear driven deeply
into his thigh.
</P>
<P>
   One wouldn't think that someone who performs root canals for a
living would get queasy over the sight of blood, but Lim didn't
want look at the wound for fear of passing out. He remained at the
surface to make sure he hadn't cut the femoral artery. He didn't
get weak, the wound eventually stopped bleeding and Lim speared
another striper, four more tautog and a bonito, finishing the day
with an individual best 77-point tally.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates did nearly as well. The trio finished the two-day
event July 31 with 377 points, nearly 100 points ahead of their
nearest competitors because of a smart strategy. The team has since
been selected to represent the United States in the world
spearfishing championship, to be held Sept. 17-20 in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Daily News Outdoors Editor Brett Pauly contributed to this
article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
