<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: GIANTS THRIVE AT SPARTAN CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Two years ago, taking a cue from the New York
Giants who were about to make SUNY-Albany their summer training
camp home, New York Knicks officials took a tour of the
university's campus and athletic facilities. The Knicks were
considering these serene Hudson Valley grounds as the site for the
team's fall training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Knicks returned to Charleston, S.C., where they
had trained previously.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in the Knicks' decision not to relocate to Albany: no
Albany-area hotel had the 12 to 15 luxury suites the team needed to
house its players.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants wrap up their third training camp at SUNY-Albany
next week, nearly 85 players, including stars such as Jason Sehorn
and Danny Kanell, will move their belongings out of the dorm rooms
they have called home since July 24.
</P>
<P>
   They will say goodbye to the cafeteria where they have served
themselves three times a day. They will clear out of the gymnasium
that has been converted to a spartan locker room, and leave behind
the classrooms where they have met until 10 p.m. almost every night
going over films and diagrams in their playbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one complains about the dorms,'' said the Giants' backup
quarterback, Kent Graham, who has been to seven National Football
League camps with three teams. ``We know the coaches never want to
put you up in too much luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, it's all irrelevant anyway. We're never in that room.
All we need is a good mattress. That's football.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dunn is the Giants' strength and conditioning coach,
affectionately nicknamed, Mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camp never was supposed to be plush,'' Dunn, a former player
now with his fourth NFL team as a coach, said Wednesday. ``Ever
since you were a kid going to football camp, you knew it was
supposed to be like boot camp in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the mind-set that sets football players apart from their
sporting brethren.
</P>
<P>
   The players' parking lot has as many pickup trucks as it has
Porsches, pranks abound as if these millionaires were high
schoolers, and prima donnas are browbeaten back into the sameness
of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Overdressing is forbidden, T-shirts and shorts are the
off-the-field uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies have to sing for veterans whenever asked and they also
carry the veterans' equipment off the practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   Being out of shape is very much noticed and denounced. Being
injured does not excuse you from practice _ most likely the team
trainers will have you riding a stationary bike and doing
calisthenics on the sideline anyway.
</P>
<P>
   No one is above the team _ just like everyone gets the same size
dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants came to Albany last year, coach Jim Fassel
noticed that the layout of the makeshift locker room separated the
defensive players from the offensive players, with some players
seeming to get positions of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel had the lockers rearranged, going end to end numerically
by uniform number.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first job as a coach was high school baseball,'' Fassel
said this week, looking back some 24 years. ``I decided pretty
quick I wasn't cut out to coach anything but football. I was too
much of a tyrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel smiled, as if he liked that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is much more of a team concept game,'' he said.
``Baseball and basketball, they're more individual. Football teams
have a bunker mentality. These guys have to rely on one another or
they could get killed. It breeds a certain camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last week, the rookie quarterback Ben Anderson has been
thinking of camaraderie whenever he looks at his blue right foot.
Anderson's foot has been blue since Graham put some combination of
colorless, odorless _ and apparently harmless _ bluish purple dye
in Anderson's sock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wear that sock and once you sweat, it turns your foot blue
for a week to 10 days,'' Anderson said. ``Kent said they did it to
him as a rookie. I walk through the locker room now and everyone
screams and yells that I've got the bubonic plague.''
</P>
<P>
   If that were Anderson's only worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never put my helmet on without checking it first,''
Anderson said. ``They'll put vaseline in it. Or sometimes, mushed
up bananas.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's linebacker Scott Galyon. At lunch one day this
month, his fellow linebackers Pete Monty and Ryan Phillips encased
Galyon's entire pickup truck in a sort of industrial-strength saran
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Galyon had to cut his way into the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Camaraderie. It's what makes the players put on a talent show
every year. Last year, along with the usual song-and-dance acts,
there was a videotape titled: What do the kickers really do during
practice?
</P>
<P>
   It showed kickers Brad Daluiso and Brad Maynard sneaking away
from the SUNY-Albany campus, their spikes clattering across the
street as they headed for a nearby bar. There, the videotape showed
Daluiso and Maynard in their Giants' uniforms playing pool with
cigarettes dangling from their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, really funny,'' Fassel said later, though one wondered
if he meant it.
</P>
<P>
   Daluiso said: ``I'm not positive, but I think I heard some guys
in the room saying to each other: `That's a joke, right?''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0519 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
