r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CAMP-AZR &LR;      08-12 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CAMP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS' CAMP ENDS AS NO STINKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin used his first
meeting of training camp to inform his team there would be a
skunk-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   He told the players that he wouldn't tolerate a similar prank of
a year ago, when then-rookie quarterback Jake Plummer carried a
maimed skunk into his dormitory room, thinking it was a plastic bag
filled with chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used the excuse that (pranks) were part of tradition,''
center Aaron Graham said. ``Coach said as far as he was concerned,
much of the tradition around here stinks, so let's get rid of that.
I agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the club breaks training camp this morning and returns
to the Valley, the worst punishment rookies endured was
fourth-round pick Michael Pittman having his clothes tied together
and free-agent wide receiver Kevin Drake finding ink in his
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, animal activists were upset with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they might have been part of the record crowds that
attended workouts at Northern Arizona, including 7,000 for a
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to see that type of turnout,'' wide receiver Rob
Moore said. '`But it tells you what expectations are.''
</P>
<P>
   Other camp highlights:
</P>
<P>
   The Eric Swann-Simeon Rice tiff, which ended with Tobin flexing
his muscles.
</P>
<P>
   While first-round draft pick Andre Wadsworth held out, rookies
Corey Chavous, Pat Tillman, Anthony Clement and Terry Hardy showed
they can provide immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries depleted the cornerback and wide receiver positions.
</P>
<P>
   The ``West Coast'' offense, installed by new offensive
coordinator Marc Trestman, has a tremendous upside, but count on
growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate tough guy
</P>
<P>
   Swann walked out of practice July 31 because he didn't think
Rice, who missed the workout because of asthmatic bronchitis, was
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin had long talks with both players and addressed the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled it,'' Moore said of Tobin. ``It wasn't an issue you
had to whisper about. He said, `This is the way it's going to be.'
' &QL; 
Baby boomers
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis doesn't think first-round
pick Wadsworth's 21-day holdout has been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This staff doesn't waste time on things it can't control,''
McGinnis said. ``We have enough to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So while Wadsworth did his media blitz _ was there any Valley
radio talk show or TV sportscast he wasn't heard on this week? _
and contemplated furthering his education, other rookies came up
big.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, a converted cornerback, and Tillman, a former
linebacker, were expected to have a rough transition but look as if
they'll be starting safeties in 1999, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, a second-round draft pick from Vanderbilt, is
second-team strong safety and cornerback. Tillman, a seventh-round
pick from Arizona State, is the No. 2 free safety and nickel
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely pleased with Pat, and Corey is what we thought
he was and continues to improve,'' McGinnis said. ``Moving from
cornerback to safety, where (Chavous) sees the field from a
different perspective and makes the calls, is a bigger jump than
what Pat is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement, a second-round pick from Southwestern Louisiana, is
further along than team officials expected and is pushing James
Dexter for the starting right offensive tackle job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going to be a great one,'' veteran center Mike Devlin
said. '`He's so strong. You're not going to overpower the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, a fifth-round pick from Southern Mississippi, has shown
no effects from a shoulder injury and has been a big surprise. &QL; 
Thin and thinner
</P>
<P>
   First, the Cardinals lost wide receivers Anthony Edwards (knee)
and Chad Carpenter (broken wrist). Then, this past week, Moore
(groin), Eric Metcalf (back) and Fred Brock (groin) missed
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerback spot also has been hit. Starter Tom Knight
remains out because of a shoulder injury and backups J.J. McCleskey
(hamstring) and Ty Howard (knee) are recovering. &QL; 
Learning on the run
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has struggled at times trying to execute the West Coast
offense, but he's not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we all grasp exactly what we are supposed to do, it'll
be a little rough, but not as rough as people think,'' Moore said.
``We have so many weapons. The sky's the limit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
