</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRE'S TUNE FALLS FLAT WITH GREED WEARY FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Hey, Andre. You're losing it.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look around. Sniff the air. Understand that no one cares
about your principles, no one thinks you deserve more cake than
Ryan Leaf, no one believes you're willing to spend another year in
a Tallahassee dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   So, you might win in the long run. You might be a cornerstone of
the franchise, worthy of the comparisons you so easily evoke. And
maybe you'll prevail in this torturous end game, forcing reform in
a stodgy organization.
</P>
<P>
   But you're losing the people. The same crowd that stood up and
cheered when your name was announced on draft day. The same group
melted by your charisma and geeked by your enthusiasm, some of whom
seemed willing to offer up their daughters for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same crowd that might boo your backside when you
finally put on the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, you know I'm with you on this subject of creative
financing. It's no coincidence that two of the old-guard franchises
_ the Cardinals and the Bears _ have high-profile holdouts. As the
NFL roars into the new millennium, as $17 billion worth of
television revenue trickles down from the top, you can no longer
ignore concepts such as voidable years and expect impact rookies to
waltz into camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals need to change this policy. For the sake of the
present and the future.
</P>
<P>
   But this has nothing to do with right or wrong. This is about
perception. And for the first time in memory, the majority is not
outraged by penny-pinching ownership.
</P>
<P>
   They are screaming at you, Andre.
</P>
<P>
   You are a smart, affable guy, which is why you've spent most of
the week with a phone attached to your ear, spending more time on
talk radio than Rush Limbaugh. But as much as you plead your case,
insisting you couldn't live with yourself if you settled for a $10
million bonus that locked you into a six-year contract, you're
losing it.
</P>
<P>
   Convictions? Try telling that to the guy sizzling in the stands,
wondering if he can afford another beer without blowing the rent.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are simply tired of the greed. Tired of Kevin Garnett
turning down $104 million, holding out for another $21 million,
then insisting it wasn't about the money. Tired of Keith Tkachuk.
Tired of Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Even the old-timers who always bristle at big money will concede
to performance. No one blinked when Terrell Davis walked off with a
$56 million contract, a just reward for winning a Super Bowl. No
one cares when Michael Jordan earns $100 million a year, a guy with
six championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   It's the money demanded by pups that drives people nuts,
especially when holding firm to a belief foreign to the rest of us:
that you deserve a gold mine before accomplishing anything.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing festers quicker than greed, and this goes beyond the
annual dance of NFL holdouts. There are people convinced the NBA
lockout will not last, citing the mind-set of today's player. There
is no principle, no sense of history, no real solidarity. Just a
bunch of wealthy, skewed kids with big posses and fast cars, a
group not willing to sacrifice a single paycheck. Don't think David
Stern and the rest of the owners don't know as much.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think the Cardinals fail to realize this shift in
momentum. They know you're starting to twist in the wind. They
don't believe you have any intentions of going back to school. They
are playing a game of chicken, seeing how deep your convictions
really are.
</P>
<P>
   As I'm writing this, the phone rings. It's Chuck from Phoenix.
He wants to know how to get in touch with you, and I'm curious why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to come to work with me, see what it's like to work
50 hours a week,'' he says. ``He's complaining about an $8 million
signing bonus? It'll take me 200 years to make that much. And I
don't see myself living that long.''
</P>
<P>
   See what I mean, Andre? And, hey, good luck. Especially if you
resemble Bruce Smith only in mouth. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
