<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-IOANE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOANE MAKING MARK WITH SUN DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYSON, Ariz. _ The first time Junior Ioane saw football pads,
he thought, ``Now what?''
</P>
<P>
   As all the other high school freshmen headed to the practice
field, Ioane sat at his locker, ashamed. How do you put these on?
He was from Samoa, where rugby is the sport of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too shy to ask,'' the Arizona State defensive tackle
said. ``I was the last one there when this one kid came in late. I
was planning to go home, and I finally got the nerve to get help.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew he would develop into one of Utah's top high school
players and become one of Arizona State's most coveted recruits?
When the Sun Devils begin drills today at Camp Tontozona, the
6-foot-5, 290-pound Ioane (pronounced Ee-oh-WAH-nay) will be vying
for a starting job on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The move from Utah, where he has lived since he was 13, has been
difficult, but he is adjusting. He has been responding to audibles
all his life.
</P>
<P>
   He was reared since the age of 3 by his uncle, Pula Pitone, and
his wife, Phyllis Ioane, a Utah-raised missionary for the Church of
Latter Day Saints who was living in Samoa. His birth mother moved
to the United States when Ioane was an infant to seek a better
life.
</P>
<P>
   After Pitone died in 1985, his wife remained in Samoa for
several years before moving to Utah with her four adopted children.
</P>
<P>
   For Junior Ioane, it was culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   He used to love to play in the warm rain in Apia. He tried it in
Utah, and it was freezing.
</P>
<P>
   And he was stunned by the behavior of his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home, we have a lot respect for parents and teachers,''
he said. ``We don't talk back. We get hit if we do. . . . And I was
the only Samoan kid in town. Everywhere I'd go, people would look
at me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough road for someone who dislikes being the center of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood English, but he really didn't speak it,''
Phyllis Ioane said. ``And he was so shy, he was worried he might
say something wrong. It was difficult because everything was so
different. The food, the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   When football coaches at North Sampete High School spotted
Ioane, they sought him out for the football team. Little did they
know he knew nothing about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it mattered. His rugby experience made him comfortable
with the sport. He was a standout offensive and defensive lineman
and recruited heavily his senior season. When he couldn't arrive at
the necessary ACT score required by the major colleges courting
him, he went to nearby Snow College.
</P>
<P>
   He excelled there and was named a first-team All-American after
collecting 30 solo tackles, 21 assists and 11 sacks last season.
</P>
<P>
   Division I schools came calling again, and Ioane narrowed his
choices to ASU and Brigham Young. He was torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Defensive line coach) Kevin (Wolthausen) did an excellent
job,'' recruiting coordinator Robin Pflugrad said. ``Every chance
we could legally be there, Kevin was there. Coach Snyder went once,
and we took a couple of other coaches so Junior could get to know
our football family a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's so quiet, it's hard to get to know him and read
his personality. You really have to be yourself. We really tried to
let him understand that we care about him on and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Although BYU was closer and many of Ioane's friends were there,
ASU's coaches won him over.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he's adjusting. He did his first media interview, ever,
five days ago. He's adapting to the heat and getting beyond the
homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quiet, but once you get to know him, he jokes and kids
around,'' said Erik Flowers, Ioane's roommate and another highly
coveted junior college defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an adjustment, but now that I'm getting to know the
guys, it's better,'' he said. ``I've adjusted before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
