<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1334 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-ASSISTANT     08-12 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-ASSISTANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA'S TOMEY STILL SURVIVING STAFF SHUFFLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. _ More than two decades as a head football coach
is a lesson in survival, if not humility. Survivor Dick Tomey will
tell you there's really nothing complicated about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no geniuses in this business,'' Tomey said Wednesday
after he opened his 12th preseason camp at Cochise College as
Arizona's coach. ``That's proven every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, there are effective assistants and coordinators. They
are the stuff, the staff, of long-term success. Lose the good ones,
and you lose your job. Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey will begin the 1998 season with a very different staff
from last year. There are five changes.
</P>
<P>
   Dino Babers moves from running backs to Homer Smith's successor
as offensive coordinator. Former Hawaii head coach Bob Wagner takes
over the linebacking and defensive special-team duties.
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Washington offensive coordinator Jeff
Woodruff, the head coach at Tucson's Cholla High School last year,
will direct the running backs. Pete Alamar moves from inside
linebackers to tight ends. Marc Lunsford goes from tight ends to
director of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody have a flow chart and few name tags to go along
with the X's and O's?
</P>
<P>
   The staff shuffle is one of many as Arizona confronts a new
season. It's another element that makes the Wildcats such a wild
card in the Pacific 10 race.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of philosophy, personality and experience will go a long
way toward determing Arizona's identity. For now, it's a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   `It's new blood but an old perspective,'' said Babers, 37, whose
resume includes San Diego State, Purdue, Northern Arizona,
Nevada-Las Vegas, Hawaii and Arizona State. ``Coach Tomey is going
to give us our leeway, but certain things have to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the turnover with assistants or coordinators, I
think the team will line up and play according to the personality
of the head football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tomey's case, it appears to be the personality of a manager
who delegates authority freely and confidently.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, the confidence is rooted in the staff's
experience. In Smith, Tomey relied on an ex-boss whose approach to
offense was said to be one of the most creative in college
football. Smith retired for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In Wagner, Tomey brought in another former head coach. Wagner
was a defensive coordinator for Tomey before he succeeded his old
boss at Hawaii, where he spent 19 years and won the school's only
Western Athletic Conference title. Wagner was without a football
job and living in San Diego last year when Tomey hired him. He also
was a candidate for a job at Texas Christian.
</P>
<P>
   They know each other. Trust each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about being a good fit,'' said Tomey, who has been a
head coach for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, a former head coach as an assistant can
create problems. The new assistant has never given up the role and
the habits of a head coach. Suddenly, a stable staff becomes a
banana republic, with rumors of a locker room coup. Tomey knows the
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``On some staffs, egos get the best of each other,'' Tomey said.
``You see that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if ego can be separated from the task, Tomey said, a former
head coach or high-profile assistant can be invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain times when experience really matters on the
sideline and in the press box,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 through 1995, Tomey said, he encouraged Jim Young, a
former head coach at Arizona, Army and Purdue, to take on
additional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted Jim Young to be more involved in other areas''
he said. ``He just wasn't interested at that point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that kind of experience is invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   And pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   There wouldn't be survivors without it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
