<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MAYFAIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEAGUES GLAD TO SEE MAYFAIR'S GOOD FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ There have been bigger victories this season
than Billy Mayfair's win last weekend at the Buick Open. Few,
however, have been as popular among the players.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair gets that kind of respect because in the sometimes
pompous world of professional golf, the Scottsdale pro is truly a
good guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lucky (expletive),'' Scott Verplank quipped, slugging
Mayfair in the arm to express his affection in jocular fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you hit some guy in the head (on the eighth hole
Sunday), and the ball bounces back into the fairway. Then you chip
in from everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair does not miss his opportunity to return the good-natured
ribbing. ``Like you didn't, right?'' he countered with Verplank's
second-place finish at the Buick, which came on the strength of a
closing 64.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes as Mayfair sits in the locker room at Sahalee Country
Club, the site of this week's PGA Championship. One by one,
everyone stops by to pat Billy on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, man,'' said close friend Mark Calcavecchia, giving
Mayfair a hearty embrace. ``I called my mom Sunday night and told
her Billy won in a breeze. He made winning by 2 (shots) look
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade of well-wishers goes on _ Phil Mickelson; Tom Lehman;
Payne Stewart; Paul Azinger; Davis Love III, who is the defending
champ here this week. Finally, Mayfair's head doctor, Bob Rotello,
capped the congratulatory train with a few choice words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you so,'' he said to Mayfair with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Life has not always been so sweet for Billy Mayfair, Arizona's
favorite son who rose from the junior ranks to be a state champion
at Camelback High School and an All-American at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bob said I just needed to be patient when I was going
through that slump,'' said Mayfair, who was No. 2 on the money list
in 1995 before dipping to No. 55 in '96 and No. 79 in '97, when he
rallied from 150th place late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've won twice in one season (he earlier captured the
Nissan Open) for the second time in my career (he also won twice in
'95). My confidence is really high, and I think it's all because
the putting has come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair, whose unorthodox stroke with the flat stick occurs by
cutting the blade across the ball, also changed putters, although
not brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week I switched from a PING Pal 2, a putter I've used
most of my pro career, to a PING ZING 5KS,'' he said. ``It's a
little heavier, especially in the center point. I was having
trouble with eight-footers, and the heavier center really
stabilized my stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Stable pretty much sums up Mayfair, both in personality and his
play these days. He ranks 10th on the money list with $976,889.
He's also 10th in the standings for the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Buick was huge because I played so well coming
down the stretch,'' said Mayfair, who celebrated his 32nd birthday
last Thursday with the belated present on Sunday. ``Truthfully, I
couldn't breathe until I hit the green at (No.) 16.''
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time that Mayfair's wife, Tammy, had not
been present for one of his five career wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tammy's sister had a baby boy, and we decided that was pretty
important, too,'' said Mayfair, who is in his 10th season as a pro.
``But she met me here when I got off the flight late Sunday night,
and we celebrated.''
</P>
<P>
   The only cloud lately, he said, was the death of the Mayfairs'
close friend, Renay Appleby, the wife of Stuart. She was killed in
a bizarre accident three weeks ago in London. She was crushed
between a cab and a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that has ever hit me harder was Heather's
death,'' he said of the fraternal relationship he developed with
Heather Farr, the former LPGA star from Phoenix who died of
complications from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was different, because we knew Heather was sick. This
other just came out of the blue. Tammy and I are still in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair added that he felt it was a good thing that Appleby
decided to return this week for the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's hurting, but _ and it's better for him to say this
_ I know Renay would want him to get on with his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair also plans to keep pointing to the future, although he
discounts his chances for a strong showing in the PGA, where his
best finish has been a tie for fifth in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get over what just happened at the Buick and go
out and play the best I can,'' he said. ``But I'll be OK once we
get started (today).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
