<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-LAYOFFS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION WON'T FIGHT BOEING PLANS FOR ASSEMBLY WORK IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After last-minute negotiations Wednesday, Boeing's
largest union agreed not to fight the company's plans to set up 737
assembly operations in California in exchange for a promise from
Boeing to limit its monthly production rate there to no more than 5
airplanes a month, according to people familiar with the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also promised the machinists union that no layoffs would
occur in the Puget Sound area as a result of the California work at
least until its labor contract expires in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But separately, Boeing has already developed a tentative
timeline that managers could use if the company chooses to
implement layoffs as a result of cutbacks already announced.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest layoffs could occur in Boeing's commercial aircraft
division would be early December, according to the company's
1998-99 ``Redeployment Schedule,'' obtained by the
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing could choose, however, to forego the layoffs until after
the Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the machinists' union, reached late
Wednesday, was the final hurdle Boeing needed to clear in order to
announce Thursday that it will begin building next-generation 737s
this fall at its Douglas Products Division aircraft factory in Long
Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing promised that no local layoffs would result from
the new California assembly line, the company already has announced
that it anticipates some layoffs as part of its plan to reduce
employment by 18,000 to 28,000 by the end of next year. Boeing also
previously announced it will cut 12,000 jobs just from the
company's commercial aircraft division beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing employs about 238,000 people in 27 states. About 118,000
work for the commercial aircraft division, headquartered in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   The ``redeployment schedule'' outlines a tentative layoff
timeline for Boeing Commercial Airplane Group workers beginning
with 60-day warn notices being issued in October and layoffs
becoming effective the first week of December.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is required by law to issue ``warn'' notices to workers
60 days and 14 days before a layoff becomes effective.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives still have not specified exactly how many job
cuts will occur or where and no decisions have yet been made to
implement layoffs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing normally has a 4 percent to 5 percent attrition rate per
year, but it is too early to tell how many of the job cuts will
come from attrition or layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of the job cuts are expected to come from the
company's commercial aircraft division, other reductions could come
from further consolidation of Boeing operations throughout the
country, which the company also expects to announce today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wednesday's agreement between Boeing and the union
also included a promise from Boeing to keep fabrication of 737
airplane wings in the Puget Sound and fuselage sections in Wichita,
Kan., where they are currently built.
</P>
<P>
   The union was concerned that Boeing would try to move that work
to California or other locations.
</P>
<P>
   By next summer, Boeing plans to build the next-generation 737
airplanes at a rate of three a month in California and possibly
five a month by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Boeing will start by building its corporate Business
Jet version of the 737-700, but eventually the California assembly
line will be used to produce all versions of the next-generation
737s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials say the new assembly line is needed to ease
congestion at the company's overburdened aircraft factory in Renton
where 14 next-generation 737 airplanes are currently built each
month. Boeing plans to increase that rate to 21 a month in October.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached Wednesday was viewed as favoring Boeing, mainly
because the company's promise to limit the California production of
its 737s is only good until the current Machinists labor contract
expires in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnson, president of District Lodge 751 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers in
Seattle, was not available for comment Wednesday and a Boeing
official declined to discuss the meeting or Thursday's planned
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But a union representative, who spoke on the condition he not be
named, said the agreement was a ``win, win'' for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This keeps union jobs from being lost in Puget Sound,'' the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union had threatened to take legal action if
Boeing went ahead with plans to establish the assembly line in
California.
</P>
<P>
   But after weeks of negotiations, the union backed off and
officially signed off on the agreement late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been struggling for nearly a year to fill all its
commercial airplane orders on time _ mainly next-generation 737s _
because of parts shortages, lack of trained assembly workers, a
rapid increase in production rates and other manufacturing
bottlenecks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
