<HEADLINE>
ORLANDO COUNTING ON COACH  
 WANTS GRUDEN TO DELIVER ELUSIVE ARENA CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orlando Predators Coach Jay Gruden, still young and cocky enough
to run the scout team offense, likes to remind his star, Barry
Wagner, how he used to burn him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I complete them on the dime,'' Gruden says.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner occasionally still runs his mouth at Gruden, once his
biggest rival at Tampa Bay, but Gruden keeps the wide
receiver/defensive back in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can quiet him down,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden does that by showing off his four ArenaBowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   He won them in six years as the quarterback of the Tampa Bay
Storm, sometimes at the expense of its in-state rival.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner has six straight Ironman Awards for being the league's
best two-way player. He keeps them in his living room, where the
row of golden helmets hides his pet boa, Bo, who resides in a
glass-encased cage. But Wagner has no rings. Nada.
</P>
<P>
   It irritates Wagner and his teammates that they've been tagged
as the Buffalo Bills of the Arena league for losing three titles
games, including the ultimate gag in '94 at home to the underdog
Rattlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Predators believed so much in Gruden as the guy who could
bring them the jewelry, that last winter they gave the Nashville
Kats cash estimated between $50,000 and $100,000 and lineman Jerry
Sharp to pry him loose.
</P>
<P>
   The Kats were reluctant to let go of their offensive
coordinator, who, in Nashville's expansion season, helped the Kats
win 10 games and make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville liked Gruden so much that it originally asked for
Wagner, considered the Michael Jordan of Arena football. Then, the
Kats asked for offensive specialist Mac Cody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very fortunate in having the opportunity to even be
allowed to speak to Jay about a position,'' Predators President
Jack Youngblood said. ``Nashville had a contract with him, and they
didn't have to let me speak to him. It was out of professional
courtesy that they did. He certainly could not take a lateral
position with anybody in the league. If offered a head coaching
position, he could.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gruden was gone, back to Florida, this time at war for the
``other'' guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little awkward at first,'' he said. ``But they
welcomed me.''
</P>
<P>
   There was rumor that Gruden was even going to don the Predators
uniform. He's 30, only a year older than Wagner and three years
older than the average age of the players he inherited from Perry
Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He petitioned the league to play,'' Rattlers Coach Danny White
said. ``I was not involved in it, but the league wouldn't let him.
You can't be a coach and a player. They're afraid teams would hide
players by paying them a coach's salary.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Gruden has the Predators (10-5) rolling. They beat
Nashville in the first round. Now they'll try to beat the Rattlers
(11-4) for the second time this season at America West Arena. The
semifinal game is Saturday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gruden's last games as a player came against the Rattlers
in '96, when he led the Storm to a 55-54 semifinal win.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the '96 title game, I was pretty beat,'' he said. ``It
was my fourth title. Nashville gave me a call and offered a nice
package. I decided to give my body a break. I can still wing it a
little bit. But I enjoy what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   White calls Gruden one of the league's new wave of young
coaches, guys who spent several years as Arena players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, it was a tremendous acquisition for us,''
said Youngblood, the former Los Angeles Rams All-Pro. ``Not only
from the standpoint of a coach and a person, but for what is ahead
of us. You have to look down the road. Where can Jay Gruden go?
He's got so much ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder whether Gruden will end up in Oakland, where his
brother, Jon, is in his first year as head coach of the Raiders.
Jay, a former quarterback at Louisville, has had chances to join
NFL staffs. But he says he believes in the Arena league and where
it's going.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a fad, the league is in its 12th season, ESPN
has gone from showing games on tape delay to telecasting them live
and, for the first time, the title game will be shown on national
network TV, by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden's fairy tale would be complete by beating his former
team, the top-seeded Storm, in the championship game in Tampa on
Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get ahead of ourselves, but, yeah, that's a dream,''
Gruden said. ``That's the goal of any coach, winning the
championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
