<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-MOORE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA BOYS MAKING NAMES IN GYMNASTICS  
 MOORE IS HEADED FOR U.S. CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The best-kept secret in Arizona gymnastics is not some
new twist or turn, or a preteen being able to float through the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing that complex. This is simple: There are young male
gymnasts who are making as big of a splash in the sport as their
female counterparts, who get the bulk of the publicity at most
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Cody Moore is a twisting, turning, jumping example of just that.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 17, one of the the top teenage gymnasts in the country,
will carry his No. 1 national ranking into next week's U.S.
Gymnastics Championships in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be competing in the 17-and-under Junior division. His best
event is the pommel horse, and he hopes his effort there will
springboard him to the top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   The top 12 finishers in both the Seniors and Juniors will make
the international traveling team, and from that group, the 2000
Olympians will be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting a good meet,'' said Moore, who will be a senior
at Horizon High School. ``I think I can finish in the top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who competes for the Arizona Sunrays, and the other top
juniors in the country compete in the preliminary and event finals
Wednesday. Finals will be next Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   While this is seen as a major step toward the next Olympics,
that won't be on Moore's mind in Indianapolis. Thinking about that
pressure is fodder for another time. Now he just wants to
concentrate on being in top form next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of time and practice (to get to this point),''
said Moore, who also plays golf and hockey while maintaining a 4.0
grade-point average. ``But it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it takes male gymnasts longer to reach their
full potential, it's usually the females who get the most
recognition. But they get their payback if they stick with the
sport because they are usually able to compete longer.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, boys seem to stick with the sport longer than girls,
although Brian Robinson, Moore's coach, said that there has been a
drop-off in the number of boys competing nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of notice can be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get frustrated because of that,'' he said. ``You never
see a large number of people around. You have to love the sport. I
just started out liking it and never stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymnastics in the Valley suffered a jolt five years ago when
Arizona State University demoted the sport to club status. That
just added to the theory that men's gymnastics was on a lower rung.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Witenstein, the owner of the Sunrays club, which has about
1,500 members, said there are hundreds of boys involved in the
sport at his gym. And top-notch performers, such as Moore, usually
don't hit their peak until their early 20s. ``These are guys who
could be doing other sports, as well,'' Witenstein said. ``We're
proud of him. He has a good shot at winning.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
