<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LOADED FOR PAC-10  
 NEW PLAYERS EX PECTED TO FILL HOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It says something about the respect UCLA commands _ or the
questionable judgment of Pac-10 media members _ that the Bruins
were picked to finish first in the conference despite losing seven
defensive starters and their top tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great, that's exciting,'' Coach Bob Toledo said.
``We're looking forward to it. Our players have a great attitude.
They're enthusiastic, and this adds fuel to the fire. They accept
challenges. And I don't mind it. I just hope to be ending up
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who won their last 10 games, including a Cotton Bowl
victory against Texas A&AMP;M, edged ASU in the preseason poll by three
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Cade McNown had a lot to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 left-hander led the nation in pass efficiency, and
his 168.6 rating was the best in conference history. The Bruins are
promoting him as a Heisman Trophy candidate. He will square off
against another one, Ricky Williams, in UCLA's opener against
Texas, a team it trounced last season, 66-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be mad as hell,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA must replace three key offensive players: running back Skip
Hicks, tackle Chad Overhauser and wide receiver Jim McElroy. Hicks
and McElroy combined for 37 touchdowns last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks' backups, Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown, will have shots
at the starting job, but don't be surprised if Toledo fills several
holes with younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Highly recruited tailback DeShaun Foster is among four true
freshmen who will be considered for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're physically capable and mature enough, there's no
reason not to do it,'' Toledo said. ``In this day and age, with the
lack of (scholarships), freshmen have to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though UCLA lost Overhauser and left guard Chad Sauter,
some believe the Bruins' line could be even better, thanks to the
return of Kris Farris (left tackle), Shawn Stuart (center) and Andy
Meyers (right guard).
</P>
<P>
   The defense was hit harder. Among those gone is defensive
coordinator Rocky Long. He was replaced by Nick Aliotti, who came
from the NFL's St. Louis Rams and also was behind the ``Gang
Green'' defense that helped Oregon win a conference title in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have many holes to fill, including those created by
linebacker Brian Willmer and safety Shaun Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo believes his line could be more imposing than last
season. Starter Kenyon Coleman has added about 15 pounds since last
season, and junior Pete Holland looked solid in the spring, Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brendon Ayanbadejo, who had 15 tackles for losses as a junior,
returns at outside linebacker and should receive national
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot to replace,'' Toledo said. ``But I feel good
about what we have to work with.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
