<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDMAN GIVEN OK TO PLAY IN '98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 and BECKY GRUHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYSON _ Safety  &UR; Mitchell Freedman successfully completed his
summer school course work and is academically eligible to compete
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be on the bus,'' Arizona State Coach  &UR; Bruce Snyder said
before the team left for Camp Tontozona on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Marlon Farlow, receiver  &UR; Ricky Boyer and
linebacker  &UR; Larry
 &UR; Johnson did not make the trip. ASU does not know yet about those
players' eligibility, and they are not allowed to attend camp until
their records are approved.
</P>
<P>
   They could come to camp later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman's eligibility is a relief to a defense that returns
only one other starter, cornerback  &UR; Courtney Jackson, in the
secondary. Freedman was an all-Pac-10 pick last season. &QL; 
Decisions, decisions
</P>
<P>
   Former Mesa Mountain View High School star  &UR; Todd Heap couldn't
bear the thought of redshirting his first year at ASU, being
confined to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really been on the sideline much in the last three
years, so I didn't really know what I'd do if I was there,'' the
1997 ``Arizona Republic'' Class 5A football Player of the Year
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the freshman has thought plenty about skipping two full
seasons with the Sun Devils in order to complete a Mormon mission.
</P>
<P>
   When Heap signed, he made it clear to the coaching staff that he
intended to take a two-year vacation from football in order to
concentrate on his religious obligations. Heap originally planned
to take the break during what would have been his sophomore and
junior seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after whispers have circulated that he could see
substantial playing time at tight end, Heap isn't so quick to etch
his future plans in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to focus on having a good year here,'' Heap said.
``I'm focusing on this year, and then we'll go from there.'' &QL; 
Sometimes, scales do lie &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman offensive lineman  &UR; Scott Peters said he didn't
realize the importance of conditioning during his first season with
the Sun Devils. Peters didn't figure out he wasn't staying in
proper shape until the spring game, where, he said, his lack of
conditioning led to a disappointing performance.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Peters began to make changes. He spent the entire
summer working out with ASU strength coach  &UR; Rich Wenner to increase
his endurance. The 6-foot-3 Peters, who appears much slimmer than a
year ago, said he didn't lose weight, but rather ``moved it around
a little.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Wenner got on me pretty good,'' said Peters, who weighs
315 pounds. ``The running did it for me, the heat really takes it
off you. And lifting just transferred the weight to better
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters has more upper-body strength and said his legs also feel
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely learned my lesson,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
