<HEADLINE>
CHANGES IN THE AIR AT NAU  
 NEWCOMERS ABOUND WITH LUMBERJACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northern Arizona will have to rework a familiar phrase. The
Lumberjacks are hoping that unfamiliarity breeds success.
</P>
<P>
   First-year Coach Jerome Souers welcomes 85 players to today's
first practice, but 41 of them are new to the program. Included in
that number are 16 scholarship freshmen and 14 transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Souers was the defensive coordinator for Big Sky rival Montana
for 12 years. He inherits a team that went a disappointing 6-5 last
season after a 9-3 mark the previous year under former Coach Steve
Axman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special opportunity,'' Souers said. ``I think there
is a chance to develop a tremendous program and build on the
successes they have already had here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are eight starters returning, four each on offense and
defense. Headlining the offense is quarterback Travis Brown of
Phoenix, who was a finalist for the 1997 Walter Payton Award.
Defensively, linebackers Jake Crissup and Terrance Petty,
all-conference selections last season, return.
</P>
<P>
   One player who was expected to be a big contributor this season,
defensive end Nick Petrucci, has not fully recovered from a knee
injury suffered in the 10th game last season and will sit out the
season. NAU is expected to petition the NCAA for a sixth season of
eligibility for Petrucci.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks will hold two-a-day workouts through Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything will be new around the field. As Souers and
his staff puts in their system, working with the large group of
newcomers, a few other things will change, as well. In the morning
sessions, the team will be split into two groups to allow players
more time to learn the system and get in more repetitions. The
entire squad will be together for the afternoon practices.
</P>
<P>
   Services for former player &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services are scheduled for 1 p.m. Friday in Tucson's
Bring Funeral Home for David Couture, 23, a former NAU player who
was killed in a skydiving accident Sunday in Pierce County, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   He started all 11 games at defensive end last fall and was named
the school's Golden Eagle Scholar-Athlete of the Year, NAU's
highest student-athlete award.
</P>
<P>
   With a degree in mechanical engineering, he had accepted a
position with Boeing in Everett, Wash. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
