<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEIVER MCDANIEL HAS WILDCATS TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. Some of Arizona's highest expectations for the
1998 football season have surrounded wide receiver  &UR; Jeremy
McDaniel, a redshirt last year beacuse of a thigh injury.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday morning's opening practice, there were 10 reasons
for all the talk.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel, a 6-foot-1, 194 pound senior, caught 10 passes. One
was a beautful reception of a tipped ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of 1996, he was the best receiver in the Pac-10,''
Coach
 &UR; Dick Tomey said of McDaniel, who is best remembered for 14
receptions and 283 yards in a four-overtime game against
California.
</P>
<P>
   UA coaches say McDaniel has improved from 1996. One reason is
off-season work against Wildcats cornerback  &UR; Chris McAlister, a
preseason All-American. &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   A full complement of 106 players is expected in camp today.
Nineteen players missed Wednesday morning's opener at Cochise
College. They were still in Tucson for final exams.
</P>
<P>
   The first practice in pads is scheduled for Saturday. Until
there is some hittiing, Tomey said it will be difficult to make any
solid judgments about some areas of concern along the offensive and
defensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   Junior tailback  &UR; Trung Canidate, a starter last season from
Central High School, will miss at least the first few days of camp.
His right foot is still in cast. He underwent off-season surgery
for a stress fracture. The cast is scheduled to be removed Friday,
when physicians hope to determine if the fracture has mended.
 &UR; Kelvin
 &UR; Eafon is the probable starter if Canidate can't play.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister, on the possibility that he'll see double duty as a
receiver: ``The  &UR; Charles Woodson era would soon disappear.''
Woodson turned double duty at Michigan last season into the Heisman
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   New offensive coordinator  &UR; Dino Babers, on whether he will use
McAlister at receiver: ``Maybe by the 12th game.''
</P>
<P>
   At the cornerback spot opposite of the much-hyped McAlister,
there is  &UR; Kelvin Hunter, who plans to play with a metal plate and
nine screws in an ankle that was broken during last year's
Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey has sophomore  &UR; Bruce Wiggins penciled in as starting
center. At backup?  &UR; Steven Grace, a redshirt freshman last year who
already is listed at starting left guard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2348EDT &QL; 
