<DOCNO> NYT19980812.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-GROWERS-BEWARE-     08-12 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-GROWERS-BEWARE-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES GONE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By FIONA ORTIZ, with SERGIO R. BUSTOS in Miami 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GUATEMALA CITY _ Roberto Castaneda exported an average of 40,000
flats of luscious raspberries to the United States each year,
fetching prices of up to US$30 per flat. He says he and other
raspberry farmers were exporting 1.5 million trays a year, with 80
percent bound for the U.S. market. But the good times ended last
year when U.S. authorities found a parasite called cyclospora, and
traced it to Guatemala.
 &HT;    The parasite sickened more than 1,000 people in the United
States and Canada with diarrhea.
 &HT;    With U.S. supermarkets rushing to cancel orders, Guatemalan
raspberry farmers were forced to suspend exports for four months in
mid-1997. The suspension was followed by a ban earlier this year by
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA). The two actions
devastated Guatemalan growers.
 &HT;    ``After two seasons without exporting, a lot of people got out
of the business for good,'' says Castaneda, president of a growers
organization called the Guatemala Berry Commission. At least 20
farmers went out of business, while others abandoned the U.S.
market in search of buyers in Europe, he says.
 &HT;    Guatemala was not the only country censured by U.S. authorities
for exporting tainted food. Last year, Mexican strawberry growers
were blamed for a breakout of hepatitis in five U.S. states. And,
in 1992, a case of Histamime poisoning involving 74 people on the
U.S. East Coast was traced back to Ecuadorean fishermen who
exported fresh tuna.
 &HT;    The public health concerns over imported food safety have
prompted a political furor in the United States. And the furor
isn't showing any signs of disappearing. In June, U.S. Senator John
Dingell, of Michigan, introduced a bill in Congress that will give
the FDA more authority to inspect food products, slap a $20 charge
on all food imports and require ``country-of-origin'' labeling on
all imported food products. The bill _ The Imported Food Safety Act
of 1998 _ has 15 co-sponsors. This summer, Congress is holding
hearings, with one specifically focusing on Central American
raspberry exports.
 &HT;    ``American consumers are being used as guinea pigs,'' Dingell
recently told Congress in introducing his bill. The bill was
prompted by a recent U.S. General Accounting Office study that
found that less than 2 percent of all food products imported into
the United States were ever inspected or tested by FDA officials.
 &HT;    For Latin American farmers, who count on the U.S. market to
receive their exported array of food products, the harsher line
being taken threatens to hurt sales of fresh fruits and fresh
vegetables. Over the last five years, the volume of imported food
has doubled into the United States. Last year, the United States
imported more than 38 percent of the fresh fruit and more than 12
percent of fresh vegetables consumed nationwide. U.S. government
figures show that Latin America and the Caribbean supplies 100
percent of all banana imports and 80 percent of all fresh fruit
imports.
 &HT;    Since being singled out for their tainted raspberries,
Guatemalan growers have promised to improve sanitation standards by
installing biological water filters, establishing a coding system
to identify flats of raspberries and insisting that raspberry
workers wash their hands more often. But the efforts are not enough
for U.S. authorities who have yet to lift the ban on Guatemalan
raspberries.
 &HT;    Ironically, it was the U.S. government in 1991 _ through the
Agency for International Development (AID) _ that helped nurture
the growth of the lucrative Guatemalan raspberry business. Growing
the fruit was touted as a way for Guatemala to diversify its
coffee-dependent agriculture industry and to satisfy American
demand for off-season raspberries.
 &HT;    The Guatemalan case is problematic because there are no lab
tests to find cyclospora on fruit. Also, nobody knows if the
parasite comes from the dirty hands of raspberry workers in packing
plants, contaminated irrigation water or some other source.
 &HT;    ``A lot of information is not known,'' says Carl Reynolds, an
FDA official.
 &HT;    Guatemalan farmers insist there is no definitive proof the bug
is on their raspberries. They say the cyclospora scare was fueled
by U.S. and Chilean farmers who could not compete with the
Guatemala raspberry boom. They say slim scientific evidence is
being used as a political trade barrier.
 &HT;    ``This measure by the U.S. will boomerang, because when they
begin to demand such minute standards, they will have to apply them
in their own territory,'' says Ricardo Santa Cruz, of Guatemala's
Association of Exporters of Non-Traditional Products.
 &HT;    Today, despite being dejected and disgruntled with U.S.
authorities, Guatemalan growers are trying to meet FDA demands.
Guatemalan Agriculture Minister Mariano Ventura has set up a joint
government-business committee to inspect all farms using a rigorous
point system, examining everything from water quality to packing
houses. The growers are also setting up a numbering system for
every flat of berries to make sure inspectors can trace any
outbreak back to a specific grower.
 &HT;    Back on Castaneda's 26-acre farm, Planessa, near the colonial
town of Antiqua, he has installed filters _ at a cost of $7,000 _
to screen parasites out of water used on the farm. Raspberry
sorters in his plant wear hair nets, dusters and masks, and a
monitor logs every time a workers goes to the bathroom and washes
their hands. The new procedures and equipment raised operating
costs by 15 percent, he says.
 &HT;    Other growers balk at the costs, and are waiting to see whether
Castaneda's filters do the trick before they install their own.
Castaneda says a dozen growers will be certified to export in 1999,
but it remains to be seen whether they can recapture the lost
market.
 &HT;    ``The hardest part is to recover the image for our
raspberries,'' he says.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
