<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-CALLAWAY-AZR &LR;      08-12 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-CALLAWAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEEL COMES BACK AT CALLAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Callaway Golf went back to the future on
Wednesday, announcing its new Big Bertha ``Steelhead'' line of
woods at the PGA Championship. The California-based club
manufacturer hopes the club will turn around a struggling market
that has sent Callaway stock plunging in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelhead, which is made from old-fashioned steel, features
significant weighting in the bottom of the club and a new ``Hawk
Eye'' sole plate. The club is a departure from titanium, the metal
that has dominated the market for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The new line is an obvious move to regain sales Callaway has
lost to smaller, shallow-faced woods made by Orlimar and Tight
Lies. Both rely on a low center of gravity like the Steelhead, but
the Steelhead is 33 percent larger, a feature that Callaway claims
allows the average golfer more latitude on mishits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a reasonably high respect for the competition, but I
take exception to their claim that `oversized is overrated,' ''
said company founder Ely Callaway, pointing out that half of the
woods used in professional golf are made by his company, and
another 30 percent of the market is dominated by other oversize
manufacturers, according to the Darrell Survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the shallow-faced club is a basic design flaw, and we
don't build flaws into our clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway said his company will continue to manufacture the Big
Bertha titanium woods, but that the Steelhead will replace its
Warbird line.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelhead also is more reasonably priced. The Big Bertha
woods cost between $300 and $500; the new line will retail in the
$250 to $275 range.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Dye, company president and chief executive officer, said
the Steelhead will boost sales, which were down to $410 million
during the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been under some level of assault because our stock moved
from the high 20s to the low teens,'' Dye said.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Golf trotted out its stable of stars for the
announcement, including Colin Montgomerie, Paul Azinger and John
Daly, who stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed my driver (on Tuesday) and gave it to a little fellow
on the eighth hole (at Sahalee Country Club),'' Daly reported.
``Goodbye, titanium; hello, steel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelhead fairway woods go on sale today in 52 countries,
although the driver will not be available until October. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-98 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
