<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL HELPS PARALYZED TEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Thanks to one huge benefactor, a Cardinals
defensive lineman, 17-year-old B.J. Carlson is free again to roam
the beautiful piney countryside around here.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 14, 1996, the first day of school, a bus carrying 32
kids rolled on its way to Sinagua High School. All 32 were injured,
with Carlson being one of the most severely injured. Ever since, he
has been a paraplegic and needs a wheelchair to get around.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lineman, who is known for his part in several
charitable activities but requested that his name be withheld, has
presented Carlson with a three-wheel, hand-controlled mountain bike
at no small expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Christian man and I do deeds like this from my heart and
not for publicity, so please don't involve my name,'' the lineman
said. ``If I gain publicity from it, it takes away from the
sincerity of the act.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, an upbeat young man who hopes someday to leave his
wheelchair ``if medical science comes through,'' is a senior at
Sinagua who plans to attend college and become an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an exercise machine in my house, but it's inside, and I
don't get to see things,'' he said after the Cardinals' morning
practice Tuesday. ``This gives me a chance to be outside and see
the trees, the countryside, and enjoy it. It really means a lot to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff resident Larry Weidner has established a B.J. Carlson
Education Fund and is selling raffle tickets in the area to help
cover Carlson's college costs. The winner will receive a new Ford
F-150 truck. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
