<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAKER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JURY CLEARS WEALTHY EX-BOOKIE IN WIFE'S SLAYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A wealthy ex-bookie accused of plotting his estranged
wife's death to protect his fortune in a divorce was acquitted of
capital murder Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Angleton, who had been incarcerated since his arrest Aug.
1, 1997, said one of the first things he would do is visit the
grave of his wife, Doris McGown Angleton.
</P>
<P>
   As the jury's verdict was read before a packed courtroom
Wednesday, Angleton tearfully hugged two of his defense attorneys,
Stanley Schneider and George Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors Ted Wilson and Lyn McClellan appeared stunned, and
the courtroom fell silent for several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, after his release from the Harris County Jail,
Angleton spoke briefly to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get much happier than I feel right now,'' he said,
before being whisked away by his lawyers in a large sports utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Angleton's mother, Ann Borochoff, would only say that she
was relieved the long trial had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just grateful that it's over,'' said Borochoff, flanked
by relatives and friends. ``It's been very emotional for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Angleton, who made his fortune running an illegal gambling
operation, is only the second capital murder defendant in Harris
County history to win acquittal when a death sentence was sought.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors, who were sequestered by state District Judge Brian Rains
for two nights, handed down the decision after 18 hours of
deliberations over three days.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the panel said a tape recording prosecutors claimed
incriminated Angleton was the key to their decision.
</P>
<P>
   They said after hearing testimony from a defense voice expert,
who was initially hired by the state, they were not convinced the
voice on the tape was Angleton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key in the case is that his voice is not on that tape,''
said lead defense attorney Michael Ramsey after the verdict. ``The
only piece of evidence in the case that was of any consequence was
the tape recording, and once we found out his voice was not on that
tape to a certainty, and it was just virtual certainty, then it was
just a matter of waiting for justice to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Angleton was accused of conspiring with his brother, Roger, to
kill Doris Angleton, whose body was found by police in the couple's
River Oaks area home April 16, 1997. She had been shot 13 times,
seven times in the head, during an ambush while her husband and
twin daughters were at a softball game.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were arrested on murder charges, but Roger Angleton
killed himself in jail Feb. 7, leaving notes behind claiming that
he had framed his brother as part of an elaborate extortion
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Rains ruled the suicide notes inadmissible, and prosecutors
discounted them, arguing that Robert Angleton hired his brother to
carry out the slaying to protect the bookie's millions from an
impending divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The defense countered that Robert Angleton was a victim of a
bizarre plot hatched by his oddball brother, who had blackmailed
him once before, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the defense said, the divorce between Robert and
Doris was proceeding amicably.
</P>
<P>
   Those contentions came in the face of circumstantial evidence
that prosecutors believed unerringly linked Robert Angleton to the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The state relied on notes outlining the plot that were found in
Roger Angleton's briefcase when he was arrested in Las Vegas in
June 1997 on an unrelated charge.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the briefcase was $64,000 in cash and money wrappers
that had Robert Angleton's fingerprints on them.
</P>
<P>
   But the most vital evidence was the tape. Two men can be heard
on the scratchy audiotape plotting the murder and discussing
security at the Angleton home. Prosecutors said the voices are
those of the brothers and they called a procession of witnesses to
identify the defendant's voice.
</P>
<P>
   Those witnesses included friends of the victim, police officers
and an FBI agent who heard Robert Angleton's voice on a wiretap in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey attacked the credibility of some of the state's voice
witnesses. He characterized many of them as members of the ``Nancy
Drew division'' of a tennis club, where he says they sat around
drinking cocktails and gossiping about the case.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also called its own string of witnesses, including
Angleton's twin daughters, who said it wasn't their father's voice.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the testimony of voice-analysis experts,
especially Steve Cain, and that's what defense attorneys say turned
the case in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Cain, who is based in Wisconsin, was hired by prosecutors to
compare the tape seized from among Roger Angleton's belongings with
a voice sample of Robert Angleton taken by Houston police.
</P>
<P>
   Cain told prosecutors the trial tape was probably a copy of an
original recording and that it was ``possible'' to eliminate Robert
Angleton as being one of the men on it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Cain was hired by the defense. His
videotaped testimony, taken before trial, was played for jurors and
was backed up by another expert who testified in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Steve Cain's honest assessment of the voice on the
tape along with (the other expert) was the cincher,'' Schneider
said afterward. ``The science is what won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had another voice-analysis expert of their own
waiting in the wings but opted not to call him to the stand.
Instead, they tried to convince jurors that their witnesses,
combined with the content of the tape, were good enough to link
Robert Angleton to the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Another twist was a defense theory that two gunmen, not one,
killed Doris Angleton. Though prosecutors dismissed that as a
convenient way to explain the two voices on the tape, at least one
juror said he believed it.
</P>
<P>
   After the shock of the verdict had worn off, prosecutors said
they could only accept the jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really, frankly thought it would be a guilty verdict or a
hung jury,'' Wilson said. ``I'm assuming there must have been some
reasonable doubt about whether he was on the tape or not.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said he looks forward to talking to the jurors soon to
get their thoughts, especially since prosecutors thought the case
was solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept waiting for something (from the defense) to fall out of
the sky and hit me like a safe, but that just didn't happen,''
McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict notwithstanding, Robert Angleton's legal problems
might not be over.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said he thinks the IRS should look into the bookie's
illegal financial dealings in light of the millions found stashed
in safety deposit boxes during the murder investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the IRS doesn't look at that, I don't know what they're
doing,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
