<HEADLINE>
WADSWORTH IN COGNITO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ Peering behind those dark sunglasses Friday
night at Sun Devil Stadium could be Andre Wadsworth, the Cardinals'
unsigned first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, continuing to make the rounds on the Valley
sports-talk radio circuit, said Wednesday on KMVP-AM (860) that he
might attend a game ``in person.'' He said he would go incognito.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play host to the Chicago Bears on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``I might sitting in the stands. .
. . I'll just wear a cap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president of player personnel of the
Cardinals, said, ``We'd love to have him.'' But Ferguson didn't say
if Wadsworth would have to buy a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's holdout reached its 21st day Wednesday and the two
sides remain far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth also said he plans to ask the Cardinals for a one-year
contract after the club rejected his offers for four- and five-year
deals. The most the Cardinals could pay Wadsworth in a one-year
deal is $1.88 million, including a $1.636 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, the Florida State defensive end who was the third
pick overall in the draft, could earn as much as a $10.4 million
signing bonus in a six-year deal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
