<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BRADSHAW-MTNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL DRIVE ON A HOT DAY  
 FOLLOW THE MEAN DERING TRAILS THROUGH BRADSHAW MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This isn't the time of year considered prime for off-highway
trips in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it's too hot. And without vehicle windows open, you
lose touch with the wilderness passing by. Besides that, the air
conditioner might heat up the engine when you climb steep grades.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   It was cloudy, warm and humid in Phoenix at 6:30 Monday morning.
But Ed Fouts of Phoenix had planned a trip to higher country _
through the Bradshaw Mountains, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to get off Interstate 17 at the Bumble Bee exit and
ride unpaved dirt roads for 60 miles or so to U.S. 89 near Kirkland
Junction.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioner ran all the way to the Bumble Bee turnoff,
where we stopped and dropped the air pressure in the Blazer's tires
to about 30 pounds. Washboard and rocky roads would seem much
smoother with the tires made softer.
</P>
<P>
   It also was much cooler at this higher altitude. So down went
the windows for much of the long trip ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of this trip would wind through the old mining
town of Cleator, famous for its independent residents. The sign was
gone, but there used to be one that said, ``Trespassers Will Be
Shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Fouts, who has traveled the desert seemingly forever, as
a rider is like traveling with a talking history book. He pointed
out the various mines, bridge abutments that supported supply
wagons on their way to the mines and the path of the mining
railroad.
</P>
<P>
   That all was impressive, but no more so than the desert
vegetation. Usually, by this time of year, there is a predominance
of dried plants. Not this year. The desert was green and lush as
the road traveled higher and higher. Agave plants sent up tall
stalks topped by bright yellow flowers. Closer to the ground were
all types of wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Then we were into the switchbacks on the steep climb to Crown
King, the mining town turned vacation community. The road is built
on the old railroad bed, and at the switchbacks, Fouts pointed out
where trains used to pull in and then back up the next grade, since
the turns were too tight for them to make.
</P>
<P>
   This part of the trip to Crown King can be made by car, but when
you leave the old mining town on Senator Highway toward Prescott,
the road gets much rougher. A high-profile vehicle is necessary,
but four-wheel drive is not.
</P>
<P>
   The road down from Crown King also was beautiful, not so much
because of the flowers, but because of the pines that kept
temperatures cool despite the slowly vanishing clouds. Like the
trip up on the switchbacks, there are great views on this road. A
look to the west even revealed the distant Harquahala Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Near the base of the mountains, Senator Highway (Forest Road
259) takes a curve to the right toward Prescott, but a marker
pointing to the left announces Wagoner Road (FR362). That would
take us through mining and ranching country, through the former
site of Wagoner, an old ranching and mining community, and to U.S.
89.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Fouts said, this road was well-maintained because
of heavy traffic. It isn't anymore. The road is rocky, rough and
complete with plenty of washouts _ not a place you'd want to take
your car.
</P>
<P>
   Now it began to heat up in the oak-juniper country. But the
terrain was beautiful and lush. We dropped into Minnehaha Flat, a
stretch of private land complete with some primitive dwellings.
Then Fouts ordered a stop to look at well-preserved Button Mine.
The mine is closed to the public, but we could get a good look from
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a drive past the remains of Wagoner, past Walnut Grove
and a crossing of the Hassayampa River into ranching country. Some
of the fences at these ranches cost more than my home. It was hot
by now, and the air conditioner was running. Fouts took a nap.
</P>
<P>
   Just as well. The drive back to Phoenix through Wickenburg
seemed as if it took forever. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
