A1382 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MAJORS-ARIZONANS-     08-12 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MAJORS-ARIZONANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S CON TRIBUTED TO MAJOR LEAGUE ROSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's the summer's dog days, and there was Curt
Schilling making Shadow Mountain look like high school was in full
session.
</P>
<P>
   The parking lot was nearly full. The marching band had worked
for weeks, preparing for Schilling's grand return to campus.
</P>
<P>
   The fight song played on, as children, adults, alumni coaches
and administrators stood to welcome back the ex-Matador who grew up
to become one of baseball's fiercest pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, whose high school jersey number was retired during
Tuesday's ceremony, is one of more than 100 Arizonans to have
played in the major leagues. According to research by Mike Holden,
editor of ``Baseball AZ,'' 54 Arizona-born players made it to The
Show. Many more major leaguers, such as Schilling, Chad Curtis and
Tim Salmon, spent much of their youth in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have thought Schilling would join that illustrious
list? Many of his high school teammates in the mid-1980s had better
statistics. Schilling mostly just pitched for Shadow Mountain, and
sometimes he let his emotions get in the way of his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that every problem was the end of the world, and I
realize now that none of it meant a whole lot in the grand scheme
of things,'' the Philadelphia Phillies star said. ``I learned a lot
of things. Coach (William) Hatcher was somebody who, early in life,
taught me a lot of lessons about life, not just about baseball. I
don't think I realized that until after I left here. I kind of
thought maybe I'd get a fair shake a lot of times here, and I
realized it's not always going to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, now making his riches in an Anaheim Angels uniform, was
a year behind Schilling in school, hammering tape-measure shots at
Greenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I didn't know who he was,'' Salmon said. ``All of
a sudden, he made it, and I thought, `Hey, I remember that guy.' I
kind of remember playing against him in American Legion.'' &QL; 
Others were stars &QL; 
Schilling is an exception in the crowd of ex-Arizona high school
baseball players who made it to the major leagues. Most dominated
at the prep level.
</P>
<P>
   There were pitchers Lerrin LaGrow at Glendale and John Denny at
Prescott, catcher Duffy Dyer at Cortez and outfielder Jay Schlueter
at Central in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   There were catchers Terry Kennedy at St. Mary's and Ozzie Virgil
Jr. at Moon Valley, outfielder Mickey Hatcher at Mesa and infielder
Bob Horner at Glendale Apollo in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Salmon at Greenway, infielder/outfielder Curtis at
Benson, pitcher Gil Heredia at Nogales and shortstop Shawn Gilbert
at Avondale Agua Fria in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, pitchers Marc Kroon of Shadow Mountain, Matt Perisho
of Tempe McClintock and Bobby Howry of Glendale Deer Valley, and
catcher Paul Konerko of Scottsdale Chaparral have seen big league
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they all had, including Schilling, was a never-say-die
desire to make it and the abilities to turn dreams real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt like I was the best,'' said Dyer, now a bench
coach for the Oakland Athletics. ``I had buddies who were just as
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just always felt I had a shot at making it. I didn't know
how good the competition was. I was just thinking all the time,
`I'm going to play pro ball.' '' &QL; 
Growing up &QL; 
Salmon in right and batting third. Horner hitting cleanup. Virgil
behind the plate. Curtis in center. Schilling, Jim Palmer and Denny
in the rotation. LaGrow and Kevin Wickander closing.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad all-time Arizona baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   They all made their dent in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and Denny were Cy Young Award winners. Salmon has been an
explosive hitter for the Angels. LaGrow once finished second to
Sparky Lyle in the Fireman of the Year balloting in the American
League. Virgil was a two-time All-Star in the mid-'80s and enjoyed
the thrill of playing in the 1985 classic while his father was one
of his coaches on the National League team.
</P>
<P>
   But high school coaches are surprised that not more have gone to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Only four players born in Arizona were on major league Opening
Day rosters this year: Rex Hudler (Tempe) of the Phillies, Jeff
Huson (Scottsdale) of the Seattle Mariners, Albie Lopez (Mesa) of
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and Tom Pagnozzi (Tucson) of the St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we don't have more,'' said Greenway Coach Ted
Blake, who coached Salmon and former San Francisco Giants pitcher
Randy McCament in high school. ``I think we've got some kids who
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   But in defense of the scouts, Blake said, ``It's a crapshoot.
You roll your dice and take your chances.'' &QL; 
Big league ingredients &QL; 
It's all about timing, work ethic and ability.
</P>
<P>
   Take one away from the other, and it's difficult for anybody to
make it.
</P>
<P>
   Most find the journey to the big leagues long and winding and
sometimes frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil, who graduated from Moon Valley in 1976 and lost to
Horner's Apollo Hawks in the 1975 state championship game, signed
out of high school with the Phillies and spent 4{ years in the
minors before embarking on a major league career that lasted about
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil said he grew up a ``clubhouse brat,'' hanging in the
summer with the Giants, for whom his his father, Ozzie Virgil Sr.,
was a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time in San Francisco, Gaylord Perry came walking in (the
clubhouse) after being pulled in the first inning,'' Ozzie Jr.
said. ``There was a big spread on the table. He flipped the table
and everything flew all over the place. At 12, all I could think of
was, `Oh, man, I'm not eating today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Virgil, who now lives in Glendale and is learning how to fly
airplanes, said that as a junior in high school, he took batting
practice with major leaguers such as Jack Clark and feel he was
blistering the ball just as far and as hard as the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is easy, I thought,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're away for the first time, you're having to learn
everything on your own,'' he said. ``Mom isn't doing your clothes
and feeding you anymore. I had to pay for everything. It's a big
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about baseball, it's all about adjusting to
everything. Guys who adjust to the pitching and the environment are
the ones who keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment seemed easy for Horner, who went straight from
the College World Series with Arizona State to the Atlanta Braves,
where he put together an outstanding career. Horner now resides in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrow, who has a son entering his senior year at Scottsdale
Desert Mountain, stayed in the minors long enough for a cup of
coffee. After his ASU career ended in 1969, he entered the Detroit
Tigers' clubhouse, a frightened child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death,'' LaGrow said. ``I had this old,
beat-up bag, and this guy walked up and said, `You must be Lerrin.'
I thought I was in trouble. He stuck out his hand and said, `I'm Al
Kaline, welcome to the Detroit Tigers.' It took all the pressure
off immediately.'' &QL; 
Progression, regression? &QL; 
Eras have changed. As the 1970s turned into the 1980s, sandlot
games in 110-degree weather, for many, turned into Nintendo
baseball battles on comfy couches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I lived in the inner city, and we didn't
have much,'' said Jay Schlueter, who now works in commercial real
estate in Scottsdale, where his son, Brian, will be a sophomore
outfielder at Chaparral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball was the only thing. We would play home-run derby. We
couldn't wait until Saturdays, when they had the ``Game of the
Week'' on TV. We'd mimic the players' batting stances. Playing
major league baseball was my dream from Day One. It didn't matter.
Every time I blew out the candles on my birthday, I wanted to be a
baseball player.'' &QL; 
Return to roots &QL; 
Tom Pagnozzi owns the distinction of being the first Arizona-born
person to play an official major league game in Arizona. That
happened July 30, when he started at catcher for the Cardinals
against the Diamondbacks at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Paul Konerko, now 22, returned to Arizona as both a
Los Angeles Dodger and a Cincinnati Red, as did Salmon with the
Angels. But neither was born in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never doubted his ability to succeed in anything he went
into,'' Hank Konerko said of his son, who used to hit so many
Little League home runs in north Scottsdale that parents dubbed him
the next Babe Ruth. ``He has an absolute commitment to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko is struggling to stay in the majors. He's been up and
down twice this season, once with the Dodgers and now with the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Dad doesn't believe son will stay down long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing his drive and commitment to to play well, I'd hate to
bet against him,'' Hank said. ``Some of his latest struggles could
be the best thing that ever happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko can look at Schilling's journey as evidence that
patience and perseverance pay off. Schilling wasn't highly
recruited out of high school, struggled early in his pro career,
but look where he is now: the Phillies' ace, a strikeout terror.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling became the first former Arizona high school player to
win an official major league game on Arizona soil. He did it this
week, shutting out the Diamondbacks, 3-0, yielding three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Many who saw him growing up couldn't help but smile and shake
their heads afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always dreamed of being a big league ballplayer,''
Schilling said. ``I think the one thing that my father gave me was
that I never doubted myself. I always believed I could do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
