<SLUG> BC-BBM-DBACKS-MINORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF POSSIBLE, OR GANIZATION AP PEARS TO BE OVERSTOCKED WITH
CATCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - An organization can always use one more good catcher _
even the Diamondbacks, who have a number of hot, young prospects on
the minor league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have enough good catchers,'' said  &UR; Mel Didier, the
Diamondbacks' director of player development. ``You can make a
trade with them if you have to. We're fortunate to have guys who
are absolute prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those young guns is  &UR; Rod Barajas at Class A High Desert,
recently named a Player of the Week in the California League. He
homered in three consecutive at-bats and was a big factor as his
club won 10 straight games. He has 21 homers, surpassing his total
of 17 from the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect him to get better,'' Didier said. ``He's only 22.
His biggest problem is that he's like  &UR; Joe Torre and a number of
other guys in the past who have had to fight his weight. He's not
fat (5 feet 11, 220 pounds), but he's a guy who has a little
softness. We want to try to get rid of that. He's not short, but he
is a stocky guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works real hard, has good hands, power and throws well. He
has a chance to be a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Barajas will have an opportunity to play for the Diamondbacks'
new Double-A club next season, and he might even get a shot at
Triple-A with the Sidewinders, Didier said. The Diamondbacks are
hoping to find a spot for Barajas in winter ball, probably in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he is in professional ball is somewhat of a
surprise in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy (Barajas) walks into a tryout camp in California, and
they (Diamondbacks scouts) look at him, and kind of say, `He ain't
gonna do nothing.' But he hit the ball, and he hit it well,''
Didier said.
</P>
<P>
   Barajas isn't alone among catchers trying to climb to the big
club.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jose Lopez, 18, is making an impression at Class A South Bend.
He's hitting under .200, but Didier says he has an above-average
arm. He's been catching only a year since he was converted from a
third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Other top young guns include  &UR; Robert Hammock at Rookie
Lethbridge, 21, and 18-year-old  &UR; Stan Closser of the Rookie Tucson
Diamondbacks. &QL; 
Award winners &QL; 
 &UR; Jack Cust of the Lethbridge Black Diamonds and  &UR; Brad Penny of the
High Desert Mavericks were named the Diamondbacks' Player and
Pitcher of the Month for July. Cust, an outfielder who was a
first-round selection in 1997, batted .404, and had 11 doubles,
seven home runs and 30 RBIs. He also was named the Pioneer League
Player of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   Cust, one of the most highly touted high school prospects last
year, leads the Pioneer League with 17 doubles and a .542 on-base
percentage. He is second in slugging percentage (.649), extra-base
hits (26) and runs (52). The left-handed hitting outfielder, who is
fourth in the league with a .364 batting average, leads the Black
Diamonds in 10 categories.
</P>
<P>
   Penny won the distinction for the fourth time. He was 4-0 during
July with a 1.58 ERA. &QL; 
Moving up &QL; 
Moving up the ladder hasn't had a negative effect on left-handed
pitcher  &UR; Stephen Randolph. Since his July promotion to the
Sidewinders from High Desert, he has appeared in 11 games, pitching
15 innings with 14 strikeouts. Hitters have managed only a .226
average against him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
