</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS' IMAGE TARNISHED BY TIRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the Diamondbacks' biggest problems are struggling over
wins and losses and whether it's a little steamy in the upper
reaches of Bank One Ballpark, just remember, things could be a lot
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Take the other expansion club, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, for
example.  &UR; Vince Naimoli, the Devil Rays' equivalent to  &UR; Jerry
Colangelo in stature and title, has not made himself look very good
in public lately.
</P>
<P>
   After an article appeared in the ``Orlando Sentinel''
documenting Tropicana Field's numerous problems, Naimoli ripped
into the writer in a profanity-laced tirade that had some observers
thinking they were watching ``The Caine Mutiny'' when Captain Queeg
shouts, ``WHERE ARE THE STRAWBERRIES!''
</P>
<P>
   Naimoli also took exception with a ``Tampa Tribune'' story in
which a business writer chronicled Naimoli's alleged past clashes
with various persons over business related to the baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Dillard's stores pulled all their Devil
Rays merchandise because of another tirade from Naimoli to the area
manager of the chain.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoli was incensed because outfielder/first baseman  &UR; Dave
Martinez appeared in a newspaper advertisement for a charity event
at Dillard's wearing his Devil Rays uniform, a no-no unless the
club gives its permission.
</P>
<P>
   The store's manager admitted he did not know of the rule. He
offered to buy another advertisement to apologize for the mistake.
But when Naimoli continued berating the Dillard's official, the
manager basically said, ``forget you,'' although he wound up buying
the ad and then pulled the club's merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent rumors continue to swirl that the Devil Rays' other
limited partners are disenchanted with Naimoli's iron-fisted way of
handling problems and is tarnishing the club's image in the local
community.
</P>
<P>
   While removing someone from the managing general partnership is
almost unheard of, if Naimoli, who owns 16 percent of the Devil
Rays, continues to lash out and to look like an out-of-control
hothead, expect something to happen in the off-season. &QL; 
Stale fish for sale! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at a four-hour drive south on Interstate 75, the
proposed $169 million sale of the Florida Marlins trudges along at
a snail's pace. Marlins President  &UR; Don Smiley is having so much
trouble putting together investors to buy the club that a new
potential owner, commodities trader  &UR; John Henry, has surfaced, and
suddenly, Smiley may wind up on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley has had 10 months to put together a group and is still
more than $15 million short of his goal. Marlins owner and scourge
 &UR; Wayne
 &UR; Huizenga, who oversaw one of the greatest shams in recent sports
history, may be souring on Smiley's troubled effort and leaning
more toward Henry.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Henry is real,'' a source close to the negotiations told
the Associated Press. ``Smiley is looking highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between Smiley and Henry is Henry's ability
to finance a new home for the Marlins, whereas Smiley has said he
would need public funding for a new ballpark or consider the
possibility of the Marlins moving. &QL; 
It's almost over &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with the New York Mets battling for the wild-card spot, the
spotlight hasn't dimmed much on catcher  &UR; Mike Piazza, who,
according to several New York papers, has told teammates he is not
digging the New York scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, in turn, said last week that any negotiations with
Piazza will be put off until after the season, almost assuring that
he will enter the free-agent market, which will open 15 days after
the end of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to work something out, but we didn't,'' Piazza
said. ``There is no acrimony. I'm trying to do everything I can to
help this team get into the playoffs. I don't see why everybody has
to make such a big issue out of the contract. The issue should be
on the baseball season, that's it. Now is not the time to address
that issue. The priority is the season. I'll just give 110 percent
until the end of the season and then think about my future.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Piazza didn't talk quite like that when he and the
Dodgers were negotiating earlier this season. At one point, Piazza
turned down an $86 million offer from Los Angeles, which turned out
to be one of the last things he did in a Dodgers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing speculation that Piazza may head over to the
American League, possibly to play for Baltimore or Boston. Of
course, Los Angeles also will remain a player in the Piazza
sweepstakes. And never discount the deep-pocketed Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect, though, seems a lock: It's looking highly doubtful
that Piazza will entertain another $86 million offer from anybody. &QL; 
Now batting . . . who? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; John Mabry started at first base for St. Louis in a game
in Milwaukee last week, he knew full well what kind of reception he
would receive.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 25,969, many of whom came to watch  &UR; Mark McGwire
slug a home run, booed loudly every time Mabry came to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there before,'' Mabry said of the jeers.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry gave a McGwire-like performance, hitting a home run in his
first at-bat, his first since July 1. Mabry added an RBI single
later in the game while the cascading of boos continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get that going in St. Louis all weekend,''
Cardinals Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa joked. ``Every time John comes to
bat, all the fans boo him. I bet you it will do some good.''
</P>
<P>
   The best line heard all night?
</P>
<P>
   ``You think I paid $80 to see you hit?'' one fan yelled at
Mabry, who turned to the fan and asked, ``If I hit a home run, will
you buy me a beer?'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
